A2286 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-VIRTUAL-WORLD_SFCHRON     11-08 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIRTUAL-WORLD </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
By BENNY EVANGELISTA 
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine every person, place and thing on the face of the earth
having a Web page. And imagine a world full of wireless consumer
devices that could read those Web pages.
</P>
<P>
   Put them together and you have more information at your
fingertips than you may even want or know what to do with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother'' issues aside, that's the vision of scientists in
HP Labs, 3the Hewlett-Packard think tank that has spent four years
dreaming up new consumer devices and systems to infuse technology
into more segments of daily life.
</P>
<P>
   HP Labs last week unveiled ``CoolTown,'' its Web-centric concept
of a future world, where Muni riders, using a wireless device,
could tap into a bus' Web site to find out how late it was running.
And where a smart alarm clock would access your electronic calendar
and know what time to wake you in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   The concept of ``pervasive computing,'' or spreading the use of
computer technology far beyond the computer desktop, is not new.
Companies like IBM, Microsoft, Lucent Technologies, Sun
Microsystems and Xerox are also researching ways to put hardware
and software into appliances like refrigerators, toasters,
telephones and televisions to make them all-seeing, all-knowing,
Internet-enabled information devices.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those companies are trying to create another layer of
new technology _ such as chips, large storage devices and software
_ to connect appliances to the Internet. For example, a small chip
the size of a staple would be embedded in a painting, shirt or
other object and transmit data about the object to a wireless
device.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, HP Labs wants to use existing Web browsers and
servers and wireless transmitters to transmit information. HP Labs
Director Dick Lampman believes that by tapping into existing
technologies, pervasive computing could start to become a reality
in one or two years.
</P>
<P>
   HP's vision would use an open standard technology that's not
dependent on any one company's proprietary devices or software,
even HP's.
</P>
<P>
   But HP would profit from wider use of its Internet servers,
printers and computers. The lab also revealed some details of
research into higher-capacity computer storage devices, including
one that could hold more than one terabit of data per square inch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't see the point in creating a monopoly here,'' said
Jeff Morgan, a scientist working on the CoolTown project. ``We're
able to bring in Web economics.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan said the scientists have even coined a simple theme to
promote their idea: ``Hey, Everything Has a Web-page,' or `HE HAW'
for short.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the scientists are serious about their vision. To a small
gathering of technology journalists, they showed off a
demonstration conference room, which had its own internal Web page
detailing the equipment available.
</P>
<P>
   Using a palm device, researcher Gene Becker called up the Web
address for a printer in the room and printed the Web page for the
room, without having to hook up wires.
</P>
<P>
   He also demonstrated how HP employees, using a desktop or
portable computer, can track the location and read the schedule of
an HP shuttle bus equipped with its own Web site and a Global
Positioning Satellite receiver. In the CoolTown idea, bus stops
would have their own individual Web sites to deliver information
like maps, weather and fare prices.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, a wristwatch could be turned into a wireless
device that could access those Web pages. In a store, a Web-enabled
blue jeans display, for example, could sense an approaching shopper
and offer an instant electronic coupon on the customer's &UR;  &LR; watch.
</P>
<P>
   Parents could use such a watch as a satellite-linked tracking
device for their children or other people. ``When I'm in the mall,
and it turns out my best friend is in Macy's, I can (find her
location on the watch) and go and have coffee with her,'' said
Frederick Kitson, the lab's client and media systems director.
</P>
<P>
   Technology analyst Rob Enderle of Giga Information Group said
HP's concept ``on the surface makes an elegant kind of sense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds like someone would have thought of this long ago,''
Enderle said. ``It's easier than creating a whole new protocol.''
</P>
<P>
   Enderle noted that the CoolTown idea could help Hewlett-Packard
change its image from a technology follower to a technology leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of the Internet, both Microsoft and IBM have been
much more aggressive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that Hewlett-Packard still has to prove that, like any
large corporation, it can allow a simple idea to flourish without
trying to put more of an HP stamp on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hewlett-Packard and `easier' are not typically two things that
come together in the same sentence,'' he said. ``This might be
first real representation of a new HP.''
</P>
<P>
   HP's researchers admit there are a number of potential barriers
before their ``HE-HAW'' concept really takes root. For one thing,
the wireless networks are not widespread yet, Becker said.
</P>
<P>
   And the researchers wouldn't touch the sociological implications
of having everyone wired to the Internet so that a computer would
know when a person sits, stands, walks, talks and buys.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are technical issues and there are social issues as
well,'' Becker said. ``That will all be sorted out over time.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
