<HEADER>
A2287 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-DOMASH-COLUMN_SFCHRON     11-08 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMASH-COLUMN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
By HARRY DOMASH 
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Many professional money managers think selecting the right
industry group is more important than picking the right stock.
</P>
<P>
   An industry group is made up of companies in the same or related
businesses _ for instance, grocery stores, computer manufacturers
or oil drillers.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks in the same industry group tend to move together. In
recent months, we have seen surges in the prices of oil, gold,
retail and financial services stocks. When those industries took
off, most stocks in the groups went along.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what the overall market is doing, you will always find
some industry groups moving up, and others heading down. A popular
investment strategy is to pick the strongest stock in a strong
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Here are three Web sites with free tools to help you implement
this strategy:
</P>
<P>
   WALL STREET CITY: Telescan's Wall Street City
(www.wallstreetcity.com) sports an impressive set of industry group
analysis tools. Telescan Inc. of Houston is a public corporation
that has been supplying stock market data and analysis tools for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   From the home page, select Industry Group Center on the
Investment Centers menu to display the Industry Group menu and a
tutorial explaining Wall Street City's approach to industry group
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Select Best &AMP; Worst Industries from the menu to see the entire
list of industry groups sorted from best- to worst-performing for
one day's returns. Unless you're a short-term trader, one day
doesn't mean much, but you can select other periods ranging from
one week to five years by clicking on the corresponding links. I
picked six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Topping the list was ``Retail/stores/mail order-catalogs,''
showing a healthy 28.9 percent return. ``Tobacco/cigarettes''
showed the worst return _ down 31.3 percent in six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Click on the industry name to see the stocks in the group,
sorted with the best performers at the top. The best company in the
retail/stores/ mail-order group was Right Start, with a 75.3
percent return. Blair Corp. was at the bottom, losing 21.8 percent
in six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   You can research Right Start, or any company, by clicking on the
company name. That displays a price chart for the stock and a
drop-down menu (Select Company Report) listing a variety of
available reports and news sources for the company. Of the 17
reports listed on the menu, four (Company Profile, Macro World
Price Forecast, ProSearch Criteria and S&AMP;P Company Report) require
a subscription. The rest are free. Some are exclusive to Wall
Street City, including two of my favorites: Quick Facts and
Telescan Rankings.
</P>
<P>
   You'll need patience when using Wall Street City; some of the
screens take a long time to display.
</P>
<P>
   MONEY CENTRAL: Microsoft's Money Central (moneycentral.msn.com)
has an easy-to-use feature that highlights the 10 best and worst
performing industries over the past month.
</P>
<P>
   From the home page, select Investor from the drop-down menu,
then click on Top 10 Lists under Markets on the left, and finally
select Industries.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft shows you the best and worst performing industry
groups, including the percentage change for each group during the
past month. The results are updated nightly.
</P>
<P>
   When I checked last Wednesday, Health Care Plans was the best
performer, with a 24.5 percent gain, and Cigarettes was the worst,
falling 27.9 percent during the past month.
</P>
<P>
   Clicking on the industry name displays a list of the 10 best and
10 worst performing stocks in the group, also based on one month's
performance.
</P>
<P>
   I selected Health Care Plans and found that LifePoint Hospitals,
a recent spin-off of Columbia/HCA, was the leader _ it soared 52.9
percent in one month. Clicking LifePoint's ticker symbol displays a
current quote and a menu accessing all of the research information
available on the site for that company.
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFING.COM: Briefing.com (www.briefing.com) takes a different
approach. Instead of relying on recent performance, Briefing.com
employs real people to analyze the prospects of each industry.
</P>
<P>
   Briefing.com charges $6.95 per month to see the ratings on their
site, but E-Trade gives it to you free. You have to register, but
you don't have to be an E-Trade customer to see the reports.
</P>
<P>
   Briefing.com refers to industry groups as sectors. From
E-Trade's home page, select Markets on the top menu, and then
Sector Ratings under Analysis &AMP; Commentary near the bottom of the
menu on the left.
</P>
<P>
   Briefing.com covers 26 industries. The ratings are summarized in
a chart at the top. The ratings range from one (outperform) to five
(underperform). Some sectors have both short- and long-term
ratings. For example, 3/2 means the short-term rating is three
(market performer), and the long-term rating is two (slightly
outperform).
</P>
<P>
   Briefing.com provides a detailed analysis of each industry. When
I checked, the only top-rated industries were the Internet and
Telecom Equipment sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco was the only industry warranting a five rating
(underperform).
</P>
<P>
   In an analysis of the industry, Briefing.com minced no words,
saying, ``Expect Philip Morris to end up declaring bankruptcy,''
and others in the field to ``face a similar threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefing.com lists all of the major companies in each group, but
only occasionally mentions favorites, and then only in passing. For
instance, it named 17 companies in the top-rated telecommunications
equipment sector without differentiating between the investment
quality of any of them.
</P>
<P>
   The ratings look like they are updated every two or three
months. When I looked, eight sectors hadn't been updated since
August.
</P>
<P>
   Industry group price trends tend to last for months, if not
years. For instance, the banking group was in an uptrend from
January 1997 until early this year. The wine and liquor segment
sector is experiencing a steep uptrend that started around the
middle of last year. Gold mining stocks were in a downtrend that
started in the middle of '96 and lasted until September of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
