<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-BLACKHAWKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS BEAT BLACKHAWKS, 3-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The strategy seemed foolproof: keep the New York
Rangers on the power play and they would not score.
</P>
<P>
   Even if that was not the Chicago Blackhawks' plan, it was
working, at least for the first two minutes of the game. The
Blackhawks took a penalty 8 seconds in. The Rangers, among the
National Hockey League's worst at scoring power-play goals, as
usual, did not tally.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were not awarded a power play for 55 more minutes,
and when they were, they again failed to score. But in between,
they scored three even strength goals and won, 3-1, to snap a
seven-game stretch (0-5-2) without a victory and gain their first
triumph in exactly three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was probably the best 60-minute effort we've had all
season,'' said Ranger goalie Kirk McLean, who stopped 23 shots,
playing in place of Mike Richter.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the Rangers' scores came in the first period _ one by the
rookie Mike York from Theo Fleury, the other by Petr Nedved from
the rookie Jan Hlavac. The third came from Adam Graves, his third
of the season and first in 11 games, on an assist from Fleury,
after the Rangers had sat back for a period and a half and let the
Blackhawks back in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``That goal released a lot of pressure,'' Rangers Coach John
Muckler said.
</P>
<P>
   With the Rangers slumping and coming in at 5-8-3 for the season,
Neil Smith, the team's president and general manager, was being
openly questioned about Muckler's job status.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers prevailed even though their power play went 0 for 3
and is now 4 for 71 on the season, 0 for 31 on the road and 0 for
its last 29 anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers' last victory had come on Oct. 17 against the
expansion Atlanta Thrashers. That was also the last time they had a
two-goal lead. The Blackhawks, meanwhile, have been pathetic on
home ice where they are 0-5-3.
</P>
<P>
   There were huge pockets of empty seats in the United Center in a
contest between two of the worst teams in the league. But there
were two Ottawa scouts present. The Rangers are host to the
Senators on Wednesday at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   But Ottawa's deadline for the holdout center Aleksei Yashin to
either sign or not come back this season is Monday. Manny Malhotra
received a little more ice time than usual on Sunday night, leading
to the question whether the Rangers might be showcasing him for a
deal.
</P>
<P>
   The play was sloppy, indicative of both teams' shoddy records.
The Rangers sat back on their heels after scores by York and
Nedved. York scored his fourth of the season 5 minutes 9 seconds
into the game, and Nedved got his fourth at 8:58.
</P>
<P>
   McLean allowed only Anders Eriksson's slap shot at 3:45 of the
third to beat him. Graves restored the two-goal lead at 11:17. And
the Rangers, a fragile team to begin with, somehow held on.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a start,'' Rangers Captain Brian Leetch said. ``We
still have a lot of work to do.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to be careful,'' said Muckler. ``We've won one game.
We should be happy and enjoy it. But Monday, we have to go to work
again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
