<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-TITANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLPHINS SHUT OUT TITANS, 17-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Steve McNair is not likely to doubt the Miami Dolphins'
standing as the National Football League's third-stingiest defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee Titans' quarterback was harassed throughout the
game on Sunday night, throwing three interceptions and getting
sacked four times, as Miami won a defensive brawl, 17-0, before
74,109 at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The victory raised the Dolphins' record to 7-1, their best start
since 1990, and dropped upstart Tennessee to 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Miami still has not given up a rushing touchdown this season.
</P>
<P>
   Cornerback Sam Madison, who had eight interceptions last season,
hogged Miami's defensive spotlight on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   He was responsible for all of McNair's interceptions, and they
all came on similar plays, where Madison could drop off his deep
coverage and turn to find the football going into his arms.
</P>
<P>
   After two late first-half interceptions, Madison developed an
upset stomach. The third-year pro sat out until two plays before
his third interception, which came late in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   He returned this one 29 yards, giving him 115 interception
return yards for the game. It was enough to set up Olindo Mare to
pad Miami's lead.
</P>
<P>
   Mare punched through a 46-yard field goal 14 minutes 55 seconds
from game's end for the final margin.
</P>
<P>
   For Miami, the injured veteran quarterback Dan Marino watched
the game from the sideline in a long-sleeve, dark blue shirt and
jeans as Damon Huard won his third straight game as a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Huard, a third-year pro from the University of Washington,
completed 15 of 25 passes for 210 yards and 2 touchdowns. He had no
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   McNair completed 22 of 42 passes for 205 yards. The Alcorn State
alumnus picked up 47 of those yards on Tennessee's final
desperation drive that reached the Miami 3-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   Yet typically on this night, his final pass fell incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans managed 308 yards of offense. Eddie George, the power
back, had the most success, with several sizable runs giving him 65
for the game. His problem: only 14 carries, with Tennessee
struggling to keep the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins, averaging just 304 yards and 16 points in Huard's
two starts, began the game like an offensive juggernaut. Huard
found Tony Martin for 16 yards on first down, then Cecil Collins
burst for 12 more.
</P>
<P>
   But so much for a quick personality makeover. Four plays later,
Miami punted.
</P>
<P>
   Derrick Mason went to field the punt and the ball bounded past
him. Miami thought he had touched it and made an official
challenge. It was denied, with Miami losing a timeout as a result.
</P>
<P>
   On Tennessee's second series, the visitors went from their 15 to
the Dolphins' 14 in 10 plays. George ate up 41 yards of it in four
runs. Yet frustration was around the corner. On fourth down, Al Del
Greco's 33-yard field-goal attempt hit the left goal post and
bounced out.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins then mustered their best drive of the game, going
77 yards in 12 plays in a convincing 6-minute-18-second statement
bridging the first and second quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Huard passes of 9 yards to Stanley Pritchett and 29 to Oronde
Gadsden gave the Dolphins good field position, and shortly
thereafter Huard salvaged a broken play impressively.
</P>
<P>
   Jevon Kearse, the Titans' pass-rushing end, stripped Huard of
the ball, but the quarterback scooped it up and threw an
off-balance pass to O.J. McDuffie for 20 yards.
</P>
<P>
   That set up Miami at the Tennessee 6. Three plays later, Huard
spotted Pritchett over the middle for the 6-yard touchdown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
