<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 00:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2297 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-911-CALLS-KAN &LR;      11-08 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-911-CALLS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOCAL 911 CALLERS ARE GETTING A RECORDING INSTEAD OF HELP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE PENN and CHRISTINE VENDEL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas City, Mo--At least 20 times a day, Kansas Citians calling
911 to report emergencies hear this recording:
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the Kansas City Police Department. You have reached
911. Don't hang up. For MAST, call 787-8835; for fire, call
274-2121. Please hang on the line.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past 18 months, an understaffed police dispatch center
has been unable to keep up with the more than 1,300 emergency calls
the center receives each day, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons behind the inability to handle calls include low
staffing _ 40 percent of call taker and dispatcher jobs are
unfilled.
</P>
<P>
   Police say they're experiencing:
</P>
<P>
   A near-doubling of the average time it takes to answer 911
calls, from six seconds to 11 seconds. At least one caller had to
wait four minutes after dialing 911.
</P>
<P>
   A 185 percent increase from last year for abandoned 911 calls,
when callers hang up before the recording kicks in, or as soon as
it begins.
</P>
<P>
   A 42 percent increase in misdials and a doubling of the number
of calls from cellular phones, many of which are nuisance calls.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems, authorities say they know of no instances
wherein someone suffered an injury or died because of inability to
reach a call taker. Nevertheless, the problem has generated
numerous complaints to city and police officials.
</P>
<P>
   City Council member Alvin Brooks, who founded the Ad Hoc Group
Against Crime, said he has called 911 and gotten a recording and
was put on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something that has to be addressed to see what we can
do,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know it's bad, but we're taking steps to address the
problem,'' said police Capt. Rick McLaughlin.
</P>
<P>
   Police Board President Jeff Simon said, ``There is a critical
need to do something about it soon. But like so many other problems
we have, it all comes back to money.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Police Department answers all 911 calls for the
city and then routes the calls to police dispatchers, fire
dispatchers or the city's ambulance service.
</P>
<P>
   During peak hours, when dispatchers are busy and calls are lined
up, callers can hear the recording telling them to call the Fire
Department or the Metropolitan Ambulance Services Trust.
</P>
<P>
   According to communications records, from January 1999 to
October 1999, about 86,000 callers hung up out of 403,000 total
calls, McLaughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   The situation alarms Matt Gratton, the city's Emergency Medical
System director . After receiving three complaints from the
management of MAST and the Fire Department, Gratton wrote police
commanders in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our concern is that someone in the middle of an emergency may
not be able to remember a number and may not decide to call at
all,'' Gratton said. ``Any time a person is given a recording, it's
a concern.'' Kansas City Maj. Dean Kelly, who oversees the
communications unit, said he has a serious staffing problem.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, 37 call takers and dispatcher positions are vacant
out of 91 slots. The department has used overtime to compensate for
the vacancies, but emergency callers are still hearing the
recordings. Eleven new call takers will start work Monday, which
Kelly said could help mitigate the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Still, they need more workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may get 300 applicants, but we're lucky if we get 15 who
are qualified,'' Kelly said. ``And while those 15 are waiting to
get hired, five of them end up getting other jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Late hours and pay are factors in retention, Kelly said .
</P>
<P>
   The day shift is manned by employees who have seniority. That
means new employees must work from 3 a.m. to 11 p.m. or from 11
p.m. to 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you've got to work holidays,'' Kelly said. ``And right
now, you've got to work mandatory overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Oct. 31, call takers and dispatchers in Kansas City
started out making less than dispatchers in three other nearby
cities _ $10.50 an hour. Last week, starting hourly pay increased
to $11.88.
</P>
<P>
   In Overland Park, Kan., communications officers start at $12.19
an hour; in Independence, call taker/dispatchers start at $11.84
per hour; in Kansas City, Kan., dispatchers start at $11.34 per
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said dispatchers also can get better-paying jobs in other
fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``In today's job market, it doesn't pay more than a job for an
airline employee who doesn't have to work holidays or weekends,''
Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   The salary range does increase the longer the employee stays on
the job. ``But we have very few call takers or dispatchers who stay
beyond three or four years,'' Kelly said. To address the delay
callers experience, the department has signed up employees to
answer incoming 911 calls exclusively. Two of the employees will
work each shift beginning Nov. 16, focusing only on directing calls
to the proper place, either police, fire or ambulance. ``Hopefully,
that will eliminate people getting that recording,'' Kelly said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the most critical calls, those for medical
help, can get routed faster if they don't have to get in line
behind police calls, some of which are nuisance calls.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin said he took a complaint from a caller recently who
was upset that his wife was put on hold after trying to report a
prowler. She hung up after getting the recording. McLaughlin said
they found out she called at the same time that seven cellular
phone callers were reporting a car fire. While call takers were
taking those calls, she was on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Cellular phones also can contribute to crowding of 911 lines. If
a cell phone user calls 911 for help with, say, a flat tire,
someone calling to report a shooting could be put on hold.
</P>
<P>
   Educating the public about when to use 911 could help alleviate
some problems, Kelly said. He said building fires can draw 40 calls
to 911, tying up the lines. He expects more problems next month
when the area introduces 10-digit telephone calls. Kansas' area
code of 913 is similar to 911 and he predicts a spike in misdials.
</P>
<P>
   The Police Department is working with Southwestern Bell and the
Mid-America Regional Council to try to head off complications.
Simon said the Police Department is looking at long-term solutions
to the problem, including waiving the city's residency requirement
for the job to attract more applicants.
</P>
<P>
   Simon said he'd also like to put dispatcher and call-taker jobs
at the top of the list when it comes time to adjust pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to simply make our case and hope the City Council will
appropriate it,'' he said. ``It's an urgent need. There's no
question about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
