<HEADLINE>
CLOCK CONTROVERSY BURNS UP GALAXY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Nearly an hour after the Dallas Burn added another
chapter to its incredible season, there was Galaxy coach Sigi
Schmid and assistant coach Ralph Perez sorting out the confusion
after a disheartening 3-2 shootout loss at the Cotton Bowl on
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas outscored the Galaxy 4-3 in the shootout to even the
best-of-three Western Conference final series at 1-1. The two teams
will meet again Thursday at the Rose Bowl to decide who will play
for the MLS Championship on Nov. 21 in Foxboro, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy striker Carlos Hermosillo scored twice to give the Galaxy
one-goal leads, but Dallas' Ariel Graziani matched him with two
goals, tying the match 2-2 in the 73rd minute to force the
shootout.
</P>
<P>
   Here is where the confusion began.
</P>
<P>
   Hermosillo gave the Galaxy a 2-1 lead in the shootout with one
Dallas shooter remaining _ Jorge Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   With only five seconds to get off a shot from the 35-yard line,
the clock mysteriously stopped with .38 left _ nearly a half-second
before Rodriguez got off his shot on the television replays.
Rodriguez dribbled away from Galaxy goalkeeper Kevin Hartman,
losing valuable time, but the goal was allowed despite an emotional
plea from Hartman.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do enough of these things, you can sort of tell
time,'' said Hartman. ``You see (the Galaxy's) Cobi (Jones) go
around the keeper, he sprints, he touches it and still barely gets
it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed he (Rodriguez) kind of cruised up, was waiting to
take a shot and I was like, `Man he's got to be almost out of
time.' Then he takes another touch and pushes it 4 or 5 yards wide
and then hits it in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea how they could say he got it off, but at the
same time, this is why I hate the shootout.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy's Paul Caligiuri and Dallas' Oscar Pareja each scored
to keep the shootout alive, but when Danny Pena missed his attempt,
Graziani scored the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, who jumped on the team bus to look at a replay of
Rodriguez's goal, came back with a disgusted look.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it was wrong when it first happened,'' said Perez.
``We tried to protest it then, but the referees wanted to hear
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I timed it four times and at best, it took him 5.2 seconds to
get off that shot. This is the reason the shootout is a hideous way
to decide a game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy had 48 hours to file a formal protest, but Galaxy GM
Sergio Del Prado said the Galaxy will not pay the $2,500 fee _
partly because the MLS ruled the play a judgment call, which is
basically not subject to a protest.
</P>
<P>
   __ Columbus 5, D.C. United 1: The Eastern Conference series is
also even after Stern John scored three times and the Crew snapped
a six-game losing streak to visiting United. The series finale is
Saturday at RFK Stadium in Washington D.C., where United has won
all 12 meetings against the Crew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
