<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2299 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     11-08 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ROBERTSON-COLUMN </SLUG>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
HERE we go again.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the two States, Florida and Penn, had stayed safely
unbeaten, the situation shaped up nicely. Because they at least
seemed to be clear-cut Nos. 1 and 2 in all the land, no matter how
much squawking might have emanated from the plains of Kansas, the
Virginia piedmont or the piney backwoods of Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   The Nittany Lions vs. the Seminoles made for a perfect
heavyweight championship bout in the Nokia Sugar Bowl. North vs.
South. Old-guard conservatism vs. the glitz of the nouveau riche.
Joe Pa vs. Bobby B., two titans of their profession, each with a
different way to skin the proverbial cat.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been a dream matchup. So clean. So neat. So tidy.
So symmetrical.
</P>
<P>
   Now, so dead.
</P>
<P>
   Since Penn State (9-1) failed to beat Minnesota on Saturday,
succumbing in maddening fashion on a last-second field goal, it's
all potentially one big, ugly mess again. Perhaps the biggest mess
ever, what with four major-conference teams still undefeated
entering the season's homestretch and a slew of others lurking in
the underbrush with just one defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Nebraska (8-1) might knock Kansas State (9-0) from its
pristine perch in the Big 12 this weekend, and you must assume
either Florida (8-1) or Tennessee (7-1) will put a quick end to 8-0
Mississippi State's pipe dream in the SEC Championship Game, if
Alabama or Mississippi doesn't bring an abrupt end to Jackie
Sherrill's run first. Fine. Then what?
</P>
<P>
   Do we send the Virginia Tech Hokies, currently 8-0, to New
Orleans arbitrarily, dismissing the protests of perhaps more worthy
teams with one loss? Does anyone honestly believe these pokey
winners over West Virginia on Saturday _ they, too, required a
field goal at the final gun _ are clearly superior to, or more
deserving than, the Vols or Nittany Lions simply on the basis of
record?
</P>
<P>
   And suppose Miami's Hurricanes do the Hokey Pokey on the
Techsters' helmets, whisking them from the ranks of the undefeated
as well. Of course it could happen. Then we might have Florida
State and a number of arguably worthy Superdome opponents for the
Seminoles, each carrying the baggage of but a single defeat, to
choose from. Wouldn't that be a laugh riot?
</P>
<P>
   Also, lest I forget, who has the temerity, or audacity, to tell
an undefeated Marshall team, owner of the nation's longest active
Division I-A winning streak at 13 games, that it doesn't have a
right to step up and also take its shot?
</P>
<P>
   Stop me if you've heard this before, but this is no way to
determine college football's national champion. The Bowl
Championship Series remains a scam and a sham. In the quest to
identify the No. 1 team, it makes no more sense than flipping
coins, drawing straws or plucking random names from a hat.
</P>
<P>
   No ``system'' that works only by sheer accident is defendable.
Hey, we're smart, people. We can do better. We won't, of course,
any time soon because self-interests and hidebound thinking persist
in the name of tradition, but we can.
</P>
<P>
   Might I explain how again?
</P>
<P>
   The logistics of football and its season, bracketed as it must
be into the fall semester at most universities, places limitations
on the size of the playoff bracket. A 32-team draw, while
desirable, would be impractical without major overhauls in
scheduling. Sixteen, however, is a workable number and would allow
for the inclusion of anyone with a remotely reasonable chance of
actually winning a national championship.
</P>
<P>
   You launch the party on the first weekend in December, including
both the Big 12 and SEC championship games among the eight
matchups. As it now stands, the losers of these games would never
be considered for the BCS biggie anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the normal Christmas break would ensue, with the Elite
Eight subsequently pairing off in the four current BCS bowls around
the New Year, replete with all the normal trappings (parades,
parties, etc.). The first-round losers would, meanwhile, have
returned to the pool from which the other bowls select their teams.
</P>
<P>
   College football's final four would follow seven to 10 days
later, depending on the calendar, with the title game always held
during the off weekend before the Super Bowl. Most schools don't
resume classes until late January anyway, so the disruption to the
academic calendar would be minimal, as if anyone at the
participating institutions other than the egghead professors would
raise a peep of protest.
</P>
<P>
   Where to play the three extra games? Rotate them among the same
four BCS sites. Whatever complications result figure to be more
than offset by the windfall dimensions of the additional revenues,
which could be shared equally among all Division I-A members for
non-sports purposes.
</P>
<P>
   And the end result would be fully validated. The only place you
should be able to claim a championship is on the playing field.
That seems such a simple concept to grasp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 0051EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
