<HEADER>
A2300 &Cx1f; tth-z
r s BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      11-08 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALLOWAY'S RIGHT ABOUT ONE THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Now that a court agrees with the Justice Department
that Microsoft is more crooked than a road in the Alps, maybe Joey
Stayaway is smarter than he appeared during his moronic holdout.
</P>
<P>
   He wants to get back to town while Paul Allen's checks still can
be cashed.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Seahawks owner's wad is mostly in Microsoft stock,
Stayaway might have deduced that the busting of Bill Gates' chops
Friday meant that the stock price would plunge.
</P>
<P>
   A foolish assumption, of course. But Stayaway has made so many
foolish assumptions that his business logic has to be considered as
soft as his game.
</P>
<P>
   He assumed he was the best wide receiver in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   He assumed he had leverage.
</P>
<P>
   He assumed that Mike Holmgren would cave during negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   He assumed that the Seahawks couldn't thrive without him.
</P>
<P>
   He assumed his agent knew what he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong, on all counts. Just like Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   He may have also assumed he would be welcomed back. On that
count, he is correct, presuming he rejoins the team Monday as he
has indicated. His teammates will embrace him, because he may the
finishing touch on an entirely unexpected surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll welcome him back with open arms,'' Cortez Kennedy said.
``He made a business decision that we wish he didn't, but nobody
will hold it against him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he is buying dinner. For all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   And the fans will embrace him too. Oh, they'll offer up the
ritual perfunctory boos on his initial appearances, but as soon as
he hauls in a touchdown pass or returns a punt all the way, it will
be kissyface just like old times.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the immediate and eventual hugs, Stayaway has thrown
away half a season and its salary, plus $210,000 in fines. Perhaps
more importantly, he has lost the trust of his mates in a team
sport where self-sacrifice is cherished ``He's not a guy that many
players will go out of their way for,'' said one in the Seahawks'
camp. ``Players will lay down their bodies for some guys. He's not
one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren described Stayaway's persona another way in his
post-game news conference.
</P>
<P>
   The coach/GM talked about Stayaway's potential return _
nothing's confirmed, he cautioned _ by saying there were a number
of logistical matters to be dealt with. Such as?
</P>
<P>
   ``Making sure his helmet fits,'' he said. As the chuckles grew,
he worked up a mock anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now some of you took that the wrong way,'' he said. ``Shame on
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Stayaway's ego will require a high-tech containment field if
he's to be more asset than liability. Fortunately for the Seahawks,
that problem will become apparent only in bad times.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, times are better than they've been in a decade here.
At a division-leading 6-2, after slapping the woeful Cincinnati
Bengals 37-20 Sunday in the Kingdome _ perhaps the most tedious
victory in club history _ some will argue that the Seahawks have no
need for the world's greatest flag football player.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is tackle football, a style Stayaway has only
reluctantly accepted.
</P>
<P>
   But the Seahawks do need him.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the offense has come this far, with a young
quarterback, damaged offensive line and a patchy, slow receiver
group, all under a new system, is remarkable _ and hard to believe.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the success is owed to an NFL whose mediocrity spans the
fruited plain. The Bengals, for example, with 16 penalties for 107
yards, apparently know less about the NFL rules than George W. Bush
knows about foreign leaders.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the success is due to Seahawks defense and special
teams, which Sunday set up the offense at the Cincy 30-yard line
twice, each time producing a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, however, the Seahawks will run into a quality,
balanced team that will have some answers, even if it may not
happen until the playoffs. It's altogether reasonable to expect
that defenses in the second half will smarten up on the Seahawks
offense, particularly with six AFC West matches among the final
eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Stayaway has something no Seahawks receiver brings to the game _
speed that warps defensive game plans.
</P>
<P>
   The Bengals flashed that weapon in Seahawks faces when receiver
Carl Pickens ran a simple fly route past Willie Williams for a
75-yard touchdown bomb, the Bengals' only meaningful score.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks have a passel of respectable receivers, but no Road
Runner to ripple the Kingdome rug.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to add another dimension,'' said receiver Mike
Pritchard, one whose catches may decline with Galloway's return.
``A lot of people will welcome him.''
</P>
<P>
   It may take him weeks to get his conditioning and timing, but it
looks more and more as if the Seahawks will tack on a week or two
onto the end of the regular season. And those are the games where
difference-makers become game-breakers.
</P>
<P>
   The man walked out on his teammates and a valid contract. But in
the NFL there is little time for or interest in moral dilemmas.
Joey Stayaway soon will be Joey Galloway again, and it doesn't
matter that he lost his fight and looked like a fool.
</P>
<P>
   It's scoreboard, baby. Leave the talk of virtue and honor at the
church door.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
