<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
GEEZ, at the rate they're going, it will probably take those
babbling heads at ESPN until the start of the new millennium to
count down their list of the 20th century's 50 greatest athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Who has time for that when you're making New Year's Eve plans?
</P>
<P>
   So in the interest of saving time _ and not getting into the
debate of whether Secretariat and Dennis Rodman should be
considered in the same category as humans _ we're here to give you
the top 30 Texas pro athletes of the '90s. Each must have some kind
of Texas background in individual sports or play for a Texas team.
</P>
<P>
   30. Sam Cassell _ Sure, we have a sweet spot for Smilin' Sammy,
the Fresh Prince of Clutch City. But why not?
</P>
<P>
   29. Billy Wagner _ Guarantees: death, taxes and Wagner in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   28. Ray Childress _ Made four trips to the Pro Bowl and was a
quiet pillar of strength for the Oilers' defense even through Jerry
Glanville's cartoon reign.
</P>
<P>
   27. Jason Kidd _ A baby who was thrown out with the bath water
in one of the Mavericks' many purges.
</P>
<P>
   26. Warren Moon _ Yes, we remember all the playoff failure. But
the numbers say he'll merit Hall of Fame consideration _ if he ever
retires and becomes eligible.
</P>
<P>
   25. Joe Nieuwendyk _ Conn Smythe Trophy winner was instrumental
in bringing the Stanley Cup into the heart of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   24. Charles Barkley _ Justifiably named one of the top 50 NBA
players of all time, he's produced the numbers in his first three
seasons with the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   23. Larry Allen _ Protects Troy Aikman and clears holes for
Emmitt Smith on his way to a bronze bust in Canton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   22. Charles Haley _ Not one you'd invite to the house for a
barbecue, but he jumped from the 49ers and anchored the Cowboys'
defense through a pair of Super Bowl runs.
</P>
<P>
   21. Payne Stewart _ Former SMU Pony was a two-time U.S. Open
champ before tragedy took him.
</P>
<P>
   20. Michael Irvin _ ``Do you know who I am?'' In or out of a
motel room, you had to notice what he did.
</P>
<P>
   19. Sheryl Swoopes _ Women's Player of the Year and MVP of the
Final Four at Texas Tech, she is half the reason the Comets have
forged a WNBA dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   18. Cynthia Cooper _ The top half of the Comets' one-two punch
has all of the trophies and honors, but more important, the drive
to compete and will to win that make her a female Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   17. Bruce Matthews _ If there was a reason to keep the Oilers in
Houston, he was it. Named seven times to the Pro Bowl, he could
well be the greatest offensive lineman of all time. Still going
strong in Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   16. Deion Sanders _ The Rev. Do-Rag has had more different
stripes than a herd of zebras but is the best at what he does.
</P>
<P>
   15. Clyde Drexler _ Didn't return home until the end of his
career but did it with a championship flourish. If only the Rockets
had drafted him in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   14. Nolan Ryan _ Was still throwing no-hitters in his fourth
major-league decade and became a deserving first-ballot Hall of
Famer.
</P>
<P>
   13. Ivan Rodriguez _ An All-Star performer at the plate and
behind it. Add in his stamina, and he's putting together a Hall of
Fame resume.
</P>
<P>
   12. Craig Biggio _ An All-Star catcher who became an All-Star
second baseman in a heartbeat and still plays with the joy and
intensity of a Little Leaguer. This is how you play the game.
</P>
<P>
   11. Tim Duncan _ He gets to lead the second 10 because we're
assuming he'll be at the top of the list for the next decade. In
one year won a title and became the best player in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   10. Jeff Bagwell _ Intense, sometimes brooding slugger whose
numbers have been held down by the Astrodome. Underrated for his
glove work at first base.
</P>
<P>
   9. Mike Modano _ The star of the Stars, who rose to the occasion
to win the Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   8. Juan Gonzalez _ Gone now, but not before winning two MVP
awards for the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   7. Lance Armstrong _ Beat the world's best cyclists and cancer.
Enough said.
</P>
<P>
   6. David Robinson _ An officer, a gentleman and now a champion
who was finally rewarded.
</P>
<P>
   5. Emmitt Smith _ Keep writing him off, and he keeps moving
toward the top of the NFL career rushing list.
</P>
<P>
   4. Michael Johnson _ The running machine finally got Butch
Reynolds' 400 record this year.
</P>
<P>
   3. Carl Lewis _ His prime was a decade earlier, but his Olympic
longevity through the '90s was astounding.
</P>
<P>
   2. Troy Aikman _ Not flashy, not fancy. Just the engine who
drove the Super Bowl machine.
</P>
<P>
   1. Hakeem Olajuwon _ MVP and two-time champ who Wilt and Russell
said was both a throwback and next-generation center at the same
time. The Dream. The best.
</P>
</TEXT>
