<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-BENGALS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG VICTORY LEAVES SEAHAWKS ALONE ATOP AFC WEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The last thing the Seahawks wanted to do Sunday was
play the Cincinnati Bengals.
</P>
<P>
   Six days after an emotionally and physically draining victory
over the Green Bay Packers at Lambeau Field. Amidst rumors and
reports that leading receiver Joey Galloway will rejoin the team
this morning. On a day when everyone expected them to handle a
Bengals team that was 1-7 and had been outscored 72-20 in its past
two games.
</P>
<P>
   All the ingredients were there for a letdown.
</P>
<P>
   But not an upset. The Seahawks stormed to a 31-10 first-half
lead in the Kingdome and coasted to a 37-20 victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough week,'' Seahawks guard Brian Habib said. ``It
is very difficult to come back after a huge win on Monday night and
be as sharp as you were that game. Emotionally, physically, it's
very difficult. You've got one less day to prepare. You've got one
less day to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's bound to be some dead spots,'' he said. ``But we were
lucky we came out like we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Because they were able to overcome all those potential stumbling
points, the Seahawks are 6-2 and in sole possession of first place
in the AFC West after the Kansas City Chiefs lost to the
Indianapolis Colts earlier in the day, 25-17.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks in first place? This late in the season? It hasn't
happened since 1988, when they captured their only division
championship on the final day of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's weird, I'm just glad that it's
happening,'' said wide receiver Mike Pritchard, who contributed a
falling catch of a 20-yard touchdown pass from Jon Kitna. ``I think
that we realize it's only the half-way point and we don't want to
collapse. So we're going to go everything we can to keep it
rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   The real test is yet to come. Six of the Seahawks' remaining
eight games are against division opponents, starting with next
week's nationally televised game against the Denver Broncos in the
Kingdome.
</P>
<P>
   In a season that has been a series of small, albeit progressive,
steps, the Seahawks' effort Sunday was a giant leap in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   The offense scored more points in the first half (28) than it
had in six of the first seven games. The defense continued to give
up too many yards (397), but also continued to make big plays that
counted even more _ and did it despite losing Pro Bowl defensive
end Michael Sinclair and disruptive defensive tackle Sam Adams to
injuries in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, they beat a bad team badly. The Bengals had more
yards in penalties (107) than they did rushing (103).
</P>
<P>
   ``We did only what we can do,'' said Cincinnati running back
Corey Dillon, who played at Franklin High School and the University
of Washington before being the Bengals' second-round draft choice
in 1997. ``I think everyone fought to the end, and that is all we
can ask of each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Again, it wasn't enough as the Bengals slipped to 1-8.
</P>
<P>
   This was not Kitna's best day, either. After being named AFC
offensive player of the month last Thursday, he threw two
interceptions _ as many as he had in the first seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight I was just fighting myself. I didn't feel on all
night,'' Kitna said. ``There weren't a lot of balls I threw that
went where I wanted them to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitna got ample help _ especially from running back Ricky
Watters, who ran for a season-high 133 yards and scored the team's
first rushing touchdown of the season. Derrick Mayes added five
receptions for 61 yards, including a 10-yard touchdown pass that he
controlled with his left hand before tumbling into the back of the
end zone.
</P>
<P>
   But Kitna's effort wasn't as bad as he made it sound. He was 14
of 24 for 202 yards, including touchdown passes to Watters, Mayes
and Pritchard. And the offense scored four touchdowns for the first
time this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Jon played pretty well,'' Seahawks coach Mike Holmgren
said. ``He has set a very high standard for himself, which is good.
He did some really fine things today.''
</P>
<P>
   So did the defense, despite that glut of yards it surrendered to
the Bengals. The most-obvious oops-play was Jeff Blake's 75-yard
touchdown pass in the first quarter that threatened to scrape the
Kingdome ceiling before it settled into Carl Pickens' hands at the
Seattle 25-yard line. Blake also scored on a 1-yard run in the
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But in between, the Seahawks kept the Bengals between that rock
and a hard place that are their growing number of interceptions _
two more, added to their league-high total of 17 entering the game.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Anthony Simmons got to Blake on the third play of the
game, causing a fluttering pass that was picked off by defensive
tackle Cortez Kennedy to set up the Seahawks' first touchdown. In
the second quarter, Darrin Smith tipped a Blake pass in the end
zone and intercepted the carom to stop a Bengals' drive that had
reached the Seahawks' 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got some big plays on us,'' Smith said. ``We knew they
had big-play capability. We wanted to come out and play much better
than we did. We wanted to improve our stats defensively. We didn't
do that today.''
</P>
<P>
   But, once again, the defense made enough plays, and made them
when they were most needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take one game at a time, and we're going to get
Joey in and when he does come in, we're going to welcome him with a
hug,'' said Kennedy, looking ahead to today's expected return of
Galloway. ``We'll have the deep threat and we'll be ready to rock
and roll next week.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Clare Farnsworth can be reached at 206-448-8016
</P>
<P>
   or clarefarnsworth &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
