<SLUG> BC-FBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLMGREN'S HAWKS HOOKED ON WINNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Let's call Mike Holmgren a fisherman. Let's pretend
this is a Hemingway novel and Holmgren is the not-so-old man who's
in charge of the Seahawks.
</P>
<P>
   And let's say he uses a single-lure fishing reel.
</P>
<P>
   Every week, Holmgren lets out a little more of his line. The
more he feels his team's life, the surer he is they can handle the
task, and the more line he feeds them.
</P>
<P>
   And when absolutely necessary, he tugs the line in, scaling
back.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if the team is a giant marlin that's edgy and strong and
needs some room to move, and Holmgren _ patient, persistent,
perfectionist, paternalistic _ gives them just what they need. No
more. No less.
</P>
<P>
   At 6-2 and in sole possession of first place in the AFC West,
what do you say about the Seahawks? That Papa Holmgren deserves the
big-kahuna dollars Paul Allen pays him?
</P>
<P>
   Why bother asking?
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great about it,'' Holmgren said last night after the
Hawks dumped on a dismal Bengals team, 37-20, at the Kingdome,
where the final season might be a celebratory swan song for the ol'
concrete cave, where the Seahawks once did play big games in
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very competitive road ahead and now we hit a little
stretch where we play in our division. These games are vitally
important,'' Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   As the Seahawks emerge at the season's midway point as one of
only eight teams in the entire, parity-happy NFL with a record of
6-2 or better, they find themselves a member of the Elite Eight.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee, Miami, Jacksonville, St. Louis, Detroit, Buffalo,
Indianapolis and Seattle have taken the first half of the season
and separated themselves from the rest.
</P>
<P>
   The Hawks are light years these days from the free-falling, such
as Denver, San Francisco and Green Bay. They are more consistent
than the flawed, such as Minnesota, Oakland and Pittsburgh. They
are not injured like Atlanta, the Jets or Dallas. And, best of all,
they are no longer in the realm of the perennial losers _ too many
in the league to name.
</P>
<P>
   That is why you have to start to wonder. What's it going to feel
like, waking up in the new century with a Seahawks playoff game on
the calendar?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what. It's an exciting time right now. I'm glad
to be a part of it. I hope the city and everybody's proud. We just
have to keep it going,'' receiver Mike Pritchard said.
</P>
<P>
   As the Mariners reel with the trade-me request of Ken Griffey
Jr. As Boeing suffers. As Microsoft deflects judgment from the U.S.
Department of Justice _ the Hawks are rolling.
</P>
<P>
   And chances seem excellent that they will continue to roll _
considering the way the Hawks keep passing the weekly tests their
coach administers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the funnest game we've played,'' tight end Christian
Fauria said after the Hawks used four wide-outs for the first time
all season, opening up the offense and taking another step.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran for a lot of yards. We had guys making big-time
catches. This is the way football should be. Fun. It shouldn't be
like pulling teeth,'' Fauria said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're helping each other. It's not about personal
achievement,'' Fauria said.
</P>
<P>
   Holmgren said Sunday he won't do anything different in managing
this Seahawks team, now that it has established a winning identity.
</P>
<P>
   And indeed, the Hawks are suddenly different from years past.
They're more real, more of a threat, less likely to blow themselves
up somewhere in the next eight weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He expects us to be perfect,'' cornerback Willie Williams
said. ``We can't always be perfect. We know it. But he still
expects it.''
</P>
<P>
   What helps the Hawks achieve this lofty goal is the measured
approach Holmgren and his staff have used to implement the offense.
Slowly. A bit of line fed deliberately, patiently each week.
</P>
<P>
   In the elevator after last night's game, Holmgren's two
offensive coaches said it is too early to predict what will happen
in January.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, quarterbacks coach Mike Sheppard and offensive
coordinator Mike Sherman said their entire mind-set is about
preventing turnovers. They will open the offense up only as far as
it can go without producing fumbles and a rash of interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   The players understand this approach. They don't seem eager to
rush it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's more to come. We haven't played our best and
that's the scary part,'' Pritchard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first half (against Cincinnati), we're out there saying
we're disappointed that we only scored 28 points. Now, I don't
think that attitude's been here ever. So the coaches bring you a
positive attitude. They bring you confidence and the way we're
playing right now, we're just taking the steps. As long as we can
take the steps, we'll be satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   On ``Monday Night Football'' last week, the Seahawks had their
coming-out party. They arrived. They marked a turning point in
their long-embattled history by going into Lambeau Field and
knocking the stuffing out of the Packers.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, it came at the expense of Brett Favre, Holmgren's former
student who, without Holmgren there to reel him in, threw four
interceptions and lost two fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Favre's crumbling only served to further underscore the
cohesiveness and soundness of the Seahawks. But as big as last
week's defining moment was, Holmgren had the right words for his
team this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, coach Holmgren stressed that this game was bigger
than Monday night because of a possible letdown (after the big
win),'' Pritchard said. ``And if teams did what they did today,
since Kansas City (did lose) and San Diego (did lose), it puts us
in a great position right now.''
</P>
<P>
   We have not seen the best of Holmgren's Hawks yet. His
assistants say that might not even be in the cards this season. In
the meantime, what we have seen is good enough to get them a play
date in mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   Start spreading the news.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
