<HEADLINE>
HUSKIES TAKE MOMENT TO PARTY, BUT IT'S `BEHIND US' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TED MILLER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ What started out as a high-five turned into a
bear hug as University of Washington athletic director Barbara
Hedges greeted Huskies coach Rick Neuheisel on the grass of Arizona
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Then things got nutty.
</P>
<P>
   A wild celebration in the stadium's southwest corner followed
the Huskies' 33-25 victory over the Wildcats. The jubilant
purple-clad fans chanted Rose Bowl. The players stuck roses in
their mouths. The Huskies cheerleaders danced, and so did
Neuheisel. He even played a little air guitar.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Saturday's) game meant a lot,'' Hedges said. ``We are
thrilled with where we are right now. There's a great atmosphere
around this football program.''
</P>
<P>
   This nationally ranked football program, that is. The UW entered
The Associated Press poll at No. 23 Sunday, while it was tapped
22nd by the USA Today-ESPN poll.
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies improved to 6-3 overall and 5-1 in the Pac-10 and
moved one giant step closer to an unlikely conference championship
and Rose Bowl invitation. If the UW wins at UCLA on Saturday and
comes home to dispatch archrival Washington State on Nov. 20, the
Huskies are headed to Pasadena on Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a bad time to be a Husky. And that means it's not a bad
time to be Hedges, who is trying to wrap up the final year of a
five-year, $50 million fund-raising effort for the athletic
program.
</P>
<P>
   The UW has raised $40 million thus far for the massive
``Campaign for the Student-Athlete,'' which aims to complete $84
million in capital improvements to campus athletic facilities.
</P>
<P>
   A winning football team always helps.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people are feeling good about what you're doing, they
are, in my opinion, going to be more willing to contribute,'' said
Hedges, who expects to sew up the final $10 million by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Those checkbooks figure to come out if the UW reaches its first
Rose Bowl since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The good fortune this season wasn't expected. The Huskies were
picked to finish sixth in the conference during the preseason.
Neuheisel was a first-year coach and was expected to suffer through
growing pains with questionable talent on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Statistically, the success doesn't make much sense. The UW
offense is ranked fifth in the conference; its defense is ranked
eighth. Evidently those proverbial intangibles have been working
their magic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have try-hard guys who find ways to get it done and make
plays they need to make,'' Neuheisel said.
</P>
<P>
   The UW's trip to UCLA will be televised at 12:30 p.m. by ABC. It
will be the Huskies' third consecutive game on ABC and fifth this
season. That means an extra $1.5 million in the school's athletic
coffers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the work isn't done. If the UW loses either of its final
games, Stanford and Arizona State also have to lose if the Huskies
are going to win the conference outright. Oregon also remains in
the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't lose sight of how we got to where we are, which is by
scratching, clawing and biting _ doing whatever it takes to get it
done,'' a cautious Neuheisel said. ``We haven't all the sudden
become a sleek race car. We are still a jalopy that finds its way
to the finish line.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA, a national title contender last season, is riding a
three-game losing streak in which it has been outscored 105-14. The
Bruins, 3-6 overall, have lost five of their past six and are stuck
near the bottom of the conference standings with a 1-5 mark.
</P>
<P>
   The matchup also is a bit of a homecoming for Neuheisel, who
quarterbacked UCLA to a Rose Bowl championship in 1983. While
admitting some special memories likely will occur to him while he
paces the field Saturday, reminiscing wasn't a priority Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's way down the list in terms of what makes this game
important,'' Neuheisel said.
</P>
<P>
   What is important is the Huskies figure to be healthier this
weekend than they have been since losing to Arizona State a month
ago. Still, UCLA had a bye this weekend, which provided extra time
to deal with its own injury woes and to prepare for the UW.
</P>
<P>
   The post-game celebration was festive. But a little while later,
a team debriefing in the locker room made it clear that a dream
season has yet to be completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great moment for all associated with Washington
football,'' Neuheisel said of the post-Arizona party. ``It is
behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ted Miller can be reached at 206-448-8017
</P>
<P>
   or tedmiller &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
