<HEADLINE>
SONICS TAKE TO THE ROAD WITH CONFIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ You may tire of the constant references to last
season. After all, it was a throwaway campaign in many ways for the
Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sonics coach Paul Westphal has a photographic memory.
Those images of bobbing undefeated through the first week are
vivid. The difference is that group somehow won while playing ugly
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   This 3-0 Sonics start has not been flawless, though their games
have gone as advertised. They are embarking on a rugged, five-game
road trip powered by an aggressive defense and an athletic flair on
offense that is pleasing and paying early dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Those ingredients have the Sonics packing plenty of confidence _
even if no one believes they are for real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys are probably unleashing a little frustration. You
know we've been getting pounded coast-to-coast about how bad we're
going to be, so they're enjoying that. I'll admit that,'' said
Westphal, whose team plays Philadelphia Monday night at the First
Union Center. The Sonics travel to Washington D.C., Cleveland,
Detroit and New Jersey before returning to KeyArena on Nov. 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very early,'' Westphal warned. ``We've only played three
games. But this team does have something.''
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the Sonics have some decent players, too.
</P>
<P>
   It still is a bit early in the season for the Sonics to have an
I-told-you-so attitude. But the wily, new veterans and audacious
no-names are proving they have game.
</P>
<P>
   Consider what has gone right and who is responsible:
</P>
<P>
   -- Vernon Maxwell is a bringing a pop-a-shot mentality off the
bench. His ability to knife through the lane for layups and his
long-range shooting have provided the Sonics with scoring punch.
That, plus Maxwell's quickness and anticipation on defense, changed
the complexion of games.
</P>
<P>
   -- When you say energy and aggressiveness, you are talking about
Ruben Patterson, the obscure second-year player who is solidifying
the small forward position. Patterson sets the tone at the start of
games with his tenacious defense and rebounding. His fearlessness
around the basket has the defensive specialist with supposedly no
jump shot averaging 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   -- Horace Grant and Brent Barry's statistics are not
eye-popping. However, both have been steady: Grant with his
rebounding, defense and midrange jumper; Barry with his
contributions on the glass, and his ability to take pressure off
Gary Payton and run the offense.
</P>
<P>
   -- The trapping, rotating defense has stymied opponents at
critical points to feed the offense. The most recent example was
the 99-94 Saturday win against Utah. Down by 17 points, the Sonics
held the Jazz to 15 points in the third to turn the game around.
</P>
<P>
   Those factors were consistent in a pair of wins against the L.A.
Clippers and Dallas. The Sonics were impressive against their first
quality opponent, Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just outworked us,'' Utah's John Stockton said. ``It's
just as simple as that. They outworked us and earned their way back
into it.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Sonics lose, it won't be because they lack hustle _
something often absent last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fast and we're quick,'' Patterson said. ``We get the
rebound, go up the floor, slam-dunk and have fun. We're going to
play hard every night.''
</P>
<P>
   It also has helped that Vin Baker has resembled his productive
self. He's off to a solid start _ rebounding and scoring with
authority. He's averaged 19.6 points, and more importantly, 10.3
rebounds a game.
</P>
<P>
   What's wrong?
</P>
<P>
   For the Sonics, it seems all good, though they haven't been
lulled into believing the season will be without bad times. Another
vivid memory from last season is how a 6-0 start quickly turned
into a dismal 25-25.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly what to expect from here on, but the Sonics
doubt things will ever get ugly. They aim to prove that on this
road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've just got to win on the road. It's important to win on
the road,'' Payton said. ``If we can get three or four wins and
establish something, then we'll be fine. We'll take care of
business at home.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Ronald Tillery can be reached at 206-448-8012
</P>
<P>
   or ronaldtillery &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
