<SLUG> BC-AUTO-JARRETT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DALE JARRETT ON NASCAR TITLE COURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By HOLLY CAIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ It's not that Dale Jarrett prefers suspenseful
endings. They just tend to work in his favor. Jarrett is known for
skillfully sizing up his competition, biding his time and then
calmly and purposefully making a clean, late-race move to the
front.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy has resulted in 22 NASCAR Winston Cup victories.
Now it appears to have landed him his first championship in stock
car racing's marquee series.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, 42, has challenged for the title the past three seasons
only to finish third, runner-up and third, respectively _
ultimately losing to hard-charging youngster Jeff Gordon twice and
wiley veteran Terry Labonte. Now, with two races remaining,
Jarrett's championship is the least suspenseful turn in his career.
</P>
<P>
   His sixth-place effort at Phoenix International Raceway Sunday
means he needs only to finish eighth Sunday at Homestead, Fla., to
give the Jarrett family its second-generation championship.
Jarrett's father, Ned, won the 1961 and '65 championships.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Jarrett's racing pedrigree and lifelong exposure to the
sport, his success has been a result of perseverance, not
privilege. Jarrett's father didn't wield his influence to help his
son start out with some big-budget race team. Jarrett spent many
years learning on the job driving cars with no legitimate shot at
winning races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to discourage him from racing because I knew the
sacrifices he'd have to make _ the peaks and the valleys _ and I
didn't want to have to watch my son go through it,'' said Ned
Jarrett, now a race commentator on television. ``We steered him
toward a pro golfing career and always thought he had the talent to
be on the PGA Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett is still a scratch golfer and was also an all-state
football and basketball player growing up in tiny Hickory, N.C. He
was 19 years old _ practically ancient by racing standards _ before
he began driving race cars competitively. Before that he worked for
his father's lumber company, worked the night shift at a printing
company, and even spent time selling vacuum cleaners. He didn't
arrive in the Winston Cup Series full time until 1987 at age 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wanted to do this, but it was a lot easier to
convince my dad to spend $400 and give me a set of golf clubs than
to convince someone to spend $10,000 and put me in a race car,''
said Jarrett, whose first Winston Cup win came at age 35.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Jeff Gordon started racing at age 4 and had
claimed three Winston Cup championships by the time he was 27. Ned
Jarrett was only 34 when he retired in 1966 with 50 wins. Dale
didn't even have a competitive ride, much less a victory, at the
same age his father had finished driving.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to fan support, the low-key Jarrett doesn't always
command the loudest cheers during prerace introductions. But you
get the feeling that everyone is pulling for Jarrett _ even those
loyal to his competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it can't be (Dale) Earnhardt, then we pull for Jarrett,''
said one fan attending Sunday's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a new breed of fans,'' said longtime Jarrett devotee
Gary Sommers, of San Diego. ``Dale doesn't go back as long as
Earnhardt and Gordon's fans are all young, women or band-wagoners.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I like about Dale is that he's still the same person as
when he started out, a real professional driver, calm and
confident. He just never really had a good car underneath him to
show what he could do until now.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Jarrett's arrival at the high-profile Robert Yates
Racing team in 1995 was a big boost to his career. The team already
had 27 victories _ 15 thanks to phenom Davey Allison, who was
killed in a helicopter crash in 1993. This team knew how to build
cars. Jarrett knew how to drive them.
</P>
<P>
   He's used finesse, smarts and poise to win races instead of
relying on instinct and raw aggression. His smooth style has
succeeded even in stock car racing's bumper-banging competition.
But that's not to say Jarrett shies away from door-to-door racing
with the likes of Gordon or seven-time champ Earnhardt, aptly
nicknamed ``The Intimidator'' for his assertive driving techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Both of Jarrett's Daytona 500 victories (1993 and '96) came by
holding off Earnhardt in dramatic final-lap fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patient is a good way to describe how I go about things,''
Jarrett said. ``I don't profess to have the talent of a Dale
Earnhardt or a Jeff Gordon. I have to think my way through things
and get my car working better to have a chance to get them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Athletes at every sport have people that perform at different
levels. Hopefully what I do gives a lot of people out there hope
that ambition, hard work and dedication pay off as much as
anything. You don't necessarily just have to have talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't mistake Jarrett's modesty for a lack of confidence,
however. He is sure of himself and his team, and eager to finally
land Yates his first championship in a decade of successful
seasons. People in the garage are taking note as well. Five of
Gordon's seven over-the-wall pit crew members will move to
Jarrett's car next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a son about to win the NASCAR Winston Cup championship
is exciting for a number of reasons, but mostly because I know
where he's come from and how hard he's worked to get to the top,''
Ned Jarrett said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ufednote &LR;
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter Holly Cain
</P>
<P>
   can be reached at 206-448-8015
</P>
<P>
   or hollycain &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
