<HEADLINE>
PICTURE BRIGHT FOR BENGALS' CURTIS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALIYA SAPERSTEIN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Bengals linebacker Canute Curtis and cornerback Ty
Howard went in to drag down the Seahawks' Ricky Watters as he ran
off the right guard for a seven-yard gain. The whistle blew and
Howard untangled himself from the pile. Watters' legs were pinned
under Curtis, who remained face down on the Kingdome turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could move all of his limbs and everything, but he was
holding his neck and he could hardly talk,'' Bengals linebacker
Takeo Spikes said. ``It's hard. It's a part of the game, but you
hate to see it happen to anybody. Not just one of your teammates,
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Play was stopped with 2:48 remaining in the third quarter, as
team doctors strapped Curtis onto a board and loaded him into a
waiting ambulance. He was taken to the hospital with an undiagnosed
cervical injury, though he reportedly had retained full motor and
sensory function. The injury apparently resulted when Curtis'
helmet slammed awkwardly into Watters' thigh pad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was real concerned,'' running back Corey Dillon said.
``Canute is a good friend of mine, and for him to go out like that,
to leave with neck injuries ... I'm just hoping that he can
function and that things are all right for him. My heart goes out
to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis, in his third year with Cincinnati as a reserve
linebacker, is the latest injury to plague the team. In a preseason
game against Detroit on Aug. 20, first-year free safety Kelvin
Moore suffered a neck fracture when he stumbled into the knee of
Lions receiver Brian Stablein. He has been on injured reserve ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   Though sidelined with less serious ailments, starting
cornerbacks Artrell Hawkins and Roosevelt Blackmon, as well as
defensive end Jevon Langford and quarterback Akili Smith, were
unable to play Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   So add Curtis to the Bengals' list of tribulations, which
includes speculation that head coach Bruce Coslet is headed for the
chopping block as the scapegoat for their 1-8 season. But while the
players have accused each other of not giving all their effort this
season, defensive end John Copeland said the Bengals couldn't
afford to use Curtis' injury as an excuse to not keep playing hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know they will not stop the game, and you know it can
happen to anyone at anytime,'' Copeland said. ``You can't think
about it, or you're beat already.''
</P>
<P>
   Down 31-13 when Curtis was taken off the field, the Bengals were
effectively beaten.
</P>
<P>
   The penalties that plagued Cincinnati early continued. The
Bengals committed four of their 16 penalties after Curtis' injury,
including a key offensive offside call on an onside kick attempt.
The Bengals also allowed the Seahawks to pad their lead with field
goals on two drives that ate up more than eight minutes in the
final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically we just killed ourselves. We didn't do the things we
needed to do,'' said Spikes, who had seven tackles and one
interception _ just before the Curtis injury. ``We got some bad
calls early, and we made stupid penalties out there all day. Once
you do that, you don't give yourself the chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense played well, but we put them in bad positions a
lot. You can't do that if you want to be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly disheartened by the loss, Copeland still came up with
something positive from the game: Though it was unknown whether
Curtis would return with the team to Ohio last night, he appeared
to have suffered no permanent damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a relief. It's just a relief,'' Copeland said. ``It could
have been a whole lot worse. That is one bright spot we can take
out of the game. Probably the only bright spot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 0107EST &QL; 
