<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-GALLOWAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALLOWAY RETURNS TO SEAHAWKS TODAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In the end, it had nothing to do with Joey Galloway's
current or future contract.
</P>
<P>
   Galloway, the Seahawks' leading receiver the past two seasons,
will end his 101-day holdout Monday morning because he misses
playing football.
</P>
<P>
   Despite premature reports and rumors that started late Friday,
Galloway did not decide to rejoin the club until Saturday night and
still was having second thoughts Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After the Seahawks' 37-20 victory over the Cincinnati Bengals at
the Kingdome Sunday, Galloway's coaches and most of his teammates
were taking a we'll-believe-it-when-we-see-him approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If and when I see him, I'll be very excited,'' coach Mike
Holmgren said.
</P>
<P>
   But friends and selected teammates said Galloway will be at the
team's headquarters today, when he and the club will send letters
to the NFL office asking that he be reinstated.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how Galloway might be received, joining a division-leading
club that has gone 6-2 without him, quarterback Jon Kitna offered
the most honest appraisal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are going good, we were 5-2, everybody has to say the
right things _ `We can win without him,' and all that,'' said
Kitna, who called Galloway late last week. ``But I wanted to let
him know that: `Hey, look, the guys here would love to have you
back. You want to come back, don't let that deter you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Galloway's return will be a distraction, if only because the
media will focus all the attention on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure it'll be a little bit of a distraction,'' Kitna said.
``But we're getting a new car if he comes in.''
</P>
<P>
   If he comes in? Galloway has struggled with this decision.
Saturday night, he told CBS SportsLine: ``People keep guessing
about what is coming down, but I'm the only person who really
knows. And even I don't know yet.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens now depends on what kind of shape Galloway is in.
He has been working out with Ohio State strength and conditioning
coach Dave Kennedy and playing flag football on Sundays with his
brother.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Seahawks placed Galloway on the reserve/did not
report list, they will receive a two-week roster exemption. It
would seem logical that Galloway might not be active for their
nationally televised game against the Denver Broncos on Sunday
night. But such a move might only increase the ill feelings that
have developed during his holdout, not to mention rob the offense
of the one element it has been lacking in his absence _ a deep
threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say how excited I am to have him back and I don't
think there should be any hard feelings,'' guard Pete Kendall said.
``Any time you can have a guy who's a game-breaker, and Galloway is
a bona fide game-breaker, you take 'em when you can get 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   Galloway also can expect to take some locker-room shots from his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure he'll get ribbed,'' Kendall said. ``I'm sure I'll rib
him.''
</P>
<P>
   So is Mike Pritchard, the leader of a wide receiver group that
has done better than just make do in Galloway's absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't come in thinking he's not going to feel some heat,''
Pritchard said through a smile. ``I'll have a little something to
welcome him back.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be perceived that Galloway caved, big-time. After all,
he opted to hold out rather than accept the team's seven-year, $35
million contract offer _ which has since been pulled from the
table.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Galloway will play for what's left of the $1.585
million he was scheduled to make in the fifth year of the five-year
deal he signed after being the club's first-round draft choice in
1995. He already has lost $837,117 by missing the first nine weeks
of the season. Another $210,000 will be deducted for the daily
$5,000 fines he incurred for missing training camp.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves $535,882, if Galloway is active for the remaining
eight games.
</P>
<P>
   By reporting at this time, Galloway will fulfill the final year
of his contract and become an unrestricted free agent in March. The
club undoubtedly will designate him its franchise player, meaning
they will have to tender him an offer that is an average of the top
10 players at his position _ somewhere between $3.5 million and
$4.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to earlier reports that this would devastate the team's
salary cap for next year, the club has factored in having to deal
with Galloway as a franchise player all along.
</P>
<P>
   But as club president Bob Whitsitt said after the game, those
are discussions for down the road. For now, getting Galloway back
on the field and back into an offense that has been productive
without him is the primary concern.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 0111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
