<HEADER>
A2313 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LA     11-08 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-KEISSER-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXCITING YEAR IN NFL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB KEISSER  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The National Football League has just moved past mid-season, and
anyone who's worried about the Super Bowl matchup is missing a
pretty intriguing season.
</P>
<P>
   After all, we all know good Super Bowls come around as
frequently as El Nino and his sister, La Nina. The 1999 season has
been riveting, in a 31-car freeway pileup sort of way. Games are
close. Games are being decided in the last minute. And the teams
winning games are not the teams one would normally expect.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: Three of the four teams that played in last
season's conference title games have essentially been eliminated
from playoff contention, and the fourth is .500. The chance exists
that the six NFC teams that made the 1998 postseason (Arizona,
Atlanta, Dallas, Green Bay, Minnesota, San Francisco) will all miss
it in 1999. It would be a first.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: All three teams currently leading NFC divisions
were sub-.500 teams last season -- St. Louis (4-12), Detroit
(5-11), Washington (6-10), and no one in their right mind thought
the Lions would do this without Barry Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: Of the six AFC teams with two losses or less, two
were 8-8 last year (Seattle, Tennessee), one was 3-13
(Indianapolis), a fourth is all of five years old (Jacksonville)
and another is winning despite its future Hall of Fame quarterback
(Miami) being injured.
</P>
<P>
   Consider this: 34 percent of all NFL games this season (43 of
127) have been decided by three points or less. More than half of
all games have been decided by a touchdown or less (65 of 127).
Five teams have had six or more of their games decided by seven
points or fewer.
</P>
<P>
   Even on a weekend that saw eight teams win by 14 points or more,
there were still two thrillers (Detroit-St. Louis, Chicago-Green
Bay), and three of the teams that won big were underdogs.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL will tell you that this is the definition of parity.
Critics will tell you that parity is synonomous with mediocrity,
and you can sell that issue. Commissioner Paul Tagliabue had one of
his many disingenuous moments this week when he used the Yankees'
25 World Series wins as contrast to the beauty of NFL parity,
conveniently forgetting the NFC's recent domination of the Super
Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But this season does have a different dynamic than in the past.
The NFL's worst kind of ``parity'' came in those years when an
unknown would pop up with a good season -- San Diego in 1994,
Atlanta last season, expansionists Carolina and Jacksonville in
1996. That wasn't parity, because you still had dynasty-like teams,
the 49ers, Cowboys, Packers or Broncos, standing tall at the end.
</P>
<P>
   That's no longer the case. I defy anyone to predict who will
make the Super Bowl, much less win it. I defy anyone to predict
which of the 11 AFC teams that are 4-4 or better will win one of
the six playoff berths, or if any NFC team will win more than ten
games.
</P>
<P>
   It is much easier to explain why things are crazy than
predicting what teams will survive:
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) The arms race: (end) The league has slowly been
morphing from an era of running backs to its current status as a
quarterback-driven league.
</P>
<P>
   But as defenses jam the box with bigger and more athletic
bodies, the need for a competent quarterback has increased, and
there simply aren't enough good ones. The 31 teams have started 50
different quarterbacks, and there are still eight weeks to play.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that a veritable unknown, St. Louis' Kurt Warner, who
the Rams didn't protect in the Browns expansion draft, can become a
sensation underscores the fraility of the position. Last season
presented a hint of things to come when the likes of Chris
Chandler, Vinny Testaverde and Randall Cunningham made it to the
Final Four. These guys wouldn't have been on anyone's short list.
</P>
<P>
   Things are even more extreme in 1999. The Vikings have turned to
their second retread in as many years, Jeff George. The Broncos
Sunday won with Chris Miller, playing his first game since 1995.
Three of the five quarterbacks selected in the first round of the
'99 draft have already started games this season. Two teams have
already started three different quarterbacks, Baltimore and the New
York Jets.
</P>
<P>
   That's a big influence on the season's lack of consistency. From
game to game, the starting quarterback is subject to change because
of injury of ineffectiveness. And even those teams with quality
quarterbacks aren't immune. Brett Favre and Troy Aikman may be Nos.
1 and 1-A, but their teams are on the bubble playoff-wise.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Shallow water: (end) The league has expanded by three
teams since 1995, creating more than 150 new jobs and spreading the
talent thinner. After watching the Browns of '99, can you imagine
what Houston of '02 is going to look like?
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Capology: (end) Little did some owners know there was
a downside to the salary cap. Teams that paid dearly to hold on to
franchise stars or sign free agents now find themselves strapped at
other positions.
</P>
<P>
   The demise of a few uberteams, like the 49ers, can be traced
directly to a misuse of funds that has gutted their secondary and
left them with few options when stars like Steve Young and Garrison
Hearst were injured. At one point this past offseason, the 49ers
found themselves $28 million over the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Injuries: (end) Besides Young and Hearst, there's
Denver's Terrell Davis and Shannon Sharpe, Atlanta's Jamal
Anderson, Arizona's Jake Plummer, Miami's Dan Marino, the Jets'
Testaverde. When you include retiree Sanders in this group, the top
four rushers of 1998 are all out of action.
</P>
<P>
   (set bold) Coaching insecurity: (end) More than a third of all
teams have changed coaches in the last two seasons (12), the kind
of insecurity that breeds conservative game plans and safe
decisions. That has a lot to do with so many close and low-scoring
games.
</P>
<P>
   But for every stinker like Bucs over Bears, 6-3, there seems to
be two games like Lions over the Rams, 31-27, and another comeback
win by Peyton Manning and the Colts. Maybe the Super Bowl will
stink once we get there. But until that time, it may be best to
enjoy the trip. It's never been wilder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 0128EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
