u s BC-FBN-LIONS-BOS &LR;      11-08 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LION-HEARTED TRIUMPH FOR DETROIT TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PONTIAC, Mich. _ From what I understand, I am supposed to be
ranting about the NFL. A froth is supposed to develop around my
mouth as I tell you how expansion, free agency, and softies from
both Generation X and Generation.Com have ruined the game. To
emphasize my point, I am supposed to strap on my authentic leather
helmet and tell you how the original Canton Bulldogs would have
crushed all of today's spoiled pretty boys.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I admit my diatribe skills were lacking before Sunday's
game at the Silverdome. Now they are nonexistent. The fashionable
thing to do these days is to bash the ``watered-down'' NFL. In some
cities _ Philadelphia, Cincinnati, Phoenix _ I don't blame people
for their football bitterness. But in Michigan, fans believe the
Lions can go to the Super Bowl and win it, Barry Sanders be damned.
There should be similar joy in New England, but that's a story for
another time.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Lions beat the St. Louis Rams, 31-27. It was one of
the most beautiful games I've seen, partly because of what athletes
did on a field and partly because of the stories they carried off
it.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect statistic of the day was that each team had the ball
for exactly 30 minutes. Quarterback Kurt Warner said he was honored
to be involved in the game and he was on the losing team. Lions
cornerback Bryant Westbrook, who was called for pass interference
three times, said, ``When I'm 50, I'll tell my kids, `Hey, your dad
was getting toasted all day but his teammates came through for him
at the end.' '' Former Patriot and current Lion Corwin Brown sat at
his locker and said, ``I love this. I don't even want to leave. You
know what? I'm going to call Chris Slade right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown got up and tried to reach the New England linebacker. He
got no answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gotta tell Chris about this,'' he said. ``And McGinest, too.
I gotta talk to Willie.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown would be wise to call collect. There is a lot to tell.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if a 305-pound backup center, Ryan Tucker, would be
the receiver of the winning touchdown. The 24-year-old Ram scored
on a tackle-eligible play. His 2-yard catch and Isaac Bruce's
subsequent 2-point conversion made it 27-24 with 2:42 remaining.
Thinking the game was won, Bruce went to the sideline and began
mocking the fans by waving his arms. The 73,224 people watching,
most of whom had been pleading for the Lions to win, were silent.
They started leaving their seats one minute later when Gus Frerotte
was sacked on third down, setting up fourth and 26.
</P>
<P>
   So that meant the Lions were going to have to overcome a
touchdown by a backup center by counting on the arm of their backup
quarterback (Charlie Batch hurt his finger). They did it. The Rams
were in a defense that they call a ``three-deep zone.'' If you
don't know football jargon, don't worry about it. On this
afternoon, three-deep zone simply meant ``bad coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Lions receiver Germane Crowell looked at what was before him and
ran a streak route. He caught a 57-yard pass. Six plays later,
Johnnie Morton was in the end zone with the ball, a 31-27 lead and
33 seconds remaining. Morton had been double- and triple-teamed all
day. And he dropped two passes. On his final catch, he saw single
coverage and easily caught the ball to finish off a nice, 12-yard
fade route.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it was a miracle, but we definitely saw a
bright light coming through the roof of the Silverdome,'' Lions
safety Ron Rice said.
</P>
<P>
   Really, both teams may have seen the light because neither was
expected to be 6-2 this morning. The Rams are led by Warner, who
says he is here because of his faith in God. His in-laws were
killed three years ago when their home was destroyed by an Arkansas
tornado. His adopted son was accidentally dropped as an infant and
suffered brain damage and partial blindness as a result of it. His
wife tells you how pleased she is to receive part of Warner's
``low'' $250,000 salary because, seven years ago, she was using
food stamps. Not long ago, the man who now leads the NFL with 24
touchdown passes was stocking convenience store shelves in Iowa for
$5.50 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   The Lions' story is not that dramatic. But they were dismissed
before the season began because Sanders, one of the top backs in
league history, abruptly retired. It was the typical breakup tale:
One party called the other a loser; one party asked for its money
back. If you look at the sorry 24 yards the Lions rushed for Sunday
_ 1.1 per carry _ you would conclude that the team misses Sanders.
The current Lions don't agree with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only speak for myself, obviously,'' said Rice, a Detroit
native, ``but I look at it like this: Last year, we were 5-11 with
Barry Sanders. And that's not good. That's terrible, actually. So I
knew we couldn't do much worse. I don't think Barry has any effect
on this team. None. He was probably at home watching the game. If
he's reading or listening, tell him I said hi. I wish him the
best.''
</P>
<P>
   A few feet away from Rice, Westbrook was sitting at his locker,
still in uniform. There was blood on his thigh pads. He sat and
smiled, saying over and over, ``Damn, I'm a happy boy.'' Brown said
he didn't want to leave because he wanted to ``enjoy the moment.''
How often do you hear people, in any profession, say that?
</P>
<P>
   The Rams had another chance after Morton's touchdown. By the
time they set up at their 23, there were 21 seconds remaining.
Warner's second pass was intercepted by Rice. The safety, who knows
all about the Lions' disappointing history, ran toward the
sideline. As he sprinted, he became emotional. He thought, ``I want
to give the ball to someone I love.'' He ran by his teammates,
searched the stands, and threw the ball to a fan he loves. It was
his father.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 0130EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
