u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-WALKER-BO     11-08 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-WALKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLENTY FOR WALKER TO DIGEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The meal lasted three hours. As Zelda Fitzgerald might
have said, it was a movable feast. At a table in the Cheesecake
Factory in Chestnut Hill, Bill Russell and Antoine Walker sat and
talked about many things: basketball, responsibility, history,
celebrity, and, at the end, the most important issue of all for the
privileged: Who gets the check?
</P>
<P>
   ``I had always wanted a multimillionaire to take me to lunch,''
Russell said. ``I wanted him to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   No one paid. When the meal was finished, the manager came over
and told the two that the meal was on the house. And after three
hours of brain picking, what did Walker take away from the meal?
</P>
<P>
   He laughed, and said, ``I know I have to go out and eat with him
more often.''
</P>
<P>
   It's still too early to know if Walker will need more such
repasts with Russell, or if he's ready to do what Russell thinks he
can and should do: mature into the leadership role that has been
crafted for him and take the team where it hasn't been in a while.
It's a challenge Walker understands and accepts, but he still can
use Russell's wisdom every now and then _ who couldn't? _ to be
reminded of how to get it done.
</P>
<P>
   While reluctant to be viewed as anything more than the voice of
experience or a shoulder to lean on, Russell did say he not only
thinks Walker knows what's in store, but has what it takes to make
the Celtics a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the key player in making this thing work,'' Russell
said. ``There are others who make important contributions, but he
is the key . . . He's a guy that can hold that team together as a
unit because of the nature of his talent. Rick (Pitino) has
confidence in him that he can do that. I do, too.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Russell who suggested the two sit down for a chat.
Basically, he looked into Walker's eyes and said, ``So you want to
be a basketball star? I can help you.'' Walker thinks of himself as
a basketball star. He's been to an All-Star Game. He's making $9
million a year. He's captain of a team that takes its captaincy
serious. He knows all this is insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   As Russell would say, ``So what? Where are the rings?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had a great career so far,'' Walker said. ``I'm looking
to get better. I've had individual glory. I just haven't had any
team glory. I'm trying to get to that point where I have team glory
on a consistent basis.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first two games of the year, Walker was the epitome of
the unselfish, team-oriented basketball that Russell played and
Pitino espouses. He played like a poised veteran leader. He avoided
stupid shots. He let the game come to him. He ended up with nifty
stats and the team won, convincingly.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two games, Walker has tended to revert to the bad
habits of the Stepford 'Toine. That's the one who's booed at home.
He had a single assist and three rebounds in 37 minutes in
Saturday's 115-108 loss at Indiana. He did have 21 points, but
needed 23 shots to get them, making nine.
</P>
<P>
   Walker has had too many games like that one in his previous
three years and not nearly enough of the kind he had against
Toronto, where he was 9 of 13 from the floor and had 22 points, 8
rebounds, and 3 assists. That has been Pitino's blessing and curse;
how to extract the 9-for-13s on a more consistent basis _ you know
they're there. It hasn't been for lack of trying.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat down with him and told him, `Antoine, you're no
different from me except you're a year ahead of me,' '' Pitino
said. ``If you're a true star, then make other people better, take
over the team, and get it to the playoffs. I think he's focused in
on all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been easy for Walker since he was anointed as the new
Chosen One when he came here in 1996. His first team lost 67 games.
He was seen as stat-conscious, selfish, immature, and, at times,
out of control. He was similarly seen as a rare package of enviable
skills which, if harnessed properly, could make him an annual
all-star. Few players at his height can do what he does.
</P>
<P>
   Pitino knows that and says he is trying to make Walker into the
best player he can, even if it does involve some very calculated
baiting by the coach, especially about Walker's weight. One year,
Pitino said Walker should go home and come back looking like Karl
Malone. The next year, Pitino said Walker should go home and come
back looking like Scottie Pippen. The two clashed recently over
what is the proper weight for Walker, who, by the way, thinks he's
fine the way he is, which is about 250.
</P>
<P>
   Russell essentially told Walker that if Pitino thought it best
for the team that he come back looking like Muggsy Bogues, then do
it. It won't always be what you'd like, but it may be for the best.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a responsibility you have to accept, besides just
playing,'' Russell said. ``Sometimes, there are sacrifices you have
to make that go against your strengths. If you understand that,
that those sacrifices are still positive in nature and will help
the team, that's what we talked about. How are you going to make
those sacrifices and put them in the framework of a team concept?''
</P>
<P>
   Russell has spoken about such sacrifices on a constant basis
since he came back to the flock. ``I do know a lot about basketball
and team play,'' he said. He tells the players he's in demand today
for autographs and speaking engagements not because of his Most
Valuable Player Awards (five), or his All-NBA appearances (11), or
his All-Star Game appearances (12). He's in demand because he won
11 titles.
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that some of what he said will rub off on Walker
and, by extension, the rest of the team. Pitino set the bar high
with his prediction that the Celtics will make the playoffs. Walker
thinks that's totally realistic and says he is prepared to do
whatever it takes. Chatting up a guy with all that history of
success can't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real good thing to have the opportunity to speak to
somebody like that on my own,'' Walker said. ``He shared some
stories and things he went through. That was interesting. I know
it's different now, but it's good to know what he went through.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having somebody like that who understands what you're going
through as a player is always good,'' he continued. ``We have a
better team now. I'm doing whatever it takes to help this team win.
I want to get into the playoffs. Obviously, I want to play well as
an individual. But I also want the team and organization to do
well.''
</P>
<P>
   If they do, Walker will be only too happy to pick up the check
at the next lunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
