<HEADLINE>
THREE'S A CROWD IN BRUINS NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Three may go into one neatly in math class, but right
now the equation is causing some extra calculating in the Bruins
net.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what we're going to do,'' said assistant general
manager Mike O'Connell. ``We really don't. What's messing this up
more than anything is the expansion draft.''
</P>
<P>
   June may seem more than an ice age away with not even
one-quarter of the NHL schedule burned off the calendar, but the
fates of Mssrs. Byron Dafoe, Rob Tallas, and John Grahame at the
moment remain tangentially connected to the June 23 expansion draft
in Calgary that will stock Columbus and Minnesota for 2000-2001.
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe, who only 10 days ago ended his holdout and signed a
three-year, $9.45 million contract, would appear the least affected
by the 24-square-foot logjam in the Boston net. It would be highly
unlikely that the Bruins would trade him now, because they well
know the agony and pain of not having a true No. 1 backstop to work
the majority of the 82-game regular-season schedule.
</P>
<P>
   But also don't believe for a moment that Dafoe is an
untouchable, for a number of reasons: 1) His salary is high, by
Boston standards; 2) The Bruins began to win while he was a
holdout, because of the good work of Tallas and especially Grahame
and; 3) Management has a history of finding ways to export those
who make a lot of money and talk a lot of talk (see Adam Oates of
601 F Street NW, Washington, D.C.).
</P>
<P>
   Dafoe could be dealt, especially if a bonafide front-line scorer
comes on the market. For example, what if the Phoenix Coyotes
suddenly wanted to live up to the rumors and wheel Jeremy Roenick?
Their No. 1 netminder, Nikolai Khabibulin, remains unsigned,
unwilling to work for the $3 million a year (that figure sound
familiar?) the Coyotes have been offering. Dafoe there, Roenick
here, and voila, suddenly the logjam is gone and the Bruins have
added the vibrant 29-year-old Roenick to their attack.
</P>
<P>
   For those still doing the math at home: Roenick is making $4.2
million this year and is due to make $5 million in 2000-2001, the
final year of the long-term pact he signed upon his trade to
Phoenix from Chicago. Roenick becomes an even more significant
acquisition if No. 1 center Jason Allison is going to be hindered
much of this season with what appears to be chronic wrist and
forearm injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, according to O'Connell, the Bruins have
received no feelers for either Grahame or Tallas in the wake of the
Dafoe signing. Boston boss Harry Sinden said there had been one
serious inquiry about Dafoe before his signing, but any talk came
to an end when Dafoe finally came to terms.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a Dafoe deal, what happens with the other two
netminders? Coach Pat Burns has stated clearly that he doesn't want
to keep three guys in gear all year. He also hasn't expressed any
urgency over the situation, but that could change in the short
stroke now that Dafoe, who backstopped the 4-2 win over the
Thrashers Saturday night, is on his feet, gaining strength and
taking his daily supplement of rubber pills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The easiest thing would be to send Grahame back to
Providence,'' said O'Connell after meeting with Grahame in the
press box Saturday night and discussing the situation. ``But that's
really not so easy, because, hey, the guy's been our best player so
far. You wonder about how that impacts him, and you wonder how the
team will take it _ what kind of message it sends.''
</P>
<P>
   Grahame has been clear about his lack of interest in starting
life over as a Baby Bruin in Providence. If the Bruins try to
demote Tallas via waivers, that's as good as giving him away,
because one of the other 27 NHL clubs will snatch him up in a
second _ if only to be able to expose him in the expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most viable scenario is a trade for Tallas. The
Bruins might be able to get a third- or fourth-line forward in
return _ potentially valuable help here for the next five-plus
months _ and then worry about making a trade to get a
draft-eligible goalie back before the March 14 trade deadline. For
that matter, it's possible they could trade Tallas now and
orchestrate a deal (wink, wink) to get him back before March 14.
Dafoe would remain the No. 1, backed by Grahame, and Tallas would
be back for the late-season finish and the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something we've had to address immediately,'' said
O'Connell, whose club finally nudged over .500 for the first time
this year Saturday. ``We wanted to see how Byron was when he got
back in there, and we'll see how he's feeling after this first
game. We'll do something, but just don't know what that is yet.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
