<SLUG> BC-RAC-BREEDERS' </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUP MUDDIES HORSE OF YEAR VOTING 
</HEADLINE>
 CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLANDALE, Fla. _ So, which one is Horse of the Year? Only in
racing could there be a championship that doesn't produce a
champion. What a fine mess Saturday's running of the Breeders' Cup
at Gulfstream Park has left the sport in.
</P>
<P>
   The top Eclipse Award was for handicap star Behrens to lose, and
he promptly lost it, finishing seventh as the 2-1 favorite in the
$4 million Classic after never having raised a hoof. Lemon Drop
Kid, who won the Belmont and the Travers, also failed, finishing
sixth. River Keen, who had taken the Woodward and Jockey Club Gold
Cup in succession, was another flop, checking in 11th. General
Challenge captured the Santa Anita Derby and the Pacific Classic,
but wound up 10th.
</P>
<P>
   With the more highly regarded Classic contenders all falling to
19-1 shot Cat Thief, outstanding 3-year-old filly Silverbulletday
would have had a strong chance to be Horse of the Year, but she was
a poor sixth at 8-5 in the Distaff. And 2-year-old filly Chilukki,
the only prominent horse to come into the Cup undefeated (6 for 6),
was outfinished by 32-1 chance Cash Run when second in the Juvenile
Fillies, tarnishing her record. What to do?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Breeders' Cup was supposed to be definitive, and show us
which way to go,'' said D. Wayne Lukas, who trains both Cat Thief
and Cash Run. ``The day turned it upside down; it didn't decide
anything. This is a popular vote. The voters are going to have to
sit down and try to get to the right decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Left standing after the dust cleared was Daylami, who was
brilliant in winning the Turf. This was Daylami's only race in the
United States this year, but a horse needs to run just once in
North America to be eligible for an Eclipse. Another serious
contender is Artax, who captured the Sprint in the brilliant time
of 1:07 4/5, tying a track record set by Mr. Prospector in 1973.
Artax finished the season by winning three in a row _ and, in May,
he broke Dr. Fager's record at Aqueduct by running 1:20 for 7
furlongs; then, in October, he broke Groovy's record by running 6
furlongs in 1:07 3/5 at Belmont.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful Pleasure was determined while authoring a
front-running victory in the Distaff, her third straight Grade I
tally. And, Soaring Softly was terrific, coming from ninth to win
the inaugural running of the Filly and Mare Turf. It was her second
Grade I in a row, following the Flower Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Observers also can go back in time and take a second look at
Charismatic, who won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness, but broke
down while running third in the Belmont in June, as his Triple
Crown bid fell short by a mere 16th of a mile.
</P>
<P>
   Some won't vote for a turf horse, especially one who has run
only a single eligible race, and that will hurt Daylami. Some won't
vote for a sprinter, figuring a sprinter is, by definition, a
failure because he cannot win at a distance, and that will hurt
Artax. And some won't vote for a female, simply because of gender,
and that will hurt Beautiful Pleasure and Soaring Softly.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the criteria for Horse of the Year?'' asked Donna Ward,
who is assistant trainer to her husband, John, who trains Beautiful
Pleasure. ``Do you get penalized for being female. I hope that
she's considered.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you beat records set by Dr. Fager and Groovy, and tie Mr.
Prospector, that's something,'' said Louis Albertrani, who trains
Artax. ``He does it pretty easy. Every race he gets better. The
word `bounce' isn't in his vocabulary. He continues to run hard,
and he's never missed an oat. He enjoys what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There were 101 horses on the Breeders' Cup card, and 27 wore
nasal strips, with three winning: Cash Run ($67), Anees ($62.60) in
the Juvenile, and Cat Thief ($41.20).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A 45-year-old man was killed Saturday when he apparently fell 40
feet from a catwalk situated above the rafters of the main viewing
stand at Gulfstream. Jonathan Lane, employed as a clocker at
Hialeah and Calder, was found by a member of the housekeeping staff
at 7 p.m., approximately two hours after the races concluded. The
Hallandale Beach Police are investigating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
