<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITE STYLES NET NY MARATHON WINS 
</HEADLINE>
 MARATHON-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joseph Chebet knew he needed to be patient. Adriana
Fernandez knew she dare not wait another moment. But while their
priceless blends of experience and intuition led them to react in
dramatically opposite ways Sunday, the results were identical:
victory in the 30th edition of the New York City Marathon, run in
comfortable temperatures and a bracing wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I am very much happy,'' said Chebet, the 29-year-old
Kenyan. It's no wonder: After finishing second to countryman John
Kagwe here the past two years, Chebet's win Sunday in 2 hours 9
minutes 14 seconds made him only the third man in history to score
a New York-Boston Marathon double in the same year, joining Alberto
Salazar (1982) and Bill Rodgers (1978 and 1979). Chebet will take
home $50,000 for the win and a $20,000 bonus for running under
2:10.
</P>
<P>
   In second place was the gutsy Domingos Castro of Portugal in
2:09:20, followed by Shem Kororia of Kenya (2:09:32), Giacomo Leone
of Italy (2:09:36), and Kagwe (2:09:39). Three-time Boston Marathon
winner Cosmas Ndeti did not finish.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, a 28-year-old from Mexico who also ended up second
here last year, earned a bit more by finishing in 2:25:06: $50,000
plus $25,000 for running sub 2:26. It was her first major marathon
win, and, despite wind gusts of 30 miles per hour, only 26 seconds
off the course record set by Lisa Ondieki in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without the wind, I probably could have broken the course
record,'' said Fernandez through an interpreter. ``At some places,
it almost stopped me.''
</P>
<P>
   For a while, it looked as if Franca Fiacconi of Italy might do
all the stopping: The aggressive defending champion, who loves to
run from the front and knew her best chance to win was to get away
early, took off with the gun and by the time she came off the
Verrazano Narrows Bridge after 2 miles had a 21-second lead. But
Fernandez wasn't about to concede that early, making up the gap
quickly in the next 2 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I let her go farther, she would gain confidence and maybe
win,'' said Fernandez. ``So I decided to catch up with her.''
</P>
<P>
   By Mile 6 in Brooklyn, it was already a two-woman race, with the
nearest challenger 38 seconds back. Fernandez and Fiacconi went
through the halfway point in Queens together at 1:13:03; by 15
miles, just before the Queensboro Bridge into Manhattan, the
Mexican had built a 12-second lead and never looked back on her
ailing rival, struggling with a painful right elbow (broken in an
August fall) and hurting left foot (injured metatarsal). With just
over 3 miles to go, Fernandez led by three minutes over Kenyan
Catherine Ndereba, who had pulled into second, and would easily
hang on to beat her by almost a minute and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Ndereba, who was sixth in Boston last April in her marathon
debut, finished in 2:27:34, while Germany's Katrin Dorre-Heinig,
bothered by the wind and her error in letting the others get away
early, was a disappointed third in 2:28:41. Fiacconi was fourth
(2:29:49).
</P>
<P>
   The men's race was much closer. A solid pack of perhaps a dozen
hit 13.1 miles in 1:04:24, and there were still eight men running
together when they turned off Central Park South back into the park
for the final half-mile.
</P>
<P>
   It was just after the turn that Leone broke things open;
although he failed at his attempt to surge, it opened the door for
Chebet, Castro, and Kagwe to take off. After Kagwe fell back, it
looked as if the still-swift 35-year-old Castro _ with 5,000-meter
speed that enabled him to challenge for a medal at the 1988 Seoul
Olympics _ might have the edge, but strength won out as Chebet
repeatedly fought him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was pushing, pushing, pushing,'' said Castro, whose twin
brother, Dionicio, finished 33d in 2:28:06. ``But I couldn't put
out Chebet.'' He was, nonetheless, all smiles in his No. 2 spot.
``Very happy, because before New York many people think Castro may
be dead, because I am old man.''
</P>
<P>
   Chebet, too, was pleased. ``Winning Boston and New York at the
same time is super wonderful to me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Top Americans were Dan Middleman of Raleigh, N.C. (26th in
2:24:52), and Kimberly Griffin of New York (12th in 2:48:29).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
