<HEADLINE>
TITANIC WIN FOR MIAMI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The odd concoction of football that is the Miami
Dolphins continues to brew, fermenting into one win after another.
</P>
<P>
   Defense and mistake-free quarterbacking again led the Dolphins
Sunday &UR;  &LR; night, Miami defeating the Tennessee not-so-Titans, 17-0,
before 74,109 at Pro Player Stadium, improving to 7-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, I felt we did what we had to do to win the
game,'' said Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson, the brewmaster of this
concoction. ``When you don't make mistakes on offense, and when you
play defense, you can win every game you play. I mean, every
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Titans quarterback Steve McNair entered the game leading a 6-1
team with intentions of making a statement that his team belonged
with Miami, the best of the NFL's best division, the AFC East.
Instead, McNair left having been shut out for the first time in his
pro or college careers, and said, ``You have to learn from these
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   It marked the Dolphins' best start since 1990 and allowed them
to maintain a one-game lead in the AFC East over the Patriots and
Colts. And, yes, Dan Marino once again was watching from the
sideline as Miami continued to build a special season.
</P>
<P>
   Damon Huard, despite aiming many of his passes, continued to be
a most able replacement for Marino as he mostly threw short passes.
Time and again Huard came up with the key pass on third down, as
the Titans shut down Miami's running game by playing eight men up
front.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say Damon isn't making mistakes, and he isn't,'' said
wide receiver Tony Martin. ``But people are missing that he is
coming up with the big pass when we need one for first downs.''
</P>
<P>
   The concoction is stirred into a stiff brew by a defense that
has not allowed a TD since New England scored on it three games
ago. Cornerback Sam Madison was the featured player Sunday &UR;  &LR; night,
picking off three McNair passes, two on identical plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a three-pick game,'' said jubilant teammate
Terrell Buckley. ``I mean, to see it live, a real three-pick
game.'' All the more satisfying, said Madison, ``because the last
few weeks I haven't been seeing many balls, but I got a lot of them
thrown my way and I made the most of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Eddie George came out running for the Titans, gaining 60 yards
in the first half, but Al Del Greco missed a 33-yard field goal in
the first quarter. Soon enough, Huard had thrown a 6-yard TD pass
to Stanley Pritchett early in the second quarter, then hit Martin
on a 43-yarder down the left seam for a 14-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Madison, not McNair, was sick to his stomach at halftime after
picking off two passes, and he was forced to sit out the early part
of the third period. Only two plays after his return, Madison
grabbed his third interception, saying ``I was in the zone.'' So
are the Dolphins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 0139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 01:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2320 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-TITANS-DOLPHINS-H     11-08 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TITANS-DOLPHINS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN McCLAIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ Now that every NFL team has reached the midway point of the
season, the state of Florida is playing the best football in the
country.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miami and Jacksonville are the only remaining 7-1 teams in the
NFL. Florida State is ranked No. 1 in college football.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins remained in the running for home-field advantage in
the AFC by defeating the Tennessee Titans 17-0 on Sunday night
before 74,109 at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins, who won their fifth consecutive game, won't have a
chance to settle the issue with Jacksonville unless they meet in
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only statement we made tonight is that we've been better
than seven of the teams we played,'' said Miami coach Jimmy
Johnson. ``Defensively, we did an excellent job of keeping a
talented team out of the end zone. Offensively, we did just what it
took to win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins played solid offense and suffocating defense before
a national television audience Sunday night. They toyed with the
Titans for a few minutes in the first quarter before taking control
and never letting Tennessee get within breathing distance.
</P>
<P>
   Miami's defense hasn't allowed a touchdown in 14 quarters and
the Dolphins haven't surrendered a rushing TD this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to know that you can have a bad game and score
seven points and still win with our defense,'' Dolphins receiver
Tony Martin said. ``That's a phenomenal feeling to have if you're
an offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Titans were trying to improve their record to 7-1 for the
first time since 1991 when they were the Houston Oilers. They
smelled a lot like the old Oilers by laying a rotten egg that stunk
up South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were where we wanted to be,'' Titans fullback Lorenzo Neal
said. ``You can't pray for rain and then complain about the mud. We
were in a perfect situation, and we let it slip away.''
</P>
<P>
   One week after returning from back surgery to spark an upset of
the St. Louis Rams, Titans quarterback Steve McNair played one of
his worst games as a pro. He was intercepted three times by
cornerback Sam Madison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little shocked,'' said Madison, who was forced to
leave the game for a few minutes because of an upset stomach. ``I
was a little dizzy, but I fought through it and came up with some
great plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been frustrating the last couple of weeks because I
hadn't been getting many balls thrown my way, but tonight I got a
lot thrown at me and I made the most of it. I was able to give our
offense some field position. It was like I could do anything I
wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   McNair's awful performance contributed to the team's first
shutout since 1989, when the Kansas City Chiefs defeated the Oilers
34-0. He completed 22 of 42 attempts for 205 yards. He was sacked
four times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a hard lesson,'' McNair said. ``That's the first time
I've ever played on a team that's been shut out, and that includes
pee-wee football. It's very frustrating. I take full
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we're 6-2 at the halfway point. If we go 6-2 over the
second half, I'll like our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Titans go 6-2 over the second half, they will finish 12-4
and tie the 1993 team for the best record in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimmy's plan succeeded,'' Tennessee coach Jeff Fisher said.
``He wanted to run the ball to keep it away from us, force some
turnovers to shorten the field and get up on us so they could do
different things with their defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's exactly what happened. We didn't get untracked
offensively. We let things slip away early when we moved the ball
and didn't score.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami, which generated only 237 yards of total offense, retained
its one-game lead in the AFC East over New England and
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The Titans were the second game of a murderous six-game stretch
in which the Dolphins play teams with nothing but winning records.
They beat Oakland and Tennessee, and now travel to Buffalo, host
New England, visit Dallas and host Indianapolis before getting the
Jets and Chargers in three of four games.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Damon Huard, who has replaced the injured Dan
Marino, won his third start in a row. Huard, an NFL Europe refugee,
badly outplayed McNair. Huard was 15-of-25 for 210 yards, threw two
touchdown passes and didn't suffer an interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came out in an eight-man front, and that left some guys
open down the field,'' Huard said. ``We're playing outstanding
defense, and our special teams are making plays. That means if we
(offense) don't do anything silly, we've got a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we'd like to make some more big plays and score a few
more touchdowns, but the object is to not turn it over and put the
defense in bad position.''
</P>
<P>
   Huard became the first Miami quarterback other than Marino to
win three consecutive games since David Woodley in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Huard's touchdown passes covered six yards to fullback Stanley
Pritchett and 43 yards to Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Olindo Mare added a 46-yard field goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
