<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BIG LOSS FOR PENN STATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ So you're Penn State this morning. Are you happy? Of
course not.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a possible unbeaten season, a berth in the Sugar
Bowl, and the chance to win the national championship, you now are
looking at the Rose Bowl _ if you beat Michigan and Michigan State
the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when you lose a game in November, as the
Nittany Lions did Saturday, 24-23, to Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   And if Penn State doesn't win its last two games, it might find
itself in the Citrus Bowl against someone like Mississippi State.
</P>
<P>
   So you're Tennessee this morning. Are you happy? Of course you
are. You're patting Smokey on the head, singing ``Rocky Top,'' and
you just know that things are going to work out so you can get back
to the Sugar Bowl, where you can defend your national championship.
</P>
<P>
   And the funny thing about it, you probably won't even have to
play in that silly elimination process called the SEC title game to
get there.
</P>
<P>
   By beating Notre Dame, 38-14, Saturday night, the Volunteers
improved their record to 7-1, winning their sixth straight game,
and jumped to third place in both polls, a heartbeat from getting
one of the two BCS championship game slots.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Vols must beat Arkansas, Kentucky, and Vanderbilt
the next three weeks, but things look very bright with Penn State
out of the picture, Virginia Tech looking very beatable entering
Saturday's Big East showdown with Miami, and Florida looking
vulnerable after barely beating Vanderbilt in the Swamp and facing
an even tougher challenge in two weeks against Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   So you're Virginia Tech this morning. Are you happy? You're
delirious because you survived what looked like a certain loss at
West Virginia. If you lost that one, you would have been Kansas
State a year ago, falling out of sight in the polls and out of the
national championship picture.
</P>
<P>
   But now you're worried. You've looked like a scared,
pressure-affected team the past few weeks, struggling against
Pittsburgh and needing a miracle play by quarterback Michael Vick
to set up a winning field goal against West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   What looked like a sure thing against Miami only a few weeks ago
now doesn't look certain at all, even though the game is in
Blacksburg.
</P>
<P>
   Not much is at stake. Just the reputation of the school, and of
the league, in the only chance you have had to play for the
national title.
</P>
<P>
   And even beating Miami may not guarantee anything, if Tennessee
keeps picking up votes and support.
</P>
<P>
   So you're Florida State this morning. Are you happy? Sure. You
didn't play, no one got hurt, no one got arrested, and you
strengthened your hold on the No. 1 ranking in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   You've got what should be a tuneup this week against Maryland
and then the showdown with Florida, but if the Gators have trouble
beating Vanderbilt at home, you have to like your chances when you
come to The Swamp Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Things, as they do each season, slowly are sorting themselves
out. We are down to a few weeks of games and the pretenders are
being thinned out.
</P>
<P>
   No playoff system in major college football? You've got to be
kidding. It's already started. It's one and done time. Lose a game
and it's see you later.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are bad seasons, and bad careers. Take the sorry plight of
Rutgers fourth-year junior wide receiver Walter King. King was part
of the carnage Saturday when Rutgers dropped to 0-9 with a 33-7
loss to Navy. That's bad enough. But King has been at Rutgers since
1996 and has a personal 23-game losing streak. He was on the team
when Rutgers lost the last three games of the 1996 season, was part
of Terry Shea's first 0-11 season in 1997, missed all of last
season with a back injury, and now comes this season, with games
against Syracuse and Miami remaining . . . Utah quarterback Darnell
Arceneaux remained in a Salt Lake City hospital with what was
described as ``a massive concussion'' sustained during a 43-29 loss
to Wyoming. Tests showed no permanent damage . . . SMU reportedly
is investigating a former football player's allegations that a
recruiter suggested he cheat on his college entrance exam.
Assistant coach Steve Malin agreed to pay $100 to have a stand-in
take the American College Testing exam for Corlin Donaldson in
1998, Donaldson alleges in Sunday's editions of The Dallas Morning
News.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Consider the race for the Heisman Trophy all but over.
Wisconsin's Ron Dayne rushed for 222 yards, including a 42-yard
touchdown, in the Badgers' 28-21 win over Purdue. With only Iowa
remaining, Dayne needs 99 yards to break Ricky Williams's
short-lived career NCAA rushing record. And with Purdue's Drew
Brees and Georgia Tech's Joe Hamilton both coming off losses, no
other legitimate candidate remains . . . Dayne didn't even top the
week's running back performances. Sacramento State's Charles
Roberts rushed for 409 yards and five touchdowns in a 41-20 win
over Idaho State, and Miami of Ohio's Travis Prentice rushed for a
school-record 376 yards in a 32-23 win over Akron . . . Watch out
for Alabama-Birmingham as a future power. The state is rich in
talent, and the Blazers have conference and school commitments to
build the program. That was evident in their 36-17 stunner over No.
18 East Carolina, the Blazers' first victory ever over a ranked
team.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Boston College, which is 25th in the coaches poll, moving up one
spot, had a week off. But the importance of Saturday's game against
West Virginia can't be overemphasized. A win would give the Eagles
seven victories, which should get them into either the Insight.Com
Bowl in Tucson or the Music City Bowl in Nashville. With Hawaii
winning Saturday, and with several Pac-10 and ACC teams also
becoming bowl eligible, any possibility of BC going to a bowl in
Hawaii appears dead. Also apparently gone is an at-large slot in
the Motor City Bowl against probable MAC champion Marshall. With
Minnesota's win, that bowl now has its pick of Big Ten teams to
fill the other slot . . . Nice to see Michigan State's defense
returning to action. After back-to-back losses to Purdue and
Wisconsin, the Spartans held Ohio State to 0 rushing yards in a
23-7 win. Michigan, which had allowed 100 points in its three
previous games, also found its defense in a 37-3 win over
Northwestern. But does that count? . . . Congratulations to Oregon
State and coach Dennis Erickson. By beating California, the Beavers
improved to 6-3, their first nonlosing regular season since 1970. A
bowl game, most likely in Hawaii, probably awaits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
