<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAVERICKS RUN AFOUL OF SHAQ, GET BUSTED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There it was, the Los Angeles Lakers just sort of
muddling along to a somewhat dull 105-97 victory against the lowly
Dallas Mavericks on Sunday, when Shaquille O'Neal learned nothing
is free.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Mavericks coach Don Nelson decided to attack the
Lakers' most glaring weakness _ O'Neal at the free-throw line.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson warned the officials that every time the Lakers inbounded
the ball, they were going to quickly foul O'Neal. And they did,
five consecutive times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, you can always count on Nellie to screw a game up,''
said bemused Lakers coach Phil Jackson. ``The guy is on the rules
committee. He finds more ways of bending the rules than Richard
Nixon did as president.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the night before, when the Trail Blazers had fouled
O'Neal hard under the basket and incurred his wrath _ and ultimate
ejection _ the Mavs gently fouled O'Neal before he could even
approach midcourt. O'Neal hit 5 of 10 free throws in the closing
minutes, including his last two, to somewhat foil Nelson's unique
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's shooting 35 percent from the line; it only makes sense,''
Nelson said. ``But the competitor he is, he made a pair. That's
part of the risk you take.
</P>
<P>
   ``We exchanged glances a couple of times, so that was fine. I
love the guy. We don't have an answer for him. His free-throw
shooting is about the only weakness he has.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal hit 10 of 23 free throws on the night and finished with a
game-high 30 points and 20 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting idea but in the end, not a particularly effective
strategy. The Lakers led 92-80 when Nelson began his unique
approach, and 99-89 when Jackson removed O'Neal with 3:16 to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a strategy Phil had,'' Nelson said. ``I was going to
continue on. If we could have just made a run, we would have had
some fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said he had used a similar approach when he coached the
Knicks and O'Neal was at Orlando, just not so blatantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was (baloney),'' O'Neal said. ``Nellie always
does that.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was not thrilled, but his anger was reserved for
Portland's Jermaine O'Neal, the Blazer who had inspired his two
technicals with hard fouls. O'Neal promised to retaliate against
Jermaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to get him back,'' O'Neal said. ``He knows that. I
promise you that.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson's late-game approach at least added some sparkle to what
had been a somewhat routine game before another lifeless Staples
Center crowd, this one of 18,068.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers led 52-45 at the half, pushed their lead to 15 points
at the end of the third quarter, and then scored six unanswered
points to take a 21-point lead. The Mavs, getting a hot hand from
Dirk Nowitzki (20 points), pulled within 10 before Nelson started
fouling O'Neal as soon as the ball was inbounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had plenty of attempts to practice his free-throw
shooting,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Glen Rice added 20 points and seven assists (his high as a
Laker). Michael Finley led the Mavericks with 29 points.
</P>
<P>
   A day after a disappointing loss in Portland, the Lakers came
back, showed more movement and took care of business. It was their
16th consecutive victory over the Mavs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of energy early,'' Rice said. ``We established we
were ready to play tonight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
