<P>
   MICROSOFT-STOCK (Undated) _ Microsoft has long been, in the
words of one analyst, ``an institutional investor's dream.'' Since
the company went public in March 1986, its market capitalization
has soared to $470 billion, making it the most highly valued
company in the world. But given the severity of Judge Thomas
Penfield Jackson's findings of fact on Friday, some analysts and
investors say that the future of Microsoft's stock suddenly seems
less rosy. By Sara Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-CONSUMERS (Undated) _ In its 18-month antitrust battle
against Microsoft, the government introduced mountains of e-mail,
documents and testimony from business partners and competitors to
show that the company had a monopoly in computer operating systems
and that it had illegally leveraged that position to muscle its way
into new markets. But proving that the software giant's tactics had
resulted in harm to consumers often seemed the hardest and most
elusive part of the case. Many software users see one of the
government's key complaints -- Microsoft's inclusion of a Web
browser with its Windows operating system -- as a boon. By Amy
Harmon.
</P>
