<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-WIZARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS CHANGE OFFENSE AND GAIN FIRST VICTORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Nets spoke about the new motion
offense they instituted on Saturday as if it were a magic potion,
as if the cutting and passing it demanded would cure all that has
afflicted them. And while the scheme did not help their heretofore
woeful perimeter shooting, it did enable them to burst into the
victory column with a much-needed 112-87 victory over the
Washington Wizards Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   With the type of balanced offense that evaded them over the
first three games, the Nets improved to 1-3 and eased the
burgeoning tension that was beginning to surround the team and
Coach Don Casey.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Johnny Newman came off the bench to lead all scorers
with 25 points and Keith Van Horn added 23 points and a career-high
18 rebounds. Kendall Gill followed with 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   Stephon Marbury, who entered the game averaging 30.3 points and
28.3 field-goal attempts a game, finished with just 10 points, his
lowest output as a Net since scoring 8 points against the Knicks on
April 11. Marbury, who shot 4 of 17 from the field, had a
season-high eight assists. Jamie Feick added 16 rebounds for the
Nets, who shot 42.7 percent from the field.
</P>
<P>
   The change in offensive strategy was evident immediately.
Instead of dominating the ball, Marbury often passed to Gill after
crossing halfcourt and cut through the defense toward the baseline.
With Gill running the offense from the top of the key and his
teammates picking and cutting beneath the foul line, the Nets were
fluid for one of the first times this season.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a balanced offense that saw four Nets take five
or more shots in the first quarter. Scott Burrell, a first-quarter
wonder who had scored more than 80 percent of his points in the
first 12 minutes of each game, canned two 3-pointers to lead the
attack with 9 points. Marbury took seven shots, making three and
scoring 8. With Gill and Van Horn combining for 10 more points, the
Nets raced to a 29-17 lead, their biggest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first three games, most of Marbury's highlights had
come on scoring moves, but four minutes into Sunday night's game,
he pulled off a spectacular assist that showed how dazzling a
playmaker he can be. Blowing by Rod Strickland, Marbury drew three
defenders in the middle of the paint before whipping a wraparound
pass to Feick, who was streaking in along the left baseline. Feick
received the pass in stride and finished with an uncontested dunk.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's humiliating loss to Toronto, Van Horn wondered
aloud about the Nets' lack of passion, noting the absence of
high-fives and screams after inspiring plays. In the second
quarter, the 6-foot-10-inch forward did his part to evoke some
emotion from his teammates. After swooping in from the left side to
catch and dunk a missed jumper by Lucious Harris, Van Horn came
down slowly and stared, then pointed at his injured teammate Jayson
Williams, who was sitting on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the play got Van Horn pumped because he went on
to grab nine rebounds in the second quarter. He would go on to tie
his career high of 16 at the 2-minute-12-second mark of the third
quarter. Feick added nine first-half rebounds to Van Horn's 12 to
help the Nets to a 28-22 advantage on the boards. The rebounding,
particularly the 11 on the offensive end, enabled the Nets to
overcome their 42.9 percent shooting and take a 53-46 lead into the
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   The momentum shifted briefly at the start of the third quarter
when Washington opened with 9 unanswered points and took a 55-53
lead on a 3-pointer by Strickland. But the Nets rallied for an 18-4
run that put them in control by the midway point of the quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
