<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 03:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2349 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-EPARTY-CAMPAIGN-SFCHR     11-08 1104
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPARTY-CAMPAIGN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MAJOR PARTIES SET THEIR SITES ON THE WEB  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With next year's presidential election fast approaching, the GOP
will fire the latest salvo tomorrow in the political war to
dominate the Internet and bring in millions of new voters and
contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Republican National Committee Chairman Jim Nicholson will
announce plans for ``GOPnet.com,'' a two-year, $2 million project
described as ``the nation's first political portal.'' It is part of
an ambitious initiative called ``e-GOP'' that insiders say aims at
transforming the Grand Old Party into a full-fledged Internet
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The GOP mission over the next decade is to create the most
active, inclusive electronic party possible to communicate with the
emerging cyber-citzenry,'' said Nicholson, in San Francisco for a
visit last week.
</P>
<P>
   Among the lures he is planning for GOP Web subscribers:
television-quality, full-screen video on demand; personalized
calendar services; custom news delivery; instant polling; and the
ability to ``talk back'' to politicians _ even during live news
events.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore its attempt to become a ``Web-driven
organization,'' party leaders plan to have GOPnet.com up and
running when the Republican National Committee holds its winter
meeting in San Jose in January, according to a GOP memo on the
project.
</P>
<P>
   And by the time Republicans meet for their national convention
in Philadelphia next August, the GOP aims for ``an established,
on-line community of 100,000 cyber-activists ... and 50,000
subscribers to GOPnet.com,'' the memo says.
</P>
<P>
   ``(This) is not your father's Republican Party,'' said the
committee's deputy chief of staff, Larry Purpuro, who said
Nicholson is now mulling plans to open an Palo Alto office for the
party's Silicon Valley interests. ``Al Gore may have invented the
Internet _ but Republicans are making it work.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats aren't far behind, racing to develop their own
``e-Party'' initiative, including an Internet portal, with the
fund-raising support and blessing of President Clinton, Democratic
National Committee Chairman Joe Andrew said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew claimed it was the Democrats, in 1996, who were the first
to fully  &LR; test the power of the Web in political organizing. He
says they have been aggressive ever since in expanding their
grassroots organizing to the Web; he cites Democratic wins across
the country in this month's elections as examples of that winning
strategy. ``In every single one of those victories, the Internet
played a significant role as an organizational tool,'' said Andrew.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans' priority is using the Internet as a
fund-raising tool ... to sign people up to get money,'' Andrew
said. ``Our goal is to use the Internet as a communications tool,
to provide more information to people, so they're more likely to
participate in elections and want to vote for a Democrat.''
</P>
<P>
   The fierce competition between Republicans and Democrats in the
development of political Internet outreach takes a direct cue from
corporate America _ where efforts to lure online customers have
long included perks like gifts, personalized shopping services,
customized calendars, e-mail alerts and interactive celebrity
chats.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, political parties ``seemed to be behind the
times,'' still heavily dependent on costly direct mail and media to
get out their message, notes  &LR; said Michael Senne, founder of
Pixelon Inc., a San Juan Capistrano-based tech  &LR; firm that has
worked on streaming video for the GOP Web site.
</P>
<P>
   But studies show that by the next presidential election, nearly
half of voting-age Americans are expected to hit the Internet for
political news _ and a whopping 70 percent will have Internet
access. That has prompted parties to seek cheaper, faster ways to
reach people, without relying on the often-critical eye of the news
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could signal a profound change in American politics,''
said Wade Randlett, vice president of San Francisco-based Red
Gorilla, an e-commerce firm, and a Democratic activist tapped to
assist the party's initiative. ``Instead of vent.com or whine.com,
we've got a place where you can (communicate) with the people who
are voting on the issues: guns, paying down the debt, education,
prescription drugs, anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Silicon Valley executives involved in the Republican project say
they are impressed with the GOP's sophisticated approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Republicans) understand the new millennium is going to be
about communication _ and the most effective communication will be
on the Web,'' said Tom Ku, president and chief executive of
Quaartz.com, a Santa Clara-based firm whose technology will give
voters customized calendar and news services. ``They've taken the
tremendous revolution in protocols and Web sites ... and used it to
increase the effectiveness of their message.''
</P>
<P>
   By offering innovations like ``television-quality, full-screen
video'' of a candidate speech or political debate at the click of a
mouse, Senne of Pixelon says the GOP will be able to attract
millions of curious voters. Better yet, a candidate can ``deliver
his themes, his platform points, his daily messages to the country,
to everyone who has an Internet connection _ without media
interpretation or mutilation.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, too, see the value of ``unfiltered'' broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, President Clinton and high-tech leaders like Marc
Andreessen will host an online town hall ``voice chat'' beginning
at 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The event _ in partnership with Redwood City-based Excite &LR; Home _
will allow anyone with Web access to pose questions to the
president by signing on to townhallmeeting.excite.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we're going into an election year, and the candidates
are dipping their toes into the Internet for political discourse,
there's a lot of interest picking up on the Web,'' said Fred Siegel
of Excite &LR; Home. ``People will take it much more seriously and be
more engaged than if we were doing it even a month ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Political observers say the potential for such  &LR; innovation is
enormous _ but bells and whistles alone won't make people
interested in voting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can build a site, but nobody will come _ unless you
provide them with something that will bring them back in,'' said
Leslie Goodman, a Republican political consultant and editor of
politicalaccess.com, a leading political Web site. ``It's not a
replacement or substitute for precinct-walking. ... Anybody who
thinks they can win an election on the Internet alone is missing a
huge slice of America.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 0333EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
