<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCRHON </SLUG>
  
 GET A TICKET, GO TO THE GYM  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The police must be reading the papers, seeing
the studies that show we're all getting fatter, expanding like the
universe, especially the yoot of America.
</P>
<P>
   Two S.F. cops in a squad car stop a young man on a bicycle, on
the cable car tracks on Powell just below Ellis. After a short
discussion, one cop tells the young man, ``If you get down and do
10 push-ups, I won't give you a ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   The young man does and the cop doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   If this is one of D.A. Terence Hallinan's diversion programs, I
support it. But I bet the rider could have plea-bargained down to
five jumping jacks and two minutes of community service, picking up
bowled-over pedestrians.
</P>
<P>
   TOM ``THE BODY'' Ammiano shocked the city by storming into a
mayoral runoff with Willie Brown despite a campaign that was
shorter than Brown's speeches and cheaper than his lunches.
</P>
<P>
   One theory is that Ammiano got a heavy sympathy vote because
he's a regular Muni rider, although ``regular Muni'' might be an
oxymoron.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano's surprise showing is being hailed as a populist
triumph, and not to be Ned Negative, but it  &UR; is  &LR; a gloomy Monday
morning, so a couple thoughts:
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the write-in vote isn't so much a testimony to Ammiano's
political incandescence as it is the answer to the question,
``Where's the outrage?''
</P>
<P>
   And: Brown and Ammiano promise to engage in noble and dignified
debate on real issues, no mudslinging. But remember that Clint
Reilly's poor showing in spite of the fortune he spent is
attributable in no small part to Jack Davis yanking an ugly
skeleton out of Reilly's closet.
</P>
<P>
   Willie probably won't attack Ammiano directly, but remember that
Jack the Ripper Davis is on Brown's payroll. Wait, that's wrong.
Davis isn't on Brown's payroll, he's on Home Depot's payroll.
Politics sure gets confusing.
</P>
<P>
   But as one insider says, ``Davis will tear Ammiano apart.''
While Brown keeps his distance, far above the flying mud.
</P>
<P>
   STEVE YOUNG and Sharon Stone were seen on the town over the
weekend. But not together. I just wanted to get your attention for
these celeb sightings:
</P>
<P>
   Young, the 49ers' sore-headed quarterback, dined at John's Grill
on Friday night with his fiancee and four friends. Steve chatted
with the house band, The Wee Three, told bassist Tony Saunders that
he (Young) plays guitar, right-handed.
</P>
<P>
   That's no big deal, unless John's announces that the upstairs
room is featuring the jazz of The Wee Four.
</P>
<P>
   Stone, S.F.'s hottest auctioneeress, presided over the Glide
Memorial charity auction Saturday night at the Marriottcq &LR; , reports
Cuffs Corbett, man-'bout-town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got five, do I hear five-and-a-half? Fiveandahalf, do I
hear six?'' Stone said, then interrupted herself. ``Hey, I'm a
blonde, but I can count.''
</P>
<P>
   And, hey, wasn't that TV legend Tom Brokaw jogging 'round the
lush grounds at Dinah's Garden Hotel in Palo Alto? No common
quarters for Brokaw, who R&AMP;R'd in the African Suite, which features
a coffee table made from the hand-carved bed of a Senfu tribal
chief. When they recycle in Palo Alto, they do not mess around.
</P>
<P>
   THE BULL played the late set at Bix one recent night, went home
and died in his sleep at 76.
</P>
<P>
   Wyatt Ruther was his name, and fellow jazz players say he put
down the beat like nobody, rock-steady and ocean-deep. ``He left
the high notes for the other bass players,'' says Benny Miller, who
plays sax in the Bix trio.
</P>
<P>
   The Bull played with Brubeck, Mulligan, Shearing, Basie _ stop
me if you hear a familiar name.
</P>
<P>
   The New Grove Dictionary of Jazz says, ``Ruther is known for his
firm tone and ebullient sense of swing.''
</P>
<P>
   What a great jazz-style legacy. Most of us will have to settle
for something like, ``He was known for his firm jowls and ebullient
sense of direction.''
</P>
<P>
   DISMANTLED: The Hooverville that sprang up along Fourth Street,
just across the Mission Creek Marina, is history.
</P>
<P>
   The scraggly quarter-mile roadside stretch of tents, cardboard
condos and assorted live-in vehicles was cleared away recently, a
couple hundred semi-homeless squatters shoo'd and scattered by
order of whoever's in charge of keeping the semi-homeless blowing
in the wind.
</P>
<P>
   TRAIN WRECK near Salinas late last week, and a Monterey TV news
show rounded up a sheriff's officer and a CHP officer at the scene.
Brief interview, then a break. The two officers assumed they were
off the air, but they were still live, with sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta get my serious face on,'' one cop said to the other. ``I
look OK? No boogers?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No boogers,'' said the other.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure what that word means, might be law-enforcement
slang for ``suspects'' or ``serious injuries.'' But I bet someone's
got a new nickname.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
