<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TEENAGERS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT TO MOM AND DAD IT'S A HARD LIFE (OR NOT) 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By TAMAR LEWIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Money doesn't buy happiness _ and among teen-agers, it may
actually make life feel harder.
</P>
<P>
   In a New York Times/CBS News Poll last month, 1,038 young people
aged 13 to 17 were asked to compare their lives with what their
parents experienced growing up. Overall, 43 percent said they were
having a harder time, 33 percent said they were having an easier
time and 23 percent said it was about the same. At the same time,
there was a divide along economic lines, with the upper-income
children saying they were feeling more burdened.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the affluent teen-agers, whatever their race or gender,
were substantially more likely than those from more modest homes to
report that their lives were harder and subject to more stress:
Among those with household incomes of $75,000 or more, 50 percent
said their lives were harder, 28 percent said easier and 21 percent
said they were about the same.
</P>
<P>
   Among those from families where the household income was less
than $30,000, only 38 percent said their lives were harder than
their parents', compared to 41 percent who said their lives were
easier and 18 percent who said they were about the same. Among
those with household incomes of $30,000 to $50,000, 41 percent said
their lives were harder, 33 percent said easier and 26 percent said
about the same.
</P>
<P>
   Some social scientists believe the gap is a measure of what
parents tell their children, and how the information is conveyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really interesting class issue,'' said Gina Bria, an
anthropologist at the Institute for Family Development in New York
City. ``In families living close to the bone, parents are more
likely to pass on family stories about how people survived, and in
the process to pass on skills for living. Wealthy kids often have
less of a perspective on the struggles of life. And in some strata,
there is a lot of pressure to keep the family's new-found status,
and children feel the pressure to get into elite schools, to be
sure they don't slide back. Everything's about going forward, about
prosperity. Falling back is the American nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   In later interviews with some of the teen-agers who took part in
the poll, the more affluent said that higher parental expectations,
more pressure for good grades, a faster pace of life and a more
dangerous world made their teen years more stressful than those of
their parents.
</P>
<P>
   It may come as a surprise to parents who came of age in the
druggy 1960s and 1970s, with the Vietnam War raging, but many of
their teen-agers sound wistful, describing their parents'
childhoods as care free, leisurely and safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents both said they felt safe growing up, my dad in Long
Island and my mom in California,'' said Ashley Nielsen, 14, of Alta
Loma, Calif. ``They could do a lot of things we can't do today,
like I don't think they had to worry about things like
hitch-hiking. Sometimes at football games, or when there's a whole
bunch of teen-agers around, I feel a little nervous, like something
could happen. My world is pretty safe, but I know there's a real
world out there. I think there's more peer pressure now than there
was in their time, and more expectations to get good grades. Grades
are the biggest stress for most kids I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Several teen-agers who said their lives were harder described a
steady anxiety about peer pressure and living up to their parents'
academic expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life was just a lot easier when my parents were growing up,''
said Tommy Shipp, 15, of Houston. ``They didn't have as much peer
pressure to do drugs and all that. There's a lot more pressure to
be popular, and to drink. I've heard my parents talk. My dad's
parents didn't really care what he did; he got kicked out of the
house at 15.''
</P>
<P>
   But now that his father is a highly successful businessman,
Tommy says: ``I'm definitely going to go to college, and they care
about how I'm doing in school.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the more affluent teen-agers who said life has gotten
harder attributed it to a sense of too-muchness: too many
activities, too many consumer choices, too much to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything's gotten harder since my parents were
growing up,'' said Molly Wilhelm, 15, of Lakeville, Minn. ``Back
then, I think everyone was more equal, but now, because there's so
much more offered in styles of clothes and stuff, we all want to
fit in. I think my parents had more free time, and the world isn't
as safe as it was in their day. It's more common for kids to do
drugs and all that stuff. Education gets progressively harder as
people learn more, and there's more to cover. And now that there's
more technology, they expect more out of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Many teen-agers from more modest backgrounds view the new
technologies and new opportunities as making their lives easier
than their parents' were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's easier now, because of technology,'' said Ariel
Garcia of Opa-Locka, Fla. ``When you want to do a report, you just
look at the Internet, you don't have to go to the library. Cars
have air-conditioning now, so you're comfortable. There's
microwaves, so it's easy to cook. My dad had it much harder. He's
Dominican, and he was in the Navy. That's tough. I would never go
into the Navy. Those rich kids, they don't appreciate what their
parents do for them. The money just goes through their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   While the more affluent teen-agers portray their parents'
upbringing as easier, and more idyllic, the lower-income youngsters
talk more of the difficulties their parents had to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 13 in my mom's family, and there's only four of us,
and without so many brothers and sisters, my mom can take care of
all of us,'' said Rae-chelle Nunn, 17, of Columbia, Tenn. ``Like my
mom drives me to school, but when she was a kid, she had to walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the richest teen-agers might see their lives as
harder, Ms. Nunn has a quick answer ``They're just spoiled brats,''
she said, laughing. ``But I am too. My mom spoils all of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 0832EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 08:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1628 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-R-TEENAGERS-REVIEW-NY     11-08 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-TEENAGERS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXT TO MOM AND DAD IT'S A HARD LIFE (OR NOT) 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By TAMAR LEWIN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Money doesn't buy happiness _ and among teen-agers, it may
actually make life feel harder.
</P>
<P>
   In a New York Times/CBS News Poll last month, 1,038 young people
aged 13 to 17 were asked to compare their lives with what their
parents experienced growing up. Overall, 43 percent said they were
having a harder time, 33 percent said they were having an easier
time and 23 percent said it was about the same. At the same time,
there was a divide along economic lines, with the upper-income
children saying they were feeling more burdened.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the affluent teen-agers, whatever their race or gender,
were substantially more likely than those from more modest homes to
report that their lives were harder and subject to more stress:
Among those with household incomes of $75,000 or more, 50 percent
said their lives were harder, 28 percent said easier and 21 percent
said they were about the same.
</P>
<P>
   Among those from families where the household income was less
than $30,000, only 38 percent said their lives were harder than
their parents', compared to 41 percent who said their lives were
easier and 18 percent who said they were about the same. Among
those with household incomes of $30,000 to $50,000, 41 percent said
their lives were harder, 33 percent said easier and 26 percent said
about the same.
</P>
<P>
   Some social scientists believe the gap is a measure of what
parents tell their children, and how the information is conveyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a really interesting class issue,'' said Gina Bria, an
anthropologist at the Institute for Family Development in New York
City. ``In families living close to the bone, parents are more
likely to pass on family stories about how people survived, and in
the process to pass on skills for living. Wealthy kids often have
less of a perspective on the struggles of life. And in some strata,
there is a lot of pressure to keep the family's new-found status,
and children feel the pressure to get into elite schools, to be
sure they don't slide back. Everything's about going forward, about
prosperity. Falling back is the American nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   In later interviews with some of the teen-agers who took part in
the poll, the more affluent said that higher parental expectations,
more pressure for good grades, a faster pace of life and a more
dangerous world made their teen years more stressful than those of
their parents.
</P>
<P>
   It may come as a surprise to parents who came of age in the
druggy 1960s and 1970s, with the Vietnam War raging, but many of
their teen-agers sound wistful, describing their parents'
childhoods as care free, leisurely and safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents both said they felt safe growing up, my dad in Long
Island and my mom in California,'' said Ashley Nielsen, 14, of Alta
Loma, Calif. ``They could do a lot of things we can't do today,
like I don't think they had to worry about things like
hitch-hiking. Sometimes at football games, or when there's a whole
bunch of teen-agers around, I feel a little nervous, like something
could happen. My world is pretty safe, but I know there's a real
world out there. I think there's more peer pressure now than there
was in their time, and more expectations to get good grades. Grades
are the biggest stress for most kids I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Several teen-agers who said their lives were harder described a
steady anxiety about peer pressure and living up to their parents'
academic expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life was just a lot easier when my parents were growing up,''
said Tommy Shipp, 15, of Houston. ``They didn't have as much peer
pressure to do drugs and all that. There's a lot more pressure to
be popular, and to drink. I've heard my parents talk. My dad's
parents didn't really care what he did; he got kicked out of the
house at 15.''
</P>
<P>
   But now that his father is a highly successful businessman,
Tommy says: ``I'm definitely going to go to college, and they care
about how I'm doing in school.''
</P>
<P>
   Several of the more affluent teen-agers who said life has gotten
harder attributed it to a sense of too-muchness: too many
activities, too many consumer choices, too much to learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everything's gotten harder since my parents were
growing up,'' said Molly Wilhelm, 15, of Lakeville, Minn. ``Back
then, I think everyone was more equal, but now, because there's so
much more offered in styles of clothes and stuff, we all want to
fit in. I think my parents had more free time, and the world isn't
as safe as it was in their day. It's more common for kids to do
drugs and all that stuff. Education gets progressively harder as
people learn more, and there's more to cover. And now that there's
more technology, they expect more out of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Many teen-agers from more modest backgrounds view the new
technologies and new opportunities as making their lives easier
than their parents' were.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's easier now, because of technology,'' said Ariel
Garcia of Opa-Locka, Fla. ``When you want to do a report, you just
look at the Internet, you don't have to go to the library. Cars
have air-conditioning now, so you're comfortable. There's
microwaves, so it's easy to cook. My dad had it much harder. He's
Dominican, and he was in the Navy. That's tough. I would never go
into the Navy. Those rich kids, they don't appreciate what their
parents do for them. The money just goes through their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   While the more affluent teen-agers portray their parents'
upbringing as easier, and more idyllic, the lower-income youngsters
talk more of the difficulties their parents had to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 13 in my mom's family, and there's only four of us,
and without so many brothers and sisters, my mom can take care of
all of us,'' said Rae-chelle Nunn, 17, of Columbia, Tenn. ``Like my
mom drives me to school, but when she was a kid, she had to walk.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the richest teen-agers might see their lives as
harder, Ms. Nunn has a quick answer ``They're just spoiled brats,''
she said, laughing. ``But I am too. My mom spoils all of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
