end to one of Washington's great gravy trains. In the last
congressional session alone, the industries affected by the bill
poured more than $300 million into lobbying and campaign
fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY'S GREAT LEAP FORWARD
</P>
<P>
   Walt Disney Co. said it would open its third international theme
park in Hong Kong in 2005. Not since China took back the former
British colony in 1997 has there been so much fuss about a new
arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Disney extracted rich terms for bringing Mickey Mouse to town.
Hong Kong will put up more than $3 billion and be the majority
owner of the park, prompting critics to dub it the Disney
state-owned enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   A RULING AGAINST GIULIANI
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge held that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani violated the
First Amendment when he cut public funding to the Brooklyn Museum
of Art for refusing to cancel an exhibition he considers offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Saying the judge had ``lost all reason,'' Giuliani promised to
appeal and renewed his claim that museum officials acted
unethically by raising money for the ``Sensation'' exhibit from
those who have a direct financial stake in the show: contemporary
art dealers, Christie's and Charles Saatchi, the owner of the
``Sensation'' art.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA DEMOCRAT WINS
</P>
<P>
   As the vote tally clicked past midnight, Philadelphia came
closer to ending a half-century of Democratic rule in City Hall.
But finally, by dint of the party machine, former City Council
President John F. Street emerged as the people's choice, just
barely, with 50.2 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   An easier election day was had by Ross Anderson, a civil rights
lawyer and unapologetic liberal, who was elected mayor of Salt Lake
City. In San Francisco, Mayor Willie L. Brown Jr. eluded the defeat
some pollsters predicted and survived for a run-off in December.
</P>
<P>
   7 UTILITIES IN POLLUTION SUIT
</P>
<P>
   Spending $60 million for five new furnaces does not qualify as
``routine maintenance.'' So said the Justice Department and
Environmental Protection Agency as they sued seven big electric
utilities in the Midwest and South, accusing them of polluting the
air by revamping old coal-burning power plants under the guise of
normal upkeep.
</P>
<P>
   The government said the utilities have hidden behind grandfather
clauses in the Clean Air Act to avoid spending money for modern
anti-pollution equipment. The utilities denied any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   MAKER OF DRUG KITS FINED
</P>
<P>
   After six yers of warning Abbott Laboratories about
deficiencies in the manufacture of its medical test kits, the Food
and Drug Administration put new restraints on the sale of products
that help detect everything from the virus that causes AIDS to
hepatitis in donated blood. Abbott also agreed to pay a record $100
million to settle accusations that the company failed to meet
federal quality standards when it made a wide variety of test kits.
</P>
<P>
   REPORT CITES MEDICARE FRAUD
</P>
<P>
   For several years, administration officials have boasted of
success in their effort to curtail Medicare fraud. But a report to
Congress from the General Accounting Office suggests that those
claims may be premature.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators told Senator Susan Collins, R-Maine, that
``career criminals and organized criminal groups'' had infiltrated
Medicare and Medicaid. ``This isn't a matter of padding the bill,''
Ms. Collins said. ``It's billing for services that were never
provided. And that is much more pernicious.''
</P>
<P>
   A BLACK EYE FOR BOXING
</P>
<P>
   The founder of the International Boxing Federation and three
other top officials were indicted on charges of receiving bribes
from fighters and their promoters in exchange for manipulating the
federation's rankings to allow boxers to qualify for lucrative
fights. A prosecutor cited the ``culture of corruption'' in the
organization, one of three major international ranking groups for
boxing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
