<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 08:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2396 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-R-IRAN-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      11-08 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-IRAN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORDER IN THE COURT! A REVOLUTION IS ON TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
(Repeating for all needing.) (The Week in Review) 
(jt) 
 By JOHN F. BURNS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEHRAN, Iran _ High on the slopes of the Alborz mountains above
the smog-choked heart of Tehran, million-dollar townhouses and
condominiums have sprung up just below the sprawling estate that
housed the shah's winter palace. Here, in the suburbs, is the
Beverley Hills of Iran, an area of high, white walls that give onto
homes with magnificent panoramas, lush gardens and swimming pools.
It is a surreal setting, the kind Antonioni might have chosen for a
film, encoded with messages about the very strange society Iran has
become after 20 years of Islamic rule.
</P>
<P>
   Side by side, living as neighbors, are representatives of the
main protagonists in a struggle for Iran's soul. There are the
``formerly privileged,'' in the contemptuous phrase the ruling
clerics use for the old bourgeoisie. There are the new rich, many
of them from the old merchant class, who have built fortunes from
favors granted by the clerics in return for support during the
revolution of 1979. And there are the mullahs themselves, clerics
who have taken over properties confiscated from those among the old
ruling class who did not survive the upheaval.
</P>
<P>
   It was here, last weekend, in a nondescript office building
constructed in the grounds of a confiscated mansion, beside an
empty swimming pool, that the ruling clerics convened a trial that
has become a tableau for the wider struggle going on across Iran.
</P>
<P>
   In the dock was Abdullah Nouri, himself a cleric and until
recently a vice president of the Islamic republic. But it was hard
not to notice a second trial as well: It could be called The People
vs. The Clergy. Even as Mohammed Salimi, a white-turbaned cleric,
starchily admonishes Nouri to show proper respect, millions of
Iranians are judging the court itself, through the blanket press
coverage Iranian newspapers are giving the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Nouri is a man who has helped to shape and lead a reform
movement that aims at curbing the clergy's absolute power. He is
charged before the Iranian equivalent of the Inquisition, the
Special Court for the Clergy, with being an apostate.
</P>
<P>
   Not for nothing has Nouri, 50, been called the Martin Luther of
Iran. Like Luther, Nouri nailed his principles where the clerical
establishment could not ignore them _ in the pages of the country's
most widely circulated reformist newspaper, Khordad, which Nouri
controls. Among other things, he is charged with ``insulting the
sanctities of Islam'' by advocating political reforms that would
undermine the principle of clerical rule. In particular, he would
establish the sovereign right of Iran's 65 million people to choose
their governments, and he is urging the re-establishment of
relations between Iran and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In a 44-page indictment that reads like an encyclopedia of
treachery, articles in Khordad are cited as proof that Nouri's
conspiracy to subvert the revolution even extended to advocating
clapping and cheering in public, a taboo under Islamic laws, and to
``propagating'' on behalf of Farah Diba, the shah's widow, by
supporting another newspaper's decision to publish excerpts from
her New Year's greeting to Iran's people.
</P>
<P>
   But after only a week of testimony, many Iranians, and clearly
Nouri himself, have concluded that the trial's significance lies
not in the verdict, but in how it has come to represent the chasm
that has opened up within Iranian society.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is being conducted, bizarrely, in the lobby of the
court building, with reporters perched on a winding staircase to
the upper floors.
</P>
<P>
   It may be years before the world will know which represents the
``real'' Iran _ the medieval process initiated by the mullahs
against the reformer, or the breezy, late 20th-century atmosphere
that invades the courtroom, of reporters in jeans and boat shoes,
with mobile phones, lounging against walls and reading reformist
newspapers replete with articles about the New York Yankees' World
Series triumph and the growing power of internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   But to an outsider, the sense taken from the courtroom, and from
just about everywhere else in Iran, is that the changes sweeping
the rest of the world cannot be halted at Iran's borders.
</P>
<P>
   Some Iranians see what is happening as a sort of Marxist
dialectic, in which the old and the new are driven into conflict,
driving the historical wheel onward. Certainly, there is an
inexorability in the way in which the conservative mullahs and
their backers have chosen to confront the reformers.
</P>
<P>
   This time last year, the climate of paranoid resistance to
change contributed to the brutal killings in Tehran of five
reformers, including three writers, all of whom had appeared on
death lists circulated by shadowy Islamic groups. Under pressure
from President Mohammed Khatami, the main standard-bearer for
reform along with Nouri, the intelligence ministry was forced to
admit in January that a ``rogue'' group within the ministry had
carried out the killings. Although none of more than 30 people
arrested have gone on trial, and two ring-leaders are said to have
committed suicide in jail, the result, many Iranians believe, has
been to persuade the mullahs that the battle for power must
henceforth be conducted within the law.
</P>
<P>
   Much the same process was visible in the upheaval in July, when
students protesting at the University of Tehran against the closure
of a reformist newspaper were attacked by policemen and vigilantes
who killed three students and ransacked a dormitory. The ensuing
riots were the worst since 1979. Hardliners appeared to have won
the day when they summoned tens of thousands of demonstrators into
the streets. But only four months later, the affair is widely seen
as a Waterloo for the hardliners. Khatami, visiting the rebuilt
dormitory two weeks ago, described the attack on the students as a
``disgraceful, bitter and ugly event'' of a kind Iranians will no
longer tolerate.
</P>
<P>
   Not all Iranians who hanker for greater democracy and human
rights believe it is too late for the mullahs to reverse the tides.
They could send Nouri to jail, depriving reformers of their main
campaigner in parliamentary elections that will be held in
February. Beyond that, the clerics retain the possibility of
violent suppression, since they control the police, the army, and
an array of vigilante and paramilitary groups. But much the same
could have been said for two other ruling elites in the past 10
years, in South Africa and the Soviet Union, and neither survived
the popular will for change.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 0842EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
