created an astonishingly large empire. They did it, initially, for
the sheer adventure of discovery, and for Christianity. A maritime
nation, they threw off Moorish rule early and professed themselves
ready to pursue Muslims zealously to the ends of the Earth, while
excoriating fellow Europeans who didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``But here at least, in this small land of Portugal, there will
not lack those who will do and dare for Christendom,'' wrote Luis
Vaz de Camoens, a 16th-century poet, in the Portuguese national
epic, The Lusiads.
</P>
<P>
   When the Portuguese finished their conquests and conversions,
they had churches as well as trading bases scattered across Asia,
at a time when the spices of the East Indies were the most valuable
commodities in Europe. ``Happily it was possible to serve God and
Mammon at the same time,'' D.G.E. Hall wrote in his classic
``History of Southeast Asia'' (Macmillan). ``By striking at Arab
trade in the Indian Ocean, Portugal aimed a blow at the Ottoman
Empire, which drew the major part of its revenues from the spice
monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Americas, Portugal had the vast colony of Brazil. In
Africa, there was Angola, one of the continent's largest and
potentially richest nations, as well as Mozambique, Cape Verde and
other islands. In India, where Muslims ruled when the Portuguese
arrived, they created Christian Goa, complete with basilicas and
the bones of saints. Goa remained a Portuguese colony for more than
four centuries, until the Indian army seized it without warning in
1961, an act of neo-colonialism that, strangely, never brought down
on India the kind of sustained international retribution Indonesia
would later face in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   The Portuguese had also dabbled in Ceylon, now Sri Lanka, where
the 16th-century King of Kotte was informed by his spies that the
outlandish folks in metal hats and coats who had come ashore seemed
to be picnicking on blood and hunks of whitish stone.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal was ultimately unable to sustain all of its
possessions, especially in Asia. But around the world, elements of
the Portuguese language and Portuguese family and place names live
on, a legacy of a relaxed colonial style _ religious zeal apart.
Portugal, unlike others, did not frown on intermarriage with local
populations. ``There was no color line,'' said Pye. ``No exclusive
clubs. No insults. The Portuguese didn't lord it over as much. They
were gentler, more tolerant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the sad thing is what they left or didn't leave
behind,'' he said. ``They left behind religion, culture. But they
never left behind anything that was political. They never had a
vision for their colonies. They never had the British white man's
burden. They never had the task of modernizing. They didn't have a
sense of mission. There was no grand design. Certainly there was no
end game. It just sort of came to an end because of the Portuguese
revolution back in Lisbon.''
</P>
<P>
   That revolution in 1974 unexpectedly cut loose the remaining
colonies that had not been lost to the Dutch, Spanish or British
over the centuries. Angola and East Timor were suddenly freed _
really left in the lurch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Portuguese stayed too long,'' said Dame Margaret Anstee,
who served as a special envoy of the U.N. secretary-general in
war-ravaged Angola. ``There was no preparation for independence.
There was no transition.'' Indeed, the extended period of colonial
rule allowed divisions to fester among the frustrated and ambitious
anti-colonialist forces.
</P>
<P>
   In East Timor, the Portuguese had left the Roman Catholic Church
in charge of administration. With the Indonesian invasion of 1975,
the church lost its temporal power, which helped make the
disaffected clergy a potent, persistent foe of the Indonesian
government. Indonesia underestimated its power.
</P>
<P>
   ``The church played an administrative role for the Portuguese in
a strange kind of way so that the state didn't have to do it,''
said Pye. ``It didn't have to modernize, like in India _ create a
civil service and all that.'' Educational institutions were as
scarce as government institutions. The best and brightest boys were
sent to seminaries. ``One of the things that is striking in terms
of both East Timor and Macao is that the Portuguese have suddenly
realized that they really didn't create any institutions that can
carry on and identify with Portugal,'' he said. Macao's only
university is already run by the Chinese, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil was different. There, by the beginning of the 19th
century, a nation had coalesced. With the help of the British, a
24-year-old exiled Portuguese prince was able to declare the
country independent of the motherland. In 1822, he was crowned
Pedro I, emperor of Brazil. Pedro took the advice of his father,
who _ according to the historian Hubert Herring _ had said: ``If
Brazil demands independence, grant it, but put the crown upon your
own head.''
</P>
<P>
   Brazil thus came of age with a strong national identity as well
as an enduring Portuguese culture, later to be blended with
indigenous American strains as well as African strains, a legacy of
Purtugal's infamous involvement in the slave trade. Brazil
subsequently grew into the largest and most influential of
Portuguese-speaking nations.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Brazil is eager to help distant East Timor create a
society true to itself and yet in tune with its history. When the
United Nations looked for the perfect administrator to guide the
East Timorese through the transition, it found a Brazilian, Under
Secretary General Sergio Vieira de Mello. He sees his role as part
of a closing of the circle of colonial history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
