<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 10:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2463 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-LANE-COLUMN09-COX     11-08 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANE-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Computer co-dependent faces shut-off
 &HT;    By Mark Lane
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ I have been living in the 1980s for the
past few weeks. For the first time since 1984, there is no computer
at home. My kids consider it equivalent to becoming Amish.
</P>
<P>
   The computer that used to live here _ the fastest, coolest one
I've owned since the day I carried a toylike Atari 800 through the
door _ stopped cold.
</P>
<P>
   And in an anticlimactic, mysterious manner. No grinding of the
hard drive. No shower of sparks. No deep blue error-message screen
Windows critics call the ``Screen of Death.'' Nada. One morning, it
just woke up dead.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer my computer failures to be more satisfyingly dramatic.
I have always enjoyed the way computer failure on ``Star Trek'' is
explosive, as though star-ship computers are powered by kerosene.
But in our boring century, you just keep pushing a button and
nothing happens.
</P>
<P>
   Repetitive button-pushing, by the way, is the universal first
response to all electronic failure. This is similar to the innate
belief that people can make elevators move faster by pushing the
``up'' button more vigorously.
</P>
<P>
   After I sprained my finger stabbing the ``on'' button, I duly
reported the problem to the customer-support department of the
computer's creator.
</P>
<P>
   My decade-and-a-half experience with computer customer-support
departments prepared me for bad things. I filled a thermos with
coffee, got out a sleeping bag, sat by the phone and prepared to
wait them out.
</P>
<P>
   I steeled myself to stay on the phone for any amount of time
they could dish out. I would listen to any amount of background
music. (Yes, even repetitive string versions of ``Close to You.'')
I would write down every option the digital voice would recite at
the speed of a horse-track announcer.
</P>
<P>
   It took time and two cups of coffee, but yes reader, I met a
kindly human.
</P>
<P>
   The kindly human had me do this and that and then pronounced the
power-supply unit dead. But dead under warrantee. The human offered
this deal: mail the computer carcass back to the land of its
creators and the creators would mail a brand-new computer back to
me.
</P>
<P>
   I was delighted. But even in our technologically advanced age,
trucks bearing boxes travel only so fast and land-mail can be slow.
I would be computerless for close to a month. How hard could that
be?
</P>
<P>
   The first days were no problem. In fact, my life improved in
subtle ways. Work could not be brought home. E-mail could not be
read and answered until working hours. I reverted to the ancient
work ethic of working at work and living at my house. This
arrangement has much to recommend it.
</P>
<P>
   Without my home finance program, I experienced the fleeting
feeling of unexpected wealth that comes from checkbook subtraction
errors. Without my computer address book, I misplaced my ex-wife's
phone number. Without the Instant Messenger program, my kids
stopped fighting over the computer.
</P>
<P>
   When I needed to look something up, I went to the library
instead of the Internet, then lazed at a coffee house on my trip
back. Double latte with cocoa.
</P>
<P>
   I noticed the seasons were changing. Life was good.
</P>
<P>
   Still, computerless living got old fast. I wait at the front
door, scanning the horizon for UPS trucks. I feel like a kid
running home from school to see if the decoder ring arrived in the
mail.
</P>
<P>
   This last sentence was written in longhand and copied into the
computer at work. The sentence seemed to end ``see foop decooden
ring amuved ni th mal.'' Longtime computer use atrophied my ability
_ never strong in the first place _ to write words with a pen.
</P>
<P>
   I wish the truck would come. The bills are piling out without
the home finance program to sort them out. I'm lonely for e-mail.
I'm mailing illegible letters with illegible address that will
arrive with postage due to Rangoon instead of Rockledge.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks into computer-free living, I have faced up to facts:
I am a computer co-dependent.
</P>
<P>
   I believe there is a Web site dedicated to curing us. E-mail
support groups, too. After the truck arrives, I'll be sure to check
them out. I put a note in the electronic organizer to remind me to
do so.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lane is a columnist for The Daytona Beach (Fla.)
News-Journal. E-mail: marklane(at)n-jcenter.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
