<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Surfing at work? Start here
 &HT;    By Mark Clothier
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Having Internet access at work is like having a
television on your desk, only cooler. The studies show that online
prime time for the Net is the daytime.
</P>
<P>
   People are online the most while they are at work. Checking
stock quotes. Reading movie reviews. Scanning NFL injury reports to
set fantasy football lineups. Checking Internet e-mail in-boxes.
</P>
<P>
   All while they should be working.
</P>
<P>
   One Web site, www.ishouldbeworking.com, is nice and brazen about
the people's online slacking. People are on the Web when they
should be working, so if people are going to do it, the site
argues, why not do it here?
</P>
<P>
   Or, as the welcome message states, ``This Web site is dedicated
to slackers, goof-offs, procrastinators, loafers, `long-lunchers,'
and Web-addicted employees worldwide. You should probably be doing
something else right now, but as long as you're here, have some
fun.''
</P>
<P>
   The site offers discussion groups, games and jokes. It also
includes a panic button on every page in the site. If your boss is
walking by, press it and immediately (or as long as it takes to
download) a business-oriented Web site appears.
</P>
<P>
   The site includes practical tools as well. One page offers links
to several online job-hunting sites. Another provides links to
alcoholic drink databases, and one offers links to travel planning
sites.
</P>
<P>
   COOKING LIGHT SITE HAS HEALTH TIPS, MORE
</P>
<P>
   We've heard all the excuses: You're too busy to eat right and
too overworked to burn off the excess from the food you shouldn't
be eating because you're too busy in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's one less excuse. The folks at Cooking Light magazine
improved their Web site, www.cookinglight.com. The only drawback to
the site is the annoying pop-up box, ``welcoming'' you to the site.
But that can easily be removed with a click.
</P>
<P>
   The new site includes:
</P>
<P>
   _ Nutritional information that lets you search recipes by fat
content or the percentage of calories, carbohydrates, sodium and
cholesterol.
</P>
<P>
   _ Twice as many recipes as the original site. Some 2,000 recipes
are included. Each is linked to dishes included as part of
last-minute menu ideas.
</P>
<P>
   _ A new, faster search engine to help find recipes when all you
know is one word.
</P>
<P>
   _ A feature called My Recipe Box, which lets you keep an online
collection of your favorite recipes.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Clueless Gourmet is geared toward someone who doesn't know
much about cooking but wants to make it seem like they do. The
selections come with tips to create ambience and advice on how to
select the fruits and vegetables in the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   LOCATE THAT HARD-TO-FIND RENTAL MOVIE
</P>
<P>
   So you want to rent an old Albert Brooks movie. But you live in
the Deep South, not exactly the holy land for movies written by and
starring a somewhat whiny, neurotic Californian. You have a few
options: You can drive to the video stores near your home and see
if they carry ``Lost in America.'' You can call and ask. Or you can
take advantage of a Web site designed to help you find hard-to-find
movies to rent.
</P>
<P>
   The site, www.formovies.com, has a search engine that lets you
type in the name of a movie and your ZIP code. After a few seconds,
it lists the phone number and address of video rental stores near
your house that carry the movie you want. A recent search on ``Lost
in America'' using a ZIP code in metro Atlanta turned up 12 video
stores, five of which were a short drive.
</P>
<P>
   The site includes more than 9,000 video stores and 160,000 movie
titles in its database. You can search for video cassettes, DVDs
and video games. You can search by movie title, actor, directory or
category.
</P>
<P>
   THE LATEST THINGS IN NET MUSIC
</P>
<P>
   Web listening: RCA's Lyra 2201 is an MP3 player that offers the
versatility of handling different formats. The RaveMP 2100 not only
looks cool but also adds a built-in microphone for four hours of
voice recording. The Rio 500, successor to the original MP3 player,
greatly improves on capacity and features.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
