<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KABAT-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First apartment experience can become a real mess
 &HT;    By Vicki Marsh Kabat
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ There are a lot of bumps along the road to
maturity. Living in an apartment for the first time is one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Most young people can't afford to set up house by themselves the
first time out, so they often take on a roommate or two. This can
be a messy situation.
</P>
<P>
   Our oldest son moved into an apartment last summer with four
friends. Here are some of life's hard lessons he has learned since:
</P>
<P>
   _ Food does not regenerate in refrigerators and cabinets, and if
it does, you shouldn't eat it.
</P>
<P>
   _ Food does not cook itself and hop onto the table and lay
itself on nice place settings ready to be consumed.
</P>
<P>
   _ Food scraps left on plates, end tables, floors, beds, desks
and couches will begin to smell bad as time passes. Eventually they
will fossilize and become a permanent part of the living
environment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Dirty clothes DO regenerate and can quickly take over all your
living space.
</P>
<P>
   _ Vacuum cleaners have a purpose, and living in the hall closet
is not it.
</P>
<P>
   As a parent, I try to help my son through this transition. For
instance, I think I handled it rather well when he came home
recently and asked, ``Mom, what do you do about the black stuff in
your bathtub?''
</P>
<P>
   Speechless, I took a moment and then asked how deep it was and
if it had texture. That gave me time to figure out how to answer
him.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, this particular question didn't catch me totally
off guard. When I first visited the apartment of my future husband,
I went into his bathroom and pulled back the shower curtain to
check out his tub. Might as well know what you're getting into with
a fellow before you become emotionally involved. His white
porcelain tub was black, and our relationship came very close to
going down the drain.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can you stand to be in that thing?'' I asked in horror.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?'' he responded, puzzled. ``Only the bottom of my feet
touch it, and I just wash them in the sink after I shower.''
</P>
<P>
   Our son obviously came by this condition honestly. Of course,
this is the same son who once asked me, ``Are the clothes in the
dryer clean?''
</P>
<P>
   No, dear, I like to fluff the dirt out of my clothes and then
wet them down. Mothers should get points for the things they manage
not to say.
</P>
<P>
   All this is a natural stage of development. I remember my first
apartment experience. My parents dropped in unexpectedly for a
visit and, having no food or clean utensils, I offered them my jar
of peanut butter and demonstrated how I often used my finger to eat
it. Much easier to clean up, you know. They took me out to dinner.
</P>
<P>
   And in all, with the wild freedom a first apartment affords,
division of labor becomes a minefield of unmet expectations. While
each roommate waits for the other to wash dishes, put away food,
vacuum, take out the trash, etc., nothing gets done. Listening to
our heretofore sloppiest son bemoan the situation, we nod
sympathetically.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine?'' we ask in mock disgust.
</P>
<P>
   The irony escapes him.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent visit home for dinner, he finished eating, thanked
me profusely for a wonderful meal, took his plate to the sink,
rinsed it and put it in the dishwasher. Stunned, we then heard him
instruct his younger brothers, ``Get back in here and clean up your
dishes, you slobs!''
</P>
<P>
   We thought we had died and gone to heaven.
</P>
<P>
   We expected our son would get an education at college. The fact
that he's actually growing up, as well, is a wonderful bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Marsh Kabat writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald. She can be
reached online at VMKabat(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
