<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Portable MP3 players take over for the computer
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ A hot trend in music is to download music
purchases directly over the Internet for storage and play through
personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with that is you probably don't want to lug your
personal computer to the beach, on the bus or to most of the other
places you want to go. That's why several companies are now
marketing small, portable players capable of playing music recorded
in the Internet's MP3 format.
</P>
<P>
   The latest portable MP3 player is the I-Jam, introduced by the
I-Jam Multimedia Corp. of Illinois. The I-Jam ``portable MP3
multimedia system,'' as the player is called, plays MP3 files
downloaded from the Internet. It also has a built-in FM radio.
</P>
<P>
   I-Jam claims its portable MP3 player is the smallest on the
market at three inches high and less than two inches wide, and it
can be worn around the neck or on a belt clip. The I-Jam player is
supposed to deliver CD quality sound through its ear bud speakers.
</P>
<P>
   To use the I-Jam system, you download music through your
computer as you normally do. Once the music is in your computer,
you can load it onto a MultiMediaCard about the size of a postage
stamp. I-Jam says its player is compatible with all the digital
formats currently being used to download music from the Internet.
I-Jam systems were being offered online for $179.95 last week. To
get further details or to order the product, visit
www.ijamworld.com.
</P>
<P>
   The I-Jam system and other portable MP3 players also are
available through major electronics stores or through other online
audio equipment sellers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
