<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Town won't forget the football team that keeps winning
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ The Gibsonburg High School football team is
10-0 for the season. Playoffs start this week. And let me tell you,
the village is going nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Uptown, orange and black Golden Bear flags are flying from every
lamp post. Store windows proclaim ``This Is Bear Country!'' and
suddenly it's cool for kids to punch the air with a fist and yell
at no one in particular, ``We're No. 1!''
</P>
<P>
   ``GO BEARS!'' posters are everywhere. It's a regular football
frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   Afternoons, when it isn't pouring down rain or blowing snow,
front lawns are transformed into fields of potential glory by
little kids in shared equipment (the guy with the helmet has no
shoulder pads and vice versa), passing, kicking, and otherwise
mopping up the dirt with each other in their best imitation of an
older brother or the kid down the street who plays
</P>
<P>
   first-string quarterback on the winningest team in our town's
history.
</P>
<P>
   In the cafes, the hardware store, the barber shop _ it's all
folks are
</P>
<P>
   talking about. At the early morning impromptu meetings of the
village movers and shakers in the back room of the bakery,
political arguments have been replaced with quotes of passing
averages and touchdown runs and predictions for the coming Friday
night. We're just not used to winning football games.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, in the four-year period, '92 through '95, we were a
disaster. Players came in for a lot of good-natured razzing from
their classmates. I'd hear them in the halls at school taunting
some hulking senior about rumors of the first string being replaced
by the girls' choir. The guys handled it as well as 17-year-olds
can. Every once in a while some little wiseguy would have to be
freed from a locker where he'd been stuffed to shut up his smart
mouth.
</P>
<P>
   For a lot of years we had such bad luck that I even began to
consider the
</P>
<P>
   possibility that I was a jinx, and that maybe if I stopped
walking over to the
</P>
<P>
   Friday night games the team would win. That didn't work either.
We kept on losing and I began to wonder where these boys got the
courage to put on their uniforms and show up on the football field
week after week. I wondered, but like the rest of the folks in
town, I respected them for doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Then an odd thing happened. Gibsonburg began winning ball games.
At first we were afraid to talk about it too much _ waiting for the
other shoe to drop, so to speak. But things kept getting better.
</P>
<P>
   In '97 we won 8 and lost only 2. Then in '98 we won 10 and lost
2. This year
</P>
<P>
   we made village history, finishing 10 and 0 and making it into
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a school so small that we have only 25 boys on the
football team.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's the first playoff game and it's here in town. A bunch
of us are
</P>
<P>
   getting together at Sharon's house for supper _ then we'll walk
over to the
</P>
<P>
   high school for the 7:30 kickoff. Since the bleachers are
expected to be
</P>
<P>
   filled by 6, we'll probably spread our blankets in the end zone.
Then we'll
</P>
<P>
   cross our fingers and hold our breath.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how the game turns out, something really big has
happened in our little town and for years folks'll be talking about
the year we went 10 and 0.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431 or e-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
