<HEADER>
A2484 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-IRIS-ID09-COX     11-08 0896
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRIS-ID09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IriScan's software, camera systems look security in the eye
 &HT;    By Heather Cocks
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After almost a decade of quietly testing and
tweaking its technology, IriScan Inc. is ready for the world to
look the future in the eye.
</P>
<P>
   And the company's cameras will be staring right back.
</P>
<P>
   IriScan makes software and small video cameras that can identify
a person based on a quick glimpse of his or her iris _ the eye's
colored ring surrounding the pupil.
</P>
<P>
   Convincing customers to shell out thousands of dollars for iris
scanning equipment and give up time-tested methods like
identification cards and fingerprints won't be easy, but in May,
the company's technology took a big step toward the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Houston-based Bank United Corp. installed automated teller
machines in Houston, Dallas and Fort Worth, each equipped with
iris-recognition systems that replace the need for carrying cards
and punching in pass codes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social security numbers, bank cards and drivers licenses
aren't secure, so if someone gets that information, they can do
things in your name,'' said spokeswoman Kelly Gates of New
Jersey-based IriScan. ``The only way to protect this information
and make sure the right person is doing the right thing is to tie
that activity to something that you are.''
</P>
<P>
   IriScan started developing its technology in 1990. But the
market for eyeball IDs didn't catch up with the company until the
advent of the Internet, which both increased availability of
information and put a premium on keeping it as safe as possible,
Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   And in biometrics _ the science of linking one's identity to an
innate physical characteristic _ the more foolproof, the better.
</P>
<P>
   The iris is widely thought to be the most unique part of the
human body, with more than 260 different places in which the tissue
patterns can vary.
</P>
<P>
   The chance of two people having identical irises is a number so
miniscule it defies comprehension _ take the number 10, pencil in
77 more zeros, and that's how many people to sort through before
you'd find two people with like irises.
</P>
<P>
   ``This could well be the most accurate biometric, with strong
potential as a security technique,'' said Jackie Fenn, an analyst
at GartnerGroup Inc. ``With fingerprints, you're looking at
minutiae and a few key features. But with the iris, there's tons of
unique information.''
</P>
<P>
   One advantage of using the iris for personal identification is
its immunity to both biology and outside forces. Fingerprints are
in constant contact with elements that can affect their appearance,
and voice patterns change based on anything from illness to simple
maturation. Conversely, the iris develops within an infant's first
three months and retains those characteristics for life.
</P>
<P>
   Sensar Inc., which built the ATM iris-recognition equipment
around IriScan's technology, plans to make it compact enough to be
embedded within devices such as personal computers, airport
security scanners and safe-deposit boxes. Already, a jail in
Sarasota, Fla., uses iris-recognition as a security measure.
</P>
<P>
   Using the eye itself as a security tool isn't altogether new.
Government agencies have used retina scanning for years to monitor
access to their high-security areas and information systems.
</P>
<P>
   But retina scanning never took off commercially because it
seemed too intrusive, Fenn said. It requires that a person stand
close to the unit, which shines a visible laser beam to the retina
at the back of the eyeball.
</P>
<P>
   ``That infrared light in the eye really turns people off,'' Fenn
said. ``That's a technology that won't take off even if it's
mass-marketed.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, the iris-recognition systems involve capturing a
video image of the person's iris. Software divides the iris image
into smaller ringed segments, translating each into digital code
that's matched against a previously recorded and stored iris
profile. The whole process takes less than three seconds, according
to IriScan.
</P>
<P>
   But speed might not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   To win over consumers, iris scanning needs to be as simple as
possible for people to use, so IriScan began licensing its
technology in 1995 to companies that are exploring its commercial
potential.
</P>
<P>
   The ATMs in Texas, plus a handful in Europe, use
iris-recognition cameras made by New Jersey-based Sensar, formerly
part of RCA Electronics. Sensar used RCA's imaging technology to
make a camera that can interpret the iris from a greater distance
than IriScan's original model.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it does that for a price. The Sensar equipment can
accurately recognize an iris from 3 feet away even when it's
shielded by glasses or contact lenses _ all for what Fenn said is a
fairly hefty $3,000 per unit. Sensar and Diebold Inc., an
Ohio-based maker of ATMs, plan to build 10,000 machines to see
whether the technology is popular and reliable.
</P>
<P>
   But it's little refinements like those that could make consumers
comfortable enough to embrace iris-recognition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very easy to stick your finger on a glass plate,'' said
Fenn of GartnerGroup. ``If iris scanning gets that easy, where
people can use it without thinking about it, then it could really
take off. But that's a good three to five years away.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
