<SLUG> BC-NETWATCH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The cyber-mall is waiting to help you with your holiday shopping
 &HT;    By Frances Katz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Don't all those Internet pundits see how obvious it is
that lots of people will be shopping online this holiday season?
</P>
<P>
   Think about it: Even people who absolutely hate shopping are
forced to do it at Christmas. Anyone who's ever had to fight his or
her way through Toys ``R'' Us or Victoria's Secret at Christmastime
knows this all too well.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the episode of the TV show ``Friends'' in which one of
the characters, probably Joey, forgot all about Christmas and
bought everyone presents from a gas station? Somebody got
windshield wipers; someone else got an air filter.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that people get desperate during the holidays.
They'll buy almost anything from anyone as time begins to run out.
</P>
<P>
   So the idea that people will be shopping online this year is
really a no-brainer. Do you really want to spend the 12 days of
Christmas trekking through every bookstore in town to find that
fly-fishing book your husband keeps yakking about? Of course you
don't. Why not just sit down at your computer, log on to an online
bookseller, have them find the book, gift-wrap it and drop it on
your doorstep? And it comes in the nifty UPS box, so if your
beloved asks you what came in the mail, you can smile sweetly and
say ``Oh, this? It's a `Cooking with Soy' book. We really don't eat
enough tofu, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   It's foolproof _ not even the most curious member of your family
is going to try to rip open a UPS package. First of all, anyone
who's tried knows it's not really possible without power tools.
Secondly, unless you work for UPS, you don't have the equipment to
return the packages to their just-delivered state. You will be
found out, and you will be presentless.
</P>
<P>
   It's not as if shopping at home is some wacky new idea that only
Web geeks and Microsoft employees can figure out. People have been
sitting comfortably catalogshopping and phoning up those cable
home-shopping channels for years. Now that most companies have at
least one computer hooked up to the Web, the end-of-the-millennium
holiday shopper can probably find his way to an online retailer and
place an order with little or no difficulty. It's hard to find a TV
show, newspaper or magazine that isn't stuffed with ads for
``Dot-com'' retailers urging you to get online.
</P>
<P>
   Online retailers say they've learned tons from last year's
surprise Christmas onslaught. More than just posting a list of
goods for sale, they finally understand that the Web offers more
opportunity for personalization and interaction than a catalog or a
retail store.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly for the novice e-shopper, retailers you know
and trust in the real world such as Nordstrom, Macy's, Neiman
Marcus, The Gap, Barnes &AMP; Noble, even speciality stores like The
Museum Co. and cosmetic companies such as Clinique and Bobbi Brown,
have all set up shop online. Each offers faithful consumers the
opportunity to bypass the crowds and do their holiday shopping by
the festive glow of their computer screens.
</P>
<P>
   Most sites offer very detailed and easy-to-read privacy
statements that you should read before you begin any online
shopping adventure. Any reputable site will promise security
measures to keep your credit card numbers safe. They'll also
promise not to give out any personal information you provide them
to any Internet con artists who ask for it.
</P>
<P>
   Converts to the wonders of online shopping will tell you that
the Web offers consumers much more besides convenience. There are
``wish lists'' users can create to help confused but
well-intentioned gift-givers pick out something you might really
enjoy. Other sites provide online ``personal shoppers.'' Type in
the person, the occasion, some information about their likes and
dislikes and a price range and you'll get several suggestions that
might fit the bill. If you find a retailer you like, you can often
select ``one click ordering option'' that will store your personal
information so you don't have to enter it over and over. It saves
time and provides extra security.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not shopping online yet, don't worry. The mall won't
be closing any time soon. But as the holidays draw closer, going
online is clearly better than last-minute shopping at the gas
station.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
