<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Health Web site alliance agrees on timetable
 &HT;    By Andrew Park
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The coalition of leaders of top Internet health
sites assembled by former Surgeon General C. Everett Koop said this
week it had taken its first steps to address the lack of ethical
standards in the new industry and made plans for regular
discussions over the next five months.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of 16 companies, including WebMD Inc., Healtheon
Corp., Medscape Inc., America Online Inc. and Austin's drkoop.com
Inc., met this week and formed working groups that will create
policies for advertising, privacy and content. The small groups
will meet weekly and the entire coalition _ dubbed the Hi-Ethics
Alliance _ will meet once a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started to discuss the issues, but we didn't come up with
anything,'' said Donald Kemper, chief executive of Healthwise Inc.,
an Idaho nonprofit group that runs a health site. ``It's too early
to say what things will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders expect to release a set of ethical principles by the end
of March, Kemper said.
</P>
<P>
   Health sites around the country have taken heat in medical
circles for creating potential conflicts of interest, providing
inaccurate information and offering diagnoses and prescribing drugs
online.
</P>
<P>
   Koop, chairman of drkoop.com, called the company leaders
together last month, but he won't play an active role in the group
despite having drawn some of the harshest criticism for perceived
ethical lapses.
</P>
<P>
   Drkoop.com, the most popular health site on the Internet, has
been judged as one of the most reliable, too.
</P>
<P>
   But in August, leaders of the American Medical Association
criticized Koop for not providing enough information about
sponsorship and commerce arrangements on the site, which derives
much of its revenue from advertising. Koop, who developed a
reputation as a tough public health advocate, was criticized last
week for telling Congress in March that medical latex gloves were
safe without disclosing that he had once been a paid consultant to
a major latex glove manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Hackett, drkoop.com's chief executive, represented the
company on the alliance and was tapped to head the advertising
group, which has already agreed that health sites should not accept
advertising from tobacco, alcoholic beverage or firearms companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goals there are to ensure that we have very high standards
and principles regarding the separation between church and state,
between content and advertising,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   While it is unclear what impact the guidelines will have on the
estimated 15,000 health sites on the Internet, Kemper said he
believes they all could stand to raise their standards and solidify
their policies on ethics and credibility. For example, he would
like to see content on Healthwise.com include more detail on the
source of the information, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been a shame that we didn't do this earlier so
people had clear guidelines as to what was appropriate and what was
not,'' Kemper said. ``Everybody's been working kind of blind as to
what standard operating procedure should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
