r a BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A09-COX     11-08 1283
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONSUMERQ&AMP;A09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Consumer Q&AMP;A
 &HT;    By Jane Greig
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Q: My daughter dropped a musical snow dome that
was her grandmother's. Is there anyone who can repair this? If
there is no way to replace the snow and the liquid, can just the
glass dome be replaced? I would like to have it for her by
Christmas. _ Kay B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Call Unicorn Studios at (800) 874-5317 and pick up a new dome
along with snow and drifting bits _ from standard white to black
flying bats. This catalog also carries musical movements, miniature
strings of lights (for doll houses) and stuffed toy parts (eyes,
joints, noses) and stoppers (plastic or rubber). You can repair the
damage yourself. Q: I am taking my nephew (12 years old) to New
York City this month so that he can be introduced to the ``Big
Apple Experience.'' I would love to visit the Soup Nazi shop made
famous on ``Seinfeld,'' so I am hoping that you can share info
about how to find it and how to be successful in ordering our soup.
_ Kim D. Brown
</P>
<P>
   A: Be nice. Be very, very nice. Follow the rules. (No comments,
no asides, no kidding _ or no soup.) Soup Kitchen International,
259 W. 55th St. Call (212) 757-7730 first, since the kitchen closes
for extended vacations.
</P>
<P>
   Regale your nephew with the origin of the Big Apple nickname.
Its likely origin was in a Harlem club in the 1920s named the Big
Apple. Musicians often referred to a gig as an ``apple,'' and no
gig was as prestigious as playing New York City _ hence playing the
``big apple.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: If I put a savings account in my name and a relative's name,
can Medicare and the government take this money and use it to pay
for my expenses in a nursing home? I am trying to look down the
road. I am 40 and would like to have my name and my children's
names on certificates of deposit, bank accounts, the house deed,
etc. But I do not know what the rules are. I do not want my
children to be taxed on the interest. I will pay the taxes. _ D.R.
</P>
<P>
   A: You are planning ahead. Preparation for incapacity is a
difficult but necessary task. Making your wishes clear will make
decisions on your behalf easier for your family to make. Christine
Larson, an attorney who specializes in elder law, says a
streamlined way to handle your financial affairs is to keep
everything in your name (you pay the taxes, etc.) and to execute a
power of attorney to a trusted family member. In addition, seek the
advice of an attorney to execute a will. Q: We've recently heard
there are 6 billion people on the planet. If we put each person on
the face of the Earth in a 1-foot square, how much space would they
take up (and please don't just tell me 6 billon square feet!)?
Would they fill up Texas, the city limits of Los Angeles? How much
space would all of the people of the United States take up if put
in 1-foot squares? Just curious.
</P>
<P>
   _ Randy Case
</P>
<P>
   A: CAUTION: Word person doing math! Converting square miles into
square feet (5,280 x 5,280) gets the number of square feet in a
square mile _ 27,878,400. In your scenario, each square foot is a
person. Dividing 6 billion by the square feet in a mile yields
215.22, the number of square miles needed to stand the world's
population on 1-foot squares. Most would need more room, I think.
Where to put them? No problem. Theoretically, if everyone sticks to
the 1 square foot allotted, the entire crowd would fit into Travis
County _ with or without water, since Travis County is 1,022.1
square miles (land and water), 989.4 square mile of land, or in the
city of Austin (252.1 square miles). Yikes! More interesting is the
observation of Sigrid Clift, University of Texas Bureau of Economic
Geology geologist. If you spread the world's population over Texas
(267,277 square miles), each person would have 1,250 square feet _
one person every 35 feet (front, back and side of another person)
across the state. Some walking on water, no doubt. The population
of the United States (271,645,000) needs only 9.7 square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I moved from Austin to Michigan and, boy, do I miss your
column. Can you help me with a customer satisfaction issue _ a
fiasco involving the Ryder truck used to move our stuff to
Michigan? Could you find out the president and CEO of the
responsible business? Ryder has been bought out and I have had a
hard time finding out who is on top. _ Pamela P.
</P>
<P>
   A: Ryder has been purchased by Budget group, whose chairman and
CEO is Sanford Miller, 125 Basin St., Suite 210, Daytona Beach, FL
32114. Ryder customer service issues are handled by Jan Richardson,
1560 Broadway, Suite 1800, Denver, CO. 80202.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My adorable 16-month-old niece recently devalued an antique
mahogany desk. She scribbled on two drawer fronts with a Sharpie
permanent marker. Please tell me I have an option other than having
the entire desk refinished. The Sharpie is black and the stain,
dark brown. I hope some type of blending process might decrease the
intensity. How about a black and brown shoe polish?
</P>
<P>
   _ Aunt Tracy N.
</P>
<P>
   A: Oops. Put the shoe polish back in the closet. Furniture
repair master Jim Neuberger says you may be able to remove the
black marks yourself. Dampen a clean rag with denatured alcohol and
quickly rub the marks. Wipe with a clean dry cloth and coat with
lemon oil. This should remove your Picasso's artwork. Not satisfied
with the results? You may be able to refinish the drawers without
refinishing the entire desk. Q: A calendar is being put together by
Sun City Georgetown called ``Aged Beef.'' It features active senior
men who, by the way, look great for their age! I would love to
purchase some of these calendars as Christmas gifts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Andrea Garduno
</P>
<P>
   A: Ideal for that senior lady on your holiday list. You can
order copies by calling (512) 864-1200, the Sun City Community
Association or online at aged-beef.com. The calendars (13 vigorous
men between the ages of 57 and 70) include retired Dallas Cowboy
Bob Lilly. Calendars are $9.95 plus tax and shipping. Proceeds go
to the National World War II Memorial Fund in Washington, D.C., and
the Georgetown Fire Department. The perfect gift for those who need
reminding that age is a state of mind.
</P>
<P>
   Q: About a year ago I co-signed a car loan for my son. He has
fallen behind on the payments, so I am now receiving letters and
phone calls to make the payments. Since co-signing, my finances
have decreased quite a bit and I do not see how I can make the
payments. Is there any way I can legally have my name removed, or
can I be forced to make these payments?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.B.
</P>
<P>
   A: Sorry, B.B., but in this case the creditor holds all the
cards, says Lonnie Williams, director of Consumer Credit Counseling
Service. You were asked to co-sign because the lender did not feel
your son could fulfill this obligation. CCCS discourages co-signing
unless you are willing and able to pay the entire debt.
</P>
<P>
   You should be concerned about protecting your credit. A lender
may offer an extension in extreme cases (loss of job, illness).
However, once the account is in arrears, extensions are rare.
</P>
<P>
   UPDATE/UPSHOT/UPROAR:
</P>
<P>
   _ Upshot/Update/Uproar: Hoping to piece together a unique
holiday gift for the runner or teen in your life? Consider making a
quilt out of that pile of oh-so-special T-shirts. Only basic sewing
skills are needed. Send $9.95 to T-Quilts, 14 Sunrise Point Court,
Lake Wylie, S.C. 29710 or order a kit online at www.tquilts.com.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Jane Greig, author of ``Thanks for Asking,'' at P.O. Box
670, Austin, TX 78767; (512) 445-3697; e-mail
jgreig(at)statesman.com or fax (512) 445-3968.
</P>
