<HEADER>
A2501 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN09-C     11-08 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLOWAY-TVCOLUMN09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Networks' youth movement got old in a hurry
 &HT;    By Diane Holloway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ And now a moment of silence _ or wild-eyed
cheering, depending on your point of view _ for the dearly
departed.
</P>
<P>
   The bodies traditionally begin piling up in late October and
early November, when the networks suddenly realize that an
embarrassing number of shows they touted so loudly in September are
fading fast in the Nielsens. Nobody's watching, and therefore
advertisers aren't buying. Pretty soon, cancellations happen.
</P>
<P>
   Cancellations, unlike development deals and premieres, are never
announced. They just happen. Thinly veiled terms like ``going on
hiatus'' are often used when replacements arrive. Asked if a series
was about to be canceled, a network president once told me, ``We
don't cancel series. We just don't renew them.'' Sometimes they
don't even finish out half the season before they're ``not
renewed.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC's lame sitcom ``The Mike O'Malley Show,'' rewritten twice in
its pilot stage (never a good sign), was the first to go _ after
two episodes. And the Peacock's ditzy 20-something relationship
dramedy ``Cold Feet'' turned toes up last week. CBS wasted no time
in axing ``Work With Me,'' a lackluster romantic comedy, after a
couple of weeks. Fox's teen sex sudser ``Manchester Prep,'' loosely
based on the movie ``Cruel Intentions,'' was canceled before it
premiered.
</P>
<P>
   Once the hottest and fastest-growing network, Fox is the sickest
this fall, down almost 20 percent in total viewership. ``Action,''
the most-hyped sitcom in recent memory (thanks to its bleeped-out
language), apparently has been bleeped from the consciousness of
millions of viewers. After the show finished in the Nielsen bottom
20, Fox yanked it from the schedule for the November sweeps with a
faint promise to return in December _ the month when absolutely
nobody watches television. Good plan.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also yanked the badge from its teen cop drama ``Ryan
Caulfield'' and deleted Chris Carter's virtual reality drama,
``Harsh Realm,'' from its mainframe. Sooner or later, the
possibility that Carter is a one-hit wonder must be considered.
``The X-Files'' is remarkable television, but Carter's second
series, ``Millennium,'' was a major dud.
</P>
<P>
   Not yet dead but heading in that direction are Fox's quirky
family drama ``Get Real,'' the half-hour ``Ally'' and Jennifer Love
Hewitt's disappointing ``Time of Your Life.'' Ditto NBC's superb
high-school drama ``Freaks and Geeks.'' ABC dropped the sitcom
``Then Came You,'' which nobody missed because nobody saw it, and
has temporarily shelved Kevin Williamson's ``Wasteland,'' a truly
vast wasteland of 20-something angst. The teen sitcom ``Odd Man
Out'' and the arrested development comedy ``Oh, Grow Up'' could be
next.
</P>
<P>
   Do you see a trend here? Actually, it's an anti-trend, a
rejection of the networks' obsession with teen and 20-something
dramas and anything resembling a comedy. The success stories this
season are dramas about adults _ ``Once and Again,'' ``Judging
Amy,'' ``Family Law,'' ``The West Wing,'' ``Law &AMP; Order: Special
Victims Unit'' and ``Now and Again.''
</P>
<P>
   When the New York advertising agency BBDO made its fall
predictions in July, dramas were correctly tagged a ``hot trend.''
But the qualifying phrase ``particularly hot are dramas targeted
toward young adults and teens'' turned out to be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Why? As Nielsen Media Research points out, teens and
20-somethings watch the least amount of TV of any demographic
group. A series on a major network targeted at this group would
have to appeal to a much wider audience to succeed, and this
season's offerings did not. ABC's ``Boy Meets World'' does to some
degree and ``The Wonder Years'' did to a great degree, but this
year's crop has a narrower focus.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-themed shows have a better chance of succeeding on the WB,
where lower ratings are tolerated. It's OK with WB and its
advertisers for ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' to be ranked 89th and
``Dawson's Creek'' to land at 91st, as they were last week, but NBC
needs much bigger ratings for 83rd-ranked ``Freaks and Geeks'' to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   With teens already juggling homework, extracurriculars and
yammering on the phone, maybe the networks should be content to
have them tuning into ``Friends,'' ``ER'' and ``The X-Files'' and
stop trying to carve out new shows in the teen image. If they're
already devoted to ``Buffy'' and ``Dawson,'' they probably don't
have time or appetite for more.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
