<HEADER>
A2503 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH09-COX     11-08 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NFK-NEWSFLASH09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Atlanta celebrates arrival of pandas
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Zoo Atlanta's two panda cubs landed Friday morning to
a cheering crowd of about 500 people. Lun-Lun and Yang-Yang flew
from China on a 767 cargo plane called the Panda Express. The zoo's
marketing director said the pandas had no problems on the trip from
Beijing and slept most of the way.
</P>
<P>
   The animals _ each inside a gray, steel cage _ were lowered
slowly to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The pandas will be quarantined for at least a week. The public
will be allowed to view them beginning Nov. 20.
</P>
<P>
   There are only about 1,000 pandas left in the world, with about
120 in zoos and other institutions. Two other U.S. zoos besides
Atlanta's have pandas.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists plan to study Lun-Lun and Yang-Yang to figure out how
to help them have babies in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   DO ACTION FIGURES SEND WRONG MESSAGE TO KIDS?
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart stores pulled a wrestling toy from its shelves last
week after complaints. The toy was a WWF wrestler carrying a
woman's head. it was modeled after Al Snow, a world wrestling
federation competitor who carries a female mannequin's head into
the ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our management has decided it is at least a questionable
item,'' said John Bisio, a store spokesman. ``So we are removing it
from the shelf, probably permanently.''
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Kinnick of Powder Springs co-authored an essay
protesting the toy in last week's Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's terrific to see corporations do the right thing _ and
that a couple of Cobb County moms can make a difference,'' said
Kinnick. ``My sons are 6 and 11. What kind of message would this
toy send them about brutalization of women?''
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM HIT BY FLOODS
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross and Vietnamese government began airlifts last week
to help thousands of victims of flooding. It is the worst flooding
in Vietnam in 40 years. More than 300 people have been killed.
</P>
<P>
   With rain still falling, helicopters landed to pass out food to
stranded residents. The United Nations estimates more than 1
million people need emergency food and more than 500,000 homes have
been submerged.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
