<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 11:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2523 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN10-CO     11-08 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: A vote for Churchill as Man of the Century
 &HT;    (For release Nov. 10, 1999.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid consternation that Adolf Hitler could be voted the most
influential creature of this waning century, I'd like to put in my
bid for the man who stamped him out: Winston Churchill. In doing
so, Churchill saved Western civilization from the Nazi hordes.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't appear that Churchill will be the ultimate leader in
Time magazine's electronic poll _ and likely will finish behind
Elvis Presley _ but that's generational stuff.
</P>
<P>
   It is much like the recent baseball team of the century, in
which relatively few who played before 1945 were voted in, while a
present-day player _ outstanding but not yet deity _ was. Most of
the voters never saw any of the players of the early part of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you had to also live the Churchill years to realize the
scope of this man's influence. Otherwise, you had to pick it up
from books such as William Manchester's two completed volumes on
him or granddaughter Celia Sandys' two volumes, both of which leave
us on the brink of World War II and the greatest Churchill years of
all.
</P>
<P>
   I've had a bit of both. I picked up Churchill where the two
biographers have left off. As a youth during World War II, I came
to realize how much he meant to England, to the United States and
to the world.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, I had no knowledge of his earlier escapades in
South Africa, or the disaster at Gallipoli. I only knew that when
the world was threatened by Nazi Germany, he stood alone to face up
to them, and he prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Rushed into the prime minister's role after Neville
Chamberlain's failed appeasement of Hitler, he inherited a
monstrous job. The Nazis ruled western Europe and had, in its
sights, the British Isles.
</P>
<P>
   With little and outdated equipment, with far less personnel than
the Nazis, and with an ocean separating Great Britain from the
nearest free country, the United States, Churchill went to war with
words.
</P>
<P>
   His speeches to the British people were exhilarating, so much so
that he rallied them from the gloom and horror of nightly Nazi
bombings: ``Never give in, never give in, never, never, never,
never _ in nothing, great or small, large or petty _ never give in
except to convictions of honor and good sense.''
</P>
<P>
   When he wasn't inspiring his people, he was romancing a
sympathetic Franklin D. Roosevelt to be a supplier of war materiel:
``Give us the tools, and we will finish the job.''
</P>
<P>
   He rallied the outnumbered Royal Air Force, whose Spitfire
fighter planes took on a superior but not as inspired Nazi
Luftwaffe. ``Never in the field of human conflict was so much owed
to so many by so few,'' he boasted of his fliers.
</P>
<P>
   Had there not been a Winston Churchill during those dark days,
the world likely would be much different today. It would be
Hitler's world with all the depravation that would result from it.
</P>
<P>
   His influence with Roosevelt, his ability to overcome an
isolationist-bent Congress and a strong America First lobby,
propelled Churchill as the pillar of Western freedom, the man who
held the Nazis at bay until such time when the U.S. was compelled
to enter the war. Britain was saved from the Nazis before then _
and it was Churchill's doing, with help from Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt that Hitler was quite influential but in a
deadly way. He was Satan on Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Others were more influential in a positive way. One such person
was Dr. Jonas Salk, who discovered a vaccine to defeat polio.
Another is Billy Graham, who evangelized much of this nation
without the circus-like atmosphere that exists among other
evangelists today. And Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., who inspired a
nation to look within itself and who was an orator on a par with
Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   But they could not have been influential had not Winston
Churchill, years earlier, saved us all from the darkness that
threatened this world.
</P>
<P>
   The last I noted, Elvis still led the pack, Hitler was third and
Churchill was back in the second ten. Think about the absurdity of
that.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
