 Monday, Nov. 8, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Tuesday. If you have questions, please call Mark Helm at
202-298-6920.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYORAL (San Francisco) _ As San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown
and Board of Supervisors President Tom Ammiano begin a political
battle to become the city's next leader, their campaigns for the
Dec. 14 runoff election already appear to be vastly different.
Ammiano is seeking to widen his base of support by registering new
voters, many of them in the Mission District. Brown's campaign is
more focused on improving voter turnout in his traditional
strongholds. By GREGORY LEWIS.
</P>
<P>
   RACIAL-PROFILING (Piedmont, Calif.) _ This affluent, largely
white enclave famed for its elegant homes, good schools and,
residents say, ``politeness and protocol,'' has found itself
grappling with race relations after allegations of racial profiling
by town police provoked a good deal of civic upset and, some say,
illuminating debate. By ANNIE NAKAO.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-NETSCAPE (San Francisco) _ Jim Barksdale's moment of
vindication came this past Friday while he was sitting in
bumper-to- bumper traffic near the Getty Museum in Los Angeles.
Barksdale, former president of Netscape Communications Corp., found
out that a federal judge had just ruled that Microsoft Corp. was a
monopoly determined to dominate the computer industry. One of the
companies the judge said Microsoft had savaged was Mountain
View-based Netscape. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NEW-PROFILE (Berkeley, Calif.) _ On a recent Friday
evening, author Michael Lewis gave a talk at the University of
California at Berkeley about his much-hyped book, ``The New New
Thing.'' He explained why he choose to focus his chronicle of
Silicon Valley on another contradictory figure, serial entrepreneur
Jim Clark. By BRAD WIENERS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS-RATTO (San Francisco) _ As the final seconds of
Sunday's 49ers-Steelers game evaporated into nothingness, one
couldn't help but notice that the 49ers and their fans had done so
as well. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS-KNAPP (San Francisco) _ San Francisco 49ers star
receiver Jerry Rice asked reporters to figure out what ails the
49ers. He said it rhetorically, as a way out of a trap, his only
way out. By GWEN KNAPP.
</P>
<P>
   OUTDOORS-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ A gray area in the California
Vehicle Code is causing a black-and-white showdown with deadly
results on the twisty back roads of the Bay Area. Every time a
group of bike riders encounter a speeding car on one of the narrow
country roads in the foothills, there becomes a moment of truth and
decision. By TOM STIENSTRA.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-GIANTS-STADIUM (San Francisco) _ Not long after Chiura Obata
immigrated to San Francisco in 1903, he fell in love with baseball.
The love affair prompted him to launch the first Japanese American
baseball team on the mainland. Now, almost 100 years after Obata's
arrival, it is his 77-year-old son Gyo Obata who is leaving his
mark on San Francisco baseball. His St. Louis-based HOK
Incorporated, founded in 1955, designed Pacific Bell Park, the new
home of the Giants scheduled to open in April. By RYAN KIM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Maybe you think Tom Ammiano
versus Willie Brown is going to be a political version of the San
Francisco Stand-up Comedy Competition. Maybe you think this will be
all fun and games, one wild and crazy liberal versus a wilder and
crazier liberal. Forget it. Of all the surprises in the San
Francisco mayor's race, the biggest surprise is yet to come. Two of
the wittiest, quirkiest, meanest show-offs in America have to play
it straight. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco, Calif.) _ Although it can become a
dangerous oversimplification of the concept, the popular idea that
you actually sow and reap karma holds a great deal of appeal.
Deliberately sow good stuff, and it will come back to you as good
stuff _ or at least as a milder dose of bad stuff you were already
in karmic line to receive. Sow bad karma and, sooner or later, it
will come back to bite you on the butt. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON (Washington) _ Enough already about Hillary
Clinton running for the Senate in New York. It's never going to
happen. Period. Over the course of the last few months, I have been
the Washington equivalent of Chicken Little, telling anyone who
would listen that the first lady is not running, never really
intended to run, and in fact will never run for the Senate in New
York State. By DOUGLAS MACKINNON,
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHERNERS (Undated) _ What should we make of the list of this
century's 100 most influential Southerners, as voted by the readers
of the Atlanta Journal-Constitution? In one way it's just another
bag of big names, another bogus Millennium List that begs to be
second-guessed. But in another way it's downright grotesque _ turns
out you don't even have to be a Southerner to make it. By EDVINS
BEITIKS.
</P>
</TEXT>
