<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2543 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-PIERCE-BROSNAN-IN-THE     11-08 1425
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIERCE-BROSNAN-IN-THE-WORLD-IS-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIERCE BROSNAN: JAMES BOND IS NOT ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Pierce Brosnan with Denise Richards in a
scene from ``The World Is Not Enough.'') 
 By CINDY PEARLMAN  
 World rights except Chicago 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    It isn't easy being James Bond.
 &HT;    Just ask Pierce Brosnan, who makes his third appearance in the
role with ``The World Is Not Enough,'' opening Nov. 19.
 &HT;    Bond may dine at lavish gourmet restaurants and sip martinis _
shaken, of course, but not stirred _ but the actor who plays him
has to watch his figure.
 &HT;    ``I lay off the red wine and the cream sauces,'' Brosnan says
with a laugh. ``It's heinous being James Bond!
 &HT;    ``Before I do the love scenes,'' he adds, ``I have to remind
myself, `Pierce, you have been seminaked on stage before. You've
been naked on film.'
 &HT;    ``Then I look in the mirror and think, `Jesus, does my stomach
look flat enough?'
 &HT;    ``I'm like any woman preparing to show her body on screen in a
love scene,'' Brosnan admits. ``I live in the gym for months before
these movies. For God's sake, I lift large weights.''
 &HT;    Over coffee on a Sunday morning, the handsome actor is dressed
in white-silk slacks, a matching shirt and two days of facial
stubble. He likes to complain about being Bond but, rumors to the
contrary, he insists that this isn't his last spin as 007.
 &HT;    ``Contractually this is my last Bond film,'' he says. ``I'm
contracted for three, with the option of a fourth. And the last
three I've gone out the door with very quickly _ I've done these
movies rapidly to establish myself as the character.
 &HT;    ``Of course, now there are other characters I want to do who are
not James Bond,'' he adds. ``So I'm not in any hurry to do the
fourth Bond.''
 &HT;    On the other hand, he admits that he'd hate to see someone else
in the role.
 &HT;    ``Look, we'll do a fourth Bond,'' he says. ``I want to do a
fourth Bond.''
 &HT;    ``The World Is Not Enough'' has a lot of excitement, action and
suspense, Brosnan reports _ and one thing more.
 &HT;    ``Great title,'' he says in all due seriousness. ``I've always
been happy with all of my Bond titles _ except `Tomorrow Never
Lies,' which ironically is how it went to the print shop. There was
a typo and someone wrote, `Tomorrow Never Dies.' And the studio
said, `Damn it, we love it!'
 &HT;    ``But `The World is Not Enough' won't change,'' he says,
``because it's James Bond's motto from the original books _ that
was actually the family motto of the entire Bond family.''
 &HT;    The film shows a newer, slightly mellower Bond, the actor says.
 &HT;    ``In the new Bond we really paid attention to character,'' he
says. ``We have a story that has a bit more maturity than the other
two. Of course, it has action _ but I couldn't do just wall-to-wall
explosions. I just can't do it, it's boring.
 &HT;    ``I wanted an emotional content,'' he says, ``so you have
something to hold onto, and then you can jump off into the fantasy
of it all.''
 &HT;    The change in Bond merely reflects the evolution of the actor
behind him, he says.
 &HT;    ``Brosnan has changed,'' the actor says. ``I've gotten a bit
more comfortable with the role, and so much of acting is about your
confidence, relaxation and your faith in yourself, because you're
constantly being judged. The last two Bond movies have done well,
so I feel very relaxed in the role.
 &HT;    ``I also put my trust in Michael Apted, a documentarian and
diverse moviemaker who really added so much as our director.''
 &HT;    The latest film features the usual curvaceous ``Bond girls'' _
this time around, Denise Richards as Dr. Christmas Jones and Sophie
Marceau as Electra King. Robert Carlyle plays the latest villain, a
terrorist who is impervious to pain and thinks he can't die.
 &HT;    ``He dies,'' Brosnan says flatly. ``He ain't coming back.
Neither did any other Bond baddie I've been given. Good actors,
good Bond villains _ they ain't coming back. I killed them all. No
bouncing back.
 &HT;    ``I'm a lethal guy,'' he jokes, ``and don't you forget it.''
 &HT;    Brosnan's success as Bond is all the more striking in that, when
he was first offered the role in 1986, he was forced to decline due
to his obligations to his hit television show, ``Remington Steele''
(1982-1987). Timothy Dalton took the role in ``The Living
Daylights'' (1987), and it wasn't until ``Goldeneye'' (1995) that
Brosnan got his chance.
 &HT;    The success of ``Goldeneye'' and ``Tomorrow Never Dies'' (1997)
has made Brosnan a major star, but he shows little signs of
Hollywood ego.
 &HT;    ``I treat what I do like a hobby,'' he says. ``I don't let it
obsess me.
 &HT;    ``Yes, I have an ego,'' he adds. ``I want to win _ I always want
to win, I always want the best. You have to strive that high. I
admit that, as soon as I step out on stage, the show is about me.
That's the way it is, whether I'm playing two lines or my name is
above the title.
 &HT;    ``Apart from that, the joy of this career is keeping it in its
place.''
 &HT;    The death of his wife, Cassie, from ovarian cancer several years
ago helped give him a sense of perspective.
 &HT;    ``Her illness was completely unexpected,'' he recalls. ``It hit
me like a shot.''
 &HT;    He pauses, his voice choked with emotion.
 &HT;    ``I guess I learned that life doesn't cooperate with a man's
plans,'' he says. ``Her illness wasn't the way we talked about it
or planned our life. But it happens, and you just have to get on
with it and make the best of it.
 &HT;    ``I learned to appreciate the time we have here,'' he concludes.
``I appreciate everything now.''
 &HT;    Brosnan has a lot to appreciate _ being a movie star was his
boyhood dream since he saw ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' (1968), one
of the first films he encountered growing up in Drogheda in County
Louth, Ireland.
 &HT;    ``That was my introduction to the movies,'' he recalls, ``and I
left that theater wanting to be Steve McQueen. But then I went to
another movie, and I wanted to be Clint Eastwood. I was a
15-year-old kid in Ireland, living through the movies.''
 &HT;    Nowadays, however, the movies isn't enough. Brosnan also has a
2-year-old son, Dylan, whose mother is the actor's longtime
girlfriend _ and, recently, fiancee _ Keely Shaye Smith.
 &HT;    Say, Pierce, when's the wedding?
 &HT;    ``Give us a break, now,'' Brosnan begs, laughing. ``Just let us
find our space here. It's a good time for us.
 &HT;    ``Relationships take patience, love and understanding,'' he
says. ``We're learning how families work, which isn't always easy
in this world _ or especially in this business.''
 &HT;    Yes, movie stars have to face the ``terrible twos,'' just like
anyone else.
 &HT;    ``A few months ago we got on the plane from Los Angeles to
Nairobi for a family holiday,'' Brosnan recalls. ``Dylan had a
total meltdown, the poor boy. Suddenly I'm not James Bond anymore _
I'm making cow noises, and if people don't like it, tough.''
 &HT;    Believe it or not, Brosnan _ who also has two sons from his
first marriage _ recently became a grandfather, courtesy of his
stepdaughter, Charlotte.
 &HT;    ``We don't say `grandfather,''' he cautions. ``We say `pappy.'
`Granddad' is just not a word I want to put on myself right now.
Please don't call me that _ I'm still young and vital.
 &HT;    ``For God's sake, I'm James Bond!''
 c.1999 Cindy Pearlman  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Cindy Pearlman is a Chicago-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``The World Is Not Enough,''
consult the MGM-United Artists Website at www.mgmua.com. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
