<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2544 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-CHRIS-ROCK-IN-DOGMA-S     11-08 1256
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHRIS-ROCK-IN-DOGMA-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROCK ON: CHRIS ROCK BRINGS HIS OWN PRIVATE EDGE TO `DOGMA' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Chris Rock with Linda Fiorentino in a
scene from ``Dogma.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Chris Rock stepped into the offices of Miramax Films with
visions of ``The Piano'' and ``Life Is Beautiful'' dancing in his
head.
 &HT;    And the powers that be in the Oscar factory handed him a script
called ``Joyride.''
 &HT;    ``I go to Miramax, the home of cool movies,'' says Rock, whose
film credits include the not-that-cool ``Boomerang'' (1992),
``CB4'' (1994) and ``Lethal Weapon 4'' (1998). ``I'd just won an
Emmy. I've got two Emmys. I'm all over the place. I'm hot, hot,
hot.
 &HT;    ``So I'm `Yeah, good. I'll do some good movies.''' he recalls.
``I get there and they offer me this, a movie with a bunch of
rappers on a bus going to make a video.''
 &HT;    Rock shakes his head and rolls his eyes.
 &HT;    ``I'm like, `Oh, my God, what the f--k is this?''' he says.
``You know what's weird? They offered me more money to date than
I've been offered for anything _ it was only a week's worth of
work.''
 &HT;    But Rock didn't give up so fast on his idea of getting in on
Miramax's cutting-edge independent-film lineup.
 &HT;    ``I said, `What's Kevin Smith doing?''' he says. ``I'd just seen
`Chasing Amy' (1997), and I loved it. It spoke to me _ I'd been in
love with girls with reputations and definitely didn't handle it
right.
 &HT;    ``And Kevin happened to be doing something. They let me see the
script.''
 &HT;    The script turned out to be ``Dogma,'' the year's most
controversial film. A black comedy about religion, it pits fallen
angels Loki (Matt Damon) and Bartleby (Ben Affleck) against a group
of unlikely heroes that includes God's messenger (Alan Rickman), a
Muse (Salma Hayek), mankind's all-too-human would-be savior (Linda
Fiorentino) and Rufus (Rock), the 13th apostle, who blames
political reasons for his exclusion from the Scriptures.
 &HT;    ``Dogma'' proved so controversial _ both in its provocative
religious ideas and its savage mocking of a corporate conglomerate
that strongly suggested the Walt Disney Company, Miramax's
corporate parent _ that the studio felt compelled to relinquish the
film after its completion. Lions Gate Films picked it up, and will
release it nationwide on Nov. 12.
 &HT;    Rock says he never even considered the possibility that
``Dogma'' might be too controversial for him.
 &HT;    ``Me?'' he asks, laughing.
 &HT;    Actually, he says during a conversation at New York's Regency
Hotel, he wouldn't mind going a lot further than writer/director
Smith does with ``Dogma.'' There are no limits at all, as far as
he's concerned.
 &HT;    ``Everything should be skewered and satirized,'' he says
matter-of-factly. ``Nothing is above jokes. You should be able to
see the funny side of everything.
 &HT;    ``I don't want to go to heaven if it ain't funny,'' he adds.
``If heaven ain't funny, it ain't heaven.''
 &HT;    Controversy comes easily to Rock. He began performing as a
stand-up comedian at age 17, he recalls, and his act consisted of
jokes about ``getting pizza and waiting for my girlfriend's period
to come.''
 &HT;    Growing up on the tough streets of Brooklyn's Bedford-Stuyvesant
neighborhood, Rock remembers being regularly beaten up and
ridiculed by white schoolmates. Religion never really played a
major role in his life, he says.
 &HT;    ``There were a lot of churches,'' the 33-year-old comedian says,
``and no sign of God.''
 &HT;    Rock later put his acerbic wit to use on ``In Living Color'' and
``Saturday Night Live,'' establishing a reputation as a fearless
funnyman. More recently, he was criticized for poking too much fun
at the likes of Ricky Martin when he hosted the 1999 MTV Awards.
 &HT;    He makes no apologies.
 &HT;    ``I think I kept the show going,'' Rock says. ``That was my job.
Where is it written that the host can't be a performer, too?
 &HT;    ``As long as you don't get personal with people,'' he says,
``you can pretty much get away with it.''
 &HT;    Besides ``Dogma,'' Rock has several other projects in the works
at the moment. The first issue of The Illtop Journal, which he
describes as ``a black version of The Harvard Lampoon,'' is due out
later this month, and he's completed the Neil LaBute comedy ``Nurse
Betty,'' which casts him and Morgan Freeman as hitmen seeking to
eliminate Renee Zellweger.
 &HT;    Early next year Rock will shoot ``I Was Made To Love Her,'' a
romantic comedy that he's co-written. In the meantime, though, his
primary focus is his HBO program, ``The Chris Rock Show.''
 &HT;    ``It's the most important thing I'm doing, artistically,'' he
says. ``It's important that it exists, because it's just a
different type of show _ it's different, from the interviews to the
comedy to the music.
 &HT;    ``There are no other black talk shows or entertainment shows at
all.''
 &HT;    The show's audience includes a substantial number of white
viewers, to the surprise of many observers _ but not of Rock
himself.
 &HT;    ``Comedy always crosses over, for the most part,'' Rock says.
``When I was a kid, we didn't say Rodney Dangerfield was a funny
white guy.''
 &HT;    Rock may be a star now, but he still remembers his leaner days,
toiling as a busboy at a local Red Lobster. Some of the people he
knew during those days still work at Red Lobster, he says, a few in
management capacities.
 &HT;    ``I was a busboy because I wasn't good enough to be a waiter,''
Rock says, smiling. ``There's nothing separating me from them,
except that I write a decent joke now and then.''
 &HT;    Well, the fact that he earns millions of dollars a year and gets
to make movies with major stars may be a bit of a distinguishing
factor. But Rock still lives in Brooklyn, and remains pretty
low-key for such a high-profile guy.
 &HT;    ``Celebrity is nonsense,'' he says. ``I look at it as people are
appreciating my work. There are a lot of celebrities who ain't
going to be here next year or six months from now or three months
from now. I'm just glad people are appreciating my work ...
 &HT;    ``I live good,'' he says. ``I dropped out of school, I'm a black
guy _ I live great.''
 &HT;    Which may be why he's always happy to turn his comic invective
against celebrities who whine about the inconveniences of stardom.
 &HT;    ``They're idiots,'' he says.
 c.1999 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Dogma,'' consult the official
Website at www.dogma.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
