<SLUG> BC-LOCKLEAR-AND-FOX-IN-SPIN-CITY-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRESH `SPIN': HEATHER LOCKLEAR AND MICHAEL J. FOX TEAM UP ON
`SPIN CITY' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of Heather Locklear and Michael J. Fox in a
scene from ``Spin City.'') 
 By ANDREW RYAN  
 c.1999 TV Guide Canada  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talking Heather Locklear into joining the cast of ``Spin City''
wasn't that hard.
</P>
<P>
   When the former ``Melrose Place'' vixen was offered the chance
to co-star with Michael J. Fox in the popular ABC political sitcom,
shortly after her previous show closed up shop last spring, she had
only one question that needed to be answered: ``Where do I sign?''
</P>
<P>
   Locklear has been a television fixture since her 1981 debut on
``Dynasty,'' and by the time she heard from ``Spin City'' was
already weighing offers to join several other series, including
``Two Guys and a Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``Spin City'' had an ace in the hole _ Locklear was a
regular viewer, and knew the show and star/executive producer Fox
intimately.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, world, even television stars watch television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's a clever, smart show,'' Locklear says. ``So,
being a fan of the show and of a cast that's so wonderful, it was
just an easy decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox welcomed Locklear's arrival as a shot in the arm for ``Spin
City,'' which despite critical raves had only-decent ratings in its
first three years, and this year inherited the crucial slot in
ABC's Tuesday-night schedule formerly occupied by the top-rated
``Home Improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's not kid ourselves,'' he says. ``She brings tremendous
attention and excitement to the show, and a real energy. Most
importantly, she's a nice person.''
</P>
<P>
   The new-look ``Spin City'' casts Locklear as Caitlin Kelly, a
no-nonsense political operative hired as campaign manager for New
York's Mayor Randall Winston (Barry Bostwick) as he plans a run for
the United States Senate. Her abrupt, miniskirted presence jars
mayoral assistant Mike Flaherty (Fox), who suddenly finds his
political clout in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, Mike has been kind of king of the office for three
years now,'' Fox says, ``and he never really had anybody on his
level of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Thinking it over, the show's writers decided that it would be
dramatically effective to introduce a strong female character to
shake up the show and put Mike on the defensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we said, `Who will we cast?''' Fox recalls. ``And we
thought, `You know, in a perfect world, you get, like, Heather
Locklear.'
</P>
<P>
   ``So somebody said, `Let's make that call _ and then we'll move
on and figure out who's really going to do it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``And, I swear to God,'' he says with a laugh, ``the next day we
get this call saying Heather is very flattered, loves the show and
is considering doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Television being television _ and Locklear having the television
history she does _ there's already speculation that Fox and
Locklear will be paired off romantically. It's understandable,
given ABC's sassy promos, which feature Locklear slapping Fox,
throwing water in his face and then landing a big smacker right on
his lips.
</P>
<P>
   So is love in the air between these two?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is that potential any time you have two characters in an
antagonistic relationship,'' Fox says cryptically. ``But that's
down the road, so we're still exploring that.''
</P>
<P>
   Introducing any new romantic interest for Fox's character is
going to be a bit tricky, though. In last season's finale, Mike
Flaherty cheated on his statuesque, in-office girlfriend Nikki
(Connie Britton) by having a fling with supermodel Heidi Klum.
</P>
<P>
   Nikki won't be disappearing into thin air, Fox hastens to add.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still Mike-and-Nikki stuff to do,'' Fox says, ``and we
want that to always be a special relationship. They have a history
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Individually, both Fox and Locklear have outside factors
complicating their efforts to acclimate to one another. Locklear
became a mother for the first time last year, and to take the role
on ``Spin City'' she had to leave her Hollywood home with her baby
and her husband, rocker Richie Sambora, to move to New York, where
the show is taped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately I have a wonderful husband who grew up on the East
Coast,'' she says. ``But a little change is good for growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox is a Canadian by birth, but by now considers himself enough
of an adopted New Yorker to be amused at Locklear's efforts to get
to know the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as New York goes, it's so funny, because Heather is
such a neophyte,'' he says. ``I mean, she has no idea. If you told
her, `Be in Greenwich Village and in five minutes meet me at
Central Park,' she'd say, `OK!'''
</P>
<P>
   Fox's situation is far less amusing, and far more complicated. A
year ago he revealed publicly that for several years he'd been
battling Parkinson's Disease. The nervous-system ailment is
degenerative and incurable, but Fox claims that his symptoms are
being kept under control through medication.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the only concession he's made has been to switch ``Spin
City's'' taping night from Friday to Tuesday, in order to allow
himself a midweek rest break.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel pretty good,'' he says, shrugging. ``It's like anything
when you have an ongoing condition ... It's something you monitor
on a daily basis and treat therapeutically.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I feel confident with my ability to do my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox and Locklear had never worked together before, but from
their first days on ``Spin City'' their chemistry was clearly
apparent. This didn't surprise him, Fox says, because he had
actually crossed paths with Locklear once before, when they shared
a table at the 1996 Golden Globe Awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know if Heather will remember this,'' Fox says,
``but she was nominated and I was nominated, and we were way in the
back ... Kathy Bates was at our table, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't win and Heather didn't win,'' Fox recalls, ``but I
really enjoyed being with Heather. So when we talked about her
coming on this show, I knew she had what we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Andrew Ryan is the features editor for TV Guide Canada, based
in West York, Ontario.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Spin City,'' consult the ABC
Website at www.abc.com. And don't forget to visit The New York
Times Syndicate Website at http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for
information on StarBeat and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
