<HEADLINE>
TORI AMOS' ROAD TO VENUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's StarBeat
entertainment package.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to StarBeat, a weekly
package of five intriguing features with color art.) 
 (Includes a color slide of singer Tori Amos.) 
 By GARY GRAFF  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Not so long ago, Tori Amos spoke of fairies that inspired her
songs and brought her ideas and melodies.
 &HT;    These days, however, she's hearing the clarion call of Venus.
 &HT;    Coming relatively hot on the heels of ``From the Choirgirl
Hotel'' (1998), Amos' new album, ``To Venus and Back'' (Atlantic
Records, 1999), is actually a happy accident, what was intended as
a B-side collection until it spun out of control and became a full
new set of songs _ in addition to a second disc of live recordings
from her 1998 tour.
 &HT;    ``The engineers started looking at me and said, `Theoretically,
this does not work in a B-side concept,''' says the Maryland-born
Amos, who resides in southwest England with her husband, engineer
Mark Hawley, and also produced ``To Venus and Back.'' ``I said `OK,
why?'
 &HT;    ``And they said, `It's like an ecosystem. You can't just extract
this out _ it'll feel random. It doesn't sonically have a geometric
shape.'
 &HT;    ``Now, they're engineers,'' she says with a laugh. ``They're out
of their minds. But they do understand that realm, and I began to
see it was valid what they were saying _ the B-side thing became
just so hodgepodge. It became clear it was to be a new work.''
 &HT;    Amos already had the title, too, from a conversation with
friends over a bottle of wine.
 &HT;    ``One of them said, `You'd go to Venus, Tori, if you could,'''
she recalls. ``Once I decided I was calling this `To Venus and
Back,' it was almost as if the songs from Venus decided to say
`These are fragments from Venus she's willing to show you this
time,' and I felt like I climbed up on this little satellite and
started roaming around her heart.''
 &HT;    If that sounds a little far-out, you've never spent any time
with Amos. Those who know her well from her work _ beginning with
``Little Earthquake'' (1992) _ are used to such mystical
pronouncements.
 &HT;    During the past eight years, Amos has established herself as an
idiosyncratic personality who also happens to be one of the most
arresting and provocative performers to emerge in decades, a
singer, songwriter and instrumentalist with a unique voice and
empathetic bent that's won her a rabid and sizable following.
 &HT;    A musical prodigy since the age of 5, when she began studying at
Baltimore's Peabody Conservatory, the former Myra Ellen Amos'
albums _ excepting the pop-tinged ``Y Kant Tori Read'' (1988) _
have been marked by distinctive approaches to songwriting and
arranging, with swooping, offbeat dynamics that have been imitated
by a legion of Lilith Fair-generation admirers.
 &HT;    In her lyrics, the minister's daughter has sung about being
raped at gunpoint and about seducing God. In ``To Venus and
Back's'' opening track and first single, ``Bliss,'' she details the
struggles between a daughter and a father, representing the latter
as both a divine and a parental entity.
 &HT;    Amos made a significant change with ``Choirgirl Hotel,''
however. It wasn't the first time she had employed other
instruments on record, but it was the first time she had used a
full band throughout. She even recorded most of the tracks live in
the studio with the other players.
 &HT;    ``The songs usually dictate what I'm going to do,'' Amos says,
adding that she usually hears ``loads of instruments'' in her head
while she's writing.
 &HT;    She's continued the full-band approach on ``Venus.'' Like
``Choirgirl Hotel,'' the album was produced by Amos and engineered
by her husband, along with Marcel van Limbeek. This time she used
the four musicians who accompanied her on the road after
``Choirgirl'' was released, who can also be heard on ``To Venus and
Back's'' live disc.
 &HT;    ``I think when you live nine months on a bus with guys, you
begin to know when all their periods are,'' says Amos, who tends to
assign female attributes to all facets of life. ``There's an
intimacy. The same people play on the live record that played on
the studio record ... So there's that continuity. We know what we
mean.
 &HT;    ``Like on `Concertina,''' she says, ``it was very much Jon
(Evans), the bass player _ who's a genius bass player _ but it was
`No, no, no. You are a fierce calm. You never let up.' And he knew
what I wanted.''
 &HT;    Working with a band presented a new challenge to Amos as
producer, too. But she says that, over time, she's becoming more
comfortable with that role as well.
 &HT;    ``I was really open to what all those knobs did in the studio,''
she says. ``I opened myself up to it on `Choirgirl.' It's like
synchronized swimming _ you work with a team and, after awhile, it
becomes improvisational, sonically. You trust that it's all going
to shift and change, and that doesn't frighten you. That fascinates
you.
 &HT;    ``And I'm somebody who goes right in there, all the way,'' she
says. ``You can see the intestines of the ant, microscopic, every
little detail. But the engineers are that way, too. They're really
hard-core, audio-pornography obsessed.''
 &HT;    Despite that adherence to detail, Amos reports that the making
of the album was relatively peaceful _ and quick, which was good,
since she went on to spend five and a half weeks on the road with
Alanis Morissette in a kind of summit of female pop powers. In
fact, she says, ``To Venus and Back'' was made in half the time she
usually takes to make a single set, which to her was ``like,
nuts.''
 &HT;    But she's not complaining, either.
 &HT;    ``We were very tweaked and very present, and this record was
demanding us to be very present,'' Amos says. ``And she was so
seductive, none of us could sleep. None of us wanted to sleep.
 &HT;    ``It was like some Dionysian frenzy _ we didn't want to stop,''
she says. ``It was a fierce calm, and I liked that.''
 c.1999 Gary Graff  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Gary Graff is a Beverly Hills, Mich.-based free-lance
writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``To Venus and Back,'' consult
the Atlantic Records Website at www.atlantic-records.com. And don't
forget to visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL; 
