<HEADLINE>
FOR THIS AUTO TESTER, A LITTLE UNIFORMITY, PLEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I slip into the driver's seat of my latest test car, snap on the
seatbelt and turn the ignition.
</P>
<P>
   The seatback comes up and forward, pushing my chest to the
steering wheel. The front of the seat rises, crunching my thighs.
And then the whole seat moves forward, amplifying all the crunching
and pushing that is going on. It's one of those automatic
driver-memory seats and the driver it is remembering certainly was
not built like me.
</P>
<P>
   Such is life when you slip behind the wheel of a new car every
week.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, one of the questions I am most frequently asked by
those curious about my job, which is testing cars and writing about
them, is how long it takes to get used to the vagaries,
idiosyncracies, and basic operation of each car.
</P>
<P>
   It can be a demanding enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   I reach to the left of the steering column for the turn signal.
Finding the stem, I click it down. Suddenly, the car surges ahead,
picking up speed on its own. Baffled, I look down. I have hit the
resume mode for cruise control. I find the turn signal stem
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   I am driving as the sun goes down and I turn on the headlights,
turning the controls clockwise as far as they will go. I drive on,
thinking the blue glow of these high-tech European headlights is
less illuminating than I would have expected. Soon, approaching
drivers are flicking their headlights at me. Do I have my brights
on? I click the dimmer switch. Nothing. I pull over, turn on the
interior lights and discover one of those idiosyncracies. On this
car, you can turn right past the headlights ``on'' position to
another where all you have lit up are side parking lights.
</P>
<P>
   These are funky variations. Others are more serious.
</P>
<P>
   On some cars, a steady pressure on the brake pedal will bring
you to a gradual, sure stop. On others, touch the brake pedal and
you are thrust against the seatbelt.
</P>
<P>
   Move from a week in a high-powered front-wheel drive car,
hellbent on torque steering you off the chosen line, and move into
a high-powered rear-wheel drive car and it takes some time behind
the wheel to stop watching out for torque steer and instead
watching for the moment the rear wheels try to break away.
</P>
<P>
   And there are wonderful, light-hearted moments that have found
me chuckling to myself as I explored _ on-the-job-training _ the
intricacies of dashboards and their knobs and buttons.
</P>
<P>
   I have reached out, mind still set on the previous car and not
the one I am driving that moment, and hit the button for more heat.
The radio responded by going up so loud it set my eardrums to
ringing.
</P>
<P>
   I have pulled up to toll booths, hit the button to lower my
window, and set off my emergency flashers _ all the better to
attract attention to this lout who is now holding up the toll line
as he searches the car for the window buttons.
</P>
<P>
   I have missed important moments in Red Sox games, rolling into
the broad reaches of New England where Boston stations fade out and
I need to find a local broadcast of the game, all because I could
not figure out how to tune the radio.
</P>
<P>
   I fairly toasted a daughter on a hot summer day _ ``Ah, dad.
Why's this seat so hot?'' _ when I hit the seat heating button,
thinking I was turning up the fan. This same daughter has a radar
for the hidden cupholders I can never seem to find on my own.
</P>
<P>
   I have opened sunroofs in the rain, rolled down back windows by
mistake, popped a trunk lid trying to automatically lock the doors,
and spent embarassing minutes at gas pumps trying to figure out how
to open the lid covering the gas cap.
</P>
<P>
   Each car is a new adventure wrapped in a puzzle. The puzzle
always gets solved, but sometimes it takes a while. But it is what
is great about driving a new car each week. Something to learn
every time.
</P>
<P>
   Another daughter once showed me how cars and culture can at
times be at odds.
</P>
<P>
   One rule on these test cars is that no one is supposed to smoke
in them _ but occasionally a prior occupant has done just that.
</P>
<P>
   That is how it happened that this daughter _ in an age when
smoking is dying as fast as smokers _ opened the ashtray in the
dash, saw that it was filled with cigarette butts and uttered,
``Gross, Dad. Somebody put cigarette butts in the coin thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, many of the moments of searching and uncertainty I
experience are self-inflicted. I could, afterall, read the
instruction booklets thoroughly before hitting the road.
</P>
<P>
   But I am a man. And that would be like asking for directions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
