</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-AUTOS-FEATURES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVENIENCE AND SAFETY, THANKS TO HIGH-TECH GADGETS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Recently, I was driving a long distance and hoped I had enough
gas to complete the trip without stopping for fuel. About 15 miles
from my destination, the gasoline warning light came on. Knowing
that most cars have 2 1/2 gallons of fuel left at that point, I
took the calculated risk that I could get where I was going without
hitting empty.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, I was right. But had I had the new ``smart gauge''
on the Dodge/Plymouth Neon, I would have known exactly how much
fuel was left, and breathed easier for those last 15 miles. The
gauge continuously reads the fuel-tank float level every six
seconds, comparing it with stored historical data to calculate a
``real-time'' reading for the gauge to give a more accurate reading
of the fuel supply.
</P>
<P>
   The smart gauge is among the many high-tech features consumers
will be finding on latest model cars and trucks this year. For the
most part, convenience and safety are their selling points.
</P>
<P>
   Night Vision, a system that utilizes ``Heads Up Display'' and
infrared technology _ similar to that used in the Persian Gulf War
_ is being offered on the Cadillac DeVille to improve driver
safety.
</P>
<P>
   Night Vision technology illuminates potential safety hazards out
of range of a car's headlights. The Heads Up Display, or HUD, then
projects the image low on the windshield and allows drivers to see
three to five times farther ahead of their low-beam headlights. The
system also helps reduce the glare of oncoming headlights.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, along with convenience and safety, some drivers _ and
passengers _ want comfort. And in a frigid New England winter, that
can mean heated seats.
</P>
<P>
   First there were heated front seats, now some manufacturs also
provide heat for the rear seats. There are seats that will massage,
and of course, many seats offer lumbar supports. Saab last year
even introduced ventilated seats for those hot sticky days _
combined with a heat pad for those cold days.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there is the climate-controled seat found as an option on
Lincoln's Navigator. The seat has a fan that directs ambient air to
two ceramic thermoelectric devices located in the seat's back and
cushions, which then release or absorb heat, depending on the flow
of electric current to them. The warm _ or cool _ air is then
directed through perforations in the seat upholstery. To complete
the package, there are five different heating and cooling settings.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors is putting its OnStar communications system into
all its models. The system, which is tied into a cell phone, is
designed to automatically call for help in the event of an accident
and air bag deployment and also provides the location of the
disabled vehicle. Saab is also offering the system as an $895
option, which includes three months free service. The system also
allows subscribers to call for help on directions, finding hotels
or restaurants, and other information.
</P>
<P>
   Other nice touches to check out: the Nissan Xterra comes with a
self-draining storage bin on the roof to stow things like muddy
hiking boots. It also has lots of other neat storage ideas, even an
inside bike rack. The Ford Taurus and Mercury Sable have trunk
hooks to hang those plastic grocery bags _ no more loose cans
rolling around the trunk. The Pontiac Bonneville SSEi offers an
emergency package with rain suit, first-aid kit, gloves, light, and
an air hose to pump air into low tires.
</P>
<P>
   Navigation systems are getting smarter and easier to use, and
are moving into more vehicles. The Honda Odyssey is the first
minivan to offer a navigation system, as a $2,000 option.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac's new Seville offers a radio that gets e-mail, stock
quotes, as well as the latest weather and traffic updates. This
radio goes beyond just providing the information. If a traffic
alert is announced, the radio broadcasts it even if the CD or tape
is playing, and if you don't know where to find traffic infomation,
the radio will do it at the touch of a button.
</P>
<P>
   Many manufacturers of pricy vehicles are now including all-speed
traction control as well as a stabilization system that senses
where the car is going and automatically adjusts brakes to keep the
car on the intended course.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac, which features the Northstar system that includes a
dual overhead cam V-8 engine, stability control system, variable
road-sensing suspension, all speed traction, antilocking brakes and
speed-sensitive steering, has made a major change in its 2000
Seville that should make owners a lot happier. The Northstar engine
has not only been improved but its compression has been lowered so
that it can now drive on regular gasoline instead of 93 octane.
Even Cadillac owners know the value of saving 20 to 30 cents a
gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz, which has been in the forefront of just about
every major automotive safety innovation, is adding the world's
only active suspenision system to its list of firsts. The system,
called ABC (for Active Body Control) virtually eliminates body roll
in cornering, accelerating, and braking. Mercedes says the system
``solves the age-old tradoff between ride comfort, handling
precision and driving safety. The new flagship CL coupe has the
sumptuous ride comfort of an S-Class sedan, while the coupe's crisp
handling surpasses most high-performance cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who thought the Audi A-6 was a bit underpowered should
take another look. Audi is offering a DOHC 30-valve V-6 in its new
S4 and A6 2.7T models. The twin intercoolers and KKK K03
turbochargers blow up to 16 psi of boost increasing horsepower by
50 to 250 at 5800 rpm. Audi has also lowered the compression ratio
and reduced the bore to make the engine quieter and the cylinder
walls of the aluminum block more durable.
</P>
<P>
   The new Saturn LS has two engine options: A V-6 that comes from
Opel in Germany, similar to the one used in Saabs and the Cadillac
Catera, and a new four-cylinder aluminum 137 horsepower engine,
which is designed for less vibration and noise.
</P>
<P>
   When do you need service? Mercedes-Benz vehicles will tell you.
The vehicles are equipped with a Flexible Service System that
monitors oil quality allowing for service intervals of up to 20,000
miles, if oil quality is poor, a system prompts the driver for
earlier service.
</P>
<P>
   What's a sports model with just an automatic transmission? The
sporty Oldsmobile Alero has a five-speed Getrag F23 manual
transmission built in Italy. Unfortunately, it is available only on
four-cylinder models. In the future, it will be offered on the
Pontiac Grand Am and Sunfire and the Chevrolet Cavalier.
</P>
<P>
   All 2000 Mercedes-Benz passenger vehicles (except the SLK
roadster, where it is an option) now come with a driver-adaptive
five-speed automatic transmission as standard equipment. The
five-forward gears are computer controled, networking with the
engine and chassis management systems to adapt to a wide variety of
driving situations, and even to the driver's style.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
