<HEADER>
A2590 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-SPCL-AUTOS-NEW-BOS &LR;      11-08 1480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-AUTOS-NEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAR MAKERS ARE TARGETING EVERY NICHE IN THE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROYAL FORD  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   These may be the best of times for buyers of automobiles, both
aficiandos and those just looking for solid transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Never before have so many manufacturers built so many good,
reliable autos. The worst car at this year's shows is probably a
safer, more reliable car than most of the best built 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Never has there been such a range of choice, from the smallest,
least expensive to the pricey, gargantuan SUVs. Sports coupes and
sports sedans. Trucks that are SUVs and SUVs that are nearly cars.
Cars that talk to you as they guide you on your journey; cars that
you can talk to _ tell them to place a phone call or boost the
radio volume _ and they will respond. Cars that protect you
immensely in driving _ with ABS brakes and driver-assist antispin
features. (These new safety features also mean we have to rethink
the way we teach driving to young people; those of us who have been
driving for some time will also have to learn new techniques. There
are, doubtless, folks reading this piece who don't know, for
instance, that you don't pump ABS brakes when you want to come to a
quick stop.)
</P>
<P>
   And finally, never before has there been such a dichotomy in
design and manufacture _ the auto industry's challenge. Everyone is
trying to build the Swiss Army Knife of cars/SUVs/trucks. All
buyers need do is pick out the blades and appliances they want.
</P>
<P>
   Spend $88,000 on an Acura NSX if you want speed and have the
money. Spend in the $10,000 range for a Toyota Echo or a new Ford
Focus.
</P>
<P>
   The car companies are designing for all of us, young and old,
sporty and sedate. How do you build cars that suit a physically
aging baby boom generation? Cars that suit the already elderly?
Cars that suit a young generation that has grown up with computer
joysticks in hand and expects computer-quickness in its cars? Cars
that suit families? Autos for parents who want to haul their kids,
fetch their own lumber for weekend projects, and go out for dinner
on Saturday night in sedan-whisper quiet _ all in the same auto.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible and these are times of great possibility.
</P>
<P>
   --Do you want the Ford Excursion _ biggest yet of the SUVs and
labeled the ``Ford Valdez'' by environmental critics _ or do you
want the Honda Insight or Toyota Prius _ small hybrids, running on
gasoline and batteries and getting upwards of 60 and 80 miles per
gallon?
</P>
<P>
   --Do you want a sports coupe _ say the snappy Honda S2000, with
its red line at nine grand _ or a sports sedan, seating 5, and
snappy in its own way, like the Acura 3.2 TL or the Nissan Maxima
with a 222 horsepower engine?
</P>
<P>
   --Do you want an SUV or a pickup truck? Or how about a pickup
truck with four doors that seats six and has that one thing the SUV
does not have _ a bed in the back?
</P>
<P>
   --Do you want economical _ $10,000 to $18,000 being economical
these days _ or do you want more luxury. Luxury itself has been
split into many levels _ low-luxury starting at around $20,000 (the
Maxima comes to mind again); mid-luxury starting around $30,000; or
upper luxury at $50,000 and upwards. It can be confusing because
there are $23,000 cars out there that are in many ways as good as
some being sold for much more.
</P>
<P>
   --And how will you shop? Go tussle with a salesman? Go on line?
However you do it, you can go in armed with more knowledge than
ever before, thanks to myriad Web sites that rate autos and tell
you how much you should pay for them _ and how much you should get
for the one you are turning in. (An estimated 2.8 million people
researched new and used car purchases before putting down any money
in 1999.)
</P>
<P>
   For the 1999 model year, 16.8 million new autos were sold, the
most ever, topping by 1.2 million the previous high, set in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   We are buying cleaner, safer, more powerful cars. Cars that come
with more and more ``luxury'' items as standard equipment: power
windows, tilting and telescoping steering wheels, power door locks,
power mirrors (heated, yet).
</P>
<P>
   The new Jaguar S Type has an option that lets you control
climate and radio by voice command. How long before this is a
standard safety feature _ no more distractions while fiddling for
the right knob, the right button or dial?
</P>
<P>
   Navigation systems, still optional, are leapfrogging each other
in content. The new Acura 3.5 RL has a navigation system that has
added millions of ``points of interest'' in just one year of
evolution. While we are still dependent on satellites _ and
therefore, the military's slight fudging of signals for national
security reasons _ a new land-based navigation system is being
developed. It will place 300-foot towers at 53 sites around the
country on old Air Force property.
</P>
<P>
   Choices will continue to unfold as automakers scramble.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, in a report entitled ``The Automotive Battlefield
2000-2003'' gives us a peek at what is to come.
</P>
<P>
   --Seventy-five percent of the models sold in 1998 will be
replaced by new models in the next four years.
</P>
<P>
   --Truck bodies built on car platforms will become more
prominent, with 28 new or next generation models expected over four
years.
</P>
<P>
   --The lifecycles of new models will continue to compress,
dropping to 2.5 years by 2003 as opposed to 3.2 years from 1996 to
1999.
</P>
<P>
   It will be a market of niches and the manufacturers' use of
shared platforms _ as in putting light truck bodies on car
platforms _ will help to fill many of them.
</P>
<P>
   We now have shared platforms appearing on the Toyota Camry and
the Toyota Sienna van; the New Beetle from VW and the Audi TT; the
Plymouth Neon and Chrysler PT Cruiser; the Ford Excursion and Ford
F-Series pickup; and when Ford brings back the Thunderbird, it will
share its platform with the Jaguar S-Type.
</P>
<P>
   Some things to watch for:
</P>
<P>
   --A shakeout in the luxury market as buyers weight bucks against
bang. Volvo is out with a sedan and wagon in the low 20s; Mercury's
Sable offers better steering, suspension and transmission than in
the past and more oomph from a 3.0 liter V-6 engine. The $20,000 to
$40,000 price range is a goldmine for discerning shoppers.
</P>
<P>
   --Station wagons are making a comeback. Volvo added the small
V40 to its lineup; Saab now has a wagon; BMW will send its 3 Series
wagon here.
</P>
<P>
   --Aging baby boomers could go in one of two directions _ snappy
sports sedans or laid-back luxury.
</P>
<P>
   For those who feel the need for speed, sports sedans to watch
include the Acura 3.2 TL, the Pontiac Bonneville SSEi, Chrysler's
300M, the Nissan Maxima, the Lincoln LS, the Lexus ES 300, the I30
Infiniti and Chevrolet's Monte Carlo SS _ a luxury sedan with hot
damn good ol' boy written all over it.
</P>
<P>
   For boomers feeling a bit grayer and ready to slow down, Toyota
has turned the Avalon into their type of car _ kicked back, less
sporty, quiet, smooth and dependable. Same for the Acura 3.5 RL.
</P>
<P>
   As the boomers age, their children _ the Echo Boomers _ are the
target of the new wave of small, reliable, and inexpensive autos.
The Echo and the Focus join this list, along with the VW Golf, and
Daimler Chrysler says a mini version of the Neon will follow.
</P>
<P>
   For young and old with a few bucks to spend, there are hot new
sports cars: the Honda S2000 (watch for price gouging on this
$30,000 car); the Audi TT in coupe and roadster form; a new M3 from
BMW to go with the Z3 and M Coupe; and at lesser prices the
Mitsubishi Eclipse 2(plus)2, the Toyota Celica GT-S, and Toyota's
MR Spyder, a high perofrmance, mid-engine, rear-wheel-drive
roadster.
</P>
<P>
   On the truck and SUV front, cross-pollination is the order of
the day.
</P>
<P>
   SUVs continue to get carlike: the Lexus RX300 sitting on a
Toyota Camry sedan chassis; Mercedes and BMW are coming out with
SUVs, developed on race tracks, which reach speeds up to 155 mph.
And look for an Acura SUV to be introduced in Detroit this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Pickup trucks get ever more SUV-like: four doors, smoother,
quieter rides, seating for up to six. Chevrolet, Toyota, and Nissan
are heavy into this market this year. Ford has been there, watching
its F-Series sales of four-door pickup trucks climb from around 10
percent of its total pickup truck sales just three years ago to
more than 80 percent of its anticipated total pickup trucks sales
in the upcoming model year.
</P>
<P>
   Toss in minivans _ a slowed market compared to past years but a
solid one nonetheless (Mazda is counting on a small, front-wheel
drive van to help boost its sales) _ and the permutations of metal
and power in which you can wrap yourself are endless.
</P>
<P>
   And this as (again, no ``M'' word here) our full first century
of auto production closes and a bolder century full of
technological and innovative possibility looms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
