<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-AUTOS-MODELS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNPRECEDENTED OPTIONS IN STYLE AND PRICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 2000 model year promises to be a good year for consumers in
the market for a new set of wheels. The millennium models are
coming better equipped, without higher price tags. There is also a
new competitiveness. Ford is aiming to win back the sales crown
from Toyota with a revamped Taurus, for example. And both Ford and
Toyota are hoping to muscle their way into the small car field by
introducing brand-new models.
</P>
<P>
   Hyundai is also coming on strong in the small car field with a
redesigned Accent. With the company's new emphasis on quality and
great warranties, Hyundai is a make to check out. Nissan's Sentra
will have more power and looks. Nissan also will offer a slightly
more expensive version of the Sentra that features a new catalytic
converter that traps hydrocarbons and hangs onto them until they
can be burned off later by the hotter exhaust of the warmed up car.
The result, Nissan claims, is an exhaust no dirtier than the air we
breathe.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Toyota took the car sales crown, selling 476,752
Camrys compared to Honda's 415,960 Accord sales and 367,582 sales
of the Ford Taurus. Even with those sales, Toyota was still third
on the list of top 10 sellers for 1999. Six of the models on the
list, including the top two, were trucks: No. 1 was the Ford
F-Series with 867,441 sales; next was the Chevrolet C/K pickup at
616,693.
</P>
<P>
   This year Ford is dropping its tear-drop styling for a more
conventional look for the Taurus, which it is packing (ditto
Mercury Sable) with more room, power, and safety. The two model
lines have all-new sheetmetal, more horsepower, all-speed traction
control, optional power pedals, inside trunk release, and front and
side air bags.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, Mercury is reporting its models are proving very
popular, especially the New England Edition of the Sable that comes
with a free moon roof and ABS, a $1,400 value. Apparently New
Englanders know a good value when they see it.
</P>
<P>
   Arch rival Chevrolet is also coming on strong with an all-new
Impala and a sporty Monte Carlo. Adding to the punch will be a new
Cavalier, Chevy's hottest selling car.
</P>
<P>
   The new Impala will come in two models, the Impala sedan, which
has a standard V-6, and the LS model, which has the 3800 SFI V6
with 200 horsepower. The roomy Impala also offers ABS, traction
control, tire inflation warning, 16-inch wheels, and dual-control
climate zone. The Monte Carlo coupe, while sharing Impala's
wheelbase and engines, has its own sheetmetal for a more sporty
look.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota is taking solid aim at the youth market with its Echo, a
new entry that is bigger all around than its predecessor, the
Tercel. Echo's interior is as roomy as the more expensive Corolla.
What's more, the Echo will start at $10,000, with a well-equipped
model costing around $12,500. For that price, you get air
conditioning, power steering, sport body kit, and a radio with CD
and cassette player. Adding to Echo's appeal is the promise of
peppy performance and gas mileage of 38 to 52 miles per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Focus is also designed for space and youth. It claims
more head, cargo, and leg room than anything in its class. The
Focus will be available first as a four-door sedan. Later,
three-door coupe and wagon versions will be offered. The Focus will
be powered by a 2-liter engine and have a choice of manual or
automatic transmission. In addition, the Focus will be sold in
customized editions. ``We don't believe in the one-size-fits-all
theory. Young people really define themselves,'' says Julie Roehm,
brand manager. So, look for some special packages for the Focus: a
pet package that includes bed, water bottle, bowl and pockets for
treats; or an ``express yourself'' version with car decals, gear
shift, seat wardrobe and wheel cover. Another option provides a
voice recorder, notepad holder, and work station. The Focus was to
replace the Escort, but Ford plans on selling both models for now.
</P>
<P>
   In the sport utility field, BMW claims its X5 performs and
handles like one of its sedans. Nissan has the Xterra, to appeal to
active young people, and Mercedes-Benz has the ML55 with a
340-horsepower engine that will blast away just about anything on
the road, doing 0 to 60 miles per hour in less than 6 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Ford brings out the biggest SUV of all, the Excursion, to
finally top the GM Suburban, which has held the size title since
1935. (Of course, no one knew what a sport utility vehicle was back
then.) General Motors is countering Ford with a totally redesigned
and more powerful Chevrolet Suburban and GMC Yukon .
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the Chrysler PT Cruiser. Chrysler calls it a truck,
but consumers may have a different opinion.
</P>
<P>
   In the minivan field, Mazda is offering its all-new, front-drive
MPV with innovative seating choices and roll-down sliding door
windows. Chevrolet is dressing up its Venture minivan with a video
system for rear seaters that includes free flicks from Warner Bros.
</P>
<P>
   BMW introduces a new 3 coupe and has a 3 wagon on the way. The
Pontiac Bonneville is all new with a longer wheelbase, stiffer
ride, and wider track. It's also offered with turbocharged power in
the SSEi model.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan has revamped its Maxima, coming up with 22 additional
horsepower by redesigning the exhaust system, and the Maxima can
now go 100,000-miles before a tune up is required.
</P>
<P>
   Infiniti has given the I30 a boost, packing it with new
equipment while holding the price at around $30,000. The car comes
with a 227-horsepower engine, Xenon headlights, an active
front-seat head restraint system, and 200-watt Bose audio system
with seven speakers.
</P>
<P>
   Honda is putting fun back into driving with its newest entry,
the S2000 sports car. A hot performing two seater, this high-tech
roadster will be priced around $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguar is moving into the mass market with its new S-Type sedan.
Selling in the mid-$40,000 range, this rear-drive vehicle is sure
to heat up sales. Almost overlooked is another model from Jaguar, a
super-charged 370 horsepower XK8.
</P>
<P>
   Oldsmobile is jumping the gun on 2001 by introducing the all-new
Aurora early in 2000. It is the first redesign since the car
debuted in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Saturn is growing in size. This year an L (for large) series
comes in sedan and wagon models alongside the S cars and wagons.
The L models come with a choice of a four-cylinder or a V-6 engine.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best alternatives to sport utility vehicles is a
Subaru. All-wheel drive is featured throughout the line, and this
year the third generation Legacy and Outback are better than ever,
even roomier. Outback, previously just a wagon series, has added a
sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln, too, has a winner in its new ``entry level'' LS
rear-drive sedan. Built on the same platform as the Jaguar S-Type,
it handles beautifully and is a real performer.
</P>
<P>
   Park Avenue, Buick's full-sized luxury flagship model, is the
first domestic car to offer whiplash protection. It also has GM's
StabiliTrak handling system.
</P>
<P>
   A nameplate from the past is being revived at Saab. Areo, which
has been ranked as a true touring sedan with great performance,
returns in the 9-5 model line, and like its predecessors, it
promises to be a winner with a turbocharged four-cylinder,
230-horsepower engine.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac is redoing its Northstar V-8 to take regular gas
instead of the more expensive 93 octane. Cadillac is also offering
the all-new DeVille, loaded with safety and comfort systems, many
of which are unavailable in any other vehicle. DeVille comes with a
night vision sensing device, STabilTrak, and three-zone climate
control inside.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes-Benz has all-new S430 ($69,700) and S500 ($77,850)
sedans. Both are lighter than previous models, but packed with
performance and safety features. Also arriving are a new CLK 430
Cabriolet with four seats, and for the performance-oriented sport
utility fan, the 340-horsepower ML55 that can do 0 to 60 m.p.h. in
less than 6 seconds. Mercedes also is introducing designer editions
with unique paint and upholstery colors on its roadsters, coupes,
and S-Class and E-Class sedans. What is truly amazing is that
Mercedes is offering vehicles at an almost affordable price _ the
C230 sedan starts at $31,750 with free maintenance for four years.
</P>
<P>
   Alphabetically speaking, Volvo is last, but certainly not least,
in the auto world. For 2000, Volvo has added two nifty compacts,
the S40 sedan and V40 wagon. Starting at around $23,000 these
vehicles are packed with traditional Volvo features.
</P>
<P>
   While there are many car and truck debutes this year, shoppers
shouldn't overlook the other models, that is, the ones that don't
look much different from a '99. Even these vehicles have changes.
</P>
<P>
   Lexus, for example, has no ``all new'' models, but it has done
some upgrading to make the line more attractive. The ES 300, for
example, has an optional Brake Assist safety system that can detect
panic braking and augment the brake pressure applied by the driver.
The feature is now standard on the GS 400/300, LS 400 and LX 470
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Lexus is entering its 10th year of selling in the United States.
In its first year, the company had just two models and sold 63,000
cars. Since then Lexus has changed the face of the luxury market.
This year Lexus offers six models, cars and SUVs, and has become
the No. 1 selling luxury make, outselling all its US and German
competitors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1201EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
