<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 12:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2595 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-SPCL-AUTOS-SAFETY-BOS     11-08 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPCL-AUTOS-SAFETY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFETY BECOMING STANDARD FARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Safety is taking on new meaning with the 2000 models.
</P>
<P>
   While few will argue that vehicles need features to protect the
driver and passengers, there is some debate about what those
features should be, and how they should work. Air bags, in
particular, have been both hailed for how well they protect, and
criticized for how dangerous they can be to driver and passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Air bags have been proven to prevent serious injuries and death.
However, there have been problems primarily with smaller people who
may be sitting too close to an air bag when it opens, and to
infants placed in the front passenger seat of a vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Both these issues have been addressed in many models in the 2000
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Because buyers want a safe environment, car manufacturers are
adding new features, many of them to lower-priced vehicles.
Mercedes-Benz, for example, has long had a lead in introducing
safety features on their more expensive models, but these features
are now showing up on the company's ``entry-level'' vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Antilock brakes, once an expensive option, are now found across
the board as standard equipment or as a fairly low-priced option.
Many safety advocates urge consumers to consider antilock brakes a
necessity rather than an option, however. While it's impressive to
know a car can do 0 to 60 mile per hour in less than 6 seconds, it
is more comforting to know it can do 60 to 0 mph in as few seconds,
and do it without pulling the vehicle into the path of another car.
</P>
<P>
   Answering air bag concerns for short drivers are the
electrically adjustable foot pedals found on Ford, Mercury, and
Lincoln products. These allow the driver to raise the pedals
without having to push the seat too close to the steering wheel.
</P>
<P>
   Mercedes has been offering a child sensing device in the front
passenger seat, that combined with the use of a specially designed
child safety seat, shuts off the air bag on the passenger side.
</P>
<P>
   Cadillac's new Seville has sensors that prevent the air bags
from deploying if the seat is occupied by a small child. The system
works with both the front and side air bags. The sensors measure
the weight and posterior of the occupant to distinguish a child
from a lightweight adult. The rear-view mirror contains a light
that indicates if the air bag has been switched off.
</P>
<P>
   Most manufacturers are now offering ``second generation'' or
low-impact airbags to help reduce injury when the bags open. On its
5 and 7 series, BMW uses a dual-system frontal air-bag system that
deploys the bag as gently or as powerfully as needed, depending on
crash severity. Another example of safety technology becoming more
widely available is the BMW 3 series, which is offering rear-side
impact air bags as an option. Until this year, those air bags were
offered only on the BMW 5 and 7 series.
</P>
<P>
   Some Mercedes and Volvos have curtain-type bags that help
protect heads and necks in side-impact crashes as well.
</P>
<P>
   Whiplash is a major concern in accidents. Mercedes-Benz, Volvo,
and Saab all offer systems to prevent whiplash, and this year Buick
becomes the first domestic car to offer a whiplash-prevention
system. Similar to the Saab's system, the Buick system, refereed to
as a ``Catcher's Mitt,'' begins with special backing inside the
seat. On impact, as the body is forced into the seat back, the head
restraint is activated, rising up and out to reach the occupant's
head, reducing the head's motion and, hopefully, neck, back, and
spine injuries. Ultimately, the seat absorbs the body's energy as
it's forced backwards into the seat and helps keep the passenger's
pelvis and lower back in proper alignment. The head rest is
designed to automatically fall back and reset in place.
</P>
<P>
   Warning drivers behind you of an impending stop can also aid in
preventing accidents. The Cadillac DeVille is the first vehicle
with LED taillights. LEDs can illuminate in 0.1 millisecond vs. the
200 milliseconds of incandescent bulbs. That translates into an
additional 17.6 feet of warning for drivers behind the Cadillac
DeVille.
</P>
<P>
   The DeVille also features a Night Vision system that can ``see''
three to five times farther ahead than the low-beam headlights
reveal. Any object, i.e. potential safety hazard, is projected onto
the lower part of the windshield. The system also helps reduce the
glare of oncoming vehicles' headlights.
</P>
<P>
   Ford is the first automaker to include an emergency trunk
release as standard equipment for its passenger cars. Last year, 11
children died after being trapped inside car trunks. General Motors
and other manufactures will also soon be offering the equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford Windstar minivan, and now the Cadillac DeVille and
other makes offer warning systems when backing up. The systems
sound an alarm as an object gets closer. Mercedes goes a step
farther with its S class system that automatically slows the
vehicle down if it gets too close to another.
</P>
<P>
   One of the dangers of driving an SUV is that in a collision with
a car, the car could submarine beneath the SUV. Among SUVs,
Mercedes has bumpers placed low enough to prevent this. For the
Ford Excursion _ the biggest SUV of all _ a bumper-like
``BlockerBeam'' crossmember (a lower bumper) is located at the
front of the vehicle 2.5 inches below and 6.5 inches behind the
main bumper. The beam is designed to engage the frame rails of a
car in the event of a collision, preventing the Excursion from
riding up and over the car. The Excursion has a similar system in
the rear that also serves as a mount for the trailer hitch.
</P>
<P>
   While many feel an all-wheel-drive system is a plus when it
comes to safety when the roads are wet or covered with snow, you
don't have to buy a big sport utility vehicle to have it. Subaru
uses all-wheel-drive throughout its lineup, and others, such as
Mercedes-Benz, Volvo, Volkswagen, Audi, and DaimlerChrysler offer
it on selected cars, station wagons, and minivans. This year,
Subaru is adding daytime running lights as standard equipment. BMW
offers drivers a choice of running with daytime lights on or off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
