<SLUG> BC-SPCL-AUTOS-HYBRID-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HYBRIDS MAKE A POWER PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   How would you like to have a car that sells for less than
$20,000 and promises up to 70 miles a gallon?
</P>
<P>
   Just when it seemed gas-guzzling SUVs were taking over the
highways, two automakers are ready to unveil economic and
environmental alternatives.
</P>
<P>
   These are not electric-powered vehicles that can't be driven too
far without getting all charged up, or might have problems starting
in cold weather. These so-called hybrid vehicles will be very much
like the cars most of us are driving now, equipped with antilock
brakes; airbags, front and side; power windows, and more.
</P>
<P>
   Having driven the Toyota Prius along Boston streets and
highways, I can vouch for its handling, room, and responsive power.
The Prius and its counterpart Honda hybrid, the Insight, use both
gasoline and electric engines for power.
</P>
<P>
   When pulling away from a stop or under a light load, only the
electric motor kicks in. Under normal driving conditions, power
from the gasoline engine is divided between the wheels and the
electric generator. During deceleration or braking, the motor
functions as a generator to recharge the batteries. Thus, the
batteries never need to be recharged from an external source.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the system is a power-split transmission that sends
engine power either directly to the wheels or to the generator
controling the electric motor or battery state-of-charge. The
power-split device uses a planetary gear to constantly vary the
amount of power supplied from the engine to either the wheels or
generator. And, it's all done seamlessly.
</P>
<P>
   When driving the Pirus, I couldn't tell whether the vehicle was
on gas or electric power. The only clue is on a 5.8-inch wide
multi-function monitor that shows the condition and energy flow of
the hybrid drive system. (It can also serve for a navigation
system.)
</P>
<P>
   To help boost system efficiency, Prius is fitted with a
regenerative braking system. If the vehicle is coasting or the
brakes are applied, the motor is turned into a generator, capturing
energy that would normally be lost as heat or kinetic energy and
transforming it into electricity to recharge the battery.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota says the Prius cuts nitrous oxide and carbon monoxide
emissions by 90 percent and hydrocarbons from 75 to 90 percent
beyond current stringent standards.
</P>
<P>
   While we only tested an early Japanese right-hand drive model,
the four-door sedan was quite comfortable and roomy with plenty of
room for four, maybe five. The trunk seemed a bit small, but this
vehicle is really designed for city use, although it appears it can
do quite nicely on the open highway. Toyota styled the car in its
California studios.
</P>
<P>
   Toyota has been marketing the car in Japan since December 1997
and has had phenomenal success, selling more than 27,000 models.
When the Prius arrives in America in mid-2000, Toyota is setting an
initial volume of 1,000 units a month for its dealerships in the 49
continental states. It is expected to sell for around $16,000.
</P>
<P>
   Honda's hybrid, the Insight, will beat Toyota to the showrooms,
arriving sometime in December.
</P>
<P>
   The Insight will be a two-door with a two-plus-two seating
configuration. It will be powered by a 1.0-liter, 65 horsepower,
3-cylinder VTEC gas engine supplemented by an electric motor. Like
the Toyota, the battery pack is recharged by both the gas engine's
power and regenerating power when the car's brakes are applied.
</P>
<P>
   A lightweight aluminum frame and plastic fenders fore and aft
keep the Insight's weight below 2,000 pounds to aid economy.
Standard safety items include driver and passenger side airbags,
antilock brakes, power windows, and locks along with remote keyless
entry.
</P>
<P>
   The American version of the Prius will be similar to the
Japanese version but some specifications and design touches are
expected to change. Actual specifications will be announced shortly
before it is introduced here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
