<HEADLINE>
SAVVY SHOPPERS WILL FIND PLENTY OF GOOD VALUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1997 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deciding what kind of vehicle to acquire is tough enough, but
figuring out how to obtain you next vehicle can be even tougher. In
the end, no matter how lofty your dreams _ and how enticing those
ads with the unbelievably low monthly payments may be _ the
dollars-and-cents facts should bring you back to Earth.
</P>
<P>
   With the median price of a vehicle hovering around $20,000, a
lot of consumers are turned off by some of the new high-tech
vehicles that are nice but out of reach. Which is why Toyota and
Ford are introducing low-priced models packed with big value. The
Ford Focus and Toyota Echo are aimed at young people who don't have
the big bucks to buy the big cars, yet both vehicles are big on the
inside.
</P>
<P>
   Even the higher-priced lines are coming out with lower-priced
but value-packed models. Volvo has the S40 and V40 starting at
$23,000; Lincoln has the sporty and high-performance L series,
starting in the low 30s; Mercedes has added even more features to
its ``entry level'' C230 which starts around $31,000.
</P>
<P>
   And you don't have to look hard to get great performance and
safety, once only found in expensive models. The new Ford Taurus/
</P>
<P>
   Mercury Sable is packed with safety features, even receiving a
five-star rating from the National Safety Board. Volkswagen is
another great safety and performance value. Even young royals
appreciate VW. Prince William reportedly learned to drive on a Ford
Focus, but purchased a VW Passat. (Well, VW does own a bit of
British heritage in Bentley and for a while Rolls-Royce.)
</P>
<P>
   The secret to getting the most for your money in any new _ or
used _ vehicle is doing your homework. First do some comparison
shopping, looking at prices and models that appeal. Do a test
drive, not just around the block, but under conditions similar to
your normal driving experience _ on the highway, on rough roads,
checking out the vehicle's pickup. Do this with similar models _
there are performance and handling difference even between models
of the same make vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Check up on the reliability of the vehicle you are considering.
One of the best sources for such information is last April's
Consumer Reports annual auto issue. Sure, you're looking at reports
on '99s, but most 2000 models have few changes, especially
mechanical.
</P>
<P>
   Then do some pricing. First, decide on the make and model
vehicle you want. Note the sticker price with all the options you
desire. That's not the final price, just a basis to work from.
Next, find out what the vehicle cost the dealer, and what your
trade-in is worth. There are many sources for this information: one
of the most reliable is Consumer Reports, which for $12 will fax a
report with the invoice price, the sticker price, option prices,
equipment recommendations, rebates, dealer incentives, and advice
on how to negotiate. Information on your trade-in vehicle is an
additional $10. Leasing advice is also offered. To obtain the
reports call 800-933-5555.
</P>
<P>
   Especially useful is the information on rebates and incentives
since many are unadvertised. For example, Mercury is discontinuing
the Contour and is offering incentives of $1,500 to move them out.
Even many 2000 models have unadvertised incentives from
manufacturers. For example, the Dodge Stratus and Chrysler Cirrus
have customer incentives of $1,250 through Dec. 13; the Buick Park
Avenue has a $1,000 incentive on 2000 models, and a $3,000
incentive on '99s.
</P>
<P>
   From here you can bargain. Consumers Reports suggests offering 4
to 8 percent more than the invoice price on popular models. And
hold off mentioning any trade-in until a price is agreed on, this
way you'll really know what the dealer is offering for your old
car. If the vehicle you are buying is in demand, you'll probably
have to forget all this and pay the asking or sticker price. Last
year, a friend wanted a Mercedes M430 sport utility, a very desired
make and in limited production. She not only had to pay the sticker
price, but was offered the lowest wholesale price on her trade-in,
a Saab. She swallowed the sticker price, but sold her Saab in a
private deal.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't like bartering, there are buying services, which
will do the work for you. They can be found in the Yellow Pages of
the phone book.
</P>
<P>
   Homework is also important if you are considering a leased
vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Leasing can be very attractive, especially when you compare the
monthly lease payments to what you may pay on a car loan. Then
there is the matter of the down payment. For sure, you will need a
hefty one if you buy, while many leases don't require much up-front
money.
</P>
<P>
   To help you decide if leasing is for you, consider how long you
intend to have the vehicle, and how many miles you are likely to
drive during that time. Most leases are 36 to 60 months. And most
leases, especially those with attractive payments, limit your
driving to 12,000 to 15,000 miles a year. Drive more than that and
you can be hit with some hefty mileage charges _ 10 to 15 cents a
mile times a few thousand miles can be costly. Leases can be
written for higher mileage, but at a higher price.
</P>
<P>
   All leases are based on the ``residual'' value _ what the bank
thinks your car or truck will be worth _ of the vehicle at the end
of the lease. You pay only for usage. Remember, you don't own the
vehicle, and the holder of the lease will want that car or truck
back in good condition.
</P>
<P>
   Recent reports indicate that leasing has dropped a bit in
popularity. One reason is that manufacturers have cut back on
subsidizing leases, especially after making some wrong guesses as
to what the vehicles would be worth at the end of the lease and
losing money on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Many people are now looking to the Internet to buy or lease. The
Internet is a great way to research various makes. Autosite.com,
for example, can help you decide between two makes with its easy to
use side-by-side comparison feature.
</P>
<P>
   For many consumer, one of the best features of shopping on the
Internet is the impersonal nature of it. No face-to-face
bargaining. You might even feel better making an offer on the Web.
One dealer says he prices his vehicles on the Internet as much as
$2,500 less than on his lot. Why? Because Internet users are
looking for low prices. To complete the sale, though, you'll still
have to go into the showroom.
</P>
<P>
   But whether you go kick tires, or use your mouse to find a new
vehicle, you need to know what's out there, what your dream is
really worth, and what your present set of wheels are worth. And,
keep in mind no matter what car or truck you settle on, it will
need service even if it does promise 100,000 miles between
tune-ups. Check out the warranty on the vehicle, and the dealer's
service department. That good deal from the sales department may
not be such a good deal after all if the mechanics and technicians
can't deliver.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
