<HEADER>
A2621 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SF-MAYORAL-HNS &LR;      11-08 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYORAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO MAYORAL CANDIDATES MAP RUNOFF STRATEGY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GREGORY LEWIS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown and Board of
Supervisors President Tom Ammiano begin a political battle to
become the city's next leader, their election efforts already
appear to be vastly different.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano is seeking to widen his base of support by registering
new voters, many of them in the Mission District.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's campaign is focused on improving voter turnout in his
traditional strongholds, including Bayview-Hunters Point,
Visitacion Valley and the Western Addition rather than registering
new voters.
</P>
<P>
   Residents have until Nov. 15 to register to vote in the Dec. 14
run- off election.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's campaign aides said they were disappointed with turnout
in some neighborhoods where his support traditionally is high.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bayview-Hunters Point district, where Brown won 84.7
percent of the vote, only about one in three registered voters
turned out last week.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, 42.1 percent of voters in the predominantly
black neighborhood cast ballots, helping Brown oust then-Mayor
Frank Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some areas where we didn't turn out all our voters,''
said Brown campaign spokesman P.J. Johnston. ``We'll try to ratchet
that up.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown leaders unofficially began the new campaign Friday by
contacting precinct captains _ those directly responsible for
turning out voters across the city _ to talk about keeping
supporters tuned in over the next five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll make sure our troops are gathered and prepared for the
final push,'' Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   But in Ammiano headquarters, supporters will push to get more
``disenfranchised'' residents registered, particularly in the
Mission, where Ammiano beat Brown by almost 2-1, said Ammiano
campaign spokesman Robert Haaland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've involved people in the campaign and in the process who
felt alienated,'' Haaland said. ``We're starting to register people
who haven't felt empowered or part of the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are areas where Tom has done very well like in the
Mission, where there's a lower registration rate,'' he added.
``We'll do extensive outreach efforts in The Mission. There's a
group of Latino activists who will run that.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Cusick, who is coordinating the voter registration drive
for Ammiano's campaign, said more than 100 volunteers armed with
voter registration cards hit shopping malls, heavily traveled
streets and movie theater lines Saturday and will continue to do so
throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good way to spend the next 10 days,'' Cusick said.
We'll be all over the city. We honestly haven't thought about what
our target (number) is. ... We want everybody who is excited about
this campaign to have the opportunity to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Ammiano campaign will print and distribute
30,000 absentee ballot applications, hoping to get supporters to
vote early.
</P>
<P>
   David Lee, executive director of the non-profit Chinese-American
Voter Education Committee, predicts both the Brown and Ammiano
camps will try to expand their pools of voters through new
registrations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard and seen Ammiano's people registering people even
as we speak,'' said Lee. ``But he's targeting younger voters. I
think in the final analysis of who voted for Ammiano it will show
that he got younger, first-time and new voters ... Ammiano's appeal
is to younger voters (through) his message of institutional change
in government.''
</P>
<P>
   But signing up younger voters and relying on them to cast
ballots is risky, said Lee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ammiano must increase the pool of younger voters because, I
kind of hate to say it, but, they are unreliable. You don't know if
they'll show up at the polls. That's why you have to augment that
with numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sheehy, a gay activist and Ammiano backer, disagrees with
Lee's assessment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think people who went to the trouble to get a pen and
write in Tom's name are going to suddenly find themselves too lazy
to get out of bed on election day,'' Sheehy said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown will increase the number of potential supporters by
registering more minority voters, particularly African Americans
and those of Asian descent, Lee predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Lee said ``the tide is with Ammiano in terms of
registration.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown must find a way to appeal to older, disgruntled voters who
might have voted for Jordan or Clint Reilly and give them a reason
to vote for him, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll have to emphasize the differences between him and
Ammiano,'' Lee said. ``He must focus on Ammiano's policies ...
paint a picture that gives (voters) a reason why change is adverse
to them and why they should come out to vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown spokesman Johnston said supporters had ``no sense of
urgency'' because they assumed from press coverage that the mayor
would win re-election. ``The urgency was replaced by complacency.''
</P>
<P>
   That will be avoided this time, Johnston said, because ``the
results themselves will be a wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Johnston believes that African American leaders,
stung by a 30 percent turnout in neighborhoods seen as Brown
strongholds, will work to improve that.
</P>
<P>
   Said campaign worker Lillian Edwards: ``I'm embarrassed, hurt
and angry'' by the lack of black support in Tuesday's mayoral race.
</P>
<P>
   She has walked her neighborhood soliciting support for the mayor
throughout the campaign. As she has most weekends this fall, she
volunteered again Saturday to walk door-to-door.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like I'm going to have to walk a little longer with
the way things went,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   +
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
