<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; DO DIM BULBS MAKE BETTER PRESIDENTS? &QL; 
 &UR; WHO'S AFRAID OF NAOMI WOLF? &QL; 
 &UR; LOOKING IN THE MIRROR AT THE ANTICHRIST &QL; 
 &UR; NET SURFERS IGNORE GORE'S SITE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SLATE, the premier online magazine of politics and culture, is
now available to your readers from The New York Times Syndicate.
</P>
<P>
   (To purchase these ``separate buy'' Slate articles from the New
York Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1. DO DIM BULBS MAKE BETTER PRESIDENTS? by Jacob Weisberg
</P>
<P>
   The case against intellect in the White House is brilliantly
counterintuitive, and might work to George W. Bush's advantage. The
argument rests mainly on some fairly compelling anecdotal evidence.
The list of less-than-brilliant men judged great by those making
this argument usually begins with Ronald Reagan and often includes
Franklin D. Roosevelt and Harry S. Truman as well. The list of
intellectually gifted but ineffectual presidents has Jimmy Carter,
Richard Nixon, Herbert Hoover, and Woodrow Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   1,200 words: Slugged BC-DUMB-PRESIDENTS-SLATE
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   2. WHO'S AFRAID OF NAOMI WOLF? by William Saletan
</P>
<P>
   Just when it looked like this was going to be the most
substantive presidential election in years, along comes the
brouhaha over Naomi Wolf. The media seized on the story (``Gore's
Secret Guru,'' shouted Time) as a fresh source of groans and
titters. Pundits agree that by hiring such a ``controversial
feminist,'' Gore has embarrassed himself and exposed his personal
and political ``confusion.'' The real confusion, however, seems to
be over why Wolf is controversial or embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   1,000 words: Slugged BC-WOLF-GORE-GURU-SLATE
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   3. LOOKING IN THE MIRROR AT THE ANTICHRIST, by Jeffrey Goldberg
</P>
<P>
   Although I have never been seized by a desire to lead the armies
of Satan in a final, bloody confrontation with the forces of God on
the plain of Armageddon, I have a feeling I may be the Antichrist.
The surest suspicion I had about my pivotal role in Christian
eschatology grew from the fact that I am Jewish, male, and alive.
These are the qualifications for the job of Antichrist as specified
by the Rev. Jerry Falwell.
</P>
<P>
   1,600 words: Slugged BC-ANTICHRIST-SLATE
</P>
<P>
   -------
</P>
<P>
   4. NET SURFERS IGNORE GORE'S SITE, by James Ledbetter
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has an Internet problem. No, it's not that silly remark
about him having invented it. Gore's real problem is that Net
surfers apparently think his site is too dull to visit.
</P>
<P>
   800 words: Slugged BC-GORE-INTERNET-PROBLEM-SLATE
</P>
</TEXT>
