<SLUG> BC-RACIAL-PROFILING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFFLUENT COMMUNITY DEALS WITH DIVERSITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANNIE NAKAO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PIEDMONT, Calif. _ In this affluent, largely white enclave famed
for its elegant homes, good schools and, residents say,
``politeness and protocol,'' it used to be that the only
``different'' folks in town were Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But an increasingly diverse Piedmont recently has found itself
grappling with race relations after allegations of racial profiling
by town police provoked a good deal of civic upset and, some say,
illuminating debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great that people are talking,'' said Maude
Pervere, a white resident and community activist. ``That's a rare
thing anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The catalyst: an Oct. 5 opinion piece in the weekly Piedmont
Post on a reported traffic stop of two black baseball coaches
visiting the city.
</P>
<P>
   Written by a white resident and teacher, the piece touched off a
flurry of reaction _ from Police Chief John Moilan, who called the
account inaccurate and incomplete, and former Mayor Clark Galloway,
who dismissed the story as ``baloney,'' to those who called it
``the ugly truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the controversy has occurred as Piedmont, on some
levels, has attempted to embrace diversity.
</P>
<P>
   Once virtually all white, this town of nearly 11,000 residents
is now 20 percent Asian American, and roughly 5 to 8 percent black
and Latino.
</P>
<P>
   Those changes _ along with an influx of young families who moved
to Piedmont after the 1991 East Bay hills fire _ have had a
dramatic impact.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the changes, some residents feel that Piedmont's
historic insularity _ perceived or real _ still makes some
minorities feel unwelcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rightly or wrongly, Piedmont had that image of being a city
that's restrictive or not welcoming to people of color,'' said Sue
Tamura, an Asian American civil rights attorney who sits on the
town's year-old Community Relations Committee. ``People have those
memories.''
</P>
<P>
   Lingering perceptions, she and others say, are what have fed the
recent controversy over resident Linda Wallace's article.
</P>
<P>
   In it, Wallace said she'd invited the coaches to a football
game, but they were stopped twice by police on their way to the
field and never came to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace said that incident _ along with another involving police
questioning a black high school student _ amounted to racial
profiling. This assertion has been vigorously disputed by police
and city leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racism is a serious charge about which we are all concerned,''
wrote Police Chief Moilan in the Post. ``Inaccurate, incomplete
information was used to accuse the Piedmont Police Department of
wrongdoing. The charges hurt the department and the community ...
and the charges were false.''
</P>
<P>
   The facts remain in dispute _ Moilan said no stops were made by
either Piedmont or Oakland police in that area. A private security
guard was at the field enforcing a parking ban.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe something happened _ I have no reason not to believe
the coach, but we have to respond with facts,'' said Moilan, who
added that Piedmont is voluntarily tracking traffic stops by race
and gives its officers diversity training.
</P>
<P>
   Moilan was strongly defended by City Administrator Geoff Grote,
who called Wallace's account ``badly mischaracterized. In the
future, I hope we get specific facts prior to making a media
event.''
</P>
<P>
   But others have chided city officials for focusing on the
disputed facts and not the underlying issues of diversity.
</P>
<P>
   A letter in Tuesday's Post, signed by five members of an ad hoc
racially diverse group of residents calling themselves the Piedmont
Human Relations Committee, said: ``Many of us moved to Piedmont
because of its safety, small-town feel, beauty and excellent
schools. Yet beneath this tranquil exterior, the larger community
often does not hear minority voices.''
</P>
<P>
   The ad hoc group, for example, had asked the City Council to
establish a Human Relations Commission to address racial incidents.
Instead, the council created an advisory Community Relations
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Patty White said the council didn't want an ``additional
layer of bureaucracy.'' A new commission also would have required
an expensive ballot measure.
</P>
<P>
   As for tensions, White said she didn't perceive any.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I would say there are problems or issues,''
she said. ``I think there's an urge to have people understand each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   But, noted Lisa Coffey Mahoney, a reporter for the weekly
Piedmonter, diversity isn't a subject people discuss easily,
especially in Piedmont.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to sweep it out of sight,'' said Mahoney. ``They
don't talk about it. Yes, there are issues. It's not that people
have mean intentions. It's just that this town has been so
one-dimensional for so long that they don't realize that the things
they say or do may offend people.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
