<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOLLOW THE MONEY: HILLARY'S NOT RUNNING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUGLAS MacKINNON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Enough already about Hillary Clinton running for
the Senate in New York. It's never going to happen. Period.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of the last few months, I have been the
Washington equivalent of Chicken Little, telling anyone who would
listen that the first lady is not running, never really intended to
run, and in fact will never run for the Senate in New York State.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, my prediction is met with raised eyebrows, blank stares
or shakes of the head that translate into, ``You poor boy. Clearly,
you haven't been reading the papers or watching TV.''
</P>
<P>
   My answer to them is, ``Well, clearly, you haven't been paying
enough attention to what motivates the first lady.'' Because
therein lies the answer as to why she isn't really running for the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   My rationale for why Hillary Clinton is pulling one of the great
political scams of recent times is as follows: First, if you look
at it from a purely political prediction standpoint, there is a
very good chance that Rudy Giuliani would not only beat her
decisively, but in fact, embarrass her with the sheer numbers of
his victory.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady is good at adding numbers, does a fairly good job
of reading tea leaves, understands that to a large segment of New
York voters her act is wearing thin and would therefore want no
part of becoming a political joke for David Letterman and Jay Leno
to bat back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   Second, if you accept the premise that the first lady cares a
great deal about money (which I do accept), then such a run makes
even less sense. A senator's salary (while great for most
Americans) would be chump-change for Clinton if she decided to
chase the coin of our realm.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three or four years, she could make between $10
and $30 million. Such money would come from a combination of a very
large book advance (which would be astronomical if she gave the
publisher the wink and the nod that she would be willing to dish
dirt on the president), speaking fees, board memberships, stock
options, movie deals, a partnership in a major law firm and various
other ways that one who aspires to real money and happens to be a
controversial former first lady could come up with.
</P>
<P>
   Third, Clinton knows she is young politically, knows that the
next few years are the prime years to cash in on her fame and
understands that it may in fact be better for her to go back to her
home state of Illinois and take on Peter Fitzgerald in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   That way she gets to make the money she aspires to while still
fanning the flame of her presidential ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   So why, you ask, is she perpetrating such an elaborate hoax on
the American people and a somewhat complicit and bored media?
</P>
<P>
   Again, if you begin with the premise that Clinton is nothing if
not Machiavellian, then it all makes sense. One could argue that
she first floated this rumor as a way to deflect attention away
from the president's impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Then, once that threat was behind them, she discovered that she
very much enjoyed the positive attention it brought her. She could
have thought that if she were to try to get into the money game,
then all of this press attention could only serve to drive up her
eventual speaking fees and book advance.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, like a small child who tells a lie about breaking
the lamp, she now cannot quite figure out how to extricate herself
from the fictional campaign web she has spun.
</P>
<P>
   She can offer up any number of plausible excuses not to run.
</P>
<P>
   She can say she decided it's not in the best interest of
Chelsea.
</P>
<P>
   She can say the mental stress has gotten to be too much.
</P>
<P>
   Or she can say that, after much soul-searching, she believes
someone like Andrew Cuomo could better serve the people of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what, she will come up with something. I have complete
confidence in her ability to stab the New York Democratic Party in
the back and still come out smelling like a rose as far as the
media are concerned.
</P>
<P>
   Nita Lowey and Al Gore may be a bit upset if Clinton pulls a
Houdini in a state so critical to the Democrats in 2000. But she
may well think, ``Well, what are two more angry Democrats added to
the long list of Democrats Bill and I have upset when there is such
a large pot of gold at the end of the disgruntled former first lady
rainbow?''
</P>
<P>
   She's not running.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Douglas MacKinnon is a former writer for Presidents Reagan and
Bush, a former Pentagon official and a novelist. He currently works
at a Washington, DC law firm.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
