<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-JOURNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BYGONE G'DAYS: AUSTRALIA COOLS TO `MATESHIP' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ADELAIDE, Australia _ It is as Australian as kangaroos and
boomerangs. Around the world, everyone knows ``mateship'' as that
uniquely Down Under brand of friendliness, shared by friends saying
``g'day'' in the outback.
</P>
<P>
   But here, the word ``mateship'' isn't greeted as warmly as it
once was.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the concept of mateship is roiling the country. What
outsiders consider a symbol of Australian good will has become a
lightning rod for ethnic and gender divisions, giving rise to a
wave of national self-analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister John Howard has suggested inserting the word
``mateship'' into the preamble of the Constitution,
enthusiastically promoting it as a vital part of the country's
psyche. Howard wanted voters to approve the matter in a national
referendum _ part of the ballot over the weekend in which
Australians decided to retain the Queen of England as their head of
state.
</P>
<P>
   He couldn't even get it on the ballot. While Australians
accomplished the colossal task of defining their relationship with
the crown, they could not settle an equally longstanding and loaded
debate: whom ``mateship'' applies to, and what it stands for.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A ``mate,'' of course, is a friend, and the word is tossed about
freely in Australian slang. Yet to the politically correct, it is a
deeply masculine word, evoking images of beer-swilling sailors and
strapping bush rangers, instead of the country's Aboriginal
population or the thousands of Asian immigrants who populate
Australia's urban centers.
</P>
<P>
   Mateship, likewise, is seen as having strong masculine
overtones. Feminists and minorities deplore it as a code word for
white male bonding and corruption _ a rough equivalent of a good
old boy network in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The myth of mateship, this male clubbiness, may have been
responsible for the exclusion of women from much of Australian
life,'' writer Jeff Corbett said in the Newcastle Herald earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the convict era, mateship has meant different things to
different social groups: bush folk and city laborers; leaders in
politics, business and the professions; outcasts and outlaws;
women, immigrants, Aborigines and artists,'' Axel Clark, an
Australian literature professor at Australian National University,
wrote last month in the Sydney Morning Herald. ``Many Australians
have been made to feel that exclusiveness painfully, while others
have found comfort, strength and faith in mateship.''
</P>
<P>
   Australian soldiers fighting at Gallipoli during World War I
drew strength from mateship, Clark wrote, and public officials have
long benefited from the power their mates provide. It has even
translated into a political ideology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some left-wing Aussie optimists liked to say that `socialism
is just being mates,' '' Clark wrote. ``They treasured the idea
that `the doctrine of mateship' represented a radical solution to
the problems of mankind.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Howard, however, the doctrine of mateship brought no such
glory. He introduced the idea of including it in the Constitution's
preamble in March, when officials were also debating whether to use
the word ``kinship'' or ``custodianship'' to describe indigenous
peoples' relationship with the land.
</P>
<P>
   But mateship was the most important addition, Howard said at the
time, describing it as ``the one word in all of this which is
unarguably, distinctively, and grammatically and proudly
Australian.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't find it in any other preamble,'' Howard said.
``I'm not surprised that that's attracted a lot of attention. It is
the most unambiguously, passionate, unmistakable Australian word,
and it conjures up whole lots of things about our way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics vehemently disagreed, however, and the Australian
Democratic Party launched a campaign to get the word dropped from
the proposal. It took only days for Howard to cave in to the
pressure. He did so, he said, in order to get the other changes to
the preamble made.
</P>
<P>
   ``To pass up that opportunity simply because I couldn't get my
way on one particular word would have been the wrong thing to have
done,'' he said. Still, he added: ``I have to say I'm very sorry
about that, very sorry indeed.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Anne E. Kornblut is a member of the Globe staff.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
