<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2669 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k BC-SOUTHERNERS-HNS &LR;      11-08 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERNERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRANGELY LIST OF TOP 100 SOUTHERNERS INCLUDES MANY NORTHERNERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDVINS BEITIKS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The South has had to put up with a lot of cruel and unfunny
stereotypes _ that Southerners are slow, parochial, too steeped in
the past, too territorial, not really aware of how the world works.
Truth is, Southerners are sharp and hardy and can carry America's
banner as well as any other part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   What, then, should we make of the list of this century's 100
most influential Southerners, as voted by the readers of the
Atlanta Journal-Constitution? In one way it's just another bag of
big names, another bogus Millennium List that begs to be
second-guessed. But in another way it's downright grotesque _ turns
out you don't even have to be a Southerner to make it.
</P>
<P>
   The daily Journal-Constitution included ballots with 200 names,
plus space for write-ins, and made a Web site available.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 people voted. When it ran the results of the
survey at the end of last month, the newspaper described the list
as ``an eclectic group, dominated by popular culture figures . . .
and they're not all Southerners.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, there are half a dozen non-Southerners on the list,
including the Wright brothers, Walt Disney, Franklin D. Roosevelt,
Earl Warren and ``the Rockefeller Foundation,'' which received 589
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King Jr. finished as the most influential
Southerner of the century. No argument there. But No. 2 is Wilbur
and Orville Wright, who were born and raised in Ohio and Indiana _
their closest touch to the South coming on that short flight at
Kitty Hawk, N.C., on Dec. 17, 1903.
</P>
<P>
   No. 3 is Jimmy Carter, arguably not half the president Woodrow
Wilson, another Southerner, was. But Woodrow Wilson is voted in at
No. 41 _ two spots below Rosalyn Carter. Bill Clinton? He's at No.
48, sandwiched between Willie Nelson and Dolly Parton, exactly
twice as far down the list as No. 24, the mythical figure of Col.
Sanders, chicken king.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 is rounded out by Ted Turner at No. 4, evangelist
Billy Graham, George Washington Carver, Sam Walton (founder of
Wal-Mart), Louis Armstrong, Henry Aaron and Elvis Presley.
</P>
<P>
   Presley pushed to the end of a line behind Carter, Graham and
Walton? Hard to believe.
</P>
<P>
   The most egregious choices on the list are in the arts.
</P>
<P>
   William Faulkner, the South's preeminent 20th century author,
comes in behind Douglas MacArthur (11), Margaret Mitchell (16) and
Michael Jordan (17). The humor columnist Lewis Grizzard is 26th _
51 spots ahead of Southern literary icon Thomas Wolfe.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby Foote, whose Civil War trilogy is the best yet written,
doesn't make the list. Neither does James Dickey, Robert Penn
Warren or Richard Wright. But John Grisham does. Pat Conroy does.
</P>
<P>
   MacArthur, Chester Nimitz (54) and William Westmoreland (74) are
there, but not John J. Pershing or George Patton, who was born in
San Gabriel but raised in the South, son of a famous Virginia
family. Oprah Winfrey's at No. 28 and Andy Griffith makes the list
at No. 30 _ ahead of Arthur Ashe, Bear Bryant, Hank Williams,
Willie Mays, Andrew Young and Lyndon Johnson. Andy Griffith ...
</P>
<P>
   Some things on the list just make you smile. Justice Hugo Black
finishes at No. 84, behind Gladys Knight (without the Pips) and
Little Richard. Even in their hometown, the Braves _ the
millennium's bridesmaids of baseball _ don't make the list. And
right in the middle there's a crazy quilt of Southerners in the
space of 10 names: Joe Louis, Mahalia Jackson, Bobby Jones, Patsy
Cline, George Wallace and James Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Spike Lee is there (No. 90), but not D.W. Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   Loretta Lynn makes it, but not W.C. Handy, Billie Holiday,
Bessie Smith or Bob Wills.
</P>
<P>
   Foodies Paul Prudhomme and Justin Wilson are among the 100.
</P>
<P>
   Newt Gingrich makes it at No. 61, but Sam Rayburn _ the Speaker
of the House in this century _ does not. Neither does Huey Long,
populist king of America, a political figure strong enough to scare
FDR.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the Journal-Constitution list is as forgettable as
all the other millennium lists. But it does have that intriguing
difference _ that you don't have to be a Southerner to make it.
Kind of opens things up, doesn't it? Most influential Irish of the
millennium _ Mao Tse Tung, Joseph Stalin, Margaret Thatcher. Most
influential gays? The sky's the limit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
