<HEADER>
A2673 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS &LR;      11-08 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MYSTERIES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWING WRITERS WHO NEED NONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBIN W. WINKS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking at mystery reviews in the press these days, a reader
might easily get the impression that the writers of the big
blockbusters are no longer at work. Perhaps the commendable (I
think) wish to introduce readers to lesser-known writers, or to
help give a first-time novelist a bit of a boost, plays a role in
this. Certainly, I am sure, the thought that the big names hardly
need the help of a review, and that their fans require no guidance,
since the books will sell in the many thousands whatever a critic
may say, is behind some of this silence. When the best-known
writers are discussed, gossip is often the main purpose: Is it true
that Dick Francis's wife, Mary, actually writes his books? That P.
D. James works out her repressions through Cordelia Gray? Such
speculation often is to the neglect of the books themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The simplest answer, I believe, is that the blockbuster writers
are both so good at what they do, and (having established
themselves at the top of a very greasy pole) so cautious about
changing their formulas, that they tend to be quite predictable,
which leads any reviewer toward silence. This month I thought I
would resist that silence and see what some of the Big Guns are up
to.
</P>
<P>
   Robert B. Parker is definitely a Big Gun, and deservedly so. In
``Family Honor'' (Putnam, $22.95), he introduces his first female
private eye. Sunny Randall is a former cop, a college graduate,
divorced, trying to be a painter, and every bit as understanding as
Spenser when it comes to confused teenagers who are a pain in the
neck. She is a more fully realized person than Parker's other
recent creation, Jesse Stone, but they have in common with Spenser
a laconic style, ability to defend themselves when driven to the
wall, and an attraction to Boston and its environs. Sunny Randall
is hired by a wealthy and very unpleasant set of parents to find
their daughter, apparently a runaway. This is quickly done, and
then comes the harder part: Should this vulnerable, hard-edged
child be returned to her parents at all? Parker handles the
slippery emotions well, and if Randall sounds just like Spenser
with a gender change, there is no reason for surprise or regret.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Grafton is another of the Dependables, and ``O Is For
Outlaw'' (Holt, $26) is precisely what one has come to expect.
Kinsey Milhone returns for her 15th ``adventure,'' as the dust
jacket tells us with unaccustomed honesty (any element of
``mystery,'' in the sense of having to unravel clues, has been
missing from the Grafton novels for some time). In this one we
learn much more about Kinsey's earlier life, her first marriage,
and what she was like in 1967, when she graduated from high school.
The action takes place in 1986 _ Grafton obviously has to slow the
calendar down if she has any hopes of keeping Kinsey out of a
wheelchair until ``Z'' is for zero, and this adds to the
attraction. I do wish Grafton wouldn't pad her books, though: ``I
turned right onto Hilgard, right again on Le Conte, and right onto
Tiverton where I paid for a parking voucher.'' Who cares?
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Woods has long since entered into the land of the
Biggies, and ``Worst Fears Realized'' (HarperCollins, $25) displays
his strengths and weaknesses perfectly. He tells a terrific yarn,
unadorned and straight ahead. His sentences, though, are
flat-footed and suffer from Harold Robbinsitis _ which is to say, a
kind of reverse gush. These are page-turners in the truest sense of
the word. Here we encounter Stone Barrington again _ he's a
handsome, omni-competent New York lawyer with attitude who moves
among the beautiful people _ and this time someone is killing all
the women in his life, improbably, melodramatically, quickly. Woods
is one of those writers whose figures become simply bodies, sex
dolls, mouthpieces for a social attitude. He makes one long for
John D. MacDonald, but one keeps reading him and his books keep
selling, for John D. is dead, alas.
</P>
<P>
   So is Agatha Christie, but Charles Osborne is trying to
resuscitate her. In 1998 he released ``Black Coffee,'' his
rewriting of a Christie play into a novel, and it worked quite well
and received much praise (including mine). Now he gives us ``The
Unexpected Guest'' (St. Martin's, $23.95), based on a 1958 Christie
play that had a 16-month run in a London theater. Osborne has made
an unfortunate choice for his second pastiche, for the central
puzzle of the play does not translate at all well into straight
prose, and any self-respecting reader will have nearly everything
figured out by Page 38. To go on reading in the hope that it can't
be this simple, and then to discover that it is, leads to
disappointment. Perhaps this should be the last of these revivals.
</P>
<P>
   I close with a brace of true revivals. In 1958 and 1959, in the
fading days of the British Empire, M. M. Kaye published two
mysteries that are now republished by St. Martin's as ``Death in
Kenya'' and ``Death in Zanzibar'' (both $12.95, paperback). Kaye
went on to write enormously popular books, including ``The Far
Pavilions.'' It is good to have these two mysteries back, for they
are well-constructed novels about life in colonial settings now
long gone, a life Kaye knew at first hand. The reader can feel the
heat, and the racial and sexual antagonisms _ for they are the real
thing, no pastiche.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1341EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2674 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-EVEREST-BOS &LR;      11-08 0943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-EVEREST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIMBERS SHED LIGHT ON MALLORY MYSTERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE DANIEL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
GHOSTS OF EVEREST 
The Search for Mallory &AMP; Irvine 
By Jochen Hemmleb, Larry A. Johnson, and Eric R. Simonson 
Mountaineers, 205 pp., illustrated, $29.95 
 
THE LOST EXPLORER 
Finding Mallory on Mount Everest 
By Conrad Anker and David Roberts 
Simon &AMP; Schuster, 191 pp., illustrated, $22 
 
LAST CLIMB 
The Legendary Everest Expeditions of George Mallory 
By David Breashears and Audrey Salkeld 
National Geographic Society, 239 pp., illustrated, $35 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   George Mallory is to mountaineering what Amelia Earhart is to
aviation. Both were young, attractive, and well-known adventurers
who disappeared while attempting historic record-breaking feats.
Earhart's remains, of course, have never been found, but the body
of Mallory, eerily preserved in the deep-freeze time capsule of
Mount Everest, was discovered in May by members of the 1999 Mallory
&AMP; Irvine Research Expedition. The startling find, which made
international headlines, has spawned two books from the search
team's members, and prompted the authors of another book already in
the works about Mallory's Everest expeditions to include the
updated information.
</P>
<P>
   What none of these books do is answer mountaineering's biggest
mystery: Did Mallory and his climbing partner Andrew Irvine reach
the summit of the world's highest mountain on June 8, 1924? Such a
feat would have made them the first, but without proof positive,
that distinction goes to Edmund Hillary and sherpa Tenzing Norgay
29 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Each book, relying on if-then scenarios, presents several
educated guesses about what happened. The one thing learned in May
is that Mallory died in a fall while roped to Irvine. The summit
question will never be answered unless the camera the two men were
carrying is found, the film is preserved, and a photo shows the two
at the summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ghosts of Everest,'' by expedition members, Jochen Hemmleb,
Larry Johnson, and Eric Simonson as told to writer William
Nothdurft, focuses as much on the entire project as on finding
Mallory's body. Hemmleb, 27, was the team's historian and trip
originator. He and Johnson, a climber and marketer of outdoor
books, met over the Internet and they asked Simonson, a top-notch
Himalaya expedition organizer, to serve as leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ghosts of Everest'' alternates between the unfolding of both
the 1999 and the 1924 expeditions, and both stories are riveting.
There are common themes: the climbers' passion, extraordinary
physical demands, mind-boggling logistics, and a constant need for
media and money to get trips off the ground. The firsthand account
of the five men who examined Mallory's remains is powerful reading,
and you know they will be forever changed by the discovery. ``We
weren't just looking at a body,'' said team member Dave Hahn. ``We
were looking at an era, one we'd only known through books.''
</P>
<P>
   The book contains astonishing photographs that include
breathtaking scenery, 1924 artifacts, climbing shots from both
trips, and bone-chilling photographs of Mallory's body on the day
it was found. What is missing from ``Ghosts of Everest'' is much of
the controversy that came from publishing and even selling those
photos of Mallory, and any serious pondering about the real-time
media coverage.
</P>
<P>
   A fascinating facet of the 1999 expedition was the reliance on
the media, and ``The Lost Explorer'' discusses that. The book is
coauthored by world-class mountaineer Conrad Anker, who was the
strongest climber on the trip and the person who found Mallory's
body; and David Roberts, a Cambridge, Mass. outdoors writer and
mountaineer. Hemmleb and crew were in many ways at the mercy of the
BBC and WGBH/NOVA, with whom they'd struck filming deals, and
mountaineering Internet site MountainZone.com, another backer. Team
members filed reports over the Web site daily _ and it received a
million hits a day for two weeks after Mallory's body was found.
</P>
<P>
   Although Anker's occasional criticism of his expedition and
teammates seems gratuitous, his first-person narrative, in contrast
to the third-person in ``Ghosts,'' is even more immediate and
gripping, particularly when writing about finding Mallory and his
subsequent summit of Everest. What ``The Lost Explorer'' sorely
lacks, however, is photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Much is made of whether the Second Step, a steep incline on the
way up, can be climbed without aid (it now has a ladder and ropes).
If not, then Mallory and Irvine could not have made it to the top.
``Ghosts'' says ``it most certainly can'' because Anker climbed it.
Anker, who compromised his free climb (without aid) by resting on a
ladder rung, disputes that in ``The Lost Explorer.'' Not only is
Anker convinced that Mallory and Irvine couldn't have climbed it,
he is unequivocal in his belief they could never have descended it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Climb,'' by photographer and climber David Breashears of
Boston and preeminent Mallory historian Audrey Salkeld, is mostly
an account of Mallory's Everest expeditions but includes
information on the May discovery. It, too, is beautifully designed
and includes splendid artwork of Everest and climbers old and new.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Climb'' echoes the other two books and every expedition
member's sentiments when it says: ``Although Mallory and Irvine
perished for their dream, they showed the way, and helped us
understand both the tug of Everest, and the indomitable nature of
the human spirit. Their achievement is so much greater than our
need to know whether or not they climbed to the top.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
