<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 13:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2681 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      11-08 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHILDREN, TOO, NEED PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it any wonder that adults are such a vexation to children? We
refuse to grant them the simple dignity of their own interior
lives.
</P>
<P>
   It is not enough that we structure their every hour between
waking and sleeping, that we insist on ``supervised'' play and
``organized'' sports, that we censor their musical selections and
monitor their television viewing. Now we insist on vetting their
imaginations, too.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Potter is the latest target of misguided parental angst.
Forget Marilyn Manson and the video game ``Doom.'' Those are
yesterday's demons. Today we fear the stories of sorcerers that are
being scooped up by pre-adolescents, the tales of wizards that are
waltzing off the bookshop shelves.
</P>
<P>
   Can Satan worship be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, vigilant adults are challenging teachers who
read the Harry Potter series aloud in their classrooms. The Family
Friendly Library Association, including its Massachusetts
affiliate, wants to know why religious themes are verboten in
public schools but witchcraft is all the rage.
</P>
<P>
   It was only a matter of time.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since J. K. Rowling took the publishing world and
children's imaginations by storm a year ago with the first of her
novels about a magical, parallel universe beneath the British isle,
the clock was ticking. How long before grown-ups found something
sinister in the Hogwarts School of Witchcraft and Wizardry? What
does it mean that so many kids love these books? Has Rowling
bewitched them? Entranced everyone under the age of 13?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe children see their own life struggles in Harry's. Maybe
they see the schoolyard bully in his horrid ``Muggle'' cousin,
Dudley. Maybe they don't see anything at all recognizable in the
universe Rowling has created. Why does it matter to anyone but the
mass marketers who most assuredly are analyzing every page of every
book in search of the ``magic'' formula in order to replicate
Rowling's success.
</P>
<P>
   The simple truth is that we aren't meant to know everything
about our children's world. It's theirs, not ours. When our
freshly-minted teenager grunts ``fine'' in response to our inquiry
about the quality of his day, he is not hiding something from us;
he is preserving something for himself. When our suddenly-secretive
daughter tucks her diary between the mattress and box spring, she
is not hoarding information; she is honing her identity.
</P>
<P>
   When did respecting our children's privacy and independence
become an indicator of parental neglect?
</P>
<P>
   We are packing the Halloween decorations away this week,
replacing the cackling witch on the mantel with the Thanksgiving
pilgrims. But as we box up the rubber skeletons and the monster
masks, it is hard not to note how different, how sanitized, the
ultimate kids' holiday was this year. Post-Columbine, the grim
reaper was stripped of his rubber sickle at the schoolhouse door;
the pirate was disarmed of his plastic dagger. Not because of
reasonable concerns that ``you could poke an eye out with that
thing,'' but because of unreasonable fears that kids would mistake
one another's Halloween props for lethal weaponry.
</P>
<P>
   In one school in Massachusetts, a child makes a list of
classmates he doesn't especially like and is sent home until a
therapist can assuage the fears of parents (or the liability
concerns of the school's lawyers.)
</P>
<P>
   In a school in Texas, a child earns an ``A'' on a class
assignment and more than a night in juvenile detention after his
jittery teacher decides that maybe his scary essay was a veiled
threat.
</P>
<P>
   It does not minimize the seriousness of school violence to ask
whether we have gone too far in our attempts to shield our children
from the normal anxieties of life at century's end. Fantasy is
fine, we say, as long as the content is regulated by us, not them.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, Harry Potter's adventures involve struggles between good
and evil. It is not giving away the plot to note that, in the three
novels published so far, good triumphs. Sounds a lot like the Bible
to me.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is something simple and pure slipped into our
children's lives. It sneaked in under the adult radar screen. Its
magic spread by word of mouth from cabin to cabin at summer camp,
from swing to slide in the schoolyard, from top to bottom bunk in
the boys' room down the hall.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe we're jealous. Our children have a rich interior life. We
can't own it. It doesn't belong to us, anymore than our children
do.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara's e-mail address is mcnamara(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
