<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHEPARD IN THE FIELDS OF KARMIC CONNECTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Although it can become a dangerous
oversimplification of the concept, the popular idea that you
actually sow and reap karma holds a great deal of appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Deliberately sow good stuff, and it will come back to you as
good stuff _ or at least as a milder dose of bad stuff you were
already in karmic line to receive. Sow bad karma and, sooner or
later, it will come back to bite you on the butt.
</P>
<P>
   It's the sooner-or-later part that makes karma a much more
mystical and long-view form of justice than versions like ``An eye
for an eye'' or ``The wages of sin is death.''
</P>
<P>
   Because karma is the weighty total of your actions in this or
any lifetime _ and the driving force of your fate _ you might have
to wait a couple of incarnations, much less 10 or 15 years, to get
back specific good or ill you once sowed. Considering that most of
us tend to forget what we sowed about 15 MINUTES after we did it,
we see no connection to our eventual harvest. Our overview of our
personal karmic farm is, ``(Bleep) happens.''
</P>
<P>
   This myopia blinds us to the fact that our karmic farm is not an
island. Our fields bleed into the fields of every other person we
encounter in life. And theirs bleed into ours. Sow bad karma, you
make the world a worse place; sow good, you improve it.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to Judy Shepard.
</P>
<P>
   The mother of Matthew Shepard _ the gay Wyoming college student
who was beaten to death by two sick, young homophobes _ Judy
Shepard sowed some truly wonderful (and powerfully countercultural)
karma last week.
</P>
<P>
   After a Laramie jury found Aaron McKinney guilty of the felony
murder of her son _ a crime that qualifies for the death penalty _
Shepard helped negotiate a deal between the prosecution and
defense. It spared McKinney's life.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Cal Rerucha initially did not want to take the deal
of life without parole or appeal, he said. But Judy Shepard
convinced him _ and her pro-death penalty husband _ that it was the
right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a remarkable woman to be able to go through what she has
and to do what she has done,'' Rerucha said. ``And what she has
done is said Matthew stood for something and that something was
tolerance, a tolerance of people.''
</P>
<P>
   In a radical departure from the angry and vengeful norm, Judy
Shepard told Rerucha, ``It would be wrong if our motives were
revenge instead of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost never do we hear the loved ones of murder victims
distinguish between justice and revenge. In case after case, the
``family's wishes'' are cited as the primary reason that only a
death sentence can equal justice. Execution has become the lone
catalyst for ``healing'' and ``closure.'' Even the youngest members
of a grieving clan ``can't wait'' for the day they get to watch the
condemned killer die.
</P>
<P>
   The aberrations from this norm are few and under-publicized.
</P>
<P>
   Who hears the sad, merciful voice of a Bud Welch, who lost his
daughter in the Oklahoma City bombing, over an enraged,
death-hungry chorus of people like Richard Thornton, whose wife was
murdered by Karla Faye Tucker?
</P>
<P>
   As he watched Tucker die by lethal injection, Thornton said
aloud to his dead wife: ``Here she comes, baby doll. She's all
yours. The world's a better place.''
</P>
<P>
   He was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Like scores of other hurt and angry family members, Thornton was
the unwitting recipient of someone else's horrendous karma dump.
But he compounded the negativity, for himself and the rest of us,
by combatting bad with bad.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Shepard chose a different seed to sow.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing her son's murderer blame the slaying on drugs,
alcohol and ``gay panic,'' after enduring weeks in a courtroom with
nightmarish testimony about (and photos of) Matthew's last hours,
she said ``yes'' to a defense plea to save McKinney's life.
</P>
<P>
   Her choice will not bring back her child, anymore than
Thornton's will bring back his wife. But, karmically speaking, Judy
Shepard has lightened her own load somewhere down the line.
</P>
<P>
   And all of us with fields adjoining hers should thank her for
making this a better world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her electronic mail address
is salter(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
