<HEADLINE>
WHAT ARE FOSSILS MADE OF? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ROPEIK  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. What minerals are fossils made of?
</P>
<P>
   A.A., Bellingham &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. ``Fossils can be made of anything,'' according to Doug Erwin,
curator of paleontology at the Smithsonian's National Museum of
Natural History. They come in four basic types.
</P>
<P>
   The first is simply the original material of the creature that
died.
</P>
<P>
   The second is called a permineralized fossil. That forms when
minerals carried by fluids fill the pores and tiny spaces in the
original biological material. When the fluid evaporates, the
minerals harden, filling those spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the fluids and minerals dissolve away all the original
material and only the hardened mineral remains. An example is
petrified wood. ``The process can be so fine that you can actually
make out individual cells in the hardened minerals,'' Erwin says.
</P>
<P>
   A third kind of fossil is made like a cast in a mold. Animals or
plants that fell on a soft, muddy spot, often in a shallow lake or
ocean bottom, left an impression of their shape, like a footprint
on a muddy trail. Over time silt and other minerals deposited into
the impression and hardened into rock in the shape of the
impression. Erwin says the oldest fossils ever found, 3.56
billion-year-old single-celled organisms, were impressions in
chert, a rock, in Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there are the fossils of ancient insects preserved in
amber, a plant resin that oozed out, enveloped the unlucky bug, and
hardened around it, preserving the entire creature. Erwin says the
Jurassic Park notion that such fossils might yield ancient DNA is
still science fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Holy Grail of fossil science,'' he says. ``But DNA is
too fragile. It breaks down.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. What is the densest element?
</P>
<P>
   LAUREN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. At the level of a single atom, there's no topping uranium.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the weight and density of an atom comes from the protons
and neutrons in its nucleus. Uranium (Ur), element 92, has 92
protons in the nucleus, along with 146 neutrons. That gives it a
total atomic weight of slightly more than 238. It's the heaviest
naturally occurring element.
</P>
<P>
   Since all atoms are about the same size, the more protons and
neutrons an atom is packed with, the denser it is. Think of it like
grains of sand inside a ping pong ball. The more grains a ball is
packed with, the denser it is.
</P>
<P>
   Lead (Pb) is atomic number 82, atomic weight 207. If Superman
couldn't see through Pb, he sure couldn't see through Ur.
</P>
<P>
   But when a bunch of atoms join and form a molecule, Osmium (Os)
wins the density title. Atom for atom it's only a middleweight,
number 76, atomic weight 190. But when Osmium atoms form a
molecule, they can squeeze together in a way that takes up less
space than when uranium or lead atoms bond together. It's like
being able to pack more grains of sand inside the ping pong ball.
More atoms in the same space means a heavier, denser molecule.
</P>
<P>
   Osmium has a density of 22.583 grams per cubic centimeter.
Uranium is 19.07. Lead is 11.34. Rock averages around 3. Water is
1. Butter is .86. Cork is .22.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Readers are invited to send science questions to How&AMP;Why. Write to
How&AMP;Why, Health/Science, Box 2378, The Boston Globe, Boston, MA
02107; or send via Internet to: howwhy(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
