<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA BAYOUS DISAPPEARING AS SEA LEVELS RISE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: Photos are being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISLE DE JEAN CHARLES, Louisiana _ The retired priest tells his
story with a faded photo of his smiling mother in her flower
garden. Those were the good old days of the 1950s, the Rev. Roch
Naquin explains, when cows grazed in a big field behind the family
home and a new road brought the first cars to this remote bayou
village.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the Gulf of Mexico began swallowing up the land,
turning the family's pasture into a marsh and salting what was left
of his mother's garden. The prized road, once flanked by broad
green fields, became a causeway through open ocean, waves washing
over the bleak asphalt when the wind blows.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do nothing, in 10 years, this place will be water,''
said Naquin, who, like many of the Chitimacha Indians living on the
low ridge, has put his modest house up on cinderblocks to escape
the advancing water.
</P>
<P>
   Coastal Louisiana is literally sinking into the sea, drowning
places such as Isle de Jean Charles and giving the rest of North
America an alarming glimpse of what may lie in store in the 21st
century if sea levels rise as much as some scientists expect.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1930, an area 50 percent bigger than Rhode Island has
returned to the sea in Louisiana, and Louisiana State University
researchers say another Rhode Island-sized patch could go in the
next 50 years. Louisiana accounts for 80 percent of the coastal
wetlands destroyed in the United States annually, a dramatic threat
to one of the most productive fisheries in the world.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Louisiana's problems are unique, at least for now.
The region south of New Orleans is so low-lying that locals refer
to land just 3 feet above sea level as ``a ridge.'' And the land is
so new, formed by sediment deposits from the Mississippi River over
the past 5,000 years, that it is still sinking.
</P>
<P>
   State officials inadvertently triggered the rapid land loss in
the 1930s when they built up the levee system to prevent a repeat
of a 1927 flood that killed hundreds. Unfortunately, the levees
also blocked the Mississippi from delivering fresh mud that could
have built up the delta region.
</P>
<P>
   Despite obvious differences in geography, New England could face
similar problems if global warming and other forces cause sea level
to rise 7 to 39 inches by 2100 as a United Nations scientific panel
predicts. Nearly 10 percent of the land in low-lying towns such as
Hull and Nantucket would be submerged, while storm surges would
flood many places that now stay bone dry.
</P>
<P>
   If sea level rises significantly and the public doesn't prepare,
warns Joe Pelczarski, senior planner with the Massachusetts office
of Coastal Zone Management, ``Every storm would be a misery and
we'd be well into disaster scenario.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Louisiana doesn't have to wait for the 21st century
for a ``disaster scenario'': it's here.
</P>
<P>
   Already, federal, state, and local officials are taking
extraordinary measures to stem the rising tide, from raising roads
to rebuilding islands to diverting the river to areas that need
sediment. Coast 2050, a state and federal plan, calls for $14
billion in coastal restoration projects over the next 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, Louisiana has less than 10 percent of the
funding necessary to carry out Coast 2050, which would be the
largest ecological restoration project in US history, almost twice
as large as the current record holder, the restoration of the
Florida Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Louisiana is dedicated to restoring the coast as best we can,
but we are a poor state,'' said state Natural Resources Secretary
Jack Caldwell, who recently shepherded $15 million for coastal
restoration through the Legislature to prove to Congress that the
state is serious.
</P>
<P>
   Caldwell is pinning his hopes on the Conservation and
Reinvestment Act, a bill in Congress that would divert offshore oil
and gas tax revenues to coastal states, with special provisions for
Louisiana. Because the sinking delta is so important to US fishing
as well as energy interests, Caldwell says its problems should be
solved at a national level, too.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, solving Louisiana's erosion problem may be only a
down payment toward coping with higher sea levels. The US
Environmental Protection Agency estimates that improving coastal
defenses nationally to face higher water will probably cost more
than $100 billion next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the prototype for accelerated sea level rise. If you're
looking for strategies of how people cope,'' Louisiana will be the
model, said Paul Kemp, a coastal geologist at Louisiana State
University.
</P>
<P>
   The people of south Louisiana have always had to live with the
deceptive power of the Mississippi River, which quietly carries
sediment from 31 states as it wends its way toward the Gulf of
Mexico. Over the last 5,000 years, the river created 7,000 square
miles of land in the delta where residents developed precise words
such as ``sloo'' and ``chenier'' to describe the meeting place of
land and water.
</P>
<P>
   But the French, Native American, and other ethnic groups who
settled the region knew that, just as the river could build, it
could also destroy. The great flood of 1927 gave New Orleans such a
fright that officials strategically dynamited the levee so that the
swollen river destroyed other communities and buried them under 18
inches of sediment.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it turned out that the very measures they took to
tame the Mississippi were stealing the land from beneath their
feet. The levee system effectively channeled the river so that it
delivered its sediments, not to the delta, but into the deep water
of the Gulf of Mexico where, ironically, the freshwater has proven
toxic, causing algae blooms that suck up most of the oxygen in a
``dead zone'' where few fish can live.
</P>
<P>
   The oil and gas industry exacerbated erosion by cutting scores
of canals through the delta for pipelines and workers, allowing
saltwater into the interior of the marshes. Meanwhile, sea level
itself rose by about a foot in the past century, allowing storms to
reach further inland than before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like Pogo said, `We have met the enemy and he is us,' ''
said Mark Davis, executive director of the Baton Rouge-based
Coastal Restoration Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even though analysts agree on the causes of Louisiana's
problem, finding a solution proved difficult. The sinking delta is
both so enormous that state and federal officials ended up funding
lots of small, often ineffectual, experiments through the 1980s and
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   Now, ironically, the cornerstone to Louisiana's strategy to save
the land is to bring in more water, cutting gates in the levees
that hold the Mississippi so that its rich sediment can reach
eroding areas. The main river diversion so far, the $26 million
Caernarvon Project in Plaquemines Parish, has rebuilt at least 450
acres of soft, mucky land since 1991, and created a world class
bass fishing area to boot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without this diversion, this marsh would die,'' said Donald
Ansardi, pointing from his airboat across a meadow studded with
black willow trees that have sprouted in the last five years.
Ansardi, land manager for Delacroix Corp. which owns the marsh,
said fresh water from Caernarvon has prevented saltwater from
killing the grass and trees.
</P>
<P>
   But river diversions have stirred opposition from those who
worry they may do more harm than good and even ruin water quality.
Oystermen have sued the state over the Caernarvon project, arguing
that the infusion of freshwater has damaged saltwater oyster beds.
Likewise, Louisiana Governor Mike Foster vetoed an $87 million
diversion after concerns were raised that it could spoil Lake
Ponchartrain.
</P>
<P>
   The only other option is to build more fortifications. Already
going forward on a massive scale are a $350 million plan to elevate
the road to Port Fourchon and a $36 million proposal to build up
barrier islands that are the first line of defense against tropical
storms and hurricanes as they come ashore.
</P>
<P>
   Out on East Timbalier Island, Secretary Caldwell beams at the
hundreds of pelicans roosting near the black mangrove trees planted
by an oil company a few years back. The island was on a track to
sink completely by 2005, but it has received more than a million
cubic yards of sand plus a new seawall courtesy of a National
Marine Fisheries Service restoration fund.
</P>
<P>
   To Caldwell, the island shows that state and federal officials
can counterattack erosion _ if they have the resources. By his
calculation, the state needs more than $400 million a year in
federal funding rather than the $40 million a year they now get.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give us the money, we can do it. This is not
experimental. We've been experimenting for 10 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, in some ways, all of coastal Louisiana is an experiment,
one that other coastal regions are watching with varying degrees of
alarm as both the damage and repair costs mount. Other states know
that global warming, driven by the burning of fossil fuels such as
oil, could eventually raise sea level so much that they will be in
the same expensive boat as Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   And the Louisianans have a message for the world as nations
brace for the erosion problems of the 21st century: it's better to
prevent the sea level rise in the first place rather than try to
fight its effects as they are doing now. As Davis of the Coastal
Restoration Council said, ``We're starting to gain some respect for
God as an engineer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1351EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2689 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MAINE-LOGGERS-BOS &LR;      11-08 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-LOGGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NORTH WOODS, JOBS VANISH, ANGER GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALLAGASH, Maine _ Even in its best days, this city was an
outpost, the last cluster of lights on a road that plunges into
forest. Allagash is not on the way anywhere, and it thrived for a
hundred years in unusual cultural isolation; surrounded on all
sides by French-Canadians, its citizens still speak with a
Scotch-Irish burr.
</P>
<P>
   But ask Mainers about Allagash now, and they will know exactly
what you are talking about. Twice in the last year, a small group
of angry, unemployed woodsmen from this town blockaded the Canadian
border, accusing their government of allowing Canadian loggers to
steal their jobs and, ultimately, drive Americans out of the North
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Their cry resonates powerfully in a thickly wooded region
surrounded on three sides by Canada, rekindling an old fear that
politicians downstate tend to forget that there are people up here
among the trees. Aroostook County juts into Canada like a
peninsula, bordering New Brunswick to the east and Quebec to the
west. As the farming economy declined between 1969 and 1994, the
county lost 14 percent of its population, even as neighboring Maine
counties gained comparable amounts, according to Robert Roper, who
teaches economics at the University of Maine in Bangor.
</P>
<P>
   Allagash's last stand is reminding people that towns can wash
away, that their children may seek work, or even build new lives,
far from the places their ancestors settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like this,'' said Hilton Hafford, 41, a leader of the
group of Allagash protesters. ``There's a certain amount of people
who were meant to live in Idaho, and there's a certain amount of
people who were meant to live in Allagash. That's why we were put
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Canadians have been allowed to work in Maine as long as they
were not taking American jobs. But Hafford and his fellow
protesters say that as the exchange rate has made Canadian labor
even cheaper, the system has broken down. Reacting to the protests,
state labor officials have ordered a study, the first since 1977,
to see what effect the Canadian workers are having on the wages of
Americans. The results are expected by mid-month.
</P>
<P>
   Hafford's critics, who include some in his town, assert that he
and his friends _ a small group that has ranged in number from five
to 12 _ have chosen protest over work. Department of Labor
officials argue that they have spent ``thousands of hours'' trying
to place the Allagash loggers in jobs, only to have them reject the
positions as low-paying or inferior.
</P>
<P>
   At root, many fault the Allagash men for resisting the economic
forces that sometimes require workers not only to update their
skills, but to leave their hometowns.
</P>
<P>
   It is a familiar dilemma in the string of towns that line the
US-Canadian border. In nearby Fort Kent, traffic picks up at 2
a.m., as young men commute hundreds of miles for work downstate,
said Kim Doustou, executive director of the Fort Kent Chamber of
Commerce. And that is the young men who stay. ``Most of the kids
here fly right out of the area,'' according to John Paradis, 40,
who owns Doris's Restaurant in Fort Kent.
</P>
<P>
   Seated at a booth, Norman Bouchard, 65, agreed. He said the last
of his nine children, a lumber hauler, was about to sell his
equipment and move to another part of the state. ``The more you
talk to people around here, the more you'll realize something's
really wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A companion requested anonymity because he was afraid of losing
his job for a large lumber company. ``They call us crybabies,'' he
said, ``but there's no more living in the woods.''
</P>
<P>
   Allagash has endured a painful decline. In 1986, on the occasion
of its centennial, Allagash roasted a whole moose on a spit in
celebration; 10 years later, both its high school and elementary
school had shut down for a lack of students. Now scores of black
flies mill on the inside of a gymnasium window and across the
street; the old fire station is for sale. The population of
Allagash, which reached a high of 750 around the turn of the
century, fell to 242 in the last count, according to town selectman
Roy Gardner. Of those who are left, the average age is 65, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are almost no young men in town. On a recent evening,
Shannon McBreairty, 19, and Donna Bernier, 35, ate dinner together
at Two Rivers Lunch as both of their boyfriends had left town to
find work logging. Bernier's son, who is 19, also has left. Troy
Jackson, 31, who has joined Hafford in the protest effort, tried to
commute for a while, waking up every morning in the dark for the
long drive south to his job, but after a while his 3-year-old
learned how to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oldest one used to hold my finger at night so I didn't
leave,'' he recalled. ``I drove five hours and you'd think about it
the whole way.''
</P>
<P>
   At a certain point, Hafford began to see the shrinking of
Allagash as a personal assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were to hire hit men from New York and start at one
end of town and work their way saying, everybody leave this town,
that wouldn't go too good across the United States. But you see,
they're doing it little by little. It's subtle,'' said Hafford.
</P>
<P>
   When he and his friends give up the fight, trundling south to
find contract work in Connecticut, he added, there will be no one
left to argue for Allagash.
</P>
<P>
   ``What chance do we have of failure?'' he asked. ``The reason
we're here in the first place is we decided we wanted to live here
more than anyone else did.''
</P>
<P>
   But down Allagash's single road, selectman Gardner _ a direct
descendant of the man who founded the town _ sees a community that
has been overtaken by history as woodsmen with chain saws and cable
skidders were gradually replaced by well-educated operators of
complex machinery. His own children never had any desire to work in
the woods, and neither does his grandson, and it has less to do
with Canadian competition than the desire to find an easier, more
stable living. For his part, Gardner sees Allagash's future in
tourism and retirement homes _ both businesses he has entered.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be three or four logging camps in the area with
100 men in each of them. Today, every one of those camps are being
replaced by machines,'' said Gardner. ``That's nobody's fault.
Times are changing. You have to change with the times.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say the people of Allagash may have to accept that
resource-dependent industries make and break small towns. John
Cashwell, president of the Seven Islands Land Company, which
manages 1 million acres of woods in northern Maine, said he made
that point to a group of legislators and labor officials who
visited the North Woods to discuss the logging issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``One night I asked everyone standing there, `Who works in the
town that he grew up in?' and not a one, including me, raised his
hand,'' said Cashwell. ``If it's a one-horse town, and the horses
leave, what are you going to do? This is a group of people who feel
they have a right to stay in their hometown, and that's all right.
But it's not everybody else's fault if things don't turn out the
way they wish.''
</P>
<P>
   Try telling that to Hafford, who built himself a log house that
he cannot afford to live in.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Calvin, recognized his son early as a woodsman _
``He was quite . . . an outdoor fella. Anything he tried, he could
do,'' he said _ and Hafford does not take kindly to the idea that
his special talent is obsolete. Asked how far he is willing to take
this battle, he mentioned the war memorial in front of what used to
be Allagash's school. He said: ``You know the scary thing about it,
is I'm not sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
