<HEADER>
A2693 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-GALILEO-2TAKES-BO     11-08 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GALILEO-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALILEO: AT THE OTHER END OF THE TELESCOPE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOUGLAS BAILEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   More than 350 years after his death, Galileo Galilei, the father
of modern science, is enjoying a renaissance of revisionism.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to an illegitimate daughter few people knew he had, a
diminutive woman writer from New York who finds extraordinary
stories in ordinary places, and a contemporary Pope with an unusual
interest in astronomy, the Italian astronomer is being
rediscovered. The high-school headlines that Galileo was the
inventor of the telescope, an enemy of the church, and a possessed
heretic are being proved either wrong or richly more complex than
the popular myths that have endured.
</P>
<P>
   There's little doubt that Galileo's insistence that the Sun, not
the Earth, was at the center of our planetary system put him at
extreme odds with the Catholic Church and led to his being
condemned and placed under house arrest for the last years of his
life. But the picture emerging today is breathing new life into the
man, providing context and texture to the one-dimensional anecdote
that Galileo was a scientific crusader and enemy of Church. He was
partly that. But now, from across three centuries, he is speaking
to us about our 20th century battles over science vs. religion and
creationism vs. evolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``To him there was one truth. Half of it was in the Bible, and
the rest was for us to discover,'' says Dava Sobel, author of the
just-released ``Galileo's Daughter,'' a portrait of the scientist
through the surviving letters of a daughter historians had all but
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   Sobel, a former New York Times science writer, was drawn to
Galileo while researching her first book, ``Longitude,'' about an
obscure but historically significant 18th-century quest to solve
oceanic navigation problems. That book has become a surprise
international best-seller.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ripping story
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What she found stunned her. Stumbling across a letter from
Galileo's daughter, one of three children the scientist had with a
mistress, Sobel immediately sensed there was ``a ripping story''
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea Galileo had a daughter,'' she said during a
recent interview at the Hayden Planetarium in Boston. ``And then to
find that she was a nun...I was overtaken by the thought of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sobel embarked on a year-long task of personally translating the
124 surviving letters that his daughter, who was baptized Virginia
but took the name Maria Celeste in honor of her father's interests,
penned in Italian between 1623 and 1633. The last was sent just
four months before her death in a convent where she spent most of
her life.
</P>
<P>
   A master storyteller, Sobel humanizes Galileo in ways no
scholarly treatise can. Presenting a vivid picture of 17th-century
Italy roiling from the bubonic plague and the 30 Years' War, Sobel
shows us a scientist keen on discovery and broadening his knowledge
of the heavens, but at the same time a man tending his garden,
enjoying his wine, and buying gifts for his beloved daughter, to
whom he would send his shirts for mending or to have the collars
bleached.
</P>
<P>
   ``He loved life,'' she says. ``And he was a character. A great
writer, philosopher and father, along with being a great scientist.
I never intended the book to speak about the current issues (of
creationism and evolution), but I think it does. The fact that
Galileo, in the middle of this great time, laid the foundation of
all modern science from his perspective as a devout Catholic is
fascinating to me. He didn't have to reject his religion to do what
he did. He becomes so much more complex and interesting when seen
in this entirety.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Galileo's motives
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most compelling fact that surfaces is that Galileo
forged a strong, meaningful relationship with the Church and that
he pressed his heliocentric theories not to destroy the Catholic
teachings, but to protect them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He essentially said `Look, someone's going to come along
someday with a more powerful telescope than mine and prove it to
you,'' says Sobel. ``He didn't want his Church to look foolish.''
</P>
<P>
   In his second heresy trial, which ultimately led to his
condemnation, Galileo accurately predicted what lay in store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take note, theologians,'' Galileo reportedly told his
inquisitors, ``that in your desire to make matters of faith out of
propositions relating to the fixity of sun and earth you run the
risk of eventually having to condemn as heretics those who would
declare the earth to stand still and the sun to change position _
eventually, I say, at such a time as it might be physically or
logically proved that the earth moves and the sun stands still.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Church's seeming immovable position that the Earth
was the center of all things, the revistation of the episode by
Sobel and others is actually elevating the Catholic Church's image,
dispelling the myth that it was entirely closed-minded about
science and astronomy. Galileo was in fact widely revered and
well-liked inside the church, and his notions were tolerated, even
encouraged, to a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of his books had to be approved by the church
censors,'' Sobel notes. ``Even `Dialogues,' the one for which he
was ultimately condemned, had been okayed.''
</P>
<P>
   Another book published last month, ``The Sun in the Church,'' by
science historian John L. Heilbron, confirms that the Church in
Galileo's day zealously studied astronomy, mostly to get an
accurate fix on Easter Sunday, and adapted many of its cathedrals,
including the Vatican's, into solar observatories.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Crossing the line
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So why was Galileo condemned? The idea that the sun was the
center of the universe wasn't his alone, having first been
theorized years earlier by Copernicus. It's even likely that
astronomers within the Catholic church correctly calculated the
earth's position among the planets. But an edict against teaching
such a revolutionary notion prevented discourse of the subject
beyond hypothesis.
</P>
<P>
   That was the line Galileo crossed. He not only taught it, he
wrote about it in Italian, instead of Latin, the traditional
language of scholars, so that his Copernican notions would spread
among the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Worse still, from the Church's perspective, the great astronomer
took it upon himself to interpret the scriptures, something only
theologians could do.
</P>
<P>
   In Galileo's mind, as depicted by Sobel and buttressed by Maria
Celeste's letters _ his missives to her do not survive _ there was
no conflict or contradiction between articles of faith and articles
of science. Both come from God's hand. Galileo wrote in a
compelling, yet ultimately damaging, letter to the Grand Duchess
Christina of Lorraine in December of 1613:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1354EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 13:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2694 &Cx1f; kan-z
r e BC-ART-HOVING-KANSAS-KAN     11-08 1774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-HOVING-KANSAS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-HEAD OF N.Y.'S METROPOLITAN MUSEUM DEMYSTIFIES ART 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALICE THORSON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now here's a fact about the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art in
Kansas City, Mo., that many avid museumgoers may not know: Esteemed
curator Laurence Sickman, who died in 1988, purchased much of the
museum's famed Oriental collection with cigarettes _ 8-cent PX
cigarettes, as a matter of fact, which were the unofficial currency
in postwar Japan.
</P>
<P>
   So notes Thomas Hoving, former director of New York's
Metropolitan Museum of Art, in his new book, Art for Dummies, a
recent addition to the ``For Dummies'' series of reference books
put out by IDG Books Worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other volumes in the series, including Horses for
Dummies Antiques for Dummies and Opera for Dummies, Hoving's book
takes a breezy Cliff's Notes approach to his topic in an attempt to
render an intimidating wealth of information comprehensible to a
novice.
</P>
<P>
   Within an airy 382 pages, he covers the whole of art history,
from prehistoric times to the present. There are chapters on how to
collect, the greatest works of Western civilization, the 10 most
interesting artists of the past and the 10 most interesting artists
of the present.
</P>
<P>
   The list of the 10 most interesting artists of the past, which
encompasses Goya, Leonardo, Rembrandt, Michelangelo and Picasso,
contains no surprises. The list of the 10 most interesting artists
of the present, which includes Andrew Wyeth, Wayne Thiebaud and
Dale Chihuly, is surprising for its conservatism and lack of
imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The back of the book offers an insider's guide to the world's
top museums and their masterworks, which is where Hoving discloses
how Sickman went about amassing the Nelson's Oriental collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me,'' Hoving said during a stop at The Kansas City
Star. ``It was (at) one of these museum directors' meetings where
all you did was drink constantly. He said, `I gotta tell you how to
really collect.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He was in the occupation army, and he had a deal with Kansas
City because he was going to come back to be the head curator or
run it or whatever, and he got these 8 cent PX cigs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American government scrip that MacArthur turned out was
virtually worthless. There was no yen, and they used cigarettes as
the currency in Japan in '45, '6, '7.
</P>
<P>
   `You didn't smoke them,' he said. `Oh, God, no; this was money.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He knew that these people had plundered the Chinese for their
great paintings, and he didn't have any feeling about taking it
away from them, and they wanted to eat. Most of those scrolls come
from that.''
</P>
<P>
   Art insiders and experts will enjoy Art for Dummies for the same
reason they devoured Making the Mummies Dance, Hoving's tell-all
1993 chronicle of his 10 years at the Met. Facts, not to mention
opinions, are entertaining, served up on the platter of Hoving's
irreverent and irrepressible personality.
</P>
<P>
   Hoving the debunker has been known to make his professional
colleagues squirm, but his frankness in Art for Dummies creates a
bridge of trust with the general reader.
</P>
<P>
   His insistence, for instance, on the book's very first page that
the art world is not as snobby as people think is more believable
for his admission that museums still have a long way to go in
communicating with the public.
</P>
<P>
   This is a favorite hobby horse of Hoving's, and one on which he
spoke with some heat during his interview at The Star.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every bloody museum in this country has in its charter, `For
the public education,' '' he said. ``And they've all failed.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoving lays much of the blame for the current controversy over
the Brooklyn Museum's ``Sensation'' exhibit of new British art
squarely on the shoulders of the museum. Contemporary art generally
is a stumbling block for museums, he said. ``They don't say what is
contemporary. They say, `This is art. Up yours.' ''
</P>
<P>
   And the man widely credited with the invention of the
blockbuster exhibition has no patience for what he labels
``mini-blockbusters,'' the trumped-up exhibits of obscure minor
masters beloved of scholarly curators.
</P>
<P>
   ``The catalog is a curatorial ego trip. You can't read it, and
it's too heavy; it's too expensive,'' Hoving said. But he also
objects to the strategy of inundating people with the familiar as a
way to engage them with art.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't do it by every ... minute another impressionist
show. Please. It's a nice movement, but it's a second-rate movement
in the history of art. We can't have that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoving, however, can be disingenuous about the business of
ratings.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he wrote the lead essay in the catalog for a huge
traveling retrospective of American illustrator Norman Rockwell,
now in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   When pressed, Hoving said his interest in Rockwell follows the
postmodernist approach to images as ``cultural texts,'' which can
be analyzed to yield interesting information about the society in
which they were made. It is a trend that has encompassed
exhibitions of all manner of low- and second-rate art forms.
</P>
<P>
   However, the difference between ``sociologically interesting''
and ``aesthetically significant'' goes unexplored in Hoving's essay
on Rockwell, leaving the dummies he is so concerned to educate
about connoisseurship free to believe that Rockwell is to be
received in the same manner as Rembrandt.
</P>
<P>
   Advice and anecdotes
</P>
<P>
   Following on the heels of his 1997 coffee-table-sized tome,
Greatest Works of Art of Western Civilization, Art for Dummies
represents the latest installment in Hoving's ongoing crusade to
get others to share his passion.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first questions he addresses in Art for Dummies is
``what a fine work of art should do for your soul.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer: ``It sets your blood racing. It changes your life
for the better every time you look at it.''
</P>
<P>
   His definition of the object of his affection is equally
straightforward: ``Art is when anyone in the world takes any sort
of material and fashions a deliberate statement with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoving devotes the first three chapters of Art for Dummies to
appreciating art. He includes the predictable advice of ``looking,
looking and more looking'' as the best way to train the eye, as
well as some less common tips.
</P>
<P>
   In the section headed ``How to Visit a Museum the Way the Pros
Do,'' he recommends visiting the museum shop first. Whatever the
country, museum shops always carry postcard reproductions of their
best works. With these as a guide, one can efficiently set out to
visit the highlights, and even in a country where one doesn't speak
the language, flash a postcard at a guard to receive directions.
</P>
<P>
   What keeps this book lively are the periodic insertions of tips,
cautions, explanations of art lingo and anecdotes. Like rest stops
along the highway of art history, they are identified by little
graphic icons _ a bull's-eye with an arrow for a tip, a bearded
figure with glasses wearing a beret for an anecdote.
</P>
<P>
   Among the latter, the item headed ``It Pays to Go With a Famous
Person _ the Likes of Jackie Onassis'' is one of the best,
recounting Hoving's burrowings through the bowels of the Hermitage
with Onassis and ``Soviet cultural nabobs'' in search of the winter
sledding cape of Princess Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   The cape was wanted for a Russian costume show at the Met, but
the Soviets, fearing that it would engender memories of Lenin's
massacre of the czar and his family, said it had vanished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jackie turned on the right pout,'' Hoving writes. As a result,
not only the cape but the princess' sled were found and lent to the
costume show.
</P>
<P>
   A chapter on the Renaissance includes a blurb about the cleaning
of the Sistine, in which Hoving participated by cleaning a
1-foot-square area. The experience convinced him that the cleaning
was not destructive to the ceiling, as some critics had argued.
</P>
<P>
   Old art for upper-middle-class dummies
</P>
<P>
   Art for Dummies was six months in the writing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started in January, and I had to be finished by June 30,''
Hoving said. ``Then I had to get rid of the Ph.D. language, the
professional jargon, the shorthand, the easy professional stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many generalist museum directors, Hoving is most
comfortable with masterworks. He admits that the book's sole nine
pages devoted to contemporary art are skimpy, in part because
contemporary art is not his area of expertise.
</P>
<P>
   Despite enthusiastic passages devoted to British painter Jenny
Saville, whose fleshy nudes are featured in the Brooklyn Museum's
``Sensation'' exhibit, and Gary Simmons, praised by Hoving as ``the
most powerful social commentator in art of his generation,'' this
book would be more appropriately titled Old Art for
Upper-Middle-Class Dummies.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there is an assumption that the reader has a good bit
of money, in the chapters geared to collecting and in offhanded
suggestions of what to do ``should you find yourself in Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoving himself characterizes his intended audience as ``people
who bypassed art when they went to school and learned engineering,
computer science etc.; people who have museum experience but are
still a little frightened and don't want to ask the wrong question.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them ask every wrong question, right away,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hoving is at his entertaining and informative best when it comes
to discussing specific artworks and his own experiences of them.
(When he travels, he carries with him a couple of tiny monotypes of
clouds by a New York artist named Wendy Mark, which he props up in
his motel room much as other people might set out family
photographs.)
</P>
<P>
   Hoving's chapters on collecting, on the other hand, with their
references to purchasing masterworks and the problem of fakes,
don't ring true. It is hard to imagine someone with the budget and
interest to pursue Old Master artworks taking their advice from a
beginner's manual like Art for Dummies.
</P>
<P>
   Hoving's advice to ``collect living artists'' seems
better-suited to his target audience. But in typical Hoving style,
he prefaces his list of ``living artists who are in the prime'' _
Wyeth, Rauschenberg, Frankenthaler and others _ with a smart-alecky
little dig at museum culture:
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you should buy one of them now,'' he writes, ``so your
grandchildren can dangle their wills before the covetous eyes of
the biggest museums in the land, and be wined and dined for the
rest of their lives at the homes of wealthy museum trustees.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly he's having fun in Art for Dummies, and it's Hoving's
shtick that makes it fun for the reader, too.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
