<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2696 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-SCI-GALILEO-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     11-08 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-GALILEO-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... of 1613.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``I do not think it necessary to believe that the same God who
gave us our senses, our speech, our intellect, would have put aside
the use of these, to teach us instead such things as with their
help we could find out for ourselves, particularly in the case of
these sciences of which there is not the smallest mention in the
Scriptures; and, above all, in astronomy, of which so little notice
is taken that the names of none of the planets are mentioned.
Surely if the intention of the sacred scribes had been to teach the
people astronomy, they would not have passed over the subject so
completely.''
</P>
<P>
   To some, Galileo's letter, which was widely copied and
distributed throughout the world, caused a rethinking of the
relationship between science and religion. But to many others,
particularly a number of ambitious firebrand priests and Jesuits,
Galileo's logic was criminal. It resulted in his first trial for
heresy and forever branded him a controversial figure.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of his trials, his constant battles with various
infirmities, and efforts to complete his books, Maria Celeste
becomes a constant source of moral and emotional support. Galileo
describes her as ``a woman of exquisite mind, singular goodness,
and tenderly attached to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rarely conveying bitterness about her own exile to the convent
in which she was placed at age 12 after being deemed unmarriagable
because of her illegitimacy, Galileo's daughter brightens the
astronomer's life with loving correspondence, bracketed with tales
of the difficulties of her monastic existence and even humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``She appears to be quite a different nun than others in the
convent and she seems to know that,'' Sobel says.
</P>
<P>
   In one letter, she asks her father to visit in order to repair a
clock that he has fixed several times but that continues to break
down, telling Galileo that ``these nuns won't let me live'' if it
is not repaired.
</P>
<P>
   ``She seems to set herself apart from the other nuns in several
of the letters,'' Sobel says.
</P>
<P>
   Often apologetic for dashing off the letters in haste, Maria
Celeste takes turns as a typical child, buttering up her father
before asking for money:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   30 August 1631
</P>
<P>
   Most Beloved Lord Father
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the measure or indication of the love one bears another
person is the trust vested in the loved one, then you must never
doubt, Sire, that I love you with all my heart, as in truth I do;
since I draw such confidence and security from you that at times I
fear I exceed the bounds of modesty and filial devotion, and all
the more so as I know you to be beset by many worries and expenses.
Nevertheless the certainty I have, that you will minister ever so
much more willingly to my needs than to those of any other person,
even including your own, lets me dare to ask you if you would be so
kind as to relieve me of a worry that weighs heavily on my mind,
regarding a debt I owe of five scudi incurred during Suor
Arcangela's illness, as I was constrained during these four months
to spend with largesse, compared to the economy that befits the
poverty of our station: and now that I find myself desperate and
pressed to repay the loan, I come to the one I know is willing and
able to help me. And also I want a flask of your white wine to make
a strengthening tonic for Suor Arcangela, who I think will be
better served by her faith in this remedy than by the remedy
itself.
</P>
<P>
   I write with so little time that I cannot possibly say more,
except that I hope you enjoy these six almond pastries, and I send
you my love.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
From San Matteo, the 30th day of August 1631. &QL; 
Your most affectionate daughter, &QL; 
S. M. Celeste &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The letters are often heartbreaking,'' says Sobel. ``But they
amount to one of the greatest stories I've ever encountered.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Celeste died in the convent at age 33, probably from
dysentery, pulling Galileo into a tailspin of grief from which he
may have never fully recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel immense sadness and melancholy,'' he told a friend.
``Together with extreme inappetite; I am hateful to myself, and
continually hear my beloved daughter calling to me.''
</P>
<P>
   In failing health, nearly blind, unable to recieve visitors or
attend Mass, and with the spectre of heresy over him, Galileo lived
his last days struggling to complete two more scientific journals
on astronomic observations.
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, Pope John Paul II, said to be fascinated with astronomy
and Galileo in particular, decided to reopen the Galileo case and
called for a commission to investigate the episode that led to the
astronomer's trial and condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why is the current Pope so interested in Galileo?'' Sobel
says. ``I think it's because of this popular perception that we
ascribe to Galileo. So if we can show this isn't true, that it
wasn't a fight between the Church and Galileo's ideas, but between
the person of Galileo and the person of Pope Urban, and the
Jesuits, it does the Church a great deal of good.''
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, on the 350th anniversary of Galileo's death, the
Pope admitted the Church had erred and conceded the popular notions
of what happened at the time were inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Galileo case has been a sort of `myth,' in which the image
fabricated out of the events was quite far removed from reality,''
the Pope declared. ``In this perspective, the Galileo case was the
symbol of the Church's supposed rejection of scientific progress,
or of `dogmatic' obscurantism opposed to the free search for
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   There are indeed places where science and religion can
intersect, the Pope said, exactly as Galileo declared.
</P>
<P>
   ``The clarifications furnished by recent historical studies
enable us to state that this sad misunderstanding now belongs to
the past,'' the Pope concluded in a written statement. ``From the
Galileo affair we can learn a lesson which remains valid in
relation to similar situations which occur today and which may
occur in the future.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
