<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2703 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MICROSOFT-HOMETOWN-BO     11-08 1233
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-HOMETOWN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDMOND HIT WHERE IT HURTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   REDMOND, Wash. _ Tyler Oppenheim, a self-described computer whiz
at 16, has a theory about why the cineplex where he sells popcorn
was all but empty Friday night: Microsoft Corp. employees were too
stunned over the company being branded an evil empire to enjoy a
movie.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was packed for the early show, but then it just emptied
out,'' Oppenheim said. ``Three new movies were opening, but after
that it was dead.''
</P>
<P>
   By Saturday, Redmond had come roaring back to life. The Town
Center mall was crowded. A line snaked outside the movie theater.
Men and women competed on the Microsoft campus soccer field.
Traffic was stop-and-go as usual.
</P>
<P>
   But in a city with more than 17,000 Microsoft employees, where
everyone has a friend or relative working for the software giant,
an undercurrent of disbelief threatened to ruin the weekend. No one
could quite believe that a federal judge had declared Microsoft a
monopoly that used its power to reduce competition, sabotage
innovation, and harm consumers _ accusations that the people who
develop software, design graphics, and stand to become millionaires
at Microsoft called unfounded and unfair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came across looking like big ogres, but you work there
every day and you see it's not like that,'' said Fabio Yeon, a
24-year-old software developer who joined Microsoft three years
ago. ``We're not the big bully. We don't win because we're so big.
We win because of our product and what we deliver to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Employee after employee displayed similar loyalty to Microsoft's
desktop computer operating systems and its challenging work
environment, although most refused to be identified. The company
asked them not to speak to the news media in the wake of Friday's
devastating ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Even some of the competitors that have sprung up in Redmond,
just northeast of Seattle, said they were surprised, confused, and
dismayed by the scope of the judge's condemnation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't say Microsoft is the best _ it's definitely not the
best _ but it saw the need, made the right product available, and
people bought it,'' said John Coyle, a software development manager
at another firm. ``I just can't understand it. How can you fault
somebody for being better at marketing?''
</P>
<P>
   The 207-page ruling issued by US District Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson is not a final ruling but a declaration that he believes
the Justice Department's version of events. Attorney General Janet
Reno hailed the ruling as ``a great day for American consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the historic antitrust case is far from over. A
settlement could yet be reached, although Microsoft spokesman Jim
Cullinan said the company stands by the core defense. Either side
could appeal the final outcome.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, Microsoft chairman Bill Gates, who
``respectfully'' disagreed with the judge's decision, told
employees in a companywide e-mail that it's business as usual. The
average age of emplyees at Microsoft is 34.5.
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, `OK, don't worry, our legal team is handling this, go
back to what you do best. We don't believe this is a disruption to
our day-to-day operations or to what you do,' '' said Cullinan, who
lived out of a Washington, D.C., hotel during the trial, which
began in October 1998. ``We know if we don't keep working hard and
stay focused we may miss the paradigm shift in where this industry
is going next.''
</P>
<P>
   Those constant shifts _ a product is hot one minute, outdated
the next _ were frequently cited as evidence that no one can
monopolize the computer industry. Competition, Microsoft supporters
in Redmond said, comes from every corner. At Borders Books &AMP; Music,
a software engineer who is working on a top-secret new product for
Microsoft underscored that point by gesturing toward shelves of
computer books, many of them touting software offered by
competitors of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is tremendous competition out there, and we're losing on
a number of fronts,'' said the engineer, 25. ``I remember three
years ago we were losing the so-called browser battle. People take
it for granted today that we're number one, but an awful lot of
hard work went into making that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Jim Francis, 36, a former software developer whose stock
options enabled him to retire in March after eight years with
Microsoft: ``You have to go out of your way to make Microsoft into
a monopoly. You have to ignore everybody else. Obviously, this
judge doesn't feel obligated to give Microsoft a break on
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, few can believe Microsoft won't triumph, even if many
conceded that Microsoft bungled much of its presentation before the
court. They can't believe the company could ever be forced to break
up along the lines of AT&AMP;T or Standard Oil. Some are so confident
that they say they haven't even bothered to follow the case closely
_ a difficult indifference in a region where every twist has been
front-page news and thousands are counting on Microsoft stock for
their children's college tuition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people I work with are more interested in getting the job
done than in politics,'' said a graphic artist who has been
designing computer games for Microsoft for 10 months. ``It's all
geeks, and that's what we care about. I heard about (the decision)
in the hallway and most of us treated it with a certain amount of
scorn. No one's taking it too seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   That casualness, however, does not extend to elected officials.
From the governor on down, they have rushed to Microsoft's defense.
After all, they have come to rely on the taxes Microsoft pays as
much as local charities have come to rely on donations from Gates
and his employees.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Boeing Corp.'s longtime presence in greater Seattle,
many described Redmond as rural before Microsoft set up shop in
1975. Net revenues for the fiscal year ending June 1999 reached
almost $20 billion; net income exceeded $7.7 billion. Microsoft
will match up to $12,000 a year in employee gifts, whether in the
form of computer software or cash. This year's in-house fund drive
raised more than $17 million, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all, Microsoft is a good neighbor, although I don't
like what it's done to the local real estate market,'' said Redmond
native Shaun Whiteman, a Chrysler Corp. manager who's hoping his
Microsoft stock doesn't plummet.
</P>
<P>
   Added Andrew Bjorn, who lives on nearby Mercer Island and works
as a construction cost estimator: ``Microsoft is our economy. It's
our area. Lots of us work for Microsoft or know people who do. It's
only natural that we'd want it to go in there favor. No one would
be happy to see them hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they say that no one, not even the mighty Microsoft,
could dampen the competitiveness of the computer market. As Tim
Donovan, who works on Microft products at another software company,
put it, new technologies hit the market daily. But, he added, there
might be more if Microsoft was not so dominant. Then again, he only
moved to Redmond from Houston a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably shouldn't say this, but I take a little bit of
satisfaction in the decision,'' Donovan said. ``They're just so
huge. It's kind of like, `Ha. Just because you're that big you
can't rule the world.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
