<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 13:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2704 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRELAND-OATLEY-BOS &LR;      11-08 1187
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-OATLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICHAEL OATLEY: DISARMING THE CANDOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Calling Michael Oatley an IRA sympathizer is a bit of a
stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that's what British conservatives and unionists in Northern
Ireland have dubbed the former British secret agent for his
recommendation that a local government in Northern Ireland be
formed without the Irish Republican Army giving up its weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily Telegraph, the voice of British conservatism and the
most outspoken advocate of retaining the union between Britain and
Northern Ireland, went even further, suggesting that Oatley had
become a ``degenerate.''
</P>
<P>
   But Oatley's recommendation on how to end the impasse over
paramilitary weapons that has stalled the peace process in Northern
Ireland for the past year, and bedeviled it for several more,
cannot be dismissed lightly.
</P>
<P>
   His is an opinion widely but privately shared in government
offices in London, Dublin, and Washington. Unlike Oatley, however,
officials and diplomats from the British, Irish, and US governments
are wary of making such a blunt assessment, lest they be accused of
taking sides and appearing insensitive to unionist feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Oatley injected himself into the debate as George Mitchell, the
former US Senate majority leader, is scheduled to return to Belfast
this week for what will probably be his last push to fashion a
compromise to end the impasse. Mitchell is eager to get back to his
wife and young son and his Washington law practice. He has already
spent nine weeks, more than twice as long as initially envisioned,
trying to rescue the political settlement he brokered on Good
Friday 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Oatley, who served with MI6, the Secret Intelligence Service,
for 32 years and became its chief of counterterrorism in Europe,
had extensive clandestine dealings with the IRA leadership during
the 1970s. Some of the IRA leaders of that era, such as Gerry
Adams, the Sinn Fein president, and Martin McGuinness, Sinn Fein's
chief negotiator, are now the politicians who have tried to turn
the republican movement from one that uses violence to advance its
cause of a united Ireland to one that relies exclusively on
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Unionists have refused to form a local government with Sinn Fein
until the IRA disarms, saying that if the republican movement is
truly committed to democratic politics, then it cannot maintain a
private army. That refusal has stalled the peace process and
threatens to unravel it.
</P>
<P>
   Oatley says the republican movement's leadership is sincere
about wanting to commit itself exclusively to politics. And he says
the ``no guns, no government'' argument being put forward by
unionists, and buttressed in London by the opposition Conservative
Party, is shortsighted and counterproductive.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue, Oatley says, is not about guns but about the
willingness of the IRA to use them. Right now, he says, the
republican leadership has enough control over the IRA to keep the
guns away. But he suggests that if the impasse continues, and the
Good Friday Agreement is not implemented with the creation of a
power-sharing government in Northern Ireland, a majority in the IRA
will conclude that the peace process is a waste of time. The
implications are obvious.
</P>
<P>
   It is rare in Britain for former senior spies to publicly offer
their opinions on political issues, particularly one as sensitive
and as fluid as the current situation in Northern Ireland. But
Oatley is frustrated by what he sees as a misrepresentation of the
stalemate, and so took his message to those he thinks need to hear
it most.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Oatley wrote an opinion piece for the Sunday Times of
London. In it, he criticized the Times and the Telegraph, the
newspapers most vociferous in their support of unionists and their
condemnation of republicans, saying the right-wing press had
presented a false picture to the British public.
</P>
<P>
   ``Decommissioning is projected as the central issue in the peace
process. It is not,'' said Oatley. ``The question is not whether an
organization has, or can, obtain weapons. It is whether it will
choose violent or political action.''
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives, Oatley said, ``are determined to portray the
deadlock on decommissioning as proof that Sinn Fein is cynically
insincere about its level of commitment to political action.''
Oatley calls this ``the picador approach to introducing a terrorist
organization to the attractions of the political arena.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If sufficient barbs are thrust into its flanks, the animal
will eventually, with reluctance, charge,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Oatley says that is what happened in 1996, when the IRA
concluded that the British government led by John Major was toying
with it by first saying Sinn Fein could take part in negotiations
if the IRA called a cease-fire, then adding the precondition of the
IRA disarming. The IRA broke its cease-fire, exploding a huge bomb
in London's Docklands section.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the politicians who say they don't trust the republicans,
Oatley has had extensive personal contacts with the IRA. Peter
Taylor, author of ``Behind the Mask: The IRA and Sinn Fein,''
describes Oatley as the most important British secret agent to have
worked in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Oatley helped arrange the short-lived 1975 IRA cease-fire. He
also helped resolve the 1980 IRA hunger strikes, the precursor to
the 1981 hunger strikes in which 10 republican prisoners died
seeking political status and violence increased dramatically as a
result.
</P>
<P>
   Before he retired in 1991, Oatley met secretly with McGuinness,
the former IRA chief of staff. Oatley's report on that meeting was
the first indication that the British government took seriously the
republican movement's intention to replace its ``armed struggle''
with a political one.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to pursue a political path, Oatley said, ``was
taken with trepidation by intelligent, ideologically committed
individuals who had spent their adult lives in pursuit of what they
regarded as a just war.''
</P>
<P>
   Oatley also shared the assessment of British military commanders
that the IRA could be contained but not militarily defeated. But he
said the IRA and its leadership also concluded that the British
government would not capitulate, leaving both sides to find a
negotiated settlement.
</P>
<P>
   Oatley considered it his duty as a British secret agent to
understand the mindset of those his agency targeted. But his
attempts to humanize the thought process of republicans has been
greeted with derision by British conservatives. The Telegraph was
moved to print an editorial, declaring that Oatley had gone soft.
</P>
<P>
   Oatley insists his solution is not based on partisan politics
but on experience in the real world. He says his job as a secret
agent required him to understand the motivation of his targets, and
to report on them objectively.
</P>
<P>
   He says he has done just that. Some don't buy his argument.
Others simply don't want to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Kevin Cullen is the chief of the Globe's European bureau, based in
London.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
