<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2707 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w BC-CANDIDATES-GRADES-BOS     11-08 1347
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANDIDATES-GRADES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKING THE PRESIDENTIAL GRADE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The buzz is that George W. Bush isn't the sharpest
knife in the drawer. That his grades at Yale were mediocre. That he
can't pass a pop quiz naming the leaders of Chechnya, India,
Pakistan, and Taiwan. That he doesn't know Slovenia from Slovakia,
and that he can't tell a Greek from a ``Grecian.''
</P>
<P>
   The grades are great grist for the late-night comics. And the
quiz indicated that Bush may be vulnerable in a foreign-policy
debate. But opponents who try to exploit the issue of braininess
should beware: Americans like their presidents smart, but not so
intellectual that they can't reach down from their ivory tower.
</P>
<P>
   On that score, this political season offers them quite a choice:
Democrats Al Gore and Bill Bradley come off as a studious, cerebral
pair, the dutiful students who retain to this day a passion for
policy detail.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, across the political campus are Bush and John McCain,
the two leading Republicans, who admit that in college they often
walked right by the library to find the best fraternity party or
touch football game, or girls who wanted to have fun.
</P>
<P>
   So what will it be, America? A wonk or a gentleman's C?
</P>
<P>
   That has been a complex question for voters through the years,
and with reason: There is no clear correlation, in presidential
politics as in corporate life, between good study habits and
leadership success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overachievers don't do very well in the White House,'' said
Dean Keith Simonton, a psychology professor at the University of
California at Davis who wrote a book about the formation of
presidential prowess. ``Remember how annoying Jimmy Carter was,
always preaching and acting smarter than everybody else?''
</P>
<P>
   This year's crop of presidential postulants seems to remember.
Some of them, in fact, seem to be appealing directly to an
anti-intellectual strain that political scientists have long
identified in the American electorate. McCain frequently jokes
about his fifth-from-the-bottom finish at the US Naval Academy.
</P>
<P>
   Even Gore, in going back to his roots, some days seems to act
more like a Tennessee hayseed than a Harvard man. And Bradley says
his pro basketball career was more life-shaping than was the
Princeton pedigree.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Bush, who certainly ranks in the Ivy League elite,
with his degrees from Yale and the Harvard Business School, but who
also has asserted that he was put off at both places by
``intellectual arrogance.'' At Yale, Bush passed every subject, but
he has made no secret of the fact that he frequently put football,
baseball, and his fraternity ahead of academics.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the New Yorker magazine published what it said was
Bush's Yale transcript. He had highs of ``88'' in philosophy and
anthropology, a low of ``69'' in astronomy, and many mid-70s scores
in between.
</P>
<P>
   A Bush campaign spokesman, Scott McClellan, said that the New
Yorker ``stole'' the report, but then discounted it as
``irrelevant'' to the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an unimpressive academic record,'' said Alan Lichtman, a
presidential historian at American University. ``If it shows that
Bush is intellectually incapable of doing any better, then I'm not
sure he is the kind of person I want in the Oval Office. If it
indicates he was simply interested in other things at college, then
the grades really don't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren Bennis, a business professor at the University of
Southern California, has spent 20 years studying what makes top
corporate leaders tick, and he is sure it is not their grade-point
average. ``Unless you are a moron, there is zero correlation
between grades or IQ and success in life,'' Bennis said.
</P>
<P>
   Ditto on SAT scores. Bush's, according to the New Yorker, were
in a respectable but not spectacular range: 566 on the verbal
score, and 640 for math, out of a possible 800 in each.
</P>
<P>
   ``The SAT is a remarkable judge of how well a student will
perform in college, but nothing beyond that,'' said Gaston
Caperton, the president of the College Board, which conducts the
SATs. Caperton, a former two-term governor of West Virginia, says
he is a good example of how grades don't make the man. He became a
successful politician despite his dyslexia, a reading disability.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skills that really help you in politics are having a huge
amount of energy and knowing how to get along with people,''
Caperton said.
</P>
<P>
   Academic achievement is not totally irrelevant, since it can be
a measure of focus, ambition, and discipline. But taking Bradley as
an example, Bennis said his success as a politician may have more
to do with the qualities that made him a great basketball star _
his timing, his intensity, his drive _ than with his Rhodes Scholar
intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who graduated with honors from Harvard, may not derive
great political benefit from what voters perceive as his superior
intellect. In a recent debate, Gore said his biggest mistake was
saying he invented the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidates who come off as some awe-inspiring Einstein will be
at a disadvantage if voters think they are too brilliant to work
with the masses,'' Simonton said. Gore may alienate people by
seeming so smart on issues like technology and science that
confound average Americans, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Academic achievement has not necessarily resulted in popular
presidencies _ Carter's (Naval Academy) and Woodrow Wilson's
(Princeton, Johns Hopkins) spring to mind. Some of the nation's
favorite presidents, including Franklin Delano Roosevelt despite
his degrees from Harvard and Columbia, Ronald Reagan , and Harry S.
Truman, seemed to show that scholarship isn't required for
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton was a Rhodes Scholar, yet he played up his
good-old-boy background in Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   President Dwight D. Eisenhower, who commanded the Allied
invasion of Europe in World War II, was no dummy, but his stump
rhetoric was deliberately homespun. He sometimes spoke in a
deliberately inarticulate way to confuse critics and make himself a
more appealing candidate. And for all his intellectual modesty,
Eisenhower certainly had no difficulty in twice trouncing Adlai
Stevenson, the self-consciously cerebral Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   Once, while campaigning, Stevenson was flattered by a woman who
had told him he would get the vote of every thinking person. ``But
madam,'' Stevenson replied, ``I need a majority to win.''
</P>
<P>
   History also shows that presidents can get into big trouble when
they surround themselves with really smart people _ the ``best and
the brightest'' are sometimes blinded by their own intellectual
firepower.
</P>
<P>
   President Lyndon B. Johnson, who seemed to have an intellectual
inferiority complex, leaned on the corps of advisers he had
inherited from the Kennedy administration _ men like Defense
Secretary Robert McNamara _ with disastrous results. Reagan put his
national security adviser, John Poindexter, first in his class at
the Naval Academy, in charge of the Iran-Contra arms sale episode.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was in the same Annapolis class, but at the bottom. He
writes in his memoir, ``Faith of My Fathers,'' that two things
brought his class rank down: terrible grades in math and science,
and very bad behavior. ``John wasn't intellectually sloppy,'' said
Frank Gamboa, who roomed with him at the academy, ``but he
deliberately did not try to excel.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's story, however, did not end at Annapolis, but continued
to Vietnam and into a Hanoi prisoner of war camp. He came back as a
hero, proving himself and rising above his undistinguished academic
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters are looking, above all, at authenticity because they
are fed up with handlers, pollsters, focus groups, and politics as
performance art,'' said Richard Norton Smith, director of the
Gerald R. Ford Library in Ann Arbor, Mich. ``There is something
refreshing about candidates who seem real, don't make exaggerated
claims, and seem perfectly comfortable in their own skin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1401EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 14:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2710 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-LATIN-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     11-08 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LATIN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... PR people.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Child, a veteran of both the LA and New York music scenes, is
cautiously optimistic. ``Miami's sort of like the Wild West right
now. People are showing up thinking something's going to happen,
and maybe it will. It took a long time to build Music Row in
Nashville. There's a showcase every night there, people auditioning
for labels, and everybody comes out. In order for that to happen
here it has to be more like a village, not just kingdoms and
serfdoms.'' To that end, Child has started Songwriters in the
Round, a monthly gathering of local talent dedicated to fostering a
sense of community among Miami's musicians. Without that sort of
interaction, Child says, ``ideas will become stale, and you'll get
the same old sound.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a cautionary message that the industry at large should
heed. If record-label honchos with dollar signs dancing in their
eyes decide to exploit the moment to roll out copies of Ricky
Martin, a great opportunity will be lost. ``This is our chance,''
says Mauricio Abaroa, president of the Latin Academy of Recording
Arts and Sciences. Abaroa came to Miami from Mexico City in 1996;
lately he's spent little time in LARAS's two-year-old Miami Beach
office between to trips to LA for screening-committee meetings and
trips to the 15 Latin American countries that are represented by
LARAS. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Carpeting the industry &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried that the industry leaders may not try to
understand our music, and they're an essential part of making this
happen,'' says Abaroa. ``Someone needs to let them know that they
have a big responsibility to find substantial talent. Jennifer and
Ricky and Marc and Enrique _ they are the best ambassadors. Now we
need to come in with all our roots, and all the power of our music,
and carpet the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Kike Santander, who's been Emilio Estefan's right-hand man since
1994, would like to lead the charge. A towering, 39-year-old former
doctor, Santander proudly shows off the just-finished recording
studio at his waterfront home, where he's currently producing four
new acts that he hopes will keep Latin music in the US mainstream.
``If you try to be somebody else, you are lost. I want to try to
create my own sound,'' Santander says, ``just as Emilio created his
own.'' Santander is so excited about one of his projects _ a cumbia
hip-hop band from Los Angeles _ he declines even to name it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a delicate balance, though, between promoting high-quality
art and feeding a profit-hungry commercial venture. While the
onslaught of Latin crossover artists may seem sudden, the process
has been ongoing, and executed with more forethought than one might
imagine, for years. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there have been plenty of crossover pockets that
were accidental things,'' says Jose Behar, president and CEO of EMI
Latin. Behar was born in Cuba and raised in Miami; in 1989, he made
crossover history by signing the late Tejano singer Selena to his
label. Her 1995 English-language album, ``Dreaming of You,'' became
the first album by a Latin artist ever to enter the Billboard
charts at No. 1. ``Santana's `Evil Ways,' or `La Bamba,' musical
events dating all the way back to Xavier Cugat, none of those,''
Behar points out,``were planned out.'' (Carlos Santana, by the way,
is enjoying the biggest hit of his 30-year career right now;
``Supernatural'' has been at No. 1 for three weeks.)
</P>
<P>
   Then in the late '80s, Gloria Estefan and the Miami Sound
Machine introduced Cuban rhythms to the US mainstream with a string
of Latin-flavored pop singles. That, Behar says, was a critical
turning point. ``When Gloria crossed over, it was Emilio's vision.
He planned it and made it happen. And then of course we were
looking for another Gloria, to sell to this new bicultural
consumer. When Selena crossed over, it sent a red alert through the
system: There's a business here. Around the same time Jon Secada
happened, and it was written in stone. Gloria, Selena, Jon . . .
the time gaps became compressed. It established the fact that the
market was there if you delivered the right product. Now you see
the phenomenon of Ricky and Jennifer and Marc Anthony, and I must
give credit to my competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Tommy Mottola, president of Sony, who threw the
full force of his label's resources behind the careers of Martin,
Lopez, and Anthony. Many feel that it was Mottola who really had
his finger on the pulse, who recognized the massive consumer
potential of the burgeoning US Latino population. ``That was
brilliantly, brilliantly planned,'' says Behar. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Opposed to the hype &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That's precisely the perspective that makes Marc Anthony
bristle. The 30-year-old salsa singer recently released his debut
English-language album, which is No. 13 on the Billboard album
charts this week. ``I Need to Know,'' a twitchy, salsa-flavored pop
track, is a huge hit, holding steady at No. 6 after nine weeks on
the Hot 100 singles charts. ``I feel so caught in the hype. It
disturbs me to even think about, that I might have been accepted
because I'm Latin and not by the merit of my music,'' says Anthony,
who became widely known several years ago when he starred in the
ill-fated Broadway production of Paul Simon's ``The Capeman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very weird moment. So many people are getting it so
wrong. It's pop music! I grew up listening to Gloria Gaynor and Air
Supply. If I had more African influences I'm sure it would have
shown up. But I'm from New York. I'm Puerto Rican. I'm both,''
declares Anthony, who recently began work on his next salsa album.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he concedes that there's a silver lining to all the hype.
``I'm glad that Latinos in general feel like this might be their
chance to express themselves. I just beg them not to do it because
it's the chic thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever their motivations, there's no shortage of Latino
musicians from every region, and every genre, lining up to explore
the possibilities. EMI Latin has 12 new artists _ Tropical, Rock,
Latin Rap, and Mexican rock _ slated for release in the next
quarter. Universal Music has seven Latin artists releasing albums
in the next four months. Welterweight boxer Oscar De La Hoya begins
sessions at Rudy Perez's house later this month for his debut
album, a bolero-pop collection due out next spring. Colombian star
Shakira is poised to make a huge crossover splash. And that's just
the tip of the iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   While there's no denying the impact of the rapidly growing
Latino youth population, the Anglo audience is buying Latin music,
too _ and not just Ricky Martin records. ``The perception a few
years ago for Anglos was that Latin music was mariachi. Restaurant
music. Great for a party,'' says Jose Behar. ``What's happened now
is it's been hipified. It's hip to like Latin music.'' Desmond
Child concurs: ``Ricky showed everyone how fun and cool and sexy it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Anglos are opening their ears to Latin music beyond
radio-ready pop. ``When I speak to an American and ask him to
describe Latin music, the first word out of his mouth is `passion,'
'' says Mauricio Abaroa _ a feature of Anglo pop and rock that's
admittedly grown dimmer and dimmer. ``That's what the crossover
phenomenon has done: It's enabled the Latin music world to expose
itself, its many flavors, and create the awareness it has long
deserved,'' says Behar.
</P>
<P>
   Still, says Abaroa, ``we are at the crossroads. The mainstream
American market is turning to us and saying, `What is this?' Now it
must be good talent. Fresh talent. I hope they don't churn out 10
more Rickys and 10 more Jennifers.'' And if they do? ``Both ways
will climb, of course. But one will only have results for five or
six years. The other,'' says Abaroa with great hope, and not a
little determination, ``will last a long, long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1402EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
