<HEADLINE>
US RISKS LOSS OF INFLUENCE IN UNITED NATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Even if Washington coughs up its back dues to the
United Nations, the United States has seen a precipitous loss of
influence in the institution it created from the ashes of World War
II, according to the UN leadership and ambassadors from around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   The senior UN officials predicted that the new US ambassador,
Richard Holbrooke, would face renewed hostility, no matter what the
outcome in Congress on UN arrears, over a US demand that it pay a
smaller share of UN costs.
</P>
<P>
   And, unless the back pay issue is resolved within seven weeks,
the costs kick in quickly under UN bylaws. For example, American
companies may be barred from bidding on millions of dollars in UN
contracts. US vendors now take home 47 percent of UN purchases. The
United States also would lose its vote in the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, the UN leaders said, the United States, which
even named this institution, risks its ability here to sway other
nations to its point of view. The world body has long been a pillar
of US foreign policy, helping the United States, for instance, to
build a worldwide coalition against Iraq's Saddam Hussein after his
troops invaded Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Deep damage has already been done. ``Member states are in a
quandary because there is no leader here now,'' said Joseph E.
Connor, undersecretary general for management and an US citizen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leader,'' Connor said, referring to the United States,
``is on the sidelines. . . . I wonder sometimes if the Iraq war
effort, which was handled so well by Tom Pickering, could be done
today.'' Pickering, the former ambassador to Russia, is a longtime
State Department official.
</P>
<P>
   The anxiety and anger toward the US Congress for holding up
nearly $1.7 billion in arrears, according to UN calculations,
became clear during meetings with UN Secretary General Kofi Annan
and 14 of his top deputies over two days last week. But it is also
apparent from conversations with ambassadors and from UN committee
meetings, including one Oct. 5 on back payments that turned into a
slam session against the United States.
</P>
<P>
   At that budget committee meeting, the British ambassador, Jeremy
Greenstock, said the United States had ``muffled its voice and
stained its reputation,'' according to UN minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Annan told a group of US journalists last week that ``the
organization needs the United States, and the United States needs
the organization.'' America, he said, ``has a natural leadership
position, which in some ways it has forfeited.''
</P>
<P>
   The secretary general, who assumed his office largely because of
a strong US push for UN reforms, said he doubts Congress would
appropriate $926 million toward the debt. ``We will believe it when
we see the check,'' Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   Reform efforts, which have cut more than 1,200 jobs in the UN
secretariat to about 8,800 positions, have been paralyzed because
of the US debt, said John G. Ruggie, assistant secretary general
and a US citizen. ``You can't talk about reform in this place
today'' because of anger toward the United States, Ruggie said.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Miyet, undersecretary general for peacekeeping
operations, said he believed it was in the national security
interests of the United States to pay for UN operations that defuse
crises without involving American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best reason for the Americans to pay their dues,''
Miyet said. ``You mobilize other countries to do the job in
difficult situations.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, only 36 of the more than 14,000 UN peacekeepers are US
soldiers, according to US officials. That number, while pleasing to
some members of Congress, has angered several ambassadors here who
see it as another example of the United States not doing its part
of bringing stability to areas of conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Another UN source, an American speaking on the condition of
anonymity, said it was ``painful to be an American at the UN these
days. We are losing our moral authority. . . . The UN is not a
lapdog to be summoned upon convenience. If we do not lead, others
will fill that vacuum. When Congress attacks the UN, it weakens the
institution and it weakens ourselves, too.''
</P>
<P>
   In Congress, the issue is now at a crossroads, its future likely
to be determined in the next 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   In June, the Senate passed legislation sponsored by the chairman
of the Foreign Relations Committee, Jesse Helms, a North Carolina
Republican, that would pay some of the arrears in exchange for a
stringent reform program and a reduction in US payments to 25
percent of UN peacekeeping operations from 31 percent, and to 20
percent of overall UN operations from 25 percent. That bill passed
97-2.
</P>
<P>
   But attached to House legislation is an unrelated amendment from
Representative Christopher Smith, a New Jersey Republican, that
would forbid abortion-rights groups from lobbying foreign
governments. Smith, under pressure to compromise by a Republican
leadership concerned about being branded isolationist, doesn't seem
in a mood to back down. `It's time for accommodation'' from the
White House, he told reporters Friday. President Clinton has vowed
to veto any bill that contains the amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Smith argues, accurately, that the United States remains the
United Nation's largest benefactor. He says that the body should
write off much of the amount due _ the bulk of it for peacekeeping
_ because the Pentagon has contributed billions of dollars in
voluntary contributions for such operations in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Other lawmakers believe that the United States pays far too much
toward foreign operations, including UN dues. Representative Sonny
Callahan, an Alabama Republican and chairman of the House
Appropriations subcommittee on foreign operations, complained last
month that ``every time somebody walks in the White House with a
turban on his head,'' the president offers them money.
</P>
<P>
   Callahan said he was going to ``buy me one of those turbans''
and seek money for senior citizens.
</P>
<P>
   While most Americans know it for the UNICEF Halloween boxes, or
the war of words inside the building among countries at war, the
institution carries out a mind-numbing number of missions. They
include reducing the threat of nuclear war, overseeing thousands of
peacekeepers around the world, condemning human rights violations,
fighting for environmental protections, and trying to save the
lives of children around the world _ a fight, like the others, that
seems endless. Last year, UNICEF estimated that 12 million children
died needlessly.
</P>
<P>
   To pay its bill, the United Nations assesses each country a bill
determined by its wealth, based on gross domestic product. Under
the formula, the United States accounts for 27 percent of the
world's wealth; under the Helms legislation, the US portion would
reduce to 20 percent in three years.
</P>
<P>
   In the US mission's 12th floor dining room, with a view of UN
headquarters, Holbrooke last week told reporters that the United
States ``can't have that leadership at the United Nations unless we
pay our debts.''
</P>
<P>
   Holbooke said he is spending three days a week in Washington to
lobby Congress. And while he said his fellow UN ambassadors have
been personally supportive, his position is exceedingly difficult
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine standing in my shoes,'' he said. ``How embarrassing it
is to give advice all day long and not getting the resources to
back it up.''
</P>
<P>
   It will be much worse, though, if Congress doesn't pay part of
the dues by year's end. If that happens, he said, ``we will be just
stumbling through the next year and a half'' until the next
president takes office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
