<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DID YOU HEAR THE ONE ABOUT THE ELECTION? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Maybe you think Tom Ammiano versus Willie Brown
is going to be a po litical version of the San Francisco Stand-up
Comedy Competition.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you think this will be all fun and games, one wild and
crazy liberal versus a wilder and crazier liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Forget it.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the surprises in the San Francisco mayor's race, the
biggest surprise is yet to come. Two of the wittiest, quirkiest,
meanest show-offs in America have to play it straight.
</P>
<P>
   We're in for a five-week civics lesson. Forget the mud. Last
week's election proved San Francisco is tired of personal attacks.
</P>
<P>
   How is Brown consultant and master mudballer Jack Davis going to
attack Ammiano before the Dec. 14 runoff?
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano doesn't seem to have any skeletons in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, he isn't in the closet.
</P>
<P>
   The two candidates are in a serious race, competing for serious
moderate voters, and they have to seriously debate the issues _
public transportation, taxes, the homeless, government waste,
development, insider deals and the almost impossible cost of living
here.
</P>
<P>
   Debating issues may sound improbable in San Francisco, where
politics are dirtier than the streets. But it could happen. Odder
things have. On Oct. 12, I predicted Ammiano would launch a
write-in campaign and throw the election into a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   OK, I was exaggerating when I said that Brown might not be in
the runoff. But isn't it great that he got a big wake-up call?
</P>
<P>
   All politics is personal, particularly in San Francisco where
liberals stab each other in the back because there are no
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   We've already heard the first discouraging words.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Carole Migden, a Brown ally, was quoted Friday as
saying, ``With Tom, you don't even know if he can get up for
work.''
</P>
<P>
   Migden said she was just talking, as she does so readily, and
regretted saying it.
</P>
<P>
   I checked Ammiano's attendance at Board of Supervisors'
meetings. In the last four years he missed only four meetings, an
outstanding attendance record.
</P>
<P>
   Just so we have things clear before the race starts in earnest.
</P>
<P>
   Another thing. This is not precisely a contest between a man who
would uplift the poor and working class and a man who would crush
them under the wheels of developers' BMWs.
</P>
<P>
   This is a race between two kinds of liberals. Brown is a more
traditional liberal who sees development and business as engines
that create jobs for diverse ethnic and labor constituencies.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano is a more radical type, reminiscent of the kind of
students who took over deans' offices in the 1960s. In a speech at
City Hall Thursday, he even used the phrases ``participatory
democracy,'' ``the belly of the beast'' and ``class,'' as in social
class, not world-class.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Brown's election-night party was by far more
ethnically diverse than Ammiano's, and Brown swept such
working-class and poor neighborhoods as the Excelsior and
Bayview-Hunters Point.
</P>
<P>
   Ammiano rides public transportation. Brown rides in a limo.
However, both remember their roots, Ammiano as a gay kid growing up
in working-class New Jersey, and Brown as an African American kid
growing up in rural Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Both have strong social consciences _ although one knows more
socialites.
</P>
<P>
   We'll be comparing Brown's record on the homeless and public
transportation with Ammiano's ideas on dealing with the homeless
and public transportation. We'll hear about Brown's improvements in
public housing and Ammiano's efforts to control rents and limit
evictions.
</P>
<P>
   We'll hear a lot about the practicality and fairness of
Ammiano's proposed ``living wage.'' We'll hear about that Ammiano
plan to tax those who make over $150,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Big business may paint Ammiano as a Bolshevik, but the runoff
comes down to a choice between two visions of a city.
</P>
<P>
   In the Brown vision, San Francisco is filled with high steel and
chain stores generating profits and jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In the Ammiano vision, San Francisco is a smaller, freer,
cheaper place, the city young people yearned for in the '60s and
'70s. Of course, it'll have to meet the political correctness
standards of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Last week Ammiano made CNN and Kathie Lee, but he has a long way
to go before he's as famous a politician as Willie Brown. He has
won four citywide elections, though, and served in plain view of
the public on the Board of Education and Board of Supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   Brown spent years as the most powerful legislator in California,
but from a safe district where voters followed him in Herb Caen's
column.
</P>
<P>
   In his election night speech, Brown said he never knew how tough
being mayor would be. He also never anticipated how tough being
re-elected would be.
</P>
<P>
   Last week was a real exercise in democracy. The little guy with
a box of pens humbled the big guy with a box of money.
</P>
<P>
   Now we get down to serious business.
</P>
<P>
   How many comedians does it take to run for mayor? Answer: That's
not funny.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
