<HEADER>
A2755 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-MAINE-LOGGERS-BOS &LR;      11-08 1299
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-LOGGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NORTH WOODS, JOBS VANISH, ANGER GROWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN BARRY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALLAGASH, Maine _ Even in its best days, this city was an
outpost, the last cluster of lights on a road that plunges into
forest. Allagash is not on the way anywhere, and it thrived for a
hundred years in unusual cultural isolation; surrounded on all
sides by French-Canadians, its citizens still speak with a
Scotch-Irish burr.
</P>
<P>
   But ask Mainers about Allagash now, and they will know exactly
what you are talking about. Twice in the last year, a small group
of angry, unemployed woodsmen from this town blockaded the Canadian
border, accusing their government of allowing Canadian loggers to
steal their jobs and, ultimately, drive Americans out of the North
Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Their cry resonates powerfully in a thickly wooded region
surrounded on three sides by Canada, rekindling an old fear that
politicians downstate tend to forget that there are people up here
among the trees. Aroostook County juts into Canada like a
peninsula, bordering New Brunswick to the east and Quebec to the
west. As the farming economy declined between 1969 and 1994, the
county lost 14 percent of its population, even as neighboring Maine
counties gained comparable amounts, according to Robert Roper, who
teaches economics at the University of Maine in Bangor.
</P>
<P>
   Allagash's last stand is reminding people that towns can wash
away, that their children may seek work, or even build new lives,
far from the places their ancestors settled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like this,'' said Hilton Hafford, 41, a leader of the
group of Allagash protesters. ``There's a certain amount of people
who were meant to live in Idaho, and there's a certain amount of
people who were meant to live in Allagash. That's why we were put
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Canadians have been allowed to work in Maine as long as they
were not taking American jobs. But Hafford and his fellow
protesters say that as the exchange rate has made Canadian labor
even cheaper, the system has broken down. Reacting to the protests,
state labor officials have ordered a study, the first since 1977,
to see what effect the Canadian workers are having on the wages of
Americans. The results are expected by mid-month.
</P>
<P>
   Hafford's critics, who include some in his town, assert that he
and his friends _ a small group that has ranged in number from five
to 12 _ have chosen protest over work. Department of Labor
officials argue that they have spent ``thousands of hours'' trying
to place the Allagash loggers in jobs, only to have them reject the
positions as low-paying or inferior.
</P>
<P>
   At root, many fault the Allagash men for resisting the economic
forces that sometimes require workers not only to update their
skills, but to leave their hometowns.
</P>
<P>
   It is a familiar dilemma in the string of towns that line the
US-Canadian border. In nearby Fort Kent, traffic picks up at 2
a.m., as young men commute hundreds of miles for work downstate,
said Kim Doustou, executive director of the Fort Kent Chamber of
Commerce. And that is the young men who stay. ``Most of the kids
here fly right out of the area,'' according to John Paradis, 40,
who owns Doris's Restaurant in Fort Kent.
</P>
<P>
   Seated at a booth, Norman Bouchard, 65, agreed. He said the last
of his nine children, a lumber hauler, was about to sell his
equipment and move to another part of the state. ``The more you
talk to people around here, the more you'll realize something's
really wrong,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A companion requested anonymity because he was afraid of losing
his job for a large lumber company. ``They call us crybabies,'' he
said, ``but there's no more living in the woods.''
</P>
<P>
   Allagash has endured a painful decline. In 1986, on the occasion
of its centennial, Allagash roasted a whole moose on a spit in
celebration; 10 years later, both its high school and elementary
school had shut down for a lack of students. Now scores of black
flies mill on the inside of a gymnasium window and across the
street; the old fire station is for sale. The population of
Allagash, which reached a high of 750 around the turn of the
century, fell to 242 in the last count, according to town selectman
Roy Gardner. Of those who are left, the average age is 65, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There are almost no young men in town. On a recent evening,
Shannon McBreairty, 19, and Donna Bernier, 35, ate dinner together
at Two Rivers Lunch as both of their boyfriends had left town to
find work logging. Bernier's son, who is 19, also has left. Troy
Jackson, 31, who has joined Hafford in the protest effort, tried to
commute for a while, waking up every morning in the dark for the
long drive south to his job, but after a while his 3-year-old
learned how to stop him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The oldest one used to hold my finger at night so I didn't
leave,'' he recalled. ``I drove five hours and you'd think about it
the whole way.''
</P>
<P>
   At a certain point, Hafford began to see the shrinking of
Allagash as a personal assault.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they were to hire hit men from New York and start at one
end of town and work their way saying, everybody leave this town,
that wouldn't go too good across the United States. But you see,
they're doing it little by little. It's subtle,'' said Hafford.
</P>
<P>
   When he and his friends give up the fight, trundling south to
find contract work in Connecticut, he added, there will be no one
left to argue for Allagash.
</P>
<P>
   ``What chance do we have of failure?'' he asked. ``The reason
we're here in the first place is we decided we wanted to live here
more than anyone else did.''
</P>
<P>
   But down Allagash's single road, selectman Gardner _ a direct
descendant of the man who founded the town _ sees a community that
has been overtaken by history as woodsmen with chain saws and cable
skidders were gradually replaced by well-educated operators of
complex machinery. His own children never had any desire to work in
the woods, and neither does his grandson, and it has less to do
with Canadian competition than the desire to find an easier, more
stable living. For his part, Gardner sees Allagash's future in
tourism and retirement homes _ both businesses he has entered.
</P>
<P>
   ``There used to be three or four logging camps in the area with
100 men in each of them. Today, every one of those camps are being
replaced by machines,'' said Gardner. ``That's nobody's fault.
Times are changing. You have to change with the times.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say the people of Allagash may have to accept that
resource-dependent industries make and break small towns. John
Cashwell, president of the Seven Islands Land Company, which
manages 1 million acres of woods in northern Maine, said he made
that point to a group of legislators and labor officials who
visited the North Woods to discuss the logging issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``One night I asked everyone standing there, `Who works in the
town that he grew up in?' and not a one, including me, raised his
hand,'' said Cashwell. ``If it's a one-horse town, and the horses
leave, what are you going to do? This is a group of people who feel
they have a right to stay in their hometown, and that's all right.
But it's not everybody else's fault if things don't turn out the
way they wish.''
</P>
<P>
   Try telling that to Hafford, who built himself a log house that
he cannot afford to live in.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Calvin, recognized his son early as a woodsman _
``He was quite . . . an outdoor fella. Anything he tried, he could
do,'' he said _ and Hafford does not take kindly to the idea that
his special talent is obsolete. Asked how far he is willing to take
this battle, he mentioned the war memorial in front of what used to
be Allagash's school. He said: ``You know the scary thing about it,
is I'm not sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
