<HEADER>
A2758 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-MCMURTRY-BOS &LR;      11-08 1017
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MCMURTRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LARRY MCMURTRY REFLECTS ON A HARD LIFE, SWEET DREAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GAIL CALDWELL  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
WALTER BENJAMIN AT THE DAIRY QUEEN 
Reflections at Sixty and Beyond 
By Larry McMurtry. Simon &AMP; Schuster. 204 pp. $21. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas may be the only province in the land where a man's
capacity for bull _ the activity, not the animal _ is considered a
thing of beauty. That holds true in a particular fashion for the
high plains of West Texas, which boasts none of the urban
treacheries (Austin's liberalism, Houston's pollution) of the more
civilized parts of the state. What you mostly see on the horizons
of West Texas are oil wells, grain elevators, and church steeples;
for the rest of culture, you generally have to look inward. This
partly explains why the region's artists and writers _ Buddy Holly
and Jimmy Gilmore, say, or Larry McMurtry _ all have a streak in
their work of sweet and private melancholy. When the watering
troughs are empty and the sun's moved on to California, what you
have to keep you company is the sound of your own imagination.
</P>
<P>
   That and the Dairy Queen, as requisite to Texas as the Eiffel
Tower is to Paris, and the place where, in small towns, guys go to
talk. After 30 years in the East, Larry McMurtry moved back to his
birthplace of Archer City, Texas, taking with him a huge personal
library of 20,000 books, another quarter-million to stock a
bookstore there, and more than 20 novels of his own _ among them
``Lonesome Dove,'' ``Terms of Endearment,'' and ``The Last Picture
Show.'' He may have been famous when he got back to Archer City,
but he still remembered where a man went to hang out.
</P>
<P>
   And read, which McMurtry has spent most of his life doing _
including his youth, when he was supposed to be helping his father
run cattle. Its title drawn from his reading the German critic's
essays at the DQ, ``Walter Benjamin at the Dairy Queen'' is an
amalgam of insight, speculation, personal history, and bull _ most
of it entertaining, some of it irritating, some of it provocative
and stirring. In this regard the book emulates McMurtry's work as a
whole _ as Texas's native son, the man has always been capable of
writing a wonderful novel one year and a castoff barnyard animal
the next. The mini-memoir he has gathered here is both erudite and
crankish; he can pontificate splendidly about the land or the sky
or his boyhood or Virginia Woolf, only to wander off a paragraph
later about, Lord help us, Cybill Shepherd (here, she's just
``Cybill'').
</P>
<P>
   The Walter Benjamin hook itself is a bit of a tease, though not
an unpleasant one. It's McMurtry's way of writing about the
necessity of story and the diminishment of oral narrative in modern
life _ the activity that belonged, in the Archer City of his past,
to discussions on the porch after supper: ``a dribble of family
history usually involving accidents, injuries, bad choices, good
choices, mistakes made with horses, misjudgments of neighbors, and
the like.'' What a fine definition! Except for those horses, he
could just as easily be describing ``King Lear.'' As romantic as it
is anachronistic, this porch tradition has now gone the way of
cattle drives and cowboys, supplanted by the gods of efficiency and
high-tech anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But McMurtry is no sentimentalist; one of the powerful assets of
his best fiction is its anti-pastoral quality. He knows that life
on the land is hard and even cruel _ that the sanitized,
Americanized myth of the cowboy is pure air-brushed delusion. He
remembers the well-regarded German dairy farmer who lived up the
road when McMurtry was a boy; the man got up and milked his cows
one morning, then put a shotgun to his head. McMurtry's own father
borrowed against his land and battled mesquite and prickly pear,
trying to get ahead while clinging to dying ways. ``My father, as
he neared the end,'' writes McMurtry, ``counted himself lucky that
he had owned a few good horses in his life and had sustained a good
name through seventy-six years.'' For a man who fought the land
most of his life in order to live on it, that had to be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of McMurtry's fiction will be able to glean good details
and minor wisdom from this long and winding essay, but I wish its
author had worked harder to make our job less difficult. There are
moments of lovely recognition _ for this native Texan, it happened
when McMurtry described the ``sky longing'' Westerners feel forever
_ but there is also too much aimless pontificating; an editor, if
such a creature exists anymore, could have taken care of some of
the repetitions and dead-end trails.
</P>
<P>
   The most puzzling piece of ``Walter Benjamin'' is McMurtry's
brief account of the quadruple-bypass surgery he endured a decade
ago, and the trauma he suffered in its aftermath. Like a number of
heart-surgery patients, McMurtry lapsed into depression after he
had physically recovered; he was unable to read or do much of
anything but look out the window for more than two years. His
description of this period is wrenching, though he never goes near
the word ``depression,'' or suggests that there was anything to be
done about it. Instead, perceiving his affliction as a loss of
self, he seems to view it as inevitable _ believing that the
medical miracle of invasive surgery took its toll by nearly
annihilating the person inside the body.
</P>
<P>
   McMurtry is at his most relaxed and charming when he writes
about what he loves, or at least what he knows. Land and literature
seem to have fought over him from early on, but literature won, and
he went on to read everything under the sun and then add his own
work to the pile, writing about the land he had left behind. Like
his father, he's owned a few good horses _ ``Lonesome Dove,''
``Leaving Cheyenne,'' and ``In a Narrow Grave'' are three _ and has
hung on to his good name. As desultory and pleasant as the Pecos
River on a slow day, ``Walter Benjamin at the Dairy Queen'' is a
plentiful reminder of that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Gail Caldwell is the chief book critic of the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
