<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPRECIATE-HIGGINS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGGINS WAS THE ESSENCE OF STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``It was written with a baseball bat,'' is how one
Webhead recently described ``The Friends of Eddie Coyle,'' George
V. Higgins's gritty 1972 novel about the Boston underworld.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty much the most immaculate short crime novel ever
written,'' gushed another reader, comparing Mr. Higgins's mastery
of scene and dialogue to Ernest Hemingway's.
</P>
<P>
   Elmore Leonard, no slouch himself at bringing lowlifes to life,
showered similar praise on ``Eddie Coyle,'' gilding Mr. Higgins's
reputation as both a fan favorite and a writer's writer. A pro's
pro.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Higgins died of natural causes on Saturday at his Milton
home, at age 59. The lawyer-turned-author had long been regarded as
a Boston institution, an outsized personality in a city that
doesn't grow too many authentic giants these days. Whichever hat he
wore _ as journalist, prosecutor, media columnist, political
analyst, script consultant, or writing professor _ he wore it with
more style and flair than a dozen downtown lawyers or 20 Raymond
Chandler wannabes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This life's hard,'' he wrote in ``Eddie Coyle,'' the first of
Mr. Higgins's 26 novels (and 30 books all told), ``but it's harder
if you're stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Higgins was not stupid _ his lifelong faith in the Red Sox
notwithstanding. He was indeed a man of crackling intellect,
prodigious appetites, and extraordinary energy. He dressed
elegantly, spoke elegantly, and wrote elegantly, even (some might
say, especially) when roaming the roughneck neighborhoods of
Southie or Dorchester in his novels. An unabashed devotee of the
good life, he glided easily from Fenway Park to the Ritz, from the
Suffolk County Courthouse to Locke-Ober, from the cockpit of a
sailboat on Nantucket Sound to the wheel of a turbo-charged sports
car.
</P>
<P>
   Producing a novel each year for more than a quarter-century,
many of them classics of the suspense genre (``Cogan's Trade,''
``The Digger's Game,'' ``Kennedy for the Defense''), Mr. Higgins
managed to make his mark beyond the fictional realm of streetwise
punks and hit men. He wrote books, for instance, on two
politicians, Kevin White and Richard Nixon, who might have sprung
full-blown from Mr. Higgins's own fertile imagination if history
had not conceived them first.
</P>
<P>
   His novels were somewhat less warmly received when he relocated
them from the Boston underworld to Washington political circles, as
he did later in his career. But Mr. Higgins resented being typecast
as a genre novelist or one-trick pony, much as he battled with
publishing houses over compromises supposedly broached to make his
novels more commercial.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one asked you to write,'' he once told a Boston University
writing class, distilling his view of the craft. ``And no one will
care if you stop. And if you succeed, no one will notice. It's a
rough, heartless business.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Higgins also firmly believed that bad writing could not pass
the sniff test of being read out loud, so he made his writing
students _ he spent a lot of time in the classroom after he quit
lawyering in 1983 _ read aloud from their work.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Higgins, his daughter, recalled how her father used to
read to her every night when she was a child. A favorite of theirs
was E.B. White's ``Charlotte's Web,'' and in particular Wilbur the
pig's feeling that Charlotte was ``a true friend and a good
writer.'' These words, Susan said Sunday, she will forever
associate with her father.
</P>
<P>
   John Higgins, Susan's brother, added that, ``Dad used to say
that what mattered was not how smart you were but how much you
knew. He knew quite a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Higgins contributed steadily to the Globe from 1979 to 1985,
during which he wrote some 300 columns slugged Amicus Curiae and
Lit'ry Life. His musings on the content and character of hundreds
of publications _ and writers _ were must-reads for anyone who
cared about journalism and popular culture. On Sept. 28, 1985, he
announced his retirement in quintessentially Higgins-esque style.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to stop,'' he wrote. ``I shall miss these weekly
outings, demurely slanging my betters in print, meekly exchanging
fond compliments with readers both approving and indignant,
indulging in respectful badinage with my fine editors, having a bit
of fun. But still and all: I have more books to write, several
promises to keep, some new ones to be made and some other things to
try. Nobody, as Clyde Barrow found out, should keep doing the same
thing too long _ they'll get a bead on you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1415EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
