<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Tuesday, Nov. 9:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-SPEECH (Washington) _ President Clinton delivers foreign
policy address this afternoon. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-TRADE (Beijing) _ Looking at the status of China-U.S.
talks on China joining the World Trade Organization. By David E.
Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-SECT (Beijing) _ Chinese officials on Monday offered the
first official tally of the government crackdown on the banned
Falun Gong spiritual movement, saying that 111 people had been
formally arrested and charged with a variety of criminal offenses,
from organizing a cult to disrupt state security to stealing state
secrets. By Elisabeth Rosenthal.
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Ramallah, West Bank) _ Final status peace
negotiations between Israel and the Palestinians begin with a
formal sit-down and exchange of views. By Joel Greenberg.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-ASSESS (Washington) _ Assessing prospects for The final
status talks. A news analysis by Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-REBEL (Khwaja Bahaouddin, Afghanistan) _ The Lion of the
Panjshir is said to be the nation's greatest guerrilla fighter
holding out against the Taliban. By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECT (Mexico City) _ Franciso Labastida Ochoa is leading
in 272 of 300 electoral districts, the AP reports, marking a
landslide victory in the first national presidential primary
conducted by the ruling PRI. An estimated 10 million people voted,
higher than expected. By Sam Dillon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ONLINE (Washington) _ President Clinton participates in
an online town meeting early in the evening. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DEATH-PENALTY (Washington) _ A roundup: The Supreme
Court, split over the issue, decides not to take a case that raised
the question of whether a very long delay between a sentence of
death and execution is itself cruel and unusual punishment. The
court does agree to take other cases. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   SPEND-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Developments on the appropriations
bills, as many on the Hill hope to finish by Wednesday. By Tim
Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ILL-SCHOOL-PROTESTS (Chicago) _ All three public high schools in
the central Illinois city of Decatur were closed Monday because of
a planned protest in support of seven black students expelled
several weeks ago for fighting. The closings were ordered by the
school superintendent a day after the Rev. Jesse Jackson led
thousands of protesters in a march.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (``p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-HEALTH (Chicago) _ Bill Bradley comments on his health
care, which has been criticized by Al Gore. By James Dao.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EARLIEST-AMERICANS (Santa Fe, N.M.) _ A growing body of
intriguing evidence is telling a much new story of the peopling of
the Americas. From Alaska to Brazil and southern Chile, artifacts
and skeletons are forcing archaeologists to abandon Bering Straits
migration theory and come to terms with a more complex picture of
earliest American settlement. People may have arrived thousands to
tens of thousands of years sooner, in many waves of migration and
by a number of routes. Their ancestry may not have been only Asian.
Some of the migrations may have originated in Australia or Europe.
By John Noble Wilford. (2150 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   For other science stories, see the separate science budget.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MICROSOFT ANTITRUST &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Ledeall on developments on
the legal front. By Joel Brinkley and Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-EUROPE (Frankfurt, Germany) _ How the findings on
Friday affect European regulators' case against Microsoft. By
Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ Looking at the decline in
Microsoft shares and the impact on the overall market. After
falling nearly 9 percent, Microsoft shares have recovered somewhat,
and were down about $2.75, or 3 percent in late morning trading. By
Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   BRITISH-AIRWAYS (London) _ Looking at the problems at British
Airways, which reported a sharp decline in second-quarter earnings.
By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ In late morning, stocks are little changed.
The Dow Jones industrial average was down 0.01 percent, the S&AMP;P 500
up 0.45 percent and the Nasdaq composite up 0.84 percent. The
30-year bond yield was at 6.06 percent European markets were mixed:
London up 0.54 percent and Frankfurt down 0.06 percent. The Nikkei
closed down 0.62 percent, while Hong Kong's Hang Seng ended down
0.66 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   REPUBLIC-HSBC (London) _ The founder of Republic New York,
Edmond Safra, has agreed to take a $450 million cut in the price
HSBC Holdings will pay for his stake in Republic, saving the $10
billion takeover after months of delay. By Andrew Ross Sorkin.
</P>
<P>
   HONGKONG-INVEST (Hong Kong) _ Hong Kong has raised $4.3 billion
_ far more than expected _ from an offering of shares it bought
last year in a costly market intervention. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   BP-EARNINGS (London) _ BP Amoco says its profit rose 72 percent
in the third quarter because of rising crude oil prices and cost
cuts. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
