<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIRTHS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MOST FIRST BABIES NOW CONCEIVED OUT OF WEDLOCK
 &HT;    Eds: Repeating to note that this story is embargoed by source
for release at 12:01 a.m. EST Tuesday.
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the early 1990s most young women in the United
States conceived their first child out of wedlock, a rate that has
nearly tripled since the 1930s, the Census Bureau reported
Tuesday.(cq)
</P>
<P>
   The proportion of first births conceived out of wedlock among
women aged 15 to 29 grew from 18 percent in the period between
1930-1934 to 53 percent between 1990-1994, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The trend was similar for first babies born out of wedlock,
which grew from 8 percent in the early 1930s to 41 percent in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the rapid growth is that having children outside
of marriage is more socially acceptable today than in the 1930s,
said Amara Bachu, a Census Bureau analyst.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not looked down on by society, parents, schools or the
federal government, which may be why more women choose to have
children before marriage,'' Bachu said.
</P>
<P>
   Bachu said she also found that more women are postponing
marriage in order to pursue career goals or attain higher
education, leading to more premarital births. The growing number of
live-in relationships and the healthy economy factor into the
growing number as well, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The study concluded that four factors tend to determine a
woman's chances of marrying after she gets pregnant _ age, race,
education level and geographic location. Teenaged women, black
women, women with less than a high school education, and women who
live in the Midwest were less likely to marry in the event of
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Bachu said researchers were unsure why women from the Midwest
were less likely to marry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Midwest tends to be more conservative. They may have fewer
live-in relationships,'' which were increasingly found to result in
children, Bachu said.
</P>
<P>
   The study reported that 89 percent of births to teenagers
occurred before marriage in the 1990s, compared to less than 30
percent 60 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Parents of teenagers tend to encourage them to pursue an
education,'' Bachu said. ``They take care of their grandkids.''
</P>
<P>
   For black women, the percentage of first births either born or
conceived before first marriage doubled from 43 percent in the
1930s to 86 percent in the 1990s. Rates of marriage before first
births among black women declined.
</P>
<P>
   The study suggested that not only are women less likely to marry
when premaritally pregnant, they are also less likely to marry even
after the birth of their child.
</P>
<P>
   Bachu said a fear of a failed marriage could account for many
women's hesitation to marry after they become pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   ``They may be looking at it from a wider standpoint,'' she said.
``Why get involved in a marriage that could end in divorce,
domestic violence or child abuse?''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
