<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of TUESDAY, Nov.
9.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EARLIEST-AMERICANS (Santa Fe, N.M.) _ A growing body of
intriguing evidence is telling a much new story of the peopling of
the Americas. From Alaska to Brazil and southern Chile, artifacts
and skeletons are forcing archaeologists to abandon Bering Straits
migration theory and come to terms with a more complex picture of
earliest American settlement. People may have arrived thousands to
tens of thousands of years sooner, in many waves of migration and
by a number of routes. Their ancestry may not have been only Asian.
Some of the migrations may have originated in Australia or Europe.
By John Noble Wilford. (2150 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INDIANS-SKELETON (Undated) _ Not all the conflicts in the
search for the earliest Americans center on rival scientists with
sharply different interpretations of the bones and artifacts they
are finding. Emboldened by a 1990 federal law, American Indians
have joined the fight with forceful claims that it is, after all,
their past that all the fuss is over. The uneasy relationship
between archaeologists and the people they study has erupted into a
bitter court battle over the skeleton of a muscular, middle-aged
man who dies sometime between 8,000 and 9,300 years ago. By John
Noble Wilford. (1000 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HOSPITAL-INFECTION (Undated) _ According to the Centers for
Disease Control and Prevention, 5 percent of the people admitted to
hospitals, about 1.8 million patients a year, will pick up an
infection there. The infections cost $4.5 billion to treat, the
C.D.C. estimates, and it says better infection control could have
prevented one-third of those cases. And the cause is simple:
doctors and nurses often don't wash their hands between patients.
By Emily Yoffe. (1750 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-OCEAN-CLIMATE (Undated) _ Scientists now believe they may
have identified a comparable kind of weather pattern involving deep
ocean currents. They say a perpetual oscillation of ocean
temperatures could warm and cool substantial parts of the globe on
longer time scales of centuries to millenniums. By William K.
Stevens. (940 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SMALL-SATELLITES (Washington) _ NASA will be testing a new
concept in tiny satellites. Some, weighing less than a pound and
hardly larger than a pack of playing cards, could be used alone to
perform simple tasks or flown in formations to execute more complex
ones. By Warren E. Leary. (1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-FISH-CONSERVE (Undated) _ As overfishing depletes the seas
of prized species like cod, tuna and swordfish, conservation groups
are urging consumers to make dining choices they say will help
damaged ecosystems recover and support sustainable fisheries. Their
lists recommend seafoods to eat and avoid. ``It's an environmental
problem whose solution is in your hands every time you buy
seafood,'' says the Monterey Bay Aquarium's seafood guide, which
made its debut last month. By William J. Broad. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LONESOME-GEORGE (Undated) _ Scientists trying to find a mate
for Lonesome George, a turtle believed to be the last of his
species, have concluded that the closest living link to the
Galapagos tortoise, or Geochelone nigra, is probably a relatively
small tortoise found in South America, not to other large
tortoises. By Eric Nagourney. (600 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Items on an
insect with 100 lenses, how the nose smells in stereo and a planet
outside the solar system that comes with two stars. By Henry
Fountain. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-MALARIA (New York) _ The Doctor's World: A Manhattan man
with a temperature of 106 baffled his doctors, who briefly thought
if may be malaria but discounted it because it had been seven
months since he had been in an area where in was common, Honduras.
But after a battery of other tests, doctors went back to malaria
when they discovered an enlarged spleen and his temperature
fluctuation continued. By Lawrence J. Altman, M.D. (1450 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANIMAL-PSYCHOLOGY (Undated) _ Animal psychology is a small
but growing field, and while psychologists have drawn lessons from
animals since Pavlov's experiments a century ago, insights now are
flowing in both directions. By Debra Galant. (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ First of two Personal Health
columns on what can be done safely in pregnancy: Now most pregnant
women are cautioned to avoid any and all medications that are not
absolutely essential, as well as ``pleasure drugs'' like alcohol
and tobacco and sometimes coffee and caffeine. But while this is
sound advice in general, it can often result in needless discomfort
for women who avoid taking a harmless drug that could help them. It
also causes undue anxiety among those women who must take
medication or who inadvertently took one or more drugs before they
knew they were pregnant. By Jane E. Brody. (1440 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BICYCLE-FITNESS (Undated) _ As a backlash to all the
technology, bike manufacturers like Bianchi and Voodoo are bringing
back one-geared bikes that resemble those of generations past. Fans
say they get a great workout. By Julie Walsh. (780 words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and
fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Makers of melatonin are urging older people to take their
product to help regulate sleep patterns and make up for declining
production. But some scientists question whether aging actually
causes the loss. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Researchers at Massachusetts General Hospital in Boston were
dismayed to learn in a new study that few American doctors counsel
young patients about the dangers of smoking. (200 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Working to develop engineered tissue that may one day be used
to repair human body parts, Michigan researchers discovered that
tissue from the lab was not as strong as that made by the body. But
exercising the tissue, like exercising the body, makes it stronger.
(200 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Almost half of 100 Chicago firefighters surveyed had lost most
or all of their ability to smell, despite their use of breathing
masks during fires. This leads researchers wonder if there could be
a hidden medical problem of serious dimensions among America's
estimated one million firefighters. (300 words)
</P>
<P>
   _ Vast numbers of people want to know where they can get a
machine that shuts up snorers, especially since a survey shows
found that when snorers used a mask, they and their spouses
reported better sex lives. (340 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANESTHESIA (Undated) _ Patients often wake up from general
anesthesia with nausea and vomiting, but researchers say they can
sharply reduce the incidence of these symptoms with a relatively
simple step: increasing the amount of oxygen given to surgery
patients. By Nancy Beth Jackson. (540 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ A science questions answered: Is the
toxicity of the scorpion's sting related to its size? By C.
Claiborne Ray.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (``e'' cope)
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN-MOVIE (Stowmarket, England) _ Arts Abroad: On the set of
Merchant-Ivory's ``Golden Bowl.'' By Warren Hoge.
