<HEADER>
A2943 &Cx1f; taf-z
s k BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV14-NY     11-08 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ON-LANGUAGE-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN-HOUSE WORD MAVEN SURVEYS NEW USAGE MANUAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Nov. 14)  
(Eds: Items in bold should be set in italics.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Nov. 1, the president of the United States lost his capital.
</P>
<P>
   This is not about the burning of the Executive Mansion by the
British on Aug. 24, 1814, just after James Madison took flight from
the nation's capital and his wife, Dolley, cut the Gilbert Stuart
portrait of George Washington out of its frame and took it with her
for safekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, I refer to the recent Triumph of the Lowercase (or, as
we are now encouraged to put it, the triumph of the lowercase). In
the latest, eagerly awaited New York Times Manual of Style and
Usage _ subtitled (curiously, all in initial caps) ``The Official
Style Guide Used by the Writers and Editors of the World's Most
Authoritative Newspaper'' _ the capital letter is decisively taken
down.
</P>
<P>
   We are guided: ``It is  &UR; President Lamm &LR;  (without a given name)
in a first reference to the current president of the United
States.'' Note: not ``the current President,'' with a capital  &UR; P &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   From now on, even when referring to the specific person holding
the highest office in the nation, Times style is to lowercase the
 &UR; p &LR; . The Associated Press stylebook has been doing this for decades
(which is why I sometimes refer to the a.p.), but I like the
respect shown to the particular president marked by the capital
 &UR; P &LR; . My preferred style, no longer stylish: ```This is an attempt
to bumfuzzle,' said the President.''
</P>
<P>
   The same lowercasing is in store for  &UR; founding fathers &LR;  (an
expression coined by Warren G. Harding, the 29th president). The
Times further suggests desexing the alliterative phrase to
 &UR; founders &LR; , though I can't think of any who were mothers.
Inconsistently, The Times holds fast to the capitalization of
 &UR; Fourth Estate &LR; ; that's got to go.
</P>
<P>
   So it's ``God save the king,'' not ``the King.'' Speaking of
God, the faithful will be happy to see that the Supreme Being
retains his capital. But note that I just wrote ``his capital''_
lowercase  &UR; h &LR; , not ``His capital'' or, as some would insist, ``Her
capital.'' The New York Times stylebook entry: ``God (Supreme
Being). Lowercase  &UR; he &LR; , &UR; him &LR; , &UR; his &LR; ,  &UR; thee &LR; ,  &UR; thou &LR; ,  &UR; who &LR;  and
 &UR; whom &LR;  when the reference is to God, Jesus, the Holy Ghost (or the
Holy Spirit) or Allah.''
</P>
<P>
   I go along with this judgment, though I may pay for it on
judgment day, because of a parenthetical remark in a letter written
in the last century by Herman Melville to his literary mentor,
Nathaniel Hawthorne: ``You perceive I employ a capital initial in
the pronoun referring to the Deity; don't you think there is a
slight dash of flunkeyism in that usage?''
</P>
<P>
   Signs of the times can be seen in the entries dropped and added
between editions of the stylebook. Gone are  &UR; Molotov cocktail &LR; ,
 &UR; women's liberation &LR; ,  &UR; monkey wrench &LR; ,  &UR; Novocain &LR;  and  &UR; zymurgy &LR;  (a
word for fermentation that hasn't been used or abused in decades).
In are  &UR; voice mail &LR; ,  &UR; postmodern &LR; ,  &UR; euro &LR;  (that unified currency is
lowercased, though  &UR; Eurocurrency &LR;  is not, to differentiate U.S.
dollars held in European banks),  &UR; feng shui &LR;  and  &UR; into the breach &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   About that last: Apparently, too many reporters have been using
that phrase instead of Shakespeare's ``Once more  &UR; unto &LR;  the
breach.'' And the Bard's usage is also neatly defended in the entry
for  &UR; gild the lily &LR; : ``An accepted phrase for overembellishment,
but writers who wish to delight the exacting reader will use
Shakespeare's actual words, from `King John': `To gild refined
gold, to  &UR; paint the lily &LR; .'''
</P>
<P>
   I think Allan M. Siegal and William G. Connolly, authors of the
new stylebook, had this column in mind on  &UR; gilding the lily &LR; ,
because an exacting readership is what I've got.
</P>
<P>
   In jocular jousting with the arbiters of style in New York, I
win a few and lose a few.  &UR; Speechwriter &LR;  is now a solid word, and
 &UR; catalog &LR;  no longer ends in  &UR; ue &LR; .  &UR; Data &LR;  is now accepted as
singular, and I'm thinking of starting a fight about  &UR; media &LR; , which
should be as singular as  &UR; fourth estate &LR; . (If the copy editor has
capitalized that, I've been sabotaged.)
</P>
<P>
   The first entry I turned to was  &UR; American Indian &LR; . For years, I
have been insisting that I am a  &UR; native American &LR; , having been born
in the United States, and resisting the seizure of that compound by
aboriginal Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Times says that ``American Indian(s) remains the most widely
used term for the native people of North America'' and notes that
 &UR; Native Americans &LR;  is rejected by some Indians because the U.S.
government uses the term to include Eskimos, Aleuts, Native
Hawaiians and Pacific Islanders. The book's solution: Use the term
preferred by the people written about.
</P>
<P>
   Fights I have lost so far:  &UR; Ms &LR; ., though not an abbreviation,
takes a period. Nicknames, at least those for bad guys, are still
in parentheses, not quotation marks, and so I cannot refer to
Willie ``the actor'' Sutton's nocturnal pioneering in automatic
teller machine withdrawals.  &UR; Pee &LR;  is still disallowed (show me a
little kid who asks to urinate), and  &UR; versus &LR;  is still preferred to
 &UR; vs. &LR; , though  &UR; v. &LR;  is OK for court cases. Even though my word
processor defaults to  &UR; stories &LR; , that word is frowned upon except
at bedtime: ``The preferred word for a newspaper or magazine report
is  &UR; article &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Siegal and Connolly grimly insist on putting an apostrophe in
decades: We're coming to the end of the  &UR; 90's &LR; . They have a reason:
Many publications omit such apostrophes, but they are needed to
make The Times' all-cap headlines intelligible and are therefore
used throughout the paper for consistency. That means that you,
dear reader, are free to drop that apostrophe if you don't use all
caps in your headlines.
</P>
<P>
   Style is not a set of rules; it is a group of conventions to
reflect an attitude and set a tone. ``In approaching the mechanics
of usage and grammar,'' write Siegal and Connolly, ``this manual
reflects The Times's impression of its educated and sophisticated
readership _ traditional but not tradition-bound. ... Throughout,
the goal is a fluid style, easygoing but not slangy and only
occasionally colloquial.''
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about this institution's language arbiters is
their sense of place _ neither on the ramparts nor on the cutting
edge. For that reason, I would cheerfully plunk down $30 for the
new york times manual of style and usage, though I would capitalize
a few of those words and put an apostrophe after the  &UR; Times &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1619EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 16:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2944 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r t BC-TV-ESTCAPE-EASTCAPEME     11-08 1969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ESTCAPE-EAST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
 CAPE MEXICO-LADN  
Mexico's East Cape beauty  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: Fact box, captions at bottom.) By Brett Pauly 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENAVISTA, Mexico _ So you've been to Southern Baja California,
but the fizzle has largely gone out of the champagne that is Cabo
San Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   You want something more authentic than the zoo of megahotels,
nightclubs and Americanized eateries that some feel has so diluted
the Mexican experience that Cabo could be Downtown Any City, U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Baja's East Cape _ smack dab in the middle of the
130-mile stretch between Cabo San Lucas and La Paz _ where the
uniquely quiet, relaxed and, some night owls might say, even boring
atmosphere is evidenced by the fact that the area's sole
discotheque was converted into a church and the only zoo is the
type with lions and tigers and bears ... oh, my.
</P>
<P>
   So often there are two sides to Mexican resorts. There's the
glitz and glamour, and then there's the reality that this is a
Third World country. With poor communities, livestock and litter
abutting the few hotels that break up this isolated region, the
East Cape leans dramatically toward the latter while still
providing wonderfully quaint and clean accommodations, classic
Mexican meals that come with the price of the room and more than
enough to see and do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see this as more laid back than a party town. It has a
definite taste of genuine Mexico,'' said Aaron Coxey of Bend, Ore.
``You can kick back, enjoy the sun, avoid the crowds and, when you
come back home, you feel like you've actually gone somewhere.
Whereas Cabo is like an American city.''
</P>
<P>
   The East Cape is the perfect alternative for those whose idea of
a Mexican vacation includes noiseless beaches, stylish pools that
are deserted at noon and bars that close each evening at 10.
</P>
<P>
   This lonely, arid outpost that is the southeast terminus of the
Baja peninsula splits the Pacific Ocean and the Sea of Cortez, or
Gulf of California. Its azure waters offer an amazing array of fish
_ 850 species _ and a seemingly endless supply. What can't be
reeled in (largely billfish, tuna and dorado) can be viewed
snorkeling and scuba diving. Indeed, like so many coastal
destinations in Baja California Sur, the East Cape is a
world-renowned magnet to saltwater anglers.
</P>
<P>
   But herein lies the beauty for those who don't fish or are less
committed: When the angling crowd is on the brine from 7 a.m. to 2
p.m., you've got the entire region, along with its rich amenities
and adventures that are often overlooked, all to yourselves.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: Bird-watching, horseback riding, hiking, kayaking,
riding personal watercraft, windsurfing, touring botanical gardens,
viewing cave paintings, absorbing slices of life on every corner _
from kids' birthday parties to dining on goat served in a private
home _ and speeding on all-terrain vehicles to lagoons and springs
one would hardly expect to find in the desert. Families and seniors
who care less about the night life should feel especially
comfortable here.
</P>
<P>
   The journey by air begins in San Jose del Cabo. Travel
itineraries list the destination as Los Cabos, referring to the
general area between San Jose del Cabo and Cabo San Lucas 25 miles
to the southwest. Alaska Airlines operates a 9-month-old terminal
that is an inviting alternative to the often-raucous and unkempt
building that is home to several Mexican carriers.
</P>
<P>
   After clearing customs _ bring a passport; a driver's license or
birth certificate complicates entry _ a driver with the name of the
hotel you'll be staying at will be on hand for those who have
transfer vouchers (which can be arranged when booking a room).
Otherwise, taxis in Baja are as common as the cattle that are your
constant companions in this open-range territory.
</P>
<P>
   Cows, goats, horses and burros line the road north toward Los
Barriles, the ``hub'' of the East Cape _ such as it is _ that is
situated on Bahia de Palmas, just north of the Tropic of Cancer.
The tranquil bay is home to seven resorts along less than 25 miles
of shoreline from Punta Colorada north to Punta Pescadero.
</P>
<P>
   During the 45-minute ride north on Highway 1 to my
accommodations at Hotel Buenavista Beach Resort, my driver, Mario
Cano Alvarez of San Jose del Cabo, explained to me in a broken
conversation that the numerous crosses and (ital)criptas(end ital)
erected on the roadside are memorials to those whose paths were
fatefully interrupted by livestock.
</P>
<P>
   A dusty road not well marked leads the way to the hotel, which
has earned a two-diamond rating from the Automobile Club of
Southern California and four stars from the Mexican government.
Room rates run from $75 (U.S.) for a standard single to $200 for a
premium triple, and include all meals a la the ``American plan.''
The price for children ages 11 and younger is $15. Tax is an
additional 12 percent and gratuity _ paid up front as a convenience
to both parties so that most hotel expenses are accounted for early
on _ is another 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tile pathways accented with fountains, bougainvillea and lazily
swaying palms direct visitors to 60 cozy rooms and their welcoming
blasts of air conditioning. A centrally located pool is highlighted
by what's billed as the region's only swim-up bar.
</P>
<P>
   Locals often refer to the facility as ``Spa,'' after its
original name of Club Spa Buenavista. Hot springs flow through the
tropical landscape; until a water-cooling system with greater
capacity was installed more recently, visitors couldn't take cold
showers. The family-operated business was opened with 12 rooms in
1976 by owner Felipe Jesus ``Chuy'' Valdez Vasques.
</P>
<P>
   The original buildings were erected in the 1940s as a residence
and servants' quarters for then-territorial governor Agustin
Olachea, according to the newly released historical account, Gene
S. Kira's ``The Unforgettable Sea of Cortez'' (Cortez Publications;
$39.95).
</P>
<P>
   The menu is changed for each meal at the hotel's restaurant,
known for awesome breakfasts (French toast, beans, sausage, bacon,
Mexican-style eggs, coffee and orange juice) and adequate lunches
and dinners.
</P>
<P>
   For a taste of the surroundings, venture just up the road to
Loncheria Tia Licha, where a shredded beef or pork torta sells for
17 pesos _ or about $1.80 with the exchange rate of 9{ pesos to the
dollar.
</P>
<P>
   A $10 round-trip taxi ride into Los Barriles is worthwhile. Such
touristy enterprises as East Cape Tackle &AMP; Art, Baja Beach Company
and Buzzard's Bay Sports Cantina are found in Plaza del Pueblo.
Taqueria La Palma on a nearby backstreet has tempting (ital)tacos
de pescado(end ital) for 6 pesos. For a most memorable meal, ask
around for the ``Goat Farm,'' where a local lady prepares goat in
her kitchen for a moderate price of about $10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks it's just the hottest deal,'' said area
fly-fishing guide Gary Graham. Dying for American-style fare? Try
the more upscale Tio Pablo's Grill, Mananas Grill or Otra Vez
Restaurant &AMP; Cantina. But, by all means, stroll the friendly
streets of Los Barriles and enjoy the culture that is Mexico.
Remember that many operations _ hotels excluded _ shut down from 2
to 4 p.m. for siesta time.
</P>
<P>
   Apart from being infused with money from tourists and _ as one
local put it _ ``gringos building houses,'' the region is largely
agricultural, with mangos, basil, tomatoes and chiles primary
crops. Then there's the beer, lots and lots of (ital)cerveza.(end
ital) You frequently can't go a city block without running into one
distributor or another.
</P>
<P>
   For the less obvious adventure, inquire back at the hotel.
Nearly any odyssey available can be personalized _ for a price _
and appropriately attentive hotel personnel will ask several times
a day if they can arrange just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``For people who think this is an entertainment capital, it's
not,'' said Steve Chism, concessionaire of fishing tackle rentals
at Hotel Buenavista Beach Resort. ``But there are so many things to
do that people don't know about.''
</P>
<P>
   Chism charges $90 for an all-day bird-watching tour via ATV.
Coastal lagoons with brackish waters attract egrets, snowy plovers,
ospreys, peregrine falcons and an assortment of shorebirds. The
same rate is applied for guided trips up an (ital)arroyo(end ital)
bottom to a mango-, guava- and palm-punctuated spring _ or
(ital)chorro(end ital) or (ital)ojo de agua.(end ital) Chism
identifies plant life _ including a boggling variety of cactuses _
en route. The ride itself justifies the price; there's nothing
quite like the thrill of punching a four-wheeled ATV full throttle
in fifth gear over open sand or riverbeds. Chism can take five
people in a Suburban to see ancient cave paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Some 20 miles to the south and inland, Parque Zoological
Santiago _ described as the only zoo in the state _ is utterly
remarkable in how close visitors can get to the animals. At less
than 3 feet from a tiger, you earn an entirely new respect for
Siegfried &AMP; Roy.
</P>
<P>
   The well-groomed grounds and neatly kept buildings are perhaps
the East Cape's most pleasant surprise. The compact facility was
completed in July 1983, reportedly built with funds raised by
politicians' wives as a way to give something back to the
community. Look for ring-tailed cats, an ocelot, a badger and a
snake pit with coiled rattlers. Cactus provides a contrasting
backdrop to the black bear display. Footpaths are framed with
plumeria, mangos, Spanish dagger and wild plum. A mural depicts the
Pueblo de Santiago y Mision in 1768.
</P>
<P>
   The town of Santiago itself is a government center. A museum
with erratic hours pays tribute to the largely defunct sugar crop
that helped define the area in earlier days. The town's namesake
hotel is thought to have been one of the places where
then-president Dwight D. Eisenhower and the Secret Service slept
during many dove-hunting and big-game-fishing trips to the East
Cape during his administration.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, fishing _ the East Cape's bread and butter _ is a
given. Boats and crews go for $225 to $400 or more per day, with
fishing licenses, bait, rental gear and tips extra.
</P>
<P>
   And, heck, if you can't go another day without more socializing,
music and dancing, $120 will rent a taxi to Cabo San Lucas for the
entire day, and the driver will serve as the guide. But save that
as a last resort for this resort.
</P>
<P>
   EAST CAPE RESORTS
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Punta Colorada, (800) 368-4334.
</P>
<P>
   Rancho Leonaro Resort, (800) 334-2252.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Buenavista Beach Resort, (800) 752-3555.
</P>
<P>
   Rancho Buenavista, (800) 258-8200.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Palmas de Cortez, (800) 368-4334.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel Playa del Sol, (800) 368-4334.
</P>
<P>
   Punta Pescadero Resort, (800) 426-2252.
</P>
<P>
   Captions for East Cape jump photos
</P>
<P>
   All credits Brett Pauly/Staff Photographer
</P>
<P>
   (TRAVEL East Cape 1)
</P>
<P>
   Swimming pools at Mexico's East Cape can be refreshingly
uncrowded at midday, as many patrons at the angler-friendly resorts
are off fishing. The pool at the Hotel Buenavista Beach Resort
boasts the region's only swim-up bar.
</P>
<P>
   (TRAVEL East Cape 3)
</P>
<P>
   Parque Zoologico Santiago, where visitors can view a tiger and
other caged critters from distances of less than three feet, is one
of the most pleasant surprises of the southeastern tip of Baja
California.
</P>
<P>
   (TRAVEL East Cape 6)
</P>
<P>
   Seaside lagoons with brackish waters _ not exactly the typical
image of such an arid environment _ are magnets for a variety of
bird life in the desert that is Mexico's East Cape.
</P>
<P>
   (TRAVEL East Cape 7)
</P>
<P>
   Food server Guadalupe Cota Ramirez, left, beckons patrons into
Taqueria La Palma in Los Barriles, Mexico, where fish tacos sell
for less than 65 cents. Such establishments enhance the
unpretentious ambience of the East Cape.
</P>
</TEXT>
