<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DON'T ANSWER THAT! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The armor cracked.
</P>
<P>
   The defensive outer shield that has protected Texas Gov. George
W. Bush's presidential campaign _ his image as politically
invincible, a sure winner _ suddenly looked dangerously porous last
week.
</P>
<P>
   It was a small verbal stumble. But a stumble it was, loaded with
grave implications for the future.
</P>
<P>
   Bush not only failed in a television interviewer's surprise quiz
to name four foreign leaders presiding over current hot spots, but
reruns of the interview show him sputtering, growing cranky and
looking decidedly unpresidential.
</P>
<P>
   He was tongue-tied, rattled and uninformed. Not quite down to
Dan Quayle's baffled level, but a bit reminiscent of it.
</P>
<P>
   As a singular episode, his blooper could be forgotten as the
campaign moves on to other issues.
</P>
<P>
   But it reinforces a growing impression that when it comes to
foreign policy, he would need a lot of on-the-job training in the
White House. At the moment domestic issues dominate the contest.
But if some terrorist nation creates alarming havoc next year, the
campaign focus will shift to international concerns, and Bush will
be in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   His performance also raises questions about how well he handles
the unexpected. Presidents cannot always anticipate what crises
will land on their desks. They cannot always follow a rehearsed
script. Yet they are required to project the public image of a
reassuring statesman, no matter how privately confused they are.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, caught unprepared, was not fleet-of-foot in the leadership
department. He rushed forward to say later that it wasn't important
to know the name of every foreign leader because people make their
choice based ``upon judgment, based upon vision, based upon
philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, that would be very nice. But on global issues we don't
know what Bush's judgment, vision and philosophy are.
</P>
<P>
   While floundering over the name of the Pakistani general who
seized power from a democratically elected leader in a military
coup last month, Bush rashly called the coup ``good news'' because,
he said, it would bring ``stability'' to the country. Challenged on
this interpretation, he claimed to be echoing the Clinton
administration's reaction.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials had not, in fact, declared the coup
good news, although they had carefully expressed a wish that the
troubled region would now stabilize so that Gen. Pervaiz Musharraf
could meet his pledge to restore democracy. The difference in the
two positions may be lost on most voters, but it goes to the heart
of diplomatic dealings.
</P>
<P>
   Bush didn't understand or couldn't articulate the nuanced
administration position _ or take an independent one of his own.
Instead of implying preliminary and temporary passivity, he sounded
as though he endorsed the military coup. He forgot to plump for a
return to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of clumsiness can be overcome with experience and
expert advice, but why go that route when there are other
candidates already prepped?
</P>
<P>
   The case for electing a governor to the presidency is that he or
she has actually run something, but the power is strictly local.
Senators and vice presidents have the responsibility for national
and international issues and possess the knowledge this experience
brings.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and Sen. John McCain, steeped in this
sort of stuff, probably knew those answers all along, although they
have been briefed by now, and it's too late to find out. Former
Sen. Bill Bradley, first up to face a sequel question about foreign
leadership, replied with aplomb that he simply wouldn't play that
game. A smart answer indeed.
</P>
<P>
   Not many of us, myself included, could have recalled without
prompting the names of the leaders of Chechnya, Taiwan, India and
Pakistan. But we are not running for president and we will never
have to form the American policy toward those countries nor deal
with those leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The quiz, a perfectly legitimate journalistic enterprise, may
mean more in the long run than it does now because it seems part of
a pattern of a serious knowledge gap. Bush has mixed up other names
and places if they don't happen to be near Texas (Mexican names
trip easily from his tongue).
</P>
<P>
   He has called Kosovars ``Kosvarians,'' Greeks ``Grecians,'' East
Timorese ``East Timorians'' and has confused Slovakia and Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, Bush has benefited greatly from the political truism
that to get ahead it's not what you know, it's whom you know. Maybe
it is only fair that the reverse can also be true: those he doesn't
know are suddenly becoming important.
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means can be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
