</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKEEFFE-EXHIBIT-1000(2TAKES)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXHIBIT ASKS TO LOOK ANEW AT GEORGIA O'KEEFFE'S WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LIZ STEVENS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So, you think you know Georgia O'Keeffe? Painter of the
uber-flower, partner and muse to photographer Alfred Stieglitz, New
Mexico desert dweller.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you know something of O'Keeffe. After all, her images and
her image are everywhere, on posters and notecards and calendars _
the poppies, the deer skulls, Ghost Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Still, you probably don't know O'Keeffe the way the Dallas
Museum of Art would like you to know her. ``Georgia O'Keeffe: The
Poetry of Things'' hopes to change that.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the DMA unveils the latest tribute to the celebrated
American artist, who died in 1986 just shy of her 100th birthday.
The traveling exhibition, jointly organized by the DMA and the
Phillips Collection in Washington, D.C., comprises 59 paintings,
watercolors and works on paper that span O'Keeffe's 60-year career.
Her admirers will undoubtedly recognize many of the images, but the
point here is not just to give this well-known oeuvre another
public showing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Poetry of Things'' asks us to look anew at O'Keeffe, and
to do so by understanding her aesthetic philosophy. Why did
O'Keeffe paint the things she did in the way she did, and what was
she trying to communicate through her art?
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to look at her paintings like posters,'' said Beth
Turner, the Phillips Collection curator who organized the show.
``They think they've already seen it; they think they know it. But
the experience of her work in person ... is something that is quite
remarkable and in some cases overpowering.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner said she conceived the exhibition because ``I just
thought people had stopped really looking at her paintings and I
wanted them to understand the source of her invention.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition originated in April in Washington, D.C., and
traveled to the Georgia O'Keeffe Museum in Santa Fe, N.M., over the
summer. When ``The Poetry of Things'' leaves Dallas on Jan. 30, the
Fine Arts Museum of San Francisco will be its final destination.
</P>
<P>
   O'Keeffe was, in some sense, a still-life painter, albeit one
who turned the traditional ideas of representation on their head,
said Marjorie Balge-Crozier, an independent scholar and author of
one of two essays in the exhibition catalog. Instead of rendering
objects exactly as they looked, O'Keeffe painted them according to
how they made her feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is less real than realism,'' the artist said in 1922.
``Details are confusing. It is only by selection, by elimination,
by emphasis that we get at the real meaning of things.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time, this was a truly innovative way of thinking _ and
painting. Over the next decade, O'Keeffe's flowers, although copied
from real life, would assume mythological proportions and pulsate
with color. Without titles, some of them might easily be mistaken
for completely abstract designs.
</P>
<P>
   O'Keeffe was ``revitalizing perhaps the most tradition-bound
genre in painting (still lifes) by trying to make the most familiar
objects look new and different and strange, so you can't just
dismiss them,'' said Eleanor Jones Harvey, the DMA's consulting
curator of American art and local curator of ``The Poetry of
Things.''
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition singles out two people who figured prominently in
the development of O'Keeffe's aesthetic: the artist and teacher
Arthur Wesley Dow and the Russian abstractionist Wassily Kandinsky.
</P>
<P>
   O'Keeffe began studying with Dow in 1914, when she was 26 and
attending Columbia University's Teachers College in New York City.
(At this point, she had already spent two years as ``supervisor of
drawing and penmanship'' with the City Public School in Amarillo,
and would return to teach art at West Texas State Normal College in
Canyon, Texas, in 1918).
</P>
<P>
   Dow's philosophy incorporated principles of Asian art,
emphasizing form and composition over ``mere accuracy.'' His notion
of ``filling space in a beautiful way'' captivated O'Keeffe, and in
1915, she began a series of charcoal abstractions that led to her
first exhibition at Alfred Stieglitz's cutting-edge New York
gallery, 291. (She and Stieglitz married in 1924, and to this day
their pairing and personalities generate almost as much interest as
their artwork).
</P>
<P>
   Kandinsky influenced O'Keeffe through his book ``Concerning the
Spiritual in Art,'' published in the United States in 1914. The
Russian artist believed that color could convey emotion, and that
``an image could almost vibrate like music,'' Harvey explained.
``And there are some images of flowers in this exhibition that
really do vibrate in that kind of way.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Keeffe synthesized both men's philosophies to come up with her
own extraordinary vision. In it, objects are boiled down to their
simplest essences or blown up to otherworldly proportions. Bones
that appear mammoth-sized frame desert landscapes or float above
them, defying gravity. Clamshells and jack-in-the-pulpits assume
sexual overtones.
</P>
<P>
   The sensuality of O'Keeffe's flower paintings has always
provoked debate, with critics viewing some as metaphors for female
sexuality or depictions of female genitalia. While O'Keeffe
rejected this interpretation of her work, art historians tend to
agree that she knew what she was doing.
</P>
<P>
   MORE nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
