<HEADER>
A2953 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT &LR;      11-08 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENCE NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Science Times)  
(jt) 
 By HENRY FOUNTAIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   100 Eyes, One Insect
</P>
<P>
   The night may have a thousand eyes, as countless lounge singers
have crooned, but a parasitic insect that lives in wasps is no
slouch in the optics department either. It has 100.
</P>
<P>
   The insect, Xenos peckii, has two raspberry-like structures on
its head, each of which has about 50 lenses. Researchers at Cornell
University have discovered that each of the lenses has its own
retina. Beneath this are other tissues that help process the images
projected by the lens.
</P>
<P>
   These structures are far different from the compound eyes found
in many insects. Common fruit flies, for example, have about 700
lens facets on each eye, but each contributes to only one sample
point that is processed by the insect.
</P>
<P>
   The larger lenses of X. peckii function as small, independent
eyes, each focusing a chunk, rather than a point, of the visual
field. The researchers, who described their studies in the journal
Science, call these lens-retina combinations eyelets.
</P>
<P>
   All those complex visual signals require a lot of processing
power, far more than would be needed if just points were being
processed. The researchers found that optical fibers constitute
about three-quarters of X. peckii's brain.
</P>
<P>
   Stereophonic Nose
</P>
<P>
   In human hearing, subtle differences in the sound that reaches
the two ears help the listener determine the qualities of the
sound. Now, researchers at Stanford University have shown that the
nose works in stereo too.
</P>
<P>
   In a nose, one nostril is always slightly swollen, and the
swelling switches between the two nostrils every few hours. The
Stanford scientists, writing in the journal Nature, discovered that
the two nostrils sense odors slightly differently, depending upon
the rate of airflow through them (the swollen nostril slightly
constricting the amount of air).
</P>
<P>
   The different chemical compounds that make up an odor must first
be absorbed by and cross the nose's mucous membranes before they
produce a response in the olfactory nerve. And some compounds are
absorbed more rapidly than others.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that a rapidly absorbing component induces
a smaller response when there is less airflow (because it is
absorbed only in a small part of the membrane, the front portion),
and a larger one when there is more airflow (and the chemical has a
chance to spread to more of the membrane before being absorbed).
</P>
<P>
   A slower-absorbing compound has the opposite effect, inducing a
smaller response when there is greater airflow (as the chemical has
less chance to be absorbed). So for any given odor, the two
nostrils provide slightly different responses to the brain. The
researchers suggest that this enhances the sense of smell.
</P>
<P>
   Square Dance in the Sky
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers have found evidence of another planet outside the
solar system. This one comes with a twist: it is the first to
accompany a pair of stars.
</P>
<P>
   As with the roughly 20 other extrasolar planets discovered
previously, the new planet, which has a mass about three times that
of Jupiter, was observed indirectly.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, astronomers from Notre Dame, the University of
Washington and several other institutions analyzed what is known as
a ``gravitational lensing'' event. Such an event occurs when a
distant object passes behind a closer one.
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers can determine the details of the closer object by
studying how its gravitational forces affect the light from the
more distant one.
</P>
<P>
   Although they caution that there could be other explanations for
what they observed, the astronomers, writing in the journal Nature,
say that the closer object is likely to be a pair of stars,
orbiting each other at a distance about twice that of the Earth to
the Sun. And the planet is orbiting both stars at a distance about
seven times that of the Earth-Sun distance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
