<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUDGET-SPENDING (Washington) _ White House and Congressional
negotiators search for common ground on education, environment and
the U.S. role in United Nations as they try to finish 2000 federal
budget. By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VIEQUES (Washington) _ President Clinton says an
``accommodation'' can still be reached in the dispute over
resumption of Navy target practice on a Puerto Rican bombing range.
It has been closed since errant bombs killed a civilian and wounded
four others there in April. Clinton says he has a month to decide
on resumption, which the Navy strongly wants and Puerto Ricans
hotly oppose. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-HATECRIMES (Washington) _ The parents of Matthew Shepard,
whose beating death has led to calls for adding gays to groups
protected by proposed hate-crime legislation, urge Congress to pass
such a law. Dennis and Judy Shepard are joined by Wyoming law
enforcement officers and several senators in their plea at a news
conference here. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DEATH-PENALTY (Washington) _ Over the strong objection of
one justice, the Supreme Court refuses to hear the appeals of two
inmates who have been on death row for nearly 20 years. The killers
had argued that their time spent awaiting execution in Florida and
Nebraska amounts to cruel and unusual punishment. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   NYSENATE-NICHOLSON (Washington) _ Republican National Committee
Chairman Jim Nicholson weighs in on the New York Senate race with
praise for New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, criticism of First Lady
Hillary Rodham Clinton and predictions that the rivals will spend
more than $20 million apiece in their campaigns. By STEWART M.
POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-TRIAL (Jasper, Texas) _ The lawyer for Shawn Berry makes
a last-ditch effort to get the trial of the accused killer moved.
By PATTY REINERT and RICHARD STEWART.
</P>
<P>
   AMBER-ALERT (Arlington, Texas) _ The infant had been missing for
about an hour _ abducted by her baby sitter _ when the police
department received a 911 call from a motorist. ``What's your
emergency?'' the operator asked. ``That Amber Alert,'' the caller
said over his cell phone. Within minutes, police stopped the car,
rescued the child and arrested the baby sitter. By JIM HENDERSON.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SCANDAL (Corpus Christi, Texas) _ For many years, the
parents of Corpus Christi school students largely focused on
academics and the recent improvement in student test scores. But
these days, conversation topics among these parents have shifted to
expensive tabs at topless bars, meals in posh New York restaurants,
and sexual predators on the schools payroll. By JAMES PINKERTON.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Jerusalem) _ Israelis and Palestinians have
stated firmly how they feel about the main issues _ refugees,
Jerusalem, settlements, borders and water. Observers are hoping
that both sides are more willing to compromise as talks continue.
By DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-2000 (JACKSONVILLE, Fla) _ GOP presidential front-runner
George W. Bush campaigns in Florida, where his brother Jeb has
assumed the role George W. had in his father's campaigns. Jeb, with
George W. at his side, poked fun at Vice President Al Gore for
hiring feminist Naomi Wolf, who charged $15,000 a month to help
Gore remake his stiff image. By R.G. RATCLIFFE.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-COWBOYS (Minneapolis) _ Winless in three road games this
season, the Dallas Cowboys try to snap that streak and move into a
share of first place in the NFC East as they face the Minnesota
Vikings in a Monday Night football game. By JODY GOLDSTEIN.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ The Houston Rockets try to avoid an 0-4
start Monday night when they play host to the Orlando Magic at
Compaq Center. By JONATHAN FEIGEN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Until now, Texas Gov. George W. Bush
has benefited from the political truism that to get ahead it's not
what you know, it's whom you know. But his failure to name four
leaders in current world hot spots has reversed that. If foreign
policy becomes a big issue, it could be a real problem for him. By
MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   ROBISON-COLUMN (Austin, Texas) _ Most races for the Texas Court
of Criminal Appeals are only slightly more exciting than watching
paint dry, and next year's campaigns may be no exceptions. But two
races will probably generate more than passing interest, at least
among the small group of people who pay any attention to the court,
namely prosecutors, criminal defense lawyers, crime victims'
advocates and other judges. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
</TEXT>
