<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 16:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2955 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-OKEEFFE-EXHIBIT-2NDTA     11-08 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKEEFFE-EXHIBIT-2NDTAKE-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: she was doing. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There are still people who don't want to look at these
things,'' said Balge-Crozier, referring to anecdotes she heard from
Phillips Collection docents about visitors turning away from
certain flower paintings in discomfort. ``Because it's so
in-your-face; it's not a comfortable distance. That's a very
powerful thing for her to have done.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather than organize the exhibit chronologically as in
Washington, Harvey chose to group the works by subject matter in
each of the four galleries. Images of crosses, bones and clouds
represent themes of time and transcendence, and 13 flower paintings
hang together in the final gallery. The point is to see ``how
O'Keeffe manipulated a certain subject over time,'' Harvey said.
</P>
<P>
   In the second gallery, for instance, three paintings of red
calla lilies from 1919, 1923 and 1924 reveal O'Keeffe's
progressively abstract treatment of the flower.
</P>
<P>
   In the first work, a watercolor, she centers several blooms and
a stem in the middle of the paper. In the second, a small oil
painting, she confines the image to a tumult of red petal forms.
And in the third, the largest canvas, O'Keeffe dives into the
center of the flower and takes us with her until we're immersed in
an emotional geyser of pinks, reds and yellows.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was profoundly, profoundly aware of the beauty of
nature,'' said Barbara Lynes, curator of the Georgia O'Keeffe
Museum in Santa Fe, which hosted the exhibition this summer. ``She
was continually trying to convey the essence of that to the world,
to convey her own experience of the singularity and beauty of the
world. And that's one thing the exhibition brings to you.''
</P>
<P>
   For Harvey, the meaning of the exhibit balances on the grouping
of three seemingly unrelated paintings that begin the show.
</P>
<P>
   O'Keeffe painted ``Dead Rabbit With Copper Pot'' in 1908 while
studying under still-life virtuoso William Merritt Chase at the Art
Students League in New York. The work, which won first prize in
Chase's class, appears surprisingly traditional, especially next to
the stark ``Green Apple on Black Plate'' from 1922 and almost
surreal ``Fishhook From Hawaii No. I,'' painted in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   But in all three cases, the objects seem about to float
unanchored in space, and, as with the fishhook, seem questionable
in scale. These are themes O'Keeffe will return to throughout her
career.
</P>
<P>
   In 1929, O'Keeffe found her spiritual home in New Mexico, where
the desert landscape seemed to beg for artistic exploration. Bones,
crosses and her own adobe homes eventually take the place of
flowers and leaves as the objects through which O'Keeffe conveys
her response to the natural, and ephemeral, world. A series of
airplane rides prompt her to paint ``It Was Yellow and Pink II''
(1959), a dreamlike vision of land and river, and ``Sky Above
Clouds III'' (1963), a vista of ever-shrinking white lily pads.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, ``The Poetry of Things'' focuses heavily on early
O'Keeffe from the 1920s and '30s, ``the seminal works that put her
on the map,'' Harvey said. The artworks here come from 27
collections and include several paintings that rarely leave their
owners' hands, such as ``Red Canna'' from 1923. Favorites
``Poppy,'' ``The Lawrence Tree'' and ``Ladder to the Moon'' are
included, too.
</P>
<P>
   But again, Harvey and the DMA hope that visitors to ``The Poetry
of Things'' will examine O'Keeffe's familiar images in a way they
haven't done before.
</P>
<P>
   ``More people have been content to look at and read the surfaces
of the pictures and her life ... and not bother to delve into an
aesthetic philosophy,'' Harvey said. ``Part of that may be the fact
that as a woman artist, as someone who was alternately charming and
cantankerous, seductive and craggy, she was as fascinating a
character _ or more so _ than her paintings, and therefore that was
a rich enough field to mine.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Harvey added, ``O'Keeffe never really talked
about her aesthetic philosophy publicly during her career. I think
she felt strongly that the paintings had to speak for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The concepts that propel ``The Poetry of Things,'' especially
those contained in the catalog, may be confusing for the art
neophyte. But Harvey stressed that viewers need only grasp the
basic principle behind O'Keeffe's works to learn from and savor the
exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, there are a lot worse ways to spend an afternoon than
contemplating the luxurious petals of a Georgia O'Keeffe petunia.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
