r l BC-ASTHMA-CHILDREN-TEX     11-08 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTHMA-CHILDREN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS ALARMED BY INCREASE IN CHILDREN WITH RESPIRATORY DISEASE
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanied by BC-ASTHMA-PARENTS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CAROLYN POIROT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the typical kindergarten class of 20 children today, at least
one child has asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Asthma is out of control.
</P>
<P>
   The respiratory disease sends more than 570,000 children to
emergency rooms each year gasping for breath. It accounts for more
than 10 million lost school days for children under age 15. And
asthma rates continue to rise, especially among young children;
since 1980, there's been an alarming 160 percent increase in the
disease in children under age 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``These statistics should disturb us. Uncontrolled asthma is
unacceptable,''said Dr. Gail Shapiro, co-chairwoman of the American
Academy of Allergy, Asthma and Immunology's committee to develop
guidelines for identifying and treating asthma in children.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the nation's leading pediatric and asthma experts
released the first comprehensive medical guide for managing asthma
in children and launched a ``Best Practice'' initiative aimed at
raising the standard of care.
</P>
<P>
   The new diagnosis and treatment guidelines are a joint effort of
major health organizations that deal with children and asthma.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing more frightening than watching a small child
struggling for air,'' said Dr. Gary Rachelefsky, whose young
granddaughter has asthma.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is lucky. She has been properly diagnosed and is getting
appropriate treatment with adequate medications, but many children
suffer with asthma every day,'' Rachelefsky said. He is past
president of the American Academy of Allergy, Asthma and Immunology
and is co-chairman of the new initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asthma is a tremendously visible disease today that causes a
tremendous decrease in quality of life for about 5 million children
... and most of that decrease is preventable,'' Rachelefsky said.
``We are alarmed and deeply disturbed.''
</P>
<P>
   He calls asthma in children one of the most crucial
public-health issues of our time and says the disturbing statistics
demand a concerted initiative to ensure that children receive the
best care, regardless of where they live, whether or not they have
health insurance or whether they see an asthma specialist, a family
physician, a pediatrician or other health-care provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asthma can be and should be controlled. ... Something needs to
be done, something very big,'' Rachelefsky said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the reasons for the increase in asthma remain unclear,
contributing factors include: children spending more time indoors,
where they are exposed to allergens such as dust mites, pets,
cigarette smoke and roaches, which trigger asthma attacks; more
young children in day-care programs where they are exposed to viral
triggers earlier; and many children misdiagnosed with a cough or
bronchitis and treated with antibiotics, which do nothing to help
asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Almost half the children with asthma are not being treated
because their asthma has not been diagnosed, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   The new guidelines are the first step to providing ongoing care
that's not just hit and miss, Shapiro said.
</P>
<P>
   The information will be available on a new Web site by year's
end.
</P>
<P>
   The guidelines will offer recommendations for the assessment and
monitoring of children with asthma; ways to control factors that
contribute to severity, such as viral upper-respiratory infections,
tobacco and wood smoke, dust mites, animal dander, cockroach
allergens and indoor mold; step-by-step pharmacologic therapy,
including both long-term control drugs and quick-relief
medications; and patient education.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
