A2959 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     11-08 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TURNING THE PEOPLE'S BUSINESS INTO A POP-QUIZ GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The American people have long suspected that the nation's media
are trivializing the people's business, especially the business of
elections.
</P>
<P>
   And now our suspicions have been confirmed. Last week, a TV
reporter in Boston officially turned coverage of the 2000
presidential election into a game of Trivial Pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Seems this guy figured it would be a great idea to test the
foreign affairs expertise of Republican front-runner George W. Bush
by challenging Bush to name the leaders of Chechnya, Taiwan, India
and Pakistan _ four countries whose leaders' names are so obscure
that citizens of the countries in question might be hard-pressed to
guess them.
</P>
<P>
   Bush flunked the test, such as it was, correctly naming only one
of the leaders. Al Gore, Bush's likely Democratic opponent in the
general election, promptly dispatched one of his flacks to proclaim
that the vice president would have answered all four correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, me too. And I correctly listed Wednesday night's Lotto
Texas numbers _ on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   There are two issues here, one being whether a presidential
candidate should be expected to memorize the name of every leader
of every foreign country so as to be prepared when some jerk with a
microphone decides to spring a ``pop quiz,'' as the media have been
calling this exchange.
</P>
<P>
   I say: Of course not. But don't take my word for it.
</P>
<P>
   Of course not, says no less an authority than George
Stephanopoulos.
</P>
<P>
   A former communications czar in the Clinton White House and
currently a commentator for ABC News, Stephanopoulos is certainly
no fan of office-seekers named Bush. But he described the Boston
reporter's questions as a ``cheap shot'' and said he doubted that
anyone could have answered all four on a moment's notice.
</P>
<P>
   The second issue is whether this sort of cheap-shot interviewing
is a legitimate journalistic technique. Oddly enough, this very
subject came up recently in the context of sports reporter Jim
Gray's ambush interview with ex-baseball star Pete Rose _ and the
consensus among the public, if not the media, seemed to be that
it's not legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, of course, is that few interviewers, especially TV
interviewers, have any interest whatsoever in obtaining information
from the interviewee. More often than not, the purpose of
interviews is not to enlighten the audience but to showcase the
interviewers, to hype their ratings and promote their careers by
enhancing their reputations as tough questioners.
</P>
<P>
   And so it was in the case of Andy Hiller of Boston's WHDH-TV,
who ``is known locally for asking sassy questions of political
leaders,'' according to The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   The operative word here is ``sassy,'' for which my computer's
thesaurus offers a number of synonyms. Among them:
``disrespectful,'' ``rude,'' ``surly'' and ``wisenheimer.''
</P>
<P>
   I especially like ``wisenheimer,'' which is more polite than a
shorter word beginning with the same four letters but which clearly
addresses the attitude of the person described. Hiller wasn't
trying to help his audience assess Bush's qualifications for the
presidency; he was showing off.
</P>
<P>
   The public is on to this stuff, of course, and has learned to
keep the media grandstanding in perspective. Voters know that if
the president of the United States needs to know the name of a
foreign leader, he only has to snap his fingers and he will have
it, along with every documented fact about the leader's personal
and professional background and some secrets that the leader may
not have shared with his most intimate associates.
</P>
<P>
   Even Clinton conceded that quiz-show questions about foreign
leaders miss the point. Here's what the president told ``Good
Morning America,'' as quoted by the AP:
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is, Do you have a clear idea of what
the world oughta look like and what America's policy oughtta be in
these areas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has a very clear idea about the world and America's role in
it. Maybe some enterprising interviewer should ask him about that.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
