<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OKLAHOMA-REBUILD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC-DEL CITY-REBUILD, BC-MOORE-REBUILD) 
VOLUNTEERS FROM ALL OVER STILL REBUILDING TORNADO-RAVAGED OKLAHOMA
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanied by BC-OKLAHOMA CITY REBUILD, BC-BRIDGE CITY-REBUILD,(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEANNA BOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGE CREEK, Okla. _ John Vanderford leans on his wooden level
and surveys the nearly completed 1-story structure that will soon
be the home of Jerry and Karen Price.
</P>
<P>
   His doctors would frown if they could see Vanderford, decked out
in blue-and-white-striped overalls and a yellow baseball cap that
reads ``Building for the Glory of God.'' He has bone cancer and has
been told by his doctors to limit his physical activity.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't stop Vanderford, 76, of Tulsa from helping
build houses for those left devastated by the Oklahoma tornadoes
six months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not supposed to be able to work anymore _ so say the
doctors,'' Vanderford said. ``Doctors don't know everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Across Oklahoma and the nation, people are setting aside the
comfort of their homes, their jobs and, in some cases, their
retirement to help families that were wiped out financially by a
series of tornadoes that pummeled the Oklahoma City area May 3.
</P>
<P>
   Project Rebuild links the volunteers, many of whom are members
of religious disaster missions, with the Oklahoma Lumbermen's
Association. The association gathers donated building materials;
the volunteers supply the labor.
</P>
<P>
   Bridge Creek, an unincorporated farming community in Grady
County, is receiving most of the project's attention. Grady County
officials estimate that about 50 percent of those affected by the
tornadoes had inadequate insurance or none at all.
</P>
<P>
   About 16 homes are under construction there.
</P>
<P>
   One house will be home to a couple who spent months living in a
tent and trailer without electricity or plumbing. A bucket served
as their toilet. Another will shelter a single mother and her
14-year-old daughter, a former cheerleader who was paralyzed in the
tornado and now uses a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   But Dale Thompson wonders whether some well-intentioned
volunteers may inadvertently be putting families in harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, the Grady County emergency management coordinator,
said a few professional contractors have expressed concern that
some of the volunteers who are helping build houses may not be
qualified. The county has no code enforcement officer to ensure the
quality of work being completed, Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of these volunteers have their heart in the right place,
but we're worried about whether things are actually brought up to
code,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharilyn Young, executive vice president of the Oklahoma
Lumbermen's Association, said the association is making every
effort to ensure that homes are built correctly.
</P>
<P>
   Experienced retired builders are assigned to oversee volunteers
at each construction site, she said. And an independent building
contractor inspects each framed structure before drywall is
installed, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a conscience about building property,'' Young said.
``We are not out to build a home that won't meet the test of time
and quality and usability and wearability. The point is most of
them are getting a better place to live than they ever have had
before.''
</P>
<P>
   After eight years in a mobile home, Charlene and Tommy Stone, a
disabled couple on welfare, are thrilled that they will be in a new
house by Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they first started talking about building me a house, I
thought, `I don't believe it. This doesn't happen to me,' '' said
Charlene Stone, 55.
</P>
<P>
   Now she can glance through her trailer window at the tan,
1-story house that has risen where only red clay had been before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had people from Georgia, Alabama, Florida, West Virginia
and Missouri here,'' Stone said. ``My house is being built by
everybody. I never knew people could help like they have.''
</P>
<P>
   On a hill where Ridgecrest Baptist Church once stood, about a
dozen recreational vehicles serve as homes for out-of-town
volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically have an RV city at the church,'' said pastor Tom
Duckett. ``We have folks that don't come in under any typical flag.
They just come in to work. Some will stay for a week, others
several months.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanderford and his wife, Myra, have lived in a small trailer
home for almost two months.
</P>
<P>
   A builder by trade, Vanderford retired 13 years ago but is a
member of the state disaster team for the Southern Baptists. He is
a volunteer coordinator but can't resist helping with the
construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've only got maybe one talent, and I don't want to lose it,''
he said jokingly.
</P>
<P>
   Vanderford said he chooses to spend his retirement helping
others because ``I'm going to wear out, not rest out.''
</P>
<P>
   Others who are helping have brought their families with them.
</P>
<P>
   David Leid, his then pregnant wife, and their six children had
just completed nine months working in flood-devastated Cuero,
southeast of San Antonio, when they received word that Christian
Aid Ministries was needed in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   In a temporary building set up in a city park in Newcastle, Leid
and a small staff coordinate the influx of Mennonite and Amish
volunteers from as far away as Pennsylvania and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   The building has been transformed into a home away from home for
the volunteers. Curtains adorn the windows and inspirational
posters decorate the walls. A full kitchen has been installed for
the women to cook for their families and other volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Sullivan left his own carpentry business in Oregon to help.
His wife, Lori, said the couple and their two young children
brought only what would fit in their car trunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned we can be satisfied and live with less,'' said Lori
Sullivan, 25, pausing as she sewed curtains. ``You just don't need
it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Although most staff members sleep in the recreational vehicles
parked outside, Leid rents a home to house his wife and seven
children, who range in age from 14 years to 3 weeks. The children
are home-schooled, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the children's life for the last two years, so
they love it,'' Leid said. ``We feel this is the Lord's will for
our lives to do this.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
