<HEADLINE>
SURVIVORS REBUILD WITH FAITH, HOPE AND A LITTLE CHARITY
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-OKLAHOMA-REBUILD) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEANNA BOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGE CREEK, Okla. _ Handwritten quotations from Scripture peek
out from behind the spackle on the wallboard of the Dawsons' future
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus is King of Kings. Lord of Lords.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, Lord, for this house.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to inspire yourself somehow when you do this,'' a
weary Detra Dawson, 27, said as she worked on a living-room wall.
</P>
<P>
   The Dawsons, like many residents in tiny Bridge Creek, had no
insurance and were financially wiped out when a tornado ripped
apart their mobile home.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, through faith, hard work and an assistance program
called Project Rebuild, the family is completing work on a
three-bedroom, two-bath house all their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I owe nothing on it,'' beamed David Dawson, 28. ``It's ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Project Rebuild, spearheaded by the Oklahoma Lumbermen's
Association, has committed to help build up to 40 homes for
low-income, elderly and disabled people in Bridge Creek, an
unincorporated area in Grady County.
</P>
<P>
   The project screened Oklahomans who received grant money from
the Federal Emergency Management Agency to identify the neediest
families.
</P>
<P>
   Lumber and building industry officials have donated more than
$2.2 million worth of materials. Church organizations and
volunteers build the homes using adapted Red Cross floor plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're doing really is giving them a fresh start so
they're not encumbered with debt,'' said Sharilyn Young, executive
vice president of the Lumberman's Association. ``A lot of them
couldn't get a home loan if they wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Dale Thompson, emergency management coordinator for Grady
County, said that about 25 percent of Bridge Creek families
affected by the tornadoes had no insurance. Another 25 percent were
underinsured, he said.
</P>
<P>
   David Dawson, a self-employed builder, made about $40,000 a year
but couldn't afford insurance on his mobile home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever try putting insurance on a mobile home? It's
high, about three times higher than a house,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado left him homeless and jobless. A shed containing
tools worth an estimated $60,000 and a car full of machinery from a
recent project disappeared in the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found one socket (wrench) a foot and a half underground when
I was digging a post hole,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Project Rebuild has given the Dawsons $10,000 worth of building
materials. Dawson has done much of the work himself. He pays for
materials for the rest of the house using money from a $13,600 FEMA
grant and earnings from subcontracting work.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the couple, their three young children and Detra
Dawson's mother cram into a trailer on their property. They rise
early each morning to work on the home, eager to move in by
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The family has lived in mobile homes for the past four years.
David Dawson says never again. In trailers, utility bills and
insurance are higher and the home depreciates with time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a house, you don't have cold air going up through the
floor,'' he said. ``There's no comparison.''
</P>
<P>
   And this time, Dawson can afford the insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord has really blessed us tremendously because he gave us
better than we had before,'' Detra Dawson said. ``I was satisfied
with what we had before, but this is better.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
