<SLUG> BC-OKLAHOMACITY-REBUILD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINE VETERAN CAN'T ESCAPE `FOUR MINUTES OF TERROR'
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-OKLAHOMA-REBUILD) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEANNA BOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY _ Thunder and rain bring back those ``four minutes
of terror,'' leaving Pat McNabb trembling.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers the wind in his face and the distinctive smell _ a
combination of rain, dust, insulation and debris.
</P>
<P>
   It matters little that McNabb, 42, suffered only minor physical
injuries when an F5 tornado, a twister with winds of 261 to 318
mph, leveled his home and buried him in debris. The emotional
wounds cut deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did almost six years in the Marine Corps,'' McNabb said.
``This tops anything I experienced there because you can't fight
back. There's no one to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Those feelings of helplessness have surfaced for many
Oklahomans, even those who were not directly affected by May's
tornadoes, counselors say.
</P>
<P>
   ``A natural disaster like that is unpredictable,'' said Rosemary
Brown, communications director of Project Heartland, a counseling
program started after the 1995 terrorist bombing of the Oklahoma
City federal building. ``It could have been you, and it still could
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Through September, Project Heartland has provided free
counseling to 492 clients. The program has served about 34,000 more
through seminars, debriefings and education. The federally funded
project is run by the state Department of Mental Health and
Substance Abuse Services.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors say the number of people seeking assistance is
climbing and may not peak until the one-year anniversary of the
storms in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them are wondering, `It's six months later. Why am I
doing this now? Is there something wrong with me?' '' said Susan
Ray, counselor coordinator with Project Heartland.
</P>
<P>
   Some victims say it helps to simply talk about the tornadoes.
Each day brings healing for McNabb's neighbors, Sherri and David
Kosfeld and their daughters, Kayla, 9, and Ashley, 16.
</P>
<P>
   Their home was destroyed and the closet they huddled in for
safety ended up on its side. Only the Kosfelds and three backpacks
that Ashley had stuffed with Beanie Babies, clean underwear and
photographs remained.
</P>
<P>
   Moving into their rebuilt home last month aided the healing,
Sherri Kosfeld said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first night we were home, I was afraid it was going to be
real hard on all of us,'' she said. ``But we all came in and went
to bed and just crashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like, `We're home.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Watching others bounce back quickly made McNabb feel as if his
fear of storms was abnormal.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb, a burly man at 6-foot-1 and 245 pounds, is a prison
employee. He wondered how someone who comes face to face with
murderers every day could cower like a child at the approach of a
storm.
</P>
<P>
   When a storm rolls in, McNabb sits glued to the television in
his rental home. When a tornado warning is issued, he plans to jump
into his red 1999 Lincoln Navigator _ with license tag ``F5 SURVR''
_ and head for Tulsa or Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to call in sick at work the next day if we have a night
storm,'' he said. ``I get no sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   McNabb sought the help of a psychologist through his employer.
</P>
<P>
   He was relieved to be told that his fears are normal responses
to a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope it's like a car wreck and I get over it in a couple of
years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
