<SLUG> BC-DELCITY-REBUILD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINGERING TRAUMA CAN'T OVERCOME RESIDENTS' GRIT
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-OKLAHOMA-REBUILD) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEANNA BOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL CITY, Okla. _ Amid the concrete foundations, brick and
2-by-4s, the Burch home represents hope.
</P>
<P>
   Six months ago, tornadoes destroyed 406 houses in this community
east of Oklahoma City. A month ago, Carolyn and Dale Burch were the
first to return to a rebuilt home in the Del Aire subdivision, the
hardest-hit area of the city.
</P>
<P>
   For many, there was no doubt that they would rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   The Burches wanted to stay where their children had been raised.
Bobby Stewart liked his house's corner location. John Reilly wanted
his 9-year-old daughter, Victoria, to understand that ``sometimes
you've got to look adversity in the eye and kick it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Edwards, city manager of Del City, said the number of
families who chose to rebuild far exceeds those moving elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some who couldn't stand the thought of coming back
in here,'' Edwards said. ``And I think some of the people were
waiting to see what kind of houses were going to be built before
they decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Many people, like the Burch family, had replacement-cost
insurance. Those with that coverage who rebuilt on the same lot
received as much as 25 percent more than the insured value of their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   Others sold their lots to builders, who are building bigger and
better.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said typical home appraisals in Del Aire are expected to
increase from less than $70,000 to between $100,000 and $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   Planning for the Burches' brick-and-stone house began almost
immediately after Carolyn Burch, 53, finished a six-week stay at a
local hospital. She was home alone when the tornado ripped through
and left little standing but her locked front door.
</P>
<P>
   A brick bedroom wall toppled onto her and shielded her from
flying debris. But it left her with a brain contusion and a
shattered pelvis. She was in a coma for two days.
</P>
<P>
   On Carolyn Burch's second day out of the hospital, a woman
varnishing the cabinets in the couple's Oklahoma City apartment
mentioned that her brother was a contractor.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the next day I was going through plans, picking out a
house,'' Carolyn Burch said. ``By the next day I was going through
the trim I wanted. I was picking out brick, carpet. We got to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The home was completed in four months.
</P>
<P>
   But the lots on both sides of the Burch home remain empty.
</P>
<P>
   Their former neighbors, Audrey and James ``Mac'' McDonald, a
retired Air Force senior master sergeant, have moved to a new house
in Midwest City.
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding, Audrey McDonald said, would take too long and revive
too many memories of that tragic day. The couple survived the
tornado huddled beneath a mattress in their bathtub.
</P>
<P>
   Audrey McDonald, 73, said she'll never forget when a neighbor
kicked open her jammed front door and she walked outside to see her
neighborhood of 28 years gone and Carolyn Burch lying injured and
unrecognizable on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``The devastation was unbelievable,'' she said. ``I just feel
like every time I stepped out of the door, I would see it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
