r a BC-MOORE-REBUILD-TEX     11-08 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOORE-REBUILD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHELTERS BRING PEACE OF MIND IN TORNADO ALLEY
</HEADLINE>
 
(Accompanies BC-OKLAHOMA-REBUILD) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DEANNA BOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOORE, Okla. _ Even before May's deadly twisters, three business
partners thought that living in the heart of Tornado Alley
presented an opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   When a twister destroyed one of their homes and damaged their
auto glass business, they were convinced.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Storm Shelters of Oklahoma has three locations across the
state. The company struggles to keep enough workers on hand to meet
the demand for underground shelters, co-owner Jim Harvey said.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of Oklahoma families, including many whose homes
weren't touched by the tornadoes, are installing storm cellars or
safe rooms in their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The protection isn't cheap, but it's worth the investment,
residents say.
</P>
<P>
   Cathy and Cody Nelsen lost their 2-story home in Moore and a
house full of antiques. Their family survived, but they're taking
no chances that closets will protect them next time around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though our physical bodies are OK, our kids have been
hurt psychologically,'' Cathy Nelsen said. ``You're supposed to
protect your children. I felt like I put them in harm's way.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of underground shelters averages $2,500 to $3,500,
depending on size.
</P>
<P>
   Safe rooms are a bit more expensive, at about $3,700 to $4,500,
depending on the size. They consist of 6- to 8-inch-thick walls of
reinforced concrete designed to withstand winds of 250 to 300 mph _
comparable to winds during a highly destructive F5 tornado.
</P>
<P>
   Safe rooms typically double as a master bedroom closet, said
Dave Watson, sales manager of Polysteel, a company that builds
them. An entire house can be built with the concrete walls at a
cost of 4 percent to 5 percent above normal construction cost, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   To offset the cost, about 7,000 Oklahomans have applied for
$2,000 rebates offered through the Federal Emergency Management
Agency, said Jim Lewellyn, an engineer in Oklahoma City's Public
Works Department.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of the people who applied, including Lewellyn,
suffered no damage from the tornado but saw the need for a shelter
after driving through ravaged neighborhoods or watching TV footage
of the destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``After spending time in those neighborhoods, you want something
more than your bathtub to hide in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Families whose homes suffered 50 percent damage or more are
given first priority, Lewellyn said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nelsens are waiting to find out whether they will receive a
rebate. Even if they do not, Cathy Nelsen insists that the shelter
is worth every penny of its $3,500 cost.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, the Nelsens filled in an underground shelter on
their property because it frequently flooded with rainwater.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sons were little at the time, and I was scared they'd fall
in and drown,'' said Nelsen, 33. ``You hear about tornadoes. ...
You just never think it's going to happen to you.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, their concrete shelter is empty. The family plans to
transform it into a clubhouse for sons Valen, 11, and Vance, 12.
</P>
<P>
   Two cots will give the boys a safe place to sleep at night if
they're frightened by storms. Animal carriers, to be stacked in one
corner, will protect the family's dogs and cats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it's never used other than as a clubhouse,'' Cathy
Nelson said, ``it's worth it for the peace of mind.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
