<HEADER>
A2979 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      11-08 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBISON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIMINAL APPEALS RACES SLOWLY TAKING SHAPE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Most races for the Texas Court of Criminal
Appeals are only slightly more exciting than watching paint dry,
and next year's campaigns may be no exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   But two races will probably generate more than passing interest,
at least among the small group of people who pay any attention to
the court, namely prosecutors, criminal defense lawyers, crime
victims' advocates and other judges.
</P>
<P>
   One race will be Judge Steve Mansfield's re-election attempt,
the first time he will have been on the ballot _ if he doesn't
change his mind again _ since his surprise election in a 1994
Republican landslide. The other will be a potentially divisive
fight between two incumbent court members for the presiding judge's
post to be vacated by Mike McCormick.
</P>
<P>
   Both races are shaping up in the Republican primary, which has
produced all the recent winners of statewide offices in Texas.
Democrats may yet try to compete, but all the early candidates are
Republicans, as are all the members of the court.
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield, who first said he wasn't going to seek a second term
and then said he was, is attracting several potential GOP
opponents, who hope that his periodic controversies will finally
catch up with him.
</P>
<P>
   Although he had little criminal law experience before joining
the court and his election was considered a fluke, Mansfield has
developed a reputation as a hard worker, and his mostly hard-line
record against criminal defendants reflects the majority viewpoint
on the court. But trouble still follows him.
</P>
<P>
   Just last month, he pleaded no contest to a trespassing charge
stemming from his arrest by University of Texas police last year
for allegedly trying to scalp his complimentary tickets to a UT
football game. He was given six months' probation.
</P>
<P>
   The Mansfield controversy five years ago overshadowed a
significant judicial milestone, the election of the first woman,
Sharon Keller, a former Dallas County prosecutor, to the Court of
Criminal Appeals. Now, McCormick's pending retirement gives Keller
the opportunity to mark another milestone.
</P>
<P>
   Keller plans to run for the presiding judge's post rather than
seek re-election to her own seat, which also comes before the
voters next year. If she is successful, she also would become the
first woman to preside over the court, although she said that
distinction wasn't the reason she was running.
</P>
<P>
   But Keller faces opposition from Judge Tom Price, another member
of the court, who also intends to run for presiding judge. Price
has the advantage of being in the middle of a term, which means he
will remain on the court if he loses his race. For Keller, it will
be up or out.
</P>
<P>
   McCormick has given Keller a taste for the presiding judge's
administrative duties by appointing her to various committees and
task forces that have broadened her experience and raised her
profile during her first-ever term as a judge.
</P>
<P>
   Keller also is strongly in the prosecutors' corner, while Price
is sometimes part of a minority that has been known to side with
criminal appellants.
</P>
<P>
   Price is a more experienced judge, but his first 22 years on the
bench were as a trial judge in Dallas. He had no appellate court
experience until he was elected to the Court of Criminal Appeals
three years ago. And he has been mostly absent from Austin since
joining the high court.
</P>
<P>
   Price attends most of the court's weekly conferences _ where he
sits next to Keller _ and attends oral arguments, held once or
twice a month. But he spends the rest of the time in Dallas, away
from the chambers where his colleagues and their staffs research
and write the court's opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't shown a lot of interest in the court,'' Keller said,
signaling a possible campaign issue. She questioned whether Price
even knew all the presiding judge's responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Price acknowledged that he spent most of the work week in
Dallas, but he said he had to take care of his elderly father and,
as a single parent, his teen-age son. But he said he takes work
home with him and has documents faxed and shipped by bus. He
promised to work full time in Austin if elected presiding judge.
</P>
<P>
   Price said he was presiding judge of Dallas County's 15 criminal
district courts for six years and oversaw the probation department
and dealt with county commissioners on budgetary matters. He said
he was ``good at getting people to work together.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite their best efforts, the candidates' qualities will
probably be lost to most voters in a low-profile race.
</P>
<P>
   Women have done well in judicial races in the Republican primary
in recent years. And Price may still have strong name
identification in Dallas. But John Bradley, a Williamson County
prosecutor who lost a race to Price three years ago, said a
campaign for the court is still a ``complete gamble.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
