<HEADER>
A2983 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-AMBER-ALERT-HNS &LR;      11-08 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMBER-ALERT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALERT SYSTEM HAS BEEN CREDITED WITH SAFE RECOVERY OF 5 ABDUCTED
CHILDREN 

</HEADLINE>
 -HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JIM HENDERSON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The infant had been missing for about an hour
_ abducted by her baby sitter _ when the police department received
a 911 call from an excited motorist.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your emergency?'' the operator asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Amber Alert,'' the caller said over his cell phone. ``The
lady's right in front of me. She's got a baby sitting in front of
her and I saw it and heard that (alert). I said, `Man, that's her.
I can't believe it.'``
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, police stopped the car, rescued the child and
arrested the baby sitter.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the more dramatic moments in a 3-year-old program
designed to locate abducted children quickly, and it is one of the
reasons that the Amber Plan _ named for a young girl who was
abducted from her Texas home and killed in 1996  &UR; _ &LR;  has begun to
spread across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma plans to run a statewide test next month and implement
it in January. Two weeks ago, Kansas City completed procedures for
its version of the plan. Houston, Battle Creek, Mich., and cities
throughout California have asked the Arlington Police Department
for help in setting up programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works,'' says Officer Dee Anderson, a spokesman for the
Arlington police, ``and it doesn't cost anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the plan evolved in 1996, following the kidnapping
and slaying of Amber Hagerman, a crime that shocked the community
and troubled Arlington police.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Amber,'' Anderson says, ``we knew within minutes what we
were dealing with, but we didn't have any way to get the word
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Working with a group of radio stations, the police department
came up with a scheme to get the word out quickly and, in effect,
turn the entire Dallas-Fort Worth area into a neighborhood watch.
</P>
<P>
   Once police were convinced a child had been kidnapped, was not a
runaway or in the middle of a custody fight, they alerted every
radio station in the area. The stations were given a description of
the child, the kidnapper and vehicle so the information could be
immediately broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-two radio stations agreed to participate by interrupting
their programming for an Amber Alert, Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research told us that 98 percent of the people driving
their cars are listening to the radio,'' he said. ``Getting it on
all the stations is critical. No matter what station you are
listening to, you will get this information.''
</P>
<P>
   However, faxing 32 stations proved to be too time-consuming, so
the system was amended. Now, the police notify two Dallas area
stations, which notify the others through the Emergency Alert
System. In the same way that listeners would be warned of severe
weather, they would now be alerted to a missing child.
</P>
<P>
   This year, 10 television stations &UR;  &LR; agreed to join the radio
stations in broadcasting the alerts.
</P>
<P>
   Since the plan went into operation early in 1997, Anderson says,
it has been activated about two dozen times and is credited with
the safe recovery of at least five abducted children.
</P>
<P>
   One of those was 9-year-old Felicia Moore, who was snatched from
a sidewalk last March while walking with a friend in southeast
Dallas. A man standing beside a pickup delayed them by talking to
them about a kitten. As the friend walked on, the man grabbed
Felicia, forced her into the truck and drove away.
</P>
<P>
   Six hours later, she was found walking beside a rural road about
35 miles from where she was kidnapped. The girl told police the
kidnapper stopped the car suddenly and told her to get out.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said it is believed that the kidnapper heard the Amber
Alert on the radio and, fearing that he would be spotted with the
girl, decided to free her.
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the Amber Plan spread across the country after it
was featured on the television show ``America's Most Wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson says he has cautioned inquiring police agencies that
the Amber Plan has pitfalls and is still going through revisions in
North Texas. The biggest problem, he said, has been an
indiscriminate use of the plan by some of the 33 police agencies
that participate in it in the Dallas-Fort Worth area.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was being activated too often,'' he says. ``Every time a
child was missing for a short time, the police were pressured to
activate the plan. The radio managers complained and some were
threatening to pull out.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson says it is rare for children to be abducted by
strangers. In most cases, they are taken by parents or relatives
and that does not justify an Amber Alert.
</P>
<P>
   ``People started thinking of it as a routine law enforcement
tool,'' Anderson says. ``When an officer showed up at the residence
(of a missing child) the first thing the parents asked was, `Are
you going to activate the Amber Plan?' They wanted it done
immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Now there are new rules: The plan can be activated only if the
missing child is under age 15 (or has a proven mental or physical
disability) and if the police believe the child is in serious
danger.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Curvy, an aide to Oklahoma Gov. Frank Keating, said that
state's 200 radio stations were enthusiastic about participating in
a statewide program, even though Oklahoma does not have a large
number of child abductions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if there aren't many,'' he said, ``these kinds of cases
stick with you for a while. People here are still talking about the
State Fair murders (two girls disappeared from the fair and have
never been found) and that was in the '70s.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
