<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Tuesday, Nov. 9. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-TRADE (Washington) _ After a long Saturday-night
telephone call with President Jiang Zemin of China, President
Clinton on Monday sent his trade representative and his top
economic adviser to Beijing in an effort to close a deal that would
get China into World Trade Organization in return for a huge
opening of its market. The speed with which Clinton dispatched
Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky and Gene Sperling, who
heads the National Economic Council, and who advised Clinton to
walk away from a huge trade deal with China in April, indicated
that the administration now believes that an agreement is within
reach. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   (Eds., this story could be subsumed by CLINTON-SPEECH, also by
Sanger, which covers a foreign policy speech by the president.)
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-WALL (Berlin) _ Virtually nobody predicted the fall of
the Berlin Wall _ and apparently nobody planned it. As a result,
two German states with divergent ideologies and cultures found
themselves propelled toward union on the panicky reaction of a
border guard who opened the gate at Berlin's Bornholmerstrasse
crossing without an explicit order to do so. Some of the effects of
that precipitation are still evident today. Most fundamentally, a
united Germany is not quite sure of its identity. By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ENVIRON (Austin, Texas) _ Early this summer, with political
pressure mounting on him to address his state's abysmal air
pollution problems, Gov. George W. Bush signed a law he regards as
the gold star of his green resume: a program targeting outdated
industrial plants that are among the heaviest polluters in Texas.
For Bush, who began his business career in the oil fields of West
Texas, the program meant confronting the state's oil, gas and
chemical industries that are among his most generous campaign
contributors. With the new law, Bush now boasts that he is the
first Texas governor ``to ever have brought industry together and
said, `Get into compliance.''' But what he actually did was a
little different. By Jonathan Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-ONLINE (Washington) _ President Clinton participates in
an on-line town meeting early in the evening. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-BUS-DRIVERS (Denver) _ A national shortage of school bus
drivers, caused by the roaring economy and a rise in the school-age
population, is making students wait up to an hour for a ride,
delaying and canceling field trips and athletic events, and forcing
mechanics, transportation supervisors and even some classroom
teachers to get behind the wheel. By Jodi Wilgoren.
</P>
<P>
   NY-TEST-SCORES (New York) - New York City's 8th grade math and
reading tests left parents and teachers perplexed. Even some of the
state's most privileged schools, like those in Scarsdale and
Pelham, performed less than impressively, raising questions about
whether the test was geared to what is actually being taught or to
what should be taught. (With graphic of sample questions.) By
Anemone Hartcollis.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   WEB-ENTERTAINMENT (Los Angeles) _ Regis and Kathie Lee, watch
out. The hosts of a new talk show are none other than the Lord and
Satan themselves. In ``The God &AMP; Devil Show,'' they interview
guests like John Wayne _ one needn't be alive to be a guest on this
show _ and viewers then vote whether to send the guest to heaven or
hell. A growing number of players, from big studios to small
entrepreneurs, are starting to provide entertainment on the Web,
either by delivering existing movies and television shows or by
creating programs specifically for online viewing. By Andrew
Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTHCARE-INSURE (Undated) _ Taking a dramatic step to break
with one of the most onerous features of managed care, United
Health Group, one of the biggest health insurance companies, said
on Monday that it is giving up its veto power over medical decision
making. United said that now doctors, not company people, would
decide when any of its 8.7 million members need hospital or other
treatment. Industry experts said United's policy change would be
followed by other companies as health insurers battle to quell the
backlash against managed care in Congress and the states. By Milt
Freudenheim.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EARLIEST-AMERICANS (Santa Fe, N.M.) _ A growing body of
intriguing evidence is telling a much new story of the peopling of
the Americas. From Alaska to Brazil and southern Chile, artifacts
and skeletons are forcing archaeologists to abandon Bering Straits
migration theory and come to terms with a more complex picture of
earliest American settlement. People may have arrived thousands to
tens of thousands of years sooner, in many waves of migration and
by a number of routes. Their ancestry may not have been only Asian.
Some of the migrations may have originated in Australia or Europe.
(With graphic.) By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
</TEXT>
