<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Tuesday, Nov. 9, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Monday, the temperature soared past 75 degrees in Indianapolis,
breaking a record that had stood for 120 years. Tuesday, gusty
breezes from the southwest will direct the unseasonable warmth
eastward, setting the stage for additional records from the Ohio
Valley to the Middle Atlantic Coast. Some of the warmest air will
occur across the Middle Atlantic coastal plain as the air mass is
further heated by compression upon descending the Appalachian
mountains. Amid abundant sunshine, daytime readings will climb well
into the 70s from Raleigh, N.C., to Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Chilly air will persist across northern New England. Clouds and
spotty light rain or snow showers will form over extreme northern
Maine as a warm front approaches from the southwest. Cooler air
will also arrive across the Northern Plains and upper Mississippi
Valley behind a weak cool front pressing south through the region.
</P>
<P>
   Ample sun and warm conditions will cover an expansive area from
Texas and the southern Plains to the Southeast States. Patches of
cumulus clouds will obscure the sun at times near the southern
Appalachians as the uneven heating of the undulating terrain
encourages ascending currents of moist air.
</P>
<P>
   Windswept rain will buffet the Northwest Coast on Tuesday as
moist Pacific air is lifted by an approaching cold front. Snow will
fall in the Cascades with snow levels lowering to pass level this
evening. California and the remainder of the Southwest will be
mostly sunny and seasonable, though low clouds will cling to
portions of the Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Duluth's Dearth
</P>
<P>
   Duluth, Minn., at the west end of Lake Superior is known for its
long, cold winters. In fact, much of the downtown is connected by
tunnels and enclosed elevated walkways so residents do not need
bundle up to go across the street in the winter. On Monday, the
mercury rose to a record high of 67 degrees, far above the normal
maximum of 40. Duluth has yet to measure its first snowfall of the
season. In a typical year, the first inch would fall by this
weekend. In 1964, the city had no measurable snow until November
24, the latest ever. The warm spell should end on Wednesday, but no
snow is in sight.
</P>
</TEXT>
