<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BCS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BCS' latest tabulations stir emotions
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Bowl Championship Series' ranking has its first big
controversy. Tennessee's 34-14 win over Notre Dame and Virginia
Tech's near-loss to West Virginia on Saturday created the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The once-beaten Volunteers jumped over the undefeated Hokies
into second place in this week's ratings, released Monday. Florida
State (9-0) remained No. 1 by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   The BCS standings are created by using the traditional polls of
the media and of the coaches, computer polls, won-loss record and
strength of schedule. The result is an overall ranking. The top two
teams in the final standings, released Dec. 5, will play in the
Sugar Bowl on Jan. 4 for the mythical national championship.
</P>
<P>
   Although Monday's rankings stirred emotions in Blacksburg, Va.,
and Knoxville, Tenn., chances are the situation will be different
next week if both teams, separated by .33 of a point, win Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee's strength of schedule is rated No. 9, the Hokies' No.
60. But Virginia Tech, which needed a field goal at the buzzer to
get by West Virginia, hosts Miami on Saturday in Blacksburg, and
Tennessee plays at Arkansas. Miami's schedule is rated the
second-toughest in the nation, so a win should improve Virginia
Tech's schedule enough to move the Hokies back ahead of Tennessee
in next week's standings.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech's final two regular-season games are against
Temple and Boston College. Tennessee, the defending national
champion, finishes with Kentucky and Vanderbilt.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is in No. 4 in the new standings, but the Gators have a
great opportunity to move up in the coming weeks. They play South
Carolina on Saturday but finish at home against No. 1 Florida
State. If Florida wins that game and then wins the SEC championship
game against another nationally ranked team, chances are the Gators
could move into one of the top two spots.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State is at No. 5, despite being undefeated. The
Wildcats' strength of schedule is No. 76. Kansas State plays at
Nebraska on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Penn State, ranked No. 2 last week, dropped to No. 7 after its
24-23 loss to Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Barnhart writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
