<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS MARTHA GOES, SO GOES THE MILLENNIUM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been hoping to spend a quiet false millennium eve at home,
but now I'm not so sure if I should, or even if I can. I feel so
inadequate. But more of that in a moment.
</P>
<P>
   It's picky, I know, to call it the false millennium, but I'm
siding with the cranks who say the next millennium doesn't begin
until Jan. 1, 2001. Why? Well, personally, I've never put much
stock in the Synod of Whitby. The whole calendar concept is iffy.
Next year is 5761 by the Hebrew calendar, 4698 by the Chinese.
Think about it.
</P>
<P>
   But let's not dwell on the tiresome debate about when the
millennium begins, because there are bigger fish to fry, or bigger
fish to poach in a carefully prepared court bouillon and to serve
garnished with a spectacular sauce cardinal, or perhaps a simple
hollandaise.
</P>
<P>
   I am, of course, referring to Martha Stewart and her plans to
greet the millennium, real or false. I don't know where Martha
stands on the possibility of a millennial apocalypse, but I do know
that as the year 2000 approaches, she will be entertaining as if
the world were coming to an end. But what else is new?
</P>
<P>
   Recently I purchased a special issue of Martha Stewart
Entertaining, devoted to celebrating the start of the next century.
Martha cannily declines to mention the M-word on the magazine's
cover, but it's clear from its contents she believes the new
millennium will begin on Jan. 1, 2000. She plans to see it in at
home _ at one of her homes, Skylands, the old Edsel Ford estate in
Seal Harbor, Maine _ with friends and family. She suggests that her
readers also stay at home and entertain. Hence the magazine is full
of festive suggestions for greeting the millennium the Martha
Stewart way.
</P>
<P>
   It occurs to me that this may explain why so many hotels,
resorts, and restaurants have been reporting a surprising slacking
off in reservations for New Year's 2000. It may be because they've
jacked up their millennium party prices beyond reason _ but the
reason could also be that Martha has spoken. Stay at home, Martha
has decreed, and ``greet this new millennium in spectacularly
original ways.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as? It exhausts me to even think about it all. Really, I
want to sit down and cry when I consider how ill-prepared I am to
usher in the year 2000 at home, a la Martha. I don't even own one
Champagne flute, let alone a set. And I am shockingly short on
caviar spoons and smoked-salmon knives and Stilton cheese scoops.
But I have only myself to blame.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine doesn't relate exactly what Martha will be doing to
celebrate New Year's Eve 1999. However, she will be greeting the
dawn of the year 2000 on top of Cadillac Mountain in Maine. There,
at 7:04 a.m., the first rays of sunrise will be visible in the
continental United States. Martha being Martha, she organized a
trial run last New Year's Day and had the proceedings photographed
for this magazine. Unfortunately, and vexingly for Martha, the
mountain trail was too icy for her party to negotiate, so they had
to settle for watching the sunrise from a rocky ledge overlooking
Frenchman Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Then it was back to Martha's kitchen at Skylands, which seats 18
comfortably, for a simple six-course country breakfast. I'm not
sure which item on the menu was my favorite. Maybe the grapefruit
mimosas, which were served in translucent candied grapefruit bowls
and garnished with caramelized grapefruit chips. Or perhaps it was
the bruleed Irish oatmeal with apple and pear chips, prunes, maple
syrup, and heavy cream. Not that it matters what I like because,
real or false, it's Martha's millennium. I'd better get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
