<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LATIN-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN LATIN MUSIC KEEP THE HEAT? 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS  
 (Repeating for all needing.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When newly minted teen star Christina Aguilera decided
to record a Spanish-language version of her smash hit ``Genie in a
Bottle,'' she didn't hop a limo to a state-of-the art recording
studio in New York or LA. Instead Aguilera _ who is half Ecuadorean
and grew up outside of Pittsburgh _ traveled to South Florida, to
record at producer Rudy Perez's home studio in Miami Beach.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tiny room, really, just off the swimming pool, with
enough space for a love seat and a few potted plants. Perez's four
sons have the run of the place, and the family dog pokes his nose
in whenever he pleases. The casual ambience, however, is deceiving.
Perez, the son of Cuban immigrants, is a 20-year veteran who has
written and produced music for virtually every major Latin artist,
from Julio Iglesias and Jose Feliciano to Mexican pop star Cristian
and salsa sensation Marc Anthony to up-and-comers Millie and Jaci
Velasquez.
</P>
<P>
   Perez is producing a full-length album for Aguilera. Her reverse
crossover, from English to Spanish, is a sign of just how
entrenched Latin music has become in the US mainstream. Far from a
novelty, the so-called Latin Explosion mirrors an exploding
generation of Latin American music fans _ kids and young adults who
are not just bilingual but thoroughly bicultural. It's a generation
that grew up immersed in pop, rock, and hip-hop, but who also heard
traditional music in their parents' and grandparents' homes. And as
the multitudes of Latin musical styles begin to merge into the US
mainstream, Miami is emerging as the epicenter of Latin music. It's
a city with unique potential, but also one that's suffering from
the problems that accompany tremendous growth. Not least among
them, of course, is the question of whether that growth is going to
continue.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its geographical and cultural proximity to Latin
America, Miami is ground zero for artists, producers, and record
labels. All six major multinational labels _ Sony, EMI, Polygram,
WEA, Universal, and BMG _ have their Latin music headquarters
there; so do publishing titans BMI and ASCAP. LARAS, the newly
established Latin arm of the National Academy of Recording Arts and
Sciences, is based in Miami, busily preparing for the first Latin
Grammy Awards show, to be broadcast next September.
</P>
<P>
   The real action, though, is happening on tony North Bay Road, a
quiet swath of upscale homes that face Biscayne Bay on Miami
Beach's North Shore. The street has become something of an enclave
in the last few years. With the exception of Emilio Estefan _
Gloria's husband and the unofficial godfather of Latin &UR;  &LR; pop music,
whose massive white villa sits on a private residential island just
across the bay _ Latin music's movers and shakers have flocked to
this quiet neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   It's where Perez lives and works. Just up the street is the home
and studio of Kike Santander, who arrived in Miami from Colombia
five years ago, promptly composed an album for Gloria Estefan, and
has gone on to write and produce songs for Thalia, Jon Secada,
Alejandro Fernandez, Carlos Ponce, Los Tri-O, and the young
Argentine folk/pop singer Soledad. A few doors down is Desmond
Child, former rock singer turned hitmaker (he penned ``Dude Looks
Like a Lady'' for Aerosmith, ``You Give Love a Bad Name'' for Bon
Jovi, and songs for Cher, Hanson, Alice Cooper, and Kiss). Child,
who's half-Cuban, returned five years ago to his hometown of Miami,
where he wrote and produced ``Livin' La Vida Loca'' and much of the
rest of Ricky Martin's crossover album. He shuttles back and forth
between home and his studio, a few blocks away, in a gold golf
cart. Conveniently, Martin's digs are just down the road. And
Jennifer Lopez was spotted touring a house for sale, catty-corner
from Perez's, just a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Around here, the question on everyone's mind is: Can Latin music
sustain the incredible trajectory of the last eight months? Such
heavily hyped trends are generally as brief as they are lucrative.
But Latin music's roots stretch much farther and much deeper than
the current chart-topping crossover stars. As cover stories
heralding the latest craze disappear from newsstands, as Ricky
Martin's new single begins to slip on the charts, one wonders if
names like Jennifer Lopez, Marc Anthony, and Enrique Iglesias _ all
of whom are topping the Billboard charts _ will disappear from the
pop radar. Or is Latin music assuming its rightful place in the
mainstream US market?
</P>
<P>
   Despite the boom this year (according to SoundScan, Latin music
sales for the first half of 1999 soared nearly 54 percent over the
same period in 1998), ``the whole Latin market in the US right now
is totally virgin,'' says Perez, an amiable, boyish 40-year-old
whose home office is lined ceiling to floor with gold and platinum
records. ``Even though it's very successful, 90 percent of the
artists are exports _ from Mexico, from Colombia. We haven't begun
to touch the artists who are here. My target will be to go into the
barrios in the Bronx, in South Central LA, and find the kids from
here who have parents who are Latin, but who have the American
culture. That's what we're going to see a lot more of.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez has demographics on his side. Fueled by massive
immigration and high birthrates, the US Latino population has grown
38 percent since 1990, to 31 million. The overall population, by
contrast, has grown just 9 percent. With more than a third of the
Latino population under 18, the boom has just begun. By the year
2005, it's predicted, Latinos will be the largest minority group in
the country, and by 2050, nearly a quarter of the population will
be Latino.
</P>
<P>
   True to his word, Perez has started the ball rolling. He
discovered a talented young singer who goes by the name Lazz
participating in a music program at a Miami high school, and
offered to produce demos for her. Lazz released her debut salsa
album on Warner Brothers International this past June, and is
planning a crossover R &AMP; B release for sometime next year. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Lack of live music &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Lazz, unfortunately, is an exception here. Vibrant as
Miami's cultural and musical landscape is, the city's live music
scene is practically nonexistent. Artists who record here generally
come from somewhere else. Many of South Florida's live music venues
have closed in the last few years. Two nights trolling for music
revealed that most clubs now boast velvet ropes and DJs rather than
bands. Cafe Nostalgia, a small storefront club on Southwest Eighth
Street in Little Havana _ a local hangout for musicians like Ruben
Blades and Bono _ is one of the few left, and it's a gem. This is a
problem that will have to be resolved, says Desmond Child, if Miami
hopes to become an industry hub on a par with Los Angeles, New
York, and Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are coming into record companies already developed from
other regions,'' says Child, who recently established his own
Miami-based label, Destin Records. ``So then it's all corporate.
Everybody's already in their own world, and there's no feeling or
desire to cross-pollinate.''
</P>
<P>
   Infrastructure is a problem, too. There are only half a dozen
world-class recording studios in the area _ barely enough to keep
up with the increasing demand. Miami's music community is also
short on support personnel: managers, marketing executives, and PR
people.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1718EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
