<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3045 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-INDIANS-SKELETON-     11-08 1047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-INDIANS-SKELETON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHAEOLOGY AND ANCESTRY CLASH OVER SKELETON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Wash., N.M., Texas, Ore., Ariz.)   (See also SCI-EARLIEST-AMERICANS)  
 (af)  
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Not all the conflicts in the search for the earliest
Americans center on rival scientists with sharply different
interpretations of the bones and artifacts they are finding.
Emboldened by a 1990 federal law, American Indians have joined the
fight with forceful claims that it is, after all, their past that
all the fuss is over.
</P>
<P>
   The uneasy relationship between archaeologists and the people
they study has erupted into a bitter court battle over the skeleton
of a muscular, middle-aged man who died sometime between 8,000 and
9,300 years ago. His remains were found in 1996 on the banks of the
Columbia River in eastern Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Called Kennewick Man, for the town near the discovery site, the
skeleton is the most complete and among the oldest uncovered in
North America.
</P>
<P>
   The skeleton's discovery and its unusual features have raised
questions about its position as a likely ancestor of modern
American Indians and, if this cannot be established, whether it
must by law be turned over for reburial by Indians in the area.
Eight anthropologists have filed a lawsuit to prevent immediate
reburial of the remains until they can be examined in greater
detail for new evidence bearing on the origins of the people who
first inhabited the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   The court case, expected to be decided sometime next year, could
set a precedent for other Indian claims over archaeological
materials that are based on the Native American Graves Protection
and Repatriation Act, under which relics found on U.S. property are
to be offered to Indian tribes affiliated with them. The question
of affiliation between distantly prehistoric remains and modern
tribes is a central issue.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the skull and bones of Kennewick Man rest under tight
security in a laboratory here at the Burke Museum of Natural
History and Culture on the campus of the University of Washington.
They are the property for the time being of the Army Corps of
Engineers, because they were discovered on land owned by the corps.
No one can take a peek without a court order.
</P>
<P>
   Though locked away, Kennewick Man was the object of scientific
conjecture, legal interpretation and impassioned debate at a
two-day symposium here.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting came days after a group of anthropologists, led by
Dr. Joseph Powell of the University of New Mexico, announced
results of a preliminary analysis of the bones. Confirming earlier
findings, the researchers concluded that Kennewick Man's narrow
face, long head and jutting chin bore little resemblance to an
Indian's typically broad face, high cheekbones and round head. The
examination, they said, reminded them more of South Asians,
Polynesians or the Ainu of Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In light of these results, archaeologists argued more forcefully
that the skeleton was too old to be ``culturally affiliated'' with
modern Indians and so the federal law should not apply. They
expressed doubts that any modern tribes could establish that they
were ``lineal descendants'' of the people represented by Kennewick
Man.
</P>
<P>
   But noting that ``modern human variation may be different from
that seen in the past,'' Powell said at the symposium that people
have probably changed over the last 12,000 years. The early
migrants to America presumably spread over the land in small groups
subject to what is called genetic drift.
</P>
<P>
   Random changes and mutations in small groups become magnified
over time, affecting the way people looked. Only after populations
increased and mingled more closely, it could be argued, did they
develop physical characteristics more like those of modern Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the early people don't look like modern Indians, it's
possible they are ancestral to today's Native Americans,'' Powell
said. ``It's an option that needs to be examined.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking a similar tack, Dr. David J. Meltzer of Southern
Methodist University said it was no surprise that Kennewick Man and
several other prehistoric skeletons did not look like modern
Indians. ``That doesn't mean the two are unrelated,'' he said, ``or
that we have to look elsewhere than Asia for their origins.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Timothy McKeown, an archaeologist with the National Park
Service, explained that the 1990 law did not require that the
relationship of modern tribes to human remains and objects be
proved ``with scientific certainty.'' According to the law, a
``preponderance of evidence'' from oral tradition as well as
geographical, historical and archaeological sources is acceptable
for repatriation of remains to Indian tribes.
</P>
<P>
   At a conference in Santa Fe the next week, a lawyer for the
eight scientists in the lawsuit, Alan Schneider of Portland, Ore.,
argued that legal restrictions on the study of early skeletons
threatened research that seeks to explain who were the first
Americans. ``Science can't proceed if scientists can't get access
to new data,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At the Seattle meeting, Rebecca Tsosie, an American Indian and
executive director of the Indian legal program at Arizona State
University, contended that legal, legislative and treaty precedents
established Indians as ``separate nations, nations within a
nation'' and, in particular, that ``European people do not have a
claim'' on remains that predate the Columbus ``discovery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Western science,'' Ms. Tsosie said, ``gives us a way of
knowing the world, a noble goal, but it's not the only way to
establish something as the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over Kennewick Man has opened old wounds over
how archaeologists and other scientists treated Indians in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they thought Indian people no longer existed, that
they were extinct,'' Adeline Fredin, historian for the Confederated
Tribes of the Colville Reservation, said with a soft, but eloquent
voice. ``Did they ever come to Indian country and say we want to
collect Indian remains? Is that all right? They never did. Did they
ever come to Indian country and say we want to do some cranial
analysis and collect all the Indian heads we can. Did they ask us?
No, they did not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1721EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 17:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3049 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-NYSENATE-NICHOLSON-HN     11-08 0649
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYSENATE-NICHOLSON-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CHAIRMAN TOUTS GIULIANI IN SENATE RACE AGAINST FIRST LADY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories0  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican Chairman Jim Nicholson weighed in on the
budding New York Senate race Monday, praising GOP New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani for making New York City a place that residents
could be proud of.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson also criticized First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton and
predicted that the Senate contest would cost up to $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson said Giuliani's performance during two terms as mayor
of predominantly Democratic New York City demonstrates the fiscal
restraint and anti-crime priorities that Guiliani would bring to
the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Both Giuliani and Clinton have completed legal requirements to
be Senate candidates from New York in 2000 but neither has publicly
declared a candidacy to succeed retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani has ``turned what was often thought of as an
unmanageable metropolis into a place where people take great pride
in living, in owning and in working,'' Nicholson told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has cut the murder rate by 70 percent and the violent
crime rate by 50 percent, as well as reducing welfare rolls by
360,000 and creating more than 300,000 new private sector jobs,
Nicholson boasted.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson credited Giuliani with encouraging major companies to
return to New York City, a one-time ``tax hell, where people
wouldn't look anybody in the eye _ they were that afraid.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson added: ``He's turned that around.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani can ``beat Hillary,'' Nicholson said in response to a
question. ``He's whomping her right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson said Clinton also has paid a price in the polls for
``waffling'' on presidential clemency for imprisoned Puerto Rican
nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   He cited a poll by Zogby International completed on Oct. 18 that
showed Giuliani leading Mrs. Clinton by 11 percentage points _ 51
percent to 40 percent. The survey of 700 likely voters had a margin
of error of 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The result showed Giuliani widening his margin over a comparable
Zogby poll completed on Sept. 9 that showed a statistical dead
heat, with Giuliani leading Clinton 48 percent to 44 percent in a
survey with a margin of error of 3.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson reiterated his earlier criticisms of Clinton's
exploration of a Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Her decision to seek a Senate seat from New York, where she has
never lived nor worked, fuels ``the carpet bag thing'' that shadows
her bid as ``sort of an overarching issue,'' Nicholson said.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson said each candidate would ``have to spend between $20
million and $25 million'' in the premier Senate race of the 2000
election. Nicholson said Clinton's nationwide fund raising for the
first Senate race by a first lady would ``pull money'' away from
the Democratic presidential nominee but not pose ``as big a drain
on us as it is on them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson said the New York Senate race was not a ``must win''
for the GOP, adding: ``I think it's more of a `must win' for the
Democrats because of who she is, the tie between her and Gore and
the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson's reference to the first lady ``waffling'' on clemency
for Puerto Rican nationalists stemmed from the president's offer of
clemency to 16 imprisoned Puerto Rican nationalists on Aug. 11. The
president said he hadn't talked to his wife about the clemency
offer before he announced it.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, after remaining silent for three weeks, later
urged her husband in a public statement on Sept. 4 to cancel the
offer.
</P>
<P>
   All but two of the Puerto Rican nationalists accepted the
president's offer on Sept. 7.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
