<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3052 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-LEARD-COX     11-08 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-LEARD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Concussion can't stop Leard's Georgia dream
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Ben Leard doesn't sound like a player considered
questionable for Saturday's game against Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   The Auburn quarterback said he will play against the 14th-ranked
Bulldogs this weekend if it means driving to Sanford Stadium
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up wanting to play between the hedges, wanting to wear
the silver britches, the whole thing,'' said Leard. ``I never
expected to be in somebody else's uniform when I played there, but
that's just the way it worked out. They're crazy if they think they
can keep me off the field this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Leard missed Saturday's game against Central Florida after being
knocked unconscious in the second quarter of the Arkansas game the
previous week. He was diagnosed with a concussion but practiced all
last week and thought he would be able to play, only to be
scratched in a game-day decision.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn scored 21 points in 1:32 late in the fourth quarter for a
28-10 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fine,'' Leard said Sunday. ``If you ask me, I've been 100
percent ever since I woke up. I understand the doctors are just
looking out for me, but I don't see how they can keep me from
playing this time. . . . I'm going to play this weekend if they
have to wheel me off in a wheelchair.''
</P>
<P>
   Leard has battled injuries not only all season but all his
career. He missed three games after separating his throwing
shoulder in a loss to Mississippi on Sept. 25. In December, he had
surgery to repair two bulging disks in his back. But when he has
been healthy, Leard has been impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Leard had completed 14 of 17 passes for 100 yards when he was
injured against Ole Miss and was 5 of 8 for 41 yards before going
out against Arkansas. For the year, he has completed 61 of 88
passes for 770 yards, six touchdowns and no interceptions. His
pass-efficiency rating of 169.16 would lead the SEC by 27 points,
but he has played in too few games to be ranked.
</P>
<P>
   In Leard's absence, the Auburn offense has been run by another
Georgian. Redshirt freshman Jeff Klein is 85 of 169 passing for
1,038 yards and six touchdowns but has thrown nine interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a better team when (Leard) is in there,'' Auburn coach
Tommy Tuberville said. ``He's got more experience, more maturity.
Jeff's had a chance to get better while Ben's been out, but Ben
knows the offense better and knows what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Either quarterback could have trouble against Georgia. Although
the Bulldogs have proved vulnerable to big plays _ as their 358
yards a game allowed will attest _ they are drawing increasing
respect from opponents for their ability to rush the passer and
force turnovers. Georgia has 3.3 sacks per game, fifth in the SEC,
leads the league with 18 interceptions and is ranked third
nationally in turnover margin, plus-9.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to come after you, and we know that,'' Leard
said. ``I was watching them against Kentucky during our off week,
and they had, like, 11 sacks and six or seven in the first half.
They're playing like the old Junkyard Dogs.''
</P>
<P>
   If not for circumstances beyond his control, Leard might
otherwise be on the Georgia sideline for Saturday's game. At the
time he was being recruited by the Bulldogs, they had just fired
Ray Goff, hired and lost Glen Mason as head coach, brought in a
relatively unknown Division I-AA coach named Jim Donnan and were
facing NCAA probation.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Georgia had a glut of players at quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hines (Ward) was still there, and Mike Bobo, and Mike Usry had
just come in; I think they had six (quarterbacks), including
Hines,'' Leard said. ``And a lot of other things were kind of up in
the air. My visit weekend was coach Donnan's first one on campus.
There was a lot of confusion. It was still a real toss-up between
Auburn and Georgia, but I made what I thought was the best decision
at the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Leard finally will live out his dream of
playing in Sanford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've wanted to play in this game so long; I can't put into
words how much I want to win,'' Leard said. ``It'll be like I'm in
a dream world or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
