<HEADER>
A3059 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-SCHOOL-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      11-08 1616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAXPAYERS IN UPROAR AS GRAND JURY PROBES TEXAS SUPERINTENDENT'S
EXPENSE ACCOUNT 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JAMES PINKERTON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORPUS CHRISTI, Texas _ Huge tabs at topless bars, meals in posh
New York restaurants and sexual predators on the school payroll
have prompted protests and a criminal investigation of practices in
the school district of this quiet, coastal city.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, community attention was largely focused on
academics, and the Corpus Christi Independent School District has
reason to brag because of dramatic improvements in student test
scores. Officials also can point to the quality of the district's
teachers, such as last month's selection of Mary Beth
Castillo-Tierce as the Texas Elementary School Teacher of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, Corpus Christi residents are mostly talking
about the grand jury investigation into the free-spending habits of
Superintendent Abelardo Saavedra, his staff and several members of
the board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   The questionable expenditures came to light when the local
newspaper, the Corpus Christi Caller-Times, reviewed the district's
American Express accounts from August 1993 to June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Saavedra, a $171,000-a-year administrator with a $7,200 annual
car allowance, has claimed $15,402 in additional reimbursement for
gasoline purchases, car washes, detailing and mechanical repairs to
his vehicle, according to the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Saavedra also charged taxpayers more than $15,000 for 144 meals
with district board members, and another $5,149 for meals with
staff members, including a $500 dinner at the posh
Tavern-on-the-Green in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   A top Saavedra aide _ who has since left _ charged $5,200 in bar
tabs at topless clubs on his district-issued credit card, and two
board members bought tickets to a Tony Bennett concert in San
Francisco plus airline fares for their spouses on district cards.
Those expenses were repaid.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent insists that there was no intent to break the
law, but claims that a concerted effort is under way to destroy his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I made mistakes in reference to judgment or whatever,
obviously they need to be corrected,'' said Saavedra, who has
canceled the district's credit card accounts. ``If there needs to
be consequences, that's fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the attacks have been so vicious and so personal that I
kind of feel the aim is to destroy people, not just
accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, Nueces County District Attorney Carlos Valdez and
grand jury members began sifting through voluminous school district
financial records turned over under subpoena. It is the second
grand jury investigation of the district this year, following an
inquiry this spring into nine district employees who had been
charged with molesting students during Saavedra's six-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The investigation is being conducted to make sure that all
financial matters involving the school district have been proper
and above-board,'' said Valdez, who declined to identify targets of
the investigation or what transactions are being questioned.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the grand jury criticized the district for failing to
screen sexual predators applying for school positions, and for not
promptly notifying police when teachers, coaches and other district
employees were discovered having sexual relationships with
students.
</P>
<P>
   While the grand jury investigation into sexual misconduct is
over, the troubling relationships between students and school staff
are not. But Valdez said Saavedra's staff is now acting much more
quickly in reporting them to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the district fired a Carroll High School
assistant football coach, Mark Marsh, &UR;  &LR; 25, &UR;  &LR; shortly after it was
reported he had a sexual relationship with a 17-year-old female
student. It was the same campus where assistant football coach and
health teacher Jason Murphy, 30, was prosecuted for having sex 28
times with a 16-year-old female student in February and March.
</P>
<P>
   Valdez said it may be weeks or months before it can be
determined if any laws were broken by the questionable
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a number of residents believe that Saavedra has
already earned a pink slip regardless of the outcome of the
criminal inquiry. But many residents have rallied around the
district's first Hispanic superintendent, and some claim that
racism by several Anglo board members is responsible for the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately he was the boss, even though there was no financial
policy (concerning expenses) in place, he had a responsibility to
see to it that there was one _ that's what everyone's
saying,'' &UR;  &LR; said one local judge, who asked not to be
identified. &UR;  &LR; ``That's the basic reason we've got problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe O'Brien, president of 1,750-member Corpus Christi Taxpayer's
Association, said his group is considering filing suit to remove
Saavedra if he is not fired by the board.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a group trying to turn it into a political, ethnic
thing, but that has nothing whatsoever to do with it,'' said
O'Brien. ``It's a question of honesty. The man has violated his
contract. His contract requires him to obey all the laws, which he
hasn't done.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien noted many taxpayers were upset by the hefty $37,000
raise voted in April, boosting Saavedra's salary from $134,000 to
$171,000. The raise was part of a package of increased benefits
that O'Brien said total $82,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since we started looking into the situation and finding out
his extravagant tabs up in New York, $500 meals and living pretty
high on the hog, it just completely outraged the people,'' O'Brien
said.
</P>
<P>
   Saavedra, a product of the Corpus Christi school system, said he
has no intention of resigning, at least until he clears his name.
And with three years and eight months left on his new contract, a
buyout could cost the district $900,000, the school district
attorney has calculated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're going to find criminal wrongdoing, but
who knows?'' Saavedra said of the grand jury's inquiry. ``What
they're going to find is a system of very poor controls when it
came to that credit card and some of the board travel.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; But the superintendent insists that he has been made a
scapegoat by warring factions of a deeply divided school board, and
he notes that criticism is coming from the very board members he
entertained.
</P>
<P>
   ``My God, how do you condemn someone when you sat across the
table with me?'' Saavedra asked.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the board held a public meeting to decide if
Saavedra would be fired. It delayed a decision until the Texas
Education Agency concludes an audit of district expenditures in a
few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The emotionally charged meeting lasted until midnight and 71
residents stepped up to speak. Many of Saavedra's supporters
charged that racism was behind the move to fire him.
</P>
<P>
   A group of mostly Anglo protesters brandished placards demanding
Saavedra's resignation, while the board room was packed with
members of Hispanic service groups who supported him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Saavedra is the target of racism by certain members of the
board of CCISD,'' insisted Mary Helen Salazar, president of the
local chapter of the League of United Latin American Citizens.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was referring to ``the ladies,'' three Anglo women
who have been at odds with the four male board members, three of
whom are Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   A major battle erupted when the four men voted to boost
Saavedra's pay to $171,000, and the women opposed it. And it was
the three women who put the request to end Saavedra's tenure on the
agenda.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, many community leaders urged the board to wait
until all the facts were in and pointed to improvements they said
were made during Saavedra's tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can see our system is working. If it ain't broke, don't fix
it,'' advised attorney Ruben Bonilla Jr.
</P>
<P>
   Bonilla held up charts indicating that district students are
leading the state in passing the writing, mathematics and reading
portions of the TAAS test. Bonilla said that when Saavedra became
superintendent, only 51 percent of the students passed the
statewide test compared with the 77 percent who passed in 1998.
Today, he said, 30 of the district's 60 schools are rated as either
recognized or exemplary.
</P>
<P>
   Outside grants to the district, which amounted to $700,000 when
Saavedra became superintendent, now exceed $20 million, Bonilla
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've listened a long time to the admiration society,''
countered resident Louis Loveless, who carried an anti-Saavedra
placard. ``Dr. Saavedra, you had it well-organized. (But) If this
district is so great as Mr. Bonilla and others claim, how come Del
Mar (Community) College has so many remedial courses?
</P>
<P>
   ``You heard the teachers say they had spent their own money on
supplies, while you live lavishly on credit cards.''
</P>
<P>
   At the close of the meeting, trustee Frank Reyes said the board,
during a closed-door session, had ``pledged to work together.''
</P>
<P>
   However, few residents have any illusions about the divisive
times ahead, given the bad blood between Saavedra and several
members of the board and the public relations fiasco the expense
account revelations have caused.
</P>
<P>
   Valdez, the district attorney, predicted that the grand jury
examination, while painful, will help restore public confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think eventually everything is going to be better, because
if there are some weaknesses in the system they will be exposed and
remedied,'' Valdez said. ``While we're going through it, it won't
be good for the community, but in the end it will be better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
