<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3062 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-BOOK-NEW-PROFILE-HNS &LR;      11-08 1083
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NEW-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR DETAILS SILICON VALLEY MOGUL'S `NEW NEW THING' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRAD WIENERS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERKELEY, Calif. _ On a recent Friday evening, author Michael
Lewis gave a talk in the library of UC-Berkeley's Northgate Hall
about his much-hyped book, ``The New New Thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, who is a visiting fellow at Cal's graduate school of
journalism, and who, in 1993, penned one of the most passed-along
slams of graduate programs in journalism (``J-School Ate My
Brain''), sat comfortably in the middle of this seeming
contradiction and explained why he choose to focus his chronicle of
Silicon Valley on another contradictory figure, serial entrepreneur
Jim Clark.
</P>
<P>
   For ``The New New Thing,'' Lewis knew he had his man the day he
looked Clark up in the phone book, got him on the line, talked
himself into a drop-in visit and followed the instructions Clark
had given to an office in a strip mall, perched above a Jenny Craig
fitness center.
</P>
<P>
   Certain there'd been some mistake, he was astonished when the
billionaire answered the door. Peering into the gloom, where
several programmers toiled at computers, he took his book-launching
mental snapshot and wondered: What was this New Economic Force
doing in there?
</P>
<P>
   Deciding to build his book around the founder of Silicon
Graphics, Netscape, Healtheon and, most recently, myCFO.com, it
must be said, took guts.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: Clark's story has been told and told some more.
Indeed, you'd have to have had your head in a bucket for going on
seven years not to have read something about Clark.
</P>
<P>
   And your bucket would have to be a lead pail if you hadn't read
the part where Clark discovered an undergrad named Marc Andreessen
at the University of Illinois and convinced him to form a business
around this nifty piece of software he and his friends had created.
This ``browser'' software soon became Netscape Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   To his credit, Lewis discovers much about Clark that hasn't been
reported. (A trip to Clark's pitiful hometown of Plainview, Texas,
is especially affecting.) But he also overstates Clark's role in
all things Dot Com as if to justify writing about him one more
time.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there are stretches of ``The New New Thing'' where you'd
think Silicon Valley really should be renamed ClarkWorld (Lewis'
coinage), and that Clark didn't just popularize the World Wide Web,
but invented it. (This is far from true, and if you're really
interested in the origins of the Web, pick up Tim Berners-Lee's
``Weaving the Web'' instead.)
</P>
<P>
   The new new thing Clark did accomplish was to take Netscape
public before the company had turned a profit. This may well be
Clark's most enduring innovation. It is certainly his most
influential one, and one that Michael Milken probably wishes he
thought up.
</P>
<P>
   On this, Lewis is justified in his assertion that after
Netscape, ``the most appealing companies became those in a state of
pure possibility. Which is to say that the U.S. capital markets
acquired the personal predilections of Jim Clark.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Lewis reflects, ``The Internet formula for success turned
traditional capitalism on its head. Traditionally, a company
persuaded people to invest in it by making profits. Now it
persuaded people to invest in it first, and hoped profits would
follow.''
</P>
<P>
   This is as precise a definition of the ``new economy'' as you
could ask for _ outside, perhaps, MIT economist Paul Krugman's
observation that technology has been the big story in economics
since the 1950s, but is also ``invoked as an explanation of
whatever we can't explain in other ways.''
</P>
<P>
   So why did Lewis take Netscape public when he did? Well, he
needed the cash. (As one engineer who has worked for Clark at three
of his companies tells Lewis, ``Jim Clark has a purity of vision
that is prompted by the purest form of greed. Nothing clouds it.'')
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Clark needed the dough for his state-of-the-art,
computer-operated sailboat, Hyperion, a ready-made metaphor that
nearly capsizes ``The New New Thing'' and does cause Lewis to miss
his point.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it's perfectly understandable Lewis would jump aboard the
Hyperion. In fact, his time at sea (Clark invites him along for a
trans-Atlantic passage) provides the book's best material: dinner-
party-length anecdotes that are masterful, often hilarious, and may
redeem the book for some readers.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, Lewis' time aboard the Hyperion encourages him
to cast The New New Thing as an adventure story. But that story
line is not Clark's, but Lewis'.
</P>
<P>
   That is, the adventure story here is the daring journalist
tracking his quarry. Clark himself is fairly bored with the
adventures Lewis details, and his exploits, finally, add up to
armchair adventure, but old-fashioned tale of revenge.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, each of Clark's most recent new new things
follows the not-in-any-respect new entrepreneurial convention of
founding a company to solve a circumstance the entrepreneur finds
aggravating.
</P>
<P>
   Clark came up with Healtheon (an Internet company that seeks to
eliminate all the wasteful paperwork in the health care industry),
after a stay in the hospital. He announced myCFO.com (a Web-based
service to run all of one's personal finances) when he realized
accountants were running too much of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, he started these firms to avenge the bureaucrats and
money-minders who waste his time _ by using the Internet to put
them out of a job.
</P>
<P>
   But these are merely two examples of Clark's penchant for
revenge. To read ``The New New Thing'' is to encounter a man
straight out of Ayn Rand who has done the most good by being
selfish, stubborn, bold.
</P>
<P>
   He is the poor kid who makes a ton of money to show the world he
cannot be denied. He is the crapped-upon Navy recruit who ends up
schooling others in math.
</P>
<P>
   He is the incredibly talented engineer who now gets a pound of
flesh from the financiers who wrested control of his first company
away from him. He is the business titan who proves that the venture
capitalists everyone thinks are so powerful are really just
squirrels after his nuts.
</P>
<P>
   And this is the contradiction that defines Jim Clark: He is
someone who, as Lewis strains to prove, only cares about the
future, but who is steadfastly motivated by what's befallen him in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   Clark wasn't just programming a sailboat in that office above
Jenny Craig; he was plotting his revenge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
