<HEADER>
A3063 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-HKN-VISORS-COX     11-08 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-VISORS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Players split over NHL visor issueBy Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ray Ferraro has worn a plastic eye shield throughout
his 16-year NHL career. But don't count him among those in favor of
making visors mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the worst thing hockey could do,'' the Atlanta
Thrashers' 35-year-old center said. ``Respect for each other
already has broken down in the NHL, and part of the reason is that
players have no fear anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't control their sticks,'' Ferraro said, ``and its
because they grown up thinking they are invincible. Hockey can be a
dangerous game. You need to learn to play it right. With shields
and other things, players don't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Visors are required now in Canadian junior hockey and full face
cages in United States college hockey. But most players disgard the
seemingly essential protection when they turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the possibility of losing an eye because of a flying
puck or high stick, only about 15 percent of NHL players wear
visors The only Thrashers who do are Ferraro and rookie Patrik
Stefan.
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro began wearing a shield after he was cut twice _ once
below the eye and once above _ by a stick during his last season of
junior hockey, which then did not require visors.
</P>
<P>
   When he was drafted by the Hartford Whalers, Ferraro decided to
keep the shield, risking being labeled soft by veteran NHL players
who were then just getting used to having to wear helmets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Helmets should be mandatory,'' Ferraro said. ``But I think it
should be a personal choice on visors. If you have an eye injury,
of course you should wear one. But (visors) aren't for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Players say shields are hot and sometimes obstruct vision. But
it mainly remains a macho thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fighters just don't wear shields,'' Thrashers enforcer Matt
Johnson said. ``That's just the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitting someone with a shield on really messes up your
hands,'' feisty Denny Lambert said. ``Sounds stupid, but in
juniors, players take off their helmets before they start
punching.''
</P>
<P>
   ``European players are more likely to wear eye shields than
North Americans. The top four scorers in the NHL last season _
Jaromire Jagr, Teemu Selanne, Paul Kariya and Peter Forsberg _ all
wore visors. All but Kariya are European.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always wore one and didn't see why I should take it off,''
said Stefan, a Czech who was the No. 1 overall pick in the NHL
entry draft in June. ``No one (on the ice) has said anything to me
about wearing it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Czechs who were with the Thrashers early in the season wore
eye shields, but that didn't keep Vladimir Vujtek from suffering a
serious cut on the side of the face when struck by a skate during
an exhibition game.
</P>
<P>
   An eye shield would have prevented an injury to Vancouver
defenseman Mattias Ohlund, who suffered a bruised right eyeball
when struck by a puck during a preseason game. He still is
experiencing blurred vision and isn't expected to be ready to play
until January.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, New York Islanders prospect Jeff Libby lost an eye
when slashed by a skate. The minor-leaguer who caused the injury
lost most of the vision in an eye later in the season when hit by a
stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying it's smart not to wear (a visor),''
Philadelphia's Eric Lindros said last season. ``We're all stupid
for not wearing them.''
</P>
<P>
   But players still resist. Atlanta defenseman Gord Murphy had to
wear a shield briefly last season after breaking his nose while
with Florida, but he discarded it as soon as he could. Lambert
suffered a 30-stitch cut between his eyes while in the minors and
wore a visor only a minimum amount of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the puck and sticks, it is unbelievable how few times you
are hit in the face,'' Thrashers coach Curt Fraser said. ``I didn't
even lose a tooth.''
</P>
<P>
   But Fraser did suffer a broken eye orbit and cheekbone while
playing for Chicago in the mid-1980s. He wore a guard for only two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wasn't right for a player like me to wear one,'' said
Fraser, a noted fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser says players should be concerned about their eyes. But
like Ferraro, he is not in favor of universal visors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stick work used to be under control,'' Fraser said. ``Now you
have broken wrists, fingers, everything. Players don't fear
retaliation. That's the problem I have with face masks. Some
players act a lot tougher than they really are with them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way that the NHL will require visors is if someone
loses an eye,'' Thrashers captain Kelly Buchberger said. ``This is
a business and money talks. It will be a liability question. I hope
that never happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Guy Curtright writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
