<HEADER>
A3068 &Cx1f; ttg-z
u a BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN     11-08 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AOL MESSENGER ALLOWS INTERNET TALK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By LONNIE BROWN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Instant Messenger on America Online allows users to type
messages to one another while on the AOL network. Using America
Online Instant Messenger, users who aren't on the AOL network can
send instant messages, too.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, AOL introduced a beta version of the AIM program: AIM
3.5. It is also known as AIM Talk. Using a microphone and headset,
users can talk back and forth just as they would if they were on
the telephone. The sounds won't be ``pin-drop clear,'' but not much
is lost in the Internet imitator of the telephone. Then again,
``Watson, come here, I need you'' sounded pretty scratchy in the
early days, too. Things will improve.
</P>
<P>
   A new ``talk'' box on this version allows users to control
volume. It also can send images, much in the same way that files
can be attached to e-mail. The image, however, opens automatically
on the other end.
</P>
<P>
   An AOL spokeswoman said the product is only in the beta stage
and _ depending on what problems are encountered and how the users
accept it _ may or may not wind up being an AOL offering in final
form. (Beta is the version of the program that has passed in-house
testing but hasn't been subjected to enough testing for final
distribution.)
</P>
<P>
   But if AOL doesn't offer it, it may not be long before it pops
up somewhere else in the competitive online world.
</P>
<P>
   The AOL Talk beta site has been closed because the company
already has enough participants in the beta-testing program.
</P>
<P>
   Saitek Offers New Gamepad
</P>
<P>
   Saitek Corp. is mainly noted for its electronic chess games.
It's the company that produces Chess Academy, a stand-alone unit
that offers more than 10 hours of oral instructions on chess rules,
openings and strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The company also makes computer game controllers, too. The
latest offering is the P120 Action Pad, a gameport device for
Windows-based computers. It's pretty simple in its operation. And
while there has been some criticism because it doesn't have bells
and whistles, it also doesn't have the price tag that comes with
them. The P120 costs about $10 or less.
</P>
<P>
   It is shaped like a bat (the kind that hangs from cave ceilings,
not the kind used in baseball) with a small pad that gives
eight-way direction on the pad's left face and four buttons on the
right face. Two trigger buttons are underneath, so the index
fingers fit comfortably over them when the pad is gripped.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-way pad has a place in its center to attach a
mini-joystick. The stick, about an inch or so high, can be stowed
in a small compartment in the controller's base.
</P>
<P>
   The game pad is easy enough to set up and calibrate and the
controls are adequate for many of the popular games on the market.
The little joystick lacks the grip found in a full-size one, but
then again, the $10-or-less price tag should provide some
forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   There are no drivers for the device (so it must be programmed
through the Windows' gameport interface), but some are available
for downloading from the Saitek site (www.saitek.com) that allow
better operation of trigger controls.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the current sophisticated games require more buttons
than the P120 has available, but playing many point-and-shoot
games, football sims and other sports games not requiring
fighter-pilot controls, the P120 delivers a product with a bargain
price.
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is associate editor of The Ledger in Lakeland,
Fla., which is part of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
He can be reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol. com.)
</P>
