<HEADER>
A3072 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-NINERS-RATTO-HNS &LR;      11-08 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-RATTO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAST ONE OUT, TURN OFF THE LIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As the final seconds of Sunday's 49ers-Steelers
game evaporated into nothingness, one couldn't help but notice that
the 49ers and their fans had done so as well.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only people left in 3WinsInNovember Park were
Pittsburgh fans, roaring their love in the rain as their heroes
completed their unanaesthetized dissection of the locals, 27-6.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if this was Three Rivers Stadium, and the 49ers were
slinking off as humiliated visitors.
</P>
<P>
   And suddenly, it all came clear. Even the Faux Faithful have
given up the ghost. They see only the hopelessness that comes with
a team utterly bereft of ideas _ losing without an inkling of why,
or how to make it stop.
</P>
<P>
   Most amazingly, they're not far wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just sitting there at the end wondering, `How did it come
to this?''' linebacker Ken Norton said, genuinely bewildered by the
state of the team with which he had once won a Super Bowl. ``I
wonder, `How did we not see what's been going wrong?'''
</P>
<P>
   These are all good questions, but what makes them real brain
bubblers is that there are no answers. There is no secret plan that
coach Steve Mariucci hasn't tried, no stash of talented players to
magically appear and replace the ones who have generated this
four-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not just a losing streak. It's a losing streak in which
three of the four losses have been by at least three touchdowns.
It's a losing streak in which the offense has scored twice. It's a
losing streak that has shown that quarterback Jeff Garcia is not
the surprise entry in the Kurt-Warner-Came-From-Nowhere
Sweepstakes.
</P>
<P>
   It's a losing streak that, were it not for New Orleans, Atlanta
and Cincinnati, might have taken them into the next century. And it
isn't smart to make any assumptions about the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci plainly is running on E, idea-wise. He had Wade Richey
try a 50-yard field goal in miserable weather when he might not do
it on a nice day. He replaced Garcia with Steve Stenstrom with the
score 20-6 ``because we hoped Steve might give us a spark.''
</P>
<P>
   He saw them combine to complete only 36 percent of their passes,
which hasn't happened to the 49ers since B.B. (Before Bill). He got
166 yards rushing from Charlie Garner, but couldn't use any of it
to create an actual score. He couldn't even hide his bald spot,
which until now had been the best-kept secret in the entire
organization.
</P>
<P>
   But never mind that. Here's your highlight for eternity from
this one: Stenstrom gained more yards receiving than Jerry Rice.
</P>
<P>
   Hope? What's to hope for here? The 49ers don't even have the
specter of their glorious past to scare teams with any longer.
</P>
<P>
   Their reputation is now of a team that cannot throw the football
with any reliability, which was the one thing they could cling to
when the running game was wheezing, when the cornerbacks were being
outjumped by tight ends, when the league's contenders were whizzing
past them without even so much as an obscene salute.
</P>
<P>
   They look, well, hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``No we're not, we're not,'' said safety and chief public
agonizer Tim McDonald. ``We just have to get back and take care of
the things we need to take care of. We have to work harder. We
won't let this become a habit.''
</P>
<P>
   They look, well, lifeless, and surely clueless.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we practiced well this week,'' Mariucci said, looking like
he couldn't decide whether to cry or drop into the fetal position.
``I don't know ... we work hard, we practice well, we meet well,
but that's not enough. We have to find a way to make it happen on
Sundays.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Practice well?`` ``Meet well?''
</P>
<P>
   Jumping anacondas, has it really come to this? Did the
winningest team of the last two decades turn into a Geico Insurance
outlet when we weren't looking?
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe so. Garner's performance, the one shiny spot in what
was mostly an indistinct mud bog, had all the feel of one of those
Paul Hofer games in the mid-'70s, when the hardscrabble little
fullback would play his heart down to the ventricles while the team
was getting dog-whipped by the Lions or Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, for all the we-gotta-do-better platitudes the
players issued from their league-issue laminated card of Things To
Say When You Have Nothing Else, the 49ers really don't have any
sparkling new concepts to offer. They have no more idea of how to
turn the barge back from the falls than the most drunken schmo
trying to find his car in the parking lot at 10:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci doesn't know, because he's already tried all the
players he's got. Norton and McDonald don't know, because it's been
years since either of them knew this feeling, and they were young
enough then to think they would have plenty of time to win. The
young players don't know, because they have no links to the glory
days.
</P>
<P>
   All they know now is, they lost ... no, they surrendered their
home park to about 4,000 Steeler fans Sunday. Hope? Unless you know
something the rest of us don't, why bother?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
