   FBC-STREETER _ Clemson quarterback Brandon Streeter was thought
to be out for season after breaking a collarbone Oct. 2 vs. North
Carolina. But he returned last week against Duke to pass for 279
yards and two touchdowns. (Clemons, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
14.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-LEARD _ Update on Auburn quarterback Ben Leard, a native of
Hartwell, Ga., who has overcome injury and two coaching changes and
is now poised to start against the Bulldogs, whom he grew up
dreaming of playing for. (Towers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
16.
</P>
<P>
   HOCKEY
</P>
<P>
   HKN-VISORS _ In a game with flying pucks and swinging sticks,
why don't more NHL players wear visors? The answer is macho pride.
Players don't want to appear weak or afraid. Only about 15 percent
of NHL players wear eye protection, although all had to in college
or junior hockey. The percentage with the Thrashers is even less.
Two major exceptions are veteran Ray Ferraro and rookie Patrik
Stefan. (Curtright, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-ATLANTABID _ ATLANTA _ IOC spokesman who made news around
the world a couple of months ago claiming that Atlanta bidders
``pushed'' favors on IOC members eats his words. Franklin
Servan-Shrieber says in an interview in Atlanta that IOC members
didn't ask for gifts and travels and Atlanta bidders were insistent
with their offers, but their intent was not to bribe. They were
operating in the environment at the time. And he hopes the reforms
voted on in December will bring closure to the whole ugly mess. IOC
survey shows public not discouraged by scandal and still holds
Olympics in high regard. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
