<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3096 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MUSIC-LITHGOW-REVIEW-     11-08 0261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-LITHGOW-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN LITHGOW SINGS _ AND DRAWS MORE THAN A CROWD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NANCY HEWITT 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTWOOD _There was no dancing in the aisles. No screaming and
swooning. After all, this wasn't a rock star strolling onto Royce
Hall's prestigious stage. This was a film and television star who
thought he could sing and dance.
</P>
<P>
   He was right.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a white dinner jacket, black trousers, a mauve lapel
flower, suspenders and red patent leather shoes, John Lithgow
looked most debonair during Sunday's performance at the concert
hall on UCLA's campus.
</P>
<P>
   When he and the orchestra launched into ``Everybody Eats When
They Come to My House,'' from his debut children's album, the crowd
went wild.
</P>
<P>
   This set the pace for the approximately hourlong program
featuring another dozen songs and Lithgow's recitation of the
original poem ``The Remarkable Farkle McBride.''
</P>
<P>
   Lithgow has an easy rapport with his audience, kids and adults
alike. And not only does he sing, he also draws _ and draws well _
to help illustrate some of this songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love to come to Royce Hall,'' he remarked. ``It is my second
favorite place to sing in the whole wide world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And what is my favorite place to sing?'' he asked the
audience. ``The bathtub!''
</P>
<P>
   Great introduction to the title track on his CD, ``Singin' in
the Bathtub.''
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the song everyone most enjoyed was ``I Had a
Rooster,'' with Lithgow's funny and appealing animal impressions. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1759EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
