<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN _ ORLANDO _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush makes
another unopposed campaign swing through the Sunshine State with
stops in Jacksonville and Orlando, pockets $2 million and heads
back to Texas. (Crowley, Palm Beach Post). 15.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-FOREIGN _ When Texas Gov. George W. Bush went head first
into a name-the-foreign-presidents trap door rigged by a Boston TV
reporter, he revealed the weakness of any governor with the
audacity to believe he is qualified for the White House. Governors,
by job description, don't dabble much in foreign policy. It's a
hole in the resume that hasn't stopped Americans from looking to
governors for three (Jimmy Carter, Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton)
of the last four Leaders of the Free World. (Herman, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-POLITICS _ WASHINGTON _ FreedomChannel.com is launched
Monday as a free Internet site that will allow candidates and
groups to put 90-second ads on the Internet. (Glass, Cox News
Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY _ An Emory health care expert who stirred controversy by
charging that Bill Bradley's health care plan would cost $1.2
trillion revised his estimate downward Monday. But only slightly.
Ken Thorpe says Bradley's plan for near-universal health care
coverage would cost about $1.05 trillion. And he says Bradley's
plan would insure only 89 percent of Americans, not the 95 percent
Bradley claims. In Chicago, Bradley touted his program to public
health professionals and proposed spending an addional $1 billion
on Atlanta's Centers for Desease Control for prevention programs.
(Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MILCRASH-DOD _ The Department of Defense, we're told, is
preparing a directive raising the $16 an hour repair estimate used
to estimate the cost of military aviation accidents. As we reported
in our series, the estimates are used to determine whether an
incident qualifies as a Class A accident, the type most closely
scrutinized by Congress. Safety officials acknowledged in the
series that the $16 estimate is unrealistic but said they were just
following orders from DoD. The new directive has been in the works
for some time, according to Defense Department officials. (Carollo,
Dayton Daily News). 12-14.
</P>
<P>
   NC-SCHOOLS _ North Carolina classrooms are more focused, or more
stressful, than those in Georgia _ depending on how you want to
view the state's system of measuring test scores. Teachers can win
up to $1,500 each for improving test scores in one year (which
gives all schools a shot), or be subject to a year of help from a
state team. Barnes is touting the NC model for Georgia, but can we
avoid its costs and stresses. (Cumming, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DELL _ Dell Computer Corp. today announced plans to bring a
second manufacturing operation and 650 more jobs to Tennessee. The
new plant will go in Nashville beside a 300,000-square-foot Dell
office building already under construction near the city's airport.
A 200,000-square-foot service center, which was previously
announced, also is planned for the Nashville campus. (Mahoney,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   OLY-ATLANTABID _ ATLANTA _ IOC spokesman who made news around
the world a couple of months ago claiming that Atlanta bidders
``pushed'' favors on IOC members eats his words. Franklin
Servan-Shrieber says in an interview in Atlanta that IOC members
didn't ask for gifts and travels and Atlanta bidders were insistent
with their offers, but their intent was not to bribe. They were
operating in the environment at the time. And he hopes the reforms
voted on in December will bring closure to the whole ugly mess. IOC
survey shows public not discouraged by scandal and still holds
Olympics in high regard. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Will move in (s) Sports and (a) General News categories.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   BIRTHS _ WASHINGTON _ More than half the first babies born in
the United States from 1990-94 were conceived out of wedlock, the
Census Bureau reported Monday. The rate has tripled since the
1930s, it said. (Hill, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 16.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-DIVIDE _ WASHINGTON - A national initiative is being
launched to narrow the ``digital divide'' separating black and
Hispanic children from whites and Asian-Americans. At a press
conference, General Colin Powell, Education Secretary Richard Riley
and AOL CEO Steve Case will announce a plan to get businesses
working with non-profit groups to help all children gain access to
the Internet. (Geewax, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
