<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 18:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3100 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-BRADLEY09-COX     11-08 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Health care questions creating divide between candidates
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ The fault line between Vice President Al Gore and
presidential rival Bill Bradley over health care reform widened
Monday as each sought to undercut the other on a crucial issue for
Democratic voters.
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, Bradley told a meeting of public health
professionals that Gore abandoned health care reform after the
Clinton administration lost a fight for universal care in 1994.
Bradley criticized Gore while outlining a proposal to invest $2
billion in public health, including a $1 billion infusion to the
Centers for Disease Control in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Gore appeared at a pharmacy to propose new laws
that would make cheaper, generic drugs more readily available to
consumers. Gore's campaign also trumpeted a new study by an Emory
University expert that found Bradley's proposal for near-universal
health care insurance would be more expensive than he claimed.
</P>
<P>
   The problem of what to do about the nation's 46 million
uninsured has become the primary point of friction between the two
Democrats since their first town hall meeting nearly two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The ex-New Jersey senator largely dismissed Gore's criticisms of
his health care plan as partisan snipping, but on Monday Bradley
shifted tactics and went on the offensive. He accused Gore of
falling victim to the ``Beltway perspective . . . that (says) if
you try something once and fail, move on to another issue that
polls better or is safer to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley even used some of Gore's rhetoric against him. When the
candidates appeared together in Iowa last month, Gore accused
Bradley of abandoning the Democratic Party and refusing to ``stay
and fight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of health care, Al Gore decided it wasn't worth
standing and fighting,'' Bradley told members of the American
Public Health Association. ``He abandoned that fundamental
Democratic principle of basic health care for all.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he added, ``The lesson Al Gore learned from the health
care defeat was that big, bold things can't get done in Washington,
so let's look to the small, symbolic things.''
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, Gore issued a statement accusing Bradley of
offering a ``flawed trillion dollar plan that will cost the
American people even more in the long run.'' Gore renewed his
challenge to debate Bradley, ending with, ``How about it, Bill?''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign found fresh ammunition to attack Bradley's
proposal to cover uninsured Americans by subsidizing their premiums
in the private network of insurers covering federal workers.
</P>
<P>
   Emory public health specialist Ken Thorpe, who two weeks ago
estimated that Bradley's proposal would cost $1.2 trillion over 10
years, on Monday downgraded his estimate to $1.06 trillion, taking
into account offsets suggested by the Bradley campaign. He
estimated Bradley's plan would cost $78.9 billion in the first
year, as compared to Bradley's own estimate of $55-$65 billion.
Altogether, Thorpe estimated Bradley's plan would provide health
insurance to 15 million new uninsured and cover 89 percent of
Americans. Gore's plan, at an estimated cost of $312 billion over
10 years, would insure 12.1 new Americans and cover 88 percent of
the population, Thorpe said. Bradley's campaign said Thorpe was
biased because he was a health care adviser to the Clinton-Gore
administration from 1993 to 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken Thorpe has never been the authority on health care,'' said
Kristan Ludecke, Bradley's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
