<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECUADOR-VOLCANO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECUADOREAN RESORT RESEMBLES GHOST TOWN AS VOLCANO RUMBLES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: A tilde is needed over n in Banos) 
 
By JOHN OTIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANOS, Ecuador _ The threat of a deadly eruption from nearby
Tungurahua volcano has turned one of Ecuador's most lively tourist
resorts into an eerie no man's land.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing disaster, the government last month ordered the
evacuation of Banos, a town of 18,000 nestled at the foot of
Tungurahua. Famous for its hot springs, Banos is also the jumping
off point for hiking, rafting and bicycle tours.
</P>
<P>
   But during a recent visit, hotels, restaurants and houses stood
padlocked. To protect their homes from lava, residents blocked one
street with sandbags. Officials even drained the town's thermal
baths. And about the only sounds came from abandoned dogs and cats
prowling the deserted neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just us and the ghosts,'' said Elias Murguizu, a Spanish
priest and one of a handful of people allowed to stay behind. ``We
have our cars ready to go in case of an emergency.``
</P>
<P>
   Active for centuries, the 16,278-foot Tungurahua began rumbling
anew five months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Each day, it spits up tons of lava, sulfuric gases and ash. Some
of the rocks are the size of automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   Plumes of gray smoke have often reached three miles above the
crater, and lava has spilled half-way down Tungurahua's cone. The
surrounding area has been placed under an ``orange alert,'' meaning
that an eruption could occur within hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``A huge eruption could happen at any moment,'' said Pablo
Samaniego, a volcanologist at the Institute of Geophysics in Quito.
Rivers of lava, mud and water could crash into Banos within
minutes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Banos' frightened residents were anxious to clear out.
They moved in with relatives or settled in government shelters just
outside the alert zone. Army troops then set up roadblocks to
cordon off the town.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that no one knows how long the threat will last.
Geologists say Tungurahua could blow tomorrow, next week or even
next year. Banos will remain off limits until the volcanic activity
dies down. Impatient evacuees now are beginning to feel like
refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Hotel and restaurant owners complain that the policy will kill
off tourism and force them out of business. Artisans, shop keepers
and farmers of Banos wonder how they will find new jobs in the
midst of Ecuador's worst recession since the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the eruption would happen immediately and that we
would be back in a few days,'' said Wilson Lara, who fled Banos
three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rosario Vallejo, a candymaker who moved into a shelter in
Ambato, 18 miles northwest of Banos, said families have been told
that they may be in limbo for up to a year. ``We are tired and
traumatized,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Farther north, hundreds more have been evacuated from the slopes
of Guagua Pichincha volcano on the outskirts of the capital city of
Quito.
</P>
<P>
   Following an eruption last month that formed a huge mushroom
cloud, Quito was covered with ash. Street venders sold surgical
face masks, and the congestion forced officials to order the
temporary closure of the city's international airport.
</P>
<P>
   Although a major eruption of Guagua Pichincha may be imminent,
geologists say that it poses little danger to Quito because the
crater points away from the city.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Tungurahua has plagued Banos for centuries.
According to Samaniego, an eruption in 1773 destroyed much of the
original community and led to the relocation of the town.
</P>
<P>
   Portraits of a fire-spewing Tungurahua decorate the Banos
cathedral. One painting depicts the Roman Catholic faithful
carrying the image of the Virgin toward the erupting volcano, an
act that is said to have silenced Tungurahua and saved the town.
</P>
<P>
   Following its last major eruption in 1918, author Nicolas
Martinez described the burning lava that flowed into the rivers
adjacent to Banos.
</P>
<P>
   ``The heat was so intense that I could not cross the streams for
four days,'' Martinez wrote at the time. ``You could light
cigarettes on the rocks and if you stuck a piece of wood into the
sand, it would be charred in an instant.``
</P>
<P>
   Yet many dismiss the danger.
</P>
<P>
   Murguizu, the Spanish priest, said that a steep mountain ridge
located between Banos and the volcano protects the town and
insisted that there is no record of deaths or substantial damage
caused by Tungurahua.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never done anything. In all of the past eruptions, the
lava has gone out into the river,'' he said. ``I sleep
peacefully.''
</P>
<P>
   But Army Col. Alejandro Recalde, who is coordinating emergency
efforts and monitoring the volcano from Ambato, said that
conditions have changed since 1918.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, he said, Banos is much larger, making the
outlying neighborhoods vulnerable. He added that lava could cut off
the main roads leading out of Banos and turn a last-minute
evacuation into chaos.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may think that we are taking too many precautions, but
it is important to remember history,'' said Recalde.
</P>
<P>
   There have been a number of recent volcanic catastrophes in
Latin America. Amid the heavy rains of Hurricane Mitch last
October, a crater lake atop La Casita volcano in northern Nicaragua
overflowed. The resulting mudslide killed 2,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Colombia, more than 20,000 people died in 1985
when the snow-capped Nevado del Ruiz volcano erupted, causing a
massive landslide that buried the town of Armero. Survivors said
local officials did not order an evacuation until mud was sweeping
through the town.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot play with the lives of 20,000 people,'' Samaniego
said.
</P>
<P>
   Others believe the Ecuadorean government may be taking extra
precautions after being stung by criticisms over its slow response
to last year's El Nino weather phenomenon. Rains and flooding
killed 292 and caused nearly $3 billion in damages.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Banos residents are clamoring to go home.
</P>
<P>
   Scores of townsfolk clashed with police last week and tried to
run army roadblocks. To relieve the pressure, convoys of vehicles
under military escort were allowed into Banos for a few hours over
the weekend so people could gather the rest of their belongings.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Resch, an Austrian who lives on the outskirts of Banos ,
found his lawn furniture covered with black ash. He collected his
passport, stereo and clean clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he took a last look around and walked away, wondering
aloud if he will still have a home once Tungurahua unleashes its
fury.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1808EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
