<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3103 &Cx1f; sci-z
u a BC-SCI-MALARIA-ART-1190(     11-08 1260
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-MALARIA-ART-1190(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MALARIA CASE, DOCTORS DISAGREED ON THE SOURCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Science Times) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN, M.D.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A 106-degree fever with teeth-clenching chills would
frighten anyone, and when the cause cannot be identified quickly
such symptoms are even more alarming.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly two weeks beginning in late October, Sean Cavanaugh,
a 30-year-old artist in Manhattan, had fevers that spiked to 104
and 106 degrees. Last week, his doctors diagnosed malaria.
</P>
<P>
   Each year millions of people in Third World countries develop
similar symptoms from malaria, a parasitic infection carried by the
anopheles mosquito, and many die. Far fewer cases occur in the
United States, and almost all patients here survive, as Cavanaugh
did.
</P>
<P>
   But where he got malaria is a matter of contention. Did he
contract it on Long Island where two 11-year-old Boy Scouts were
infected in August? Or did he get it on a springtime visit to
Honduras, where the infection is common, even though he took
anti-malarial drugs and never experienced symptoms suggestive of
malaria until late last month?
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the case underscores the importance of diagnosing
once-common infections like malaria that are now rare in the United
States. Earlier this century, malaria infected half a million
Americans each year. Now all but about 10 cases reported here each
year are in Americans who contracted malaria while overseas or in
people who moved to the United States from areas where the
infection remains.
</P>
<P>
   Control of the infection in the United States came from getting
rid of the parasite with drugs, not from eliminating the anopheles
mosquito.
</P>
<P>
   Cavanaugh said his first symptom was ``a run-down feeling'' that
began on Oct. 22, which he attributed to stress surrounding the
opening of his art show at a gallery the previous night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just been the center of attention and talking to 200
people, so I felt I should feel run down,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 23, Cavanaugh took guests to the Brooklyn Museum and to
his show at the Long Fine Art Gallery in Manhattan. He intended to
meet friends for dinner but returned home for a nap instead. ``I
put my head on the pillow, and as I was falling asleep the pillow
felt like it was burning up, because my head was so hot,'' he said.
His temperature was above 104.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning his temperature was normal, but he felt tired
and had no appetite. Cavanaugh said he ``thought it was just going
to be a 24-hour thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But on Oct. 27, while working at the Milton Avery Trust, he
suddenly felt cold and started shaking violently, and his fever
reappeared. ``That was really scary,'' he said, ``and the time to
go to my doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   His doctor, James Salik, ``thought it was probably a virus that
would go away in a couple of days, and that reassured me,''
Cavanaugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Then shortly after awakening on Oct. 29, he was shaking again.
His temperature was 106.1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never been sicker than that in my life, not even
close,'' he said. ``My girlfriend put me in a tub of cold water
because I was afraid my brain was going to start boiling.''
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon, Salik referred Cavanaugh to Dr. David Silverman,
an expert in infectious diseases at New York University. Both
doctors asked the same question: Where have you traveled recently?
Honduras in the spring, Cavanaugh told them.
</P>
<P>
   Between the fevers, Cavanaugh told friends that he identified
with malaria victims he had seen in the movies, ``shaking
uncontrollably and teeth chattering.''
</P>
<P>
   But he dismissed the notion of malaria because his doctors felt
that the seven months since his trip to Honduras was too long an
interval for the illness to be malaria, and he had not been in
another infected area. Silverman said, ``We kept figuring this is
some sort of bizarre viral thing that will probably just go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend of Oct. 30 and 31, Cavanaugh's temperature
hovered around 100.5 and he felt much better; by Nov. 1, he
thought, ``This is over.''
</P>
<P>
   At 2:30 a.m. on Nov. 2, the fever and shaking chills returned.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors were perplexed. Initially, the doctors focused on
the possibility of endocarditis, a potentially fatal infection of
the lining of the heart, because treatment is most effective if
given in its earliest stages. But Cavanaugh had none of the risk
factors for endocarditis, like a damaged heart valve, recent dental
work or invasive medical procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman said he wondered whether Cavanaugh was developing
hepatitis, because a urine test showed traces of bile, a pigment
made in the liver. (As it turned out, the bile resulted from the
destruction of red blood cells by malaria parasites.)
</P>
<P>
   An ultrasound test showed a normal liver, but it also revealed
an enlarged spleen. That finding and the fever pattern refocused
attention on malaria.
</P>
<P>
   Salik recalled reading about the Boy Scouts who were infected
with malaria while camping on the North Fork of Long Island. But
Cavanaugh had only been on the South Fork, where the disease had
never been reported, Silverman said.
</P>
<P>
   The doctors also considered another parasitic infection,
babesiosis, which is transmitted by ticks and has occurred on
Shelter Island, off eastern Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman ordered tests for malaria and babesiosis at New York
University and sent a sample of Cavanaugh's blood to the Centers
for Disease Control.
</P>
<P>
   During his illness, Cavanaugh's anxiety rose as he recalled
books and movies about outbreaks of Ebola virus infections in
Africa, and West Nile encephalitis in New York City in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I have some new disease that nobody knows about?'' he said.
``I do not want to be the breakthrough of some new disease.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours later, Silverman learned that a laboratory at New
York University had identified Plasmodium vivax, one of the four
types of parasites that cause human malaria, in Cavanaugh's blood.
Silverman double-checked the results and called his patient to tell
him the puzzle was solved: He had malaria.
</P>
<P>
   Relieved to know what was tormenting him, Cavanaugh rushed to a
pharmacy to start anti-malarial therapy.
</P>
<P>
   His temperature and appetite have returned to normal, and
Cavanaugh, who is 6-foot-5 and usually weighs 185 pounds, is trying
to regain the 10 pounds he lost.
</P>
<P>
   But there is still an unsolved mystery: where he contracted the
infection.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Timothy Holtz and Dr. Peter Bloland, two CDC malaria
experts, believe Cavanaugh got malaria in Honduras.
</P>
<P>
   ``The probabilities in this case would favor association with
travel to an endemic area where transmission occurs at orders of
magnitude higher than they have ever been in Long Island,'' Bloland
said.
</P>
<P>
   Malaria can recur, even after therapy, and some strains are
resistant to drugs. For these and other reasons, the doctors said,
the agency considers anyone with vivax malaria to have had a
relapse from a primary infection if the person had traveled to an
endemic area within four years before becoming ill. .
</P>
<P>
   Silverman sees it differently. ``CDC is playing a statistics
game. It's a coin toss with Sean,'' he said. ``It is an unlikely
scenario that he got it in Honduras, and it is an unlikely scenario
that he got it on Long Island. But he certainly got it someplace.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Cavanaugh said he had been bitten by mosquitoes while he was on
Long Island in late September and early October. ``At a barbecue,
we joked about the encephalitis scare, and how in the modern world
any disease is possible in New York,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Mahfouz Zaki, the Suffolk County public health director,
said, ``You have to be a magician to say that this guy did not get
it here or got it there.''
</P>
<P>
   DNA tests can help trace the source and pattern of spread in
outbreaks of some viruses. But similar tests are not available for
malaria, Bloland said.
</P>
<P>
   Zaki, who had extensive experience with malaria in his native
Egypt, said the Long Island cases pointed up the need to be alert
to malaria, which can mimic many diseases, among patients with
fevers in areas from which the parasite was thought to have
disappeared. And Cavanaugh's case illustrates why travelers should
tell their doctors about visits to infected areas.
</P>
<P>
   Most American physicians ``know little about parasitic diseases
and do not look for malaria,'' Zaki said. And sometimes, he said,
physicians may not report new cases or relapses to health
departments, because their patients are illegal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet there are many malaria cases here that we know nothing
about,'' Zaki said.
</P>
</TEXT>
