<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3106 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ELECT-1109-COX     11-08 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECT-1109-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEXICO'S RULING PARTY RELISHES ELECTION RESULTS, BUT MUST
CONTEND WITH DISSIDENTS
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service(at) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexico's Institutional Revolutionary Party, or
PRI, is celebrating its first-ever presidential primary election as
if it had just given birth to a beautiful new baby.
</P>
<P>
   Winner Francisco Labastida Ochoa, who will go on to compete in
Mexico's July 2000 presidential election, proclaimed ``a new PRI''
after balloting on Sunday. The PRI, which supervised its own
election, claims it attracted as many as 9 million or 10 million
voters _ many more than the 6.5 million the party expected.
</P>
<P>
   The primary represented the first time this century that the
powerful party allowed voters, rather than Mexico's president, to
select the presidential candidate for the PRI, the world's longest
ruling political party.
</P>
<P>
   Even ardent PRI foes who believe the primary was mostly for
show, acknowledge that the balloting helped renovate the PRI's
image as an authoritarian, corrupt dinosaur responsible for
Mexico's chronic economic woes.
</P>
<P>
   Alleging that the media favored Labastida over his rivals and
that public money was used to muster votes, opposition politician
Jose Ortiz Pinchetti said, ``I think the old and the new PRI are
basically the same. But the primary showed that the PRI is still
fantastic at turning out votes . . . It wasn't democracy, but it
showed imagination and a will to take risks.''
</P>
<P>
   But political analysts here also say the PRI _ which has
controlled Mexico's presidency since 1929 _ can't afford to be too
cocky about its chances in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Although the final count has yet to be released, it may show
that Labastida won the primary with barely half the total number of
direct votes cast in the election, said Luis Linares, a political
analyst with Mexico City's Special Investigations Systems. ``That
means that inside the PRI there is a dissident current that is
almost a majority.''
</P>
<P>
   For the 2000 election, Linares said, the PRI can't automatically
count on those dissident votes going over to Labastida. Most
dissident votes were cast for PRI maverick Roberto Madrazo Pintado,
who ran a ferocious campaign against the free-market economic
policies of President Ernesto Zedillo and other party elite.
Labastida was until recently Zedillo's agriculture secretary, and
then his interior minister.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida is projected to have won 272 of 300 electoral
districts in Mexico, compared to only 20 for Madrazo. Victory was
based on whoever won the largest number of electoral districts,
rather than popular votes.
</P>
<P>
   With 70 percent of districts counted, Labastida won about 4.1
million direct votes and Madrazo almost 2.3 million. Two other
candidates together won about 795,900 votes. The total vote against
Labastida, with this partial return, was almost 3 million.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI's opposition in 2000 is divided between two top
candidates, leftist Cuauhtemoc Cardenas and conservative Vicente
Fox. In some polls Fox is neck-and-neck in popularity with
Labastida. But either opposition candidate could benefit from a
floating bloc of votes not committed to the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Linares pointed out, sentiment against the PRI
has been strong enough that the party hasn't been able to win a big
election like a governor's race with more than about 45 percent of
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``So If the PRI doesn't integrate those (dissident primary)
voters, there could be trouble in 2000,'' Linares said.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo will be a key figure in this accommodation.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the primary campaign, Madrazo, along with two other
candidates, relentlessly attacked Labastida as the PRI's ``official
candidate'' imposed by the party elite. The rivals also accused
Labastida of benefiting from an old-fashioned PRI election tactic:
the use of public money to buy votes, as well as pressure tactics
by PRI-affiliated governors and other functionaries.
</P>
<P>
   After the PRI handed out official preliminary returns
effectively making Labastida the victor late Sunday night, Madrazo
appeared on Mexican television early Monday morning conceding
defeat.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't cry fraud and he announced he would stay with the PRI,
putting to rest, for now, the specter of a potentially damaging
break with the party. But he made it clear he was not going to fall
silent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am proud of have participated in this internal process,
which had imperfections and inequities,'' Madrazo, a former
governor of Tabasco state, said. ``We knew throughout this campaign
we'd be fighting against old party inertia, against resistance. We
will continue fighting inside the party, we will continue leading a
current within the PRI that is looking for change.''
</P>
<P>
   Joel Estudillo, an analyst with the Mexican Institute of
Political Studies, said, Labastida can't ignore Madrazo's crowd
inside the PRI. ``To ignore them, might not be political suicide,''
he said, ``but it would be a big risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Estudillo predicted that the party would be busy over the next
few weeks trying to rein in dissidents by offering some leaders
candidacies for next year's congressional elections. But Labastida
will also have to offer something for those individual voters who
want to see some changes in how the party is run and its policies.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Labastida told a Mexican television station that he
hoped to meet with Madrazo soon. In his first televised victory
speech early Monday morning, however, Labastida fell short of
inviting his rivals within the party to join his presidential
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have concluded a process of open, real, passionate and at
times bitter competition,'' Labastida said. ``That's the way it's
been because that's what competition is.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
