u a BC-RALEIGH-ARENA-NYTR &LR;      11-08 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RALEIGH-ARENA-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACKERS OF A NEW RALEIGH ARENA HOPE FOR MORE THAN HOCKEY PUCKS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GREG RETSINAS   
 New York Times Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. _ Now that it's built will they come?
</P>
<P>
   For the brand-new Entertainment and Sports Arena in Raleigh,
there is a lot riding on that question, not the least of which is
the $98 million contributed to the $154 million project by the
North Carolina public.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the public money has come from revenues from a hotel
tax levied on Wake County hotels and from the city of Raleigh and
Wake County governments, and the state General Assembly has
contributed at least $18 million so far.
</P>
<P>
   In an era when multimillion-dollar arenas are nearly obsolete as
soon as they open and middle-class families are increasingly unable
to afford a trip to a ball game, Raleigh's glitzy new arena is
hoping to buck those trends.
</P>
<P>
   When planning started in 1984, it was to be a basketball venue
for North Carolina State University. By the time a groundbreaking
was held nine years later, it had evolved into a multi-purpose
sports arena. Three years later, organizers, led by Raleigh's
mayor, set out to add a professional hockey franchise to the
equation.
</P>
<P>
   The Entertainment and Sports Arena, which opened Oct. 29 just
west of downtown Raleigh, is the new home of the Carolina
Hurricanes, the Research Triangle's first professional sports team.
But, it is more than a hockey rink, according to the people in
charge of filling up the place 365 nights a year. Professional
hockey will take up 41 dates between October and May, which leaves
a lot of blank space on the calendar.
</P>
<P>
   In its first two months, the arena, which seats between 18,000
and 20,000 people, depending on the event, will host a range of
tenants. First off were the Hurricanes, whose NHL match-up with the
New Jersey Devils sold out the arena.
</P>
<P>
   The 'Canes will play 16 games at the arena before the end of the
year, and N.C. State, the other prime user of the facility, will
play eight games as well. All but six of the N.C. State basketball
games are sold out, even though the new arena has 50 percent more
seats than Reynolds Coliseum, the team's former venue.
</P>
<P>
   The arena will have five nights of Disney on Ice in mid-December
and a ``success-in-business'' seminar featuring such luminaries as
talk-show host Larry King, actor Christopher Reeve and Gen. Colin
Powell. Add in World Wrestling Federation matches, women's soccer
exhibitions and four music concerts, including a $125-a-ticket
James Taylor concert on New Year's Eve, and the calendar fills up
pretty quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Raleigh officials say they want to link the arena with other
attractions to make Raleigh a destination for visitors. The new
Exploris museum, an interactive hands-on place, opened last month
in downtown Raleigh, and the N.C. Museum of Natural Sciences will
open in a new building in April.
</P>
<P>
   ``We finally have a big-league team. We're already the
Smithsonian of the South,'' said Martin Armes of the Greater
Raleigh Convention and Visitors Bureau, noting the downtown museums
and the North Carolina Museum of Art, which is currently host to a
Monet art show.
</P>
<P>
   Armes said his office is working to attract large conventions
and religious groups to the arena in an effort to tout Raleigh as
on a tourism par with Nashville and Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Travel Industry Association of America, which
tracks visitor spending in major cities, tourists spent about $1.02
billion in Wake County last year, or nearly $2.8 million a day.
``Raleigh's a big market, and this should provide a spark,'' said
Michael Pina, a tourism industry spokesman in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   With several new attractions scheduled to open next year and the
arena generating business, Armes said the area ``is still
scratching the surface in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Entertainment and Sports Arena won't be successful if it
does not solve one opening-night problem. Many motorists headed for
the opening face-off sat in traffic for hours as arena officials
underestimated their parking needs.
</P>
<P>
   When the puck dropped around 7:40 p.m. after a light show, a Big
Bad Voodoo Daddy music concert and player introductions, many of
the best seats were empty and stayed that way through the first
period. After the game, arena officials said more parking
attendants would be used, and more lanes would be opened.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a N.C. State basketball scrimmage last week that drew
about 6,000 fans also produced a traffic tie-up.
</P>
<P>
   Solving traffic problems and other headaches is the
responsibility of Gale Force Holdings, which owns the Hurricanes
and has a long-term contract to run the arena as well. The
Hurricanes have a 20-year lease to stay in the arena, but the
public is ultimately responsible for the building. Officially, the
Centennial Authority, a public body that was set up by the state's
General Assembly in 1995 and given $7 million, owns the facility.
</P>
<P>
   A thorny, yet lucrative, issue still to be resolved concerns
what corporate name will be attached to the arena. Industry sources
estimate a naming contract could bring in between $40 million to
$200 million, depending on the length of the commitment.
</P>
<P>
   The state has invested millions, as has N.C. State, which owns
the naming rights. University and arena officials say they are
negotiating over the rights, but for now, the facility is one of
the few new arenas in America without a corporate name attached to
it.
</P>
<P>
   (Greg Retsinas is Raleigh Bureau chief for the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
