<HEADER>
A3109 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HOG-FARMERS-NYTR &LR;      11-08 0615
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOG-FARMERS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOG FARMERS EYE NATIONAL COOPERATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Iowa)  (mk) 
 By SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Agriculture Secretary Dan Glickman sounds the
alarm about consolidation in the farm industry, independent and
small hog farmers, whose ranks have thinned drastically this
decade, are pursuing one option to bolster their strength _ joining
forces to form a national cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   While not yet a reality, the proposed cooperative got a
significant boost in the recent agriculture spending bill, which
commits $500,000 to study the feasibility of the venture.
Supporters believe a national pork cooperative could be up and
running by spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would allow us to create an atmosphere where we would not
only survive, but grow and prosper'' said John Adams, a hog farmer
in Greene County, N.C., who supports the idea. A cooperative, Adams
said, would give hog farmers some economic muscle and control
``from the farm to the fork.''
</P>
<P>
   Glickman likes the idea. In recent months, the agriculture
secretary has talked repeatedly about his concerns that small
farmers are being driven out of business by large operations that
have come to characterize American farming.
</P>
<P>
   ``A giant shadow looms over the ability of independent family
farmers and ranchers to get a fair shake in today's agricultural
economy _ concentration,'' Glickman wrote in one column.
</P>
<P>
   In another speech, Glickman spoke specifically about hog
farmers. ``We don't want hogs to go the way of poultry, where most
of the industry operates under contract,'' he said. In one sense,
Glickman added, such farmers act as employees of the processing
plants. ``That's not the role we want farmers to play in our
economy,'' Glickman said.
</P>
<P>
   To underscore his concerns about the hog industry, Glickman has
written Attorney General Janet Reno, asking her to ``scrutinize
closely'' Smithfield Foods Inc.'s proposed acquisition of Murphy
Family Farms in Rose Hill, N.C. He questioned whether there would
be ``reduced opportunities'' for hog farmers ``to bargain with
different contractors.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department's antitrust division is reviewing that
proposed merger, but officials there refuse to comment.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Agriculture Department, roughly 12 percent of
today's hog farms have more than 1,000 hogs and account for 78
percent of total hog inventory nationwide. In 1988, just 3.1
percent of hog farmers had inventories of 1,000 or more hogs, and
they accounted for 36 percent of the total hog inventory.
</P>
<P>
   That trend is adding fuel to the cooperative idea. Under a
national cooperative, hog farmers would pool their resources to
possibly build their own processing plant, so they would not be at
the mercy of the few, large plants that dominate the market today.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the National Pork Producers Council in Washington
is acting as the catalyst for the cooperative initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could immediately be a very powerful marketing tool,'' said
Steven Cohen, a spokesman for the council. A task force will meet
in Des Moines, Iowa, later this month to discuss the cooperative
idea, which appears to be gathering steam in agriculture circles.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, some Senate Democrats introduced a bill last month
calling for an 18-month moratorium on large agribusiness mergers.
Even if that bill falters this year, Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, a
prominent voice on American farm policy, said he will pursue the
issue into the next congressional session.
</P>
<P>
   ``Family farmers are being pushed out of the picture,'' Harkin
said.
</P>
<P>
   (Sean Loughlin is a Washington correspondent for the New York
Times Regional Newspapers.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
