<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 18:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3110 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-GREEN-INTERVIEW-LA     11-08 1766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GREEN-INTERVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREEN GIANT A MASTER AT ANNOYANCE AND HUMOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(Eds: Fact box at bottom.) 
 
 
By DAVID KRONKE 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; As he winds up the taping of yet another episode of ``The Tom
Green Show,'' chock full of practical jokes and atrocities _ one of
his first produced in Los Angeles _ Tom Green is ready to hit the
showers. He drags his beloved supporting stooges _ Glenn Humplik,
who, having a name like Humplik, is accustomed to abuse, and is
therefore the victim of many of Green's pranks; and Phil Giroux,
the guy who spends the show sipping java and chortling _ into a
tiny showering booth.
</P>
<P>
   All three are as naked as MTV's standards and practices will
allow _ which, you might be surprised to hear, is not entirely
naked _ and, once packed into the shower, reed-thin Tom starts
getting a little too familiar with his more substantially built
buddies. Glenn reacts accordingly _ which is to say, with dismay _
and the combination of cramped environs and slippery floor sends
the three sprawling across the stage as the entire shower
contraption collapses in a heap of scrap aluminum. It's the perfect
bookend to the beginning of the taping, when a rowdy group of fans
swarmed Green and very nearly snapped him in half.
</P>
<P>
   These are halcyon days for Tom Green, though he admits things
are moving a bit fast. He's been in town for little more than a
month, and the reception area of his new L.A. office looks like a
disaster area, with a 4-foot-tall mountain of boxes _ his? the last
tenant's? _ tossed, not stacked, in one corner. Green has to shoot
a battery of shows before those boxes can even be dealt with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely not the ideal schedule,'' he sighs while
relaxing in his office. Unlike a lot of comics, Green isn't ``on''
during interviews _ in fact, he's so laid back and somniferous you
could almost say he's ``off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the victim of the show popping like it did. It's
shoot-shoot-shoot, throw on three shows, shoot-shoot-shoot-shoot,
throw on four shows. In Canada, we'd shoot (remote-location
segments) for six months, then go in the studio and do 13 shows.
But we're moving toward that. At least I hope we are.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day before taping that shower scene _ which is as scary
as Hitchcock's but for different reasons _ the between-segment
material for that show hadn't even been written. And 10 minutes
before the scheduled taping time, the construction crew was still
piecing together the set.
</P>
<P>
   But that's what happens when you're an overnight sensation.
Green, for the uninitiated, is a Canadian who, after years of cult
success up north, appeared on MTV back in January and became an
immediate sensation. Certainly, he was attention-getting,
performing such bits of conceptual comedy as filling his parents'
home with farm animals, trashing a grocery store with a motorized
wheelchair and enjoying fresh milk direct from its source.
Americans got a taste of Green in a series of
on-the-road-to-the-Super-Bowl commercials he did for Pepsi last
January.
</P>
<P>
   His demeanor is normally placid, but his eyes tend to betray an
element of dementia. ``He is our audience,'' declares John Miller,
MTV's senior vice president of programming and development. Miller
got a tape from Green and put the show into production without
pausing to produce a pilot episode.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not afraid to make an ass of himself, yet you still like
him. He apologizes after he does things. But oh, my God, he likes
to push people's buttons. He's your friend who's always pushing
you, who's seducing you and all the while you're getting into a
load of trouble. He's just egging you on.''
</P>
<P>
   Green's schtick is the sort of thing David Letterman used to do,
mixed with Andy Kaufman's brand of comic confrontation. It's
``Candid Camera'' as run by the Marquis de Sade's bratty nephew,
only the camera is never hidden. It's right in his victims' faces,
which usually amps up their irritation quotient.
</P>
<P>
   The show includes the spectacle of ostensibly ordinary people
undergoing psychological torment _ an element that's wildly popular
these days. Look at the hit film ``The Blair Witch Project'' or
prime-time game shows such as ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.''
Even the Food Network, of all places, has concocted its own,
exceedingly benign, version in which Gordon Elliot enters random
homes with a chef and makes a gourmet dinner from whatever's in his
subject's fridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, if you wanted to do a TV show, you had to have a
studio, and you had to have cameras, and it was more controlled,''
Green observes. ``TV got used to making things that were
controlled. And it's taken people a while to get used to the idea
that we can make things smaller, and when you do that, you
instantly get realer. You get real life and the public, once they
saw that for the first few times, felt a little fed up with seeing
the same thing over and over.''
</P>
<P>
   The outraged reactions Green elicits from his subjects are no
accident, he explains. ``The reason people get a little freaked out
is that we've set up our shoots in a way that we don't look like
we're from MTV or a TV station,'' he says. ``We have one cameraman,
a small-format camera _ the goal is to make people think I'm some
college student out doing some avant-garde, guerrilla piece. They
don't think it's serious in any way. So they have no problem with
punching the camera or telling me to get the hell away. Then, when
they find out it's a real show, they usually change gears.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he concedes that it's a challenge to get people he has
royally miffed to sign agreements allowing the footage to be shown
on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes we lose people _ it's one of the most difficult
elements of the show, to be honest,'' he admits. ``We still haven't
been able to figure out how to do it. We have a few people who are,
you could say, highly trained at telling people, `It's just a joke
_ you've been on ``Candid Camera,''' that kind of thing. People
eventually see the humor, even if they've been really mad on
camera, to the point of being violent. I had a woman punch me in
the head three times, and as soon as the camera stopped rolling,
and the release person started talking to her, she realized she had
seen me on `Oprah.' People come around really quickly once they
realize we're from MTV.''
</P>
<P>
   Such problems didn't exist when Green did his show in Canada,
first on a cable-access channel and later on the Canadian
equivalent of Comedy Central. The show was essentially a reaction
to the youthful abuse he got from myriad security guards for doing
silly things on the premises of businesses they protected a bit too
seriously. In college, Green worked the late-night shift at the
university radio station, where he met Humplik, who is five years
his senior.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did a lot of weird stuff,'' Green recalls. ``We were in
Ottawa, which is like doing a show in Washington, a conservative,
government town. We'd tell everyone listening to meet us on the
front lawn of the Parliament Building at 2 a.m. to play soccer, and
about 100 kids'd show up. ... The police'd be there, wondering what
the hell we were doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Humplik represents the quintessential good sport. ``The most
embarrassing thing was when he put a hidden camera in my dressing
room while I was trying to get into supertight Spandex,'' Humplik
says, prying off the wooden clogs and Scottish kilt Green forced
him to wear for a taping. ``But it's all in good fun. It has to
hurt me for them to find it funny. Hanging out with him keeps me
mentally ageless.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has opened doors for me in real life,'' says Humplik, who
works for a computer company in Ottawa, on why he puts up with the
incessant abuse. ``My co-workers are weirded-out a lot (by the
attention).'' At this taping, Green dragged a teen-ager out of the
audience to send home with Humplik. ``I'll give (him) a blanket and
let him sleep in the car or put him up at Tom's parents' house,''
Humplik confides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Glenn stands up for himself _ he just reacts so perfectly to
Tom,'' says MTV's Miller. ``It's a challenge to come up with stuff
that will upset him.''
</P>
<P>
   The show's most popular vignettes involve Green annoying _ or
humiliating _ his long-suffering parents, Dick and Mary Jane. Green
has painted their home plaid, air-brushed a lesbian love scene on
the hood of his pop's car and dropped a cow's head in their bed
while they were sleeping. Though the bits are generally billed as
All In Good Fun, he admits there's a certain catharsis, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, when I was in high school and younger, they were
more controlling,'' he says. ``They've mellowed quite a bit since I
went to college and found a direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``But before that, they were extremely concerned that I was
going to end up drifting off into (oblivion) _ but I think they
took it a little more seriously than a lot of parents do.
</P>
<P>
   ``A funny thing about their situation, though, is that they were
always angry with me while growing up for doing precisely the
things I'm now doing for a living. And they were angry that I was
doing those things because they felt that if I kept doing them, I'd
fail school and I'd never be able to get a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a Catch-22 that my parents are in right now,'' he says
with a wicked smile. ``When we barge in in the middle of the night
and toss a cow's head on their bed, they're really mad that this
cow's head is bleeding on their mattress, but on the other hand,
they're really glad I'm working.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his antics _ attempting to pleasure a dead moose he
found on the side of a road, barging into viewers' homes at 3 in
the morning and irritating their parents, bellowing into a bullhorn
at passers-by that they suck _ Green has never gotten in serious
trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have called the police, but there's never been any
grounds to arrest me,'' he insists. ``I'm not this irrational,
crazed lunatic who goes out and does these things without thought.
There are a lot of writers here, and we spend a lot of time before
we go out planning these things. We don't want anyone to get hurt
or emotionally distraught over anything.''
</P>
<P>
   He pauses a beat, then drops the punchline like a hammer:
``Except maybe my parents, but they deserve it.'' &QL; 
---
</P>
<P>
   _ The show: ``The Tom Green Show.'' &QL; 
_ What: Comedy series in which the host irritates, obfuscates and
in general makes life a little more surreal for unwitting victims. &QL; 
_ Where: MTV. &QL; 
_ When: 7:30 p.m. Thursdays, repeated at 7:30 p.m. Saturdays. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
