<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 18:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3114 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-SINDEN-3TA     11-08 1701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SINDEN-3 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE IN HIS VEINS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The generic nickname was the giveaway; the Whitby
Seniors' shoestring budget had unraveled. Formerly the Oshawa Smith
Truckmen, they had lost their transport company sponsor for the
1955-56 Ontario Senior B amateur hockey season, and even as they
were skating to their second straight provincial championship, they
were sputtering along on financial fumes.
</P>
<P>
   Wren Blair, the full-time housing appraiser and part-time hockey
impresario who ran the team, couldn't afford to pay the players
their nominal $10-$20 stipend for each game, so he hit upon a
unique solution: If the Seniors would finish out the season, he
would split the year-end revenue among them, on a percentage basis
according to their individual value. All but two of the players
agreed, and at midseason, Blair agonizingly computed the
compensation formula. One by one, he called the players to meet him
at the Spruce Villa hotel, the local hockey hangout in the Lake
Ontario coastal town of some 7,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Attersley, the Seniors' star center, was at the top of the
scale; he would get 7 percent of the take _ probably some $180 _
Blair informed him. Done.
</P>
<P>
   Next in line was the team's top defenseman. Over a beer in the
lounge, Blair revealed his remuneration: 6 1/2 percent. The
recipient, 24-year-old Harry Sinden, exploded into a rage of
indignation. ``(Expletive) you,'' he told Blair. ``I'm a
7-percenter.''
</P>
<P>
   Blair volleyed with equal vigor. ``(Expletive) you, too,'' he
said. ``As far as I'm concerned, you're worth 6 1/2 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden, who unlike most of his teammates was married with
children _ three young daughters _ got up and stormed toward the
exit. Blair pleaded for him to reconsider. ``For Christ's sake,
Harry,'' he said. ``Half a percent is going to be worth about 8
bucks. What's the big deal?''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden spun on his heels. ``It's not the half-percent,'' he
advised Blair. ``It's the principle.'' And he walked out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Whether the battleground is $8 or 8 cents or $8 million, it
always has been a matter of principle to Harry Sinden. And there is
no price he is willing to place on that.
</P>
<P>
   At 67, retirement age for most of his peers, he is in his 28th
season as Bruins general manager, 11th year as team president,
still feisty, still fascinating, always successful by most
standards. He won the Stanley Cup in his fourth and final year as
coach. He guided Team Canada to an earthshaking victory over the
Soviet Union after a two-year hiatus from the game. In the 31 years
he has been in Boston, the Bruins have reached the playoffs 30
times, an unprecedented achievement. And after that lone failure
two years ago, Sinden recast the club on the fly, providing this
fall's FleetCenter patrons with perhaps the most promising Boston
edition since the Big, Bad Bruins of Orr and Esposito and Cheevers.
He has presided over more victories _ 1,148 and counting _ than any
other GM in National Hockey League history. And he has done it all
with a ferocious sense of fiscal responsibility, for the past 25
years on behalf of the Buffalo-based conglomerate Delaware North.
As former scout Bart Bradley says, ``The bottom line is always
black'' for the Black and Gold.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, this last item on the ledger has left Sinden on
the debit side with some critics, as if the Bruins should be a
nonprofit organization, operating as a civic trust. Though it would
be convenient to pass the buck, Sinden emphasizes that he is under
no mandate or budgetary constraints from headquarters, and Delaware
North CEO Jeremy Jacobs corroborates this autonomy. ``The position
he's got, he's earned,'' says Jacobs. ``A number of people who work
for me have great latitude, and Harry's one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden operates by a steadfast, implicit credo: ``Mr. Jacobs
would give up an awful lot to win, but he won't give up his
business. Winning is much more important, but not if you win and
put your team in a position where it can't survive. I want to win _
the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's the rub, because it's not necessarily the most
popular way. The one blank on his resume that Sinden would love to
fill is the lack of a Stanley Cup during his administration.
Detractors point to this, note that the Bruins rank 20th in payroll
(at some $27.5 million) among the 28 NHL teams, inspect the fallout
from notorious contract stalemates he's engaged in over the years _
most recently with All-Star goalie Byron Dafoe, who missed the
first dozen games of the season before signing a three-year, $9.45
million deal last weekend _ and target Sinden as the Cup culprit.
Admirers _ and they are legion outside the ranks of the Players
Association and agents _ applaud him for maintaining a consistent
level of excellence while adhering to sound business principles.
While short-lived dynasties have crumbled under the weight of their
bills, Sinden has overseen five Stanley Cup finalists and constant
contenders. Yet he acknowledges that the lack of the grand prize
feeds into the notion that he is a cheapskate and that bothers him.
</P>
<P>
   But he doesn't duck the public relations flak, refuses to
retreat from a stance that assistant GM Mike O'Connell says has
been arrived at ``through very careful research, a lot of
homework,'' and has earned the grudging admiration of even those in
an adversarial position.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harry's pay scale is different from the vast majority of
general managers, and he sticks to it,'' says Steve Freyer, agent
for 21-year veteran defenseman Ray Bourque, the most beloved Bruin
of Sinden's tenure who nonetheless endured a traumatic arbitration
process in 1992 that Freyer believes was unnecessary. ``One of
Harry's defining characteristics is that he's a believer. He deeply
believes in his position and he sticks to it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been that way, on both sides of the bargaining table,
throughout his life, no matter the cost.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He was at the pinnacle. After a 29-year famine, and more
recently an eight-year stretch as bottom feeders in the six-team
NHL, the Bruins had captured the 1970 Stanley Cup. There seemed no
horizon to their dominance. With dynamic defenseman Bobby Orr,
scoring metronome Phil Esposito, swashbuckling goaltender Gerry
Cheevers, and a roguish, robust supporting cast, the Big, Bad
Bruins had become the rage of Boston and seemed on the threshold of
becoming the scourge of the now 12-team NHL. And at the helm was
37-year-old Harry Sinden, seemingly about to reap the rewards of a
hardscrabble journey through hockey's hinterlands.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Bruins were a sublimely talented outfit that
presumably could run on autopilot, the stars themselves exposed the
fallacy of this conventional wisdom. ``Harry Sinden was the best
coach I ever had in pro hockey,'' says Esposito. ``He understood
our team totally. He handled everybody really well. He understood
each player as an individual.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was his genius,'' says Esposito's fellow center from that
era, Derek Sanderson.
</P>
<P>
   There was one problem. Money. Sinden had received a $15,000
salary when he was promoted to Boston after leading the Bruins'
affiliate in Oklahoma City to the Central Hockey League title in
1966. While on the trail to the Cup, he had received a $2,000
raise, ``so I could go out and get myself some new clothes,'' he
recalls with a laugh. But he had made a discovery that he didn't
find funny: The going rate for an NHL head coach was $30,000. And
during the 1969-70 season, he had received an eye-popping offer
from an old Toronto high school friend, Dave Stirling: a $40,000
salary plus some $1 million in stock options to join the booming
firm of Stirling-Homex, a company based in suburban Rochester,
N.Y., that sold prefabricated housing. He informed Bruins owner
Weston Adams Sr. of the salary discrepancy and was offered a raise
_ to $22,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they'd gone to $25,000,'' he says, ``I probably would have
stayed. I didn't want to leave hockey.''
</P>
<P>
   But, with four daughters now to support, he did leave. When he
rejected the Bruins' raise and advised Adams of his business
alternative, the owner told him, ``Have a nice career.''
</P>
<P>
   So less than a week after taking a triumphal ride through the
streets of Boston during the championship parade, Sinden shockingly
announced his retirement. Hearing of this, a stunned Sanderson told
management, ``You just lost the Stanley Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   The divorce didn't last long. Within two years, the bottom fell
out on prefab housing and the company stock, and Sinden lost his
life savings. Having no income, he accepted international hockey
wheeler-dealer Alan Eagleson's invitation to coach the Canadians in
an eight-game exhibition series against the Soviets, with nothing
more than world supremacy at stake in a true Cold War environment.
After they staggered to a 1-2-1 record on their home ice, Sinden
convinced the cocky Canadians of what he already knew from his
participation in the 1960 Olympics: The Russians were for real.
Both chastened and galvanized, Team Maple Leaf salvaged the series
with three one-goal victories in the Soviet Union, and Sinden
parlayed that success into a return to Boston in 1972, this time
strictly as an executive: managing director of hockey. He's been
running the Bruins ever since.
</P>
<P>
   That his break with hockey amounted to little more than a
sabbatical is not what resonates some three decades later. The fact
that he was willing to make it _ a supreme sacrifice for a man who
had grown up wanting nothing more than a life in the game _ speaks
volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Blair, his mentor, had learned that day at the Spruce Villa that
Sinden, who took his 6 1/2 percent and finished out the season,
``is a man of principled values.'' In other words, an overriding
sense of duty _ not in pursuit of every possible dollar but for the
sake of his family. That's why his own interests always finished
second.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
