<HEADER>
A3115 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR &LR;      11-08 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW&AMP;NOTABLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE STEPHENSON  
 c.1999 Special for The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are Anne Stephenson's capsule book reviews:
</P>
<P>
   ``MY GARDEN (BOOK)''  &QL; 
By Jamaica Kincaid (FSG, $23) &QL; 
Jamaica Kincaid has written books full of her difficult feelings
for her mother and her brother, but boy, does she love her garden.
She is agitated and vexed when she's in it, but she's happy:
``Nothing works just the way I thought it would, nothing looks just
the way I had imagined it, and when sometimes it does look like
what I had imagined (and this, thank God, is rare) I am startled
that my imagination is so ordinary.'' This book is dense with
growing things, overrun with blooms, fertile with every plant
you've ever heard of and then some. Fellow gardening author Michael
Pollan says Kincaid's voice is that of ``an exquisitely attentive
gardener thinking out loud.'' We'd note that ``exquisitely
attentive'' is a kind way of saying ``obsessed,'' but then it's all
New &AMP; Notable can do to water the tomatoes. Kincaid celebrates seed
and plant catalogs, discusses the link between gardeners and
conquerors, and notes that ``everyone I have ever met who has a
garden has something growing in it from seeds that were gathered in
Monet's garden.'' That means she cultivates exotic friends, too. &QL; 
``THE BOOK BORROWER'' &QL; 
By Alice Mattison (Morrow, $24) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This odd and meandering novel begins with the meeting of two
young mothers at a park in 1975. Deborah Laidlaw is there with her
daughters, Toby Ruben with her baby son, and in the course of their
conversation Toby borrows a book that Deborah has been carrying
around but has not found time to read. Two things begin in this
scene: a lifelong friendship between Toby and Deborah, and our
interest in the fate of that borrowed book, ``Trolley Girl,'' the
story of a tragedy that occurred during a strike among trolley
workers in 1921. For much of her novel, Mattison alternates the
interplay between Toby, Deborah and their families with sections
narrated by the author of ``Trolley Girl.'' We're not sure why she
does this but we're grateful for it, because ``Trolley Girl''
proceeds with a sense of purpose and anticipation. The ground is
not so firm under Toby and Deborah, whose friendship unfolds in
rambling conversations and unseen resolutions. One chapter ends
with a terrible conflict between the two friends when Toby almost
gets Deborah fired from her teaching job. To our surprise, the next
chapter begins years later, with their friendship obviously
restored, although Mattison does not say how. This is exasperating,
but ``The Book Borrower'' is not without saving graces. One is Toby
Ruben, an authentic character who slips into mean-spiritedness when
she feels threatened. Another is Mattison's portrayal of the give
and take between friends, between men and women, between parents
and children _ that messy navigation of emotional ties. In the end,
her novel is less notable for its story than for these small
moments that ring true. &QL; 
``IF THIS HOUSE COULD TALK'' &QL; 
By Elizabeth Smith Brownstein (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $35) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I have found that it is the visible, the tangible, that goes a
long way in softening prejudices,'' Booker T. Washington wrote in
``Up From Slavery.'' ``The actual sight of a first-class house that
a Negro has built is 10 times more potent than pages of discussion
about a house that he ought to build, or perhaps could build.'' And
so, against the wishes of some of his benefactors, Washington built
``The Oaks,'' a red brick house with parlor, library, dining room,
kitchen, family and guest bedrooms, den, breakfast room, five
bathrooms and a veranda on three acres of land overlooking the
campus of Alabama's Tuskegee Institute. Among the other buildings
included in this look at historic homes and the people who lived in
them are the stunning ``symphony in wood'' built in 1908 (for a
mere $55,000) for Proctor &AMP; Gamble heir David Gamble in Pasadena,
Calif.; the New Hampshire farm of poet Robert Frost; Lorenzo
Hubbell's house and trading post in Ganado; the Massachusetts
homestead of Rebecca Nurse, who was hanged during the Salem witch
trials; the Bronx, N.Y., cottage of Edgar Allan Poe; and Frank
Lloyd Wright's Storer House and Auldbrass Plantation. Our favorite
is illustrator Edward Gorey's Cape Cod cottage, where books are
piled precariously high on every horizontal surface in sight. This
engaging blend of history, architecture and interior design
contains what its author calls ``stories of great passion, courage
and brilliance . . . and enough cruelty, greed and ignorance to go
around.'' &QL; 
``THE COST OF LIVING'' &QL; 
By Arundhati Roy (Modern Library, $11.95) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roy follows her Booker Prize-winning first novel, ``The God of
Small Things,'' with two essays, one on dam projects that have
scarred her native India and the other on India's detonation last
year of a nuclear bomb. The first, called ``The Greater Common
Good,'' is more demanding reading, but both benefit from Roy's very
personal and appealingly abrasive style. In the second essay, ``The
End of Imagination,'' she touches on the success of her novel.
``The more I thought about it,'' she writes, ``the clearer it
became to me that if fame was going to be my permanent condition it
would kill me. Club me to death with its good manners and hygiene.
I'll admit that I've enjoyed my own five minutes of it immensely
but primarilyBECAUSE (editor: ITAL) it was just five minutes.
Because I knew (or thought I knew) that I could go home when I was
bored and giggle about it. Grow old and irresponsible. Eat mangoes
in the moonlight. Maybe write a couple of failed books _
worstsellers _ to see what it felt like.'' Instead, she has written
this, a thought-provoking challenge from a citizen of India and of
the world. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can reach Anne Stephenson at
amstephenson(at)worldnet.att.net, viae-mail. &QL;
</P>
