<HEADER>
A3116 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-SINDEN-2ND     11-08 1498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SINDEN-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  
 BOSTON: ... finished second.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Riding through Toronto a few years back with Bradley and Bruins
director of development Bob Tindall, Sinden conducted a nostalgic
tour of his boyhood neighborhood in York Township. He stopped in
front of a house and told his passengers, ``That's where I grew
up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The car was almost as long as the house,'' recalls Tindall.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Sinden Sr. was in charge of maintenance at the Ontario
Hydro power plant, ``and we were middle class,'' says Harry Jr.
``Lower middle class.''
</P>
<P>
   The boy shared a second-story bedroom with his grandfather,
Jimmy Sinclair. Every morning at 3, his grandfather would sit at
the edge of his bed smoking a cigarette, ``and he'd wake me up,
too,'' says Sinden.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't so bad. It gave the boy more time to play in the
huge park known as Red Square across the street. ``I grew up on the
city streets,'' says Sinden. More accurately, he grew up on the
fields of Red Square, joining hundreds of other kids in whatever
sport was in season. During the winter, the baseball diamonds were
flooded to create three or four rinks, and Sinden would spend the
entire day playing a helter-skelter game of hockey. ``There might
be 100 kids on a rink at one time,'' he says. ``The older kids
would play end to end. The rest of us would play side to side or
corner to corner. You'd have to know who you were playing against
to stay in the right game.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden would go home to eat lunch, keeping his skates on while
his mother placed a towel under his feet to protect the floor, then
dash back to the pond until supper time. This was formal dining,
skates prohibited, but Sinden quickly would rejoin the action under
a lone street light and continue playing until the upstairs lights
in his house flashed. ``That was the signal to get your ass home,''
he says.
</P>
<P>
   When he could afford it, his father would take him to see the
NHL in action at Maple Leaf Gardens. Otherwise, ``it was the
pastime of every Canadian kid to listen to Maple Leaf games on the
radio,'' says Sinden. ``If they lost, you'd cry yourself to
sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   More often than not, Sinden would be playing the game,
developing into a slick, savvy defenseman _ ``like Brian Leetch
today,'' says Tindall _ with two major deficiencies: size (5 feet 9
inches, 180 pounds) and skating ability. Still, ``I never had
hockey off my mind,'' says Sinden. ``I never got it out of my mind
that I was going to be a player someday.''
</P>
<P>
   He was good enough to play at the major junior level, and at 17,
he joined the Oshawa Generals, relocating on his own 32 miles from
Toronto. ``Back then, it was forever,'' he says. ``There were no
throughways. My parents would come to see every home game, but I
was billeted with a family in Oshawa.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same street lived the Brodies, and each day, Sinden would
see their 16-year-old daughter, Eleanor, walking either to school
or her job at the telephone company. ``I wanted to ask her out,''
says Sinden, ``but I was kind of shy, so a buddy of mine did. Then
I said, `I'm going to ask her next.' Nobody else ever asked her
out.''
</P>
<P>
   They were married three years later, and within four years,
Nancy, Carol, and Donna were born; Julie would complete the family
a decade after that.
</P>
<P>
   His junior career finished, he no longer could afford to be a
carefree hockey player with big dreams. His skills were obvious:
``He was a real heady player,'' says Attersley, now a tire magnate
and for 11 years Whitby's mayor. ``When he'd get the puck in our
end, I'd know where to go and he'd put the puck right on my
stick.'' But his drawbacks were evident, too. In an expanded NHL,
he'd have had no problem becoming a mainstay, but the six-team
league had little room for diminutive, slow-footed defensemen.
There was only one minor league _ the American Hockey League _ at
the time, and it was the logical path for players biding their time
for a shot with the Original Six. ``But it also could be the path
to oblivion,'' says Sinden. And stability had become paramount. ``I
had plenty of opportunities to go to the AHL _ Hershey, Cleveland _
but I had to make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   He opted for the sure thing: employment at the General Motors
plant in Oshawa, where he had begun working as a stationary
engineer at age 19, running the gargantuan coal-driven steam
boilers that powered the tools for the production line. It was
steady work at decent money, and with union protection _ the NHLPA
might not appreciate the irony that Sinden eventually became a shop
steward _ it meant security. So while Sinden says that ``in the
back of your mind, you never give up the idea that you might make
it to the NHL someday,'' practically speaking, he was a full-time
blue-collar worker and part-time world-class amateur hockey player.
Just to keep a skate in the game, he accepted Blair's invitation to
join the Senior B team, and he often would work the graveyard shift
at GM, the team bus dropping him off at the plant's gates after
night games in Belleville or Kingston or Brockville or Cornwall so
he could start feeding the voracious furnaces at 1 a.m. And the
next day, there might be another game three hours away and more
graveyard duty at the end of the trail. But it was worth it to
Sinden, and Blair's boys flourished on the ice. After their
perilous second season, they became the Whitby Dunlops, sponsored
by the tire company, moving up to Senior A and winning the Allan
Cup as Canada's national amateur champions. They represented their
country at Oslo and won the world championship in the spring of
1958, and two years later, Sinden earned a silver medal as Canada
finished second to the upstart United States at the Squaw Valley
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, another minor circuit, the Eastern Professional
Hockey League, had begun play, and the woebegone Bruins intended to
install a team at Kingston, Ontario, with Blair in charge. He
wanted Sinden to go with him, but by now, Blair's best defenseman
was making $5,200 at GM, having risen from fourth- to second-class
engineer at the plant. And while he'd drop by Blair's house and
share a beer while sitting in his car in the driveway after his
shift, family man Sinden couldn't be enticed to make the move.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Blair called Boston GM Lynn Patrick and said, ``I want
to pay Sinden $5,200.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick almost swallowed the phone. ``Just what I need,'' he
barked at Blair. ``A slow 27-year-old defenseman for $5,200.
That'll get us out of last place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Who says I'm talking about him just as a defenseman?''
retorted Blair. ``You and Milt (Schmidt, the Boston coach) aren't
going to be around forever, and I think this kid has the potential
to take over the Bruins.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we're going,'' said Patrick, ``I may not be around
next week.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the GM needed no convincing about Sinden's leadership
possibilities. While scouting the Detroit-Toronto playoff series
that spring, he had shared several train rides with Sinden, who was
commuting to play on loan for the Montreal Canadiens' Hull-Ottawa
EPHL team. They had talked a lot of hockey; Patrick had liked what
he heard.
</P>
<P>
   So Sinden became Blair's captain at Kingston for the same money
he was making at GM. There even was a sweetener to the deal. ``They
gave me $2,500 to sign,'' says Sinden. ``That enabled me to get out
of debt.'' It seems the tax man is as relentless north of the
border as here; Revenue Canada was cracking down on the senior
amateur players for not reporting their per diem pittances as
income, and Sinden's toll came to $1,200, which he borrowed from
his grandmother.
</P>
<P>
   At last, he was a full-time hockey player at a living wage, but
as a fallback, he took a summer job as an engineer at a Kingston
nylon plant, then began selling real estate. Besides, he knew
playing wasn't his future. ``I never would have made the move from
Oshawa to Kingston,'' says Sinden, ``if I hadn't been interested in
coaching.''
</P>
<P>
   In his third year at Kingston, he became a player-coach under
Blair, and the following year, when the EPHL became the CHL and the
Bruins relocated their farm club to Minneapolis, Sinden went behind
the bench full time. Minneapolis gave way to Oklahoma City, and
after his title run there, Sinden was deemed ready to take over the
worst team in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   Those penny-pinching days and the Bruins' era of futility now
seem like ancient history. Sinden is entrenched as a seven-figure
executive, ``and that team has been consistent for so long,'' says
Glen Sather, the Edmonton Oilers president-GM who played for Sinden
in Oklahoma City and Boston and now accompanies him on offseason
hunting and fishing retreats in the Canadian wilds. ``It's very
well managed. Those people in Boston have no idea what that team
was like before he took over the reins.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he has spoiled them, because for all the rewards, it
seems the grief never ceases.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
