<HEADER>
A3117 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-HKN-BRUINS-SINDEN-3RD     11-08 1306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-SINDEN-3RD </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 (Repeating for all needing.)  
 BOSTON: ... never ceases.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is no simple label to place on the man or his reign.
Perhaps because of the disheveled look he presents after an evening
of intensive inspection of the product on the ice from his skybox
perch at the FleetCenter _ ``as if he just played the game,'' says
Sanderson _ and his often intransigent negotiating, Sinden is
caricatured as a rough-and-ready street brawler. That is as
inaccurate as it is simplistic.
</P>
<P>
   Sinden is a gourmet cook _ ``Well, I cook gourmet food,
anyway,'' he says with a laugh. ``I started it when I was coaching
because I found it relaxes me.'' He is a ravenous reader with a
preference for history who can expound on Churchill as readily as
he does the neutral zone trap. ``He's very complicated in many
ways,'' says Mark Witkin, agent for Bruins defenseman Don Sweeney,
among others. ``He's much more sophisticated than people would
think. He's a very intelligent man who can be gracious, and you can
learn a lot from him on a ton of subjects.''
</P>
<P>
   And, contrary to his bulldog reputation, he is a doer of good
deeds, though he prefers that they be kept below the radar. Sather
remembers being a lonely 20-year-old in Oklahoma City who was
invited to Christmas dinner by his coach, thus triggering a
lifelong friendship. Bruins senior assistant to the president Nate
Greenberg says Sinden regularly donates his speaking fees to
charity _ with the proviso that there be no publicity. Mark
Perrone, a former agent who represented Cam Neely, recalls that
when the Bruins star's father died of cancer, two people came to
his home in the middle of the night to console him: Perrone and
Sinden. He expressed similar sorrow when former loose-cannon Bruins
coach Don Cherry's wife, Rose, died; in the process, Sinden put
aside the fact that Cherry, now Canada's foremost TV-radio hockey
personality, had made him an object of ridicule ever since the
five-year relationship between GM and coach degenerated into a
blood feud before Cherry left in 1979. Cherry now says, ``I owe
everything I have to Harry Sinden.'' And Islanders GM Mike Milbury,
who served under Sinden as player, coach, and assistant GM, says,
``He's a good-hearted man. I won't even begin to list the number of
players he's helped with their lives after hockey. There's a
thousand of them. Just look at how many ex-Bruins wind up working
for the team in some capacity.'' Sometimes it goes beyond that.
Sanderson, now a successful businessman whose career was curtailed
by substance abuse, is forever grateful to Sinden for paying out of
his own pocket for part of his ex-player's hip replacements. ``And
he gave me the TV analyst's job early in my sobriety,'' says
Sanderson. ``He took a chance on me. He didn't have to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden's reputation at ice level is no less glossy. Through the
years, the Toronto street kid with the high school diploma and the
engineer's license has developed into perhaps hockey's most
eloquent spokesman. ``At the league level,'' says former Islanders
GM and current Florida Panthers president Bill Torrey, ``he's tried
to put the good of the game right at the top of the list.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheevers, now a Bruins scout, considers his boss ``the best
hockey guy I've been around, one of the few guys I've seen who
could coach in 1968 and 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it seems that recently, all that has been overshadowed by
the contract confrontations _ such as with Jason Allison, Anson
Carter, and Kyle McLaren last season, and Dafoe this year. And
there is a hornet's nest looming next summer, when the contracts of
Bourque, Allison, Sweeney, Carter, Dave Andreychuk, Joe Thornton,
and Sergei Samsonov, among others, expire. ``It's a lot of work,''
acknowledges Sinden. ``As always, we'll tinker with it, do what we
can, but we can only go so far.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because, as O'Connell says, ``We'll meet the market but
we won't set new markets.'' Meanwhile, Sinden looks at the
extravagant Rangers, who are paying a league-high $59 million for a
team that missed the playoffs last season, and warns, ``If we all
did business like New York, we'd all lose $40 million-$50
million.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not what the players and agents want to hear. Perrone
speaks for the minority when he says, ``I regard him as a true
purist, a guardian of the game, who carries the banner for the
traditionalists day in and day out.''
</P>
<P>
   Others believe Sinden's interpretation of tradition has become
tiresome. Allison, whose 1998-99 season began with a contract
hassle and ended with Sinden criticizing him for poor play in Game
6 of the second playoff round when the Bruins were eliminated at
Buffalo, won't discuss his boss. And Witkin says, ``If there's one
thing I could change, it's the specter of money that always
overhangs the team. I wish it wasn't so predominant.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who held out for 15 games last season, claims that
around the league, ``a lot of players I talk to think Boston is a
great city but don't want to play for Harry. That's the reputation
he's got. When I came here from Washington, I was surprised the
first time I met him to find out he was a regular guy. I thought he
was going to be the Grinch or something.''
</P>
<P>
   But even Carter acknowledges what Sinden always has maintained:
It's nothing personal. ``He's a nice man,'' says Carter. ``I try to
tell that to other guys. The negotiations are just something you
have to go through every couple of years, like a rite of passage.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a basic philosophy, and Sinden won't budge from it.
Dafoe, who was seeking a raise to $4 million from $850,000 and
eventually dimissed his agent, Ron Salcer, recalls, ``Harry told me
at one point, `It would be easy for me to give you $3.5 million,
considering the beating I'm taking from the public and press. But I
just don't think it's right.' What can I say? You have to respect
him for that. I think he thought he was being fair with me. And
after it was over, he talked to me for a half-hour and cleared the
air. I appreciated that.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's not as if the players are at the poverty level.
``There's a lot of healthy contracts around here,'' says Bourque,
who in the wake of losing his arbitration case signed a five-year,
$12.5 million contract that made him the highest-paid Bruin at the
time. ``There's a reason for that _ because Harry's so good at his
job.''
</P>
<P>
   His sheer longevity in that job, given its massive headaches and
burnout quotient, defies logic. Tom Johnson, recently retired as
Sinden's longtime lieutenant, takes a stab at explaining it. ``The
challenge,'' he says. ``The rules and regulations of the game, the
free agency and contracts _ he thrives on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Others marvel that he can stomach it. ``Although he keeps saying
he wants to go and he deserves that time, can he cut the cord?''
says current coach Pat Burns. ``As a friend, I'd like to see him do
it. As a coach, I don't want to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Sinden may be getting ready for a gradually reduced
role. He says he'd like to stay on for another five years but hints
that this may be his last as GM. ``It's definitely on my agenda,''
he says. In fact, he was ready to become exclusively club president
three years ago, but he thought that would be taking the easy way
out. The Bruins' three-decade playoff run had just ended, ``and I
didn't want to look like I was walking out'' on the mess.
</P>
<P>
   His heir apparent, O'Connell, is handling more of the daily
chores but isn't eager to let Sinden head into the sunset.
``Everything that comes up, I want to include him,'' says
O'Connell, ``because he has such good insights.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinden realizes that's subject to debate; it's the nature of the
beast. ``But I'm still doing it,'' he says, ``so I must enjoy it,
right?''
</P>
<P>
   That's the bottom line.
</P>
</TEXT>
