<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VIEQUES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BUYS TIME FOR DECISION ON TARGET RANGE IN PUERTO RICO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton is buying more time to seek a
compromise solution to a six-month standoff between the Navy and
Puerto Rico over using the island of Vieques for target practice.
</P>
<P>
   There's still ``a chance that we will reach an accommodation''
between the Navy's appeal to resume using the 58-year-old target
range and Puerto Rico's opposition to any resumption of
bombardment, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, citing his ``heavy responsibilities'' as
commander-in-chief to ensure preparation of American forces for
combat, said he hoped for a compromise that ``respects the
legitimate interests both of the people of Puerto Rico ... and the
national security interests of the Navy.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said ``about a month'' remained for a compromise to
emerge, adding: ``We're going to work hard at it.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's remarks came in an interview with the
Spanish-language television network Telemundo on Friday evening
during his visit to Hartford, Conn. The White House released a
transcript of the interview on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has pressed the White House for a presidential go-ahead
by mid-November to enable a Navy-Marine Corps battle group led by
the aircraft carrier USS Dwight D. Eisenhower to conduct four to
six weeks of combat rehearsals on Vieques beginning in early
December.
</P>
<P>
   The armada is scheduled to head to the Persian Gulf on Feb. 18.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's latest timetable for a decision give his
administration and the government of Puerto Rico more time to seek
a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Navy Lt. Cdr. Herman Phillips, a Navy spokesman at the Pentagon,
said Atlantic-based Navy and Marine forces ordinarily train
together for about a month around Vieques before returning to home
ports for about a month and then deploying overseas for six months.
</P>
<P>
   White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart said the president will
leave it to Defense Secretary William Cohen to seek a compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is very much looking forward to the Pentagon
continuing their dialogue and mediation and will look to their
recommendation on coming up with a solution to the Vieques
problem,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Puerto Rico Gov. Pedro Rossello continued to reject any
negotiations with the Pentagon that include resumption of live-fire
combat training on the nearby island.
</P>
<P>
   Rossello's spokesman, Alfonso Aguilar, said late Monday that the
governor was aware of the president's latest remarks but would not
open negotiations that included resumption of Navy and Marine Corps
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are willing to accommodate almost everything except that
the Navy has to close the target range and end the bombing on the
island of Vieques,'' said Rossello's spokesman. ``We're willing to
talk to the administration and continue talking _ but those two
conditions are not going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said last Thursday that he hoped to meet with Rossello to
``have a dialogue'' on the bitter dispute, adding: ``I would like
to talk to the governor.'' Rossello's spokesman said late Monday
that neither Cohen nor any of his staff had contacted the governor
to set up the summit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't received anything,'' Aguilar said.
</P>
<P>
   On Vieques, the 899-acre bombing range and an adjacent
11,000-acre Marine maneuver range have been closed since April 19
when a Marine Corps pilot mistakenly targeted a hilltop observation
post. The accidental twilight attack with two 500 pound bombs
killed David Sanes Rodriguez, 35, a Puerto Rican security guard
working for the Navy, and injured four other civilians working on
the bombing range.
</P>
<P>
   The accident, the first civilian death on the range since it
opened in 1941, took place almost 10 miles from a three-mile wide
swathe of land where 9,300 civilians reside on the island.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's renewed quest for compromise comes amid mounting
political pressure on Capitol Hill to clear the way for the Navy to
resume combat training on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman John Warner, R-Va.,
backed by Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., the panel's top Democrat, have
vowed to convene an emergency Senate hearing to challenge any White
House attempt to send the Navy battle group to the Persian Gulf
without combat training on Vieques.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
