<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3128 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-HNS &LR;      11-08 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELIS, PALESTINIANS BEGIN TOUGH PEACE TALKS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DEBORAH HORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank _ After a series of stops and starts,
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators Monday launched tough
negotiations aimed at reaching a comprehensive peace treaty by
September 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian negotiators, flanked by teams of
military advisers and experts, met for 75 minutes at the Grand Park
Hotel in the West Bank town of Ramallah, where they staked out
their opening positions on the most sensitive issues dividing them.
</P>
<P>
   They include the future of Jerusalem, the fates of Israeli
settlers and millions of Palestinian refugees, security
arrangements, secure borders and ``issues of common interest,''
such as water rights.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides sounded upbeat about reaching a deal by the date set
in the latest Israeli-Palestinian peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started with a very open and frank atmosphere, without any
barriers, and with this atmosphere, I believe we will be able to
build the agreement we all seek,'' said the lead Palestinian
negotiator, Information Minister Yasser Abed Rabbo.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli diplomat Oded Eran, who heads the Israeli team,
predicted the negotiators would be able to meet their ambitious
deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long road we have to cover in a very short time, but
(with a) joint effort we can make it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most political analysts predicted that the real bargaining will
be done through back channels similar to the secret talks in Oslo,
Norway, that led to the first Israeli-Palestinian peace agreement
in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing novel or unprecedented about this,'' said Mark
Heller, a political analyst at the Jaffee Center for Strategic
Studies, Tel Aviv University. ``This is the way negotiations have
always gone on.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, former Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres held the
first round of final status negotiations, a largely symbolic
meeting. Peres lost to Benjamin Netanyahu and serious negotiations
stalled after only one session.
</P>
<P>
   Three-and-a-half years later, Prime Minister Ehud Barak
relaunched the talks during a September meeting with Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's meeting was the first working session since then.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts said they expect a deal will be struck after both
sides make difficult concessions but that an agreement will not be
wrapped up in 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   On the Israeli side, the most difficult concession likely will
involve tearing down some settlements in the West Bank, which
Israel seized from Jordan in the 1967 Middle East war, and the Gaza
Strip, which Israel captured from Egypt in the same conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Barak has already talked about creating ``settlement blocks'' in
the West Bank and Gaza that would stay under Israeli sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   And the Israeli leader has proved his willingness to take on the
settlers by ordering 12 rogue West Bank outposts removed _ a move
not even the late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin felt he had
the political clout to do.
</P>
<P>
   On the Palestinian side, the most difficult bargaining will
probably be over the number of refugees allowed to return to the
West Bank and Gaza, analysts said. Most said the two sides will
likely agree on a number far smaller than the 4 million or so
Palestinians currently living outside the territory that became the
state of Israel in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Israelis have to make the huge step that they are going to
concentrate some settlements and remove the rest,'' said Reuven
Hazan, a political analyst at Jerusalem's Hebrew University.
</P>
<P>
   Hazen said Arafat must make ``the huge leap,'' but he added that
``I don't see the possibility of ... half a million (refugees) to
show up on the doorstep of the Palestinian Authority.''
</P>
<P>
   As for borders, Palestinians want Israel to withdraw from all of
the West Bank and Gaza to the boundary that existed before the 1967
war. Even the most dovish Israeli leaders talk about ceding 90
percent of Gaza and no more than 70 percent of the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The sides remain far apart on Jerusalem, by far the most
emotional issue at the talks. Israel maintains the city is its
indivisible, eternal capital. The Palestinians consider the eastern
half of Jerusalem as part of the West Bank and claim it as their
future capital.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Barak also has pledged to reach some kind of
understanding with Lebanon, or a full peace agreement with Syria,
that would allow him to pull troops out of southern Lebanon within
roughly a year. Israeli soldiers have occupied a strip of land
inside Lebanon since 1985. But their losses have mounted in recent
years in small-unit firefights with Islamic guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Some movement has occurred on the Syrian negotiating track,
which has been stalled for more than three years. Over the weekend,
Bashar Assad, Syrian President Hafez Assad's son, met with French
President Jacques Chirac. The president was expected to pass on the
issues they discussed to Barak, who arrived Monday in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
