A3138 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-MOLD09-COX     11-08 0286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOLD09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Five things to know about mold
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mold isn't just the stuff that grows on stale bread and old
cheese. Microscopic mold spores can trigger allergies and worsen
asthma, especially during the fall season. A few varieties are even
toxic. Here are some tips on how to reduce mold in your home.
</P>
<P>
   1. Mold likes wet places. So keep your house dry. In your
bathroom, run the exhaust vent while bathing or showering and for
at least 15 minutes afterward. If you don't have a vent in the
bathroom, open a window to let out moist air. (Generally, though,
windows should stay closed.) Fix cracked basement walls and leaky
pipes. Damp wallboard, wet carpets and even wet cardboard boxes
also are havens for mold. If flooding occurs, dry out everything as
quickly as possible. Once mold gets inside walls, it's very
difficult to eliminate.
</P>
<P>
   2. Keep windows closed. And use a dehumidifier.
</P>
<P>
   3. If you're sensitive to mold, find someone who isn't to mow
your lawn and rake leaves. Those activities can stir up mold
spores.
</P>
<P>
   4. Store firewood outside. Don't keep too many plants indoors _
mold likes wet soil.
</P>
<P>
   5. If you want to clean up mold yourself, wear a special mask
such as a respirator or a HEPA filter mask that will filter out
mold spores. Scrub _ don't scrape _ at mold patches, using a
solution of 1 cup of chlorine bleach to 1 gallon of water.
</P>
<P>
   Major mold problems may require professional cleaning. Look in
the Yellow Pages under ``Flood Control Equipment and Services.''
</P>
<P>
   _Lillian Lee Kim writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
