<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0369 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3141 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NC-SCHOOLS-COX     11-08 1797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NC-SCHOOLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barnes backs N.C. plan for Georgia schoolsBy Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SMITHFIELD, N.C. _ Teaching to the test.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what seventh-grade language-arts teacher Susie
Holloman is doing. Her 26 students have just been graded on a
practice version of North Carolina's seventh grade writing test,
five months before the real thing. Holloman is going over their
results like a coach at half-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state is going to give you a page and three-quarters of
another page,'' she explains. She's told them before, and tells
them again, this means you don't just fill one page. ``No, no, no,
no, no, no,'' she says. ``If the state gives you one and
three-fourths, how much will you write?''
</P>
<P>
   ``A page and three-fourths,'' the whole class chants.
</P>
<P>
   The weight given these standardized tests in North Carolina _
Holloman could buy a new dining room suite with the $1,500 bonus
she might win if Smithfield Middle School's scores improve enough _
is the engine that drives the kind of school-accountability system
that Gov. Roy Barnes has in mind for Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Barnes extols the North Carolina system for
replacing a sizable chunk of teacher pay raises with bonuses that
go only to schools that earn them based on state test results.
</P>
<P>
   The education reform commission Barnes created and chairs is
putting the finishing touches on a set of recommendations likely to
put Georgia on the same trail North Carolina has blazed since 1995.
On Monday, the commission will put together a preliminary plan.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina's ABCs of Public Education has been credited with
raising student achievement more dramatically than in any other
state, except perhaps Texas, which implemented similar reforms.
</P>
<P>
   The high stakes in North Carolina _ teacher bonuses, public
recognition of top schools, a year-long visit by a school
assistance team for a few very low-achieving schools _ create
intense pressure not to waste time in school.
</P>
<P>
   State officials say teaching to the test is part of why the
system works, because the tests are carefully matched with the
state's curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   But North Carolina's average SAT score, while rising a lot
faster than Georgia's, remains only one place above Georgia's
near-the-bottom ranking. Complaints and a few lawsuits have dogged
North Carolina's reforms since the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a while, and it's not foolproof and not perfect,''
said Jay Robinson, retired chairman of the state's Board of
Education, who is credited along with Gov. Jim Hunt with creating
the ABCs system. ``But it's better than anything we had.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's advice for Georgia: ``You're about in the same shape
we were in when we started this. If you don't start making
progress, we seriously run the risk of losing public schools as
we've known them.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina's bumpy ride can offer important lessons to
Georgia, though no easy solutions. As it turns out, getting
improved results is hard work, and never finished. Some unintended
consequences require fixes. Others require waiting and watching.
Others take toughing it out, say supporters of the reforms.
</P>
<P>
   But even disgruntled teachers and other critics in North
Carolina say a school accountability system is the only way to go.
The arguments now are about making adjustments in the system, not
turning back the clock. The main complaints heard in North Carolina
these days are:
</P>
<P>
   _ High-stakes testing is stressful for teachers and students
alike.
</P>
<P>
   _ Winning the big bucks seems to be unfairly difficult for some
schools, and seems to get harder after a few years of steady
improvement.
</P>
<P>
   _ Teaching to the test can squeeze instruction, giving short
shrift to in-depth projects or untested subjects such as art, music
and elementary science and social studies.
</P>
<P>
   Holloman's class at Smithfield Middle School may be an extreme
example of teaching to the test, since she specifically clues
students on what test-scorers will look for.
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to tell whether the students are pumped up, or
stressed out. Probably both. That ambiguity cuts through the entire
North Carolina school system.
</P>
<P>
   The two students who scored a perfect ``4'' on Holloman's
made-up test _ Larryshia Lewis and Juanita Flonard, who were asked
to stand for classroom applause _ had used what the state's
checklist calls ``power words'' (hard words like ``morose'' and
``tentative''), ``transitions'' (such as ``meanwhile'') and
``sensory details'' (details that use one of the five senses).
</P>
<P>
   ``Does it count on our grade, because the fourth grade writing
test didn't?'' asked Tracy Peele.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Holloman said, explaining to them that scores on the
real test will count for the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Troubling Consequences of the ABCs,'' a recent critical
report by The Common Sense Foundation, a Raleigh-based
social-justice advocacy group, called for extra incentives to keep
teachers from leaving low-performing schools, rewards for
successfully educating students of all races and tests that are
more open-ended, in contrast to the current dominance of
multiple-choice questions.
</P>
<P>
   Even the state Board of Education was concerned about what are
called the unintended consequences of the ABCs, such as whether to
test a student with excessive absences
</P>
<P>
   At a special meeting last week to look at such questions, no
changes were made. ``Our sense now is that this has served us
well,'' said Henry Johnson associate state superintendent for
instruction and accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Teachers feel heightened stress, clearly, but most say it has
brought a welcome focus to everything they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ABCs in North Carolina have improved instruction more than
anything,'' said Jerry Stevens, the engagingly informal principal
of Selma Elementary. ``I'm more focused, my faculty is more focused
and my parents are more focused on the basics of education.''
</P>
<P>
   The B of ABCs stands for the basics. The A is for
accountability, and the C for control, as in local control. The
state Department of Public Instruction drastically slashed its
staff and its regulations, on the theory that if you hold schools
and districts accountable for student achievement through a good
test, much of the state staffing and regulations aren't necessary.
</P>
<P>
   In unanticipated ways, accountability requires new state
controls, new regulations. At first, teachers who won bonuses voted
on whether to share their winnings with non-teaching staff. But so
many teachers complained about the pressure to share, the state
abolished the local vote on money-sharing and gives the money
directly to teachers and administrators, and a lesser bonus to
teacher aides. When the state discovered a district was shifting
struggling students out of high school courses midway through the
year into courses that aren't tested to avoid lowering the
end-of-course test average, it imposed a rule against the practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brings you back to rules and regulations,'' said Lou
Fabrizio, state director of accountability services. ``That's the
bottom-line, number one problem. Local control and accountability
are in conflict, or sometimes at odds.''
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, the principal, has bones to pick with the ABCs.
Although the formula is designed to be fair to high-poverty schools
like Selma Elementary by rewarding year-to-year improvement,
Stevens believes the formula has worked against him. He said the
reason his school failed to make even ``expected'' improvement last
year was because its scores were high to begin with. Also, he
believes improvement comes more slowly with students like his, many
from ragged circumstances in housing projects and trailer parks.
</P>
<P>
   Selma Elementary missed winning a ``School of Distinction''
rating only because its writing scores fell from number two in the
county to dead last. Stevens said he has no idea why those scores
fell.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he says the tests are fair because they are strictly
based on the state's curriculum. The ABCs make everybody work
harder to teach that curriculum, he said. ``We're biting and
clawing as hard as we can to get that money,'' he said. ``It
becomes my job to keep the morale of this school up.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnston County, a half-hour drive southeast of Raleigh, has
been an incubator of school reform. When Gov. Barnes kicked off his
reform commission June 7, the county's superintendent, James
Causby, was the keynote speaker, after Barnes.
</P>
<P>
   When the ABCs were introducing high-stakes accountability to
schools in 1996, Causby was using the same test for high-stakes
accountability for individual students in Johnston County. Students
in grades three through eight must score at grade level or better
to be promoted, with exceptions allowed on appeal. High school
students must do the same on state end-of-course tests to get
course credit.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the state is phasing in a similar student accountability
system. The Johnston County system, which includes Selma Elementary
and Smithfield Middle Schools, requires parents to sign a
school-partnership agreement and begin having conferences with
teachers the first month of school. Failure to do so means their
child will be barred from extracurricular activities, won't bring
home a report card and can't have a parking space in high school.
</P>
<P>
   The county, struggling between tobacco farming and industries
not close enough to benefit from the Research Triangle miracle,
used to have a real estate slump because of its schools. Now
schools are driving the real estate market. Student performance has
skyrocketed, even compared to rising scores statewide. The gap in
achievement between black students and all students, which has been
narrowing statewide, has narrowed far more dramatically in Johnston
County. Locally, between '94 and '98, the percent of black students
scoring at or above grade level in math rose from 37 percent to 69
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The gap between this black achievement locally and that of all
students in the state, during the same years, fell from 27
percentile points to only 7 percentile points.
</P>
<P>
   Causby says that critics who complain schools can't show
improvement after two or three years are wrong. Further improvement
simply requires a change in strategy. Once you've moved your
borderline students up to grade level, you have to start teaching
all students in much smaller groups at their various levels. ``It's
wonderful, but no one knew this was going to happen,'' Causby said.
``The thing about the ABC plan is, it's working out to be exactly
what we need, step by step. It was never designed that way. It just
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Cumming writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
