<HEADER>
A3143 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-NEWSTAND09-COX     11-08 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWSTAND09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magazine maps genealogy route for families
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everything is relative, it seems, as ``roots mania'' has spread
from county courthouses to the Internet. Nearly 19 million adults
are actively tracing their family histories, according to American
Demographics. Now they'll have more help.
</P>
<P>
   Family Tree ($3.99), a glossy, colorful magazine, debuts this
month with articles about Web sites, scrapbooking, historic travel
and other resources. The January issue (the magazine will be
published bimonthly) offers step-by-step advice on getting started,
preserving family photos and researching arrivals at Ellis Island,
and gives tips from author Homer Hickam Jr. (``October Sky'') on
how to make the chronicle of your life take off like a rocket.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Counterfeit chipper: Some of the most prized archaeological
treasures are Clovis points _ the spear tips carved from stones
13,000 years ago by the inhabitants of what is now New Mexico. In
The New Yorker ($3), Douglas Preston locates a Warner Robins man
who can reproduce these exquisite artifacts so faithfully even
experts were fooled. Woody Blackwell, a former counterintelligence
specialist in the Air Force, rediscovered the techniques of rock
``knapping'' after years of trial and error. Under financial
pressure, he began selling his reproductions as genuine. When
Blackwell was finally exposed, in part by his own admission, he
returned all the money. Now he says it all began with a dream in
which he could see a group of Clovis men sitting around a campfire,
telling stories and passing around big, beautiful spear tips. With
every Clovis point he makes, Blackwell says, ``I wonder if this
will be the price of admission, the ticket to let me go back and
sit with those guys.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wolf in the door: The fallout continues from the story that Al
Gore hired controversial feminist author Naomi Wolf to help in his
presidential campaign and, perhaps, convert him from a Beta male to
an Alpha male. Time ($3.50) reports that Gore's female supporters
were surprised and angry to learn that Wolf was being paid $15,000
a month.
</P>
<P>
   Since campaign manager
</P>
<P>
   Donna Brazile found out
</P>
<P>
   about it, that amount has been reduced to $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Secret life: Newsweek ($3.50) follows presidential contenders
John McCain and Bill Bradley and explains the candidates are
gaining ground because of their air of authenticity. But the most
intriguing article this week is the profile of Laurie Hiett, the
U.S. Army colonel's wife in Fort Bragg, N.C., who has been charged
with cocaine trafficking. The former high school Spanish teacher
led a double life _ one as a dutiful military spouse, the other as
an associate of an ex-stripper and part-time prostitute.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More than a game: Mother Jones ($3.95) assesses computer games
such as Duke Nukem and Kingpin and finds an astonishing level of
violence. Kids who play graphic games say the violence doesn't
translate into reality. But, says University of Miami professor
Eugene Provenzo, ``We're on a trajectory toward increasing realism,
or hyperreality, that makes people start thinking they can shoot
someone and it doesn't hurt, that they can recover.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quick reads: Maxim ($3.99) features a revealing photo layout
of actress Jennifer Love Hewitt and a not-so-revealing interview.
We do learn that her biggest vice is Coca-Cola. ... U.S. News &AMP;
World Report ($3.50) picks the best Web sites and reviews the
glitzy new gadgets for the holidays, including the Reebok Traxtar,
electronic shoes that rate kids' athletic performances.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
