<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3144 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SLAVERY09-COX     11-08 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAVERY09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    African-American psychiatrists a rare breed
 &HT;    By John Head
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After a 15-year broadcast journalism career that
included prize-winning work on medical issues, Sandra Clement
Walker decided she could do more good practicing medicine than she
could reporting on it, especially in the mental health field, where
there are few African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Becoming a black psychiatrist made her a rarity: There are only
a few thousand in the United States, according to the National
Association of Black Psychologists. And Walker, 50, is one of only
a few of the country's African-American psychoanalysts in training,
according to the American Psychoanalytic Association.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle-based psychiatrist is on a three-day visit to
Atlanta sponsored by the Atlanta Foundation for Psychoanalysis.
She'll lead a public discussion of ``Sankofa,'' a film about the
impact of slavery on African-Americans, and will make presentations
to the Emory University Department of Psychiatry and the Morehouse
School of Medicine. Staff writer John Head talked with Walker by
telephone last week.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What do you hope will be the impact of the first surgeon
general's report on Mental Health, due out this year?
</P>
<P>
   A: It really brings attention to mental health in a way that's
important. The absence of mental health is highly stigmatized in
this country, and it makes it very difficult for people who have
mental and emotional problems to feel comfortable getting care.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So having the surgeon general focus on mental health will
bring changes?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not that simple ... There are a lot of intrinsic,
difficult things about mental illness that make solutions not
simple. But focusing more attention and educating the public more
about mental illness _ about what mental illnesses are, about what
treatments are available _ is going to be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Surgeon General David Satcher has expressed concern over the
``national epidemic'' of suicide, particularly the rising rate
among young African-Americans. What accounts for the increase in
the suicides in this group that traditionally has had a low suicide
rate?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm not a guru in that area, but I think the pressures on
kids across the board are very great today. There's a lot of
pressure on kids to do well, to succeed materially. The
opportunities for many kids are not keeping pace with their
expectations ... I don't think there's one answer to that question.
There are many factors that play into the kind of concerns we face
with kids killing themselves. The other big one is access to lethal
things, like guns. That's a big problem.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are there special mental health concerns for
African-Americans who have had to deal with racism?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's a fascinating question, and that's something that I
think about every day in my practice and my work. Racism and the
heritage from slavery in this country have ongoing meanings for
African-Americans and for whites ... Many of the African-American
patients I work with have experienced narcissistic injury _ injury
to their sense of self _ as a result of racism ... For
African-Americans who are seeking treatment and help, providing a
setting where those issues can come up comfortably is important.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's more important: Bringing in more African-American
mental health-care providers or training all providers to take into
account cultural differences in deciding on how to treat patients?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's not either/or. It really has to be both. Having more
minority providers is complicated, but important ... Since that
isn't going to happen overnight _ and maybe never will happen _
it's important to help other providers understand the needs of
African-American and minority patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sankofa,'' by Ethiopian filmmaker Haile Gerima, will be shown
and discussed at 8 tonight in the Emory University Geosciences
Building, 1557 Pierce Drive Information about the movie is
available at www.sankofa.com. The discussion is free and open to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   John Head writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
