<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3146 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-USHER09-COX     11-08 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USHER09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With first major film role, Usher does it his way
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Usher Raymond IV has never been a high school student.
He has never had a close relationship with his father. And he's
more likely to lead people to dance than revolt.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in ``Light It Up,'' in theaters Wednesday, the 21-year-old
plays a crusading high school student whose bond with his father is
shattered by a policeman's bullet. (Raymond describes his
relationship with his biological father as ``basically
nonexistent.'') His character, Lester, leads an uprising of
students fed up with conditions in their high school. For Raymond,
this is acting.
</P>
<P>
   While his peers were in algebra and gym class, Raymond _ who
attended school through eighth grade and finished his education
with tutors _ was developing a recording career with Atlanta-based
LaFace Records. His self-titled 1994 debut hit the respectable
500,000 mark, but its 1997 follow-up, ``My Way,'' hit big. The 4
million-selling album earned him a Grammy Award nomination, the
distinction of being named Billboard magazine's artist of the year
and widespread attention both inside and outside the music
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (we) first saw him, we saw the star potential,'' says
Kenneth ``Babyface'' Edmonds, co-president of Raymond's label and
executive producer of ``Light It Up.'' ``We just had this feeling
that whatever direction he took, he would be a force in the
entertainment business.''
</P>
<P>
   Raymond also has become a businessman. He has a deal to write
and produce for other artists. He has his own record label, Us
Records. And he and his mother and manager, Jonnetta Patterson, run
J-Pat Management.
</P>
<P>
   It was at the Doraville office of J-Pat that we learned how
Raymond is managing his three pursuits:
</P>
<P>
   Q: How have you prepared for being an actor?
</P>
<P>
   A: For earlier roles like on (television's) ``Moesha,'' I just
applied things from my life. I had a girlfriend who studied theater
at Spelman College, and I would use little things that she told me.
Outside of that, I had an acting coach for this role. And I didn't
go into it with fear. I prayed to God like, ``I know I've never
done this, but just give me the strength to go in here and present
myself as professionally as I possibly can.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: What did being in the movies ``The Faculty'' and ``She's All
That'' do for you as an actor?
</P>
<P>
   A: It gave me experience.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In those small roles we didn't get a sense of whether you
could act or not, did we?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think people were deceived. Because of the way they
promoted (``The Faculty''), they made it seem like it was my movie.
But now I finally have a leading role. And there's others to come.
I've done another film called ``Texas Rangers'' (with James Van Der
Beek of ``Dawson's Creek'' and Dylan McDermott of ``The
Practice''). And for television I've done ``Geppetto'' with Drew
Carey.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In ``Light It Up'' though, your character really has to
exhibit a range of emotions, doesn't he?
</P>
<P>
   A: And I really had to pull from a lot of mine. Some things ...
some things I would ... like my relationship with my father, I
would apply that to the relationship that Lester has with his
father.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Can you characterize your relationship with your father?
</P>
<P>
   A: Basically it was shattered at a young age. Unfortunately, my
father wasn't mature enough to be there for his child. But I had
someone who was there and believed in me, and that was God. He
placed people in my life that made me believe in myself. And my
mother was the main person. I've spoken to my father. We're sort of
building a rapport with each other. But more or less we're just
trying to have conversations, because what do we have in common
other than he's my father and I'm his son? Those are titles with no
real meaning. I did have a stepfather, who was a great guy. He
taught me a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Another thing that distinguishes Lester from Usher on-screen
is that Lester has a hard times with the girls, right?
</P>
<P>
   A: (Laughs.) That's one of the things I liked about the
character. I just wanted it to be cute like, ``Aw, he likes her.
And she won't give him a chance.'' I didn't want to seem too sexy,
sexual, you know, licking my lips (like) ``What's up baby? How you
feeling?''
</P>
<P>
   Q: You didn't want to be the guy on the cover of Vibe?
</P>
<P>
   A: With the shirt off, the water running down my chest and the
whole nine? Naw.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are you done with that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Am I done with it? Well, I know people say every time Usher
is on TV he's taking his clothes off. But a lot of people go
through that. Marvin Gaye went through that for a while. He was
dropping his pants and taking off his shirt for a while because he
knew how to give the crowd what they wanted. And as an entertainer,
that's what your job is.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes you have to reserve something for yourself. And
I'm being a little more cautious now because I have a broader
audience. I have younger kids watching me, looking up to me and
listening closely to what I'm singing about.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does acting do for you that singing doesn't?
</P>
<P>
   A: It allows me to have multiple personalities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does singing do for you that acting doesn't?
</P>
<P>
   A: With singing, you have more of a direct connection. You speak
directly to the souls of people.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How do you think ``Light It Up'' will connect with teenagers?
Afraid it may start some copycat school takeovers?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. I think this movie clearly says these are mostly smart
kids who made a dumb move. I think because some of the situations
are so real to life _ police harassment, overflowing classes,
schools being in bad shape and so on _ hopefully it will really hit
home. But no, I don't think kids will leave home and light up their
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
