</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-WALL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BERLIN WALL IS GONE, BUT THE QUEST FOR IDENTITY GOES ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., see related GERMANY-BERLIN) 
 (HLW)  
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Having guarded the ramparts of East German communism
for 28 years, Harald Jaeger knew his business at the Berlin Wall.
So the statement by the Politburo member on television on that
night _ Nov. 9, 1989 _ struck him as lunacy.
</P>
<P>
   But the words were clear enough. Guenter Schabowski,
representing the communist state's highest authority, said that
East Germans were free to travel ``without meeting special
provisions'' and that the new rule would go into effect
``immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaeger, then a 46-year-old lieutenant colonel in the East German
border guards, almost choked on his sandwich. ``On the one hand, I
knew what the party said was law,'' he said recently. ``On the
other, I was commanding a critical border post, and nobody had
alerted us to any change of policy.''
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, it is clear that Jaeger's confusion was widely
shared. Virtually nobody predicted the fall of the Berlin Wall, and
apparently nobody planned it. At its most sensitive point, the
Soviet empire imploded, undone by economic decay and by Mikhail
Gorbachev's renunciation of the force ultimately needed to hold it
together.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, two German states with utterly divergent ideologies
and cultures found themselves propelled toward union on the panicky
reaction of a border guard, Jaeger, who opened the gate at Berlin's
Bornholmerstrasse crossing, in the absence of instructions about
what to do. Some of the effects of that precipitation are still
evident today.
</P>
<P>
   Most fundamentally, a united Germany is not quite sure of its
identity. ``Is Germany a great power?'' the weekly magazine Der
Spiegel asked this week on the cover of its issue commemorating the
10th anniversary of the wall's fall. The image above the question:
a German eagle borne aloft by the Brandenburg Gate's winged goddess
of Victory.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder recently answered the question in
the affirmative, calling Germany a ``great European power.'' On one
level, even though the country has no nuclear bomb, he is clearly
right.
</P>
<P>
   The German economy is one-third bigger than any other in Europe.
And in a potent symbol of the country's post-Cold War emancipation,
a German general now commands allied forces in Kosovo, something
unthinkable even five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But the nature of that power, and of a new German patriotism, is
less clear because German unity abruptly brought together in a
single state zealous Communists like Jaeger, mild West Germans
anxious to escape German identity by calling themselves
``Europeans'' and some East Germans with strong nationalistic
feelings for a united Germany.
</P>
<P>
   What seems evident, a decade after the wall's fall, is that the
broad postwar consensus around the ``constitutional patriotism''
proposed by the prominent intellectual Juergen Habermas has eroded.
This, in essence, was an almost abstract German patriotism built on
values like free speech and the rule of law _ those that the Nazis
had trampled.
</P>
<P>
   In its place is a jumble. Hans-Peter Mueller, a political
scientist, said, ``The reference point of `never again' to the
Holocaust still exists, but alongside it we have the patriotic
nostalgia of those who feel they lost their state in the East, the
right-wing radicalism of the frustrated and some conservative
attempts to lift German taboos.''
</P>
<P>
   The project of the last decade has been the unification of a
highly developed Western country that is ashamed of its past and
rooted in NATO with a crumbling East German state raised to believe
it had fought an anti-fascist struggle against Hitler and to see
NATO as its mortal enemy. Given the dimensions of the task,
difficulties were inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   But most Germans of east and west now agree that, however great
the achievements of the last decade, there were also mistakes that
increased the difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Among them were the headlong economic reforms that left about 20
percent of eastern Germans unemployed, a failure in the west to
come up with gestures to soften the eastern sense of being taken
over and the too-easy promises that suggested to eastern Germans
that capitalism was a code word for get-rich-quick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have paid for having no plan,'' said Willi Heidemann, the
top administrative official in Jerxheim, a town that once stood
just west of the border. ``West Germany's Constitution made clear
from 1949 that the aim was unification, but it was an aim without a
project right up to the last moment. Nobody believed that border
would disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Least of all Jaeger, who became a border guard when the wall _
102.7 miles of a barrier encircling West Berlin _ went up in 1961
to stanch the flow of about 2,000 people a day fleeing to the West.
</P>
<P>
   He believed in socialism; he believed that the people on the
western side of the wall were his ``class enemy.'' Because East
Germany was independent, he considered it that state's right to
protect its borders as it saw fit, even after the killing of more
than 450 people who had tried to escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was lucky I was never placed in that situation, but
believing what I believed then, I too would have shot anyone trying
to flee,'' said Jaeger, who now runs a small newspaper store in
Berlin. ``At the same time, by that night in 1989, I could see that
we were directionless, that the leadership had lost control.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in the summer of 1989, though, thousands of East
Germans had been escaping through Hungary's newly opened borders
with the West without any response from Moscow. In East Germany, on
Oct. 18, Egon Krenz eased out Erich Honecker, the autocrat who had
governed since 1971. But the new leadership could not control
mounting street demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   Krenz visited Moscow on Oct. 31 and met Gorbachev, who made
clear that the Soviet leadership opposed German unification, but
also that it opposed any use of force. The people, Gorbachev said,
should not be regarded as an enemy; on the contrary, policies
should be found to bring them around.
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Jaeger said, he received instructions several days
before Nov. 9 that force should not be used on any account. But as
to what he should do if a crowd came toward his command post at the
wall, there was silence.
</P>
<P>
   In the early evening, shortly after Schabowski's televised news
conference, about 10 or 15 people gathered in front of Jaeger,
shouting that the party had declared they were free to travel
``immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Jaeger was at a loss. What these people said was true. But he
had no instructions, and, like many in the East, he had spent his
life obeying orders.
</P>
<P>
   So he called his superior, Col. Rudi Ziegenhorn, to ask what to
do. The following conversation, as Jaeger recalled it, ensued.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you hear that nonsense on television?'' Ziegenhorn asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, that's why I'm calling.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How many are there in front of you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``About 15.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the law _ send them back,'' Ziegenhorn concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The group of soldiers under Jaeger's command tried to do just
that, but more people kept arriving, and unwilling to threaten
force, the border guards had no means of coercion. An attempt to
persuade people to go to their local police stations to obtain
visas backfired when a few went, found the stations closed, and
returned more determined to cross.
</P>
<P>
   About a half-hour later, Ziegenhorn called back, saying that the
people he described as ``provocateurs'' _ essentially those
shouting loudest _ should be allowed out to the West, but that the
photographs on their passports should be stamped with the
understanding that they would not be allowed to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea was to open the valve a little and relieve the
tension through what amounted to selective expulsions,'' Jaeger
said. ``But the idea proved disastrous because people got the
impression that if they shouted loudly enough, they would be
allowed out.''
</P>
<P>
   So the commander of the Bornholmerstrasse section of the wall
called his superior again. Colonel Ziegenhorn had meanwhile spoken
to his superior, the deputy minister of state security, Gerhard
Neiber, to see if anyone knew what should be done. Apparently no
one did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ziegenhorn told me that there were no more orders, nothing
else to say,'' Jaeger said. ``In effect, I was on my own.''
</P>
<P>
   By 10:30 p.m., that isolation was becoming increasingly painful.
Thousands were in the street, pressing forward. The soldiers under
his command were urging him to make a decision. ``But,'' Jaeger
said, ``that wall was my life. I'd defended it for 28 years. It was
not like kicking over a bucket.''
</P>
<P>
   For about another 30 minutes, Jaeger wavered, torn between fear
of a violent catastrophe and terror of opening up a wall he
regarded as his. But with the pressure from the crowd mounting
constantly, he gave the order, shortly after 11 p.m., to open the
gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not free Europe, or release my people, or any of that
nonsense,'' Jaeger said. ``It was that crowd in front of me, and
the hopeless confusion of my leadership, that opened those gates.''
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmed by what he had done, Jaeger hesitated to call
Ziegenhorn back. But eventually he informed his superior of his
decision. ``Das ist gut, mein Junge,'' _ ``You did right, young
man'' _ was the cursory reply.
</P>
<P>
   So ended East Germany, the division of Europe, the Cold War, and
around the globe, much else that, for good or ill, had depended on
the global struggle between capitalism and communism. Jaeger's long
career as a border guard also ended, of course.
</P>
<P>
   As for millions of eastern Germans, unemployment followed for
him and for his wife, and a long struggle to adjust to the values
of a society he had long opposed.
</P>
<P>
   Many thousands of eastern Germans moved from the east to the
west. But while there is still a lot of migration each year, an
increasing number of western Germans also move to the east. Last
year, the Federal Statistics Office reported, 182,000 Germans moved
from east to west, 30,000 more than moved in the opposite
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Jaeger stayed in Berlin, and finally, in 1997, he was able to
borrow the money so that he and his wife could start a newspaper
store.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose I'm a capitalist,'' he said. ``I exploit my wife,
and she exploits me. That's our capitalism. But I listen to the
people in the store worrying about jobs for their children, and I
still have my doubts about this system.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not alone. ``Wir sind das Volk'' _ ``We are the people'' _
was the cry of East German protesters in 1989. Today, a large, sad
banner hangs at the Alexanderplatz, the former center of East
Berlin, saying: ``Wir waren das Volk'' _ ``We were the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, stalls sell T-shirts emblazoned with the German eagle
and the bold word: ``Deutschland.'' Between the nostalgic
disillusionment of that banner and the patriotism of that shirt, a
united Germany struggles today to define itself.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1840EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
