<HEADER>
A3166 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS &LR;      11-08 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CELTICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS SIGN DOUG OVERTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL HARBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Hello, Doug Overton; goodbye, Wayne Turner.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics made a move to add depth and experience to their
backcourt Monday by signing Overton, 30, an NBA journeyman who has
played 351 games with five teams over the last seven years. To make
room on the roster, the Celtics released Turner, 23, a free agent
rookie who grew up in Boston and had a starry career at the
University of Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Turner's inexperience and inability to play at the NBA level
were exposed during Dana Barros's absence. He appeared in three
games and averaged 1.3 points, 1.7 assists and 1.0 rebound, in 41
total minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne needs experience and playing time,'' said coach Rick
Pinto, ``either with another team that has one or two point guards
or in the CBA, where he can play 35 or 38 minutes a game. We're
very interested in Wayne in the future. But playing no minutes or
one or two minutes is not going to get him any experience to grow
as a basketball player.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics have been looking for help at point guard for a
while and contacted Overton's agent last week. Overton's contract
is not a 10-day deal; it's for the remainder of the season.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, he expected to be playing in his hometown of
Philadelphia. Overton went to training camp with the Sixers but was
cut Oct. 28, just days before the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised when they let me go,'' said Overton, a La
Salle graduate. ``I sort of got caught in a numbers game. But I've
been in this business and in this situation before. You just got to
look at it for what it's worth and move on. Some things you can't
control.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitino considers Overton an insurance policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we need is experience,'' said the coach. ``We need
somebody so that if Kenny (Anderson) rolls his ankle for five games
and he's out, we need an experienced point guard and keep Dana with
the second unit.''
</P>
<P>
   Overton understands that he is behind Anderson and Barros.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm going to be ready,'' he said. ``Injuries happen.
Different things happen when you get your opportunity. Just got to
be ready to perform.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's played a lot of minutes in this league,'' said Pitino.
``And we got great reports about his attitude, his desire to work,
and everything checked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We waited for a veteran to become available. We wanted to give
Wayne a good look and we're interested in his future. But it's best
for him and best for us that he gets some experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Overton originally was drafted by the Pistons in the second
round (40th overall) in 1991. His best year in the NBA was with
Washington in 1994-95, when he appeared in 82 games, averaging 7.0
points, 3.0 assists, and 1.7 rebounds. He split the abbreviated
1999 season with Orlando, New Jersey, and Philadelphia, averaging
3.8 points in 24 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited,'' said Overton. ``I've been around with quite a
few teams in the league. It's a fresh new start and the team's off
to a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Overton will be reunited with former teammates Pervis Ellison
and Calbert Cheaney. He also played with Marty Conlon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty's been everywhere,'' joked Overton. ``Who hasn't played
with Marty?''
</P>
<P>
   He brings to the Celtics a go-go attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know how the NBA game is played,'' said Overton. ``I've been
around. This is my eighth year. Whether I play three minutes or 30
minutes, I'm going to go out there and scrap. I'll play hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Overton has accepted the idea of being a journeyman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing is to never get down when things are
tough, and I'm the type of guy that's fighting for my life every
year,'' he said. ``I know that, so that's how I play every day. I
come out and I play hard and I leave everything out there, and
whatever happens, happens.''
</P>
<P>
   He is looking forward to playing for Pitino.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he plays a lot of guys and he gets them in there
fast,'' said Overton. ``I hope to get some minutes. You've always
got to be ready for him to throw you into a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Overton, who worked out with the Celtics Monday morning, will
wear No. 20, last worn by Marlon Garnett. Picking up the offensive
system shouldn't be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played in this division for most of my career,'' he said.
``So I've been in the middle of a lot of the plays on the defensive
end, so I know the calls and know what they are running.
Defensively, I think that will be the adjustment, with all the
trapping and different signals, but I'll pick it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1843EST &QL; 
