<SLUG> BC-PAGENET-ARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCH COMMUNICATIONS TO BUY PAGENET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Arch Communications Group Inc., the Westborough, Mass. number
two-ranked US paging company, agreed Monday to buy its larger rival
Paging Network Inc. of Dallas for $1.36 billion in an effort to
fend off fierce competition from wireless phone companies and a
possible PageNet bankruptcy filing.
</P>
<P>
   The companies hope to wipe out $1.6 billion in debt and
preferred shares by exchanging them for common stock. Arch will
also swap its stock for PageNet shares at a price 12 percent below
Friday's close, but PageNet warned it will file for Chapter 11
bankruptcy unless enough shareholders and bondholders accept the
deal.
</P>
<P>
   The new company will continue to be called Arch and remain based
in Westborough. It expects to save $80 million over the first two
years after the deal closes in mid-2000 and enjoy gross revenues of
$1.7 billion annually, with positive free cash flow before taxes,
depreciation and amortization.
</P>
<P>
   The paging industry has been struggling in recent years as more
than 70 million Americans have come to own wireless phones, some of
which now include paging capabilities or are used as a
direct-calling alternative to paging. Arch bought bankrupt paging
company MobileMedia Corp. in April, one of 34 companies it has
acquired to build a nationwide footprint.
</P>
<P>
   Shares in PageNet, which have plunged 78 percent this year,
gained 1/16 to close at 1 1/32 in Nasdaq Stock Market trading. Arch
shares, which have climbed 43 percent, shed 5/8 in Nasdaq trading
to close at 6 3/16.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best of poor alternatives,'' Sean Egan, a managing
director at bond rating firm Egan-Jones Ratings Co., told Bloomberg
News. ``It's either this or Chapter 11, where the legal costs will
eat up what's left'' of PageNet.
</P>
<P>
   The companies would combine under a complex deal that requires
shareholder and regulatory approval and involves:
</P>
<P>
   --Arch exchanging 12.47 of its shares for every 100 PageNet
common shares, worth about 85 cents per PageNet share.
</P>
<P>
   --PageNet bondholders owning 44.5 percent of the combined
company, or just over $500 million in stock. PageNet has $1.2
billion in senior notes and $804 million in bank debt.
</P>
<P>
   --Arch investors swapping $384 million in senior notes and $28
million in preferred shares for common stock, which with the
PageNet debt swap would reduce the combined company's total debt to
$1.8 billion, down 46 percent from current levels.
</P>
<P>
   --PageNet stock and note holders will get an 80.5 percent stake
in its Vast Solutions unit, a business wireless services operation
that is to be spun off as a freestanding company. Shareholders in
the new Arch will own the other 19.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both Arch and PageNet serve all 50 states. Arch has 7 million
pagers in service, while PageNet has 9.7 million, but has never
turned a profit since it went public in 1991. Arch officials hope
to grow profits by moving into two-way paging and other high-value
services such as news and information broadcast to pagers from
Bloomberg, CNN, ESPN and other outlets.
</P>
<P>
   C. Edward Baker Jr., Arch chairman and chief executive, who will
be CEO of the combined company, said, ``We believe the combination
of two very strong distribution vehicles will build a formidable
competitor whose business will extend far beyond the industry's
traditional focus in paging.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1845EST &QL; 
