<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HAGEN-WOOLF-ART-NYT &LR;      11-08 1253
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAGEN-WOOLF-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UTA HAGEN RETURNING TO `VIRGINIA WOOLF' FOR A DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Great Britain)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MEL GUSSOW    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Uta Hagen played Martha in the original Broadway
production of Edward Albee's ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?'' in
1962, she placed her galvanic imprint on the role and helped to
define the play.
</P>
<P>
   Something similar occurred at least twice in plays by Tennessee
Williams, with Laurette Taylor in ``The Glass Menagerie'' and
Marlon Brando in ``A Streetcar Named Desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hagen has occasionally returned to other roles, but after
closing in ``Virginia Woolf'' in London in 1964 and making an
original cast recording, she has never again appeared in the play _
until now.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday she will once more assume the mantle of Martha, for
one performance only in a staged reading at the Majestic Theater on
Broadway. The reading will be for the benefit of the HB Playwrights
Foundation (created by Ms. Hagen and her husband, Herbert Berghof)
and in celebration of her 80th-birthday year. Jonathan Pryce will
play opposite her as George (replacing the previously announced
Anthony Hopkins) and Matthew Broderick and Mia Farrow will be Nick
and Honey. Tickets to the event, which will begin at 6 p.m., and
the birthday supper after the performance are available through the
HB Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Ms. Hagen made it clear she was very
aware of the pitfalls of replaying such a signature role, for which
she won a Tony Award as best actress. ``It's a terrible risk for
me,'' she said. ``I'm 28 years too old for the part. I was 42 when
I played it. Martha's supposed to be 52. People have such
incredible memories of my performance. I don't see how anybody
could possibly live up to it, certainly not me almost 40 years
later.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of challenging herself is pervasive in her career: her
book on the art of acting is called ``A Challenge for the Actor.''
She indicated that her performance would be different, but said she
did not not yet know what direction it would take. Looking back on
her first Martha, she said, ``I remembered what I experienced
playing the role, but I don't remember how it came across.''
</P>
<P>
   The reading was suggested by Robert Callely, the managing
director of the HB Foundation. After Ms. Hagen agreed to take part,
her first step was to reread the play. ``I forgot how vicious
Martha is,'' she said. ``The play is still one body blow after
another. I'd be curious to see how an audience responds to that
now.''
</P>
<P>
   She added quickly that both Martha and George, the mutually
abusive, intimately allied faculty couple, are victims: ``Both
those people have to be in hell. If only one is in hell, the play
is still wonderful, but not as good as it could be.'' Saying that,
she paid tribute to her first George, Arthur Hill (who also won a
Tony Award for his performance) as acting partner.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what qualities an actress needed to play Martha, she
answered, ``Intelligence, voluptuousness and hypersensitivity,''
and then added, ``wit.'' When the question was raised about the
difficulty that Albee and his producer Elizabeth McCann were having
in casting the role for a projected revival, she was unable to name
any actress of the correct age to play the role today. ``I'll wrack
my brains and come up with somebody,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   It has often been said that George and Martha are roles of equal
dimension. Ms. Hagen objected: ``If you read it, it's George's
play. The part of George is Hamlet for an actor. It's a great
role.'' Depending on the pairing of the performers, one or the
other can seem to be the stronger character.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virginia Woolf'' is one peak in Ms. Hagen's distinguished and
diverse career. She made her acting debut in 1937 in Dennis, Mass.,
at 17 playing Ophelia to Eva Le Gallienne's Hamlet. ``She pulled it
off,'' she said, ``but I was so in awe of her and so dazzled at
being onstage that I don't remember anything about that
production.'' The following year she was on Broadway as Nina in the
Lunt-Fontanne production of ``The Seagull,'' and then went on to
play Desdemona to Paul Robeson's Othello. She won her first Tony in
1950 for ``The Country Girl.''
</P>
<P>
   As she developed as an actress, she stressed the fluidity of
performance. ``That's my whole goal as an actress,'' she said,
``the spontaneity that comes without planning.'' From her point of
view, a performance should change in the course of the run,
according to the identity of the other actors, the audience
response and the actress' mood and temperament.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, she replaced Jessica Tandy in the first production of
``A Streetcar Named Desire.'' On Broadway and then on tour, she
played Blanche DuBois opposite Brando, Anthony Quinn, Ralph Meeker,
Richard Kiley and Jack Palance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go on with another actor and your performance doesn't
change, you're a bad actor,'' she said. In the case of
``Streetcar,'' she thought that Quinn gave the finest performance:
``Brando was a stunning actor, but I felt he tipped the play
because he was more sensitive than Blanche.'' In contrast, ``Tony
was a brute and didn't know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hagen savors long runs. ``After a couple of months, it
really starts to get in my bones,'' she said. ``So few actors know
how to keep a part alive, and when you're in a country that's built
on runs and not on repertory, you should know how to do that. For
that, Laurette Taylor was my guide. I went to see her in `Glass
Menagerie' 10 times, 10 different, exciting performances. To me,
that is the magic of the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Sunday's performance of ``Virginia Woolf'' is a reading
with actors holding scripts, she is thinking about beginning the
evening with an entrance, as Martha and George, returning from a
late-night faculty party, stumble into their home in the dark.
Martha's first words, ``Jesus H. Christ,'' are soon followed by her
mimicking Bette Davis saying ``What a dump'' in the movie ``Beyond
the Forest.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hagen said she had once spoken that line at a benefit to
introduce herself to an unfamiliar audience.
</P>
<P>
   Then she recalled her favorite, other line from ``Beyond the
Forest.'' Davis is out hunting and while lying in the grass shoots
a porcupine out of a sequoia tree. Asked why she did that, she
replies _ and Ms. Hagen did her best Davis imitation _ ``Porkies
make me nervous.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the interview, she had still not thought of a
younger actress who could play a new Martha, and she commented
critically on a few who were reluctant to do so: ``It is such a
challenge that you would think anybody would leap at the chance.
But everybody is so afraid of making the wrong move. Everything is
about the salability of a career rather than doing the work you
love doing.''
</P>
<P>
   If she had any lingering doubt about the decision to return to
Martha, albeit briefly, she could remember a conversation she had
with Dame Sybil Thorndike during the London engagement of
``Virginia Woolf.'' Thorndike played the title role in the London
premiere of ``St. Joan'' in 1924 and periodically revived the play.
In 1951 Ms. Hagen did ``St. Joan'' on Broadway. Thorndike asked her
if she was going to do it again, and Ms. Hagen said that she was
much too old for the part.
</P>
<P>
   Thorndike replied haughtily, ``Too old for St. Joan? You can
only be too young to play St. Joan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1846EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
