<HEADLINE>
`DECODING NAZI SECRETS': THE UNBREAKABLE CODE BROKEN IN WORLD WAR
II 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Battle of Waterloo was won on the playing fields of Eton,
then the Battle of Britain can be said to have been won in the
warrens of Bletchley Park, a mansion 50 miles north of London.
There, early in World War II, when the German blitzkrieg was
sweeping through Europe, a team of British crossword puzzle
whizzes, chess masters, mathematicians, paleontologists and other
brilliant eccentrics contributed to the Allied victory by breaking
a seemingly unbreakable German code.
</P>
<P>
   The story has been told before in bits and pieces, but
``Decoding Nazi Secrets,'' Tuesday night's two-hour ``Nova''
program, relies on recently declassified secrets and the memories
of the code breakers to give the most detailed account of how
intellectual ingenuity helped to foil German assaults in crucial
encounters and incidentally pioneered the age of the computer and
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The German high command had put its trust in Enigma, described
Tuesday night as ``a seemingly invincible code-making machine,'' to
communicate with its worldwide forces. Using a series of electrical
rotors, Enigma was capable of scrambling messages in an
astronomical number of ways. Each day German operators would
receive a new set of instructions on how to set up the wiring for
their transmitters and receivers. Lacking those instructions, the
code breakers at Bletchley were faced with what seemed to be
gibberish.
</P>
<P>
   This account of how inspiration, calculation, counterespionage
and a little bit of luck cracked the puzzle of Enigma makes for an
intriguing two hours. Trying to follow the deductions of the code
detectives, like the visionary Alan Turing, whose thought carried
intimations of the Internet, can be daunting, but the ``Nova''
producers are skilled enough to give even the mathematically
challenged a fair notion of how clues were tracked down as the
Germans kept refining their code-making techniques.
</P>
<P>
   Just keep in mind that no code can be entirely random, which
means that flaws are inherent in even a code as complex as Enigma.
And never forget the human element of simple carelessness, laziness
or routine mindlessness that may give away even the shrewdest code.
</P>
<P>
   (One German operator set his daily rotors to the first three
letters of his name, Walter, and then typed in the first three
letters of the name of his girlfriend, Klara. It was a gift to the
code breakers. Other operators used set phrases like ``Heil
Hitler.'' Missing from the program, told from the Allied point of
view, are insights into the thinking of the overconfident German
code makers as they tried to confound the code breakers.)
</P>
<P>
   Among the achievements based on the Bletchley Park deductions
were the destruction of much of the Italian Navy; a defense against
U-boat attacks on Allied convoys in the North Atlantic; and the
decimation of supply shipments for General Rommel's North African
campaign. One of the code breakers says that the work at Bletchley
Park shortened the war by two years.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   ``NOVA: Decoding Nazi Secrets''
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Tuesday night at 9 ET (Channel 13 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Paula S. Apsell, director, WGBH/Boston Science Unit, and
executive producer, Nova; Peter Bate, producer for Darlow Smithson
Productions; Nova produced for PBS by the WGBH Science Unit; a
Darlow Smithson production for Nova, WGBH/Boston and Channel 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
