<HEADLINE>
JUSTICES REFUSE TO HEAR INMATES' APPEAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court, over the vociferous objection of
one of its justices, refused Monday to hear the appeal of two
inmates who have been on death row for at least 19 years.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Stephen G. Breyer, in a written dissent, said the court
should have considered the Florida and Nebraska cases to decide
whether it is ``cruel and unusual punishment'' for states to have a
death sentence hanging over an inmate's head for nearly two
decades. But Justice Clarence Thomas, in a separate writing,
responded that it was not the states but the condemned men who
caused the delay by continually appealing their assigned
punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Under its practice, the high court will not consider an appeal
unless four of the nine justices request a hearing. The court did
not disclose whether any other justice joined Breyer in calling on
the court to hear the two cases.
</P>
<P>
   The high court's decision not to hear an appeal sets no legal
precedent and the justices remain free to consider the issue later.
The dispute between Breyer and Thomas reveals an argument between
justices about the Constitution's Eighth Amendment prohibition on
cruel and unusual punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Their public disagreement also stands in contrast to the high
court's quiet refusal Monday to hear the appeal of a Texas man on
death row for a 1993 Dallas-area murder.
</P>
<P>
   Breyer, in a spirited defense of the rights of the condemned,
said long delays between a death sentence and execution can exact a
``frightful toll'' on the inmate, including driving the person
insane. He added that the Constitution's 18th-century authors,
while supporting the death penalty, would have regarded lengthy
delays as cruel and unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult to deny the suffering inherent in a prolonged
wait for execution _ a matter which courts and individual judges
have long recognized,'' Breyer said. ``Nor can one justify lengthy
delays by reference to constitutional tradition, for our
Constitution was written at a time when delay between sentencing
and execution could be measured in days or weeks, not decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, however, disagreed with Breyer's view of the
Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is incongruous to arm capital defendants with an arsenal of
constitutional claims with which they may delay their executions
and simultaneously to complain when executions are inevitably
delayed,'' Thomas wrote.
</P>
<P>
   In the Florida case, Thomas Knight has been on death row since
he was sentenced April 21, 1975, for the shooting deaths of Sydney
and Lillian Gans the previous year. Knight had shot them both once
in the back of the neck.
</P>
<P>
   The Nebraska inmate, Carey Dean Moore, was sentenced to death
April 14, 1980, for robbing and fatally shooting two Omaha
cabdrivers in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   In the Texas case, the justices declined without comment to
consider George Alarick Jones' appeal of his death sentence for the
shooting death of 22-year-old Forest Hall. Hall was found face down
in a ditch with two gunshot wounds to the head.
</P>
<P>
   In his unsuccessful appeal to the justices, Jones claimed that
prosecutors improperly excluded a potential juror from sitting on
the jury. He also argued that the trial judge wrongfully allowed
prosecutors to allege during the penalty phase of the trial that
Jones had killed another person.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Court of Criminal Appeals last year rejected these
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In successfully urging the Supreme Court to deny Jones' appeal,
Texas Attorney General John Cornyn argued that the jury selection
was proper and that allegations of another violent crime are valid
to help jurors decide whether a murderer should be executed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Admission of all evidence regarding the defendant at capital
sentencing furthers the state's interest in assuring (jury)
consideration of evidence about the individual defendant,'' Cornyn
wrote. ``It is directly relevant to the jury's assessment of future
dangerousness, which is a constitutionally permissible sentencing
criterion.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In other high court news, the justices agreed to hear the appeal
of a Mississippi man, 57, who claims he was illegally fired because
of his age.
</P>
<P>
   The 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New Orleans agreed with
Roger Reeves that Sanderson Plumbing Products Inc. had fabricated
legitimate reasons for firing him, such as his alleged failure to
reprimand tardy employees. But the 5th Circuit, which governs
Louisiana, Mississippi and Texas, added that Reeves had not proven
that the company fired him because of his age.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are expected to render their decision in the case,
Reeves vs. Sanderson Plumbing Products Inc., by July.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
