<HEADER>
A3177 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-BBN-GIANTS-STADIUM-HN     11-08 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-GIANTS-STADIUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GENERATIONS OF JAPANESE AMERICANS HELP SHAPE BASEBALL IN S.F. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RYAN KIM  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Not long after Chiura Obata immigrated to San
Francisco in 1903, he fell in love with baseball, the grand pastime
of his new country.
</P>
<P>
   The love affair prompted him to launch the first Japanese
American baseball team on the mainland, which would later inspire
countless more teams throughout California and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It also kept him riveted to his beloved Giants in his later
years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, almost 100 years after Obata's arrival in the city, it is
his 77-year-old son, Gyo Obata, who is leaving his mark on San
Francisco baseball. His St. Louis-based HOK Inc., founded in 1955,
designed Pacific Bell Park, the new home of the Giants scheduled to
open in April.
</P>
<P>
   The distinctive red brick structure in China Basin will seat
42,000 fans and is a long-awaited improvement over cold and windy
Candlestick Park. Pacific Bell Park is one of many baseball
stadiums designed by HOK, including Jacobs Field in Cleveland,
Coors Field in Denver and Baltimore's Camden Yards, which Obata
personally helped design.
</P>
<P>
   For the younger Obata, a San Francisco native and former
Japantown resident, the ballpark is a wonderful opportunity to
further his father's passions, both for baseball and for his
favorite team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a sports person, he would have just gone out of his
mind,'' said Obata of his late father. ``He loved going to baseball
games.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese baseball historian Kerry Nakagawa said it's remarkable
to hear the story of the two Obatas, bookends on a century of San
Francisco's baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have this family legacy span two generations and almost a
hundred years and to have both be pivotal pioneers in inspiring
baseball in San Francisco, it's very unique,'' said Nakagawa,
curator of the Diamonds in the Rough exhibit, which chronicles the
birth and growth of Japanese American baseball.
</P>
<P>
   A fine artist, Chiura Obata came to the city in search of work
and a new life. Despite baseball's emerging popularity in Japan at
the time, Obata hadn't played the sport before coming to the
States.
</P>
<P>
   It was in 1905, when the Waseda University baseball team from
Japan toured the West Coast, that Obata began looking into forming
a local team for the issei, or first-generation immigrants, said
Gary Otake, a curator with the National Japanese American
Historical Society in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had such a fun time,'' said Otake. ``He just saw this as a
great opportunity for issei to have recreation and play the
national sport of America and Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   Chiura Obata, a pitcher, started the Fuji Athletic Club with a
handful of other immigrants and even helped design their uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   They would play games against white and Chinese American teams
at Golden Gate Park and Ewing Field, on the site of the University
of San Francisco's Lone Mountain campus, and were soon joined by
another Japanese American team, the Kanagawa Doshi Club.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, baseball provided the immigrants with a
chance to showcase their love of America and their prowess on the
field, Nakagawa said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting on the baseball uniforms was like putting on the
American flag,'' Nakagawa said. ``But they really wanted to show
how well they could compete and knew the game.''
</P>
<P>
   During the '20s and '30s, as the Japanese immigrants in San
Francisco started fanning out to find agriculture jobs in the
Central Valley, baseball teams began popping up in Fresno,
Stockton, Lodi and Sacramento. Many of those teams still flourish
today, filled with third-and fourth-generation Japanese Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But while baseball's popularity among Japanese Americans took
off, Chiura Obata focused his attention on his professional
calling, taking an art professorship at UC-Berkeley in 1932.
</P>
<P>
   He was recognized as one of the foremost Japanese
watercolorists, helping introduce the art form to many on the West
Coast. He and his wife, Haruko, a Japanese floral designer, were
later awarded emperor's medals for improving relations between the
United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Gyo Obata didn't pursue organized sports the way his father did,
preferring instead to play impromptu street games in Japantown. In
his teens, his studies demanded all of his time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, after his freshman year as an architecture student at
UC- Berkeley, Gyo Obata's Japanese lineage threatened to derail his
promising future. Following the Japanese attack on Pearl Harbor,
more than 100,000 people of Japanese descent were ordered to
evacuate the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   While his family was forced to relocate to an internment camp in
Utah, Gyo Obata managed at the last minute to get accepted to
Washington University in St. Louis, where he could continue his
studies. He still recalls the absurdity of it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was absolutely foolish that just because you had
Japanese blood, you have to be put in these camps,'' Obata said.
``Everyone thought this was so crazy, that it wouldn't last very
long.''
</P>
<P>
   The family would be reunited in St. Louis. After the war, Chiura
Obata returned to Berkeley to resume his teaching while Gyo Obata
remained in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the upheaval caused by the West Coast evacuation of
Japanese Americans, Gyo Obata said the ordeal opened doors for him
and paved the way for his success. In 1955, Gyo Obata started HOK
in St. Louis with two other Washington University graduates,
something that would never have occurred had Obata not been pushed
to the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really opened up a whole new world for me,'' said Obata,
who is chairman of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The firm is now the world's largest architectural design
company, employing about 1,800 people on three continents. In
recent years, it has made a name for itself with its HOK Sport
division, which has built most of the new ballparks across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   After the Giants moved to San Francisco, Chiura Obata became one
of the team's most devoted fans. During the early '60s, he attended
Saturday games at Candlestick, cheering on the likes of Willie Mays
and Juan Marichal.
</P>
<P>
   Chiura Obata died in 1975, long before San Francisco began
looking into replacing Candlestick. Gyo Obata said he plans to
attend the opening of Pac Bell Park in April and his thoughts will
likely turn to his father.
</P>
<P>
   He said he's certain his father would have loved to take in a
game at the Giants' new home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would have loved it,'' Obata said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
