<HEADER>
A3181 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-INDIA-COX     11-08 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cyclone devastation turns India into 'hell'
 &HT;    By Moni Basu
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BHUBANESWAR, India _ It is Diwali, the Hindu Festival of Lights,
but the state of Orissa's capital city, like many of the nearby
towns and villages, is in darkness.
</P>
<P>
   India's largest religious festival is normally celebrated with
lights and fireworks, but this year northern Orissa is silent.
Millions are homeless and thousands are dead after one of the
mightiest storms in India's history ravaged this state's populous
and poor eastern coastline Oct. 29.
</P>
<P>
   The ``super cyclone'' with 165 mph winds blew inland, causing
destruction unprecedented in living memory. Fifteen million people
were directly in the storm's path.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven days later, most of Bhubaneswar is still without
electricity. It could be a month before normal power is restored.
After the sun goes down at 5:30, it is impossible to negotiate
streets without a flashlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we celebrate Diwali, tell me? We can't,'' said Gayatri
Das, a schoolteacher.
</P>
<P>
   From the airplane, it is obvious that something terrible
happened here. Orissa, one of India's greenest states, wears the
color of straw. Its lush coconut and betel palms and its grand
banyans are stripped of their leaves like shorn sheep. From the
taxi, the naked, warped arms of trees can be seen jutting out every
which way amid the rueful remains of human habitation.
</P>
<P>
   There are huts halved by enormous branches while fallen palms
serve as bridges over stagnant pools of flood water.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty coastal villages have vanished, the government said, and
773,000 acres of rice fields were washed out. The government's
official count so far lists 3,417 people dead _ victims who have
been properly identified. But no one really knows for sure how many
lives have been lost. Figures of 10,000 and more are suspected by
relief workers.
</P>
<P>
   In Salia Sahi, a slum just outside Bhubaneswar, rows on rows of
thatched roof huts lie flat as pancakes. The poorest of the poor
survived the storm by fleeing their homes and seeking refuge in an
unfinished multistory apartment house half a mile away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is Diwali, but there is no happiness in my heart,'' said
Manoj Das, a day laborer. ``It was 2 in the morning when everything
crashed. The wind was howling. I have never seen anything like it
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Das pointed to his two daughters sleeping under a makeshift
palm-frond gazebo. ``I feel lucky I survived.''
</P>
<P>
   Many did not.
</P>
<P>
   Ulla Reddy was buried alive by the stone and clay of his own
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the poorest of the poor, and now they have nothing.
Nothing at all,'' said Rashmi Mohanty, a field worker for CARE, the
international relief agency. Late last week, CARE's U.S.
headquarters in Atlanta announced it needs to raise $5 million to
respond to the devastation in India.
</P>
<P>
   Other agencies are also trying to help but the needs are clearly
staggering. The state of Orissa said $581 million was needed.
</P>
<P>
   The northern highway out of Bhubaneswar is dotted with trucks
and four-wheel-drive vehicles carrying relief supplies to cyclone
victims. Swarms of starving men, women and children mob vehicles
that stop to divide up rations. Some people rush out from destroyed
homes; others are already on the road, living in ramshackle tents
made from bamboo and plastic bags. They cling to the trucks like
bees on a hive.
</P>
<P>
   The trucks, they say, may truly be their only chance of
survival.
</P>
<P>
   In Kalagarh, a mob rushes toward a taxi, mistaking it for a
relief vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Babadharan Jena said his village lost 50 to 60 cattle, some of
their carcasses still rotting in watering holes around Kalagrah.
Jena, a factory worker, started rebuilding his brick and mud hut
this week.
</P>
<P>
   His next-door neighbor, Gourang Jena, recalled how villagers
rode out the storm in a hut whose roof caved in. ``I was lucky I
managed to get out of my house with my wife and children before a
tree fell on it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing in abundance in the vicinity is wood _ plenty of
it from felled trees. Along the highway, men and boys work all day
chopping whatever they are able to carry away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will use this as firewood for cooking and also to rebuild
our homes,'' said Rajendra Bari.
</P>
<P>
   At the main food distribution center in Kendrapara, dust, heat
and confusion abound.
</P>
<P>
   The dirt parking lot is crammed with 50 trucks loaded with bags
of rice, lentils, powdered milk, vegetable oil, plastic bags,
candles, matchboxes and medical supplies. By late afternoon, they
will be dispatched to nine neighboring districts. Relief workers
are also racing against the spread of diarrheal disease. Snake
venom has been rushed in, too, as flooding drove poisonous snakes
from their holes.
</P>
<P>
   After a brief discussion with veterinary experts on the disposal
of animal carcasses, Basant Swain, the government official in
charge of the Kendrapara relief operation, turns his attention to
the human toll.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now there is no difference between rich and poor,'' Swain
said. ``I heard that the entire village of Kanpur has gone into the
sea. I haven't been there yet, but that's what I heard.''
</P>
<P>
   Swain's office organizes the relief effort in tandem with the
Indian army. There is no electricity in any of the state offices.
Many offices don't have working phones.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are cut off from everyone,'' said G.C. Lenka, inspector
general of police for the Kendrapara area. ``Television is a dream
for us. We are working here without knowing what is happening in
the outside world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Orissa government has allotted 500 grams or a little over a
pound of food per adult for three days and 250 grams each for
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aid is reaching the people, but it's way too little,'' said
Aniruddha Mukherji, a freelance film maker and photojournalist
retained by CARE to document the crisis. ``Many of these people are
stretching the food they get for more than three days. Five hundred
grams per person for three days is nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   On the road to the port city of Paradwip, not a single tree
still stands. The air is still thick with death.
</P>
<P>
   This is the port town where the cyclone made its landfall.
Corpses litter the roadsides and charred remains of freshly
cremated bodies mar the beaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw people flying in the air in front of me,'' said B.K.
Samal, a member of the Paradwip Port security force. ``I saw 10
people blown away. We didn't even find their corpses. The wind _ it
was so strong we couldn't see anything.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as the death toll continues to rise, the living confront
uncertain futures.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have lost all sources of livelihood,'' said CARE's
Mohanty. ``All their income sources are ruined, all their homes
ruined.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is a hell,'' the relief worker added, ``this is it.''
</P>
<P>
   How you can help
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of relief, development and refugee assistance
agencies is trying to help the people of Orissa state. These are
among groups accepting donations for the effort:
</P>
<P>
   _ CARE, Orissa Emergency Fund, 151 Ellis St. NE, Atlanta, GA
30303-24260-521-2273
</P>
<P>
   _ American Red Cross, International Response Fund, P.O. Box
37243, Washington, D.C. 20013
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. Committee for UNICEF, 333 East 38th St., New York, NY
10016
</P>
<P>
   Moni Basu writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
