<HEADER>
A3189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-SURRENDER-BOOK-REVIEW     11-08 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SURRENDER-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MUSEUM OF UNCONDITIONAL SURRENDER': TREATING EXILE AS A SEPARATE
COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes appear at end of review.) 
(DW) 
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Exile is the only country without a geography. It has, however,
a climate, a culture, an ecology, an archaeology and virtually a
national smell. They figure on the doleful map drawn by Dubravka
Ugresic, a refugee from the repressive nationalist politics and
culture of post-Yugoslav Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   It shows us:
</P>
<P>
   ``That exile is the history of the things we leave behind, of
buying and abandoning hair driers, cheap little radios, coffee
pots. . . . That exile is changing voltages and kilohertz, life
with an adapter, so we don't burn ourselves. That exile is the
history of our temporary rented apartments, the first lonely
mornings as we spread out the map of the town in silence, find on
the map the name of our street and mark it with a cross in pencil.
(We repeat the history of the great conquerors, with little crosses
instead of flags.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Those little firm facts, stamps in our passport, accumulate
and at a certain moment they become illegible lines. Then they
suddenly begin to trace an inner map, the map of the unreal, the
imaginary. And it is only then that they express precisely the
immeasurable experience of exile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Museum of Unconditional Surrender'' is a strew of such
factlets, a Hansel-and-Gretel trail of crumbs into the witch's
forest of our time. Seemingly disjointed and sometimes forced, they
assemble a universal _ the human displacements of Bosnia, Kosovo,
Rwanda, East Timor, Chechnya _ in strikingly individual terms.
Ugresic's stream-of-consciousness exile in Berlin gives us not the
gory amputation of refugee flight but arrival's grayer course of
tissue-rejection.
</P>
<P>
   The author, who has spent years of expatriation in Germany and
the United States and now lives in the Netherlands, is a novelist
and essayist. Her style is personal and aphoristic. ``Museum,''
originally in Croatian, is a mix of diary, notebook, commonplace
book and memoir; its facts and conversations slide between record
and invention. There is much that is arbitrary and self-indulgent,
yet ``Museum'' is a precious portrait of exile as internal
displacement.
</P>
<P>
   Ugresic knows she writes in the line of greater and more
spacious chroniclers of the theme. She freely quotes Nabokov and
Joseph Brodsky; her spitfire artistic assertiveness has a curious
humility to it. Nevertheless, she must be numbered among what
Jacques Maritain called the dreamers of what is true; she draws us
into the dream.
</P>
<P>
   Scattershot and posturing as she can be, there is a startling
aim in her master image at the beginning. A display case in the
Berlin Zoo holds the contents of the stomach of Roland the Walrus,
who died in 1961: a pink cigarette lighter, a water pistol,
sunglasses, a toy parachute, a small doll, a beer can, a poodle
brooch, a sewing kit, car keys and much else.
</P>
<P>
   I Am the Walrus is the leitmotiv of Ugresic's narrator/alter
ego, Bubi. Exiled out of a polar remove, Bubi lives not in a zoo
but an equivalent: the museum of the title. Exile reality, no
longer nourished by roots, is a collection of orphan sensations,
artifacts and memories. One of the most persuasive themes in the
Berlin jottings around which the book is constructed _ other parts
include childhood memories, the story of her mother and an account
of the breakup of Yugoslavia and a band of college friends along
with it _ is photographs.
</P>
<P>
   There are two kinds of refugees, a Bosnian friend remarks,
``those who have photographs and those who have none.'' The
narrator tells an anecdote about the Bosnian-Serb general and war
criminal Ratko Mladic. Noticing that the Sarajevo house of an
acquaintance was on his bombardment list, Mladic phoned to inform
him he had five minutes to collect his photograph albums and leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``The general, who had been destroying the city for months, knew
precisely how to annihilate memory. That is why he `generously'
bestowed on his acquaintance life with the right to remembrance.''
</P>
<P>
   Remembrance is possession, but it rusts. The narrator haunts the
Berlin flea market where Europe's displaced _ Ukrainians, Bosnians,
Africans, Gypsies, Turks and her own countrymen _ peddle a tumulus
of memory as objects. A shadow passes over the reader. How special
a case can exile be? Just across the tracks from the global village
the global flea market is setting up.
</P>
<P>
   The narrator promenades a series of tags to test out her
particular estrangement. ``Ich bin muede'' (``I am tired''): her
first German phrase, and for a while she wants to learn no other.
``Learning more means opening up.'' Later comes ``Guten Tag,''
exchanged with Herr Schroeder, the postman. Apparently a greeting,
to the exile it warns: come no farther.
</P>
<P>
   Herr Schroeder draws arrows on the envelopes to remind her to
give him the Croatian stamps. ``Berlin loneliness is as acute and
unambiguous as Herr Schroeder's arrow,'' she notes, and she's off
to test ``I'm lonely'' among her exile friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not surprising,'' says Zoran. ``Everyone in Berlin is
lonely. And for some reason, no one ever has any time.'' Again
she's off, asking a dozen people: ``Have you some time?'' They
ignore the question. Only the exile ``has'' time; the settled,
lonely or not, ``use'' it.
</P>
<P>
   Interspersed with the Berlin wanderings are vignettes from the
past. There is a tender account of the narrator's mother, from her
girlhood in Bulgaria to the gradually easing rigors of postwar
Yugoslavia to the bleakness, for an old Yugoslav believer, of
seeing the country fall apart. There is a soured love affair, a
cheerful passage with a Portuguese gigolo, a zany feud with three
Indian students in a London rooming house.
</P>
<P>
   The writing here can be overmannered. So is the story of eight
Croatian, Serbian and Bosnian women whose friendship ruptures when
the civil war begins. The many jagged and poignant details are
dimmed by fictional and symbolic inflation, including a magic
realist angel.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Berlin notes that give ``Museum'' its sharp and
haunting edge. There are times, of course, when a reader may wonder
about the treatment of exile as a depressive finality. After all,
untold millions have found a life beyond it. For a moment, though,
italicize that ``have.'' Like entrails for the ancient Greeks, the
inspired particularities of ``Museum'' have a suggestion of
prophecy. The story of illness is not subsumed by the story of
cures. In our day is exile still an illness or the beginnings of
pandemic?
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE MUSEUM OF UNCONDITIONAL SURRENDER'
</P>
<P>
   By Dubravka Ugresic
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Celia Hawkesworth. Illustrated. 238 pages. New
Directions. $24.95.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
