<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON AND GOP DISAGREE OVER CLASS-SIZE REDUCTION
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 CoxNews Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Republican leaders in
Congress said Monday that the biggest obstacle to finishing this
fiscal year's budget is their disagreement over the president's
class-size reduction plan.
</P>
<P>
   Their other differences _ mostly over spending levels for dozens
of small programs _ were melting away hour by hour in quiet
compromises, as staff members from both sides phoned and faxed
offers and counter-offers back and forth between the White House
and Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., both
said they expect to reach all the necessary compromises without any
threat of a government shutdown. At separate news conferences, both
men said it is possible the budget bickering will end before the
Thursday Veterans Day holiday, but said that, if necessary, they
would continue to bargain next week.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man mentioned that, after agreeing to raise education
spending by 12 percent last year, Republicans and Democrats have
reached a tacit agreement to raise it this year by less than 4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they emphasized the profound differences between their
parties on what kind of strings to attach to one federal education
program _ class-size reduction, which cost $1.2 billion last year
and would cost $1.4 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton demanded continuation of the policy of requiring that
districts use the money to recruit, hire and train teachers or meet
other costs of reducing the average class size to 18 in the first
through third grades. He vetoed a bill in which Republicans tried
to give every school district the option of using its share of this
year's $1.4 billion for any educational purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of keeping their commitment to hire more teachers and
reduce class size _ again, I say, something they bragged on and ran
on last year _ now they want an open-ended block grant which could
even be used for vouchers for private schools,'' Clinton said. ``I
think that is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue is, who controls it?'' Lott said. ``Will
Washington bureaucrats assert and control where this money is used,
or will there be some discretion at the local level, based on what
local needs are _ whether it's books or computers or training for
teachers, or for teachers themselves?''
</P>
<P>
   They couldn't even agree on what has been done with the first
$1.2 billion, which was sent to the school districts this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that preliminary data from the Department of
Education shows that districts used much of their money to recruit,
hire and train 29,000 teachers, with the result that 1.7 million
children in the early grades will be educated in smaller classes
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said districts have spent only $67 million of the $1.2
billion, which shows ``you're talking about a large sum of money
that has not resulted in producing a large number of additional
teachers as of yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton cited independent studies containing ``mountain upon
mountain of evidence that smaller classes in the early grades lead
to permanent learning gains if the teachers are well qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said, ``Do you know what the local needs are in Liberty,
Miss.? I don't, but I'll bet you the teachers and administrators
and the parents there know whether they do need more teachers or
they need some more books or computers or other needs.''
</P>
<P>
   Both men said they expect their differences on the class-size
program to be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
