<SLUG> BC-TIMES-CAPSULE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM TO DISPLAY NEW YORK TIMES CAPSULE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ This year, editors of The New York Times Magazine
invited 48 designers, architects and engineers to submit proposals
for The New York Times Capsule, a vessel to preserve artifacts from
this century for the next 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   The winning design is to be announced on Dec. 4, and it will be
displayed, along with a sampling of the items considered essential
for understanding the 20th century, beginning that day at the
American Museum of Natural History.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition, ``Capturing Time: The New York Times Capsule,''
on view through March 26, will explore concepts like biological
time, time and the universe, and time and civilization. The
proposals of the 10 finalists will be displayed, as well as
time-related artifacts culled from the museum's collection.
Computer stations will allow visitors to log onto the Times Web
site to observe and add to readers' suggestions for the capsule's
contents.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition coincides with the publication of the magazine's
sixth and final millennium issue. The capsule and many of the items
inside will be featured in that issue.
</P>
<P>
   The capsule, to be permanently displayed as the centerpiece of
the museum's new plaza on Columbus Avenue, will be sealed at the
close of the exhibition. It is to be reopened in 3000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The museum's vast collection represents a history of life on
Earth,'' said Ellen Futter, president of the museum. ``The Times
Capsule offers a snapshot of civilization today intended to last
1,000 years. It is appropriate that we assume the guardianship of
this millennial treasure, and we are honored to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   The competition began in January when editors from the magazine
convened a panel of experts in preservation, geology, archival
materials and ``deep-time messaging,'' efforts at communication
across the centuries. Forty designers were approached; an
additional eight volunteered to participate. Competitors were asked
not to limit their designs to practical works but to be as
imaginative as possible.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time a Web site was set up to generate ideas about
the capsule's contents. Ideas were also solicited from residents of
the United States, Russia, India, France, Zimbabwe and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   In addition the capsule will include all six of the magazine's
millennium issues printed on acid-free archival paper and a
microengraved nickel disc that includes one minute of ``New York
sounds'' recorded at 9:09 a.m. on 9/9/99, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   The winning design and 10 finalists were selected by a panel of
judges drawn from The Times, including the editors of the final
millennium issue, the architecture critic Herbert Muschamp, the art
critics Michael Kimmelman and Roberta Smith, the design reporter
Julie Iovine and the magazine's design editor, Pilar Viladas.
</P>
<P>
   Editors declined to discuss the winning entry, saying only that
some of the proposals were meant to be buried in places like
Central Park or otherwise hidden for 1,000 years, while others were
meant to be thought of as so beautiful that people would want to
protect them.
</P>
<P>
   The finalists are the Antenna Group; a team from Cooper Union,
Caples Jefferson, Wes Jones, Jaron Lanier and Maya Lin, all from
the United States; Santiago Calatrava of Spain; Droog Design of the
Netherlands; Kenji Ekuan of Japan; Dagmar Richter of Germany; and
the Ocean Group, a collection of designers from Finland, Norway and
Germany who practice together in a paperless office in cyberspace.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1857EST &QL; 
