<HEADER>
A3193 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-GOLDEN-MOVIE-2TAKES-N     11-08 1005
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOLDEN-MOVIE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING THE CAPTURE OF ANOTHER GLORIOUS SPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOWMARKET, England _ The refined perils listed on the day's
shooting schedule were a good clue that the filmmakers lurking
about on a dewy morning in Suffolk might be James Ivory and Ismail
Merchant.
</P>
<P>
   Equipment would have to be moved with care ``due to narrow
drawbridge and moat,'' it said. Technicians should make sure their
hot lights don't get too close to ancestral paintings. It warned:
``There are a large number of deer on the grounds of the house. It
is rutting season and they can be dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   The handyman to contact in an emergency? It identified him as
the Lord Tollemache.
</P>
<P>
   He turned out to be Timothy John Edward Tollemache, 59, the
fifth Baron Tollemache, member of the 19th generation of his family
to inhabit Helmingham Hall, and it was his stately 16th-century
pile in a privileged corner of East Anglia that the Merchant-Ivory
team had chosen as their latest sumptuous period drama setting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is in this,'' Ivory said, walking through
high-ceilinged rooms with busts and tapestries and portraits. He
rubbed his hands together to ward off the dawn chill, but it looked
as if he was exulting in the capture of another glorious space.
``You could build sets to look like this,'' he said, ``but you'd
never get the texture or the feeling or the ambience like this.''
</P>
<P>
   This concern with authenticity and utter comfort with the
luxuries of the past has produced a signature look that filmgoers
have come to associate with Merchant-Ivory in movies like ``A Room
With a View,'' ``Howards End'' and ``The Remains of the Day.'' This
time the two filmmakers have turned their adoring lenses on the
opulent Edwardian settings of Henry James' ``Golden Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Merchant is the producer, Ivory the director, and the novel has
been adapted by the third member of the team, Ruth Prawer Jhabvala.
The film stars Angelica Huston, Nick Nolte, Uma Thurman, Kate
Beckinsale, Jeremy Northam, James Fox and Madeleine Potter.
</P>
<P>
   Ivory makes no apologies for finding inspiration in books by
authors like James and E.M. Forster that other directors might find
dated. ``There's power in these books, the power of wonderful
stories and characters and great scenes to shoot,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   These great scenes have brought Merchant-Ivory acclaim, but they
have also drawn detractors. The director Alan Parker once dismissed
their oeuvre as ``the Laura Ashley school of filmmaking,'' and the
swipe still provokes the unflappable Ivory. ``The comment will be
better remembered than any film he ever made,'' he said with
uncharacteristic venom.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism has not diverted Merchant-Ivory from their
continuing quest for gorgeous surroundings. Other locations for
``The Golden Bowl'' include the 18th-century Renaissance-style
Mansion House with an imposing Corinthian portico in London's
financial district, which is the official residence of the Lord
Mayor of London, and Syon Park, the 16th-century home of the Duke
of Northumberland, with a spectacular conservatory and 30 acres of
gardens and parks where Queen Victoria once frolicked as a young
girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The atmosphere is demanded by the context,'' Ivory said. ``All
this detail doesn't overwhelm, it makes the story accessible; it
adds to the pleasure of the story. A lot of people may think the
story is swamped by the atmosphere, but I can't help that. If
people look at the curtains instead of listening to the witty
dialogue, that's not my fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of his sureness of touch with British scenes, people are
often surprised to find that Ivory is an American. ``The French
always refer to me as the `cineaste anglais,' and it drives me
crazy,'' he said. Even though Merchant, Ivory and Mrs. Jhabvala all
have apartments in the same building on Manhattan's East Side, the
paths that took them there involved kinds of cultural
disinheritance that may give them a particular appreciation of
James' Americans in Europe or Forster's Englishmen in India.
</P>
<P>
   Merchant, 62, is the son of a textile trader in the Bombay
bazaars and grew up in a family of nine living in two rooms. His
last name was Rehman, but he took on the surname Merchant before
beginning his studies at New York University.
</P>
<P>
   Ivory, 71, a Catholic, was brought up in Klamath Falls, Ore.,
and studied architecture at the University of Oregon. He lived for
years in India, and he and Merchant share a 14-room manor house
built in 1805 in Claverack, two hours north of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Prawer, 70, was born in Cologne, Germany, of a Polish
father and German mother. Her family fled Germany in 1939 for
England, where she was educated. She met her husband, Cyrus
Jhabvala, an Indian architect, at London University and spent 24
years in New Delhi before moving to New York in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   The collaboration began in 1961, when the two filmmakers bought
the rights to her novel ``The Householder'' and persuaded her to
turn it into a screenplay. Then came their attention-getting
``Shakespeare Wallah,'' the story of British theatrical troupers in
India, and the partnership was fully cemented.
</P>
<P>
   The family spirit of the venture these days carries down through
the ranks. Strike up conversations with people on a Merchant-Ivory
set and they'll tell you the year they joined the company and the
films they have worked on, the way alumni recall their graduation
class and the honors they earned.
</P>
<P>
   It's also a team with individual appeal. Jeremy Northam said he
was drawn to ``The Golden Bowl'' by Mrs. Jhabvala's script. Uma
Thurman cited her enthusiasm for John Bright, the film's costume
designer, who has worked on 11 Merchant-Ivory films and won Academy
Awards for ``A Room With a View'' and ``Howards End.'' James Fox
mentioned the cinematographer Tony Pierce-Roberts, who has shot
eight Merchant-Ivory films, including ``Howards End,'' ``A Room
With a View'' and ``The Remains of the Day.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The car delivering Merchant and Ivory to the set swung into the
driveway of Helmingham Hall and threaded its way through the
trailer park of vans and tents covering the grounds. ``It sure
didn't look like this on our first films,'' Merchant said. Their
success and the advent of so much new technology have combined to
turn a Merchant-Ivory landing into a full invasion force, though
one with impeccable manners.
</P>
<P>
   This particular day the set had taken on a real-time aspect of a
weekend in the country. Fox, who played a retired colonel in ``The
Golden Bowl,'' bantered with Lady and Lord Tollemache; it developed
that he had served 40 years ago with Lord Tollemache in the
Coldstream Guards.
</P>
<P>
   Lord Snowden, on assignment for ``Vanity Fair,'' wandered the
lawns in hacking jacket and woolen tie and kept asking if an
underdressed visitor wasn't ``freezing to death'' from the autumn
gusts. The winds famously arrive in East Anglia, unimpeded by a
single hill, from Ukraine, the Urals or Siberia, depending on which
local you ask. Moments later, an assistant hurried across the field
with an overcoat.
</P>
<P>
   The Helmingham Hall grounds include an oak that was painted by
John Constable and three newer ones planted by Queen Elizabeth,
Prince Philip and Princess Margaret. Told that his former wife's
tree was not doing as well as the others, Lord Snowden had a
chivalrous response. ``It must have been planted more recently,
don't you think?''
</P>
<P>
   Merchant-Ivory sets are renowned for being free of
scenery-chewing actors, producer blowups or cape-swinging
directorial tantrums. Merchant is a constant visitor to his sets,
but he is more likely to be busy fetching tea for a member of the
company or making one of his celebrated curries for the cast than
pitching a fit about cost overruns or schedule mix-ups.
</P>
<P>
   He is so unfailingly courteous and ingratiating that the actor
Simon Callow once said the phrase ``to curry favor'' was invented
for him. But behind the scenes his persuasiveness has more to do
with being impulsive, scheming and persistent. ``It's the only
thing we get into arguments about,'' Ivory said. ``He's a natural
showman, a great publicist, and he's just very, very good at
getting his way. He's made some casting decisions by just going
ahead and offering jobs to people on the spot. He shouldn't do it,
but then when it's people like James Mason and Maggie Smith, how
can I complain ?''
</P>
<P>
   Uma Thurman sat sipping coffee in the mess tent with extras in
their bustles and feathered bonnets and young men in snug tweeds,
high collars and wide-knotted cravats. She looked out at the
graceful sweep of Helmingham's grounds and the turreted mansion
beyond and said, ``You'd think this was a movie with three times
the budget that he has. I think of Ismail as this person who keeps
pulling rabbits out of hats.''
</P>
<P>
   He has stolen props and bailed actors out of jail in foreign
lands, but perhaps his most famous stunt was getting around a ban
on filming inside the Trianon Palace Hotel in Versailles by draping
himself in robes and posing as the Maharajah of Jodhpur. His crew
for ``The Proprietor'' masqueraded themselves as his entourage and,
once inside, set up the shoot.
</P>
<P>
   They have been at this awhile _ ``The Golden Bowl'' is the 43rd
Merchant-Ivory collaboration _ and they impart a sense of knowing
what they are doing that actors say they appreciate. ``Being asked
to act in one of their films is a nice invitation,'' Fox said.
``The set is very disciplined, and they interpret the material with
such intelligence, which isn't a luxury actors enjoy much today.''
</P>
<P>
   Their partnership, nearing its fifth decade, goes forward on an
instinctive division of labor and an ability to turn potentially
debilitating irritations into moments for grudging admiration. So
what's the latest point of friction, Ivory was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got this crazy scheme now to have a golden bowl made and
get it sold at Tiffany's,'' the director said while Merchant sat
grinning naughtily by his side. ``It's a horrible idea, but he's
not going to be stopped. And I know I'll be the first one to go and
admire it in the window if it ever happens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
