<HEADLINE>
JEB BUSH TAKES SHOT AT GORE, AS GEORGE W. LOOKS ON
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Florida Gov. Jeb Bush introduced his older
brother, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, at an event here Monday with
a pointed dig at Vice President Al Gore, saying that his brother
would be a great president because ``he doesn't have to go get a
consultant to tell him how to dress.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florida governor was alluding none too obliquely to reports
last week that Gore, the leading candidate for the Democratic
presidential nomination, had been paying the writer Naomi Wolf
$15,000 a month for sartorial counsel, among other bits of advice.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Bush was also illustrating the way in which his
brother, Gore or people affiliated with their campaigns are already
sniping at each other as if Bush and Gore were general election
opponents. The first state primary is still two and a half months
away.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a spokesman for Gore had a quote at the ready to
ridicule Bush, the front-runner for the Republican presidential
nomination, after he failed to answer three out of four questions
about foreign leaders during a television interview. And Gore took
public issue with some of the comments Bush had made in the
interview about recent political turmoil in Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, it was the Bush camp's turn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call last week from Naomi Wolf,'' Jeb Bush told
several hundred people at a $1,000-a-plate fund raiser at a
downtown hotel. Then, gesturing to his beige suit, pale blue shirt
and yellow power tie, he added, ``Alpha man, don't you think?''
</P>
<P>
   The reports about Ms. Wolf contended that she had been coaching
Gore not only on his wardrobe but also on transmitting the image of
a dominant alpha male and not a subservient beta male, the role a
vice president is almost invariably assigned. Ms. Wolf later said
that this was a gross simplification and mischaracterization of her
work with the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush nonetheless reveled in the topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Running for president's got to be one of the wackier things in
the world _ where you pay someone $15,000 to teach someone how to
dress after they're 50 years old,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why my brother is going to be a great president and a
great candidate,'' Bush continued. ``He doesn't have to go get a
consultant to tell him how to dress _ although he's got his mom,
and that may work better. He doesn't have to read polls to know his
heart. He doesn't have to do all the things that you apparently
have to do in post-modern American life to run for president of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush has repeatedly said that his campaign would be a
positive one devoid of personal attacks. But although he was not
the one mocking Gore on Monday, he did respond to a reporter's
question on the topic at a subsequent campaign stop.
</P>
<P>
   And asked if his younger brother was indeed an alpha male, Bush
said, ``I'll have to ask my consultant.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether his performance on the pop quiz about foreign
leaders last week had potentially hurt his candidacy, Bush
expressed certitude that it had not. He noted that an array of
people _ including, to some extent, President Clinton _ had
defended his inability to answer such questions.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly referring to his honesty about what he does and does
not know, Bush added, ``I think a lot of Americans are saying, `You
know something? I kind of respect old George W. I appreciate the
way he handled it.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
