<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-BERLIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COURT UPHOLDS MANSLAUGHTER CONVICTION AGAINST EAST GERMANY'S LAST
LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds., see related GERMANY-WALL) 
(HLW) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ An appeals court upheld a manslaughter conviction on
Monday against the last communist leader of East Germany for his
role in the shootings of people who were trying to escape to the
West.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict from the court in Leipzig, the highest appeals court
in Germany, appears to make it almost inevitable that the leader,
Egon Krenz, who ultimately opened the Berlin Wall 10 years ago,
would go to jail after legal formalities have been completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will wear my prison uniform with more honor than certain
judges wear their robes,'' Krenz, 62, said after the verdict had
been read out to spectators' derisive cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Krenz's lawyers said that they would appeal the sentence in the
European Court of Human Rights, in Strasbourg, France, a process
that is certain to be protracted.
</P>
<P>
   Occurring on the eve of celebrations on the anniversary of the
fall of the wall, the decision showed the many ways in which
Germany's past continues to weigh heavily. But most Germans
apparently now feel that the quests for justice over the actions of
the East German police state are close to exhausting themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Krenz's lawyers have argued that the acts of another state, East
Germany, cannot be judged by German courts today and that Krenz is
the object of persecution that reflects the West's triumph in the
Cold War. The lawyers have also said that the border policy could
not be changed because East Germany was under the sway of the
Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   At least 450 people were killed as they tried to escape after
the wall went up in 1961 and other areas of the border with West
Germany were heavily fortified. The killings have been the object
of intermittent, often inconclusive, legal actions.
</P>
<P>
   The decision on Monday concerned an appeal against a
six-and-a-half-year sentence against Krenz handed down in 1997.
Krenz, who ruled for six weeks before the wall fell, served two
weeks of the sentence before being released on bail.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals of two other leading members of the Politburo,
Guenther Kleiber and Guenther Schabowski, were also rejected. They
face lesser sentences of three years each.
</P>
<P>
   Krenz's predecessor, Erich Honecker, went to jail briefly in
1993. He was released because of poor health and died in 1994 in
exile in Chile. Hundreds of border guards and other officials have
been indicted. But fewer than 20 prison sentences have been handed
down.
</P>
<P>
   A principal difficulty in the trials has been whether guards
could be held accountable for obeying orders. At a higher level,
the tracing of orders from specific individuals has often proved
arduous.
</P>
<P>
   In a reflection of continuing divisions here, the Party of
Democratic Socialism, successor to the East German Communists, said
in a statement that the verdict was ``a continuation of the Cold
War in a new form.'' Such arguments have won the party a wide
following in the east.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
