<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-2000-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA GOVERNOR TAKES SHOT AT `ALPHA' GORE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Gov. Jeb Bush took on Democratic
front-runner Al Gore on his brother's behalf Monday, portraying the
vice president as shallow and insincere for hiring feminist Naomi
Wolf as his personal consultant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call from Naomi Wolf _ Alpha male, don't you think?''
Jeb Bush said, modeling his khaki suit, blue shirt and yellow tie.
``Running for president has got to be one of the wackier things in
the world, where you pay 15 grand to teach someone how to dress
after they are 50 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been under criticism lately following a revelation that
his campaign was paying Wolf $15,000 a month as a consultant. Wolf,
whose writings espouse controversial ideas about sex education,
advised Gore to wear ``warmer'' clothing and act more like an
``Alpha'' male.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush went on to tell a fund-raising luncheon for Texas Gov.
George W. Bush's presidential campaign that the Naomi Wolf incident
showed a sharp contrast between his brother and Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, that's why my brother's going to be a great
president, why he's a great candidate, because he does not believe
in that nonsense,'' Jeb Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have to go get a consultant to tell him how to
dress. Or maybe he's got his mom. ... He doesn't have to read polls
to know what's in his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   When George W. Bush was asked later whether Jeb was an ``alpha''
male, George responded: ``I haven't asked my consultant.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate response from the Gore campaign. But Wolf
said on weekend talk shows that she advised him on women's issues,
from the wage gap that women face to making a better balance
between work and family. Her pay recently was reduced to $5,000 a
month.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a new Florida poll shows Bush leading Gore in the
Sunshine State 49 percent to 39 percent. But Bush's lead narrows to
45 percent to 37 percent with Bill Bradley as the Democratic
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   The Miami Herald/St. Petersburg Times poll found Bush with a
commanding 59 percent support in the GOP primary. Sen. John McCain
of Arizona was the only other Republican in double-digits, with 14
percent. Gore led Bradley 54 percent to 32 percent among Democratic
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has complained about sharp campaign jabs as
``Washington-style politics,'' allowed his brother's shots to serve
as a reply to Gore's criticism of Bush last week for failing a
reporter's pop quiz on foreign leaders' names.
</P>
<P>
   Gore said Bush's inability to answer showed he was unprepared to
be president. Bush also has become the subject of late-night
television jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Bush shrugged them off at a Monday news conference after touring
the Duval County jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters know I will have a strong foreign policy,'' Bush
said, noting he has promoted rebuilding the military, deploying
anti-ballistic missiles and renewing alliances. ``So I'm confident
people are hearing what I am talking about.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he also believes the pop quiz may have a positive
effect on his campaign, especially since several foreign policy
leaders and President Bill Clinton came to his defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't feel cheap-shotted at all,'' Bush said. ``The fallout
was very positive, I thought. A lot of people, including the
president of the United States, came to my defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Americans are saying, `I kind of respect George W. I
appreciate the way he handled it,'`` the Texas governor added.
</P>
<P>
   Questioned Monday about the results of Mexico's primary
elections Sunday, Bush gave a far more detailed answer than he gave
the Boston reporter last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Ernesto Zedillo told me a year ago he was going to
open up the (Institutional Revolutionary Party) PRI primary. I told
him I thought it was going to be one of the most interesting
reforms in Mexican political history. I haven't seen the final
results, but the fact that the PRI primary was open is a big step.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met (primary winner Francisco) Labastida when I was down
there, when I was in Mexico. He was in the Cabinet, the president's
Cabinet. I went to the Cinco de Mayo celebration with he and some
of the other Cabinet officials. He seemed like a really decent guy.
To me it's a very positive sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president, President Zedillo, to his credit has done what
he said he was going to do. It's unusual for a president to make a
big reform decision like that after years and years of the
president getting to pick who the candidate is.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, Bush's campaign issued a statement calling for full
funding of the Land and Water Conservation Fund, which uses oil and
gas drilling revenues to help local communities build and improve
parks and recreational areas. Since 1996, the statement said,
federal funding has stopped.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
