<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3198 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SCHOOL-BUS-DRIVERS-AR     11-08 1238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-BUS-DRIVERS-ART-1150(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL DISTRICTS STRUGGLE WITH BUS-DRIVER SHORTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Fla., Conn., Mich., N.H., N.J., N.Y., Neb.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT16, NYT17 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ A national shortage of school bus drivers, caused by
the roaring economy and a rise in the school-age population, is
making students wait up to an hour for a ride, delaying and
canceling field trips and athletic events, and forcing mechanics,
transportation supervisors and even some teachers to get behind the
wheel.
</P>
<P>
   School districts and private bus companies are responding to the
shortage with ambitious recruiting initiatives, offering $1,000
signing bonuses, higher wages, longer hours, child care and other
benefits, plus cash prizes for referrals and good attendance. They
are seeking new drivers through television and radio advertisements
as well as through job fairs and, in some areas, door-to-door
canvassing.
</P>
<P>
   Industry experts, who attribute the shortage mainly to record
low unemployment levels, are worried that the pool of potential
drivers has largely disappeared as fewer people pursue part-time
work, particularly the kind that involves discipline of and
responsibility for children.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Fischer, a school bus consultant based in Peyton, put
the national shortfall at 20 percent. In recent surveys by School
Bus Fleet, a trade magazine published in Torrance, Calif., more
than 70 percent of the United States' school districts said they
were struggling to fill drivers' seats, with officials in 44 states
citing the shortage as a problem, and 17 of them calling it severe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge problem that no one seems to have an answer for
right now,'' said Michael Martin, executive director of the
National Association for Pupil Transportation, whose annual
convention here last week was dominated by discussion of the dearth
of drivers. ``It's not a problem that's getting better, it's a
problem that's getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Schools throughout the country have staggered starting times so
that buses can deliver elementary school pupils, loop around to
pick up middle school students and then make a third run for
high-schoolers.
</P>
<P>
   Athletes on Long Island, N.Y., and in Florida have forfeited
games because they had no way to get there. In Hartford, Conn.,
dozens of students missed breakfast at school and morning classes
in September because buses arrived as late as 10 a.m. The student
ski club in Aurora, Colo., now has to charter buses to the slopes,
and in Caledonia, Mich., field trips must fit in between 9 a.m. and
2 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A bus company in New Hampshire is offering drivers college
tuition, and a company in New Jersey is posting fliers on golf
courses, suggesting that duffers drive the morning route, hit the
links, and then return for the afternoon run. Laidlaw Education
Services, the largest private contractor in the business with
35,000 buses in 35 states, has hired full-time recruiters and has
begun offering a 401(k) plan for the first time in many areas.
</P>
<P>
   In Basalt, an old mining town about 20 miles northwest of Aspen
that has become a bedroom community for service workers at nearby
resorts, a driver was doing double duty, stranding children at
school for an hour before and after classes, until Ronald Goth, a
teacher at the elementary school, agreed to take on a second job.
</P>
<P>
   Like several of his colleagues, Goth had obtained a commercial
driver's license so that he could take students on field trips
without having to hire a bus. While reluctant at first to give up
his early-morning lesson-preparation time, Goth said that picking
up and dropping off 65 students at a trailer park each day helped
broaden his understanding of his students' lives, and had padded
his income to help with expenses for his 9-month-old daughter,
Annie.
</P>
<P>
   Of Basalt's nine drivers, six are teachers, and signs posted
throughout the elementary school sound the bell for more.
</P>
<P>
   Kicking tires and checking hoses is not exactly what Goth, 32,
expected when he chose a career in education. And while he enjoys
the serenity of cruising alongside the Roaring Fork River,
surrounded by white-blanketed mountain peaks, his responsibility on
the road is, in some ways, more daunting than the challenges of the
classroom, where he teaches first- through fourth-graders in a
special program.
</P>
<P>
   ``If somebody has trouble reading, I can work with a child over
and over until the child gets it,'' Goth said as the children
settled into the seats behind him. ``If I injure a child with this
bus, it's something I can never get over.''
</P>
<P>
   School bus accidents routinely make headlines _ like the one
last month in Albany, N.Y., that has prompted a $10 million lawsuit
against the bus company and its 79-year-old driver, or the one last
week in Odessa, Fla., in which a 10-year-old boy was dropped at the
wrong stop, four miles from home, and than was struck by a car and
killed. But statistically, the big yellow bus is among the safest
ways to travel.
</P>
<P>
   About 24 million children ride 418,000 school buses 4.5 billion
miles a year in the United States. From 1988 to 1998, school buses
were involved in just 0.3 percent of the nation's 416,000 fatal
traffic accidents, the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration says. There have been an average of 128 fatalities
per year in school bus accidents, though only 10 percent of those
victims were riding on the buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's safer to be in a yellow school bus going to school than
to walk or to have your mother drive you,'' said a spokesman for
the traffic safety agency, Tim Hurd. ``There are special mirrors
and lights and regulations that make it the safest way to get from
point A to point B.''
</P>
<P>
   But neither the federal government nor the school transportation
industry tracks nonfatal crashes or other incidents, like students
being dropped at the wrong place or abandoned in the back of the
bus. It is impossible to know whether such problems have increased
during the current shortage.
</P>
<P>
   In separate incidents in September, two 5-year-olds were left on
buses in Long Island, one of them stranded at the depot during
Hurricane Floyd. In Yonkers, N.Y., there were three cases last year
of children not being returned home at the end of the school day,
leading the district to demand that all its contractors install
child-find alarm systems in the backs of buses that alert drivers
if children are left behind.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the district has hired bus monitors for every
elementary school bus. In Stamford, Conn., parents have complained
about buses never showing up, and twice recently, drivers have been
cited for stopping on railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   A Westchester County, N.Y., grand jury impaneled after two fatal
accidents involving school buses in the last three years
recommended two weeks ago that a trained monitor ride every bus in
New York state and escort children off at each stop, and that
vehicles have alarms to make sure riders are not left behind.
</P>
<P>
   At the convention in Denver, several vendors were hawking
high-tech devices that survey seats for passengers before drivers
leave the bus, suggesting a growing concern.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Industry leaders insisted that the driver shortage is not
causing them to cut corners on qualifications and training, but
they acknowledged that scrambling for substitutes could lead to
safety problems. If mechanics are driving, they are not available
for emergency repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Substitute drivers don't know the routes, don't know the
children, can't control the kids _ that's when a lot of accidents
happen,'' said Steve Hirano, editor of School Bus Fleet. ``It's
just like a substitute teacher in the classroom. The kids are going
to test them, they're going to see what they can get away with.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Sutherland, director of transportation for the Academy
School District in Colorado Springs, took her cellular phone along
when she drove a route recently, because she knew a driver would
need her counsel on dealing with a parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phone rang; I said to the kids, `I need to pull over to do
my other job,''' Ms. Sutherland recalled. ``It's a great experience
for me to be behind the wheel, but it's very difficult to be both
people at the exact same minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Managers in most school districts have patched together
solutions to cover the shortfall in the short term, but they are
worried about the future, especially in light of the growing
student population. (Several states are also considering
legislation that would shorten the distance from school that
requires busing, further increasing ridership.)
</P>
<P>
   The problem is particularly acute in fast-growing suburbia,
where families often have two parents working full time, increasing
the demand for busing while also shrinking the supply of drivers.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, requirements for drivers have gotten more
rigorous. Federal law now mandates drug and alcohol testing, and
most states also conduct criminal background checks and physical
exams, and require regular refresher courses. And all this for a
job that pays as little as $8 an hour (in large cities like Boston
and San Francisco, it can be $16 to $18), often for just four hours
a day, starting before most people are awake.
</P>
<P>
   Turnover is high, and many school districts complain that they
train applicants only to lose them to more lucrative jobs in
trucking once they obtain their commercial licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Page, who is president of the national pupil
transportation group and director of transportation for the schools
in Lawrence, N.Y., said a Suffolk County company this year spent
$100,000 to recruit and another $100,000 to train 92 drivers. Only
two remain on the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can make more money at McDonald's flipping hamburgers,''
said Fischer, the consultant, ``and you won't have any problems
disciplining kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Many districts are trying to provide longer hours _ either by
combining driving with custodial or cafeteria work, or by
guaranteeing pay even if there is no midday driving _ because they
say their traditional work force of stay-at-home mothers, college
students and retired people seems less available.
</P>
<P>
   Private companies are filling out driver schedules with charter
work. Contractors and schools alike are allowing drivers to take
their own young children on their routes, or paying for child care.
Health benefits are becoming common even for part-time workers;
some districts are offering further perks, like free legal advice.
In Houston, starting salaries rose to $11.22 an hour from $9.36 an
hour in one year.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Mann, the transportation supervisor in Lincoln, Neb.,
started the school year short 40 of 170 drivers. Students sat in
gymnasiums while drivers circled back on double and triple routes;
office staff drove every day, and then stayed until 10 p.m. to do
paperwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every phone call I get, it's usually somebody complaining
about the service,'' said Ms. Mann, who wore a pewter school bus
pin. ``After we've said, `Your children are safe _ I'm sorry we're
late,' I say, `Would you like to drive a bus?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
