<HEADLINE>
JUDGE DELAYS TESTIMONY IN JASPER CASE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ohio) 
 
By RICHARD STEWART 
and PATTY REINERT 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JASPER, Texas _ A judge has delayed testimony for a day in the
capital murder trial of Shawn Berry while he reviews thousands of
news stories and tapes to decide if the trial should be moved.
</P>
<P>
   Testimony had been set to begin Tuesday morning in one of the
most publicized racial murders in East Texas history, last year's
dragging death of a black man.
</P>
<P>
   State District Judge Joe Bob Golden said he would rule at 8:30
a.m. CDT Wednesday on a last-minute request by defense attorney
Joseph ``Lum'' Hawthorn to move the trial.
</P>
<P>
   If Golden decides to keep the trial in Jasper, testimony will
begin Wednesday. Berry's two co-defendants were tried earlier in
Jasper and Bryan.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn had originally said he wanted Berry's trial to be held
in Jasper, where, he said, the 24-year-old manager of the local
theater had a good reputation. He said he changed his mind during
jury selection when potential jurors said they'd heard people in
the community express opinions that Berry is guilty.
</P>
<P>
   ``A jury can be influenced either consciously or unconsciously
by the sentiment of the community,'' Hawthorn said.
</P>
<P>
   Golden said he observed jury selection and all the jurors
qualified to serve ``appeared to be candid, honest, sincere and
completely unbiased in their answers.''
</P>
<P>
   He said lawyers in Berry's case took the same amount of time and
interviewed a similar number of potential jurors as attorneys did
when Berry's co-defendant, Russell Brewer, was tried in Bryan
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The judge added that there had been ``a substantial amount of
pre-trial publicity generated by the defendant's appearance on
CBS.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn said much of the recent publicity had been from legal
wrangling between the Jasper County District Attorney's office and
CBS over unaired portions of an interview of Berry by network
anchorman Dan Rather.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing I wanted to do was file a motion for change of
venue. I have always wanted the trial here,'' Hawthorn said Monday.
``But the latest round of publicity is just too much.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he wasn't the one who subpoenaed CBS's out-takes and
that investigators and prosecutors could have watched and taped
last month's three-hour jailhouse interview, a small portion of
which appeared on ``60 Minutes II.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I assumed they had,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been picking a jury for two weeks, and the judge has
listened to all those jurors,'' Jasper County District Attorney Guy
James Gray said. ``That is the best evidence of whether you can get
a fair jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that you can go anywhere in this whole country,''
Gray said, adding that potential jurors in Bryan, where Brewer, 32,
was tried and sentenced to die, knew just as much about the case as
did those in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   A Jasper jury had earlier sentenced John William King, 25, to
die.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant prosecutor Pat Hardy agreed. ``The bottom line is
Jasper County has been just doused with a ton of publicity.
However, no more than Harris County, no more than Smith County, no
more than London, England.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media coverage really doesn't throw a case out. It's got
to be that there is such a bias in that county that he can't get a
fair trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Reporters from all over the world have flocked to the East Texas
town of 8,000 since June 7, 1998, when the dismembered body of
James Byrd Jr. was found after he was dragged for three miles along
back country roads.
</P>
<P>
   Hawthorn handed Golden stacks of articles from newspapers as
well as transcripts of radio and television broadcasts. He said
three area television stations told him it would take at least a
week to produce copies of about a thousand news items broadcast on
the Byrd case since March.
</P>
<P>
   An obviously irritated Golden gave him until noon Tuesday to
submit what tapes he could get.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are expecting me to read all this, aren't you?'' Golden
snapped at Hawthorn, ``and you haven't even read it yourself, have
you?''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Monday's half-hour hearing provided the first
opportunity for Berry to hug his father since he was 3 years old.
``I've waited 21 years for this,'' said Louis Hezebicks of Geneva,
Ohio. ``This makes the 1,300-mile trip worthwhile.''
</P>
<P>
   Hezebicks said he and Berry's mother, Kathleen Berry, never
married. Over the years he regretted not fighting to get custody of
Berry and his older brother, Louis, but ``back then I didn't even
know how to get into a courthouse, much less what my legal rights
were.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputies Monday brought King back to the Jasper County Jail from
Death Row as a potential witness. But King refused to cooperate and
was sent back. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
