<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3209 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SAMARITAN-COX     11-08 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAMARITAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One-of-a-kind facility
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENGLEWOOD, Ohio _ When Good Samaritan Hospital officials decided
to build a center for outpatient treatment, they looked around the
country for a similar facility that didn't feel like a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't one. We had to create our own model,'' says Anne
McNeill, the Good Sam vice president who directs Samaritan North
Health Center. So they hired an architect that had worked in both
the health-care and hotel businesses, and they enlisted patients,
teachers and government leaders to tell them what an outpatient
center should look like.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not just for focus groups,'' McNeill says. ``We kept them
involved in work groups all the way through.''
</P>
<P>
   Less than five years after Sam North opened, McNeill hears two
or three times a month from hospital administrators who want to see
the center. The outpatient facilities' trade group gave Sam North a
national award this year for its customer focus in a project called
``Creating New Levels of Customer Satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   With an open house Sunday, Samaritan North will unveil a $37
million expansion that more than doubles its size and makes it the
largest free-standing outpatient center in the country. Now 329,000
square feet, it has new surgery, sleep-disorders and well-being
centers, along with much bigger areas for rehabilitation and
doctors' offices.
</P>
<P>
   Outpatient services are growing fast throughout the area, mostly
because health plans are paying for far fewer overnight hospital
stays. But most hospitals' outpatient facilities are on their main
campuses, such as Kettering Medical Center's well-regarded women's
and cancer-care centers at Southview Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a lot of physicians who wanted to come out here because
their patients were telling them that's where they wanted to go,''
McNeill says. ``People don't like to go to hospitals. This doesn't
feel like a hospital, but it has almost everything a hospital has
in it.''
</P>
<P>
   So as proud as she is of the cancer center's high-tech linear
accelerator for radiation therapy, McNeill also points out the
skylight above the patient's bed, where people can look at
stained-glass dogwood branches and listen to soothing music while
their tumors are being bombarded with radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the fancy equipment in the outpatient surgery center,
patients can take advantage of valet parking and the natural light
flowing through atriums and windows. In upgrading the rear entrance
for rehab and the doctor's offices, Sam North also added a
waterfall to its manmade lake and landscaped its parking deck with
a view of the deer and Canada geese that wander past.
</P>
<P>
   As a variety of health-care venues springs up, hospitals are
feeling the need to view patients more as discerning customers than
as passive victims. All five general hospitals in Montgomery County
are using consultants or task forces to help them think more like
retailers in catering to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients bring in their computer printouts and want to know,
`Do you have this?' and `Can I get that?''' McNeill says. ``In this
day of health care, you better be looking at everything through the
eyes of patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Samaritan North has done away with all the public-address paging
and most of the white coats that people so closely associate with
places for the sick. Its walls and floors are earth-toned, its
elevator doors look like entries to Cape Cod homes and some of its
bathrooms have homey mood lighting. The furnishings even in
clinical areas run more toward wood and wicker than plastic and
metal.
</P>
<P>
   There's a free child-care room for kids of the many patients who
make regular trips for rehab or treatment. McNeill tells of an MRI
technician who found out his elderly patient was taking the bus
home, so he took her to the bus stop and waited until he could help
her into her seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's really what we expect of the people who work here,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   Before this expansion, Samaritan North was primarily for cancer
care, rehab and diagnostic testing. It now has 135 doctors' offices
instead of 50, a rehab and sports medicine center with a
health-club ambiance even outside the new aerobics room, and a
surgical area of 24,000 square feet with four operating rooms,
another for laser eye surgery and two rooms for such procedures as
endoscopies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can do anything that doesn't require an extended stay or an
intensive care unit,'' says the unit's director, Stephen Speak. The
recovery room has a soundproof area in anticipation of an increase
in outpatient pediatric surgery, and the patients will go from
pre-operative rooms to surgery by foot or in wheel chairs.
``There's nothing as debilitating as being rolled on a gurney and
looking up at the ceiling,'' Speak says.
</P>
<P>
   Sam North's free-standing surgicenter is the third such
partnership between doctors and a hospital in Montgomery County,
but its scope is broader than those of Kettering's eye center and
Miami Valley Hospital's orthopedics center. As with any outpatient
surgery center away from a hospital, the disadvantage is that if
anything goes wrong, the patient must be transported to a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The new wellness center at Sam North gives a home to existing
programs for tai chi, yoga and meditation and adds rooms for
massage, counseling, aromatherapy and other alternative techniques.
Its health-information library, says McNeill, reflects the medical
industry's trend away from just treating illnesses to teaching
people about health.
</P>
<P>
   ``It goes back to what we told people when we opened this,''
says Good Sam president Douglas Deck. ``We want to be a part of the
community's wellness, not just its illness.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lamb writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
E-mail: kevinlamb(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
