<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0416 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3210 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-AFGHAN-REBEL-ART-665(     11-08 1052
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFGHAN-REBEL-ART-665(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLDING OUT AGAINST THE TALIBAN: LAST REBEL CHIEF FIGHTS FOR
SURVIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map has been sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KHWAJA BAHAOUDDIN, Afghanistan _ The Lion of the Panjshir is not
a big man, especially so for someone thought to be Afghanistan's
greatest guerrilla fighter. With his beret cocked to the side and
his brow in a pensive wrinkle, he has the look of a Beat Generation
poet, more at home in a basement coffee house than in high-altitude
combat.
</P>
<P>
   This nation, so poor otherwise, is rich with storied commanders,
bearded chieftains loping through the mountains, stopping only to
praise Allah or to set an ambush.
</P>
<P>
   But among them, only the Lion _ Ahmed Shah Massoud _ is left to
fight on against the Taliban militia, the others all killed or
chased into exile or bought off with cash.
</P>
<P>
   Some 85 percent to 90 percent of this nation is controlled by
the Taliban, known worldwide for their justice by amputation and
the forced head-to-toe swathing of women. What remains for them to
conquer _ and they have tried and tried and tried _ is the land
that has long been Massoud's lair, Afghanistan's far northeast,
which includes the Panjshir Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Winter is fast closing in, and soon the mountain passes of the
cragged Hindu Kush will be snowbound, ending the prime weather for
warfare. Massoud's forces have beaten back coordinated assaults by
the Taliban on two fronts, including a stunning nighttime
counterattack on Aug. 4 that has further magnified the Lion's
mystique for cunning.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the flatlands of the north, Massoud recently shuttled
back and forth between the combat five miles away and his
stronghold in Khwaja Bahaouddin. One afternoon, while in
conversation, he suddenly dropped to the floor with a blank sheet
of paper and sketched a rough map that at first seemed a rendering
of an amoeba.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Afghanistan,'' he proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   He grew excited. ``The Taliban came at us from five directions,
so we withdrew all our forces and collected in the Panjshir
Valley,'' he said, furiously drawing arrows to show the early
August troop movements. ``Two nights later, after they assumed we
had fled for our lives, we hit back at them here and here and here
and here.''
</P>
<P>
   He stopped to take a call from the battlefield on one of his
several satellite telephones, positioned a few feet away on the
carpeted floor next to his fax machine. Then he continued with the
arrows. ``Here and here also,'' he said. ``They were asleep when we
attacked them. By 5 a.m., everything was finished.''
</P>
<P>
   Self-congratulations still in the air, he abruptly turned
reflective.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my life, the fighting seems to go on and on,'' his brow
folding into three neat vertical lines. ``So much fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   At 46, Massoud has spent more than half his years at war,
beginning while he was an engineering student in Kabul. He has
fought against a dictator, the Soviet army and the Taliban. An
ethnic Tajik, he has also been at war with other Afghan guerrillas,
their ethnicities different from his and their loyalties notably
fluid.
</P>
<P>
   He rarely sleeps in the same place two nights in a row. He
seldom gets to return to his family home in the Panjshir, where he
has a library with 3,000 books. His wife and five children live in
Dushanbe, the capital of neighboring Tajikistan, where they are
safer.
</P>
<P>
   He is a man who wanted to be an architect in a nation that was
once starting to prosper, and instead he became a military
tactician in a woebegone country whose cities are in ruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it will end, I don't know,'' Massoud said with the
exaggerated shrug of a man fighting less now for victory than
survival. ``But what choice is there?''
</P>
<P>
   He then employed a dramatic gesture that he has used before,
dropping his Afghan beret _ the brown pakool, which looks like a
pie crust _ to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all the space I need to fight,'' said the Lion of the
Panjshir.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Afghanistan is a nation of 18 million to 24 million people.
Proper figures are hard to come by, the land is so numb with death.
Between 1 million and 1.5 million people have been killed during 21
years of war. Perhaps another 4 million have fled. It is a nation
where every major road has been torn apart by tank treads. Every
major building has been blown full of holes.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, from 1979 to 1989, the country's pinnacled mountains
_ severe as a moonscape _ made an icy center stage for the Cold
War. The Soviet army had invaded, and the West supported the Afghan
resistance with the latest tools of battle.
</P>
<P>
   With their rifles slung over their shoulders, and with their
long-tailed shirts flapping beneath woolen waistcoats, these
mountain warriors _ the so-called mujahedeen _ struck as bold a
pose as any Hollywood icon.
</P>
<P>
   Massoud, among the best-known, was a prime target for the
Soviets. They invaded the Panjshir seven times. Each attempt
failed. Once, in 1983, Massoud and the Soviets agreed on a
carefully worded one-year cease-fire in the valley. The guerrilla
commander used the pause to organize new fronts and operate outside
the Panjshir.
</P>
<P>
   When the Soviets left Afghanistan in ignoble retreat, the
attention of the West drifted. In war, the mujahedeen had seemed to
most of the world to be a monolithic horde of freedom fighters. In
triumph, they revealed themselves to be fractured by a multitude of
ancestries _ Pathans, Uzbeks, Hazaras, Tajiks, Turkmen _ their
hatreds stoked by age-old ethnic and tribal rivalries as well as
modern-day avarice and the thirst for power.
</P>
<P>
   Burhanuddin Rabbani, a former theology professor, became the
nation's president in 1992. Massoud, a one-time protege and
long-time ally, was named defense minister. But the Tajik-dominated
government, tottering from day one, could not unify so divided a
land.
</P>
<P>
   Kabul, the capital, became a war zone, awakening each day to
blasts from rockets and artillery. Mujahedeen commanders, each with
his own militia, made alliances, double-crossed each other, allied
again. The nation was lawless.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban, with their puritanical version of Islam, were born
of this chaos. Its fighters were largely Pathan students from
religious schools favored by refugees and the poor. They promised
to right the wayward country, and while their formidable military
operations were assisted by neihboring Pakistan, the key to their
success was their welcome by the masses.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban marched into Kabul in September 1996. Massoud barely
escaped with his life. To the end, he says now, he found himself
arguing with the treacherous commanders of other militias about who
would defend what parts of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Again, he reached for paper and drew a map, but this time no
smiles accompanied the arrows. The Rabbani government had been a
failure, and the Lion of the Panjshir could only say: ``I evacuated
my forces without taking casualties.''
</P>
<P>
   After three years of rule, the Taliban find themselves in bad
repute internationally, what with their strict prohibition of
television, music, card playing, kite flying and beard trimming,
punishable with whippings and imprisonment. Women are not permitted
to be seen in public, girls are denied schooling. The government is
the host of Osama bin Laden, the man thought responsible for the
bombing of two U.S. embassies in Africa last year. Military
training camps are many, attracting foreigners ready for martyrdom.
</P>
<P>
   Massoud, a man alert to the need for a persona, is keen to
present himself as an alternative. He is deeply religious, often
fingering a strand of red prayer beads, but he and his top aides
stress that their Islamic practices are far from tyrannical.
</P>
<P>
   In Dushanbe, Massoud's lieutenants sometimes dine at the Casino
restaurant, where waitresses wear short skirts and a rock band
plays ``Hotel California.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Islam is not in contradiction to the world community,''
Mohammad Daoud Panjsheri, one of Massoud's aides said eagerly.
``The world should help us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lion is determinedly coy about how he pays for his waging of
war, but it is unlikely that the world has denied him help. Barnett
Rubin, who follows Afghanistan at the Council on Foreign Relations
in New York, said that Iran, Russia and others assist Massoud,
``trying to keep the Taliban menace out of Central Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerald and lapis lazuli mines in the mountainous northeast also
produce revenues, and, in a perplexing bit of banking, the Massoud
forces control the printing of Afghan currency. The Rabbani
government _ formally the Islamic State of Afghanistan _ is still
the one recognized by most nations, though Rabbani lives in
Dushanbe.
</P>
<P>
   Printing money may have its lucrative equal only in the growing
of it, which is the approach of some of the Taliban. This year,
Afghanistan's crop of raw opium was estimated by the United
Nations' International Drug Control Program to be a record 5,070
tons _ about 75 percent of the global yield. Despite disavowals,
the government not only seems to tolerate the trade but taxes it as
it is trucked to distribution points outside the country.
</P>
<P>
   However financed, war in Afghanistan is often catch-as-catch-can
for so well-practiced an activity. The nation has dozens of
independent ``commanders,'' each with his own weapons and
following. Massoud must continually woo allies with dickering and
cajolery. He seems to be able to reliably field 12,000 to 15,000
men, said Anthony Davis, a military analyst.
</P>
<P>
   The more disciplined Taliban can count on a militia of about
45,000, Davis said, though they too depend on volunteers. Before
last summer's offensive, Mullah Mohammad Omar, the Taliban's
supreme leader, beseeched students in madrasahs, or religious
schools, to join the jihad. Thousands rallied to the call,
including busloads who came from Pakistan with that government's
apparent godspeed.
</P>
<P>
   Yet while Pakistan's money, munitions, and military advice have
long been evident, the alleged participation of its regular army
units in combat remains unproven.
</P>
<P>
   In a jail in the Panjshir, a dozen Pakistani prisoners of war
sat sadly. Muhammad Saleh, 22, a student from Karachi recovering
from bullet wounds to the stomach, was typical.
</P>
<P>
   Madrasah teachers had sent him off to fight ``the Russians and
other infidels,'' he said. He had received 15 days of meager
training, capped by the opportunity to fire three shots, one each
from the standing, sitting and prone positions.
</P>
<P>
   His time in battle had lasted three days. ``When the Taliban
retreated, we weren't aware they had left,'' he said. ``Then we saw
people with rifles, and they called out to us, `Who are you?' And
when we told them we were Taliban, they were so angry they shot us.
We'd be dead if we hadn't begged them and convinced them we were
good Muslims.''
</P>
<P>
   Mealtime with Massoud is not necessarily an inelegant repast. At
the Khwaja Bahaouddin stronghold, food is served outdoors beneath
the shade of two giant maples within sight of a fast-moving river.
Carpets cover the ground, and tablecloths cover the carpets. Boys
wait at attention with huge platters of rice while diners settle
in, sitting cross-legged. Even with 20 guests, everyone gets a
metal tea pot.
</P>
<P>
   The aging Rabbani, who lives in Dushanbe, remains the titular
president of his ever-shrinking Afghan jurisdiction, but it is
Massoud who makes most decisions, civilian or military. Battered
and cranky Soviet-era helicopters drop off a regular supply of
visitors near the front lines, many of them commanders allied with
Massoud and others who are considering it. He seats them at his
side at mealtime and tells them of his democratic vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``To stop the fighting, we are ready to join the Taliban in a
temporary state with a neutral head,'' he said. ``Then we must go
on to elections and let the people decide.''
</P>
<P>
   If Massoud can survive the next inevitable Taliban offensive,
his chances to negotiate such a deal would seem to depend on two
long shots: that Pakistan, under its new military government, will
cut back its support and push the Taliban into talks _ or that
large numbers of Pathans, the nation's biggest ethnic group, will
rebel against their pious brethren.
</P>
<P>
   At one of those mealtimes, with a sporadic breeze rustling the
maple leaves above, the Lion was flanked by two Uzbek commanders
who have joined him in making war.
</P>
<P>
   With the rice eaten, and toffee now brought out to go with the
final sips of tea, the men were angrily condemning the Taliban for
having burned people's crops and homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must defeat, defeat, defeat them,'' Massoud said, his right
hand cutting karate chops through the air. Then his mood lightened,
enough for him to make a joke for his Uzbek confederates.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, we must defeat the Taliban,'' he said. ``Then we can
fight each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
