<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS RIGHT RIGHT-OF-WAY FOR CYCLISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TOM STIENSTRA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a gray area in the California Vehicle Code is
causing a black-and-white showdown with deadly results on the
twisty back roads of the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   Every time a group of bike riders encounter a speeding car on
one of the narrow country roads in the foothills, there becomes a
moment of truth and decision: The cyclists often intentionally
block the car, citing it unsafe to yield the lane _ and legal under
the Vehicle Code to drive in the roadway of a narrow road.
</P>
<P>
   The car driver, irate at being blocked and believing it illegal
for the cyclists to impede traffic, often forges ahead, forcing the
group to the side and into danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law says the bicyclist shall ride as close as practical to
the right side of the road,'' said Len Stone of the Bicyclery in
Half Moon Bay. ``The problem is that everyone has a different
definition of what it means to be `as close as practical.' That
makes it a gray area for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   In two dozen calls to county sheriffs in Marin, San Mateo, Santa
Clara, Alameda and Contra Costa counties, only sheriff deputy Lou
Lozano of the Alameda County Sheriff's Department would stick his
neck out and issue a clarification: ``If they're (bicyclists) going
to be in the street, they can be cited for impeding the flow of
traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   That comment, quoted in a recent San Francisco Examiner story,
inspired dozens of responses from cyclists. They revealed how
dangerous right-of-way showdowns between cars and cyclists are the
most contentious outdoors recreation issue in the Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Department of Motor Vehicles, more than 100
cyclists are killed in accidents each year, and ``hundreds of
thousands more'' are injured.
</P>
<P>
   In e-mails, cyclists explained that there is a moment of truth
when riding a back road, car vs. bike, with no room to spare: ``A
bicyclist trying to ride along the edge will be subjected to
sideswipes and their consequences. When conditions permit, a
bicyclist should allow other traffic to pass, but he should not
compromise his own safety to do so.'' _ Alan Forkosh. Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Riders are not required to ride single file, especially on the
narrow roads to which you refer in your article. If you are riding
in a group on a narrow road (one that is too narrow for a car and a
bike to safely travel side by side) and you ride single file, as
the motorist expects, nine times out of 10 the motorist will
attempt to pass, make it past the first trailing few riders and
then encounter a corner and pull into the sides of the middle
riders. It is far, far safer for us to bunch up and `take the
lane,' which is ours after all, until the road widens sufficiently
for the car to be able to pass safely. As it is our butts that are
on the line, don't you think that it is fair for us to decide when
it's safe to pass?'' _ Oren Noah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowhere in the California Vehicle Code does it require riders
to ride single file. ... The sad fact is that most law enforcement
officers are just as ignorant of the Vehicle Code, re bicycle
riding, as the rest of the general public.'' _ Casey Kerrigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``No cyclist enjoys having an impatient driver behind them.
Cyclists will facilitate passing when it's safe to do so.'' _ Dean
Ruggles, San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that you ride as far to the right as you can, but
it's up to the bicyclist, based on his/her assessment of how safe
the conditions are, to decide how far that is. What many drivers do
realize is that the far right edge of the roadway is not always a
safe place to ride. There may be glass, debris, poor pavement,
sewer grates and other hazards that may cause conditions to be very
unsafe. . . . At times this may require the driver to slow down a
bit and/or wait a few seconds. It is hard for me to understand how
waiting a few seconds can be used to rationalize the rage directed
at bicyclists.'' _ Art Wong, Valley Spokesmen Bicycle Touring Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, those poor drivers. Forced to follow cyclists. Even more
demoralizing than following a ... bus. I guess some homicide is
perfectly justifiable. But seriously, there's another law of
physics you forgot to mention. It's the over 100-to-1 weight ratio
enjoyed by those unfortunate drivers. Show us the stats of drivers
killed by cyclists. I'd be interested in reading about that.'' _
Mark Roderick.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Motor Vehicles provides an excellent web site
on the internet for bicycle safety, rider contacts and the vehicle
code. It can be accessed at www.dmv.ca.gov/about/bicycle.htm.
</P>
<P>
   From this site, you can read Vehicle Code Section 21202, which
states, in part: ``(a) Any person operating a bicycle upon a
roadway at a speed less than the normal speed of traffic moving in
the same direction at that time shall ride as close as practicable
to the right-hand curb or edge of the roadway ...''
</P>
<P>
   However, exceptions include ``when reasonably necessary to avoid
conditions that make it unsafe to continue along the right-hand
curb or edge,'' and then specifies a narrow road as one of those
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   And thus two groups, car drivers vs. bike riders, each
respectively believing they have the right of way, confront each
other on the back roads again and again, ready to fight over a
small patch of asphalt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1939EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
