<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3220 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-DEPOT-EXPO-COX     11-08 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEPOT-EXPO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Depot's Expo revamped, ready to open another store
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It took a while, but Home Depot is finally ready to
show its shimmer off to the hometown.
</P>
<P>
   The retailer's new Expo Design Center in Alpharetta, Ga., could
be followed by at least four more in metro Atlanta, President
Bryant Scott said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Alpharetta Expo, which opens Thursday, is the second Expo in
Georgia. The first opened 1994, when executives were still
struggling with the upscale format.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten better with every Expo we've opened,'' Scott said
during a tour of the new store. ``Now we're ready to roll it out in
a big way'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   The Expo division, designed to sell renovation and decor in a
showroom setting, is in the midst of a nationwide rollout.
Executives have been reworking the concept for eight years. The
first Expo opened in San Diego in 1991, followed by stores in
Atlanta and Long Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the sixth Expo opened in Davie, Fla., last year, the
concept had been completely revamped. The Alpharetta store differs
dramatically from previous Expos, for example, with a heavier focus
on lighting and rugs. Lamps, furniture and kitchens are displayed
in lifelike rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Expo aims to take the best from interior design
showrooms and put them under one roof. ``People say it's like
walking through a magazine,'' Scott said. ``We're opening up a new
channel of distribution for products that were only available in
small retail stores or through designers.''
</P>
<P>
   Expo currently operates 13 stores. The company has announced
that it plans to have 26 Expos open by the end of next year and 200
in North America by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say they've heard discussions of a much more
aggressive expansion. Some estimates call for as many as 500 Expos,
said analyst Dan Wewer of Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Home Depot has an open playing field with Expo,'' Wewer said.
``Lowe's (Home Improvement Warehouse) is not moving into this
business...and Sears isn't really a threat.''
</P>
<P>
   Sears, Roebuck &AMP; Co. is trying to compete with Expo with its new
home project store called The Great Indoors. Last month, Sears said
it will build 15 stores over the next year and a half, including
some in Expo markets. Despite Sears' early success with its first
Great Indoors in Denver, analysts generally expect Expo to
out-muscle the retailer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have new competition, it's a threat, but it also
makes you better at what you do,'' said analyst Wayne Hood of
Prudential Securities.
</P>
<P>
   One key to Expo's success is how well the retailer can manage
the order and delivery end of the business, Hood said. In a
complete kitchen remodel, for example, the components for the
flooring, cabinets and countertops typically arrive in many pieces
at different times.
</P>
<P>
   ``That calls for a completely different set of systems than what
you'd find at a Home Depot (warehouse) store,'' Hood said. ``In the
early days of Expo, the systems side of the business was a problem,
but they're doing a much better job.''
</P>
<P>
   Expo's Scott, who has beep president since 1995, admits he
didn't fully appreciate the operational differences between Home
Depot and Expo in the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``When someone buys a drill at Home Depot, that transaction is
over at the cash register,'' Scott said. ``At Expo, when they write
their check or pull out a charge card, it's only the beginning of
the process.'' Indeed, it can take months to design, order and
install a kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Expo has had some growing pains in learning the installation
side of the business, too. In light of a tight labor market, it has
been a challenge to coordinate installers, Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said Expo has improved its service level in the past year.
Expo representatives now try to contact each customer following an
installation project to get feedback. Last year, Scott started
tying 10 percent of each store manager's compensation to that
customer feedback.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say they're comfortable with the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're paying more attention to follow-up,'' Wewer said.
``They wouldn't be expanding Expo if they hadn't worked on this,
because they wouldn't jeopardize the Home Depot name.''
</P>
<P>
   Patti Bond writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 1940EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
