<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HYPOCRITES IN POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ANTHONY LEWIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There have been contemptible Congresses before, and historians
can argue about which was worst. But I remember none in modern
times as dismal as the one now sitting, the 106th Congress. It has
set new records in cynicism and hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leaders of the House appoint, as conferees on a
bill to give patients more rights in managed-care health plans,
members who oppose the bill. Without debate, the House votes to
give an extra $1.7 billion in profits to companies that make
student loans _ $692 million to one company alone.
</P>
<P>
   They bleat about states' rights. But they push through a bill to
override the physician-assisted-suicide law twice approved by
Oregon voters, and another bill to bar state courts from hearing
class actions brought against industries that make big political
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to do what they want through the regular legislative
process, senators have tacked on to appropriation bills a dozen
riders stripping away environmental protections. Indeed, there
hardly is a regular legislative process anymore; controversial
measures are increasingly embodied in riders.
</P>
<P>
   But for me the most vicious example of the corrupted process was
the Senate's 54-to-45 vote last month to reject the nomination of
Justice Ronnie White of the Missouri Supreme Court to a federal
district judgeship. Every one of the 55 Republican senators except
one who was absent voted against White. They all did so at the
urging of their ultra-conservative colleague John Ashcroft of
Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft charged that White was ``pro-criminal,'' had ``a
serious bias against the death penalty'' and showed ``a tremendous
bent toward criminal activity.'' As first demonstrated in a column
by Benjamin Wittes of The Washington Post, those statements were
lies.
</P>
<P>
   In support of his charge that White is biased against the death
penalty, Ashcroft cited the case of a black defendant, Brian
Kinder, sentenced to death for murder. When the Missouri Supreme
Court affirmed the conviction, White dissented. Ashcroft said the
basis for the dissent was that the trial judge, Earl Blackwell, had
said he ``opposed affirmative action.'' That was a brazen
falsehood.
</P>
<P>
   Blackwell was running for re-election to the bench. A week
before the Kinder trial he announced that he was switching parties
to Republican because ``the Democrat party places far too much
emphasis on representing minorities such as homosexuals, people who
don't want to work and people with a skin that's any color but
white ... While minorities need to be represented, of course, I
believe the time has come for us to place much more emphasis and
concern on the hard-working taxpayers in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Kinder's lawyer asked Blackwell to recuse himself because of his
hostile statement suggesting that minorities were not
``hard-working taxpayers.'' The judge refused. The majority on the
State Supreme Court said the statement would not ``cause a
reasonable person to question the impartiality'' of Blackwell. It
was from that dubious assertion that White dissented.
</P>
<P>
   White has voted to uphold 41 death sentences. He dissented in
one case that involved the murder of a sheriff, and for that reason
Missouri sheriffs and the National Sheriffs' Association opposed
his confirmation. But the Missouri police organization endorsed
him, saying White's record ``has been far more supportive of the
rights of victims than of the rights of criminals.''
</P>
<P>
   The real reason for Ashcroft's opposition was that he is running
for re-election next year and wants to look tough on crime. What is
shocking is that the other Republicans joined in his cynical
performance _ even a supposed moderate like Arlen Specter, who
voted for White twice in committee, and then against him on the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   Because White is an African-American, the Republicans were
accused of racism in rejecting him. I think they were innocent of
that charge. They were guilty of something else: dirtying the
confirmation process and stabbing a good judge and a good man in
the back. Stuart Taylor Jr., The National Journal's respected legal
commentator, put it exactly: ``The Senate's vote and the smearing
of Justice White were shameful acts of pettiness and
partisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
