<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTHCARE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Survey shows costs rising in health care coverage
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ National employers are reporting health-care cost
increases of 8 percent to 10 percent for 2000, a new survey finds.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the survey of 600 employers by consulting firm Hewitt
Associates, released Monday, showed a second consecutive year of
benefits' costs rising toward the double-digit range, after years
of smaller increases.
</P>
<P>
   And the 2000 surge will mean higher costs for employees as well,
Hewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Reasons for the cost increases in 2000 include the overall aging
of the population, and prescription-drug spending rising at more
than 18 percent a year, Hewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, insurers now are trying to pump up profits after
years of artificially keeping prices low to boost market share,
said Mike Marotta, a consultant with Hewitt Associates in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health plans are getting tremendous pressure from shareholders
to make money,'' Marotta said.
</P>
<P>
   To compile the Atlanta market figures, for example, Hewitt
surveyed 16 large companies based in the Atlanta area. But smaller
companies in Georgia are reporting even bigger increases for health
insurance, according to the National Federation of Independent
Business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Premium increases from 15 percent to 25 percent are common,
with some insurers giving final quotes as high as 120 percent,''
said NFIB's Bert Fridlin. Hardest hit, he said, are employers that
cover fewer than 10 workers and dependents.
</P>
<P>
   Marotta said employers often respond to the price increases by
passing some of the costs on to employees, through higher premiums,
co-pays or deductibles. Workers, though, pay only about 20 percent
of the overall cost of health insurance, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many companies in the survey said they will pass along at
least 25 percent of the cost increase to their workers.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, with the average health plan projected to cost
$4,853 per employee next year, up from $4,412 in 1999, most
employees will pay $110 more for their health coverage next year,
Hewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies also may start shopping for better prices in
local markets, rather than contracting with a single national
insurance plan, Marotta said.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Miller writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
