<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-KNAPP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICE AS MUCH AT A LOSS FOR ANSWERS AS ANYONE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GWEN KNAPP  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In Sunday's final sign of desperation, Jerry
Rice asked reporters to figure out what ails the 49ers. He said it
rhetorically, as a way out of a trap, his only way out.
</P>
<P>
   The questions came at him endlessly after the Niners' 27-6 loss
to Pittsburgh. He caught two passes all day, for two yards, but he
grabbed dozens of questions and ran with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Have you lost confidence in Jeff Garcia?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could tell Steve Mariucci to do one thing to improve
the offense, what would it be?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you envy John Elway for retiring from a championship
team?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Two catches, two yards. Does that embarrass you personally?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, yes, it does,'' he replied to that last one, ``but a lot
of other things have to factor in also. So you know, I feel, I
don't know. To be honest with you, I don't know. Maybe you guys can
shed some light on it, but right now it's basically very hard to
deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice, the franchise's longtime emblem of excellence, didn't know
which way to turn. Should he start ripping into everyone, cause a
furor, insist on changes that might be impossible to make? Or
should he be the quiet diplomat, which could be even more damaging
to team morale?
</P>
<P>
   ``You wish for more opportunities and try to be patient,'' Rice
said. ``I'm dealing with it, but sometimes that can work against
you because people, they feel like, ``OK, he's content.
</P>
<P>
   He feels like he doesn't have to go out there, show his
emotions, or go off (on a rant) during the week, or in the middle
of the game.' `` He's right about this. All those years, his
fussiness was an exasperating reminder that the 49ers were
chronically dissatisfied perfectionists. It was the team persona.
Rice embodied it more than anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Now, there isn't room for fussiness. Instead of perfectionism,
they seek competence. Instead of another career record, Rice seeks
. . . well, even he's not sure, but it certainly isn't two catches
for two yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to deal with because I have tasted the
best,'' he said after the Niners' fourth straight defeat and his
least productive game since his rookie season. ``I have been there,
on top for so many years, but what are you going to do? You can't
give up.''
</P>
<P>
   Half-seriously, Rice agreed that he might feel a little envious
of Elway, whose career had meaning right up to the last snap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was raining so hard out there,'' Rice said, ``and when it
starts pouring down like that and when you've got things not really
going the way you want, you think about that. You really do. You're
like ``Wow, what am I doing out here?'''
</P>
<P>
   One answer: He's fulfilling a commitment. Rice clearly wants to
erase the stigma of last year's tantrums over his number of
catches. He wants his legacy to be one of dignity, of a
championship-maker, not as a me-first performer. He returned this
season vowing to behave as an elder statesman, a contributor to but
not the fulcrum of the team, a feisty opponent but a cooperative
teammate.
</P>
<P>
   So there have been no impetuous threats to retire if he didn't
get what he wanted. If this ship is sinking, he's not jumping off
for the sake of convenience. ``Right now, I'm just trying to fight
my way out of this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he's not sure what that entails. Silence? Screaming? He can
understand why the Niners are flailing, but he can never accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say we're losing confidence in Jeff,'' he
said, laughing off a reporter's attempts to fill his mouth with
treason. ``As a whole, I think something has to happen. (Maybe)
it's going to take someone saying: ``Hey, let's open it up. We have
nothing to lose.' `` How predictable, right? A receiver wants to
open up the offense. But Rice also said he would prefer to see more
of a commitment to the run on a day like Sunday, when Charlie
Garner was galloping all over the field.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly, he reminisced about the old days, when 49ers receivers
had rehearsed lovely, precise routes, knowing exactly when and
where the ball would descend into their arms. ``It was
repetition,'' Rice said, snapping his fingers. ``It was automatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would I like to have that offense? Yes, I would,'' he said,
``but I can't make that call. I wish I could.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the 49ers could try something different and fail all
the same. Rice knows the problem well. He's looking for answers,
from any source, anywhere. It's the only way he knows how to convey
desperation without declaring a surrender.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
