<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPENDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PRESSES GOP LEADERS ON EDUCATION ISSUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton pushed his case in budget
negotiations Monday for hiring more teachers, but Republican
leaders continued to balk, as both sides sought to work out
differences over Year 2000 spending matters before Veteran's Day.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides sounded optimistic that a deal could be reached by
midnight Wednesday when the latest in a series of temporary
spending measures expires. But Clinton's demand for $1.4 billion in
education money dedicated specifically to hiring up to 100,000 new
teachers was still an obstacle as negotiations continued late
Monday evening. Congress has targeted Veteran's Day for
adjournment.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have offered $1.2 billion but are insisting that
states and local districts be given the flexibility to spend the
money any way they choose, whether on teachers or other pressing
needs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, however, calls that approach a reversal of the
commitment Republican leaders made last year when they agreed to
fund the first installment of his plan to hire up to 100,000 new
teachers over several years in an effort to reduce class sizes. The
White House said the 1999 funding had helped hire nearly 29,000 new
public school teachers, but Republicans disputed that claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about the money. As a matter of fact, our
appropriations bill has more money in it for education than the
president asked for,'' said Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
referring to an extra $300 million that Republicans added to the
education budget for the 2000 fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big issue is who controls it. Will Washington bureaucrats
assert and control where this money is used? Or will there be some
discretion at the local level based on what local needs are,
whether it's books or computers or training for teachers or for
teachers themselves?'' Lott, R-Miss., said.
</P>
<P>
   However, despite opposition among Republicans to Clinton's plan,
Lott said it was still possible to reach a compromise before
Veteran's Day on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to work through that in the next few days, and I
think we can. We certainly should,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he warned members to be prepared to work through next
week if necessary. If a deal can't be reached, Clinton might be
forced to delay a scheduled trip abroad that begins Friday, and a
number of senators and House members would be forced to cancel
planned trips abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't get our work done, I assume that neither the
members nor the president will be going anywhere. We've got the
people's business to do, and that's here. Now, we can do it by
Wednesday or we can do it the next week,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to teacher funding, a number of other spending
issues have yet to be resolved. They include Clinton's request for
nearly $1 billion to pay off overdue U.S. financial obligations to
the United Nations, as well as $1.3 billion to help finance the
hiring of up to 50,000 local police officers. Clinton is demanding
nearly $500 million for the purchase of more public lands.
</P>
<P>
   But teacher funding is Clinton's top priority, and he pressed
that issue Monday during a White House event, where he unveiled a
new government study showing that the reduced class-size program
initiated in his administration in grades kindergarten through
third grade has helped improve student performance. The study also
reinforces other findings in independent studies that have also
shown that children who get more attention in smaller class often
perform better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over 1.7 million students are now directly benefiting from
this class-size initiative. It shows we are headed in the right
direction, and that's the good news,'' Clinton said. ``We have
mountain upon mountain of evidence that smaller classes in the
early grades lead to permanent learning gains if the teachers are
well-qualified.''
</P>
<P>
   He called on Republicans not to back down from the commitment
they made last year to the new teacher program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last fall, congressional Republicans agreed to support this
initiative. Indeed, it was election season, and they even went home
and campaigned on it. It was a good idea then, and it's still a
good idea,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   He accused Republicans of trying to turn his program into ``an
open-ended block grant'' that would allow local authorities to use
the money for private school voucher programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that is wrong,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, however, insisted that the federal government should not
be able to dictate what local authorities do with the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know what the local needs are in Liberty,
Mississippi?'' he asked one reporter. ``I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged that local authorities should have
flexibility to use federal education money to address needs unique
to their communities. But he said money for hiring new teachers
should only go to communities that desperately need it for that
purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't want the money, they don't have to take it. If
they're offended by it, they can give it to other states and other
school districts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., who heads the appropriations
subcommittee on education, called on Clinton to be a little more
flexible. He reminded Clinton that it is the job of Congress under
the Constitution to appropriate money and decide how it is
distributed, not the president's.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we give up the power of the purse, which is at issue here,
it really reduces the Congress to being a eunuch,'' Specter said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Clinton has signed eight of the 13 annual appropriations
bills needed to fund the government. He and Congress have worked
out a deal on the ninth. But the remaining four measures account
for nearly half of the $618 billion budget for the 2000 fiscal
year. The remaining bills cover funding not only for education, but
for health, state, justice, commerce, interior and labor programs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
