u f BC-DOW-MICROSOFT-COX     11-08 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOW-MICROSOFT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nasdaq up more in wake of Microsoft ruling
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Investors shrugged off a potential Microsoft scare on Monday
with a broad-based rally among other technology stocks that sent
the Nasdaq composite index to its seventh straight record.
</P>
<P>
   Even Microsoft's shares eventually rallied from early losses in
the first trading session since a federal judge found last Friday
that the world's largest software company is a monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had been concerned that a big sell-off of Microsoft
shares would depress the broader market, given the company's size
and also its recent addition to the Dow Jones industrial average.
</P>
<P>
   But after overnight losses in foreign markets and early declines
of as much as $7 per share on Wall Street, Microsoft ultimately
rebounded to end the regular session at $89.93 3/4, down only $1.62
1/2. Turnover was almost 122 million shares, or nearly five times
average daily volume.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investors who abandoned Microsoft turned to the other
technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``While (Microsoft CEO) Bill Gates is under the gun, his
competitors are dancing in the streets,'' said Prudential
Securities analyst Brian Piskorowski.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com rose $13.06 1/4 to $78, Yahoo gained $13.75 to
$197.18 3/4, and Cisco Systems rose $1.87 1/2 to $75.31 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   The net effect was to boost the technology-laden Nasdaq
composite by 41.68 points to 3,143.97, the index's eighth straight
gain and seventh straight record.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow and the S&AMP;P 500 stock index posted small gains.
</P>
<P>
   Several analysts defended Microsoft as an ongoing profit-maker.
</P>
<P>
   Standard &AMP; Poor's analyst Brian Goodstadt reiterated his
``accumulate'' recommendation, pointing out that a final court
ruling is still months away, and the appeals process will take
several years beyond that.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he said, Microsoft shares will be propelled by strong
earnings growth, fueled by the February launch of its Windows 2000
system.
</P>
<P>
   At BB Robertson Stephens, analyst Marshall Senk reiterated a
``buy'' rating on the stock.
</P>
<P>
   In general, the still-upbeat U.S. economy continued to support
the market, especially after last Friday's October payroll report
indicating that wages are still under control despite a tight labor
market.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said this diminishes inflation fears and possibly
reduces the odds of another Federal Reserve interest rate boost
when it meets Nov. 16.
</P>
<P>
   Several reports due for release this week may shed more light,
especially the October producer, or wholesale, price index on
Wednesday and the October retail sales and third-quarter
productivity reports on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
