<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY ATTACKS GORE ON HEALTH CARE ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also HEALTHCARE-INSURE) 
(sw) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley issued his strongest critique
yet of Vice President Al Gore on Monday, asserting that Gore had
fallen prey to what he called the incremental mentality of
Washington and had betrayed a fundamental Democratic Party
principle by not pushing for universal health care as a candidate
for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the case of health care, Al Gore decided it wasn't worth
standing and fighting,'' Bradley said in a speech before 6,000
health care professionals, bluntly throwing Gore's own words back
at him. The Gore campaign has accused Bradley of failing to ``stand
and fight'' for the Democratic Party when he retired from Congress
in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The two men are locked in an increasingly tight battle for the
Democratic presidential nomination, and in recent weeks Gore has
been aggressively attacking Bradley on a range of issues, from his
record as a three-term senator to his plan for making health
insurance available to almost all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday, Bradley had sought to avoid responding directly to
Gore's criticisms, contending that American voters were tired of
negative campaigning and hungry for positive ideas from their
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   But on Monday, he clearly diverged from that strategy, using his
most forceful language to date to describe Gore as lacking the
vision and the confidence of his convictions to fight for a plan
that would cover the nation's 44 million uninsured people.
</P>
<P>
   ``He abandoned that fundamental Democratic principle of basic
health care for all Americans he had talked about so much in the
campaign of 1992 and during the first two years of the
administration,'' Bradley said, reading from a prepared text with
his usual calm tone.
</P>
<P>
   To emphasize that point, Bradley's press office released a list
of statements by Gore in 1992 and 1994 strongly endorsing universal
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, Gore's spokesman, responded to the speech by
saying that Bradley ``acted today like a typical politician.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Unable to defend the merits of his own health care plan, he
launched a negative attack on Al Gore,'' Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said that the downfall of President Clinton's universal
health care plan in 1994 had made Gore fearful of proposing a
sweeping plan today, even though, he asserted, the public is more
eager for one than ever and the federal budget is flush enough to
pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson Al Gore learned from the health care defeat was
that big bold things can't get done in Washington, so let's look to
the small, symbolic things,'' Bradley said. ``But that was the
wrong lesson. Indeed, big rhetoric followed by small actions
contributes to the disillusionment people have with politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, a former professional basketball player who has tried
to cast himself as a populist outsider running ``a different kind
of campaign,'' also accused Gore of being a captive of Washington,
cowed and myopic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe something happens when you listen to Washington voices,
instead of the people's,'' Bradley said. ``The Washington view of
things says, `Don't propose anything bold in a campaign because
your opponent will surely pick it apart.' The Beltway perspective
says that if you try something once and fail, move on to another
issue that polls better or is safer to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued by his campaign, Gore defended the
proposal, saying, ``I have put forward a plan that offers health
insurance to every child, covers nearly 90 percent of all Americans
and does so while strengthening Medicare, preserving Medicaid and
focusing on those who lack coverage today.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley has called for federal subsidies and tax credits to
enable lower income people to buy private health insurance. He
contends that his plan would cost $650 billion over 10 years, to be
paid out of a $1 trillion federal surplus, and would make insurance
available to 95 percent of all Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign asserts that Bradley's plan would cover fewer
people than Bradley claims and cost $1 trillion over 10 years,
eating up the entire non-Social Security surplus and leaving
nothing for shoring up the Medicare system or other social
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's own plan focuses more on poor children and the elderly.
The vice president's aides contend his proposal would extend
coverage to almost as many uninsured people as Bradley's, while
costing much less: between $300 billion and $400 billion over a
decade. To bolster his contention, Gore's aides released a report
on Monday by Dr. Ken Thorpe, a former Clinton health adviser now on
the faculty of Emory University, saying that Bradley's plan would
cover 89 percent of the population, compared with 88 percent under
the Gore plan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bradley's aides said he was simply trying to use his speech to
point out clear distinctions between himself and Gore, and had
refrained from using the kinds of pejorative words or scare tactics
they claim the Gore camp has employed.
</P>
<P>
   But they acknowledged that Bradley had put more muscle into his
speech on Monday because of Gore's recent attacks, and said he was
likely to continue responding more aggressively in the coming
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley gave his 25-minute speech in a cavernous convention hall
on the shores of Lake Michigan filled with members of the American
Public Health Association who repeatedly interrupted him with
applause.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the event said that Gore was also asked to speak
but had turned down the invitation because of a scheduling
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the speech, which received a standing ovation, the
association's executive director, Dr. Mohammad Akhter, praised
Bradley for having the ``courage, wisdom and foresight'' to make
health care a major part of his platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time a presidential candidate spoke here, it was
Jimmy Carter,'' Akhter told the crowd. ``Maybe history might repeat
itself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
