u i BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-BOS &LR;      11-08 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING PARTY STRENGTHENED BY PRIMARY VOTE, OBSERVERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexico's ruling party appeared Monday to have
weathered, even thrived on, its biggest experiment in letting
voters _ rather than the party elite _ choose its standard bearer.
</P>
<P>
   In the process, the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI)
allayed fears that a break from its authoritarian past would cause
it to splinter in the heat of a primary campaign, which ended with
the runner-up throwing his support behind winner Francisco
Labastida Ochoa in a conciliatory concession speech.
</P>
<P>
   For both of these reasons, the party and Labastida, a former
interior minister, are now considered the odds-on favorites to win
the presidency in the crucial July 2000 general elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an enormous show of force by the PRI,'' said Sergio
Aguayo Quesada, a political scientist at the Colegio de Mexico.
``At this moment this party clearly has the momentum.''
</P>
<P>
   After even the most optimistic PRI officials predicted that
about 6 million Mexico voters would cast ballots, the actual
turnout _ according to party figures _ was more than 8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than leaving the party fractured in a close vote, as some
party insiders feared, voters handed a landslide victory to
Labastida, who won 272 of the country's 300 districts.
</P>
<P>
   And instead of creating deeper internal divisions or leaving the
party in protest, as some observers had expected, all of the
candidates immediately accepted the outcome and pledged to stay
with the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will keep working from within to make the changes (we
want),'' said Roberto Madrazo Pintado, governor of Tabasco state
who was Labastida's closest and most bitter rival.
</P>
<P>
   Although some analysts wondered whether Madrazo might yet leave
the party in protest against a process that he publicly criticized
as tilted toward Labastida, there were smiles and sighs of relief
at party headquarters in downtown Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's election marked the first time in its 70-year history
that Mexico's dominant political party allowed voters to choose its
presidential candidate rather than having the sitting president
pick his successor. Even so, the election and the campaign were
dogged by constant accusations that the PRI machine was engineering
a victory for Labastida because he was the choice of outgoing
President Ernesto Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   In the final weeks, Zedillo, who decided last spring to abandon
the practice of anointing a successor, made repeated statements
stressing his neutrality. In a nationally televised address after
the polls closed Sunday, the president revealed that he nullified
his own ballot by marking a vote for each of the candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's candidacy will be made official at a ceremony on
Nov. 20, the holiday celebrating the 1910-1920 Mexican revolution.
For the 57-year-old former governor of Sinaloa state and three-time
cabinet minister, the climb to the top of Mexico's political
establishment has been quick and steep.
</P>
<P>
   Only five years ago, as the ambassador of Portugal, Labastida's
political future was cloudy. But he was brought back to Mexico City
and made his way up the bureaucracy, from federal highway chief to
agriculture secretary and then to interior minister, a post similar
to that of vice president in the United States, which he quit in
June to mount his run for president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only began thinking about running for president late last
year when I started hearing my name mentioned on radio and TV,''
Labastida said last weekend. ``This isn't something I've wanted to
do since I was a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Politically, many observers think Labastida closely mirrors
Zedillo's technocratic, free-market policies. But toward the end of
the campaign, he distanced himself from administration policies,
probably in an effort to attract support from the populist wings of
the PRI that have become disenchanted with Mexico's current
generation of Ivy League-trained policymakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labastida is a game player,'' said Jaime Gonzalez Graff, a
sociologist at the Mexican Institute of Political Studies. ``He
isn't isn't completely technocratic but not entirely populist
either.''
</P>
<P>
   The open question is whether the PRI's new democratic face will
be enough of a change to keep most of Mexico's 58 million voters
from looking for something different in other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's two main opponents will be former Guanajuato state
governor Vicente Fox Quesada, candidate of the conservative
National Action Party, and Cuauhtemoc Cardenas, son of a beloved
president, former mayor of Mexico City, and the candidate of a
leftist coalition led by the Party of the Democratic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the opposition has begun to poke fun at the PRI's new
image of reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I congratulate the 50 million Mexicans who didn't vote in
Sunday's primary,'' Fox told reporters Monday. ``I applaud them for
not falling for the PRI's greatest hoax.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
