<SLUG> BC-DELL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dell to set up another Tennessee plant
 &HT;    By Jerry Mahoney
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Three months after Dell Computer Corp. opened a
manufacturing plant in Tennessee _ its first U.S. factory outside
of Central Texas _ it announced Monday a second assembly plant in
Nashville, where it is building a regional campus.
</P>
<P>
   When it opens next year, the plant on 150 city-owned acres near
the Nashville airport will add nearly 700 jobs to Dell's Middle
Tennessee work force. Dell has been assembling its Dimension
desktop PCs in leased space 25 miles east of Nashville since early
August.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's Middle Tennessee payroll already includes more than 1,300
workers at the leased site, which Dell executives say will continue
to operate when the new manufacturing plant opens next year.
Another 400 customer-support workers are in leased space in
Nashville, awaiting completion of a 300,000-square-foot office
building at the airport site.
</P>
<P>
   The new manufacturing building, at 300,000 square feet, will be
about the same size as Dell's newer plants in Central Texas. Also
planned for the campus is a 200,000-square-foot customer-support
center. .
</P>
<P>
   The Tennessee operations are still small compared with Dell's
presence in Central Texas, where it has more than 20,000 workers.
But the plans for the additional plant is an indication that the
nation's biggest computer maker is happy with its move there last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Dell executives said Nashville reminded them of
Austin, with its large college population, state capital and music
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Moving operations to the Nashville area also limits the
company's dependence on Central Texas, where the work force and
roads have been taxed by the economic boom and population growth of
the 1990s. Strategically, Nashville's location near hubs of Federal
Express and other deliver companies cuts the time it takes to
deliver PCs to East Coast customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are putting the capacity where it makes the most sense to
support the consumer and the small business lines of our
business,'' Dell spokeswoman Cathie Hargett said Monday. ``This is
about managing our growth in a way that is good for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials at Dell, like their counterparts at many growing
companies, are concerned about Austin's tight labor force and
worsening traffic congestion. But the company, which releases
third-quarter results after the financial markets close on
Thursday, will continue to expand in Central Texas, Hargett said.
</P>
<P>
   Dell said this summer that it expected its Nashville operations
to employ at least 3,000 people in five years. Adding salaries,
construction costs and local purchases, Dell estimated its
investment in Middle Tennessee will be about $340 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making good on our pledge to the people of Tennessee,''
Michael Dell, the company's chairman and chief executive officer,
said in announcing the expansion in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's expansion into Tennessee has been somewhat controversial
in that state. Critics complained that the promised new jobs did
not justify a 40-year property-tax exemption and other incentives
that government leaders guaranteed the company.
</P>
<P>
   The package, which also includes an inexpensive lease of public
land where the campus will be built, is estimated to be worth about
$50 million during the 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Dell opened a leased manufacturing, sales and
customer-support facility in southeast Brazil. There, Dell plans to
build a campus valued at $120 million, including about $20 million
in government incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Mahoney writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: jmahoney(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press and Dow Jones News Service contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
