<SLUG> BC-EGYPTAIR-BOXES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAVY RETURNS TO SITE WHERE BLACK BOXES WERE DETECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS AND BRIAN MACQUARRIE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWPORT, R.I. _ As strong winds churning waves up to 20 feet
high slowly abated, the Navy returned Monday to the crash site of
EgyptAir Fight 990 off Nantucket and launched a second high-tech
drone to search for the black boxes of the doomed jet, while FBI
agents waited on a command ship to search for any telltale signs of
explosives.
</P>
<P>
   The Magnum, a more advanced, remote-controlled submarine, was
sent to the ocean floor shortly after 4 p.m. from its mother ship,
the Carolyn Chouest. The USS Grapple, with another drone on board,
left safe harbor here and was expected to join in the hunt by early
Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   At a briefing, US Navy Rear Adm. William Sutton said he expects
the two remote vehicles to continue working through Wednesday, when
more rough weather is forecast to move through the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are taking every advantage and maximizing every
opportunity,'' Sutton said. ``The weather has been driving the pace
of the investigation and will continue to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, as broken-hearted family members began to leave Rhode
Island with few answers about the crash, state Attorney General
Sheldon Whitehouse filed a request for presumptive death
certificates for everyone on board. The documents will enable them
to attend to legal matters regarding their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   During the briefing, National Transportation Safety Board
chairman James E. Hall seemed to bristle at the suggestion that the
federal government was not bringing all its resources to bear on
finding out why the Boeing 767-ER300, bound for Cairo from New York
City, mysteriously plunged into the Atlantic Ocean Oct. 31, killing
all 217 on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are committed to finding the answer to the cause of the
accident of EgyptAir Flight 990,'' said Hall. ``I am confident we
will find the cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Barry Mawn, FBI special agent in charge of the New England
division, said that there was no indication that the plane was
downed by a criminal act. About 20 agents were at sea waiting to
test and catalogue wreckage as possible evidence.
</P>
<P>
   In a bizarre twist, however, Mawn said agents had arrested a
Hyde Park, Mass., man for phoning in eight separate bomb threats to
Northwest Airlines from mid-October to Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   The suspect, Pedro Antonio Castillo-Ferrer, 33, made statements
that he was working on behalf of FARC, an armed Colombian
revolutionary force, and claimed the group was responsible for the
EgyptAir crash.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``we are very comfortable that he had nothing to do
with it,'' Mawn said.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB investigator in charge Gregory Phillips said US personnel
have arrived in Cairo to begin reviewing the maintenance history of
the ill-fated jet.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he said, crews have recovered only small, light pieces
of debris, such as aircraft seat cushions and tires from the nose
landing gear.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said the NTSB was aware of a recent report that two
bolts on the tail of another Boeing 767 were not tightened to the
appropriate specifications, and that investigators would closely
examine the tail of the EgyptAir jetliner.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing checked all 767s in production and found that eight
planes also had loose bolts. The aircraft manufacturing giant is
expected to notify all airlines currently flying the 767 later this
week of the potential problem. A spokeswoman said that, as a safety
measure, the plane is designed with 16 bolts on the tail _ many
more than are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also have about 10 hours of high-quality videotape
from the Deep Drone on the Grapple that reveals the complete
devastation of the airplane.
</P>
<P>
   ``The visibility is very limited, but very clearly you can
identify aircrft wreckage,'' said Phillips. ``I can only say it is
very fragmented.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the wreckage is stacked in piles several feet high.
</P>
<P>
   Though search crews located the pingers _ signals that are
designed to guide investigators to the jet's ``black boxes,''
flight data and cockpit voice recorders _ last week, they are
believed to be buried under debris and possibly the silty ocean
bottom, about 250 feet below the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Admiral Sutton said Monday that the jagged edges of the aircraft
wreckage, the water's depth and the churning surface prevent divers
from safely searching for the devices, which could contain vital
clues.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said there were two main debris fields that side-scan sonar
has mapped so far in a six-mile by six-mile area, some 60 miles
south of Nantucket. The pingers are in the eastern debris field.
</P>
</TEXT>
