<SLUG> BC-HACKERS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
`hV2k' HACKER HITS TEXAS AGENCIES 
 
(Attn: Calif., Nev., N.Y., Va. and Wash.) 
 
By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
and CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A hacker, who has struck government Web sites
around the nation and even a federal department, targeted six Texas
agencies over the weekend, chastising them for poor security.
</P>
<P>
   The hacker, using the tag ``hV2k,'' left graffiti on the state
Web sites expressing everything from disgust to annoyance to
boredom. While early reports said as many as a dozen agency Web
sites were breached, only six were confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Texas agencies received alerts and advice on how to
tighten their security, and the Texas Department of Public Safety's
high-tech crimes unit began an investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The hacker did not breach the privacy of sensitive state records
or the security of state tax dollars, officials reported. He did,
however, manage to hack the DPS Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our investigators are still conducting a criminal
investigation and I would expect it to go on for a while,'' said
DPS spokeswoman Tela Mange.
</P>
<P>
   Also hit were the Texas Department of Health, Texas Protective
and Regulatory Services, Alcoholic Beverage Commission, State
Auditor's Office and the Department of Licensing and Regulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``gAH. after defacing this site, i think i will try to get my
drivers license again for the 3rd time. .sigh, '' the hacker wrote
at the Department of Licensing and Regulation's page. ``Learn
sekurity.''
</P>
<P>
   Hacking as a form of graffiti is not that difficult if ``that's
how you spend your whole life,'' said Steven Wilkins, the agency's
director of information resources. It does, however, consume
considerable time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't identify with that mentality. Also, we don't issue
drivers' licenses,'' he added. ``We license auctioneers, boxers,
air-conditioning contractors. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Agencies said the hacking did alert them of weaknesses in their
systems, which are under repair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have taken the action to notify all agencies that they
could be targets,'' said Carolyn Purcell, executive director of the
Department of Information Resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like them to know how to preclude it in the future. .
.but meanwhile to put them on the alert to look out for it so they
can remedy it as soon as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The state government Web sites that were attacked around
midnight Sunday all use the Microsoft Windows NT Internet
Information Server. That program has been wracked by security
troubles in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   At the state auditor's Web site, the hacker complained, ``this
is getting boring, SEKURE YER DAMN NABIT NT SYTEMS.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Health was told it had been turned into
the ``Texas Department of Hacked.'' The department isn't exactly
amused, said spokesman Doug McBride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say they're the sharpest pencil in the box,'' he
said of the hacker. ``It may be a prank, it may be a joke, but
we're asking that it be taken seriously because it is a violation
of state and federal laws.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Department of Protective and Regulatory Services took
offense as well. Under a drawing of an elderly woman kissing the
cheek of her companion, the hacker wrote ``woah. .those are some
pretty damn ugly faces above'' and indicated that's why the site
was hacked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like more of an embarrassment. I think it's a shame
they targeted a state agency whose purpose is to help abused and
neglected children and vulnerable adults,'' said spokeswoman Marla
Sheely.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites that track hackers' movements _ www.attrition.org and
www.2600.com _ noted the attacks on Texas agencies Monday and
indicated the hacker responsible had been particularly active. Web
pages also vandalized by ``hV2k'' include Pension Benefit Guaranty
Corp., a federal government agency, and government Web sites in
California, Nevada, New York, Virginia and Washington state.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the nature of the hacking and the damages
resulting, penalties under Texas law can range from a Class B
misdemeanor to a felony carrying prison time, said Mange at the
DPS. She said, for now at least, the FBI has not been brought into
the case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
