<SLUG> BC-BP-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BP AMOCO HAS 72 PERCENT RISE IN PROFITS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Bolstered by higher oil prices and deep reductions in
costs, BP Amoco on Monday announced a 72 percent rise in third
quarter profits and forecast higher gains next year from its
planned $33.6-billion purchase of ARCO.
</P>
<P>
   The increase pushed BP Amoco's stock up 4.5 percent, to 565.5
pence, or about $9.16, maintaining strong gains that have increased
the company's share price by 29 percent this year, ahead of two
larger rivals, Royal Dutch/Shell and Exxon.
</P>
<P>
   The company said that profits from operations rose to $1.96
billion compared with $1.14 billion in the similar period in 1998.
The results partly reflected the effects of a restructuring plan
announced last July aimed at cutting annual costs by $4 billion, as
well as the effect of higher oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco said the average price of oil rose from $11.59 a barrel
in the 1998 third quarter to $19.17 in the third quarter of this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This continuing performance improvement will underpin further
growth in the business, assuming a continuation of firm aggregate
demand,'' said Sir John Browne, the company's chief executive.
``Additional potential will arise next year from the ARCO
acquisition.''
</P>
<P>
   The purchase had been held up by objections from Alaskan
authorities who were concerned that the resulting oil giant would
be in an overwhelmingly strong position there. But last Friday, the
company struck a deal with the Alaskan authorities to sell some
assets and thereby reduce its dominance.
</P>
</TEXT>
