<SLUG> BC-FEINSTEIN-OGILVY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OGILVY PR UNIT BUYS BOSTON CONSULTANT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feinstein Kean Partners Inc., the largest Boston-area public
relations and consulting firm specializing in startup biotechnology
companies, Monday said it has been bought by Ogilvy Public
Relations Worldwide of New York, the nation's 10th largest public
relations firm.
</P>
<P>
   Financial terms were not disclosed, aside from a statement that
the five Feinstein Kean owner-partners, led by chief executive
Peter Feinstein, will receive payouts over several years based on
the Cambridge firm's performance.
</P>
<P>
   The sale is the latest in an industry consolidation wave that
has turned several of the Boston area's best-known advertising and
public relations companies into subsidiaries of larger
conglomerates. The list includes Hill Holliday Connors Cosmopulos,
Mullen, Arnold Communications, Weber Group, and, last month,
McDermott/O'Neill &AMP; Associates.
</P>
<P>
   Ogilvy Public Relations itself is a subsidiary of WPP Group plc,
based in London. WPP also owns the Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide and J.
Walter Thompson advertising agencies, and Hill and Knowlton, the
world's second largest public relations firm.
</P>
<P>
   The Feinstein Kean acquisition will allow Ogilvy Public
Relations to expand its health care public-relations practice to
biotechnology. Ogilvy has renamed the company Feinstein Kean
Healthcare and is operating it and its business-development and
consulting unit, Kendall Strategies, as a wholly owned subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein Kean and Kendall Strategies together have 75 employees
and had more than $9 million in revenues last year.
</P>
<P>
   Ogilvy said the acquisition will boost its annual revenue from
public relations services for pharmaceutical and other health care
companies to more than $32 million. The company had $79 million in
revenue from all operations last year and is projecting 1999
revenue at about $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement, Ogilvy Public Relations' president and chief
executive, Robert Seltzer, said Feinstein Kean's ``strength in
helping biotech companies through the early stages of their
existence meshes perfectly with both our pharmaceutical expertise
and our strength in corporate communications.''
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein Kean was formed in 1987 by Feinstein and Robert
Gottleib, both of whom worked for Biogen Inc. Its client list
includes Aquila Biopharmaceuticals Inc., Cambridge Neuroscience
Inc., Immunogen Inc., and SafeScience Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said the sale was prompted by market opportunity and a
chance to gain international presence. ``We were facing a bit of a
hurdle that we needed to overcome, as a local company that could
bid on small companies but did not have the capabilities for large
biopharmaceutial product launches,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein said Ogilvy can provide these, along with the depth of
staff needed to serve the emerging, related field of genomics, in
which genetic information will be the basis for development of new
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein Kean is the second US public relations agency bought
this year by Ogilvy, which two weeks ago aquired BWR Inc. of Los
Angeles, which specializes in the entertainment industry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
