A3257 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HEALTH-BOOKS09-COX     11-08 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-BOOKS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Read of the week on yoga
 &HT;    By M.A.J. McKenna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Yoga Journal's Yoga Basics: The Essential Beginner's Guide
to Yoga for a Lifetime of Health and Fitness'' by Mara Carrico and
Yoga Journal (Henry Holt, 1997, $15.95 paperback).
</P>
<P>
   Gives the basics of all different styles of yoga and takes the
reader through basic postures. The history and philosophy of yoga
are accessible to the greenest beginner, and the photos and
descriptions of poses make for easy-to-follow replication. Author
Mara Carrico has 25 years' experience instructing hatha yoga, and
she begins the book with an exploration of the roots of the various
hatha yoga styles
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Yoga: The Spirit and Practice of Moving into Stillness'' by
Erich Schiffmann (PocketBooks, 1996, paperback, $16).
</P>
<P>
   A more in-depth book on the philosophies of yoga. Local yoga
instructor Rebecca Thurman often recommends this book for people
wanting to learn more about the breathing, meditation and energy
involved in practicing yoga. The author is a yoga master who's been
featured in best-selling yoga videos with actress Ali MacGraw.
Recommended for those wanting to learn more about achieving asana,
the pose of stillness.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Yoga and the Quest for the True Self'' by Stephen Cope
(BantamDoubleday Dell Publishers, 1999, $24.95).
</P>
<P>
   Just released, this book is by a psychotherapist who intended to
take a four-month break from his harried Boston yuppie lifestyle to
recover from a painful relationship loss and to explore the
question of his own life purpose. Ten years later, Cope is still at
the yoga retreat center in Lenox, Mass., teaching and hearing tales
from thousands of other contemporary soul seekers. His book
explores why Americans suffer from ``self-estrangement'' _ how
we're so self-involved that we've lost all connection to
surrounding communities of people and nature.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Integral Yoga Hatha'' by Swami Satchidananda (Integral Yoga
Distribution, 1998, $16.95 paperback).
</P>
<P>
   Continuously in print since 1970, this book is considered the
master of all yoga books. It's the book most often recommended by
local yoga instructor and chiropractor Deana Guadagno. She says the
large format size and 160 photographs make for easy comprehension
of postures, breathing practices, relaxation, cleansing and
concentration techniques. The author is one of the most followed
yogis in the country and will be appearing this weekend at the
Whole Life Expo in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   _Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET SITE OF THE WEEK
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes health care consumers go to the Internet because they
are looking for information on a specific disease or drug.
Sometimes, they're just looking. Medscape (www.medscape.com) is a
good place to start looking. The multipage site, which claims more
than 1 million subscribers, is headed by Dr. George Lundberg,
editor of the Journal of the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Medscape offers daily medical news culled from wire services,
interactive dictionaries of medical terminology and drug
information, and searches of medical literature using MedLine, the
database of the National Library of Medicine. It also features
articles from medical journals, summaries of new research presented
at recent conferences and personalized home pages that can be
customized for particular areas of interest such as children's
diseases or HIV.
</P>
<P>
   Using MedScape requires that you register as a member.
Membership is free but requires divulging the usual personal
information: age, gender, profession. You'll also be asked if you'd
be willing to participate in market research.
</P>
