<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3262 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OLY-ATLANTABID-COX     11-08 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ATLANTABID-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IOC official changes tune in effort to improve Olympic image
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (a) General news and (s) Sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Melissa Turner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The International Olympic Committee official who
accused the Atlanta Olympic bidders of ``pushing'' all those gifts
and favors on the unwitting IOC was in Atlanta on Monday eating a
bit of crow and drumming up support for closure of the corruption
scandal that has rocked the Olympic world.
</P>
<P>
   Insisting that the IOC is headed for a radical shake-up next
month with new age limits for members and controls on gifts and bid
city visits, IOC spokesman Franklin Servan-Schreiber said the
public will accept the reforms and be ready to once again focus on
the core values of the Olympics _ peace, friendship and fair
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a major earthquake,'' said Servan-Schrieber, who
is visiting media and sponsors in the United States to explain the
49 reforms the IOC membership is set to vote upon in a special
meeting in Lausanne, Switzerland in December.
</P>
<P>
   He's trotting out a just completed worldwide study on the
Olympic image to demonstrate that while the public is disappointed
and concerned about the IOC as an institution, they still hold the
Olympic Games and the athletes in high regard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Games have been totally untouched,'' he said. ``I'm not
talking about the IOC, but the Olympics. The value of the property
for the sponsors has not diminished at all.''
</P>
<P>
   If the reforms are passed, and he expects they will be,
Servan-Schreiber said he believes ``people will be satisfied we
have moved as fast as we could and have achieved a spectacular
proposition that will fundamentally change the IOC.''
</P>
<P>
   However, it still remains to be seen if the IOC members will
give up their favorite perk _ visits to bid cities. IOC President
Juan Antonio Samaranch wants to ban visits by all members except
those on a special evaluation commission, but others object.
</P>
<P>
   When the vote comes up in Lausanne, members will be asked to
either vote for a total ban, or agree to visits in organized groups
paid for by the IOC, not the city.
</P>
<P>
   Servan-Schrieber concedes the visits are a controversial issue,
brought to a glaring head with the Atlanta Olympic report prepared
for the U.S. House Commerce committee by former attorney general
Griffin Bell in September.
</P>
<P>
   IOC rules at the time only allowed one visit to a bid city and
members could only be accompanied by one guest, usually a spouse.
However, Bell found that dozens of IOC members made several trips
and often brought several family members.
</P>
<P>
   That was more troubling to IOC officials than the list of
excessive gifts lavished on visiting delegates by eager Atlanta
bidders. ``Yes, there were gifts, but the gifts don't seem to have
been very expensive,'' Servan-Schreiber said. ``It's the trips that
were an issue. It begs the question, should there be any trips at
all?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the only intense debate among members of the IOC 2000
reform commission last month was on the issue of visits to bid
cities. ``Some of the African members said it makes us looks like
criminals and a lot of people resent that,'' the IOC spokesman
recalled. ``But there's no question the way the visits have been
handled up to now would be radically changed.''
</P>
<P>
   While the IOC hierarchy now believes the visits to Atlanta were
excessive, Servan-Schreiber reiterated his earlier comments that
the Atlanta bidders essentially begged IOC members participate.
</P>
<P>
   When Samaranch's wife and two friends visited Atlanta, Savannah
and Charleston, S.C., at the expense of the Atlanta bidders _ an
egregious example of excessive hospitality cited by Congressmen
during a hearing in October _ it was at the insistence of Atlanta
bidders, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a clear invitation by the bid committee who repeated
and insisted, and in that light, out of politeness, she accepted,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   But today Servan-Schreiber doesn't see anything nefarious in
those overtures. ``It's clear that Mr. Payne and Mr. Young had no
ulterior motives except to be friendly,'' he said. ``It should be
clear also this was the environment in which the bid was done.''
</P>
<P>
   That was precisely the defense argument Bell made in his report
to Congress. Every bid city was excessive in its courtship of IOC
members, and most cities were more excessive than Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Servan Schrieber doesn't disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, it was just not the same caliber as Salt Lake City,''
he acknowledged. ``For example, in Salt Lake City some cash
exchanged hands. And that is a clear difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Turner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 2011EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3264 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT-PRICE-BOS &LR;      11-08 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-PRICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIT ON MICROSOFT SHARES NOT AS BAD AS EXPECTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: $8.4 billion in lede is cq)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp. stock fell 1 5/8 a share Monday, far less than
expected, but wiped out $8.4 billion of investors' money in a day
filled with anticipation that a much bigger slide might pull the
entire market down with it.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street held its collective breath and braced for the
reaction to a finding by Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, released
after the markets closed Friday, that the world's biggest software
company exerted monopoly power over would-be competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's stock slid as much as 8 percent early in the day but
recovered smartly. Trading volume reached a level four times the
daily average for the stock, indicating there were buyers eager to
snap up Microsoft shares being sold off by more negative investors.
The company's stock closed at 89-15/16.
</P>
<P>
   It could have been worse. Not only were Microsoft's losses
contained _ some had predicted the stock might drop as much as 15
percent _ major market indexes posted small declines Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Wall Street is telling you is Microsoft is the biggest
bully on the block, and they're not going to get hurt too badly by
this,'' said Katherine Kirk, a technology managing director in the
Boston office of Hambrecht &AMP; Quist Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The techology-heavy Nasdaq stock index suffered most, falling
41.68 points, or 1.34 percent, and closing at 3143.97. The other
two major indexes dipped less than half a percentage point. The Dow
Jones industrial average _ which added Microsoft to its basket of
30 stocks last week _ fell 14.37 points, closing at 10,718.85, and
the S&AMP;P 500 index fell 6.78 points, closing at 1377.01.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's founder and chairman, William H. Gates, saw the
value of his holdings in the company decline by $1.27 billion
Monday. His Microsoft portfolio was still worth $70.24 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of companies that might benefit from the Microsoft ruling
soared. Red Hat Inc., a developer the Linux software that may one
day challenge Microsoft's Windows operating system, gained 18-1/16
a share, closing at 104. Apple Computer, maker of the Macintosh
operating system, jumped 8-1/16, to close at 96 3/8. Archrival Sun
Microsystems Inc., which is developing software that runs on any
operating system, gained 2 3/16, to close at 111 7/8.
</P>
<P>
   Fears that a Microsoft downturn could trip a broader market
decline were hardly alarmist: The software company's market value
of $460 billion value is the biggest of any US company and accounts
for about 4.5 percent of the value of the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
stock index. Microsoft is held by about one-third of US mutual
funds and is typically among the biggest holding in their
portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Jackson's preliminary finding that Microsoft ``stifled
innovation'' by using its dominance in PC operating systems to
quash rivals was ``pretty negative,'' according to Mark Corcoran, a
technology analyst with D.A. Davidson &AMP; Co. in Portland, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Windows operating system is installed in more than
90 percent of all personal computers sold worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised,'' Corcoran said. ``I thought Microsoft would be
down 10 or 15 bucks this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Microsoft's losses were contained because its
dominance is hardly news. Heavy trading in Microsoft's stock _
about 121 million shares traded Monday, compared with about 30
million on a typical day _ reflected division among investors over
whether the court would order a remedy, what that remedy might be,
and what its impact might be on the Redmond, Wash., software
behemoth would be.
</P>
<P>
   Given the harsh wording in Jackson's finding, analysts predicted
that the court's and the US Justice Department's choices boil down
to either requiring Microsoft to change its brutish tactics in
selling software or to spin off as separate companies the
businesses units that sell Windows, or the Internet Explorer
browser, Office software, and other products.
</P>
<P>
   In the most extreme outcome, a breakup of Microsoft, the
company's future may be bright, said William Rhodes, vice president
of investment strategy in the Boston office of Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Standard Oil or American Telephone &AMP; Telegraph are any
guide to what happens, shareholders will not end up losing,''
Rhodes said. ``They'll be just as well to hold the stock, ride it
out, and hold the companies in the new portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   After the 1984 breakup of AT&AMP;T in an antitrust case brought by
the US government, the stocks of the Baby Bell telephone companies
climbed, as did shares of the equipment division, Lucent
Technologies Inc. Under the court-ordered breakup, AT&AMP;T
shareholders received shares in each of the spinoffs.
</P>
<P>
   At Microsoft, some units are growing faster than the overall
company, analysts said, providing evidence the parts may one day be
worth more than the whole company. Sales by Microsoft's Internet
business, for example, are growing more than 75 percent per year,
compared with 20 percent annual sales gains companywide.
</P>
<P>
   Short of busting up Microsoft, analysts speculated on other
remedies the judge might choose.
</P>
<P>
   Most clear in Jackson's ruling, analyst Corcoran said, was a
finding that Microsoft hampered the success of other companies
selling browsers, namely Netscape Communications Corp., by
requiring that Microsoft's Internet Explorer be bundled with its
Windows operating system. (Earlier this year, America Online Inc.
acquired Netscape.)
</P>
<P>
   If Microsoft misused its muscle in selling everything from its
Office software suite to its Internet product, the judge may seek a
broader remedy to halt Microsoft from obstructing competition in
selling a range of products, Corcoran said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge might ``say is Microsoft cannot obstruct other
companies and other software developers from building
Windows-compatible products that can be ported to other platforms,
such as Unix or Java or Linus,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts listed several reasons Jackson's finding did not result
in pandemonium, as some feared.
</P>
<P>
   First, since the finding was issued Friday, investors had the
weekend to digest its meaning. Most concluded that Jackson's next
decision _ whether Microsoft violated antitrust laws and how to
remedy that _ will be more important. That won't be known for
months, or even years, if the case is appealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was just the opening chapter in a multichapter book,''
said James Weiss, deputy head of equities for State Street Research
&AMP; Management Co. in Boston.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 2011EST &QL; 
