<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3261 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-HEART09-COX     11-08 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEART09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New approach: Drug helps clear arteries
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A new drug made by an Alpharetta, Ga., company shows
potential in unplugging millions of Americans' clogged arteries,
researchers said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A report on the drug, called AGI-1067, was among research
presented at a meeting of the American Heart Association in
Atlanta, where scientists also heard about new blood pressure drugs
and the heart-healthy benefits of exercise.
</P>
<P>
   The drug treats clogged arteries by reducing inflammation of the
arterial lining and lowering cholesterol. In experiments on mice
that were bred to have high cholesterol levels, the drug inhibited
the progression of atherosclerosis _ the narrowing or blocking of
coronary arteries _ by 66 percent after 12 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a whole new notion that inflammation of the blood
vessels is a big part of atherosclerosis,'' said Dr. Uday Saxena,
vice president of preclinical research at AtheroGenics, an
Alpharetta biopharmaceutical company. ``There are no drugs out
there now that can do this. This is a whole new approach to disease
management.''
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 11 million Americans suffer from clogged arteries,
which puts them at high risk for a heart attack or stroke. Eating
too much food that's high in cholesterol, such as meat and
whole-milk diary products, can lead to the buildup of plaque in the
arteries. The accumulation of plaque presents a major health threat
as people age because their arteries become too narrow for blood
and oxygen to reach the heart or brain.
</P>
<P>
   Bypass surgery and angioplasty have been common treatments to
clear narrowed arteries. But research in the past decade has
focused on developing drugs to lower elevated cholesterol and
reverse or prevent atherosclerosis.
</P>
<P>
   While AtheroGenics' researchers cautioned that the successful
research to date is only based on mice models, they also provided a
dose of hope at the medical conference that continues through
Wednesday at the Georgia World Congress Center.
</P>
<P>
   It could take seven to 10 years for the drug to pass all
required federal mandates of safety, efficacy and risk.
</P>
<P>
   Other findings released at the conference included:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Women who follow all the standard health advice _ eat
sensibly, don't smoke, exercise, keep weight down, have only an
occasional drink _ can reduce their chance of heart disease 82
percent. But only 1 percent of the women in the Nurses' Health
Study actually followed all those rules.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A study proving that middle-aged women can avoid weight gain
accompanying menopause by following a low-fat, reduced-calorie diet
and increasing physical activity. The five-year University of
Pittsburgh study divided women into two groups, a behavioral
intervention group and a control group. Women who did not exercise
regularly or follow the low-fat diet gained an average of 5.2
pounds, while the intervention group maintained weight or dropped a
pound on average.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  An experimental class of drugs appears to be the most potent
ever at reducing high blood pressure. The new medicines are called
vasopeptidase inhibitors. Several are in development, but the
furthest along is Bristol-Myers Squibb's Vanlev, known generically
as omapatrilat. Like standard ACE inhibitors, the vasopeptidase
inhibitors block an enzyme that raises blood pressure. However, the
medicine also stops another enzyme called neutral endopeptidase,
protecting the body's supply of helpful substances that make blood
vessels relax.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  AIDS patients taking protease inhibitors may be at risk for
developing coronary artery disease because the drugs lead to a
dysfunction of the lining of the blood vessels that regulate blood
flow and blood clotting. University of Wisconsin researchers
stressed that the findings are preliminary and ``in no way suggest
that HIV protease inhibitors in fact do more harm than good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
