<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3273 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     11-08 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
By LEAH GARCHIK 
Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; WHY SHE HATES SAN FRANCISCO &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ex-New Yorker  &UR; Alexandra Zissu &LR;  moved to San Francisco in
September _ to follow a boyfriend who was chasing an e-career _ and
hasn't yet left her heart here. In an essay in the New York
Observer, Zissu shares some of her complaints:
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco sucks. I mean really, really sucks. ... I loathe
San Francisco. You can't hail a cab. You can't jaywalk. The people
are ugly and unfashionable. Nobody has boundaries: They walk right
up to you on the street and say things or even tap you on your
arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Her living space is too big. ``The apartment makes me
uncomfortable; growing up in New York, my bedroom was the size of
my closet here. What to do with all this space?'' What's more,
``There are more homeless people here than I have ever seen in my
entire New York life, and most of them are 16-year-old white kids.
You can buy California wine in New York, but you can't get a slice
of pizza in San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Zissu calls the nightlife ``pathetic,'' and complains that ``to
go from one bar to the next you have to walk and walk and walk.''
Furthermore, ``bars close at 2 a.m. and you can't smoke in them. No
one ever has wet hair, which leads me to believe no one bathes.''
</P>
<P>
   When Personals called to ask Zissu if she had anything to add
for San Francisco readers, the author responded: ``This piece is as
much about my own limitations as it is about the limitations of San
Francisco. I am sure any San Franciscan new to New York could
produce an equally amusing and spirited rant; the material is
certainly there.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE GENDER GAP &LR;
</P>
<P>
   According to weekly Nielsen/NetRatings tabulations of Internet
use, 87.8 percent of the Web surfers visiting BabyCenter.com last
week were women, and 87.3 percent of surfers visiting the
sports-only site Rivals.com were men.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - The Los Angeles magazine Glue says that  &UR; Nicolas Cage &LR; 's body
double, a Canadian, ``doesn't seem to be as tough as the man he
plays.'' During a recent stay in Los Angeles, he called the front
desk to complain that actress  &UR; Julia Stiles &LR; , in a neighboring
room, was playing loud music and interfering with his sleep. ``It
was only 11 p.m.,'' sniffed the clerk. ``I had to remind him we're
in L.A., not Toronto.''
</P>
<P>
   - An unexpected unseasonal rain in Kemi, Finland, caused the
melting of an ice castle that was to have been the backdrop for
A&AMP;E's ``Winter Solstice on Ice,'' a holiday special starring the
Bay Area's own  &UR; Brian Boitano &LR; . When the set turned into puddles,
the cast and crew moved northward, to the Arctic shelf, where the
cameras caught a polar bear watching the skaters.
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Beverly Brown &LR;  writes she was ``silently commending'' the
driver of a Jeep in front of her in Mill Valley on Saturday, which
bore a ``Hang Up and Drive'' bumper sticker. Then she watched the
driver pull out his electric razor and shave his bald head, while
``I followed him from Mill Valley to 101 North. ... He was still
shaving at Corte Madera.''
</P>
<P>
   - Five San Francisco police cars pulled up at Brannan and Second
last Tuesday night, and eight cops stormed a building and raced up
to the fourth floor. There, writes student  &UR; Marc &LR; 
 &UR; Levinson &LR; , participants in  &UR; Cliff Osmond' &LR; s acting class were doing
``The Fabulous Baker Boys'' scene in which the two brothers are
yelling and fighting over their stalled careers. At least the two
actors ``got their first public recognition outside of the class,''
writes Levinson.
</P>
<P>
   Another San Francisco acting teacher, honored with a theater
named here yesterday, is Jean Shelton, not Jack.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOLIDAY GIFT NO. 3 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Steve Finacom  &LR; forwards an item from www.realgoods.com company
with a conscience that provides ``the kind of eco-friendly
alternative we need _ an everyday item made better by sustainable
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The $39.95  &LR; Reclaimed &LR;  T-Shirt  &LR; B &LR; ath  &LR; M &LR; at is ``crafted from
reclaimed garment industry waste that would otherwise stuff our
landfills.'' Gift wrap is available.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``My big success is over, and it's no longer interfering with my
life the way it was in 1990, when I was on the cover of Time
magazine. The minute I saw that magazine, I knew it was over, and
at that point a dark cloud began to form over me. I wasn't unhappy
during that period, because there's a freedom that comes when
you're down _ you've taken the beating, things aren't gonna get any
worse and it's all just part of the cycle. It's no fun, though.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &LR;   &LR; Director  &UR; David Lynch &LR; , whose new movie is ``The Straight
Story,'' in Premiere magazine.
</P>
</TEXT>
