A3280 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-MAGNET-THERAPY-LIFEBE     11-08 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGNET-THERAPY-LIFEBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAGNET THERAPY HAS ROOTS IN ANCIENT CULTURES
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes color photos of magnets in use on body and a couple using
magnet therapy) 
 By MATTHEW K. PRUITT 
 c.1999 NYT Regional Newspapers 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pat and Maria McCall have a shared attraction. You could even
call it a magnetism.
</P>
<P>
   The faux-pearl necklace that Maria McCall, 58, wears is laden
with magnets in disguise _ every other bead is a little ball of
magnetic activity.
</P>
<P>
   Her 61-year-old husband, Pat, wears his magnets inside a cloth
brace covering his left knee. One flat, circular disk is on one
side of the knee, its twin on the other side.
</P>
<P>
   The Spartanburg, S.C., couple, like a growing number of
Americans, wear the specialized magnets to relieve a host of
ailments, ranging from joint pain to breathing difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Many professional athletes, especially golfers, swear by them.
Magnets are now being sold in shoes, wrist bands, jewelry, mattress
pads and pillows.
</P>
<P>
   Using magnetic fields for healing dates back to ancient cultures
in Egypt, China and Greece. Lodestones, rocks with strong magnetic
properties, were the agents of choice then.
</P>
<P>
   The modern practice consists of one of two methods: placing
magnets on the affected area, or using machines to generate highly
focused electromagnetic fields applied to aching joints or muscles.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that magnets, when placed on painful joints or
muscles, stimulate blood flow to the areas, which facilitates
healing and pain relief. But few significant controlled studies
have been done to verify the healing effect of applying magnets to
the body.
</P>
<P>
   Both the American Medical Association and the Food and Drug
Administration say there's not enough scientific proof that such
magnet therapy works.
</P>
<P>
   There have been several scattered studies supporting the claims,
however.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) A 1997 study at Houston's Baylor College of Medicine
found that applying magnets of a relatively high intensity can
control pain for postpolio patients. But the doctors reported they
couldn't find any other significant research on the healing effects
of magnets.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) In a New York study published last year in the American
Journal of Pain Management, 24 patients found that wearing magnetic
footpad insoles relieved foot pain caused by diabetes and other
ailments.
</P>
<P>
   (BULLET) A number of patients were successfully treated for
chronic joint pain and swelling with highly focused and controlled
magnetic fields by Dr. Robert Holcomb and Dr. Michael McLean at the
Vanderbilt University Medical Center in Nashville, Tenn. A summary
of this work can be found on the Vanderbilt Web site.
(www.vanderbilt.edu)
</P>
<P>
   Chiropractor and acupuncturist Alan Bonebrake of Irving, Tex.,
says the use of magnets has been proven effective over thousands of
years, since it stems from the ancient healing arts. He has treated
patients for a variety of ills with magnets for about 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's most effective on pain and circulation disturbances,''
Bonebrake says. ''When you get a negative polarity field, it causes
blood vessels to dilate and a shift in the ions. This can correct
nerve functioning.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, some companies sell cheap, bipolar magnets placed in
mattresses and such, which can even make things worse in the long
run.''
</P>
<P>
   The monopolar magnets used in research and sold by catalogs are
anywhere from 10 to 400 times as strong as ordinary,
refrigerator-type magnets. These powerful magnets cost from $40 for
joint supports or bracelets to $1,000 for larger, more specialized
devices.
</P>
<P>
   ''These products are safe, and it's certainly worth a try,''
says Mike McCormick, founder of Magnetic Solutions, L.L.C., a
manufacturer and distributor of magnetic therapy products in
Arlington, Tex. ''They work effectively for the greater majority of
people, and the worst that can happen to you is...nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   While doctors tend to agree that magnet therapy is, at the
least, harmless for most, they caution pregnant women and people
with pacemakers or other electronic implants not to use magnets.
</P>
<P>
   The varied applications of legitimate magnet therapy are only
starting to be discovered, say researchers.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Dorlan, of Spartanburg, is conducting a controlled
study examining the effects of electromagnetic fields on a common
form of arthritis. Dorlan will study 60 patients over a six-month
period.
</P>
<P>
   The fields are generated by a patented machine that pulses
magnetic fields over the affected area for about an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Dorlan said the treatment has proved effective in easing the
pain of arthritis and stimulating cartilage growth. This treatment
is so well accepted abroad that doctors routinely use it to treat
acute sport injuries, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no correlation between this and those magnets that
stick on,'' he said. ''We don't know what those do. There is
anecdotal evidence, but you cannot point to legitimate studies in
the literature that show improvement.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters such as the McCalls, however, strongly believe in
magnets' healing powers. Maria McCall sometimes places magnets on
her chest when she sleeps to help her breathe and uses a roller
containing magnets on her back to relieve pain or just to relax.
</P>
<P>
   And Pat McCall, an engineer for 20 years, says the magnets
alleviated a near-crippling pain in his knee, allowing him to
continue competitive cycling and even to shorten his racing time.
</P>
<P>
   ''These things work,'' he said. ''There's no doubt about it.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Matt Pruitt writes for the Herald-Journal in Spartanburg,
S.C.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
