A3281 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-CHILDHOOD-SPEECH-PR0B     11-08 1282
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDHOOD-SPEECH-PR0BLEMS-LIFEBEAT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOES YOUR CHILD HAVE A SPEECH PROBLEM?
</HEADLINE>
  By KATHERINE MARTIN  
 c.1999 Katherine Martin 
 World rights 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents of a new baby eagerly watch for each milestone in the
developmental process: the first smile, the first step, the first
babyish babbling. But if that babbling doesn't turn into clear
speech after a few years, parents become concerned and wonder if
they should intervene.
</P>
<P>
   If you notice some difficulty when your child speaks, how can
you tell whether it is a genuine speech or language problem or if
your child is simply going through a developmental process of trial
and error? Here are some guidelines to help you consider if it's
time to consult a professional or simply to take a ''wait and see''
approach.
</P>
<P>
   Experts consider three basic areas essential to communication:
articulation, language, and listening and auditory processing.
 &UR; Articulation &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Articulation is our ability to speak clearly and intelligibly.
An example of this would be the child who mixes up speech sounds
within a word, such as ''wed'' for ''red'', ''diddy'' for
''kitty'', or ''cah'' for ''car''. It is quite normal for children
to go through a process of trial and error until their articulation
skills emerge and mature.
</P>
<P>
   So what should you do if you observe these behaviors?
</P>
<P>
   Keep the following factors in mind:
</P>
<P>
   1. The age of your child. Articulation skills develop
progressively. In other words, some sounds develop earlier than
others. If your child is in preschool and can't say ''s'' or ''r''
yet, remember that these sounds don't emerge until later (age 6 for
''r'' and age 8 for ''s'').
</P>
<P>
   However, if your child is school age and cannot say the earlier
developing sounds (for example, ''p'', ''m'', ''n'', ''w'', ''b'',
and ''k'' to name just a few) then it may be cause for concern. In
general, most children can say the speech sounds of the language by
age 8, assuming there are no other physical or congenital problems
present such as hearing loss, cleft lip or palate.
</P>
<P>
   2. The number of sounds in error. In other words, the more
speech sounds your child has difficulty with, the more likely he or
she will be a candidate for speech therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Resist the temptation to force the child to say the word
correctly. Rather than stating, ''No, don't say that, say ____'',
simply model the correct production for the child after he or she
makes an error and move on.
 &UR; Language &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What are some of the behaviors you may see in a child with
language difficulties? One example might be the child who can't get
the right grammar, for example, ''Me eated apple.'' Another
possibility might be the child who uses the improper name for a
concept, such as calling a horse a cow. Or maybe the child is
talking in sentences, but he or she just rambles and it is
difficult, at best, to make sense of what the child means.
</P>
<P>
   Again, it is quite normal for children to have grammatical
errors in their speech as they develop their skills, and confusion
with vocabulary terms will occur.
</P>
<P>
   So how will you know if your child is going through a stage
rather than developing a true problem?
</P>
<P>
   First, consult one of the many language development guides
available through the American Speech-Language Hearing Association
(ASHA) or a book that specifically addresses language issues in
children.
</P>
<P>
   In the meanwhile, it is important to keep these guidelines in
mind:
</P>
<P>
   1. The development of speech and language skills in the first
three years is critical to a child's future academic success in
school. In order for children to build a strong language base, it
is important to provide them with a variety of experiences from
infancy onward. This includes play through toys, objects, books,
games (make up your own) and interactions with real people, rather
than the television, Nintendo, or a computer.
</P>
<P>
   2. Whenever we develop language, remember that our understanding
or comprehension of a concept (receptive language) will always
develop before our expressive language. In other words, if you want
your child to say the word ''ball'', he or she will first have to
develop an understanding of what a ''ball'' is through exposure to
it via play, games and so forth.
 &UR; Listening &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   How are your children's listening skills? Are they getting
plenty of practice at home before they are of school age? Our
listening skills (some refer to this as auditory processing) are
very important to building a strong foundation for language and
subsequently academic success. If your children aren't taught at
home how to listen, don't expect this skill to spontaneously
develop once they are in school.
</P>
<P>
   Listening goes beyond having good hearing. Good hearing means
that if we hooked our ears up to an audiometer to be tested, we
would have no problem hearing the tones that are presented through
the headset. Good listening means that the message traveled from
the ears to the brain where we comprehended and attached meaning to
what was said, and then responded appropriately.
</P>
<P>
   What can a parent do to develop better listening habits,
particularly if the child is displaying some difficulty listening
anyway? Here are some suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   1. Good listening habits are learned from people, not things.
Listening takes practice, and it requires that there be a listener
and speaker interacting with one another in a ''live''
give-and-take process. Once again, the television, computer, or
videos won't substitute.
</P>
<P>
   2. If you want your children to listen to you, listen to them by
giving them your full attention. Turn off the radio, television,
dishwasher, or computer. Be present in the same room, have your
face visible to your child, and obtain eye contact before speaking.
</P>
<P>
   3. Keep it simple. You can tell your child, ''After you go
upstairs to brush your teeth, come back to the kitchen and feed the
dog'' or ''Brush your teeth and feed the dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Get to the point. The content of the message is the key, not the
length. Always be ready to modify and change what you say. If the
child cannot get a two-part direction, give him or her one part. If
one part is still too much, use visual cues like pictures for
smaller children or the written word for older children to
supplement what you say.
</P>
<P>
   If you believe your child's speech or language behaviors are
more than just developmental, what can you do? First, contact your
state speech and hearing association for a local speech-language
pathologist certified by ASHA. You could also contact your local
medical clinics, hospitals, or schools.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, learn if your child qualifies to receive speech
therapy. Based upon guidelines in the Individuals with Disabilities
in Education Act, speech language therapy can be obtained for
children in the public schools from ages 3 to 21. A copy of the act
can be obtained by calling ASHA (1-800-638-8255).
</P>
<P>
   If your child is in need of early intervention, there are many
state-sponsored programs for children from birth to 3 years. Your
state health and human services agencies can provide more
information.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Katherine L. Martin is a certified speech-language pathologist
and author of ''Does My Child Have a Speech Problem?'') &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Website at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on LifeBeat
and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this ``separate buy'' article, call
New York Times Syndicate sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
(732) 390-4480 or fax her at (732) 390-4697.
</P>
