<HEADER>
A3282 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BOX-LENNOX-COX     11-08 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-LENNOX-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis returns to spotlight, awaits respect
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ This is the moment for Lennox Lewis. The defining
moment. To this point of an accomplished career, the heavyweight
champion from England generally has been regarded as a big man with
a big punch _ and, significantly, a big, lingering question mark.
Whom has he beaten?
</P>
<P>
   In truth, Lewis has conquered all challengers, except, of
course, Evander Holyfield in March, which is a point of contention
for many people, particularly him. The problem with the fighters
Lewis did defeat is that none are of renown.
</P>
<P>
   So, now comes Holyfield again, Saturday night at the Thomas &AMP;
Mack Center. This time, he represents the hurdle that could lift
Lennox Lewis to more than the undisputed heavyweight championship.
A win, a resounding win over one of boxing's true warriors would
give Lewis respect.
</P>
<P>
   In the fight game, that's a coveted label, worth more than the
$15 million he'll earn for the bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox is a two-time champion and he still hasn't won the
public's respect,'' Lewis' trainer, Emanuel Steward said. ``He
still hasn't had that great, solid fight. Lennox has not enjoyed a
great victory over a big, great fighter. Mike Tyson and Riddick
Bowe threw away their belts to not fight Lennox. Then he gets
Evander, controls the fight and gets a bad decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, he has a second chance now. But Lennox has to win big to
even be in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's exactly what Lewis said he expects. The response from
people on the street has bolstered his confidence into the
stratosphere. And the more he watches footage from the first
Holyfield bout, the more Lewis feels like a winner, if not an
official victor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I gave (Holyfield) a bit too much respect,'' Lewis said.
``But I was hitting him three shots to one. And I look back, and
there was so much more I could have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``This time will be even easier,'' he said. ``I really feel I
need to knock him out. . . . The only way I lose this fight is if I
stick out my chin and say, `OK, Evander. Hit me.' I'm still
unheralded. There's still a lot from me you haven't seen. If
Evander is better, it'll bring out the best in me.''
</P>
<P>
   Steward, a highly respected trainer, said Lewis has prepared
himself physically to perform at his best, which would be too much
for Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lennox is in better condition this time,'' Steward said. ``He
played with Evander the first time, made him look like a little
kid. This time, he's trained much harder. He's focused on a
knockout.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6 feet 5 inches and somewhere around 245 pounds, Lewis dwarfs
Holyfield, who is 6 feet 2 inches and about 216 pounds. But Steward
claims that Lewis' performance in the first fight has fostered a
greater advantage for his fighter over Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Lennox and Evander are together, it's to the point where
Evander is almost intimidated to be around Lennox,'' Steward said.
``Lennox got through his first super fight. That was big for him.
And he's over that. He's ready now, relaxed and confident that he
can knock that guy out. Now, Evander has a psychological respect
and fear of Lennox.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Holyfield, who did not avoid Lewis' left jab in New York,
conceded that Lewis, 34, is more talented than he thought. ``The
guy has more skills and more movement than I gave him credit for,''
Holyfield said.
</P>
<P>
   As for fearing Lewis, Holyfield could only laugh. ``I fear no
man,'' Holyfield said. ``I'll be there on Nov. 13th. We'll see
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he's seen the New York bout about 25 times, and each
viewing only solidifies his expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This fight will lead to (Holyfield's) retirement,'' Lewis
said. ``When I hit him, he'll know I'm the real deal. He will get
hurt this time. I don't see anything Evander can do. He's never
seen anything like Lennox Lewis. He has no game plan for me. I'm
very confident, especially coming off the last fight. I made a mark
that I'm the real deal and there's no more Evander Holyfield.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' training has dealt mostly with landing power punches that
could stop Holyfield. In their initial encounter, Lewis kept
Holyfield on the end of his long jab but was timid about stepping
in to inflict serious damage. With a second chance, Lewis said, he
will seize a knockout opening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have stepped up my pace when I had him hurt in the
fifth round,'' Lewis said. ``I'm going to pick up the pace from the
start (Saturday). If the opportunity presents itself, I'd like to
get rid of him. I don't get paid for overtime.''
</P>
<P>
   All Lewis' bravado and talk aside, he's ``not a bad fighter,''
Don Turner, Holyfield's trainer said. ``But every time Evander
fought him (in March), he ran right through him. He did what he
wanted to do. And Lennox didn't want to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   To this point, that's Lewis' legacy. He beat up on Andrew Golata
and avenged a loss to Oliver McCall and beat Shannon Briggs in a
slug-fest. But Lewis has not done much to generate true excitement
or to raise his name as a respected champion.
</P>
<P>
   Holyfield had Bowe, whom he beat two of three times in memorable
battles. Holyfield had Tyson twice; once winning by TKO, the other
by disqualification when Tyson bit his ear.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis has _ Holyfield. This is his moment. It ultimately will
define who he is as a boxer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is a really important fight for me,'' Lewis said.
``And I'm going to take advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Steward was more emphatic. ``The fight will end in a knockout. I
wanted a knockout the first time, but Lennox wanted to show all his
talents, his boxing skills. This time, Lennox is more focused on a
knockout. And for his legacy, he needs it.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Bunn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
