<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ELECT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUNNER-UP IN MEXICO PRIMARY SAYS HE WON'T PROTEST THE RESULT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Roberto Madrazo Pintado, the candidate who
finished second in the governing party's first presidential primary
after a rancorous campaign that had seemed to threaten a party
rupture, acknowledged his defeat on Monday. He said he would not
protest the results of Sunday's balloting, or leave the party.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters just past midnight, Madrazo did not
congratulate the winner, Francisco Labastida Ochoa. But because
Madrazo had repeatedly accused party leaders in the campaign of
displaying favoritism toward Labastida, Madrazo's acceptance of the
outcome amounted to a crucial endorsement of the primary.
</P>
<P>
   Two other candidates who had been equally critical also decided
not to lodge formal protests. One, Humberto Roque Villanueva,
publicly acknowledged Labastida's broad victory. The other
candidate, Manuel Bartlett Diaz, refused to acknowledge his defeat
late on Sunday, and he remained silent on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   According to the official results announced on Monday by the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, Labastida won 55 percent of the
9 million votes, a showing that won 273 of the 300 electoral
districts. Madrazo won 29 percent of the votes, Bartlett 6 percent
and Roque 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The primary, which ended the lengthy tradition under which
Mexican presidents have handpicked their successors, attracted
tremendous news coverage, and Madrazo's decision opened the way for
a general closing of ranks in the party, known as the PRI. As a
result, analysts said that the outcome had greatly bolstered the
party's prospects of keeping its long-held presidency in the
election on July 2, when Labastida will face two opposition
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the PRI, this was an extraordinary success,'' said Luis
Rubio, a political scientist who is often critical of the party.
``And Madrazo put the cherry on top at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo, a former governor of Tabasco state, campaigned as a
rebel who was defying the party establishment. Even on Sunday
evening, when preliminary results were already showing that
Labastida had won by a landslide, Madrazo appeared to be preparing
to challenge the results.
</P>
<P>
   After television and radio stations broadcast Labastida's
dramatic victory, Madrazo appeared before a few dozen dispirited
followers
</P>
<P>
   ``I recognize that the vote tendencies are not favorable to
me,'' he said. He spoke of continuing to lead a movement for
democratic change. But aides to Labastida had said before the vote
that if Labastida won, they would offer posts to Madrazo's
followers to seduce them back into the party mainstream. Several
appeared more than willing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We here in Veracruz totally accept Labastida's victory, with
great enthusiasm,'' said Guillermo Zuniga Martinez, Madrazo's
campaign coordinator there.
</P>
</TEXT>
