<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL NOTEBOOK: Car accident led to death in childbirth
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A coroner has ruled that the wife of Indianapolis Colts
defensive back Steve Muhammad died Sunday from excessive bleeding
during labor, caused by injuries in a car accident last week.
</P>
<P>
   Frances Kelly, Marion County's chief deputy coroner, said the
injuries Nichole Muhammad had on her chest and lower abdomen
appeared ``consistent with a steering wheel she hit in an accident
last Thursday.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Muhammad was arrested and charged with battering his wife
and their 6-year-old son 10 days before she died while giving birth
to a stillborn child.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. John Pless, of Indiana University forensics, said the
injuries Mrs. Muhammad received in the alleged attack were to her
back and arm and were ``no bigger than a dime and not
significant.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple had argued about money at their apartment Oct. 28. A
police report said Muhammad twisted his wife's right wrist behind
her back, pushed her against a wall and threw her to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad then struck his son, Eric, several times after the boy
began striking his father with a yellow plastic baseball bat. The
report added that the player disconnected the telephone when his
wife tried to call 911.
</P>
<P>
   Colts coach Jim Mora, who announced the deaths Sunday after his
team's 25-17 victory over Kansas City, said he spoke to Muhammad on
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was struggling, as you would imagine,'' Mora said. ``I
don't think it will be a distraction. I think (the players) are
saddened for Steve and his family, but I don't think they'll be
distracted in preparations for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Colts, one game out of first place in the AFC East, visit
the New York Giants this week.
</P>
<P>
   It's Miller time
</P>
<P>
   Chris Miller will make his second start in a row for Denver on
Sunday night in Seattle. This past Sunday, Miller played in his
first-regular season game since Dec. 3, 1995, and led the Broncos
to a 33-17 victory at San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Miller completed 14 of 24 passes for 166 yards and avoided the
mistakes that plagued Denver in its six losses this season. Miller,
who retired nearly four years ago after suffering five concussions
in 14 months, called it ``one of the greatest days of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Mike Shanahan said Brian Griese's right shoulder is still
sore and that Bubby Brister will probably miss at least one more
game while nursing a strained oblique muscle and loose cartilage in
his knee.
</P>
<P>
   Dilfer's redemption
</P>
<P>
   Former University of Georgia quarterback Eric Zeier's sore ribs
cost him a starting job with Tampa Bay. Trent Dilfer, benched two
weeks ago, completed 15 of 20 passes for 227 yards and three
touchdowns in a 31-16 win at New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Tony Dungy said Dilfer will start Sunday against Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   ``More than anything else, you're a great leader when you win,
and you're a terrible leader when you lose,'' Dilfer said.San
Francisco's dilemma
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco coach Steve Mariucci said he'll decide by
Wednesday whether to start quarterback Jeff Garcia or Steve
Stenstrom on Sunday at New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers, who have lost four games in a row, had only 90
passing yards in their 27-6 loss to Pittsburgh. Garcia, a former
Canadian League star who replaced injured Steve Young, completed
only 7 of 18 attempts for 39 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci said Garcia is leaving the pocket too quickly.
Stenstrom, a former Bears starter, is more of a drop-back passer.
</P>
<P>
   Banks out for season
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville running back Tavian Banks will miss the rest of the
season with a torn anterior cruciate ligament in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Banks was injured late in the fourth quarter of a 30-7 victory
over the Falcons. Atlanta cornerback Ray Buchanan hit Banks after
he had stepped out of bounds on the left sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville coach Tom Coughlin said he did not think the hit
was a cheap shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Tavian knew he was out of bounds. I don't think
Buchanan did either,'' Coughlin said.
</P>
<P>
   But some Jaguars players were miffed about the hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was sick,'' running back Fred Taylor said. ``That ain't
right. He was out of bounds. He wasn't trying to run. He was trying
to catch his balance.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Schlabach writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
