<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL AND PALESTINIANS BEGIN TALKS BY STATING POSITIONS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RAMALLAH, West Bank _ Israeli and Palestinian teams sat down
here Monday to begin negotiating a permanent settlement of their
century-old conflict, staking out opposing positions, but promising
to work faithfully to reach an accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be an honor to disagree with you,'' Oded Eran, the
head of the Israeli negotiating team and a former ambassador to
Jordan, told the head of the Palestinian team, Yasser Abed Rabbo.
``But it will be a fulfillment of a life's dream to shake hands
with you at the end of the process and to say, `Brother and
comrade, we did it.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a historical moment for all of us,'' Abed Rabbo, a
minister in the Palestinian cabinet, said after the hour-and-a-half
meeting, which began an intensive effort to negotiate a framework
agreement on a permanent peace by mid-February.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that through continuous and extensive work we will
be able to meet the date,'' Abed Rabbo said. ``We started with a
very open and frank atmosphere, without any barriers.''
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, said he would
meet Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel on Tuesday. Both leaders
are in Paris for a meeting of the Socialist International.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Israeli-Palestinian accord, reached in September at
Sharm el-Sheik in Egypt, commits the two sides to try to reach the
framework agreement by Feb. 13 and to conclude a permanent treaty
by September.
</P>
<P>
   The issues to be tackled are the most intractable in the
Palestinian-Israeli conflict, and they were deferred in the 1993
Oslo interim accord. They include the future of Jerusalem,
Palestinian refugees displaced in the 1948 and 1967 Arab-Israeli
wars, Jewish settlements in the West Bank and the Gaza Strip,
borders, water and security arrangements.
</P>
<P>
   Eran said that because each side was well versed in the other's
positions the ambitious timetable for reaching an accord could be
met.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long road we have to cover in a very short time, but I
believe that through our joint efforts we can make it,'' Eran said.
``After several decades of conflict and negotiations now for almost
six years, all the problems between us are known. There is nothing
that we will learn in another 10 years or 15 years of conflict and
strife. All the issues, all the views, all the opinions are known
to each other. It is not a matter of discovery. It is a matter of
negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the cordiality of the first session, the opening
statements restated the sharply conflicting positions that the
sides have long maintained. Although clearly a starting stance by
both sides, the yawning gap between them testified to the hard
bargaining ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Abed Rabbo began with a demand for a full Israeli withdrawal
from the West Bank, Gaza Strip and East Jerusalem to the boundaries
before the 1967 Arab-Israeli war. ``Without return by Israel of all
land acquired by war in 1967, including Jerusalem, our efforts will
amount to no more than the deferral of crises,'' he said. ``The
only formula that is acceptable is land for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian ``self-determination,'' a code word for statehood,
is another goal, Abed Rabbo said, as well as ``the right of
Palestinian refugees to return and to receive compensation and
restitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Abed Rabbo demanded an end to the construction and expansion of
Jewish settlements in the West Bank and Gaza Strip, saying such
activity predetermined the outcome of the talks. ``We find it
inconceivable and quite contrary to the logic of negotiation to
continue changing facts on the ground,'' he said. In later remarks
to reporters, Abed Rabbo called continued settlement building ``the
main obstacle to progress in our negotiations.''
</P>
<P>
   Eran named security as Israel's priority, putting it at the top
of a proposed agenda for the talks. But in his remarks he took up
the issue of Jerusalem first.
</P>
<P>
   ``To all Israelis, regardless of their political views,
Jerusalem is our capital, and it should continue to be so,'' he
said. ``Under its sovereignty, Israel has proven its sensitivity to
all religions and to the sanctity of freedom of worship. We
therefore maintain that it should remain united, open and under
Israel's sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   Borders have to be secure, and ``the pre-1967 lines clearly do
not provide for this,'' Eran added.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to Barak's plan to retain large sections of settlements
under Israeli control, Eran said, ``Establishing secure borders
should equally leave most of the Israelis residing today in the
West Bank and Gaza under Israeli sovereignty.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution of the refugee problem ``cannot be found within the
borders of Israel,'' Eran said. Speaking to reporters, he added
that the solution ``should be based on absorbing the refugees in
their current places of residence'' with an infusion of ``massive
economic aid.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegation heads said their teams would meet here again on
Thursday and hold regular meetings two or three times a week. The
first order of business will be to come up with an agreed agenda.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
