<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS09-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weary Falcons to get 4 days off
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Falcons players and coaches got the extra day off they
wanted _ despite losing a game.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's 30-7 loss to Jacksonville, coach Dan Reeves
figured that the best medicine for his 2-7 team would be all the
time away from football they can get. The players suggested it
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons will practice Wednesday morning, then players and
coaches will be off Thursday through Sunday in the team's bye week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, they will get just a little bit healthier . . . but
I also think just being away from it for a while may mentally help
everybody, too,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to take a whole different perspective,'' cornerback
Ray Buchanan said. ``Beating us down is probably not going to get
the job done. He said it's not physically that we're losing
football games; it's mentally.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have made costly mistakes, including the penalty for
illegal blocking that nullified Tim Dwight's 99-yard kickoff return
against Jacksonville. Many of Jacksonville's franchise-record nine
sacks were attributed to blown assignments, and these problems are
causing anxiety in the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been with each other since the offseason program (in
late March),'' wide receiver Terance Mathis said. ``It's time to
forget what we've done . . . and go on from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves and his staff usually spend Monday reviewing the previous
game before beginning to prepare for the next opponent. Reeves said
coaches will break down tendencies and try to figure out whether
they should scrap certain philosophies.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves couldn't remember giving players four days off after a
loss. But in a season in which expectations have been swamped by
frustration, he is willing to try anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, this is probably the most frustrated I've
ever been . . . because I know we are better than what we are
playing,'' he said. ``If I thought working would help (we would
work), but . . . I think it is best just to get away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   Count linebacker Henri Crockett among those perplexed about the
Falcons' performances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm at a loss for words,'' Crockett said. ``We've got 10 guys
doing the right thing, and one guy not doing the right thing almost
every play.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Reeves) made the statement, `We've got to find out who wants
to play.' Everybody has to look in the mirror, myself included, and
just do a gut check. (The time off) should help. It all depends on
how we use it.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, in fact, cautioned players how to spend their time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wanted us to be smart . . . and keep our bodies in shape,''
Buchanan said. ``He wants us to stay out of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   That's another kind of problem the Falcons don't need.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
