<HEADLINE>
ALUMNUS GIVES $100 MILLION TO MIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was a gift that surprised even the giver.
</P>
<P>
   A 58-year-old Cambridge, Mass. software entrepreneur stood up
before officials and his fellow alumni from the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology on Saturday night and said he wanted to say
a few words.
</P>
<P>
   In off the cuff remarks, Kenan E. Sahin said he wanted to give
the institute $100 million, which was a cool and spontaneous way of
saying he wanted to make the largest donation in the history of the
school, and one of the 10 largest donations in the history of
higher education.
</P>
<P>
   A self-made billionaire, Sahin was supposed to be giving a
speech in China on Saturday. When the trip was canceled at the last
minute, he decided instead to attend the black tie gala celebrating
the launch of MIT's $1.5 billion fundraising campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of the sound and light show at the height of the
festivities, he was overwhelmed with gratitude for all the
institute had done for him, and decided that the time had come to
give back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been contemplating some sort of gift, obviously, but
during the dinner, it just seemed the timing was right,'' Sahin
said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, college administrators, or at least the president, have
some idea when a donor is about to make a big gift; usually, in
fact, they have worked assiduously for years or months to land it.
</P>
<P>
   But Sahin simply walked over to MIT president Charles Vest at
about 9:15 and said, ``Chuck, I want to say something.'' When Vest
asked ``What is it?'' Sahin refused to answer.
</P>
<P>
   Vest stood up before the 500 guests just finishing their dinners
and introduced the alumnus and former faculty member, saying ``I
really don't know what he's going to say.'' Sahin agreed, ``He
really doesn't know what I'm going to say. Up until a half an hour
ago, I didn't know what I was going to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Sahin recalled how as a student at Robert College in his native
Istanbul, he had a chance conversation with the late Harold Hazen,
a dean at MIT and then-interim president of the Turkish school.
Hazen encouraged him to go to MIT.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' Sahin told the curious crowd, ``spontaneous, spur
of the moment conversations have deep, deep consequences. Little
did I know how that would shape my life. I can't tell you how much
I have benefitted from this institution.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he announced the gift.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd rose for a standing ovation that lasted several
minutes, punctuated by the personal thanks of Vest and other MIT
trustees. Only 12 gifts to colleges or universities have ever been
more than $100 million, though ten have been the same amount,
according to the Chronicle of Higher Education.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my privilege, really,'' Sahin said Monday. ``When one is
fortunate enough to have this kind of wealth, it translates from
hitting the wealth to using it responsibly, in a way that
recognizes what has been given to you.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hitting wealth'' began for Sahin with the remark from Hazen,
which led him to MIT, where he got a bachelors degree in 1963 and a
doctorate in 1969. He began his software company, Kenan Systems
Corp., with $1,000, as an MIT faculty member in 1982. In 1986,
after 16 years on the faculty, he left to run the company full
time, creating software that was quickly used by most major
telecommunications companies for billing and customer service.
</P>
<P>
   In an industry famous for brash entrepreneurs, he was the quiet
one, remaining the sole owner and never sending out press releases
announcing his successes.
</P>
<P>
   And his successes have been many, culminating in January, when
Lucent Technologies bought his company for $1.45 billion in stock _
which all went to Sahin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had been, all day and at the gala, listening to some of the
best minds at MIT and what they were doing and predicting for the
future. I wanted to be a significant contributor to MIT, which
inevitably will shape the thinking about the future.''
</P>
<P>
   The gift is unusual for a reason other than its sheer magnitude
and surprise: it is also unrestricted, meaning that it can be spent
on anything the university deems fit. Most donors, by contrast,
restrict their gifts to go to buildings or things with their names
on them. Sahin set up a committee, of himself, Vest, former MIT
presidents Howard Johnson and Paul Gray, and Teledyne founder Alex
D'Arbeloff, to decide how best to spend the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a gift from the heart, and one that represents a
belief in the importance of what MIT is and will be,'' Vest, who
was traveling in England, said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson called Sahin a ``classic American success story'' _ and
also suggested that maybe MIT shouldn't have been so surprised at
his gesture.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always interested in moving beyond what most people
expected, even what most people imagined.'' Johnson said. ``His
talents were matched by a kind of daring and tenacity that have led
to remarkable success. And yet, there is a kind of modesty and
quiet dignity about him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
