<HEADLINE>
FATE OF RAYTHEON CONSTRUCTION UNIT IN THE AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. Monday backed off assurances it will keep a
Cambridge, Mass. construction unit that builds power plants and
refineries, stepping back from another ambitious goal set by its
new chief executive Daniel Burnham a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham also plans to reorganize Raytheon's big defense unit in
Virginia, a move that will likely diminish the influence of the top
executive there, sources familiar with the matter said.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are the latest steps at the Lexington, Mass. defense
contractor as it struggles to regain its financial footing after a
string of disappointing announcements, culminating in charges for
1999 of about $638 million.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosures, announced last month, sent Raytheon's shares
plummetting to half of what they were worth last July and
foreshadowed renewed rounds of layoffs including up to 300 workers
in Quincy, Mass. There Raytheon plans to close a microelectronics
plant that has operted in the city for decades.
</P>
<P>
   The engineers &AMP; constructors unit in Cambridge recently has
become a thorn in Raytheon's side. The segment once was a cash cow
for Raytheon, drawing contracts to build many of the country's
nuclear power plants. But a series of acquisitions begun in 1993
have failed to pay off, partly because of pressures to hold down
the costs of large-scale industrial building projects.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the unit reported a loss of $253 million on revenue
of $2 billion, and it laid off about 1,600 people. The unit's
performance has suffered lately as well, reporting an operating
loss of $115 million on sales of $659 for the three months ended
Oct. 3.
</P>
<P>
   After taking over as chief executive last year, Burnham brushed
aside suggestions the unit should be sold and said it could be
reorganized and made profitable again. Late last week, a Raytheon
representative said that position remained unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday spokesman David Polk said of the unit that parent
Raytheon is ``looking at its fit in our portfolio.'' Polk declined
to say if any talks were under way to sell the unit, or to comment
on a published report in the Wall Street Journal that said the
company is seeking a buyer. Neither Burnham nor Shea Assad, the
head of the unit, was available to comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who follow the engineering business say they would not
be surprised if the company sold the unit. ``We've heard for a
while that this wasn't core to the operation,'' said Tobias
Levkovich, construction industry analyst for Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Potential buyers for the unit include Morrisson Knudsen Corp. of
Boise, Idaho, Swiss-based ABB and Japan's Mitsubishi Group,
industry observers said. Officials at all three companies declined
to comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Raytheon also plans to reorganize its defense unit
in Virginia, according to sources familiar with the matter. The
changes weren't expected to result in new charges or layoffs, the
source said.
</P>
<P>
   But the changes will likely reduce the influence of William
Swanson, who had been head of the division previously known as
Raytheon Systems Co. The unit last year accounted for about $15
million of Raytheon's company's $20 million in revenue.
</P>
<P>
   That name will be dropped and the divisions that made it up will
now report individually to Burnham. Swanson will stay to oversee a
sensors and defense-systems divisions, at the same level as three
executives he had previously overseen. Swanson was not available to
comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Another executive who once reported to Swanson, Ken Dahlberg,
now will also report to Burnham, the sources said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
