<HEADLINE>
CARDIOLOGY RESEARCH FOCUSES ON PLAQUE IN ARTERIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LEIGH HOPPER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The ability to identify pieces of plaque in arteries
that may break off and cause heart attack or stroke is one of the
most intriguing new areas of research in cardiology _ and the
outgrowth of a discovery made three years ago in the Texas Medical
Center in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the thing that's been missing from our ability to
identify patients most at risk for heart attack and stroke,'' said
Dr. James Willerson, chief of cardiology at the Texas Heart
Institute. ``To be able to detect a vulnerable plaque is very
important.``
</P>
<P>
   Willerson, editor of the medical journal Circulation, is
attending the American Heart Association meeting this week in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Most patients who have a heart attack or stroke have had a
change in their plaque.
</P>
<P>
   Plaque is the thick, hard deposit of cholesterol that cakes up
on artery linings. Sometimes a piece of plaque ruptures and breaks
off, blocking a blood vessel. The result is often a heart attack or
stroke.
</P>
<P>
   Willerson, working with his partner, cardiologist Dr. Ward
Casscells, observed that this happened 50 percent of the time in
arteries that weren't significantly narrowed, and therefore weren't
considered a threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd usually leave them alone,'' he said. ``But they're
dangerous ... We need to know about plaques themselves, regardless
of narrowing.``
</P>
<P>
   The doctors began noting temperature variations in the pieces of
plaque they removed from patients with blocked neck arteries. Using
a hand-held thermometer with a pinlike tip, they could measure
temperatures throughout a piece of plaque. What they discovered was
that the plaque had different temperatures in different spots and
at the site most likely to rupture the temperature was slightly
higher.
</P>
<P>
   Now scientists are building catheters capable of heat detection
to pinpoint these unstable areas of plaque before they break off.
Doctors in Greece have confirmed the Houston findings using such an
instrument. Willerson hopes to start clinical trials in Houston of
a similar device.
</P>
<P>
   Willerson said that because many people with unstable plaque
have no symptoms of heart disease, it is important to develop
noninvasive ways of detecting the potential killer.
</P>
<P>
   A reactive protein found in veins may indicate the presence of
unstable plaque, but it doesn't give a specific location, Willerson
said. But unstable plaque has distinct physical characteristics
that might permit doctors to spot troublesome areas with magnetic
resonance imaging. The plaque that is likely to rupture has a thin,
fibrous cap, with inflamed cells beneath it, and a core of lipids,
or fats.
</P>
<P>
   ``The point is, they're dangerous and this is the first way
we've had to predict them,'' Willerson said. ``This is about
predicting risk of heart attack before it occurs.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
