<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY STOCKS CLIMB AGAIN DESPITE MICROSOFT FINDINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MICROSOFT-MARKETPLACE) 
(mk) 
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Technology stocks on Monday shrugged off the stinging
judicial rebuke delivered to Microsoft last Friday and surged to a
seventh consecutive record.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is insatiable demand right now,'' said Michael Clark,
head of U.S. stock trading for Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand fully where all the demand is coming
from,'' Clark added, ``but for the first time in months we are
seeing people thinking beyond the first of the year and acting on
those thoughts.''
</P>
<P>
   Led by some of Microsoft's major competitors, including Apple
Computer and Sun Microsystems, the NASDAQ composite index rose
41.68 points, or 1.3 percent, to 3,143.97.
</P>
<P>
   But gains in technology stocks were not limited to those who are
likely beneficiaries of the court case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, which is expected to release its third-quarter
earnings after the market closes Tuesday, and Lucent Technologies
helped to pull the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index up by 6.78 points,
or 0.5 percent, to 1,377.01.
</P>
<P>
   And the Dow Jones industrial average managed to rise 14.37
points, or 0.1 percent, to 10,718.85, aided by gains in Exxon, IBM
and Proctor &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Worries persisted through the weekend that Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson's findings of fact in the government's antitrust case
against Microsoft would not only hammer Microsoft, but could drag
down the entire technology sector. Those worries proved unfounded
and analysts and traders said they were surprised with how well
Microsoft fared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured Microsoft would be down at least 10 points,'' said
Philip Dow, a managing director in equity research at Dain Rauscher
Wessels in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the thinking seems to be that if the Justice Department
ultimately breaks it up, the parts will be worth more than the
whole company.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Microsoft was the most actively traded stock
Monday, with 122 million shares changing hands.
</P>
<P>
   The stock was sharply lower during the day, but rallied as the
session progressed and closed at 89 15/16, down 1 5/8.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investors rewarded a number of Microsoft's most
vigorous competitors and critics.
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems gained 2 3/16, to 111 7/8. Oracle, the world's
largest maker of database software, gained 3/4, to 59 7/16. And Red
Hat Inc., developer of an operating system that competes with
Microsoft's Windows, jumped 18 1/8, to 104.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the technology sector, Monday was a good day in the
oil patch.
</P>
<P>
   Exxon gained 3 11/16, to 74 5/16. BP Amoco, which reported a 72
percent increase in third-quarter profit Monday, gained 3 7/16, to
55 3/4. Mobil was up 5 5/8, to 97. And Royal Dutch/Shell closed at
57 5/8, up 2.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was not a good day for Providian Financial, however.
</P>
<P>
   The credit card company slumped 26 1/4, to 89 1/4, after it said
the Connecticut attorney general was investigating the way it
issues cards and bills customers. The investigation is the latest
in a list of legal inquiries that have been piling up for months.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the wholesale gains in technology shares, market breadth
was negative, with more stocks falling in price than rising. And
trading volume was moderate.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange, 802.4 million shares were
traded. On the NASDAQ stock market, 1.29 billion shares changed
hands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
