<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3318 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-WANTED-FOR-MURDER-BOS     11-08 1300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WANTED-FOR-MURDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIZZA RUN ENDS `BLACK WIDOW' MURDER SUSPECT'S FLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ She ran from murder charges for nearly three years,
mastered disguises and aliases, wove a tortured path from Las Vegas
to Mexico to Massachusetts _ and met her undoing at the hands of a
pizza delivery man.
</P>
<P>
   It was a Domino's worker who told police he had recognized
Margaret Rudin _ accused of shooting and beheading her fifth
husband in Las Vegas _ in Revere, just outside Boston, Friday
night. And it was a police officer, disguised in a Domino's uniform
and bearing a pizza box, who knocked on the apartment door shortly
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   When police went in, they found Rudin in the bathroom, wearing a
black wig, the door closed, the lights off. She gave up without a
fight. Police say she seemed almost relieved.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sudden, almost comical end to a murder investigation
that began with her husband's death on Dec. 18, 1994, and ended
with the help of tipsters who saw the twisted story on ``America's
Most Wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudin, 56, arraigned Monday, told her lawyer she plans to fight
extradition to Las Vegas. But police say it's a matter of time
before she faces a jury there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll get her back here,'' said Lt. Wayne Petersen of the Las
Vegas Metropolitan Police homicide squad. ``It'll just take a
little longer.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a long wait already since the day when Ron Rudin, a
Las Vegas real estate developer worth some $10 million, was shot in
his bed, loaded into an antique trunk, decapitated, burned, and
tossed in a remote spot near the Colorado River. Margaret Rudin,
his pretty, petite fifth wife of seven years, filed a missing
person report. Fishermen found her husband's body more than a month
later.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the body was found, friends of the couple had told
police they suspected his wife, Petersen said. But it wasn't until
two years later, he said, after police found physical evidence that
linked Margaret Rudin to the crime, that she was charged.
</P>
<P>
   Before a grand jury could indict her, she disappeared; tipsters
spotted her in Phoenix, Chicago and Guadalajara, Mexico. It was
there, in Mexico, that she met Joseph Lundergan, a retired
Boston-area firefighter.
</P>
<P>
   And it was there that, in stages, she told him the strange tale
he came to believe wholeheartedly: that she was wrongly accused and
fleeing for her life, from an evil Israeli terrorist named Yehuda,
who was ``in cahoots'' with the trustees of her late husband's
estate.
</P>
<P>
   Rudin first identified herself as Marie, said Lundergan, 61, a
youngish-looking man with gray-blond hair and a measured way of
talking. She gave a last name, four or five syllables long, that he
couldn't recall, he said. They lived in the same apartment building
in Guadalajara, where he had moved while he awaited an insurance
settlement for an injured knee.
</P>
<P>
   At first, the pretty younger woman ``was in the background,'' he
said. ``We didn't date or anything. Just, `Hi, how are you.' '' He
busied himself with Mexican women, who he said ``love American
men.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, they started to take meals together, he said. When
he asked her what she was doing in Mexico, ``she didn't give me a
direct answer at first.'' But eventually, a story came out. She
said she was from Las Vegas, that her husband was rich, and that he
had been murdered.
</P>
<P>
   She spoke of a man named Yehuda, dishonorably discharged from
the Israeli army, and a plot she said he had hatched with her
husband's trustees _ a plot that involved killing her to get her
share of the estate.
</P>
<P>
   It was an incredible story, Lundergan said, but in Mexico, he
had grown accustomed to hearing incredible things. And ``by that
time, I knew her and I trusted her,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And kept up with her, even when he returned to Massachusetts for
knee surgery. When he was recovering, he said, she made ``a
friendly call'' to him; he didn't know from where. He invited her
to stay with him, to help him cook and clean.
</P>
<P>
   She arrived in December 1998, this time calling herself Leigh
Brown, Lundergan said. He figured she had taken the new name to
conceal herself from Yehuda, he said. He chalked up her rotating
set of wigs to the same motive: survival.
</P>
<P>
   He said she didn't want to go to the police because she didn't
trust them. And though he said they grew attached, he wouldn't say
whether their relationship turned romantic.
</P>
<P>
   In his low-ceilinged kitchen, lit by a bare lightbulb, Rudin
cooked his food. She also baked for next-door neighbor Donnamarie
Mason, 34, who said she took an instant liking to the ``wicked
nice'' woman who called herself Leigh Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, she thought it was strange that she kept changing her hair
color, and wore dark, tinted glasses, and wouldn't answer the door
if you knocked, Mason said. But she never imagined her friend was a
fugitive.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did folks at the U.S. Post Office down the street, where
Rudin picked up mail from a post office box registered to Leigh
Brown. Window clerk Rudy Colucci said his coworkers used to joke
that she was allergic to the sun, because her hair always covered
her face, and she always wore a handkerchief around her head.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Rudin, who was known in Las Vegas as the ``Black
Widow,'' grew skilled at disguising herself in her protracted run
from justice. Through detective work and tips _ often received from
``America's Most Wanted,'' which aired her story three times _ they
learned that she took on several aliases; she also went by Annette
Boatright, Margaret Mason, Margaret Frost, and Margaret Krafbe. She
sometimes wore brown contact lenses to mask her blue eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Rudin was nearly caught in August 1998, Petersen said, in
Phoenix, where she lived at a YMCA and worked in a hotel gift shop.
Police, responding to a tip following another ``America's Most
Wanted'' airing, picked her up for questioning, he said. But, with
a new fake ID, and an alias police did not know, she was released.
</P>
<P>
   The latest ``America's Most Wanted'' episode aired on Oct. 23,
as part of a ``Bad Girls Special.'' On Friday, Oct. 29, Las Vegas
police contacted the Massachusetts State Police with new leads,
pointing to the Boston area, Lt. Kevin Horton said.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, police spoke to Colucci, who identified Rudin in a
picture. That afternoon and night, Colucci said, police gathered in
the post office to stake out Rudin's apartment house. They got
their breakthrough when the Domino's Pizza delivery man drove up.
</P>
<P>
   After he left the building, police followed him back to the
pizza shop and showed him a picture of Rudin, state police Sgt.
Mark Lynch said. He said he was ``90 percent sure'' he had seen
Rudin inside.
</P>
<P>
   Police wanted to enter the apartment peacefully, Lynch said,
because they feared Lundergan might have a gun. So they borrowed a
Domino's uniform and pizza box and knocked on the door. Lundergan
opened it.
</P>
<P>
   When police rushed in, and knocked him down, ``my first thought
was Yehuda. My heart was going a mile a minute.'' Lundergan said.
</P>
<P>
   State police have interviewed Lundergan, but have not charged
him with anything, Lynch said. Rudin spent the weekend at a State
Police lock-up where, Lynch said, ``she has made many attempts to
be charming.'' She was transferred Monday to Framingham, near state
police headquarters and a women's prison.
</P>
<P>
   At her arraignment, Judge Robert Greco gave her a
court-appointed lawyer and set a pre-trial hearing for Nov. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Lundergan said that he still believes her story, and considers
her incapable of murder. Police in Las Vegas say they believe that
she did not act alone. They also say her husband had changed his
will before his death, leaving her only $500,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
