<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY SEEKING HELP FROM MADISON AVENUE IN POLISHING IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From the time Bill Bradley began planning his
insurgent presidential campaign, he has met quietly for more than
16 months with Madison Avenue advertising executives who are
polishing his sometimes ponderous image by creating television
commercials and slogans.
</P>
<P>
   The advertising team calls itself the Crystal Group _ named
after Bradley's hometown of Crystal City, Mo. _ and its members
said they were preparing a multimillion-dollar television, print,
radio and Web advertising campaign to begin next month. They have
already come up with a possible tagline for Bradley's commercials
that is intended to persuade the public that he can topple Vice
President Al Gore for the Democratic nomination: ``It can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   That Bradley has met for so long with advertising executives
demonstrates the seriousness of his presidential campaign. It is
another example of how the campaign, far from a fly-by-night
operation, has long been painstakingly preparing to take on Gore.
</P>
<P>
   In a touch that seems more corporate than political, the
advertising executives said they were considering an offer from
Spike Lee to appear in the advertising campaign _ but that no
decision had been made. They said there had also been discussions
about featuring Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's outreach to advertising executives with more
experience marketing high-end products like Lotus automobiles and
huge corporations like AT&AMP;T and Colgate-Palmolive, underscores the
degree to which his campaign is seeking help from professionals who
know little about politics but do know how to run slick advertising
campaigns _ a strategy perfected by Ronald Reagan. By contrast,
Gore has turned to an advertising team with deep political
experience.
</P>
<P>
   Mark DiMassimo, the head of a New York advertising agency which
held the initial meeting with Bradley in July of 1998, said the
former senator was an appealing client because he was ``ready to
hear the good news along with the bad'' and immersed himself in
discussions about advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news was he has a reputation for brains and
independence and courage and he's got incredible credentials on the
race issue,'' DiMassimo said in an interview. But, he said, the bad
news was that the advertising team had to quiz Bradley repeatedly
to prod him to open up about why he wanted to be president. Then,
DiMassimo said, ``there was the boring,'' and the fact that Bradley
had two kinds of ideas: ``Smart ideas that will move people and
smart ideas that will make people's eyes glaze over.''
</P>
<P>
   DiMassimo said he and his colleagues had asked Bradley about
many of the questions his critics have raised: ``What do you stand
for? Are you ready to take off the gloves and get into a real
presidential contest? Are you going to be a real executive? Are you
going to make the fast decisions and throw the jabs that you need
to throw to get into this? Are you going to open up a little bit
emotionally? Why is your heart in this? Do you want to be president
so badly to put up with this significant gauntlet that you have to
go through?''
</P>
<P>
   At first, DiMassimo said, Bradley ``wasn't opening up.'' But
after long discussions, which he said people thought were ``like an
encounter group or A.A. meeting,'' he and others were satisfied
Bradley had responses that would play well with the public.
</P>
<P>
   Many details of Bradley's advertising campaign were reported in
the current issue of Adweek magazine. The Bradley campaign has kept
its advertising team so closely held that several of the executives
said they decided as a group not to speak to the press.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better if it comes out of one person's mouth,'' said
Marvin Waldman of the advertising agency, Young &AMP; Rubicam. ``We're
all in agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Declining to confirm details of the advertising plan, the
Bradley campaign's spokesman, Eric Hauser, said, ``We're not
interested in announcing to the world our strategy before we go out
and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if it was improper for a campaign that prides itself on
eschewing handlers and slick packaging to turn to Madison Avenue,
Hauser said: ``That's ridiculous. There's talent in a lot of
places. There are ideas that come from everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bradley campaign appears to have tested its advertising with
New Hampshire voters. Mary Anne Mueller, a homemaker from
Londonderry, N.H., said she was paid to attend a focus group near
her home last week during which she and several other Democratic
women were asked for feedback on several Bradley commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mueller said she was not told who sponsored the gathering,
but that it appeared to be the Bradley campaign. She said she was
shown commercials that were biographical as well as ones that
featured the former senator at town meetings answering questions
about health care and other issues. She said all the advertisements
closed with the ``It can happen'' slogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The town meeting ads were good,'' said Mrs. Mueller, who is
leaning toward supporting Gore. ``The bio ones were a little too
schmaltzy.''
</P>
<P>
   Details of the advertising drive were confirmed by DiMassimo as
well as by participants who spoke on the condition that they not be
identified. DiMassimo said the team of consultants has changed over
several months but includes fewer than a dozen principals. He said
they have no immediate plan to develop advertisements that attack
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And he explained that Bradley has taken part in many of the
meetings to discuss advertisements and often resists pleas to be
more succinct.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very smart guy, but intelligent answers are not the
stuff that great drama is made of,'' DiMassimo said. ``He was very
open. He's looking for help in focusing himself. But he's going to
be himself. He isn't necessarily going for the high drama
performance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
