<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANAGED-CARE COMPANY TO LET DOCTORS HAVE SAY
</P>
<P>
   United Health Group has decided to give decision-making power
over patient care back to physicians, breaking with a longstanding
element of managed care that has infuriated many doctors and
frustrated their patients. The managed-care company, which insures
14.5 million people, including 8.7 million in health maintenance
organizations and other managed-care units, said the new rules were
being applied nationally.
</P>
<P>
   SAFRA CLEARS WAY FOR HSBC DEAL
</P>
<P>
   A prolonged delay in HSBC Holdings' $9.9 billion acquisition of
Republic New York and Safra Republic Holdings ended after Edmond
Safra, who founded both banks, agreed to accept $450 million less
for his stakes. HSBC had delayed completion of the acquisitions
pending the outcome of an investigation by Japanese regulators into
Republic's securities unit. HSBC's internal inquiry has concluded
that its liability for possible damages is manageable enough to
proceed with the deal.
</P>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD EXTENDS REACH ONLINE
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of players in Hollywood, from big studios to
small entrepreneurs, are starting to provide entertainment on the
Web, either by delivering existing movies and television shows or
by creating programs specifically for online viewing.
</P>
<P>
   RESEARCH GROUP TO FOCUS ON WEB
</P>
<P>
   A diverse collection of corporate sponsors, Internet pioneers
and political figures is forming a nonprofit research organization,
the Internet Policy Institute, to assess the effect of the Internet
in areas like the economy, privacy, security, government and
society.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. TRADE ENVOYS HEAD FOR CHINA
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton sent his trade representative and his economic
adviser to Beijing to close a deal that would bring China into the
World Trade Organization and open its markets to American-made
goods.
</P>
<P>
   NASDAQ STAYS IN RECORD TERRITORY
</P>
<P>
   Technology stocks shrugged off the judicial rebuke of Microsoft,
sending the Nasdaq composite index up 41.68 points, or 1.34
percent, to 3,143.97, a seventh consecutive record. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index rose 6.78 points, or five-tenths of a
percent, to 1,377.01. The Dow Jones industrial average managed to
rise 14.37 points, to 10,718.85.
</P>
<P>
   PROVIDIAN SHARES DROP ON INQUIRY
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Providian Financial, the issuer of credit cards to
consumers with tarnished credit, fell after the company said that
the Connecticut attorney general was investigating the way it
issues cards and bills customers. The move adds to legal inquiries
that have dogged the company for months. Shares fell $26.25, to
$89.25.
</P>
<P>
   HOSPITAL FORMS TECHNOLOGY VENTURE
</P>
<P>
   First Consulting Group, a health care consulting firm, plans to
form a venture with New York Presbyterian Hospital to run the
hospital's information-technology and telecommunications
departments.
</P>
<P>
   HONG KONG OFFERING BEATS FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong's government has raised $4.3 billion from an offering
of shares it bought last year. That makes it the largest stock
offering ever on the Hong Kong stock exchange.
</P>
<P>
   EARNINGS RISE 72 PERCENT AT BP AMOCO
</P>
<P>
   BP Amoco announced a 72 percent rise in third-quarter profits
and forecast higher gains next year from its planned $33.6 billion
purchase of ARCO.
</P>
<P>
   REPORT SAYS REGULATORS ARE LAX
</P>
<P>
   A key regulatory agency has been lax in monitoring banks for
possible money laundering abuses, according to a preliminary and
still confidential report by the Treasury Department's inspector
general's office. The report criticizes the office of the
comptroller of the currency for a lack of independence when
examining how well banks comply with federal anti-money laundering
laws.
</P>
</TEXT>
