<HEADER>
A3331 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-STUDENTS-AR     11-08 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-STUDENTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S STUDENTS PLEDGE TO PRESS DEMOCRATIC AGENDA
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ ``Welcome, Gus,'' read a big white banner
the other day, using a nickname for Indonesia's new president. ``We
are the students and we will be your opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Motorists slowed down to avoid the small, lively crowd and
sighed in weariness. More student demonstrations. Hadn't they
already got what they wanted?
</P>
<P>
   Yes and no. As the country has learned over the last two years,
there is no compromising with the students' moral agenda. And there
is no denying their influence. Indonesia would not be where it is
today without the students: free of a dictator, under a government
duly elected by a national assembly and moving forward with
democratic reforms.
</P>
<P>
   It was their relentless rallies that kept alive the struggle
early last year against President Suharto, when he had almost
managed to quash his opposition.
</P>
<P>
   It was their exhausting enthusiasm in the months following
Suharto's resignation in May 1998 _ their often daily protests,
their hair-trigger moral indignation, their deaths at the hands of
the military _ that assured that democratic reforms would not
founder in inertia.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after the election on Oct. 20 of President Abdurrahman
Wahid _ also known as Gus Dur _ the student movement is redefining
itself as his political opposition. They will do what they do best:
keep the heat on.
</P>
<P>
   ``A new president is not a new era,'' said Bachtiar Firdaus, 23,
an engineering student. ``Transition to democracy is a long
journey, so we must watch what the government does. So we declare
that the student movement has changed from a reform movement to an
opposition movement, from an agent of change to a director of
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel S. Lev, a professor of political science at the
University of Washington, said: ``Those students out there have
made a big difference. If you want to talk about democracy, it's
right there on the streets. Those students from the beginning have
been the ones who kept their minds most on national interests.''
</P>
<P>
   Their basic agenda stays the same: the withdrawal of the
military from politics, the supremacy of law, clean government and
an investigation of corruption by Suharto.
</P>
<P>
   Students have been a moral force with potential political
influence throughout Indonesia's history and they have their own
lore and their own notable generations, somewhat like the
graduating classes of military academies.
</P>
<P>
   Firdaus said they were acting now on the basis of lessons
learned in the late 1960s when a student movement that had helped
Suharto come to power allowed itself to be co-opted and
neutralized, only to see him become more and more repressive.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps abashed by their own passivity, members of Indonesia's
middle class have allowed their children to lead them. When the
protests became dangerous, professional groups sometimes supported
them with food and funds. Some professors, publicly cautious, urged
their students to cut class and save the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But few people joined them on the front lines. Indonesia's
protests have been notable for the absence of labor unions,
professionals, clergy and political leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Megawati Sukarnoputri, the figurehead of opposition to Suharto
and his successor, B.J. Habibie, shunned the protests. More than
once, she refused requests to step in when demonstrators were being
killed in her name.
</P>
<P>
   On the day of her inauguration as vice president on Oct. 21,
though, she thanked them. Their noisy protests during the electoral
assembly, and the threat of widespread unrest if she lost, had been
one of her strongest campaign planks.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the tide has turned and the students' democratic agenda
dominates, even the military feels compelled to offer them a bow.
</P>
<P>
   The country's most prominent military figure, Gen. Wiranto, the
former armed forces chief of staff, has called them heroes and
offered condolences for those who had died in clashes with his men.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Welcome, Gus'' demonstration was tiny by the standards
Jakarta has come to know, perhaps 50 people in all. The
demonstrators raised their fists as they read a list of demands:
Public figures must disclose their wealth, unqualified ministers
must be fired; military officers must withdraw from government
positions; the political, economic, social, cultural and
educational systems must be improved.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with eight police officers following lazily in a small
van, the students marched down a familiar protest route near the
house where Suharto lives.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them have spent far more time over the last two years in
political teach-ins than at their studies, and they explain their
role with the confidence of youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the political parties want to be part of the government
and no one wants to be in the opposition,'' said one of the small
group's leaders, Goenawan, 22, an electrical engineering student.
``That is not a good way to be a democratic country. We want to
make a democratic system that will be balanced. The students can do
that. We are a moral and intellectual movement. We have no policy.
We have no ambition to be in government.''
</P>
<P>
   Muhammad Firman, a law student who is a leader of a militant
group called City Forum, said its platform is governed by ``what
most of the people want.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That is pure democracy, am I right?'' he said. ``We don't have
our own interests. We don't bargain.''
</P>
<P>
   But as they have shown, they do have bargaining power.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the government starts to forget what the people want, we
will start the demonstrations, we will go down the street again,''
Firman warned. ``We don't care who is in the government; we don't
care. If you want to do your job and be credible in people's eyes,
just listen to us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
