<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON OUTLINES FOREIGN POLICY OBJECTIVES FOR REST OF HIS TERM 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo _ NYT19 _ is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(sw) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton celebrated the tenth anniversary
of the fall of the Berlin Wall on Monday with a speech outlining
the major challenges he believes Europe faces and a warning that
any hope of bringing stability to the Balkans will require pushing
President Slobodan Milosovic of Yugoslavia from power.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at Georgetown University, his alma mater, Clinton took
the unusual step of praising his two Republican predecessors,
Ronald Reagan and George Bush, and how they handled the last days
of communism in Europe. And with his latest call for America to
resist isolationism, he described in sketchy form his foreign
policy agenda for the remaining 13 months of his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's worth devoting some small fraction of this
nation's great wealth and power to help build a Europe where wars
don't happen,'' he said, ``where our allies can do their share and
we help them do so, to seize this historic opportunity for peace
between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East, to make sure that
nuclear weapons from the former Soviet Union don't fall into the
wrong hands.''
</P>
<P>
   And he ticked off other goals, from debt relief for the poorest
nations to paying off American obligations to the United Nations _
all components of the final budget negotiations Clinton and
Congress haggled over through the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   But his tone was far more muted than after Republicans led the
drive last month to defeat the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, and
both Clinton and his national security adviser, Sandy Berger, have
backed away from their earlier assertions about a rising tide of
Republican isolationism.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he never referred to Republicans at all, only alluding
to isolationist tendencies that ``are disproportionately
represented in the deciding body.'' Nor did he mention Democrats,
who have scuttled several of his global trade initiatives and who
may be a much greater threat to his effort to integrate China into
the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton described the first challenge in Europe today as
``building the right kind of partnership with Russia, a Russia that
is stable, democratic and cooperatively engaged with the West.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton called Milosevic ``the last living relic of the age of
European dictators,'' and said ``there can be no future for him.''
And Clinton said he was prepared to turn to ending the hatreds
between Greece and Turkey, both of which he is scheduled to visit
starting this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   His praise for Reagan was particularly effusive. The former
president ``said so plainly what many people on the other side of
the wall had trouble understanding, that the Soviet empire was evil
and the wall should be torn down.'' Bush was credited with
``managing skillfully the fall of the Soviet empire and the
unification of Germany in setting the stage for a Europe whole and
free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
