<HEADER>
A3334 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-REPUBS-PARDON-NYT &LR;      11-08 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-PARDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT BY HOUSE REPUBLICANS SAYS CLEMENCY FOR PUERTO RICANS WAS
CAMPAIGN MOVE
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Ind., Ill., Conn.)  (nk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A report by House Republicans asserts that
President Clinton's grant of clemency to a group of Puerto Rican
nationalists followed discussions in the White House that such a
move would provide political help to some Democratic members of
Congress and Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the Republicans on the House government Reform
Committee included documents subpoenaed from the White House and
Justice Department in connection with the president's Aug. 11 grant
of clemency to 16 of the prisoners. The prisoners were convicted
more than two decades ago of crimes on behalf of the FALN, a Puerto
Rican nationalist group.
</P>
<P>
   The report's assertion of a political dimension to the
deliberations is partly drawn from a memorandum from Jeffrey L.
Farrow, co-chairman of the president's interagency group on Puerto
Rico. In the memo, Farrow urges that the president or vice
president meet with three Puerto Rican members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The memo, sent on March 6 by e-mail to several colleagues in the
White House, said: ``The VP's Puerto Rican position would be
helped.'' It said the clemency issue was a top priority for Rep.
Luis V. Gutierrez and ``of high constituent importance'' to Reps.
Jose E. Serrano and Nydia M. Velazquez. Gutierrez is from Illinois
and Serrano and Ms. Velazquez are from New York. All three are
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, Maria Echaveste, the deputy chief of staff at the
White House, sent an e-mail message, attaching and approving of
Farrow's ideas, to Charles F.C. Ruff, then the White House counsel,
who oversaw clemency issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck _ Jeff's right about this _ very hot issue,'' Ms.
Echaveste's e-mail message said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Kennedy, a spokesman for the White House, said Monday night
that ``neither the vice president nor his staff were involved in
the decision-making process on this issue.'' Kennedy also said:
``The president's decision was made on the merits. And as his
former counsel, Mr. Ruff, has publicly stated, politics was not
involved.''
</P>
<P>
   The three members of Congress did meet with Ruff and senior
officials in the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican report was prepared by the staff of Rep. Dan
Burton of Indiana, the committee chairman and a vigorous critic of
the Clinton administration. The report was circulated to all
members of the committee on Monday and was made available by
congressional officials.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's clemency offer was widely opposed by law-enforcement
officials, including the U.S. attorneys in Illinois and
Connecticut, where many of the trials took place, and FBI Director
Louis J. Freeh.
</P>
<P>
   The events leading to Clinton's clemency offer have remained
murky because the White House and the Justice Department have
declined to release much information. The Constitution explicitly
gives the president the sole authority to issue pardons, so
administration lawyers have argued that Clinton's discussions with
subordinates over clemency for the Puerto Ricans are privileged and
need not be disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   The documents in the House Republicans' report, along with
documents disclosed last month by the Senate Judiciary Committee,
provide a partial picture of how the issue was debated in the White
House and the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   The documents appear to show that the deliberations over
clemency were a blend of political and humanitarian concerns. Most
of the documents focus on the arguments that the prisoners had
served long enough and that it was time to show mercy.
</P>
<P>
   The documents show that Mayra Martinez-Fernandez, an assistant
to Farrow, had tried to build support for clemency by seeking
letters of approval from prominent people like former President
Jimmy Carter. Carter did, in fact, write supporting clemency.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Martinez-Fernandez's other ideas suggest she did not
play a major role on the issue. She wrote that the White House
should seek support for clemency from Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of New
York. Giuliani has become one of the most vocal critics of the
clemency offer.
</P>
<P>
   The Farrow and Echaveste messages show that there were political
considerations at least among some staff members. There is,
however, no mention of Hillary Rodham Clinton, who has denied that
the clemency offer was designed to help her likely Senate candidacy
in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 16 people who were offered clemency, two refused it and
two others, who were already out of prison, did not respond. Twelve
accepted the offer and were freed, and some have returned to Puerto
Rico.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
