<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3335 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i BC-MEXICO-PRI-HNS &LR;      11-08 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-PRI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRI EMERGES FROM DEMOCRATIC ELECTION WITH A POLISHED IMAGE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DUDLEY ALTHAUS 
and MICHAEL RILEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ In the end, a democratic election proved a
cakewalk for the bosses of Mexico's long-ruling party, which had
gained a reputation through the decades as arrogant and corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Labastida, seen as the candidate of the leaders of the
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, won a landslide victory
in Sunday's four-way primary for the party's presidential
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida's main opponent, who many feared would contest the
results and split the party, accepted defeat Monday and said he
will stay with the PRI.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling party's leadership, disparaged by many as vote-fixing
relics, emerged with a freely elected candidate and a polished
image of electoral righteousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody thought it was going to come out this
well,'' said Francisco Abundis, a pollster for the PRI. ``There's a
clear victor, a big turnout and a humble loser. Does the world get
any better than this?''
</P>
<P>
   Since the party took power in 1929 to quell infighting among the
victors of the Mexican Revolution, the PRI's presidential
candidates were handpicked by Mexico's outgoing president and were
then duly voted into office in stage-managed national elections.
President Ernesto Zedillo announced in March that he was scrapping
that backroom system in favor of an open primary.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 10 million people voted Sunday, far more than PRI
officials had hoped. As many as a fifth of the votes were cast by
people who did not belong to the PRI. And Labastida's image as a
man of the system, and his message of economic and social
moderation, easily won the day.
</P>
<P>
   A former interior minister and career PRI bureaucrat, Labastida
won 272 of 300 electoral districts, according to official party
results. He out-polled his closest rival, former Tabasco state Gov.
Roberto Madrazo, by a 2-to-1 margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The electorate in general prefers a stable course in economic
and social policy,'' said Federico Estevez, a political scientist
with Mexico City's Autonomous Technological Institute of Mexico.
``The PRI politicians have changed, and the rules have changed.
It's the electorate that is conservative.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want radical change,'' Estevez said. ``That's the
dynamics of this primary.''
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo, a longtime PRI politician who tried to run as an
outsider, gained in the polls last summer by attacking the
market-oriented economic policies carried out by PRI national
governments since 1985 and by painting Labastida as the party
elite's candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo's challenge rested on a bet that millions of PRI
rank-and-file members were so angry with their party leadership's
free-market reforms _ which have slashed incomes of the workers and
peasants who are the ruling party's bedrock _ that they would be
ready to revolt.
</P>
<P>
   Similar discontent led Cuauhtemoc Cardenas and other PRI leaders
to defect from the party in 1987, taking millions of voters with
them. Many Mexicans believe Cardenas was cheated of victory in the
1988 presidential elections officially won by Carlos Salinas de
Gortari.
</P>
<P>
   But Madrazo's wager on discontent was a bad one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was not 1988,'' said Estevez, who as late as September
was predicting a Madrazo victory. ``There was no revolt waiting to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Madrazo and the two other primary candidates had complained in
the weeks before the election of unfair campaign practices in favor
of Labastida. Madrazo had made indirect threats that he would leave
the party if Sunday's vote appeared fraudulent.
</P>
<P>
   But Labastida's lopsided win, and the perception that the
election was clean, if not exactly fair, has all but erased the
possibility of a split in the party.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are sweet defeats and bitter victories,'' Madrazo said
in a concession speech early Monday. ``I recognize the tendencies
weren't favorable for me, but you know the process was never
equitable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought against the machine and demonstrated it could be
done,'' he said. ``We're going to continue working within the party
in order to create change.''
</P>
<P>
   His victory gives Labastida a strong mandate within the PRI.
Analysts say that over the next week the PRI's opposing factions
will quickly mend fences to get behind their candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida is considered the front-runner in what will
essentially be a three-man race in the July 2 presidential
elections. Although a handful of splinter parties will field
candidates, Labastida's main opponents are Vicente Fox of the
center-right National Action Party and Cardenas, who leads a
center-left coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Talks aimed at forming an alliance between Fox and Cardenas to
support a single presidential candidate collapsed in September,
guaranteeing the PRI a splintered opposition in next July's general
elections.
</P>
<P>
   The more democratic image provided the PRI by the primary had
driven up the party's standing in opinion polls by 10 percent even
before Sunday's vote. The outcome will further bolster the ruling
party's fortunes, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The party is enjoying the equivalent of a convention bounce,''
said Carlos Elizondo, director of CIDE, a Mexico City think tank.
``It has emerged from the primary in a much stronger position than
when it began.''
</P>
<P>
   Its improved fortunes come at a crucial time for the PRI, which
has faced ever stiffer political opposition since 1983. The party
lost control of the lower house of Congress in 1997's elections.
Opposition parties now govern about a third of Mexico's 31 states
and most of its largest urban centers, including Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   The big loser may well be Fox, a charismatic former Coca-Cola
executive who resigned the governorship of Guanajuato state to run
for the presidency. Labastida polled strongest Sunday in the
northern Mexico states that have traditionally supported Fox's
National Action Party.
</P>
<P>
   Although Fox has fared well in recent polls against Labastida,
some analysts say there's not enough difference between the two
men's economic and social policies to entice voters to throw the
PRI out of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poor Fox,'' Estevez said. ``The truth is there are no burning
issues. There is nothing he can grab on to. It will be very hard to
beat back (Labastida's) lead at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sunday's surest winner may have been Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   Elected in 1994 after the PRI's original presidential candidate
was assassinated, Zedillo oversaw the collapse of the peso in
December of that year, which sparked the worse economic crisis in
modern Mexican history. A Yale-trained economist and bureaucrat,
Zedillo gained points for economic management but was seen by many
analysts as politically inept.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot who doubted him after the 1997 election and
the loss of Congress. But now he's going to be much stronger.``
said Sergio Sarmiento, a newspaper columnist and political analyst.
``Zedillo now will be known as the president who democratized the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
