<HEADLINE>
FROM THE CANDIDATES, SILENCE ON MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also MICROSOFT-MARKETPLACE) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal court's finding last week that Microsoft
is a predatory monopoly that has stifled competition has left this
year's crop of presidential candidates speechless.
</P>
<P>
   In an already overheated campaign season with candidates
commenting on a wide range of issues, the lack of comment on the
landmark case has been striking.
</P>
<P>
   No top Republican or Democratic candidates or their spokesmen
have said anything substantive about the findings of fact released
Friday by Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson, even though the document
has rocked the technology world. Nor have they laid out their views
on the kind of antitrust issues that the Microsoft case and its
yearlong trial have raised.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley told reporters Monday: ``My sense is,
based on what the judge said, we're probably moving toward some
kind of settlement.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Vice President Al Gore said: ``The White House
has a long-standing policy of not commenting on ongoing Justice
Department litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Gov. George W. Bush, R-Texas, said that as long
as the case was in litigation, Bush would have no comment.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Steve Forbes, the Republican businessman, said:
``Technology, the free-enterprise system, is going to make this
lawsuit obsolete.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., could not be reached, although as
chairman of the Senate Commerce Committee, he has suggested that
the federal government was interfering with the free-enterprise
system and stifling innovation by taking Microsoft to court.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a deafening silence,'' said Brett Bader, a Republican
political consultant based in Bellevue, Wash., near Microsoft's
home in Redmond.
</P>
<P>
   Bader, like other analysts, suggested that the candidates did
not want to choose between Microsoft and the rest of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if a presidential candidate wants to make points in the
Northwest, they need to show they are upset over this lawsuit, and
Al Gore should be prepared to defend himself against that next
year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts suggest that Microsoft will try to drag out the
case until the Clinton administration expires in January 2001 and a
new president appoints a new chief of the Justice Department's
antitrust division.
</P>
<P>
   Money from the computer industry is playing an increasingly
important role in political campaigns. Microsoft gave $1.3 million
last year to candidates in both parties and has already donated
$600,000 so far this year. Its chairman, Bill Gates, has met
recently with Bush, Bradley and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   Financial reports show that Bush has received nearly $29,000
from Microsoft employees since January. Bradley got $21,000, McCain
$18,000 and Gore $13,000.
</P>
<P>
   Wade Randlett, a consultant who advises Democrats on technology
issues, and a co-founder of TechNet, a lobbying firm for the
industry, said the candidates' silence was more likely a result of
lack of understanding of the complex issues facing the industry
than any attempt to play both sides of the aisle.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   He said contributions from the non-Microsoft world outweighed
those from Microsoft by about 10-to-1, so there was little for a
candidate to fear from supporting the judge's findings.
</P>
<P>
   In other action Monday, the judge published a schedule for the
remaining proceedings that will carry the trial through the end of
January with a final verdict likely in February.
</P>
<P>
   By Dec. 6, he said, the Justice Department must file conclusions
of law, the legal arguments and precedents behind a ruling;
Microsoft must file by Jan. 17, and each side can file reply
motions through Jan. 31.
</P>
</TEXT>
