<P>
   GERMANY-WALL (Berlin) _ Virtally nobody predicted the fall of
the Berlin Wall _ and apparently nobody planned it. As a result,
two German states with divergent ideologies and cultures found
themselves propelled toward union on the panicky reaction of a
border guard who opened the gate at Berlin's Bornholmerstrasse
crossing without an explicit order to do so. Some of the effects of
that precipitation are still evident today. Most fundamentally, a
united Germany is not quite sure of its identity. By Roger Cohen.
(The story has moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   See also GERMANY-BERLIN.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   SCOTUS-DEATH-PENALTY (Washington) _ The question, as framed for
the Supreme Court by lawyers for death row inmates in Florida and
Nebraska, was whether a decades-long wait for a death sentence to
be carried out is itself so ``cruel and unusual'' as to be
unconstitutional. It was a question the court announced that it
would not answer. The justices turned down appeals by two convicted
murderers, and the action left in place a system under which the
length of time a person spends on death row is free of
constitutional scrutiny. By Linda Greenhouse. (The story has moved
in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo inside.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   WEB-ENTERTAINMENT (Los Angeles) _ Until now, Hollywood has used
the Internet mainly to promote films and television programs,
rather than to transmit them. But a growing number of players, from
big studios to small entrepreneurs, are starting to provide
entertainment on the Web, either by delivering existing movies and
television shows or by creating programs specifically for online
viewing. The efforts could allow for development of new types of
interactive entertainment and could give voice to artists not seen
or heard through traditional media. By Andrew Pollack. (The story
has moved in ``f'' news file.) 2,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ENVIRON (Austin, Texas) _ Early this summer, with political
pressure mounting on him to address his state's abysmal air
pollution problems, Gov. George W. Bush signed a law he regards as
the gold star of his green resume: a program targeting outdated
industrial plants that are among the heaviest polluters in Texas.
For Bush, the program meant confronting the state's oil, gas and
chemical industries that are among his most generous campaign
contributors. Bush now boasts that he is the first Texas governor
``to ever have brought industry together and said, `Get into
compliance.''' But what he actually did was a little different. By
Jonathan Yardley. (The story has moved in ``p'' news file.) 3,200
words.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-BUS-DRIVERS (Denver) _ A national shortage of school bus
drivers, caused by the roaring economy and a rise in the school-age
population, is making students wait up to an hour for a ride,
delaying and canceling field trips and athletic events, and forcing
mechanics, transportation supervisors and even some teachers to get
behind the wheel. By Jodi Wilgoren. (The story has moved in ``a''
news file.) 1,900 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   AFGHAN-REBEL (Khwaja Bahaouddin, Afghanistan) _ The Lion of the
Panjshir is not a big man, especially so for someone thought to be
Afghanistan's greatest guerrilla fighter. This nation, so poor
otherwise, is rich with storied commanders, bearded chieftains
loping through the mountains, stopping only to praise Allah or to
set an ambush. But among them, only the Lion _ Ahmed Shah Massoud _
is left to fight on against the Taliban militia. By Barry Bearak.
(The story has moved in ``i'' news file.) 2,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   reefer: MICROSOFT-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Break-up of Microsoft
Corp. appeared somewhat more plausible Monday, following the
release Friday of a federal judge's ruling that the government had
proved that the company had a monopoly and had used it to stifle
competition. But after a weekend of reflection, investors seemed to
conclude that even a break-up would not be a disaster either for
Microsoft shareholders or for the stock market. By Floyd Norris.
(The column has moved in ``f'' news file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
