A3343 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-STREETER-COX     11-08 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-STREETER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For Streeter, many big returns
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A month ago, the odds of Clemson quarterback Brandon
Streeter playing another college football game were about as long
as the Tigers' prospects of earning a bowl invitation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Streeter, who broke his collarbone during a game against
North Carolina Oct. 2, returned to the lineup last week and helped
lead Clemson to a 58-7 win.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers finally had fully grasped the nuances of the
wide-open attack implemented by coach Tommy Bowden and offensive
coordinator Rich Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very good system, `` Streeter said Monday. ``I wish I
had the opportunity to play in it longer. We move the ball so
quickly and we don't huddle, and we throw a lot of formations at
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Streeter passed for 279 yards and two touchdowns, and tailback
Travis Zachary rushed for a career-high 141 more as Clemson
compiled 558 total yards.
</P>
<P>
   Now, heading into Saturday's game at No. 14-ranked Georgia Tech
(6-2, 4-2) Streeter and the Tigers (5-4, 5-2) are thinking of not
only bagging the one win needed to qualify for postseason play, but
also claiming second place in the ACC standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really didn't envision it 10 or 11 months ago when I took
the job,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor could he have imagined Streeter, a graduate student from
Gettysburg, Pa., would be available as the Tigers, whose 2,267
passing yards are just 33 yards shy of school record, march toward
an improbable turn- around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was rolling out to the right, and a North Carolina
linebacker hit me and another player fell on me,'' Streeter said of
the hit that nearly ended his college career. ``The weight of both
of them landed on top of me where my collarbone broke.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I thought about was that it's my senior season
and that would be my last time playing for Clemson. . . . (But)
when I learned it was a four-to-six week injury, I knew I had to
work and I prayed hard.''
</P>
<P>
   In returning, Streeter sent sophomore Woodrow Dantzler to the
bench. In his second start, against Maryland, Dantzler broke one of
the oldest records in Clemson annals with 435 total yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We work really well together,'' said Streeter, who received a
standing ovation in his final home game Saturday when replaced by
Dantzler. ``We support each other so well. We both really want
what's best for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Clemons writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
