<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTO-CLINTON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON WILL SPEND TWO DAYS IN SEATTLE AT WTO MEETING  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY and MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ President Clinton will come to Seattle for two days
during the upcoming World Trade Organization meeting, delivering a
major policy speech and meeting with citizens concerned about the
human face of global trade, congressional and Clinton
administration sources said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is scheduled to arrive the evening of Nov. 30, the first
day of the conference and the day anti-WTO organizers are vowing to
put thousands of demonstrators into the streets.
</P>
<P>
   The president will face a dual challenge during his visit. The
WTO will use the Seattle meeting to launch a new round of trade
talks, and 11-hour negotiations are under way to bring China into
the 134-member organization.
</P>
<P>
   But the president also needs to bolster the position of his
favored successor, Vice President Al Gore. Gore used a recent
Seattle trade luncheon to argue that labor standards and
environmental protection ``are not second-class issues anymore''
and should be on the table at the WTO meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The president will be renewing a commitment to free trade
articulated during the 1992 campaign, in which Clinton used a
Seattle appearance to say he would fight to remove foreign barriers
to U.S. products but would not yield to trade protectionists in the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years later, the issue of trade remains divisive within
the Democratic Party. Two of the party's core constituencies, labor
and environmentalists, have been angrily critical of the Clinton
administration's handling of trade issues and are organizing
protests during the WTO meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Divisions within the Democratic Party have led to congressional
refusal to grant Clinton fast-track authority for expedited
negotiations of trade agreements with other countries, and Clinton
has called international trade ``the one remaining issue on which
we have not forged a consensus within our party.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't go to the American people and say, we have a whole
vision for the future that will be a unifying vision until we get
over this one last big hump,'' Clinton told the Democratic
Leadership Council last month. ``This is an exciting issue, and it
is a difficult issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore will be back in Seattle next Monday, and his schedule will
include meetings with labor and environmental leaders, but he will
not attend the WTO conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Words are cheap. We want real action to implement core labor
standards into trade agreements,'' Washington State Labor Council
president Rick Bender said after hearing Gore speak on his last
visit.
</P>
<P>
   The AFL-CIO has since endorsed Gore. But many of the vice
president's union and environmentalists supporters are waiting to
see if Clinton will deploy his clout on behalf of their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he should push hard for more openness in the World
Trade Organization. ... There is a lot of legitimate concern that
labor, the environment and human rights don't get the attention
they deserve,'' said former Gov. Mike Lowry, a free trade advocate
who is also close to labor and environmental activists.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Lanham, political director for the Boeing Machinists,
added: ``We're not anti-WTO. ... What we want is to elevate core
labor, environmental and human rights standards. Such core
standards include freedom to organize unions, a prohibition of
forced labor, and a minimum wage for work.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite criticism of U.S. trade policy from the streets of
Seattle to the halls of Congress, strong pro-free trade views have
been voiced by almost all of the Republican and Democratic
presidential candidates who have visited the state.
</P>
<P>
   In recent presidential elections, only two significant
candidates have questioned the wisdom of U.S. Trade policy _ Texas
billionaire Ross Perot and conservative commentator Pat Buchanan.
Perot had the most success with his first presidential bid in 1992,
when he successfully tapped into a vein of economic dissatisfaction
by railing against the North American Free Trade Agreement and
predicting a ``giant sucking sound'' of jobs heading south for
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan, who ran as a Republican in 1996, has switched to a bid
for the Reform Party nomination. He appeared earlier this year at
the Port of Seattle to dramatize the United States' $58 billion
trade deficit with China.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan argued that China was ``not remotely qualified'' to
join the WTO, and decried U.S. trade negotiators as ``too weak and
wimpish'' for not demanding complete access to Chinese markets as a
trade-ff for China's continuing to sell its products here.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Leadership Council, which is the ideologically
centrist wing of the party with which Clinton is closely
associated, has made trade policy its major concern, and is trying
to forge a new relationship between business and labor in support
of trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration contends that union officials are
blaming trade for jobs that are really lost because of technology,
and that the number of jobs created in this country by a booming
economy over the last several years far outweighs the number of
jobs lost for any reason.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the size of Seattle's anti-WTO protests, most experts
believe trade will not play a big role in how voters ultimately
cast their ballots. That is in part because economic issues are low
on voter priority lists in times like this when the economy is
strong, in part because trade issues are complicated, and in part
because all the major candidates espouse similar positions on trade
policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The major candidates out there _ Gore, Bradley, Bush and
McCain _ they're all essentially centrists, supporting a position
on trade that big business supports and that generally even labor
supports except when it impacts them quite narrowly,'' said Douglas
Schuler, a management professor at Rice University who studies
international trade policy and politics.
</P>
<P>
   Because the issue is complicated for Democrats, Gore in
particular has gone out of his way to voice his concern for labor
and environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters expect Gore to be their advocate. ``He doesn't just
have to be the loyal vice president,'' said Bill Arthur, director
of the Sierra Club's Northwest office.
</P>
<P>
   But James Thurber, director of the Center for Congressional and
Presidential Studies at American University in Washington, D.C.,
predicted that the WTO and trade will not be ``hot issues in this
campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   `` Environmentalists and labor are trying to push the
candidates, and this president, to be more moderate, and to take
care with respect to the health and safety of workers and
environmental protections, but it's not a national movement that
catches people,'' Thurber said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the year that Perot had some success with the trade
issue, the national economy was thought to be in recession; this
year's strong economic growth makes trade a less important issue in
politics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
