<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-COKE-VEEP-NYT &LR;      11-08 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-VEEP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIGNATION LEAVES COCA-COLA ALL WHITE, ALL MALE AT THE TOP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (mk) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Coca-Cola shuffled its senior management last month, Carl
Ware, a senior vice president responsible for African business, was
told he would no longer report to M. Douglas Ivester, the chairman
and chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Ware, the highest-ranking black at the company, was
reassigned to Douglas Daft, another senior vice president whose
portfolio before the announcement consisted of Coke's business in
Asia and the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Ware, 56, announced his resignation a week ago, saying he would
leave at the end of next year and that ``this decision reflects
thinking I have been doing for some time.'' He added, ``I've always
made choices based on setting priorities, and my decision to leave
the company is indicative of that.'' He said he would be spending
more time with his wife, his son and his grandchildren. A Coca-Cola
spokesman, Randal Donaldson, characterized the move as a
``retirement 14 months from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Ware's departure will result in an entirely white and entirely
male team in charge of operations at the Atlanta-based company.
People who know Ware, a former Atlanta city council member, say his
resignation followed a long period of frustration over his
treatment at the company, where he has worked for 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   His decision also comes as Coca-Cola is facing a
racial-discrimination lawsuit brought by four black employees in
April. The lawsuit contends that the plaintiffs were denied
promotions, pay raises and other benefits because of their race.
One prominent civil-rights organizer in Atlanta expressed concern
about Ware's departure but did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola has emphatically denied the allegations in the
lawsuit. After it was filed, Ivester named Ware and Jack Stahl,
another senior vice president, who is white, to lead a diversity
council within the company. Donaldson said Ware would continue to
head the diversity council until his retirement takes effect.
</P>
<P>
   With Ware's resignation, the highest-ranking minority employees
at Coca-Cola are three corporate vice presidents out of 23 total.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was not a good relationship over time between him and
Ivester,'' said one person who knows Ware. Ware, who did not return
telephone messages left at his office and who was said to be
traveling Monday, was put in charge of the company's African
business by Roberto Goizueta, the chairman and chief executive who
died in October 1997, and Don Keough, Goizueta's longtime No. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were his mentors,'' the person continued. ``With
Ivester, there were some very strong discussions regarding
performance.''
</P>
<P>
   Ivester praised Ware in the company's statement. ``Carl Ware is
a tremendous asset to me, our Africa business and the Coca-Cola
Co.,'' he said. ``We are fortunate he will remain with us for the
next year to ensure a smooth and successful transition of the
leadership of the group.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Ivester took charge following Goizueta's death, he
presented his own ``Africa Strategy'' to the board of directors.
The strategy called for doubling Coke's sales on the continent by
2002. He also delivered a speech at the World Economic Forum in
Switzerland in which he outlined the company's commitment to
building its business in Africa. ``To be very candid, Africa has
not historically been a real priority for the Coca-Cola Co.,'' he
said. ``But over the past two years, we have come to a very
different perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Ware, the company's volume in Africa, measured in case
sales, remained about 5 percent of the company's worldwide volume.
But its growth was about 7 percent last year. By comparison, the
company's European division reported a 5 percent increase, and the
Middle East and Asian division 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent quarterly filing with regulators shows that
while Coca-Cola's worldwide operating income declined 10 percent in
the first nine months of this year, it declined 19 percent at the
African division. Part of the slide was caused by fluctuating
currencies, meaning case sales were stronger, said Andrew Conway, a
beverage stocks analyst at Morgan Stanley. The company's European
division, which suffered from a recall, fell 18 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In general, growth of the Africa division has been strong,
Conway added, noting that operating income grew from 24 percent of
sales to 36 percent of sales in just three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carl Ware has been a very significant player in advancing
Coke's agenda in Africa,'' Conway said. ``He has been a major part
of the margin expansion and the expansion of Coke's pervasive
distribution on the continent. He's very well known to political
leaders, and has been very successful at establishing relationships
in which Coca-Cola received beneficial tax treatment in exchange
for the building of facilities for use by Africans.''
</P>
<P>
   The management rearrangement seemed an insult to Ware, said the
person who knows him. ``If you know Carl, he's a very, very proud
person,'' he said. ``Daft was his peer. He would perceive that as a
negative.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
