<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPEND-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATION IS A STICKING POINT IN NEGOTIATIONS ON SPENDING BILLS
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress and the White House met late into Monday
night on the long-overdue spending bills, after fighting a verbal
war all day over education programs.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides planned to confront issues in two politically
problematic bills, one financing education, labor and health
programs and the other for the Commerce, Justice and State
departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a big difference of opinion on education,'' said
President Clinton, challenging Congress to pass his $1.4 billion
provision to help hire 100,000 new teachers and reduce class sizes
in public schools.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton calls the plan one of his most important goals. He wants
the money spent entirely on hiring teachers, and he and aides say
he will not compromise. Republicans want instead to give $1.2
billion to states and their school boards to spend as they please
on books, computers and teachers, or other needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about the money,'' said Senate Majority Leader Trent
Lott of Mississippi. ``The big issue is, who controls it?''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., asked, ``Is every school district in
the United States going to be run by the president?''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., the chairman in charge of the
spending bill governing education, health and labor programs, said
he had little desire to deal with a president making ultimatums.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any room for compromise as long as the president
says it's nonnegotiable,'' Specter said. He called the White
House's negotiating stance unconstitutional and said the two sides
were still more than $2 billion apart on the education, health and
labor bill, a figure the White House confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, there were offers and counteroffers between
the White House and the Republican leadership, but no deals were
made on the five unresolved spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can we do it all by Wednesday? In a heartbeat, if we work
together,'' Clinton said. But, instead, the noise level of the
arguments over billions of dollars and crucial paragraphs of
legislative language increased.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said the White House might still have to agree to an
across-the-board spending cut of less than 1 percent to make sure
the Republican-written spending bills do not draw on Social
Security funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have staked their fiscal and political
reputations on meeting that goal. Clinton last week vetoed an
across-the-board cut of .97 percent, denouncing it as ``blind'' and
``mindless.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said Congress ``absolutely, absolutely'' would insist on
the across-the-board cut if necessary. ``We have to look at all the
numbers and see how they add up,'' he said. ``And if there's any
chance that it would dip into the Social Security trust fund, we
should have an across-the-board cut.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And a new potential obstacle loomed. Sen. Robert C. Byrd of West
Virginia, the ranking Democrat on the Appropriations Committee,
wants a new law favoring his state's coal miners added to the
legislative stew before Congress adjourns.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd wants to overturn a federal judge's ruling, handed down
last month, that said the state had violated clean water laws by
letting coal companies clog hundreds of miles of streams with fill
dumped from mountainsides.
</P>
<P>
   To bring that provision to the floor, Byrd threatened to block
the $15.3 billion foreign operations bill passed by the House on
Friday. He lifted that threat Monday night, and his office said he
would declare his intentions on Tuesday. But the rest of the
unresolved spending bills remain potential legislative vehicles for
his effort.
</P>
<P>
   One of those bills, relatively small, contains federal money for
the District of Columbia and is all but finished and ready for the
president's signature. A second, covering the Interior Department,
still has provisions favoring the oil, gas and mining industries
that are objectionable to environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the big dispute over education programs. And the
bill financing the Commerce, Justice and State departments is in
limbo, too.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher H. Smith, R-N.J., wants language in the bill
blocking federal funds from going to any organizations that seeks
to change abortion laws overseas. He has attached that to the
section of the bill that would allow the United States to pay the
$1 billion in dues it owes the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dues issue should be resolved in an appropriate way,''
Lott said. ``The administration needs to come to grips with some
limitations on taxpayer dollars being spent to lobby for abortion
around the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
