A3360 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-LEVI'S-LEVI'S_SFCHRON     11-08 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVI'S-LEVI'S </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Levi's Chief of Marketing Will Resign  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Gordon Shank, Levi Strauss &AMP; Co.'s chief marketing officer and one
of the last members of its old-guard leadership, is leaving the
company after 25 years.
<P>
   In a memo circulated yesterday among Levi's employees, Chairman
Robert Haas said Shank and Philip Marineau, the company's new chief
executive officer, ``have agreed that (Shank's) CMO position is
redundant and unnecessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Marineau, a former PepsiCo executive who was brought aboard in
September, will assume Shank's duties. The CMO position, which was
created for Shank last spring, will be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Shank and Marineau ``believe strongly that the steward of the
company's vision and strategic marketing direction should be the
chief executive officer,'' Haas' memo stated. ``Regretfully, we do
not have any other open positions that match Gord's experience,
stature and interests, so he will be leaving the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Behind the official verbiage, Levi's watchers said that the CMO
job was largely a toothless position and that yesterday's
announcement didn't surprise anyone, including Shank.
</P>
<P>
   As chief marketing officer, Shank had little role in developing
or approving advertising. The company's top ad executives reported
directly to the chiefs of its three global divisions, bypassing
Shank.
</P>
<P>
   Opinions about Shank's prowess are mixed. Although Levi's
advertising generally has been considered strong over the years,
campaigns for the past three years have received a tepid response
from consumers and done little to halt Levi's hemorrhaging sales.
</P>
<P>
   Shank is regarded by some Levi's observers as a key member of a
generation of leaders who joined Levi's in the 1970s and presided
at the top as it headed toward three-straight years of serious
sales shortfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Other senior managers of that era who have left the company in
recent years include Peter Jacobi, Tom Fanoe, George Porter, Thomas
Tusher and Robert Rockey.
</P>
<P>
   Still, other company insiders believe that Shank was a strong
marketer and an important asset to Levi's. ``Gord was the one
person (among top management) who had any strategic vision for the
company,'' said one.
</P>
<P>
   At any rate, Shank's fate was sealed this fall when Levi's
decided to pull the plug on its e-commerce business, Shank's pet
project.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview yesterday, Shank defended his tenure as
CMO. ``My job was to help facilitate, oversee, counsel and guide''
rather than be involved in day-to-day operations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shank acknowledged that the company has ``stumbled'' in its
recent U.S. advertising campaigns as it has been ``trying to find
its way. ... We'd be hard pressed to say anything we're doing is
working tremendously well when the company is at the point where it
is,'' Shank said.
</P>
<P>
   Shank, who joined the company as a salesman in his native Canada
in 1974, will leave the company by the end of the month and take
several months off to ``decompress,'' he said. Then he will look
for a CEO job, something he once believed he might attain at
Levi's.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
