<HEADER>
A3361 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BAPTISTS-EVANGELIZE-A     11-08 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAPTISTS-EVANGELIZE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINDUS AND JEWS PROTEST SOUTHERN BAPTISTS' TACTICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Southern Baptist Convention, the United States' largest
Protestant denomination, has always proclaimed that it had a
mission to reach out to people worldwide to urge them to a belief
in Jesus Christ as the Messiah. But new efforts it has undertaken,
aimed at converting Jews and Hindus, have generated a backlash from
members of those faiths.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, in an unusual display of unity between Orthodox and
non-Orthodox Jewish leaders, the heads of the four major Jewish
theological seminaries, together with officers of an umbrella
organization representing more than 60 Jewish groups, sent a letter
to the Southern Baptist president, the Rev. Paige Patterson, asking
the denomination to stop supporting ``deceptive'' tactics to
convert Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The letter represents an increasing concern among Jewish
organizations over an issue that has set Jews at odds with leaders
of the nation's nearly 16 million Southern Baptists.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, written on the stationery of the umbrella group, the
Jewish Community Relations Council of New York, asserted that the
denomination had endorsed a form of proselytizing in which Jewish
symbols and rituals were ``expropriated for the sake of converting
Jews'' _ a reference to Southern Baptist support for ``messianic
Jewish'' organizations that use prayer shawls and skullcaps in
services that center on the worship of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   The letter coincidentally followed a demonstration on Sunday by
about 100 Hindus outside a Southern Baptist church in Houston. The
demonstrators were protesting a Southern Baptist booklet asking
prayer for the conversion of Hindus, whom it described as ``lost in
the hopeless darkness'' of their faith.
</P>
<P>
   The prayer guide, published to coincide with Divali, the Hindu
festival of lights, was the third such document produced by the
Southern Baptists' International Missions Board in Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, the board published a guide for use during the
Jewish High Holy Days, asking Southern Baptists to pray for Jews'
conversion. A guide asking Southern Baptists to pray for the
conversion of Muslims was published earlier. In an article posted
on its Internet site, the mission board said a fourth guide, on
Buddhism, was planned.
</P>
<P>
   The prayer guide on Jews encourages Southern Baptists to tell
Jewish friends they would not cease being Jewish if they converted
to a belief in Jesus Christ. That position has been rejected by
Jewish leaders, and the signers of the letter to Patterson restated
their objection, saying that ``those who adopt another religion
discard any true connection with their Jewish faith and heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter stated: ``Our quarrel with the Southern Baptist
Convention is not over its right to proselytize. Rather, the Jewish
community is deeply offended that the SBC has formally embraced a
strategy that attempts to deceive Jews into believing that one can
be both a Jew and a Christian.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter was signed by Rabbi Norman Lamm, president of the
Rabbi Isaac Elchanan Theological Seminary at Yeshiva University, an
Orthodox institution; Rabbi Ismar Schorsch, chancellor of the
Jewish Theological Seminary, a Conservative institution; Rabbi
David Teutsch, president of the Reconstructionist Rabbinical
College, and Rabbi Sheldon Zimmerman, president of the Hebrew Union
College-Jewish Institute of Religion, which trains men and women
for the Reform rabbinate.
</P>
<P>
   It was also signed by Gedale Horowitz and Michael Miller,
president and executive vice president, respectively, of the Jewish
Community Relations Council, whose members include such
organizations as the American Jewish Committee, the American Jewish
Congress, B'nai B'rith and others.
</P>
<P>
   Commenting on the relative rarity of collaboration by Jewish
leaders across all denominational lines, Miller said the letter was
prompted by a broad concern that Southern Baptists, as ``a
mainstream faith group,'' were supporting an approach to conversion
that alarms many Jews. It is, he said, ``a communal response to a
significant challenge to the integrity of our faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Lamm said he would give the same advice to Southern Baptists
that he had given to some Jewish groups, to reach out religiously
to their own people before they try to reach others. Of the
Southern Baptists' support for messianic organizations, he said,
``The effort smacks of imperialism, which should have no place in
the world of religious discourse.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter follows a written exchange six weeks ago between
Patterson and Philip Abramowitz, director of the council's task
force on missionaries and cults. Then, Abramowitz wrote to
Patterson, protesting his involvement in a conference on
evangelizing Jews that was held in New York with leaders of
messianic groups that say one can be Jewish and also accept Jesus
as the Messiah.
</P>
<P>
   In reply, Patterson said the accusation that Southern Baptists
had been using deception to win converts was ``false and
reckless,'' and that Southern Baptists believed in ``absolute
religious liberty'' and freedom from coercion.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview from Florida, where he was traveling
Monday, Patterson said he had not yet seen the letter. But he said,
``Show me a single case where a Southern Baptist has acted
deceptively and I will do my best to see it never happens again. We
are not a deceptive people.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, he did not believe that ``Hebrew
Christians,'' another name for messianic Jews, were being deceptive
in their use of Jewish ritual objects together with declarations of
a belief in Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now what would be deceptive is if you're not telling people
where you stand and what you believe,'' Patterson said. ``Just to
hold onto factors in their Jewish background like prayer shawls, as
long as they're out in the open, I'm afraid I don't see that as
deceptive.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Southern Baptists' prayer guide on Hinduism, Dr. Uma
Mysorekar, secretary-treasurer of the Council of Hindu Temples of
North America, said she was ``deeply saddened'' by what she called
a mockery of Hindu prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important point is that Hindus are proud of what they
are and they are also proud of their form of worship,'' said Dr.
Mysorekar, who is also president of the Hindu Temple Society of
North America, a temple in New York. She added that Hindu leaders
were ``willing to have a dialogue'' with Southern Baptist officials
``and to teach them what Hinduism stands for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 2134EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0502 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3362 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MSFINDINGS-MSFINDINGS     11-08 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MSFINDINGS-MSFINDINGS </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 ON TECHNOLOGY/HENRY NORR  &HT;     Microsoft Findings Brilliantly Insightful 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Unless you've kept your head in several feet of sand since Friday,
you know by now that Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson's ``findings of
fact'' in the Department of Justice's antitrust suit against
Microsoft were blunt, biting, even blistering.
<P>
   What you might not realize, unless you've taken the time to slog
through the 207-page document, is that it's also brilliant.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, parts of it are debatable, and not just by Microsoft's
lawyers. But overall, it adds up to a subtle and remarkably
insightful analysis of the software marketplace and Microsoft's
behavior over the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson even learned to sling around industry jargon and
acronyms with the best of them.
</P>
<P>
   The achievement is all the more remarkable when you consider
that the judge apparently knew next to nothing about the computer
business before taking on the case. Undoubtedly, he has some sharp
young law clerks helping him out, and perhaps they deserve much of
the credit; some of the arguments were also supplied to him by the
government's lawyers and witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Jackson who put it all together into a persuasive
narrative. Although the document's title _ ``findings of fact'' _
and its form _ 410 numbered paragraphs _ might suggest nothing more
than a potpourri of judgments about the wide variety of factual
questions raised in the trial, it's actually a coherent
interpretive essay.
</P>
<P>
   From start to finish, the document's central organizing
principle is what Jackson first calls the ``chicken-and-egg
problem,'' before switching to a more decorous term for the same
idea: the ``applications barrier to entry.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's how Jackson explains what he means (on Page 14 of the
document):
</P>
<P>
   ``The overwhelming majority of consumers will only use a PC
operating system for which there already exists a large and varied
set of high-quality, full-featured applications and for which it
seems relatively certain that new types of applications and new
versions of existing applications will continue to be marketed at a
pace with those written for other operating systems.''
</P>
<P>
   The other side of that coin, from the perspective of software
developers: ``Software developers generally write applications
first, and often exclusively, for the operating system that is
already used by a dominant share of all PC users.''
</P>
<P>
   Those ideas are by no means original _ in fact, they sound like
hollow truisms. But in Jackson's hands, they're the threads that
tie together what otherwise might look like unrelated episodes.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, in analyzing Microsoft's responses to a long list
of industry innovations _ above the Netscape Navigator browser and
Sun Microsystems' Java development technology, but also including
initiatives from IBM, Apple, Real Networks and even Intel,
Microsoft's partner in the ``Wintel'' axis _ Jackson looks behind
Microsoft's belligerent bullying and finds a systematic campaign to
protect that ``applications barrier to entry.''
</P>
<P>
   Using Microsoft execs' own e-mail messages, among other
evidence, the judge shows that Chairman Bill Gates and his
colleagues saw each of the disputed technologies as a threat, of
one degree or another, because each raised the prospect that
developers would step up production of applications not tied
specifically to Windows.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of the long document, like the majority of the
witnesses at the trial, addresses the Netscape case. It's no secret
that Microsoft, from the moment it learned that Netscape was
developing a Web browser for Windows 95, made every effort to
squash the product.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson details that effort in excruciating detail, showing how
Microsoft threatened to deny even its No.1 customer, Compaq, access
to Windows if it didn't stop distributing Navigator; how the
company threatened to cancel Microsoft Office for the Macintosh
simply because Apple, while distributing both browsers, was giving
top billing to Navigator; and how Microsoft coerced 14 of the 15
top Internet access providers in North America to make Internet
Explorer their standard, even when it meant compensating them for
breaking contracts with Netscape.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson doesn't quote the Microsoft executive who allegedly
threatened that his company would ``cut off (Netscape's) air
supply,'' but the facts he cites are more damaging than any
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   What made Netscape such a threat was not that it was a popular
application, but that it threatened to become what the industry
calls a ``platform'' _ an environment in which other developers can
create a variety of applications. Since Netscape was writing
versions of Navigator for the Mac, Unix and other computer systems,
and integrating them all with Sun's platform-agnostic Java
environment, continuing success for Netscape could have created a
compelling alternative to Windows in the eyes of software
developers.
</P>
<P>
   That's why Gates et al were so determined to stop it. To a very
large degree, they succeeded. But now that Judge  &LR; Jackson has so
perceptively exposed their game plan, their response may yet come
back to haunt them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
