<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-MICROSOFT </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Microsoft to Reboot MSN Site, Capitulate in AOL Struggle  &HT;     By Tom Stein 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
In an effort to finally capture the hearts and wallets of Web
surfers, Microsoft Corp. will relaunch its MSN.com portal site
today.
<P>
   The redesign of the MSN site, which trails in popularity behind
Yahoo and America Online, also carries broader implications in
terms of Microsoft's continuing instant-messaging struggle with
America Online and Friday's antitrust finding against the software
titan.
</P>
<P>
   MSN.com attracts 28.2 million visitors a month, compared with
32.1 million visitors for Yahoo, which is the most frequented site
on the Net, and 28.4 million for second-place AOL, according to
Internet research firm Media Metrix. But these numbers do not tell
the full story. MSN.com is the default home page for the Internet
Explorer Web browser, so many people automatically go to the site
whether they want to or not.
</P>
<P>
   MSN.com has gone through many iterations since it first went
online in the mid-90s, but Microsoft executives say they finally
have created a site that will appeal to consumers. It will include
the standard news, weather and entertainment content, as well as
e-commerce links and such new features as MSN Web Communities, an
area for affinity groups.
</P>
<P>
   For example, with MSN Web Communities, a local soccer club can
create its own Web page _ complete with a schedule of game times,
photo album and message boards _ to stay in constant communication.
</P>
<P>
   The site also features a new version of MSN Messenger Service,
Microsoft's instant-chat software that alerts Web surfers when
their friends are online and then allows them to communicate by
typing and sending text messages in real time.
</P>
<P>
   The first version of MSN Messenger also allowed users to chat
with friends using AOL's competing software. But Microsoft is, at
least for now, admitting defeat and ending its interoperability
tussle with AOL, which reigns supreme in instant messaging, with
about 65 million users.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft did not even have a messaging product until July but
now says it has 4 million users.
</P>
<P>
   AOL was outraged when Microsoft first introduced its product.
AOL argued that Microsoft was gaining unauthorized access to its
subscriber lists and consequently blocked MSN Messenger customers
from communicating with its user base. Microsoft, for its part,
kept looking for new ways to worm its way into AOL's messaging
service. But now the company has backed down completely.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no interoperability for now,'' said Deanna
Sanford, lead project for MSN. ``We are still exploring our best
alternatives.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe that the ``best alternative'' rests in the
hands of the Internet Engineering Task Force, an independent body
that is trying to create a common standard that would allow all
instant-messaging products to interoperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're still months away from any kind of standard,'' said Rob
Enderle, an Internet analyst with Giga Information Group.
``Microsoft realized its cat-and-mouse game with AOL was
aggravating users and wasn't doing good for anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts believe Microsoft has other problems with MSN.com _
namely, that it comes off as a cold, corporate Web site that holds
limited appeal to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unlike Yahoo or AOL, MSN.com is not a friendly destination
where people go to hang out,'' said Barry Parr, an analyst with
International Data Corp. ``Microsoft is great in the corporate
market, but they have never been really good at marketing products
and services to consumers.''
</P>
<P>
   At least on the Internet, Microsoft is far from a monopoly. But
Friday's antitrust ruling could have a significant impact on MSN.
For one thing, analysts say, it will be a lot harder for Microsoft
to make an acquisition that would allow it to compete on equal
footing with the likes of Yahoo or AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Also, if Microsoft ultimately is forced to remove its Internet
Explorer Web browser from its Windows operating system, the MSN
site would suffer because, as the default home page for Internet
Explorer, it likely would attract fewer visitors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
