<SLUG> BC-PROVIDIAN-PROVIDIAN </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 Providian Drops 23% on News of Another Probe  &HT;     By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
The Connecticut attorney general's office said yesterday that it is
investigating business practices of Providian Financial, opening
another front in the credit card giant's legal troubles and
prompting panicky investors to dump the company's stock.
<P>
   Shares of Providian, the nation's sixth-largest Visa and
MasterCard issuer, plummeted $26.25 to close at $89.25 after the
company disclosed the probe. The stock's 23 percent plunge wiped
out nearly $4 billion in market value.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal said yesterday
that his office was investigating Providian's credit card practices
in response to consumer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general issued a statement noting that ``complaints
against Providian include failure to credit payments in a timely
manner to customer accounts, charges for unauthorized services and
inadequate disclosure of interest rates and fees.''
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Providian specializes in issuing credit cards to
customers who previously have had problems paying debts.
</P>
<P>
   Providian spokesman Konrad Alt said the Connecticut attorney
general's office on Friday sent a formal demand for answers to 15
questions about the company's business practices. ``We will respond
appropriately and cooperatively,'' Alt said.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Blumenthal met with Providian general counsel Ellen
Richey, who promised to cooperate with the attorney general,
according to both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut investigation is the latest of several official
probes into charges that San Francisco's Providian sold customers
products they hadn't requested, failed to disclose terms adequately
and added improper fees to customer bills.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Providian said it was holding talks to settle a San
Francisco district attorney's office investigation of alleged
unfair-business practices. In August, Providian said the Office of
the Comptroller of the Currency, the federal agency that regulates
nationally chartered banks, was examining the company's consumer
practices.
</P>
<P>
   The company also faces a series of private lawsuits seeking
class-action status in state and federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   Providian has not admitted any wrongdoing but has changed some
of its business practices. For example, after customers complained
they were hit with late fees even though they paid on time, the
company began offering a three-day grace period for payments before
imposing charges.
</P>
<P>
   The free-fall in Providian's stock erased sharp gains posted
during the past two weeks. Until yesterday, strong profit reports
plus news of settlement talks with the San Francisco district
attorney's office had convinced many investors that the company's
legal problems were under control.
</P>
<P>
   Now ``investors are totally exasperated,'' said Mark Alpert, an
analyst with the investment bank Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown. ``Even
if they settle with the D.A., does it mean they also have to settle
with Connecticut or whoever else comes up?''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Providian's stock also was hurt by a disclosure
that chief executive Shailesh Mehta had sold nearly 113,000 shares
of the company's stock for about $12.5 million last week before the
Connecticut probe was made public.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the sale ``could not have been worse,'' CIBC World
Markets analyst Steven Eisman wrote in a note to investors
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The sale ``was made for personal financial reasons and was
planned well in advance,'' Providian's Alt said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
