A3368 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG_SFC     11-08 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-MONEYBAG </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 MONEYBAG/ARTHUR M. LOUIS  &HT;     For Indexes, Trusts Beat Funds 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Q: My husband and I are conservative investors, so we are willing
to put our money into investments that track the stock-market
averages, rather than trying to beat the market. We are considering
investments that track the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500, the Dow Jones
industrials and the Nasdaq 100. We wonder if you could discuss the
pros and cons of investing in index mutual funds versus investing
in the index trusts traded on the American Stock Exchange.
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A: OK.
</P>
<P>
   But first you should understand that investing in the stock
market _ whether through individual stocks, index funds or index
trusts _ is not what most people consider conservative. In
particular, an investment in the red-hot, highly volatile Nasdaq
100 is anything but conservative, even though it has been a great
performer over the long run.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative investors usually put a significant amount of money
into U.S. Treasuries to provide safe income and low volatility when
the stock market gets caught in its occasional downdrafts.
</P>
<P>
   As for index funds versus index trusts, the trusts seem to have
the edge.
</P>
<P>
   For short-term traders, they offer greater flexibility than
mutual funds because they trade as stocks. You can move in and out
during the day and sell them short _ neither of which you can do
with funds.
</P>
<P>
   For long-term traders, the chief advantage is that the trusts
charge rock-bottom management fees _ generally less than 0.2
percent of assets per year. Some index mutual funds also charge
very little, but others charge as much as 1 percent and more. Over
the long run, that can chip away a substantial portion of your
investment.
</P>
<P>
   The principal index trusts are the S&AMP;P 500 Depositary Receipt
(ticker symbol: SPY); the Diamonds Trust (DIA), which tracks the
Dow; and the Nasdaq-100 Shares Trust (QQQ). You can buy or sell
them at the prevailing price any time during trading hours through
any stockbroker.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Capital Gain
</P>
<P>
   Q: I own shares in a tax-free mutual fund, which invests in
municipal bonds. I have the fund managers automatically reinvest my
tax-exempt dividends in more shares. However, that seems to pose a
complication: If I were to sell some shares at a profit, how would
I calculate my capital gain for tax purposes, considering that part
of the gain is generated by tax-free dividends?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: The calculation is fairly simple, says Internal Revenue Service
spokesman Jesse Weller. Whatever amount of tax-free income you
invest in new shares is added to your cost basis on the shares you
own.
</P>
<P>
   For example, suppose you own $10,000 worth of a tax-free fund's
shares, of which $2,000 is a capital gain and $8,000 is your cost
basis. You then invest $500 of tax-free dividends in more shares.
Now you have $10,500 worth of shares, but your cost basis moves up
to $8,500, so the capital gain remains unchanged. Which is another
way of saying that your dividends will remain untaxed.
</P>
<P>
   If your new, $500 investment grows in value, however, the
increase will be considered part of your capital-gains liability
and will be taxed when you sell your shares.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Work Expenses
</P>
<P>
   Q: For about three months during 1996, I worked in New Mexico at
the request of my employer. The employer paid me my usual salary,
but I had to pay my own expenses, totaling $3,000, for travel, a
temporary apartment, etc. Were these expenses tax-deductible, and
if so, can I still take advantage of this? I didn't claim them at
the time. Also, would it make a difference if my wife and I filed
an amended return separately, rather than the joint return we filed
originally?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A: It's not too late to act, because your 1996 return was due in
April 1997, and you have three years beyond that to file an amended
return and claim a refund. So get it done by next April.
</P>
<P>
   Whether you could do better by filing separately rather than
jointly is irrelevant at this point, says IRS spokesman Weller,
because you have to stick with the joint return once you've passed
the original (April 1997) due date.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing you'll want to do is determine whether your
itemized deductions, including those you are adding, exceed the
standard deduction for the 1996 tax year. That figure was $6,700
for married couples filing a joint return. If you can't top that by
itemizing, then there is no point in filing an amended return.
</P>
<P>
   To file an amended return, you will need Form 1040X, and you
also must file Form 2106, detailing your travel expenses. The
overall job-related deduction can be claimed on Schedule A, under
the heading `'Job Expenses and Most Other Miscellaneous
Deductions.'' Bear in mind that deductions claimed in this section
of the form can be used only to the extent that they exceed 2
percent of your adjusted gross income.
</P>
<P>
   You can claim your expenses for travel to and from New Mexico,
your commuting expenses while there, your rental costs, cleaning
bills, telephone bills, tips and up to half the actual cost of your
meals. If you don't have meal receipts, you can deduct up to half
the maximum IRS-mandated meal allowance, which ranged from $26 to
$38 per day in New Mexico in 1996, depending on the town.
</P>
<P>
   For a full discussion of allowable deductions, get IRS
Publication 463, entitled ``Travel, Entertainment, Gift and Car
Expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   You can download tax forms and publications from the Internet at
www.irs.gov, or you can order copies by calling (800) 829-3676.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Send questions about how to manage your money to
moneybag &LR; sfgate.com, or to Arthur M. Louis, Moneybag column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
