r f BC-ATM-ATM_SFCHRON &LR;      11-08 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATM-ATM </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO ELUDE PESKY ATM FEES  &HT;     BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
 _ SF CHRON   &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
San Francisco's just-approved ballot measure to ban ATM surcharges
caused the fur to fly in the city.
<P>
   Consumer groups blasted banks for gouging customers. Bankers
accused fee critics of inflaming public passions against reasonable
charges for convenient ATM access.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as they were at each other's throats, the two sides
agreed on one point _ there are plenty of steps consumers can take
to avoid ATM fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do have alternatives,'' said Greg Wilhelm, an official
of the California Bankers Association.
</P>
<P>
   That's important because San Francisco's surcharge ban, as well
as a similar measure recently approved by the Santa Monica City
Council, might not stand up in court. Big banks and the CBA are
suing in federal court to overturn San Francisco's law before it
takes effect.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, there now are no bans on ATM surcharges in
California outside San Francisco and Santa Monica.
</P>
<P>
   So, what are fee-hating consumers to do when they need cash
fast?
</P>
<P>
   First, it's important to know that ATM fees come in two
varieties. One is the fee that your own bank, thrift or credit
union charges when you use a cash machine belonging to another
institution. In California, that fee typically is $2.
</P>
<P>
   The second fee is the ATM surcharge, the fee that the outside
bank charges noncustomers who use their machines, typically $1.50
in the state. Only that second surcharge is banned under the San
Francisco and Santa Monica laws.
</P>
<P>
   Add the two fees together and you come up with a combined charge
of $3.50 for withdrawing money from a cash machine not owned by
your own financial institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate the fees,'' said Aileen Agricola, a South San Francisco
resident who works as program director at a nonprofit Web site in
the city. ``If it's necessary, I'll go out of my way to avoid
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Eluding the first fee, the one banks charge their own customers
for using somebody else's ATMs, is easy. Keep your money at an
institution that doesn't impose that fee.
</P>
<P>
   Many small banks and credit unions don't charge for using an
outside cash machine, sacrificing the revenue in order to compete
with big banks that have vast ATM networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The suburban banks that have a lot of customers who are
commuters feel they have to'' offer free access to outside ATMs,
said CBA spokesman John Stafford.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding the second fee, the one the ATM owner slaps on
noncustomers, is a little harder. The basic rule is simple: Use
ATMs belonging to your own financial institution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get an account at a bank that has ATMs that are convenient to
you,'' said David Sorkin, a law professor at the John Marshall Law
School in Chicago who operates an Internet site on ATM fees,
www.atmsurchages.com.
</P>
<P>
   Still it isn't always easy to find your own bank's ATMs. Here
are some tips for dodging that annoying ding at the cash machine.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Consider doing business with a big bank. Bank of America has 4,133
ATMs in California and about 14,000 in the West and Southeast.
Wells Fargo has 2,876 machines in the state and 6,500 throughout
the West and Midwest. Those far-flung networks usually make their
ATMs easy to find, especially in California.
</P>
<P>
   If one of the big banks has cash machines near where you live
and work, keeping your money with them might be the best way to
avoid ATM fees.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this advice contradicts the previous recommendation
to use an institution that doesn't levy a fee for using outside
ATMs. Both Bank of America and Wells Fargo sock account holders
with $2 charges for using another institution's cash machines. So
only bank with them if you have the discipline to stick with their
ATMs most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Find a bank that will rebate surcharges. Many banks don't charge
for using outside cash machines. Some go further, actually
refunding the second fee, the surcharge levied by the ATM owners.
</P>
<P>
   Most banks operating exclusively on the Internet, such as
Telebank, refund ATM surcharges because, as Web-based institutions,
they don't have cash machines. Some suburban banks do the same.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, for example, Richmond's Mechanics Bank, with
extensive operations in the East Bay, rebates $6 to $9 per month in
outside ATM surcharges, depending on account type, to customers who
meet minimum balance requirements. Bank of Fremont, with branches
from Danville to Carmel, rebates up to five surcharges per
statement period, regardless of amount.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Look for ATMs that don't impose surcharges. Nationwide, about 4
out of 5 banks impose surcharges, but that still leaves plenty of
cash machines that don't sock consumers. In the Bay Area, most
credit unions and many small banks let noncustomers use their ATMs
for free.
</P>
<P>
   Find ATMs with ``No Surcharge'' logos at locations convenient to
you and use them regularly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Consider alternatives to ATMs when you need cash. It wasn't so
long ago when people cashed checks at the supermarket when they
needed money. You still can do that for no cost at many stores.
</P>
<P>
   These days, though, there may be another tool in your wallet or
purse. If your ATM card has a Visa or MasterCard logo on it, it's
also a debit card that you can use to buy products and services,
subtracting the cost directly from your checking account. At
thousands of stores, you can debit more than the cost of the item
you're buying and get the difference in cash.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers can take their ATM card and get cash back at no
cost, right at the point of sale,'' said CBA's Wilhelm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Cash checks when traveling. It can be especially hard to find a
free ATM when you're on the road. Take your checkbook. Your hotel
or airline probably will cash checks for free.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Avoid ATMs that don't belong to financial institutions. Cash
machines that don't belong to banks, thrifts or credit unions _ the
kinds often found in gas stations, convenience stores, supermarkets
and casinos _ frequently are rip-offs charging as much as $5 or $6
to withdraw cash. Steer clear of high-priced ATMs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
_Withdraw large sums. OK, you're a hopeless ATM junkie. You don't
plan ahead. When you're wallet is empty, you just go to the nearest
machine and rack up the fees.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, who asked to remain nameless, confessed to paying $30
to $40 in ATM fees every month. Guess what. She often took out only
$20.
</P>
<P>
   If you are hooked, withdraw more money every time you hit the
cash machine. If you take out $80 instead of $40, you'll cut the
fees you pay in half.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 2139EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
