<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3373 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CARTIER-HEIST-COX     11-08 0324
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARTIER-HEIST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Postal worker accused of theft
 &HT;    By Thomas R. Collins
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT PIERCE, Fla. _ Luxury combined with technology to nab a
Stuart, Fla., postal worker accused of stealing mail when an
electronic transmitter in a Cartier watch led inspectors to the
getaway car.
</P>
<P>
   John Bruce Cooper of Stuart was charged Friday with embezzlement
of a first-class parcel, according to a criminal complaint filed
Monday in federal court in Fort Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   Suspecting that Cooper had been stealing mail at the main post
office in Stuart, a U.S. postal inspector mailed a Cartier watch
containing ``an electronic beacon transmitter which enables
inspectors to track the parcel,'' the complaint says.
</P>
<P>
   At 10:30 a.m. Friday, the regular mail carrier marked the parcel
``no such number'' and left it for further processing.
</P>
<P>
   About an hour later, Cooper allegedly took it to a part of the
post office where workers handle mail that can't be delivered
because of incorrect, illegible, or insufficient addresses, the
complaint says.
</P>
<P>
   At about noon, Cooper waited for a co-worker to leave, then put
the parcel under his desk.
</P>
<P>
   At 12:30 p.m., he got his lunch and ``proceeded to end his tour
of duty,'' leaving the post office in his Toyota Camry station
wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their bug, inspectors knew he had the watch with him
and stopped him near U.S. 1, according to the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The identifiable first-class parcel was discovered rifled and
in plain view on the front passenger seat next to Cooper's lunch
bucket,'' it says.
</P>
<P>
   Postal authorities also found two credit cards not in Cooper's
name in his lunch bucket.
</P>
<P>
   Postal officials were unavailable for comment Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas R. Collins writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla. E-mail: thomascollins(at)pbpost.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
