</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-INVEST-605&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALE OF SHARES GREATLY EXCEEDS HONG KONG'S GOAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ In another boost to this economically resurgent
city, Hong Kong's government has raised far more money than
expected from an offering of shares it bought last year in a costly
market intervention.
</P>
<P>
   The offering, called the Tracker Fund of Hong Kong, raised $4.3
billion Monday, more than triple the government's target price of
$1.3 billion. That makes it the largest stock offering in the
history of the Hong Kong stock exchange _ ahead even of the China
Telecom offering in October 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the offering confounded analysts here, who
predicted that investors would shun a fund that tracks the
performance of Hong Kong's benchmark Hang Seng index. While some of
the success was attributed to the pricing of the fund, it was also
a powerful vote of confidence in the local economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The short answer is: I'm surprised by the level of
enthusiasm,'' said Adrian Faure, a strategist at Merrill Lynch in
Hong Kong. ``They've clearly done a great deal better than they
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   The fund was priced at a 5.25 percent discount to the trading
price of the Hang Seng index. Investors will also receive bonus
shares for holding the shares more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   The offering comes at a time when Hong Kong, after two years of
economic anguish, is on something of a roll. Last week, Walt Disney
Co. announced that it would build its third overseas theme park
here. And the offering follows a successful $2 billion secondary
stock offering by China Telecom.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they had launched this last summer, when things looked bad
in Asia, there would not have been much interest,'' said Marc
Faber, the head of his own investment firm here and another
surprised skeptic. ``But now everyone thinks the bad news is over,
and there are only good times ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tracker Fund is an outgrowth of one of the darkest episodes
of the Asian financial crisis: Hong Kong's decision to buy $15
billion worth of shares to foil currency traders whom it accused of
trying to undermine the stock and currency markets during the
financial turmoil in August 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The government declared victory in that battle, but was left
holding a huge portfolio of stock in companies like HSBC Holdings
and China Telecom. While the value of the shares rose along with
Asia's rebounding markets, analysts feared that the government
would not be able to sell the stock at a decent price.
</P>
<P>
   Hong Kong officials considered their options for months before
deciding to package the shares in a fund that would track the Hang
Seng index. The offering priced Monday is only the government's
first batch of shares. The total value of Hong Kong's portfolio is
roughly $22 billion, which analysts expect the government to
whittle away over the next decade through stock offerings.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to these shares, the Chinese government hopes to
issue stock in several of its largest state-owned companies,
including China National Petroleum, China Petrochemical and the
Bank of China. Analysts calculate that those offerings will have a
total value of more than $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of all those shares flooding the market has
dampened some analysts' enthusiasm. They say Hong Kong's stock
market will not be able to soak up the surfeit of equity without
depressing the price of existing stocks.
</P>
<P>
   For people here, however, the security of investing in Hong Kong
seemed to outweigh concerns about a glut of shares. Residents
flocked to local banks for applications. Bill Choy, who runs a
garment-trading business, said, ``I don't trust fund managers, but
it's the government, so I have more confidence in it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bankers said people were attracted by the discount, the savvy
marketing of the fund and perhaps the changing outlook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong has a reputation for short-term traders,'' said Jim
Sheridan, the head of equities at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., which
co-managed the offering with ING Barings and Jardine Fleming. ``But
this came at a time when Hong Kong investors are questioning what
was their primary investment vehicle _ land.''
</P>
<P>
   When institutional investors saw that the fund was a hit, they
bought heavily as well. But overseas hedge funds, which the
government accused of manipulating the market during last year's
turmoil, were allocated relatively few shares in the fund,
according to an executive familiar with the process.
</P>
<P>
   Faber noted that the fund was still overly vulnerable to
property developers, which have performed poorly. But as China's
state companies issue shares, several are likely to be added to the
Hang Seng index. That will change the complexion of Hong Kong's
market, making it less sensitive to the property market and more
reliant on corporate reforms in China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
