   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Monday, 11/08/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) NEW YORK -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- OBIT-MARTIN, 11-08 --
Richard Martin in 1996. Martin, who infused the Costume Institute
of the Metropolitan Museum of Art with his deep knowledge of
popular culture and art history, died Monday at his apartment in
New York. He was 52. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- CLINTON-ONLINE-2, 11-08 --
President Clinton, right, gets his microphone attached while
Democratic Leadership Counsel President Al From adjusts his
earpiece before the start of a ``virtual town hall'' meeting on the
Internet on Monday at George Washington University. Clinton said
the event was the Internet's answer to Franklin D. Roosevelt's
radio chats. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- CLINTON-ONLINE, 11-08 --
President Clinton looks at his computer screen during a ``virtual
town hall meeting'' on Monday at George Washington University.
Clinton said the event was the Internet's answer to Franklin D.
Roosevelt's radio chats. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) NEW YORK -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- RUN-NY-MARATHON, 11-08 --
New York City Marathon winners, Joseph Chebet, from Kenya,
foreground, and Adriana Fernandez, of Mexico, during a news
conference on Monday. One day after their victories, Chebet and
Fernandez were awakened at dawn to make the rounds of New York.
(Librado Romero/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- CAMERINO-HANDBAG-FASHION-2,
11-08 --A buckle-strap bag, now on display at the Fashion Institute
of Technology, in the colorful, logoed velvet for which Roberta di
Camerino is famous. Off the radar of the status-conscious for
decades, Camerino bags resurfaced in 1996 at Barneys New York.
(Barbara Alper/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- CAMERINO-HANDBAG-FASHION-1,
11-08 --Two of the purses currently available from Roberta di
Camerino, which began producing its status-symbol bags again in
1996. Camerino bags are also on display at the museum of the
Fashion Institute of Technology through Dec. 31. (Barbara Alper/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) UNDATED -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- BALENCIAGA-FASHION-2, 11-08
-- From left, a V-front blouse and slim skirt for fall echoes
Balenciaga shapes by Nicolas Ghesquiere; a distressed leather top
for next spring; a crinkle-pleated skirt under a black dress with
leather sleeves evoking Balenciaga's obsession with sleeves. (Dan
Lecca/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) NEW YORK -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- BALENCIAGA-FASHION-1, 11-08
-- Nicolas Ghesquiere, the designer who has revived the Balenciaga
name. ``I came to Balenciaga from what many people would say is the
worst position in fashion,'' says Ghesquiere, 28. And yet, in just
the past two seasons, he has emerged as a kind of cult designer, a
favorite with stylists like George Cortina, who does John
Bartlett's shows, as well as the actress Chloe Sevigny. (Tony
Cenicola/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) PARIS -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- PARIS-DOGS, 11-08 -- Dog owners
pause in front of a poster from a campaign urging Parisians to
clean up after their dogs. Tourists here are revolted at what they
find underfoot as they gaze overhead: An average of 650 people a
year break bones or are hospitalized after slipping on dog poop.
(Michel Setboun/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) TRENTON, N.J. -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- SCOTUS-DEATH-PENALTY,
11-08 -- An incomplete chess game inside the caged recreation area
of death row in the New Jersey State Prison in September. The
Supreme Court, split over the issue, decided on Monday not to take
a case that raised the question of whether a very long delay
between a sentence of death and execution is itself cruel and
unusual punishment. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) MONTE DOURADO, Brazil -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- BRAZIL-JUNGLE,
11-08 --Passengers on small boats near the Jari Celulose, S.A.
station in the Amazon. Like the China market, the notion that there
are unlimited riches to be had from the Amazon is one of those
myths that never seems to die. Since the first Spanish colonizers
in the New World fell under the spell of the legend of El Dorado,
adventurers have arrived with the conviction they can build empires
in places such as this, only to run afoul of one of the most
hostile natural and business environments on the planet. (Larry
Rohter/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) NEW YORK -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- AIRCRASH-SCHILIRO, 11-08 --
Lewis Schiliro, assistant director of the F.B.I. in charge of the
New York office, stands in front of portraits of his predecessors
at the agency's New York headquarters on Monday. To some extent,
the low profile criminal investigation of EgyptAir Flight 990, in
contrast to the investigation of the crash of TWA Flight 800, is
characteristic of Schiliro, who concedes he does not have the kind
of charisma as his immediate predecessor, James Kallstrom, now
retired. (Nancy Siesel/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) TRENTON, N.J. -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- NJ-REPUBS, 11-08 --
Steve Forbes, running for the Republican presidential nomination
for president, greets students from Jersey City at the Trenton War
Memorial during a rally to support public school teachers and
principals on Monday. Forbes dropped into New Jersey's capital on
Monday, making a campaign speech on the steps of the war memorial,
a block from the office of his childhood pal Gov. Christine Todd
Whitman. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- SPEND-CONGRESS, 11-08 --
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, center, heads to a news
conference Monday afternoon on Capitol Hill to discuss developments
in the ongoing budget negotitations between Congress and the White
House. At right is John Czwartacki, Lott's press secretary. (Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- CLINTON-SPEECH, 11-08 --
President Clinton waves to the crowd after delivering a speech as
part of the Herbert Quandt Distinguished Lectures at Georgetown
University on Monday. Celebrating the advances of democracy in the
decade since the fall of the Berlin Wall, Clinton called for
continued U.S. engagement in world affairs. (Shana Raab/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) NEW YORK -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- HAGEN-WOOLF, 11-08 -- The
actress Uta Hagen. On Sunday, Ms. Hagen will assume the mantle of
Martha in Edward Albee's ``Who's Afraid of Virginia Woolf?,'' for
one performance only and for the first time since closing the
production in London in 1964. Proceeds will benefit of the HB
Playwrights Foundation. ``It's a terrible risk for me,'' says Ms.
Hagen, who will also be celebrating her 80th-birthday. ``I'm 28
years too old for the part.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) BASALT, Colo. -- Nov. 5, 1999 -- SCHOOL-BUS-DRIVERS-2,
11-05 -- Ron Goth, an elementary school teacher, checks the tires
on a bus before taking to the road on a route through the small
mountain town. A national shortage of school bus drivers fueled by
the roaring economy and a rise in the school-age population is
making students wait up to an hour for a ride, delaying and
canceling field trips and athletic events, and forcing mechanics,
transportation supervisors and even some classroom teachers to get
behind the wheel. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) BASALT, Colo. -- Nov. 5, 1999 -- SCHOOL-BUS-DRIVERS-1,
11-05 -- Ron Goth, an elementary school teacher, driving a school
bus earlier this week. A national shortage of school bus drivers
fueled by the roaring economy and a rise in the school-age
population is making students wait up to an hour for a ride,
delaying and canceling field trips and athletic events, and forcing
mechanics, transportation supervisors and even some classroom
teachers to get behind the wheel. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEWTON, Mass. -- Nov. 8, 1999 --
EDLIFE-MARY-DALY-FEMINIST, 11-08 -- ``That tree is elemental,''
says Mary Daly, whose work is being featured in the ``Rereading the
Canon'' series. Trees - and women - have e-Motion - a word of her
own conjuring that means ``elemental passion which moves women
out/away from the fixed/framed state of stagnation; pyrogenetic
passion that fires deep knowing and willing, stirring metamemory,
propelling wild women on the otherworld journey.'' (Michael
Quan/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) HANOVER, N.H. -- Nov. 8, 1999 --
EDLIFE-DARTMOUTH-FRATS-4, 11-08 -- Students gathering for a Psi
Upsilon rally at Dartmouth in support of the Greek way of life. The
previous February - in a proclamation that seemed ominously
millennial - Dartmouth's governing board and its new president,
James Wright, declared that the college would begin a fundamental
rethinking of how its 4,300 undergraduate students live and
socialize. (Paul O. Boisvert/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) HANOVER, N.H. -- Nov. 8, 1999 --
EDLIFE-DARTMOUTH-FRATS-3, 11-08 -- A member of Phi Delta Alpha at
Dartmouth removes some post-party debris. Administrators have long
cringed over Dartmouth's association with ``Animal House,'' the
1978 film that was partly based on the excesses of one of the
college's frats. (Jared Leeds/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) HANOVER, N.H. -- Nov. 8, 1999 --
EDLIFE-DARTMOUTH-FRATS-2, 11-08 -- At Dartmouth's Alpha Chi Alpha,
where traditions die hard, brothers lob Ping-Pong balls at cups of
beer. The ball lands, the opponent drinks, everybody's happy.
Worried about alcohol-related deaths, sexual assaults and hazing,
but mostly by deep divisions within their student bodies, more than
a dozen colleges have either banned fraternal organizations from
campus or forced them to become coeducational. (Amy Thompson/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) HANOVER, N.H. -- Nov. 8, 1999 --
EDLIFE-DARTMOUTH-FRATS-1, 11-08 -- Phi Tau, a coed Greek house at
Dartmouth, serves milkshakes and Pecan Sandies at party time. ``I
don't like random drunk people,'' says one member. Dartmouth's
initiative to rethink Greek life is being viewed as an important
test case. (Jared Leeds/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LEISTON, England -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- EDLIFE-SUMMERHILL-3,
11-08 -- Students at Summerhill practice the rigors of
self-government through the forum of weekly meetings. Despite the
remarkable self-assuredness of the student body, the British
government threatened to close the school last spring after
inspectors from the Office for Standards in Education concluded
that ``Summerhill is not providing an adequate education for its
pupils.'' (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LEISTON, England -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- EDLIFE-SUMMERHILL-2,
11-08 --Summerhill is fighting for its life under the command of Zo
Readhead, daughter of the school's founder, A.S. Neill. Ms.
Readhead, a lanky farmer's wife of 53 who attended Summerhill in
her father's day, has turned her modest office at the school into
battle headquarters, where she sells T-shirts and coffee mugs to
raise money for the cause, and lobbies parents, alumni and
politicians for support. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LEISTON, England -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- EDLIFE-SUMMERHILL-1,
11-08 --Students at Summerhill are free to attend class or skip it,
all part of the school's unorthodox teaching methods, as first put
forth by its founder, A.S. Neill. ``Personally, I do not know what
type of teaching is carried on, for I never visit lessons, and have
no interest in how children learn,'' he wrote in a typically
provocative vein. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-B&AMP;W, 11-08
-- President Clinton gestures to President Jiang Zemin of China
during a ceremony at the White House during Jiang's state visit in
October, 1997. After a long telephone call last Saturday with
Jiang, Clinton sent a trade team to Beijing on Monday in an effort
to close a deal that would get China into World Trade Organization
in return for a huge opening of its market. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- Nov. 08, 1999 -- HKN-BRUINS-SINDEN, 11-08 --
Boston Bruins general manager, Harry Sinden, watches a game from
his box in the Fleet center. Sinden, 67, is in his 28th season as
G.M. and 11th year as team president. He won the Stanley Cup in his
fourth and final year as the Bruins' coach. In the 31 years he has
been in Boston, the Bruins have reached the playoffs 30 times, an
unprecedented achievement. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- SCI-MALARIA, 11-08 -- Sean
Cavanaugh, center, turned his doctors into detectives when he came
down with a fever of 106 that came, went and came back again.
Eventually, the spiking fever and an enlarged spleen provided Dr.
David A. Silverman, left, and Dr. James Salik with the clues they
needed. Cavanaugh, a 30-year-old artist from Manhattan, was
suffering from malaria. But how he contracted the disease remains a
mystery. (Richard Perry/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- SCI-BICYCLE-FITNESS, 11-08 --
Single-speed bikes do away with gears, and fans say it's
liberating. While the frames are made out of the lightweight metals
used in traditional mountain or road bikes utilizing gears, the
single-speeds lack the extra chain rings, front and rear detailers,
derailleur cables, shift levers and multiple cogs on the rear
wheel. (Thomas Dallal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- SCI-ANIMAL-PSYCHOLOGY, 11-08
-- Many people do not do their homework when they buy dogs, warns
Brian Kilcommons, receiving a kiss from Astor, an 18-month-old fox
terrier. ``A lot of these dogs are hard-wired for specific
behaviors,'' says Kilcommons, co-author of the book ``Paws to
Consider.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- SCI-HOSPITAL-INFECTION-2,
11-08 -- A water-free hand cleaner, operated by a foot pump, may
make hospitals safer. ``Hands are the most dangerous thing in the
hospital,'' says Dr. Robert A. Weinstein, director of infectious
diseases for the Cook County Bureau of Health Services in Chicago,
of the hand's ability to transmit germs. (Ozier Muhammad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- SCI-HOSPITAL-INFECTION-1,
11-08 -- Dr. Elaine Larson is looking into products that make hand
washing easier for hospital workers, like a foam that needs no
drying or rinsing. A recent study - conducted at the Duke
University Medical Center and published last month in The Lancet, a
medical journal - found that only 17 percent of physicians treating
patients in an intensive care unit washed their hands
appropriately. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
