<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3385 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BABIES-UNWEDMOMS-COX     11-08 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABIES-UNWEDMOMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Record number of babies born to unwed moms
 &HT;    By Suzanne Gamboa
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Outlining some of the most striking evidence of
how the American family has changed, the U.S. Census Bureau reports
today that slightly more than half the first babies born to women
ages 15 to 29 in the early 1990s were conceived out of wedlock.
</P>
<P>
   That's a tremendous jump from the one of every six births to
that age group during 1930-34 and shows no signs of slowing as the
new century approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``Society has fundamentally changed, and along with it the
American family,'' said Ronald Angel, chairman of the University of
Texas sociology department.
</P>
<P>
   The new Census report also notes that the proportion of pregnant
women who married before the child was born fell from 53 percent
for 1930-34 to about 24 percent for 1990-94, showing not only a
change in family structure but also a change in attitudes about
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The declines (in marriages) ... may also reflect the opinion
of some women that they may be better off in the long run relying
more on the support of their parents and their relatives for
financial and emotional assistance than by entering a potentially
unstable marriage undertaken solely to prevent an out-of-wedlock
birth,'' the Census report said.
</P>
<P>
   A lot has happened in the past six decades that has contributed
to the changes in family. More women are working, societal
attitudes about premarital sex have relaxed, men and women are
waiting longer to get married, divorces are easier to get,
awareness about domestic abuse has risen and society has become
more accepting of single parenthood.
</P>
<P>
   What that means is that in the coming millennium, family will
have a whole different meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I absolutely think, without a doubt, the notion of family
itself is in transition,'' said Barbara Risman, editor of
Contemporary Sociology published at North Carolina State University
and author of ``Gender Vertigo: American Families in Transition.''
``There's no longer one kind of family. Families come in all shapes
and stripes.''
</P>
<P>
   Teri Gonzales, 23, is part of that transition. She was living in
San Benito when her son was conceived. She and his father moved in
together after she became pregnant, but the relationship didn't
work, and they never married. She now is raising her 4 1/2-year-old
son on her own in Austin. Nevertheless, she considers the
traditional two-parent family to be the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ``My idea of a family, my goal, my dream,'' Gonzales said, ``is
to have the mom and the dad and the kids. I don't think that
concept is going to change in anybody's mind. That's the way it's
supposed to be.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added that she considers herself and her son a family
``because we are here for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales, a member of Parents Without Partners, said she
receives a lot of support from relatives. She and her son's father
also have a good relationship, and they make sure he spends time
with both parents, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although efforts have been made to cut the number of
out-of-wedlock births _ and recent statistics show drops in teen
birth rates _ the number of single parents remains high. The trends
aren't likely to reverse any time soon, said Angel, the UT
sociology department chairman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our next century is going to have an alternative of family
forms. We are not going to stop in our tracks. Single-parent
families are a fact of life, and our federal and state programs are
going to have to deal with the reality of many different kinds of
families,'' Angel said.
</P>
<P>
   There's also been a rise in couples living together, said Kelly
Raley, an assistant professor of sociology at the University of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Census report, recent research estimates that
41 percent of children born out of wedlock in the 1990s were born
in co-habitating families. Raley said research still must be done
to understand the implications of such arrangements on children.
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, ``it's clear to me that marriage matters a lot
less for fertility. That really is a change in the concept of
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Gamboa writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: sgamboa(at)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
