<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3386 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-GREED-REVIEW-SFCHR     11-08 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GREED-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GREED' IS GOOD _ FOR FOX'S RATINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Greed'' found its comfort level in about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The new Fox quiz show, with its $2 million-plus jackpot, had
barely begun last week when there was a question about the musician
Yo-Yo Ma.
</P>
<P>
   It was a multiple-choice question about which instrument he
plays. The contestant, whose name was Dwalu, guessed cello.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greed'' has rules. Dwalu's answer didn't count until his team
captain, Will, accepted or rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Woolery, the show's host, asked Will if he knew the answer
himself. Interesting question; $100,000 was at stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' Will said, ``but if I get it wrong I'll kill his
mother.''
</P>
<P>
   And just then, deep in the black heart of Foxland, someone who
may even have been Rupert Murdoch himself surely leaped out of his
chair, pumped his fist and screamed, (set ital)``Yes!''(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Then he probably thought: Hmmm, I wonder if we really could get
him to kill Dwalu's mother.
</P>
<P>
   But we'll never know. The answer was right.
</P>
<P>
   So Fox has thrown its tail into the burgeoning quiz-show genre
with a marvelously conceived monstrosity on Thursday nights.
</P>
<P>
   Quickly conceived, too. Dick Clark and his minions concocted
``Greed'' for Fox in four weeks flat to cash in on TV's latest
craze.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greed'' was no immediate threat to NBC's powerful roster. But
on its first night, it practically doubled Fox's Thursday
viewership.
</P>
<P>
   If Satan programmed Fox _ and the offer might well be on the
table _ the first show on the schedule would be ``Greed.''
</P>
<P>
   It gives us a team of players answering increasingly difficult
questions in an effort to ascend the ``Tower of Greed.'' The
``Tower of Greed'' goes from zero to $25,000 to $50,000 and so on,
until it tops off at $2 million plus some carry-over cash.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who probably could tell you where he's spent every dime
for the past 30 years, might as well have made his jackpot $100
million. After all, it doesn't appear anyone is going to win it.
One group of contestants got to $500,000 last Thursday and wisely
called it quits rather than risk it all on a difficult $1 million
question.
</P>
<P>
   One of the show's beauties is that from $100,000 on up, the
``teammates'' are encouraged to turn on each other.
</P>
<P>
   Woolery, the chucklehead, activates the show's ``Terminator,'' a
hopped-up battery of lights that lands on a contestant and allows
him or her to challenge a teammate _ winner take all.
</P>
<P>
   The lighting really does go a little screwy during these
``Terminator'' moments. When the players stand at their buzzers for
the showdown, the lights play across their eyes to bring out the
beadiness.
</P>
<P>
   It's worth noting that the biggest winner of all last week, a
``Terminator'' terror who took home $300,000 of his team's $500,000
winnings, was an Atlantic City lawyer with a five-day shadow and an
ill-fitting sport coat. He was almost licking his lips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Greed'' is brazenly, giddily, heartlessly reprehensible. It's
a show with built-in backstabbing, a show where Woolery actually
hands wads of cash to the contestants to tempt them.
</P>
<P>
   (set ital)Smell it,(end ital) he tells them. It's the smell of
fresh money. Don't you love it? Well, don't you? He does it with
all the aplomb of waving meat before the snouts of starving
animals.
</P>
<P>
   And you know what? ``Greed'' is also tense, and darkly amusing,
and riveting in a deep-down horrible way. I kept looking at the
clock and silently urging Woolery to hurry things along, to get to
more questions, more contestants, more money and still more
``Terminator'' strikes.
</P>
<P>
   It's come to this. Sitting at home, peeping noxiously, Foxiously
through the screen of my Sony and into the ``Tower of Greed.'' Help
us all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
