James Wright, declared that the college would begin a fundamental
rethinking of how its 4,300 undergraduate students live and
socialize. (Paul O. Boisvert/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) HANOVER, N.H. -- Nov. 8, 1999 --
EDLIFE-DARTMOUTH-FRATS-3, 11-08 -- A member of Phi Delta Alpha at
Dartmouth removes some post-party debris. Administrators have long
cringed over Dartmouth's association with ``Animal House,'' the
1978 film that was partly based on the excesses of one of the
college's frats. (Jared Leeds/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) HANOVER, N.H. -- Nov. 8, 1999 --
EDLIFE-DARTMOUTH-FRATS-2, 11-08 -- At Dartmouth's Alpha Chi Alpha,
where traditions die hard, brothers lob Ping-Pong balls at cups of
beer. The ball lands, the opponent drinks, everybody's happy.
Worried about alcohol-related deaths, sexual assaults and hazing,
but mostly by deep divisions within their student bodies, more than
a dozen colleges have either banned fraternal organizations from
campus or forced them to become coeducational. (Amy Thompson/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) HANOVER, N.H. -- Nov. 8, 1999 --
EDLIFE-DARTMOUTH-FRATS-1, 11-08 -- Phi Tau, a coed Greek house at
Dartmouth, serves milkshakes and Pecan Sandies at party time. ``I
don't like random drunk people,'' says one member. Dartmouth's
initiative to rethink Greek life is being viewed as an important
test case. (Jared Leeds/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LEISTON, England -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- EDLIFE-SUMMERHILL-3,
11-08 -- Students at Summerhill practice the rigors of
self-government through the forum of weekly meetings. Despite the
remarkable self-assuredness of the student body, the British
government threatened to close the school last spring after
inspectors from the Office for Standards in Education concluded
that ``Summerhill is not providing an adequate education for its
pupils.'' (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LEISTON, England -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- EDLIFE-SUMMERHILL-2,
11-08 --Summerhill is fighting for its life under the command of Zo
Readhead, daughter of the school's founder, A.S. Neill. Ms.
Readhead, a lanky farmer's wife of 53 who attended Summerhill in
her father's day, has turned her modest office at the school into
battle headquarters, where she sells T-shirts and coffee mugs to
raise money for the cause, and lobbies parents, alumni and
politicians for support. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LEISTON, England -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- EDLIFE-SUMMERHILL-1,
11-08 --Students at Summerhill are free to attend class or skip it,
all part of the school's unorthodox teaching methods, as first put
forth by its founder, A.S. Neill. ``Personally, I do not know what
type of teaching is carried on, for I never visit lessons, and have
no interest in how children learn,'' he wrote in a typically
provocative vein. (Jonathan Player/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) WASHINGTON -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- CHINA-U.S.-TRADE-B&AMP;W, 11-08
-- President Clinton gestures to President Jiang Zemin of China
during a ceremony at the White House during Jiang's state visit in
October, 1997. After a long telephone call last Saturday with
Jiang, Clinton sent a trade team to Beijing on Monday in an effort
to close a deal that would get China into World Trade Organization
in return for a huge opening of its market. (Paul Hosefros/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) BOSTON -- Nov. 08, 1999 -- HKN-BRUINS-SINDEN, 11-08 --
Boston Bruins general manager, Harry Sinden, watches a game from
his box in the Fleet center. Sinden, 67, is in his 28th season as
G.M. and 11th year as team president. He won the Stanley Cup in his
fourth and final year as the Bruins' coach. In the 31 years he has
been in Boston, the Bruins have reached the playoffs 30 times, an
unprecedented achievement. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- SCI-MALARIA, 11-08 -- Sean
Cavanaugh, center, turned his doctors into detectives when he came
down with a fever of 106 that came, went and came back again.
Eventually, the spiking fever and an enlarged spleen provided Dr.
David A. Silverman, left, and Dr. James Salik with the clues they
needed. Cavanaugh, a 30-year-old artist from Manhattan, was
suffering from malaria. But how he contracted the disease remains a
mystery. (Richard Perry/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- SCI-BICYCLE-FITNESS, 11-08 --
Single-speed bikes do away with gears, and fans say it's
liberating. While the frames are made out of the lightweight metals
used in traditional mountain or road bikes utilizing gears, the
single-speeds lack the extra chain rings, front and rear detailers,
derailleur cables, shift levers and multiple cogs on the rear
wheel. (Thomas Dallal/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- SCI-ANIMAL-PSYCHOLOGY, 11-08
-- Many people do not do their homework when they buy dogs, warns
Brian Kilcommons, receiving a kiss from Astor, an 18-month-old fox
terrier. ``A lot of these dogs are hard-wired for specific
behaviors,'' says Kilcommons, co-author of the book ``Paws to
Consider.'' (Chester Higgins Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- SCI-HOSPITAL-INFECTION-2,
11-08 -- A water-free hand cleaner, operated by a foot pump, may
make hospitals safer. ``Hands are the most dangerous thing in the
hospital,'' says Dr. Robert A. Weinstein, director of infectious
diseases for the Cook County Bureau of Health Services in Chicago,
of the hand's ability to transmit germs. (Ozier Muhammad/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Nov. 8, 1999 -- SCI-HOSPITAL-INFECTION-1,
11-08 -- Dr. Elaine Larson is looking into products that make hand
washing easier for hospital workers, like a foam that needs no
drying or rinsing. A recent study - conducted at the Duke
University Medical Center and published last month in The Lancet, a
medical journal - found that only 17 percent of physicians treating
patients in an intensive care unit washed their hands
appropriately. (Ozier Muhammad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
