<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3390 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-COX     11-08 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush ducks foreign leader issue, says voters look for `trust'
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Picking up endorsements from Democrats and
nearly $600,000 in contributions, Texas Gov. George W. Bush
shrugged off questions about his knowledge of foreign policy
Monday, saying what voters really want to know is, ``can I trust
this person to be president.''
</P>
<P>
   While unable to name the leaders of four of the world's hot
spots when surprised by the questions from a Boston television
reporter last week, Bush said he gave the answer the voters wanted
when he said he didn't know, ``I just told the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Still offering only broad strokes about foreign policy, Bush
went on to say, ``The voters know I'll have a strong foreign policy
that promotes peace. The voters know that I intend to rebuild the
military power of the United States so we can keep the peace. The
voters know I intend to use our technological brainpower to bring
certainty to an uncertain world.''
</P>
<P>
   Making his third campaign trip to Florida this year, Bush
attended a lunch in Jacksonville and a dinner in Orlando. He also
visited a juvenile justice program in Jacksonville. Campaign aides
said Bush raised about $200,000 in Jacksonville and nearly $400,000
in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   Five Democrats endorsed Bush during an Orlando press conference.
They included Agriculture Commissioner Bob Crawford, former Gov.
Wayne Mixson, Mayors James Naugle of Fort Lauderdale and Dick Greco
of Tampa and Tallahassee lobbyist Steve Uhlfelder, a member of the
Board of Regents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never supported a Republican for governor before Jeb Bush,''
said Uhlfelder, who backed the late Gov. Lawton Chiles in 1994
against Bush. ``He has been an outstanding governor and a great
friend.''
</P>
<P>
   Uhlfelder said he was supporting the Texas governor for
president because ``no governor in this nation has done a better
job improving education. I believe education does not have a party
label.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said winning the endorsements is proof that his message is
working. ``We have fewer voters than the Democrats and we have to
nominate someone who can not only get support from Republicans but
who can reach across party lines,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   What people are looking for in this election is a ``candidate
who has a positive agenda,'' Bush said. ``Someone who can lead and
not leave people behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Sticking to his stump speech, Bush said he wants to simplify the
tax code, make it easier for the poor to move into the middle
class, remove the so-called marriage penalty and ``get rid of the
death tax'' on inheritances.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about school vouchers, he said he supports vouchers and
charter schools but the decision to start those programs should be
left to the states.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's little brother, Gov. Jeb Bush, may have gotten himself
into a little public relations trouble while at the Jacksonville
lunch. Big brother was given a Jacksonville Jaguars football
jersey. His reaction was to grin and say he'd never be able to wear
it in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush, a former part owner of the Jaguars, proclaimed them to
be the best pro football team in the nation. He may have to explain
that to the fans of the Miami Dolphins and the Tampa Bay
Buccaneers.
</P>
<P>
   Brian E. Crowley writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
