<SLUG> BC-MILCRASH-DOD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crash costs to be told; Official denies `Daily News' behind
change
 &HT;    By Russell Carollo
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Department of Defense is changing the way it
calculates repair costs for aircraft involved in accidents, a
decision that could raise the rate of serious accidents reported
each year by the military.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon announced the change following published stories by
The Dayton Daily News on military aviation safety. The newspaper
reported in October that the military was concealing its true
aviation safety record, partially because the cost of repairing
aircraft involved in accidents was based on a standard rate of
$16-an-hour _ several times less than what the repairs cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will do away with that paragraph in Department of Defense
instructions,'' said Lt. Col. Steve Campbell, a Pentagon spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Campbell said, the services will use actual repair
costs when estimating damages. The new estimates will vary, based
on the type of repairs needed and the location of the shop, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said he expects the change to take effect within two
months.
</P>
<P>
   Repair costs estimates are critical in deciding which accidents
are reported to the public and Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates often are based on hundreds _ even thousands _ of
hours of labor, and the $16-an-hour rate has served to keep the
rate of Class A accidents artificially low, the Daily News found.
Class A accidents _ the most serious type _ involve at least one
death, a permanent, total disability, the loss of an aircraft or at
least $1 million in damage.
</P>
<P>
   John Lewis, technical expert for the Professional Aviation
Maintenance Association, said hourly repair costs for civilian
planes range from $45 for small planes to $2,000 for commercial
airliners.
</P>
<P>
   Other military rules and practices have enabled the military to
conceal its aviation safety record.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Department of Defense guidelines were rewritten, making
it easier to withhold from official statistics incidents in which
someone falls from an aircraft and is killed, accidents involving
experimental aircraft and accidents occurring on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would call that creative reporting,'' said U.S. Rep. David
L. Hobson, R-Springfield. ``Somebody is playing games with our
sons' lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said the decision to change the repair rate was
unrelated to the Daily News articles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe they had been looking at doing that about a month
before your articles came out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping repair costs low was just one way the military concealed
its aviation safety record from the public.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Carollo writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The DAYTON NEWSPAPERS INC., DAYTON, OHIO
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-11-08-99 2135EST
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
