<HEADER>
A3393 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OHIO-FLEA-MARKET-NYT &LR;      11-08 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHIO-FLEA-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEAPER BY THE ACRE, GIANT FLEA MARKETS THRIVE EVEN IN THE GOOD
TIMES  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky.)   By PETER T. KILBORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONROE, Ohio _ Darryl Haun has discovered yet another
opportunity in the great American tradition of making a buck. Haun
is a machinist during the workweek, but at amusement parks he has
become an ace thrower of objects at targets, like rings around
bottles and quarters on plates. ``After you figure it out,'' he
explained, ``it's not total chance.''
</P>
<P>
   As a reward for his unerring aim, Haun wins stuffed animals that
are bigger than most 7-year-olds. Every four or five months, he
hauls his bounty off to the Traders' World flea market here. This
weekend he was selling many of the animals for $29 each, a lot less
than they would cost in a conventional store but a lot more than
they cost him.
</P>
<P>
   Traders' World, midway between Cincinnati and Dayton on
Interstate 75, has almost half a million square feet of indoor and
outdoor selling space for 1,200 vendors, who do business with more
than 20,000 shoppers pouring through every weekend. It is hardly
alone: scores of giant flea markets like it dot the country,
although most, unlike Traders' World, operate only part of the
year. Even in a robust economy, it seems, the flea market can
thrive by drawing enough bargain hunters, particularly those who
crave the opportunity to find a product not only cheap but perhaps
rare or unique.
</P>
<P>
   Traders' World, one of the largest, charges a vendor $40 a
weekend to set up a table outside and $68 for a booth inside,
prices that offer novice merchants a cheap way to enter the
marketplace with their goods. Fall weekends are its busiest time of
the year, and all available space was in use both Saturday and
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   While no one keeps comprehensive statistics on flea markets,
what evidence there is suggests that others are having at least
some of the success enjoyed by the one here. Ron Simmons, president
and general manager of the 1,800-vendor Traders Village near Dallas
and senior vice president of the National Flea Market Association,
says that when he surveyed 130 of more than 2,500 markets around
the country last summer, he found that the industry was more than
holding its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry is up as a rule,'' Simmons said. ``Fifty-three
percent of the markets showed an increase in attendance and gross
income'' from the summer before. ``About 20 percent showed a
decrease, and the rest were showing the same. The decreases were
the result of road construction, competition or extreme weather
conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Traders' World is a wonder of enterprising vision, the fantasy
of a sod farmer, Jay Frick Sr., who opened it 15 years ago at the
age of 62 and has made it a major contender for the dollar of
southwestern Ohio's consumers. Starting with 3 buildings then, he
has now erected 13, which look like ribs extending from a
spine-like core building.
</P>
<P>
   Frick pipes in polkas, waltzes and golden oldies, has decorated
the interior with hundreds of rural artifacts and has strung
aphorisms from the ceilings like ``Don't spend all your money on
wine, women and song. Save some to spend foolishly.''
</P>
<P>
   It's all a little overdone to Becky Lugibihl, a visitor who said
she preferred garage sales. Ms. Lugibihl, a 43-year-old word
processor for the state of Ohio, had taken a bus tour to Traders'
World from Lima, Ohio, an hour and a half away. ``I got some
zucchini for 39 cents a pound,'' she said, 40 cents less than she
can find it at home. ``And I got two cans of Sani-Flush for $1
each. At stores they're $2 something.'' But the savings did not pay
for the $24 trip.
</P>
<P>
   For every Becky Lugibihl, though, there is a couple like Scott
Wood, 42, and his wife Margie, 29, of Erlanger, Ky., 40 minutes
away. They have seized on flea markets, where the vendors own the
business, as an alternative to malls, where the sellers are
sometimes ill-informed clerks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love thrift shopping, so I can buy more,'' Mrs. Wood said.
``Jeans. I got a pair for $1.50, and they're new.'' Wood said he
was considering a leather jacket that costs $297 here and $429 at a
mall.
</P>
<P>
   The Woods said they could find just about everything here:
appliances and antiques, new wedding gowns and used boots, jeans
and custom-embroidered sweatshirts, old compact discs and old
videotapes, birdhouses and produce, fast food and pony rides. Few
merchants carry silk purses anymore, but sows' ears are $1 each.
Dogs use them to gnaw on.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM. STORY CAN END HERE.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On the other side of the transaction, there are at least some
success stories. Flea-market merchandising has been a boon to Gary
Berding, strictly a wholesale liquidator until he opened a booth
here six weeks ago to try retail liquidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sell shelf-pulls,'' Berding said _ that is, he buys goods
that big stores like Wal-Mart and Target cannot sell and that
manufacturers therefore pull off the stores' shelves and sell to
him. ``I'm kind of like a cemetery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Berding's hottest items this past weekend were Foster Grant
reading glasses with original price tags of $13.49. He was selling
them for $2 each or three for $5.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're averaging $2,000 a weekend,'' he said, or about four
times the receipts that Jay Frick Jr., who has taken over
management of the market from his father, estimates to be the
average for all booths.
</P>
<P>
   Business is slipping, however, among a mainstay of flea markets,
vendors of limited-edition collectibles: thematic plates with
images of Marilyn Monroe and Elvis Presley, Hummel figurines,
Beanie Baby dolls. Nancy and Ron Dornbusch said their hottest line
was Precious Moments, white porcelain figurines of children, every
one with dewy black eyes. New ones are $30. Discontinued models can
exceed $900.
</P>
<P>
   But ``something's going on,'' Mrs. Dornbusch said. ``Ebay,'' she
said, referring to the Internet auction service. ``I have people
coming in and saying, `I bought the same thing on the Internet.'''
</P>
<P>
   Tom and Linda Engelhaupt speculate that in the lush economy, too
many merchants have sprung up to court the consumer, so the
competition has intensified. From a large indoor booth, the
Engelhaupts sell jackets, shirts and baseball caps that they
embroider on order on the premises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years ago,'' Engelhaupt said, ``there weren't a lot of
embroidering machines. It was great. It peaked three years ago.
Everybody and his brother has a machine now.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, David and Maria Hamm sell a variety of collectibles and
knickknacks. ``Cookie jars are real hot,'' Mrs. Hamm said, as are
Christmas items. But they said shoppers were tougher than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want something real expensive,'' Hamm said, ``that
doesn't cost very much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
