u a BC-CATHOLICISM-YOUNG-BOS     11-08 0936
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CATHOLICISM-YOUNG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNGER CATHOLICS' BOND WITH CHURCH SLIPPING, STUDY SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARCELLA BOMBARDIERI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A majority of US Roman Catholics between 20 and 39 have
a tenuous relationship with their church, attending Mass
sporadically and not getting involved with local parishes,
according to a national study to be released Tuesday at Emmanuel
College.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most critically, while younger people tend to feel
attached to Roman Catholic rites and theology, they find church
leaders deaf to their concerns, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   To many young Catholics, the institutional church looms like a
stern disciplinarian, scolding them for straying from church
teachings on such hot-button topics like divorce, abortion, and
birth control.
</P>
<P>
   Younger Catholics ``are not firmly embedded in the life of the
church,'' said Sister Mary Johnson, a sociology professor at
Emmanuel. ``In some cases, they are hanging on by a slender
thread.''
</P>
<P>
   The study's findings should serve as a ``wake-up call'' to
church leaders to provide a compelling argument to younger
Catholics about the importance of the church in their lives,
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   What is at stake is the future vitality of the church in America
_ home to more than 60 million Roman Catholics _ which because of
dwindling numbers of priests and nuns, is coming to rely more and
more on lay Catholics to keep its parishes running.
</P>
<P>
   Many Catholic leaders already realize they need new campaigns to
reach younger members of the church. The Archdiocese of Boston and
four other Massachusetts and New Hampshire dioceses have launched
``Pilgrimage 2000,'' an ambitious effort to engage thousands of 14-
to- 40-year-olds in discussions about faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future belongs to our youth and if we don't do enough to
reach out and embrace them then we're shortchanging them,'' Sister
Marian Batho, Pilgrimage 2000 coordinator for the Archdiocese of
Boston, told the Globe in May.
</P>
<P>
   The study, authored by scholars at three universities, says the
Roman Catholic Church needs to become more inclusive and less
hierarchical.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Second Vatican Council told us the church is `the people
of God,' not the church hierarchy,'' said Johnson, referring to the
famous conclave more than 30 years ago that was an attempt to
create a more open and modern church.
</P>
<P>
   ``There needs to be a more expansive sense of what it means to
be in the church,'' said William Dinges, a religious studies
professor at the Catholic University of America.
</P>
<P>
   During his pontificate, Pope John Paul II has made it clear the
church is not a democracy, a message that has filtered down to
dioceses worldwide, including the United States.
</P>
<P>
   If the church seeks to remain relevant in a country where
Catholics coexist with people of many faiths, leaders must
explicitly accept those who do not fit the mold of the model
Catholic, they say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people we talked to have the conception that it's all or
nothing, and you have to be a good Catholic in every possible way.
That's not easy today,'' said Dean R. Hoge, professor of sociology
at Catholic University in Washington, D.C. ``It's important to
convey that it's not a total package where if you don't follow
everything, you're not OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on 848 phone interviews with Catholics in dioceses
nationwide who had been confirmed as adolescents, the study took
three years and cost $500,000. Of those surveyed, 90 percent still
identified as Catholic, 65 percent called themselves active
Catholics, and 70 percent said they attend Mass at least once a
month.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of these young Catholics called lay people
``just as important a part of the church as priests,'' said the
church should put more women in positions of authority and called
for open debate on divorce, remarriage and sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Similar ideas have been voiced by Catholics around the world. At
a meeting of European Catholic bishops at the Vatican two weeks
ago, several bishops argued that the church leadership is
heavy-handed in governing and outmoded in thought.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Carlo Maria Martini, the archbishop of Milan who is
considered by some as a possible successor to Pope John Paul II,
stunned the gathering with his diplomatic but sharp critique.
</P>
<P>
   There is a growing awareness of the usefulness, ``even the
necessity, of a . . . consultation among the bishops on sexual
morality, the shortage of priests and other issues facing the
church,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a 4-year-old Austrian-based movement calling for a
``democratic'' church is gaining momentum across the world,
according to recent press reports. Called ``We Are Church,'' it
claims ties to 127 Catholic reform groups in 27 countries,
including the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The next generation of Catholics will require even more
flexibility and creativity from the church, said the authors of the
study. According to their survey data, half of Catholics between
the ages of 20 and 39 are married to non-Catholics, including
Protestants, Jews or spouses who practice no religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will their kids go to CCD (religious education classes)? Will
they go to Protestant Bible school in the summer?'' Johnson asked.
``The Jewish community talks about this all the time. We've got to
talk about it right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The church cannot afford to ignore such challenging questions,
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a very good chance that young generations will be even
more diverse, the social factors that are at work becoming even
more complicated,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
