u l BC-DISABILITY-COX     11-08 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISABILITY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New foundation to aid disabled
 &HT;    By Tom Beyerlein
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ For years, parents couldn't leave money to their
severely disabled adult children without jeopardizing federal
benefits that provide life's necessities.
</P>
<P>
   That's changing with the establishment of the Disability
Foundation. The new foundation allows parents to set up trust
accounts that will continue to provide money for life's ``extras''
_ recreational activities, hobbies, vacations _ after the parents
are dead, without causing the children to become ineligible for
Medicaid and Supplemental Security Income.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've very excited about it,'' said Darrell Murphy, president
of the Dayton Foundation, the parent organization of the new
foundation. ``We think it fills a big need in the community and,
frankly, I think it'll be a national model.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 22,000 physically and mentally disabled people in the
Miami Valley who receive the income-based Medicaid and SSI benefits
are eligible to participate . The program, open to those who are
considered disabled for Social Security purposes, is made possible
by changes in Medicaid rules and state law.
</P>
<P>
   Before the changes, the disabled couldn't receive bequests
without jeopardizing their federal benefits, which are tied to a
recipient's income and assets. For example, a Medicaid recipient is
not permitted to have liquid assets _ including savings, cash,
stocks or certificates of deposit _ of more than $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Lynne Pietz, the Dayton attorney who is executive director of
the Disability Foundation, said it works like this:
</P>
<P>
   Using the foundation's Ohio Community Pooled Trust, parents,
grandparents, legal guardians and disabled people themselves , in
anticipation of receiving a bequest, can set up a charitable gift
annuity account s designated for particular individuals. , to be
managed by the Disability Foundation . Accounts can also be
established by others, with a court order: Montgomery County
Probate Judge George Gounaris recently allowed an aunt to set up an
account.
</P>
<P>
   The donations are invested, and the disabled person receives a
fixed amount quarterly for life. , to be used for ``supplemental
needs.'' as a guaranteed obligation of the Dayton Foundation. The
fixed amount is based on the amount of money in the account and the
person's age and life expectancy.
</P>
<P>
   Families can designate a person to oversee the spending of the
money, subject to review by a foundation committee. Acceptable uses
of the money include concert tickets, cable television, vacations,
cosmetic or elective surgery, magazine subscriptions and the like.
The person can save disbursements to buy more expensive items or
services.
</P>
<P>
   Upon the disabled person's death, any unspent funds
disbursements are first used for funeral expenses, with additional
money returned to the state to underwrite the person's public
assistance benefits. Any unspent funds money that had not been
disbursed are retained by goes to the foundation, to be used for
other programs and services for the disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Pietz said the payout schedule is designed so the foundation is
likely to retain about 20 percent of the funds.
</P>
<P>
   Such trusts were made possible by changes in Medicaid rules
starting in 1993 and a 1995 Ohio law. Cleveland has the only other
pooled trust in Ohio, Pietz said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Beyerlein writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
