<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: MEDIA SERVICES FOR INTERNET COMPANIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It often seems these days as if dot-com companies are peddling
their wares by buying up every moment of commercial time and every
inch of advertising space everywhere from matchbooks to cyberspace
to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, those purchases are usually the result of decisions
made by specialists in media planning and buying, who, despite
appearances, are trying to spend finite amounts of money as
efficiently and effectively as possible.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, one of the largest agencies devoted to media
services, Media Edge in New York, is forming a unit dedicated to
online media. The unit, Digital Edge, will focus on planning and
buying for Internet media, electronic commerce, fledgling
technologies like video on demand and the so-called convergence of
new and traditional media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that there's so much going on here that we wanted
a group to concentrate on it as well as educate the rest of us
about it,'' said Beth Gordon, president of Media Edge, which is
part of Young &AMP; Rubicam, in an interview Monday. Details about the
formation of Digital Edge are to be announced Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Edge joins a growing list of operations specializing in
Internet media that are being set up by bigger media services
agencies to counter the competition from the new breed of Internet
agencies like Agency.com and Modem Media.Poppe Tyson, which was
spun off from True North Communications.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, in January, Starcom Worldwide, the media services
unit of the Leo Group in Chicago, opened Starcom IP to handle
online media planning and buying functions. (IP is from ``Internet
protocol''; the long strings of numbers known as Internet protocol
addresses are what enables computers to seek one another out.)
</P>
<P>
   Starcom IP is already ``becoming a global brand,'' said Wally
Petersen, a spokesman for Leo.
</P>
<P>
   Digital Edge, which like Media Edge will be based in New York,
is opening with a staff of 15, handling 13 accounts with billings
estimated at $30 million. Some clients like Gifts.com _ a new Web
site jointly owned by the Reader's Digest Association and Startek
Inc. _ are being transferred from Media Edge, which has worldwide
billings estimated at more than $8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Some clients like AT&AMP;T, with billings estimated at $10 million
to $15 million, and Wine.com, formerly Virtual Vineyards, are new.
AT&AMP;T had used Modem Media.Poppe Tyson in Norwalk, Conn., as its
interactive agency until July, when the Strategic Interactive Group
unit of Bronner.com in Boston was named to handle creative and
media duties in what was described as a mutual parting over
philosophical differences.
</P>
<P>
   Strategic Interactive will keep the AT&AMP;T Internet creative
assignment as the media duties shift to Digital Edge. Because Media
Edge is the agency of record for AT&AMP;T in traditional media, the
appointment of Digital Edge permits a closer integration of
interactive and mainstream campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The client roster for Digital Edge also includes Blink.com, a
bookmarking Web site; Celebrity Cruises, part of Royal Caribbean
Cruises; Ericsson, the cellular telephone company; interactive work
for Helzberg's Diamond Shops, a unit of Berkshire Hathaway, and
Webstakes.com, a Web site that links consumers to promotional
offers.
</P>
<P>
   Three executives from Media Edge are being named to run Digital
Edge, reporting to Steve Lanzano, executive vice president at Media
Edge.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the leadership is a troika, to use a term the Russian
digirati might, Ms. Gordon replied that ``because there's so much
to cover, it doesn't make sense to have a single leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Schanzer, 31, vice president and associate planning
director, will become vice president and managing director of
Digital Edge. David Adelman, 34, senior vice president and
technology director at Media Edge, will become senior vice
president and convergence media director at Digital Edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``What David will concentrate on,'' Ms. Gordon said, explaining
his title, ``is how TV and some combination of the Internet and
other media will ultimately converge.''
</P>
<P>
   And John Donnarumma, 28, vice president and associate technology
director at Media Edge, will become technology director at Digital
Edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll be looking into what systems do we need to run the media
operations of the future,'' Ms. Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds like something for one of the ``In the Year 2000''
segments on ``Late Night With Conan O'Brien.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
