<HEADLINE>
DRIVING INTO MEXICO? $800 DEPOSIT, POR FAVOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Nov. 14) 
(jt) 
 By SAM DILLON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ For American and Canadian tourists who are
dismayed over a new plan to charge deposits of up to $800 for
foreign-registered cars driven into Mexico, the government has some
advice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Get used to it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Customs officials were to begin collecting the increased
deposits on Nov. 1, but after criticism by American lawmakers,
residents of border states and some Mexican officials, the
government postponed the start-up until Dec. 1 _ when, it insists,
the daunting measures, meant to discourage illegal importation of
cars, will take effect. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under current rules, a traveler who wishes to drive a car with
American plates into Mexico at any of the 23 legal crossing points
along the 2,000-mile border can receive a six-month permit by
paying an $11 deposit by credit card. Two other, cash-based options
are far more expensive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, the deposits rise to $400 for a
foreign-registered car manufactured before 1994, to $600 for cars
made between 1994 and 1998, and to $800 for models newer than that.
The deposits are to be paid in cash or by credit card; in the
latter case, the Mexican government will not simply retain the
voucher but will immediately debit the card, officials said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The deposits apply only to cars that pass into the Mexican
interior, beyond a legally defined border zone that extends 25
kilometers, or about 16 miles, south of the frontier. The deposits
do not apply at all to the peninsula of Baja California, which
includes two states that have traditionally enjoyed a variety of
free-trade provisions, officials said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Highway checkpoints are set up at the perimeters of the 16-mile
zone, and a driver caught without a permit can lose his car. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new deposits will probably greatly reduce cross-border
tourism. Experts on car travel to Mexico, including owners of
agencies that sell Mexican car insurance to foreign motorists, say
that if the new deposits take effect, a large percentage of
American and Canadian tourists are likely to cancel their Mexican
plans.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be terrible,'' said Olivia Bravo, co-owner of
the Bravo Insurance Agency in Laredo, Texas Her agency sells 5,000
policies a year to motorists heading into Mexico. She predicted
that sales of Mexican policies would fall by at least half under
the new rules. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to kill the goose that lays the golden eggs,''
Mrs. Bravo said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 2.7 million Americans and 34,000 Canadians crossed
into Mexico beyond the border zone, and the American motorists
spent $679 million in their Mexican travels, said Camilo Perez
Venegas, a director at the Council for Tourist Promotion, a
government agency. Another statistic measuring the same
cross-border tourism is that Mexican Customs issued 750,000
six-month permits for foreign cars to circulate in Mexico in 1998. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Five congressmen, from Texas, Arizona and California, outlined
the broad discontent in border states in a meeting Nov. 3 with
Mexican Ambassador Jesus Reyes Heroles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the lawmakers, Rep. Solomon Ortiz, D-Texas, said his
constituents in Corpus Christi have been organizing to protest the
measure, and other demonstrations and boycotts appeared to be
brewing all along the border. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very unhappy with this, because they just don't
have the money,'' Ortiz said. ``A lot of people can't afford to
even get a credit card, much less have $600 to $800 for this.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new deposits are designed to force people who drive cars
into Mexico to drive them out again, since at least 1.5 million
cars have been left behind _ in effect, imported illegally _ said
officials at the treasury ministry, which together with the
interior ministry wrote the new rules. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The 1.5 million owners of the illegal cars are so powerful
politically that authorities simply discard the possibility that
police might seize the illegal cars or arrest the owners. Last year
federal police confiscated only 8,000 of the illegal cars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Marco Provencio, a treasury ministry spokesman, said that the
owners of the illegal cars pay no taxes, making them a drag on
government revenues and a threat to Mexican car dealers. Pretax
prices on new cars in Mexico are on average about 5 percent higher
than in the United States, he said. When taxes are included,
Mexican prices increase by 21 percent, United States prices by
about 8 percent. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But the new deposit's impact on tourism appears to have gone
largely unconsidered in the government's internal debate. Several
tourism ministry officials expressed surprise over the new rules,
saying they had not heard of them. One asked a reporter to explain
the measures. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An American official said he believed that the Oct. 28
postponement of the new plan was a first step toward canceling it
completely. But Provencio said that people should plan to comply. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not planning to repeal this,'' he said. ``We wouldn't
postpone it for a month and then cancel it. That wouldn't be a
serious way to operate.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
