<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AFTER THE WALL 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Nov. 9:
</P>
<P>
   What began in 1961 as a crude expanse of cinder blocks and
barbed wire became in time a 113-mile stretch of fortified concrete
and steel, imprisoning West Berlin. It was both a physical and
psychic barrier, for 28 years the most powerful symbol of the Cold
War, dividing not just Berlin and Germany and Europe but East from
West. Then, 10 years ago, on the evening of Nov. 9, 1989, the
Berlin Wall came down, its collapse a dramatic expression of the
larger failure of a Soviet empire brought down by economic decay,
the cynicism of its citizens and the historic decision of its
leader, Mikhail Gorbachev, not to use the force needed to hold it
together. In fact, by allowing the wall to be breached without
military response, Gorbachev did exactly what President Reagan, on
a visit to Berlin two years before, had demanded: `` Gorbachev,
tear down this wall!''
</P>
<P>
   The day after the wall fell in 1989, what had been a trickle of
dangerous crossings became a flood of humanity seeking to exchange
the East's oppression for the democratic promise of the West.
</P>
<P>
   On balance, that exchange has yielded huge dividends for the
nations and citizens of the old empire. Freedom of thought has
replaced the deadening conformity of a single ideology. Oppressive
five-year economic plans have given way to freer markets. The
secret police and other devices of totalitarianism have largely
disappeared. But any honest stock-taking, 10 years later, must
concede that progress has been uneven.
</P>
<P>
   In Eastern Europe, for example, Poland, Hungary and the Baltic
states _ Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia _ have prospered. Romania,
Bulgaria and the components of the old Yugoslavia have fared less
well. Most observers agree that the countries that bit the bullet
first _ closing inefficient industries, reducing state subsidies _
have shown the best results. In political terms, the differences
are less pronounced. Democracy, with multiple parties and free
elections, has taken root nearly everywhere, though at varying
speeds, with the former Yugoslavia being the most glaring
exception.
</P>
<P>
   Germany itself illustrates the complexities of moving from one
system to another. The German economy is a third larger than any
other in Europe. But integrating two economic systems and two
ideologies has not been a seamless process. Headlong economic
reform, including a misguided high-wage policy, left a 20 percent
unemployment rate in the former East Germany. Even now there is a
certain nostalgia for the old days when everyone had a job, however
meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   But except for unreconstructed Communists, few wish to go back.
True, there is too much crime and corruption in some of these new
societies. Even so, thoughtful Eastern Europeans have made
remarkable strides toward reclaiming their pre-Communist cultural
identities and pressing their political leaders for greater
democracy. Indeed, in country after country the tyranny enforced
behind the wall seems a rapidly receding memory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 2204EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
