<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAVEL QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., Nov. 14) 
(jt) 
 By RAY CORMIER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Classes in Cuba
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am a Spanish teacher and would like to get information
about travel to Cuba for language courses. _ Jim Rodgers,
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   A. You may see a few Cuban cigars and baseball pitchers around,
but the 1963 embargo on trade and travel with Cuba is still in
effect. So, travel by Americans to Cuba is limited and can be
illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there has been an increase in travel to the island by
Americans in recent years. Some Americans circumvent the law by
using foreign travel sources, but the regulations allow trips to
Cuba for certain reasons, including education.
</P>
<P>
   According to Maria Ibanez, a spokeswoman for the Treasury
Department, ``it's not that complicated'' for a teacher to gain a
license to visit Cuba to take courses there. Essentially, you would
have to write a letter to the Office of Foreign Assets Control,
Department of the Treasury, Washington, D.C. 20220, confirming your
position and stating the purpose of your visit. First, Ms. Ibanez
suggested, check out the office's Web site, www.treas.gov/ofac, or
call (202) 622-2520 for details. A summary of the policy is also at
a new today State Department site,
www.state.gov/www/regions/wha/cuba/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   There are also organized educational trips. The group Global
Exchange has been leading trips to Cuba for about 10 years, said
Roberto Leni, who runs its Cuban program. The trips, which leave
from Cancun, Mexico, include two and four-week language courses at
the University of Havana.
</P>
<P>
   These trips are licensed as ``fully hosted'' by a Cuban
organization, Leni said, adding, ``We've never had a participant
fined or jailed'' (fully hosted trips require that no American's
money go to any Cuban entity; so, for example, a non-Cuban airline
must be used). The students take classes four hours a day and take
part in other activities tailored to the interests of the group _
from bicycle outings to meetings with human rights advocates.
</P>
<P>
   The cost for two weeks is $1,200, and $1,750 for a month. This
includes round-trip air fare from Cancun, double or triple
accommodations in a guest house (hotels cost extra) and two meals a
day. Contact Global Exchange at 2017 Mission St., No. 303, San
Francisco, Calif. 94110; (415) 255-7296, fax (415) 255-7498, or
www.globalexchange.org.
</P>
<P>
   It is wise to ask any American organization running a trip to
Cuba whether it has a license from the foreign assets office and
whether you can see the license. Also ask whether the air carrier
is licensed.
</P>
<P>
   In Canada, which has formal relations with Cuba, the Bureau de
Tourisme de Cuba, 440 Boulevard Rene Levesque, Montreal, Quebec H2Z
1U7, (514) 875-8004, says education trips are offered by Unique
Tours, 666 Rue Sherbrooke Ouest, Montreal, Canada H3A 1E7, (514)
844-2831, fax (514) 844-2018, www.vuvoyage.com; and Voyages
Culturels Cuba, 5059 St.-Denis Street, Montreal, Canada H2J 2L9,
(888) 691-0101, fax (514) 982-2438, www.culturecuba.com.
</P>
<P>
   Getting to Slovenia
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am going to Kobarid, Slovenia, for a World War I
commemoration. I have booked a flight to Venice. How can I get from
there to Kobarid by public transportation? _ Guy Cavallaro,
Poughkeepsie, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   A. Kobarid is known to many as Caporetto, which in World War I
was part of Italy and at the center of the fighting chronicled by
Hemingway in ``A Farewell to Arms.'' The Kobarid Museum documents
the battle in great detail.
</P>
<P>
   The town lies below Mount Krn (7,362 feet) in the Soca Valley,
an Alpine resort area. It is only a few miles from the Italian
border, but getting there is not easy, according to Darja Gacnik,
director of the Slovenian Tourist Board in New York, and Branko
Moric, who handles Central Europe for Central Holidays of Englewood
Cliffs, N.J. They said your best bet may be to rent a car.
</P>
<P>
   You can also take the daily 7:04 a.m. train from Venice to
Ljubljana, the capital, in the center of the country (a five-hour
trip costing about $29 in second class, at 1,800 lire to the
dollar), then take a bus or train back west to Kobarid.
</P>
<P>
   But you can avoid that. From the Venice airport, take a bus to
Mestre and get off at the train station. Trains to Gorizia, on the
Italian-Slovenian border, leave every hour or two at 53 minutes
past the hour (most also leave from Venice Santa Lucia 20 minutes
earlier). It is about a two-hour trip and costs $8.
</P>
<P>
   Once in Gorizia, you will have to take a cab (about $15) or two
buses (switching at the border) into adjoining Nova Gorica,
Slovenia. Kobarid is about a 30-mile drive north, so you could take
a cab, for about $55. But there are direct buses from Nova Gorica
to Kobarid at 9:40 a.m. and 3:35 p.m for about $5. For details,
call the bus depot at Nova Gorica, (386) 65-21-447.
</P>
<P>
   Another option involves staying overnight in Udine: a bus runs
from there to Kobarid at 9 a.m. on Monday and Wednesday only, for
about $4.50. Information: (39-0432) 608-111.
</P>
<P>
   The Slovenian Tourist Board is at 345 East 12th St., New York,
N.Y. 10003; (212) 358-9686, fax (212) 358-9025. Ms. Gancik also
runs an agency, Slovenia Travel, (212) 358-9024, fax (212)
358-9025. Central Holidays is at 120 Sylvan Ave., Englewood Cliffs,
N.J. 07632; (800) 935-5000, fax (201) 228-5327. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Christmas Dinner in Paris
</P>
<P>
   Q. I will be in Paris with my children for Christmas. Will any
restaurants or cafes and tourist attractions be open on Christmas
Day? _ E.M., Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   A. Most attractions and restaurants in Paris will be closed on
Christmas Day. But you should be able to find a good meal. In
general, the best areas to find one are Montparnasse and the
Champs-Elysees.
</P>
<P>
   Both La Coupole, 102 Boulevard de Montparnasse, (33-1)
43.20.14.20, with a bustling grand room out of the 1930's, and Au
Pied de Cochon, 6 Rue Coquilliere, (33-1) 40.13.77.00, near Les
Halles, say they will be open. Near the Opera, Le Grand Cafe
Capucines, 4 Boulevard des Capucines, (33-1) 3.12.19.00, has a
Belle Epoque interior. A bit pricier than those is Fouquet's, 99
Avenue des Champs-Elysees, (33-1) 47.23.70.60.
</P>
<P>
   As far as major attractions go, the Eiffel Tower will be open
from 9:30 a.m. to 11:30 p.m. The children might enjoy the Grande
Gallerie de l'Evolution in the natural history museum in the Jardin
des Plantes. It includes a zoo and is open 10 a.m. to 5 p.m. on
Christmas; (33-1) 40.79.30.00.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving, you might seek more information from the French
government Tourist Office, 444 Madison Ave., New York, N.Y. 10022;
(212) 838-7800.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
