<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-EDUC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: YES, THE REGENTS MEAN BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Nov. 9:
</P>
<P>
   New York's education commissioner, Richard C. Mills,
crisscrossed the state for three years urging school districts to
upgrade their curriculums to meet the challenging new standards and
tests that the state Board of Regents began to phase in this year.
But new statewide test scores show that even some suburban school
districts turned in disappointing scores and may have failed to
beef up course offerings.
</P>
<P>
   This year's tests _ keyed to the new Regents' standards _ have
revealed mediocrity at many levels, sending a shock through
affluent small towns and suburbs that are accustomed to looking
good in statewide comparisons. Only 67 percent of the fourth
graders statewide met the new math standard. The news was more
dismal for eighth graders, where only 38 percent performed at grade
level. The performance drop between fourth and eighth grades
reflects a statewide problem with middle schools, which have
consistently failed to incorporate challenging new material into
their courses.
</P>
<P>
   On the whole, the big-city systems lagged behind the suburbs.
New York City placed ahead of the four other large urban systems,
with 23 percent of its eighth graders meeting the math standard,
compared with 22 percent in Buffalo, 19 percent in Syracuse, 10
percent in Rochester and 13 percent in Yonkers. But some suburban
systems also performed in the mediocre range. In Suffolk County's
East Hampton district, for example, only 41 percent of eighth
graders met the standard. A fifth of the children in exclusive
suburbs like Rye, Mamaroneck and Great Neck failed to meet the
eighth-grade math standard.
</P>
<P>
   When Mills visited high-performing schools, he typically found
the new standards prominently displayed in teachers' lounges and
classrooms and encountered principals who could discuss the
standards issue fluently. In failing schools, the principals and
teachers had gone on teaching the watered-down curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and political leaders have a right to be angry about
dismal test performance. But they need to direct their anger at
school officials who took the new standards lightly when they
should have been retooling to meet them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
