<SLUG> BC-RUN-NY-MARATHON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DAY LATER, NEW YORK CITY MARATHON WINNERS RUN THE MEDIA
MARATHON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Australia, Italy, Kenya, Mexico, Austria)   By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joseph Chebet was so relieved after winning the New
York City Marathon on Sunday that he slept soundly that night.
Adriana Fernandez was so hyped up after winning the women's title
that she could not sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Sleepy or not, Chebet, a 29-year-old Kenyan, and Fernandez, a
28-year-old Mexican, needed all their energy Monday for another
tour of the city. This one truly deserved the name marathon, for it
never seemed to end. The schedule:
</P>
<P>
   --6:45 a.m. _ Appearance on Channel 4's ``Today in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   --7:15 a.m. _ Appearance on CBS's ``The Early Show.''
</P>
<P>
   --7:45 a.m. _ Visit the Chase Manhattan Bank headquarters on
Park Avenue, where the race results were posted, followed by a
meeting between bankers and the two nouveau riche marathoners,
whose prize money, time bonuses and appearance fees totaled
$105,000 for Chebet and $100,000 for Fernandez.
</P>
<P>
   --8:15 a.m. _ Appearance on Channel 5's ``Good Day New York.''
</P>
<P>
   --9:30 a.m. _ Sound the starting bell at the New York Stock
Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   --10:30 a.m. _ News conference at Tavern on the Green.
</P>
<P>
   --12:30 p.m. _ Visit the Mazda dealer who gave a new $25,000
Miata to each winner.
</P>
<P>
   --2 p.m. _ Trip to City Hall to receive the keys to the city
from Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   --4:45 p.m. _ Tape CBS's ``Late Night With David Letterman.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, Chebet returns home to spend time with his family. Then
he will go to the spartan camp at 10,000-foot altitude that serves
as a training base for 15 or 20 Kenyan marathon runners. ``There is
no telephone, no electricity, no water,'' he said. ``We have to go
down to the river to get water. Everything we must do by
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez had planned to return home Monday, but her trip was
delayed for a day because the Mexican Consulate here is giving a
party in her honor Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Her victory was the first by a Mexican woman in a major
international marathon and has created a commotion in the
Spanish-language news media. Univision, which reaches all of Latin
America, did a television special hours after the race. The New
York daily newspaper El Diario carried a huge front-page photo of
Fernandez crossing the finish line and big black type that read
``Viva Mexico!''
</P>
<P>
   Race officials want both winners back next year, but based on
their words Monday, Chebet appears doubtful and Fernandez
questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Chebet plans to run next April in Boston, a marathon he also won
this year. He also expects to run a late-year marathon; he hopes
that it is in the Sydney Olympics. Chebet's agent, Federico Rosa of
Italy, who is the son of his coach, Dr. Gabriele Rosa, said running
in the Olympics and then, five weeks later, in New York was an
impossible double for Chebet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he does not run in the Olympics,'' Rosa said, ``I still
don't know about New York. He wants the world record, and New York
is not the fastest course for that. We have plenty of time to
decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez said she would probably run one marathon before the
Olympics. As for an Olympic-New York double, she said, ``My coach
will decide.''
</P>
<P>
   Her coach is Rodolfo Gomez, the runner-up to Alberto Salazar in
the 1982 New York City Marathon. Fernandez trains at 12,000 feet in
mountains near Mexico City. She also runs on the track and this
year won the 1,500 meters in the Mexican championships and the
5,000 meters in the Pan American Games. Gomez said she could easily
run New York after the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran Tokyo and Rotterdam in six weeks and was 2:09 in both,''
Gomez said. ``She's a very young marathon runner. She's run only
eight marathons in her life. She's very strong. A double is very
possible because she doesn't run many races in a year. We will
decide after the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez said she believed that her victory would encourage
Mexican women to run. Gomez said he hoped that would happen. ``When
Mexican women runners get married,'' he said, ``they stop running,
stay at home, have a baby and we don't see them anymore. Maybe this
will change that.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FINISHING KICKS
</P>
<P>
   Allan Steinfield, the marathon director, said the race had
32,503 starters and had 31,807 finishers, both records. He said the
10,000th runner finished in 3 hours 59 minutes 53 seconds, the
20,000th in 4:38:56 and the 30,000th in 5:56:13.
</P>
<P>
   Joschka Fischer, the German foreign minister, ran under the name
of Martin Fischer and finished in 3:56:13. Steinfeld said he did
not know how fast or even whether Joerg Haider, who heads Austria's
right-wing Freedom Party, finished. For security reasons, Steinfeld
said, Haider was given another race number under an assumed name.
But Steinfeld said he thought that Haider ran without the computer
chip that was issued to all runners to record their times. ``He was
unrecorded at any of the check points,'' Steinfeld said. ``He said
he finished. We have no record of him running.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
