<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNITEDHEALTH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doctors rule, insurer decides
 &HT;    By Andy Miller
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Physicians groups in Georgia and elsewhere are
applauding a move by the nation's second-largest health insurer to
let doctors have the final say on treatment decisions.
</P>
<P>
   UnitedHealth Group's new policy, announced Monday, could put
pressure on the managed care industry to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   It is a startling departure from a long-held practice of
cost-cutting in managed care plans. The decision coincides with
patient protection legislation in Congress that focuses on denial
of treatment by managed care plans such as HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   UnitedHealth, based in Minnesota, covers about 14.5 million
Americans, including about 400,000 in Georgia. The insurer is
second in enrollment size to Aetna.
</P>
<P>
   United said it costs the company more to review doctors'
decisions than it would to cover those treatments in question.
About 99 percent of doctors' decisions are upheld by United, said
Jay Silverstein, chief marketing officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were spending $100 million a year to anger physicians, to
anger consumers and impact just 1 percent of our claims,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   United began testing the policy in Tennessee two years ago and
brought it to six other markets, Silverstein said. The policy will
roll out nationwide this month. Doctors' decisions will be reviewed
by United after treatment is delivered, he said.
</P>
<P>
   HMO managers' ability to overrule doctors' decisions about what
procedures and services are medically necessary _ and thus covered
_ has been a basic tenet of managed care. Such practices have
helped HMOs control health care costs during the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   United said its policy is not a response to the so-called
Patients' Bill of Rights proposed in Congress. Still, U.S. Rep.
Charlie Norwood (R-Ga.), a leading sponsor of such legislation,
said of the United policy, ``The best care, in the long run, is
less expensive than cutting corners. ... Giving the right care
upfront is always cheaper than paying to correct the problems
created by inadequate care.''
</P>
<P>
   Other managed care plans ``will take a wait-and-see attitude''
and judge its savings impact, said Gay Ann Williams of the Georgia
Association of HMOs.
</P>
<P>
   Many HMOs will be pressured to follow United's lead, said Ken
Thorpe, an Emory University health policy expert.
</P>
<P>
   He said the policy would reduce United's exposure to liability
provisions being considered in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The Medical Association of Georgia, which represents about 8,000
physicians statewide, called United's decision ``a monumental
event.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The medical necessity of treatment should be determined by a
physician,'' said Bill Clark, an attorney for the doctors group.
</P>
<P>
   He added, though, that United could end up jettisoning doctors
who approve treatments the company doesn't want to cover.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
