<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MEXICO'S POLITICAL EXPERIMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, Nov. 9:
</P>
<P>
   Mexico took a step toward greater democracy on Sunday when the
party that has supplied all its presidents for the past 70 years
held a competitive primary to choose next year's presidential
nominee. The primary was an important but not flawless exercise in
free political choice.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco Labastida Ochoa, the man closest to President Ernesto
Zedillo and the establishment, won a decisive victory over Roberto
Madrazo Pintado, an insurgent governor. But Labastida's triumph was
clouded by questionable campaign practices, such as using
government funds to solicit votes and intimidating Madrazo
supporters. Madrazo also seems to have bent the rules.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the vote count itself seems fair, and that represents
significant progress. The charges of earlier abuse, however, are a
reminder that the PRI's habits of electoral manipulation may die
hard and could resurface in next year's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Labastida is a strong favorite to win next year's vote. Polls
show that a majority of Mexican voters favor one or another
opposition party. But these parties are split by ideology and the
competing egos of their leaders. The PRI needs only to win more
votes than any of its opponents to extend its grip on the
presidency for four more years. But unless the forthcoming election
campaign is more scrupulously policed than Sunday's primary, a
victorious PRI could lack the public confidence it will need to
govern. Opposition candidates must have a fair chance to get their
message out to potential voters or democracy will be shortchanged.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, who cited the primary as proof of political reform in
Mexico, needs to make clear before next July's presidential
election that official favoritism on behalf of the PRI candidate
would be no favor to democracy. Washington must also send a clear
message that America's interest in maintaining political stability
in Mexico is best served by a clean campaign and vote.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 2217EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
