<HEADLINE>
NEW PACT SENDS GREEN TO DODGERS FOR MONDESI  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Canada)   By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANA POINT, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Dodgers finished a distant
third in their division this year, but they are 1-2 in the player
salary standing.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, who less than a year ago made Kevin Brown the
highest-paid player in baseball history with a seven-year contract
that averages $15 million a season, Monday made outfielder Shawn
Green No. 2 over all and the highest-paid position player ever with
a six-year contract that averages $14 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The contract completed a trade with the Toronto Blue Jays for
Raul Mondesi that had been contingent on the Dodgers reaching
agreement with Green and his agent, Jeff Moorad. They wrapped it up
with a $4 million signing bonus and salaries of $8.75 million,
$11.5 million, $12.75 million, $15 million and $16 million each of
the last two years. The Dodgers, for the icing, added award bonuses
and a complete no-trade provision. Not bad for a kid who grew up
about 40 miles south of Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers did everything but sing ``Happy Birthday'' to the
outfielder, who turns 27 on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The $29-million average annual value of the combined contracts
of Green and Brown exceeds the entire 1999 payrolls of seven teams
_ Pittsburgh, Montreal, Florida, Minnesota, Oakland, Kansas City
and the Chicago White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Mondesi, also represented by Moorad, had the two
option years in his contract guaranteed by the Blue Jays, who also
added award bonuses for all four years left in the contract in
return for the outfielder waiving his right to demand a trade after
next season as a player traded in the middle of a multiyear
contract. The Blue Jays, who offered Green $48 million for five
years, will pay Mondesi $44.5 million for four years.
</P>
<P>
   Green, whose contract surpassed Mo Vaughn's $13,333,333 a year
as the highest for a position player, may not retain his status for
long. Other players in his circumstance, Ken Griffey Jr., for
example, may be traded and sign contracts that surpass his. Green's
circumstance was that he was a year away from free agency and
unwilling to sign a multiyear contract with a club that didn't want
to keep him around for the 2000 season, then lose him and get
nothing in return.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig was asked his view of the new phenomenon,
advance free agency, earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thrilled to tears over these developments,'' Selig
said after addressing general managers at their annual meetings.
``But it is what it is. It's not a surprising development in
relation to the system. You could see this coming. I may be
surprised at the number, but other than that I'm not really
surprised. Given what has happened to a lot of clubs over the years
about losing players to free agency and not getting anything in
return, this is just a very logical development and not a
surprising one.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Rangers began the early exodus of superstars a week
ago when they traded Juan Gonzalez to the Detroit Tigers after
determining it would take more than $12.5 million a year, though
not knowing how much more, to sign the two-time American League
most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Green had an mvp-type season with the Blue Jays, hitting .309,
socking 42 home runs and driving in 123 runs among other impressive
statistics. The Blue Jays wanted to sign him to a multiyear
contract, but he told them he wanted to play in a major U.S. city
with a large Jewish population.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely excited,'' Green said at a news conference. ``I
get a chance to play at home. This is a dream come true for me to
play at home and play for this organization that has such a great
tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi, on the other hand, wanted to leave the Dodgers. He had
incidents with the manager and the general manager this past
season. Moorad said he had one last conversation with his client
Monday, before he completed his negotiations with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said you're sure you don't want to be a Dodger,'' the agent
related. ``He said it's been a great organization for me for many
years, but at this point I feel I have to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Davey Johnson, the Dodgers' manager, said Mondesi was frustrated
this year with his own performance and the team's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made an outburst that he apologized for to everybody,''
Johnson said. ``I don't have any problem with him. I think Mondesi
talks to other players like Pedro Martinez or Pedro Astacio or
Roger Cedeno and they seem to blossom in other places. He gets this
idea that you go somewhere else and you really flourish. I tried to
tell him it's not always that way. Each situation is different. The
guys you talked to didn't get the opportunity here. Just because
you go somewhere else doesn't mean it's going to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi had the lowest batting average of his career, .253, but
reached career highs in home runs with 33 and runs batted in with
99. Kevin Malone, the Dodgers' general manager, acknowledged that
the high salaries of Green and Brown present problems for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult because you're trying to improve in other
areas,'' he said. ``That's what we're working on, analyzing the
market place and where it's going. We felt it was an opportunity to
get a player of Shawn's caliber, and we had to take that step
forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Two other players were included in the deal. The Blue Jays
received Pedro Borbon Jr., a left-handed relief pitcher, and sent
the Dodgers a minor league infielder, Jorge Nunez. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
