<HEADLINE>
NELSON, MAVS LEAVE FOUL ODOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; DALLAS _ If Don Nelson didn't set basketball back far enough
Sunday night in Los Angeles, he just might get another opportunity
to crush the game's aesthetics tonight.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers and Mavericks meet for the second time in three days,
this time at Reunion Arena, and if the game is close in the fourth
quarter, expect more foul treatment of the Lakers' Shaquille
O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson managed to shave a few points off the Lakers' lead late
Sunday with a series of quick intentional fouls of O'Neal. The game
slowed to a crawl and predictably, O'Neal missed 5 of 10 down the
stretch. But the strategy, while effective, fell short as the
Lakers held on to win 105-97.
</P>
<P>
   So is Lakers coach Phil Jackson worried about another long night
of O'Neal clanking shots off every inch of the rim?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not concerned about it,'' he said. ``Don did that to
the Bulls when Dennis (Rodman) was with us, two years ago. He used
that same format in the third and fourth quarter. Dennis, of
course, made 8 out of 10 free throws in the process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a great experience for Shaq. We think that it's
good for him to have that kind of pressure, to have that
notification, to bring attention to the fact that he's got pressure
on him to carry his weight in that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that Jackson is thrilled with the strategy, noting that the
NBA in the 1960s discouraged intentional fouling by giving players
three attempts to make two foul shots. To gain ground through
continuous fouling ``strategically makes sense'' but ``is away from
the intent of the game,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Through four games, O'Neal is shooting 39.2 percent from the
line, but Jackson has no other complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's playing great in all aspects of the game except
the free throws, and I don't know if he can do anything about that
until he absolutely changes his mind as to how he's going to
approach shooting foul shots,'' Jackson said. ``Sometimes it's like
an alcoholic . &UR;  &LR; . &UR;  &LR; . they have to actually seek the help to get
response from what they're trying to get.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Money matters: So far, no $5,000 fine from the NBA for
Jackson's criticism of officials in Saturday's loss to Portland. He
doesn't regret the remarks, but he's also not thrilled with paying
a hefty tax on free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never like for money to be taken away from me,'' he said.
``I think that's inappropriate for the league to do that, but
that's their policing activity, and if they want to control the
game as much as they do, I kind of anticipate it will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; __  &LR; Ouch report: Kobe Bryant continued to push forward in his
recovery from a broken right hand. He's now allowed to remove his
protective splint to practice dribbling and shooting, which he did
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt all right,'' he said. ``I don't have my whole
confidence in it. I feel a little tweak going on.''
</P>
<P>
   He hopes to return ahead of the projected Nov. 24 date.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you had asked the doctors would I be dribbling
right now, they'd probably have said hell no. So I guess I am ahead
of the game,'' he said. ``Hopefully I'll get back soon, God
willing.'' &UR; !dlim!!end &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
