<SLUG> BC-GEORGE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL TAKES A TIMEOUT FOR GRIEVING
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pro football coaches often lament that it is nearly impossible
to acquire the complete attention of their players for more than a
reasonable stretch. We stress reasonable. Four or five hours of
work a day and, hey, after that, in many circles, coaches lose
players' eyes, ears and brains, no matter how creative the snatch.
</P>
<P>
   Crafty coaches attempt to keep practices short and crisp,
meetings blunt and brief, film study precise and timely. Today's
players roam toward so many other interests and obligations that
sometimes it is the football regimen that appears to get in the
way.
</P>
<P>
   There are off-field business meetings, to discuss investing
their millions. Family obligations surface. Social events beckon.
And for many, the music industry attracts; it is a venue many of
them view as equal in entertainment value to their own.
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally, however, a season rolls along and a few events
sprout up that command their total attention. It has been that kind
of season, that kind of week.
</P>
<P>
   This National Football League season began with the shocking
retirement of Detroit's Barry Sanders in a year when he might have
become the league's career rushing leader. In the first week, Jets
quarterback Vinny Testaverde was injured and lost for the year,
drastically altering the Super Bowl chase.
</P>
<P>
   Also early on, last season's Super Bowl running backs _ Jamal
Anderson of the Atlanta Falcons and Terrell Davis of the Denver
Broncos _ each blew a knee, ending their season.
</P>
<P>
   The Super Bowl champion Broncos crawled to an 0-4 start. The
Super Bowl runners-up Falcons did, too.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas Cowboys receiver Michael Irvin recently lay motionless on
the turf and was feared paralyzed. He was not, but is his career
over? Same for quarterback Steve Young, who suffered the fourth
concussion of his career and has not played in six weeks for the
San Francisco 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   While mighty teams fell, some forlorn ones rose.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Giants, the Seattle Seahawks, the Detroit Lions and
the St. Louis Rams are first-place teams. It is a mild surprise
that the Jacksonville Jaguars and the Miami Dolphins own the
league's best record at 7-1, both with defenses that glow.
</P>
<P>
   Players across the league have noticed these things. And then in
the last few days, their minds were riveted by death and tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Their football week began with the death of Walter Payton at age
45 from bile duct cancer last Monday. It ended with the stunning
news Sunday that the wife and child of defensive back Steve
Muhammad of the Indianapolis Colts had both died.
</P>
<P>
   Payton's death shook the players to the core. He was not much
older than they are. Most had followed his career and found it
inspiring. Before every NFL kickoff Sunday, there was a moment of
silence in remembrance of Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Chicago Bears players took notice. Last week they
apparently practiced in a manner that they seldom had. They were a
3-5 team playing at the Green Bay Packers, tackling a bunch that
had defeated them 10 consecutive times.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago won, 14-13, blocking a field-goal attempt by the Packers
on the last play of the game. The Bears, to a man, were on a
mission, attentive and in tune. How else can such a game be
explained?
</P>
<P>
   The Colts did not learn until after beating the Kansas City
Chiefs that Muhammad's wife, Nichole, had died at an Indianapolis
hospital during their game and that the Muhammads' child was
stillborn.
</P>
<P>
   The news devastated players around the league and especially the
Colts. At least three Colts and their wives are expecting children:
Cornelius Bennett, Jeff Burris and Chad Cota.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw her out of the complex on Wednesday,'' Bennett said.
``Today she's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   With the season half complete, the stage has been set. This is
not an ordinary NFL season by any standard. It is odd in nature,
shocking in game results and tragically twisted in scope.
</P>
<P>
   The league spins toward Super Bowl XXXIV with anticipation of
the unexpected, with a new order among its teams and, in many
instances, with heavy hearts.
</P>
<P>
   It churns with more players alert, more with wide-open eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes after a game, when I talk about God, some of the
writers look at me like I'm crazy,'' said Chris Hayes, 27, of the
Jets. ``But that's where my understanding comes from. I wonder how
others find a way to make sense of some of the stuff that's going
on. There's a lot out there, for sure. All the guys around the
league are talking about it. We feel it. We notice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
