<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK-HAVANA FLIGHTS WILL RESUME 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIRTA OJITO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Almost 40 years after the last Havana-bound
commercial airplane took off from a New York City airport, flights
between the two cities will resume next month, fulfilling one of
the key elements of the Clinton administration's more relaxed
policy toward Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The direct flights are expected to start Dec. 3 from Kennedy
Airport. While it will remain illegal for Americans to travel to
Cuba as tourists, the flights will make it easier and faster for
the thousands of Cuban-Americans in the New York-New Jersey region
to visit relatives on the island legally.
</P>
<P>
   It will also ease travel for an increasing number of U.S.
citizens from the Northeast traveling as scholars, journalists or
members of religious groups, who are exempt from the American
embargo on trade and travel to Cuba. Until now, flying to Havana
has required traveling through Miami, the Bahamas or Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Marazul Charters has been approved by both governments to handle
the flights. The company, which has already started selling tickets
from its office in Weehawken, N.J., has scheduled one flight per
week to Cuba that will leave Kennedy at 8:35 p.m. on Fridays, with
a return flight scheduled for before dawn every Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Charles Rangel, a Democrat of Harlem, said he believed
the flights would help normalize relations between the two
countries and might encourage his colleagues in Congress to move
toward lifting the decades-old embargo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason today why we can't trade with Cuba,''
Rangel said Monday at a breakfast sponsored by Marazul Charters.
``The more people travel to Cuba and come back with stories that
the Cuban people really love us, the better it is.''
</P>
<P>
   About 140,000 Americans travel to Cuba every year, said John
Kavulich II, president of the U.S.-Cuba Trade and Economic Council,
a New York group that advocates the lifting of the embargo. About
25,000 travel illegally through third countries, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kavulich said that 92 percent of the people who travel to the
island legally were Cuban-Americans with relatives there. He also
said that American business people were increasingly traveling to
the island in anticipation that the embargo will be lifted; by the
end of this year, he said, 3,000 business people will have traveled
to Cuba, 500 more than last year.
</P>
<P>
   The direct flights from New York will be flown by Grupo Taca, an
alliance of Central American airlines, and a round trip will cost
$629; most of the 150 seats on the first flight have already been
sold, Marazul officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these flights we hope to provide needed services, but we
are also creating a link between the financial capital of the world
and Havana,'' said Francisco Aruca, president of Marazul Charters.
``Within the law, we stand ready to facilitate communication
between the two countries, in accordance with the new policy of the
United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, President Clinton announced a series of
measures intended to increase contacts between people in the United
States and the people of Cuba. They included expanding direct
charter flights, allowing more Americans _ not just those with
relatives on the island _ to send money to Cubans, establishing
direct mail and permitting the sale of food and agricultural
supplies to nongovernmental entities.
</P>
<P>
   The president's initiative was well received by those who oppose
the embargo and by many who support it. Some supporters of the
embargo, who fear that tourism would amount to economic support for
Cuba's communist leader, Fidel Castro, described the initiative as
a sign that the president was committed to keep a tough policy
toward Cuba while helping families. Opponents of sanctions said the
president's announcement was an opening that could help unite the
voices of people asking Congress to lift the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Armando Collazo, an official with the Cuban Interest Section in
Washington, Cuba's only formal diplomatic presence in the United
States, said Monday that the direct flights would contribute to
``normalcy in the communications and the relations between Cuban
families, here and over there.''
</P>
<P>
   But Yvonne Conde, a freelance writer in Manhattan who left Cuba
38 years ago and has never been back, said she feared the flights
would facilitate travel to Cuba for those who have no family there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowadays, anyone can be a scholar,'' she said. ``Anybody can
say they are doing research, when in fact it is tourism. I can't
condemn anyone who goes to Cuba to see relatives, but I find
tourism to Cuba appalling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
