<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3445 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MAINE-ELECTION-465&AMP;AD     11-08 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAINE-ELECTION-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL JUDGE UPHOLDS MAINE'S CAMPAIGN-FINANCE LAW 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., Mass., Vt.)  (lb) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a victory for advocates of an overhaul of how
campaigns are financed, a federal judge has upheld Maine's
groundbreaking Clean Election Law, ruling that the incentives it
offers to candidates to take public money instead of private
contributions are constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Voters approved the measure in 1996, putting the state in the
forefront of the movement for full public financing of campaigns,
or what supporters call ``clean money.'' Since then, the Vermont
Legislature and voters in Massachusetts and Arizona have approved
similar measures. All the states offer candidates who qualify a set
amount of public money to cover their campaigns. In return, the
candidates agree to spend no more than that amount.
</P>
<P>
   In all four states, the public financing laws have encountered
obstacles. Legal challenges also have arisen in Vermont and
Arizona, where, like Maine, the new finance rules take effect for
next year's election. In Massachusetts, where the new financing
measure will take effect in the 2002 election, lawmakers seem to be
balking at providing money for the new law.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of laws to provide public financing for campaigns
hailed the decision by Judge Brock Hornby of U.S. District Court,
which was released late Friday, as a significant legal precedent
and a boost for state-level attempts to change from the ground up
how campaigns are financed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a big green light for clean elections to take effect
here in Maine, to take effect in Massachusetts and Vermont and
Arizona, where they've also been challenged in court,'' said John
Brautigam, director of legal advocacy for the Maine Citizen
Leadership Fund, which helped defend against the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the law, which include the American Civil Liberties
Union, the Maine Libertarian Party, political action committees,
campaign contributors and some candidates, plan to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lopez, a lawyer for the ACLU, said that the organization
supported the idea of public financing. But, he said, ``the basic
premise of the case was that the public financing system they
adopted in Maine was structured in a way to coerce maximum
participation,'' rather than allowing candidates a real choice
about whether to take public money.
</P>
<P>
   The Maine law not only gives public money to candidates willing
to accept overall campaign spending limits, he said, but also
lowers the limits on contributions that people and groups can make
to privately financed candidates, making it harder for candidates
to run without public financing.
</P>
<P>
   Hornby has not ruled on the challenges to Maine's contribution
limits, which were included in the Clean Election Law. The campaign
limits dropped from $1,000 from an individual or $5,000 from a
group, to $250 across the board, Brautigam said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his ruling on Friday, Hornby noted that opponents had raised
several objections to the new law, including the complaint that it
involved certifying publicly financed candidates as ``clean,''
implying that their privately financed opponents were not.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents also complained that the levels of spending set for
publicly financed candidates were too low to foster hearty public
discourse. They also took issue with the mechanism by which money
spent outside a privately financed candidate's campaign could
trigger matching public funds for that candidate's publicly funded
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   The Maine law provides incentives to candidates to take public
financing, Hornby wrote, ``but the incentives hardly are
overwhelming or of an order that can be said to create profound
disparities.'' And state officials testified, he said, that they
would call publicly financed candidates ``certified'' rather than
``clean.''
</P>
<P>
   In addressing opponents' complaints concerning matching money,
Hornby wrote, ``their view is that there is no point in speaking if
your opponent gets heard as well.'' But the First Amendment aims to
promote a marketplace of ideas, he wrote, and so ``the public can
only gain when the opposing candidate speaks in return.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar court challenges are facing Vermont's campaign-finance
measure, passed in 1997, which includes lowered contribution
limits, making it vulnerable to accusations of First Amendment
violations.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, the new campaign-finance law faces two challenges,
both brought by the Arizona Chamber of Commerce, said Sharlene
Bozack, executive director of the Clean Elections Institute, the
group that led the initiative that passed the law. The challenges
focus in part on the source of the public money for the campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, the state Legislature each year must
appropriate money for the public financing of campaigns. And this
year, the first for the new measure, the lawmakers are holding up
the money. Among the conditions they have set for approving the
money is a constitutional review of the law, said David Donnelly,
director of Massachusetts Voters for Clean Elections, the group
that successfully led the ballot initiative here.
</P>
<P>
   The Maine decision, with its constitutional stamp of approval,
``certainly clears one hurdle out of the way toward implementation
of the law in Massachusetts,'' Donnelly said. But still, he said,
he fears that the law's opponents ``are going to try to use the
courtrooms or legislative back rooms to try to defeat reform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
