<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3451 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBO-SPORTSNET-TEX     11-08 0684
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-SPORTSNET-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROTISSERIE TO REALITY: INTERACTIVITY THE FUTURE OF INTERNET SPORTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOMMY CUMMINGS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is one surfer's vision of a cool application of sports on
the Internet in the not-too-distant future:
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Peyton Manning is outfitted with a button-sized
multimedia transmitter on his Indianapolis Colts helmet. The tiny
camera, accessed by millions of users from an NFL-sanctioned site,
follows everything Manning sees and picks up everything he hears.
</P>
<P>
   Other players are rigged the same way.
</P>
<P>
   If this ever happens, users can experience an NFL game as if
they're on the field _ free from the dangers of concussions or
serious injury _ all from the comforts of their personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this is one surfer's vision. What about an analyst
who follows the sports technology industry and has access to the
think tank?
</P>
<P>
   Aram Sinnreich, consumer content analyst for Jupiter
Communications, an industry watchdog, said a peak into the future
is as close as ABC's Enhanced TV (heavy.etv.go.com/snfnow)
interactive site.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's Enhanced TV allows users to play a Java-powered online
game that's in synchronization with the Monday Night Football
telecast. Users can also access real-time statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes the enjoyment of the game, as a user on the Internet,
that much more intense,'' Sinnreich said. ``It allows you to get
more involved with the game directly.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinnreich's colleague, Patrick Keane of Jupiter Communications,
told Yahoo! Internet Life that with Internet access built into many
of the new video-game systems, virtual leagues will bridge the gap
between ``rotisserie and reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Interactivity is only to get more intense as technology
develops, Sinnreich said. ``A lot of that depends on how people are
accessing the Internet, as we move from a two-screen \RTV and
computer monitor\S to a one-screen experience with integrated
content,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Sinnreich said he foresees the technology advancing
so that hot links are embedded in a video stream for e-commerce
purposes. Users will be able to click on the live moving image of a
player and be able to buy the team's official jersey. Or the user
can access the player's real-time statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the programming available down the line,'' he said.
``Clearly the technology isn't there, but that's the direction.''
</P>
<P>
   And then there is broadband, the technology in progress that
channels all of the multimedia into one cybercast pipeline.
Sinnreich predicted that 25 percent of all homes with Internet will
be able to handle broadband capabilities by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to make a huge difference,'' Sinnreich said. ``It's
not going to look like TV; it's going to be video on demand. Let's
say you missed the big home run of the day. Rather than catch it on
the news, you go to a site and see it on demand.''
</P>
<P>
   As for a player's-eye-view, such as helmet cams, Sinnreich said
his job as an analyst is not to make pie-in-the-sky predictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is something to think about,'' he said. ``I'm sure someone
out there is thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   SCORING AT HOME: Viewers of the Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis
fight, scheduled Saturday on pay-per-view, can score the fight from
home on Excite &LR; Home (sports.excite.com).
</P>
<P>
   Showtime's fight sites provide online scoring, but this is
Excite\NHome's first effort at providing round-by-round scoring.
Results of the fans' scoring are scheduled to be posted after the
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it could work well, given the little controversy of
the last fight (which was a draw),'' said Shira B. Kallus, a
spokeswoman for Redwood City, Calif.-based Excite &LR; Home.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKING ODD ODDS: Sportsbook.com, a betting site based in
Margarita Island, Venezuela, is booking action on which NBA player
will ``succumb to the pitfalls of life and surrender to the
pressure on stardom in the NBA.'' Peter Childs, Sportsbook.com's
bookmaker, said in a news release that the odds-on favorite is the
Atlanta Hawks' Isaiah Rider (3-to-1).
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 2237EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
