<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3458 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LAD     11-08 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KRIKOR-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES WITH MAURY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Maury Wills is sitting there in the restaurant booth across from
me, and I remember back to that magical summer of 1962 when he
revolutionized base-stealing and changed forever how baseball was
played in this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my MVP year,'' says Wills softly. ``A great year. A
memorable year. Broke Ty Cobb's stolen base record. Actually, set a
record that never will be broken. Played in 165 regular season
games. Remember, we finished tied with the San Francisco Giants,
and in those non-playoff days they settled ties in a best-of-three
series. And it went the full three games. Unfortunately, we blew
the last one. Still, a wonderful season...''
</P>
<P>
   Maury Wills smiles gently in fond remembrance of that long-ago
season when he altered the fabric of the national pastime with his
104 stolen bases that brought the running game into a game that
long had ignored it.
</P>
<P>
   He is 67 years old now, but he doesn't look it and still weighs
the lithe 170 pounds he did when he was inspiring ``Go! Go! Go!''
chants at Dodger Stadium and when he was streaking around the bases
leading the light-hitting Dodgers to unlikely National League
pennants and World Series championships.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Koufax and Don Drysdale did the pitching for those Dodger
teams of the 1960s, but it was the fast legs and inexhaustible
spirit of Wills that propelled them to their dizzying heights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stole bases to help us win games, not to set any records,''
says Wills. ``If my intent were to steal as many bases as I could,
I probably could have stole 150 or 160 in 1962.''
</P>
<P>
   I look at Maury Wills, and I get the feeling the old shortstop
smiles through a wounded heart because he has become the Forgotten
Man of his sport, shunted into the shadows in recent years despite
his heroic achievements across the 13 blazing seasons he spent in
the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   While there has been an understandable furor about Pete Rose's
absence from the Hall of Fame, no one has vocally stood up and
railed about the injustice of Wills not having a plaque hanging in
Cooperstown.
</P>
<P>
   All Wills did during his career was bat .281, collect 2,134
hits, steal 586 bases, play on four NL pennant-winning and three
World Series-winning Dodger teams, and alter forever the contours
of his sport.
</P>
<P>
   He has a higher lifetime batting average than Phil Rizzuto
(.273), Pee Wee Reese (.269) and Luis Aparicio (.262) and stole
more bases than all of them. And none of those players came faintly
close to impacting games like Wills routinely did throughout his
career.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Phil Rizzuto, Pee Wee Reese and Luis Aparicio are
shortstops who have been enshrined in the Hall of Fame, while Wills
hasn't even been given serious consideration despite his
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't give you a reason why I haven't made it,'' says
Wills, slowly shaking his head. ``I wish I knew. I've always been
late in doing things in my life. I was nearly 27 before I was
brought up by the Dodgers. Maybe it'll be the same way with the
Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   There are those who believe that Maury Wills has been shunned in
the Hall of Fame voting because of the serious drug problem that he
endured throughout most of the 1980s, including his brief but
disastrous managerial tour with the Seattle Mariners.
</P>
<P>
   If this is the main reason, then it's pure humbug because the
Hall of Fame has in it men who were hopeless alcoholics, certified
bigots, addicted gamblers, outrageous misogynists, and those with
various other vexing shortcomings.
</P>
<P>
   It's ridiculous that Wills would be shut out of the Hall of Fame
because of what he did after (italicize after) his playing days
were long finished, but there are those in the baseball
establishment who insist this is the case.
</P>
<P>
   Maury Wills has been clean now for nine years, and all I know
about Wills is that he just might have been the most fiercely
competitive baseball player I've ever seen perform, if not among
the most exciting.
</P>
<P>
   Wills grew up in Washington D.C., and signed as a pitcher with
the Dodgers in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   ``But once I went to spring training camp in Vero Beach, and saw
how many minor league pitchers the Dodgers had, I quickly became an
infielder,'' says Wills.
</P>
<P>
   He recalls returning to his hometown in the off-season, and
watching an incredible basketball player at Phelps High School who
totally dominated games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called him the `Rabbit,' ''says Wills. ``Never seen anyone
jump, or hang like he could. His name was Elgin Baylor.''
</P>
<P>
   Maury Wills bounced around the minor leagues for 8{ seasons
before he finally was called up by the Dodgers in June of 1959, and
it wasn't easy for a young black athlete in those Jim Crow days in
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget the time I was playing in Ft. Worth, Texas,
and I got in the bus and sat on a bench in the front of it,'' says
Wills. ``The bus didn't move and the driver turned and glared and
me and said, `Hey, boy, get your ass in the back where you belong.'
I've never felt so embarrassed in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   But Maury Wills endured the slights and the rejections, and
season after season kept playing minor league baseball for the
Dodgers when the manager his Spokane team, Bobby Bragan, made a
suggestion to him in the July of 1958 that would turn his life
around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bragan told me I had been in a seven and a half year slump
batting right handed,'' says Wills. ``He told me with my speed that
I should try switch-hitting. And he worked with me for a few days
before I tried it. Bragan also taught me how to bunt and how to hit
to the left side of the infield.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest, of course, is history.
</P>
<P>
   Maury Wills soon would be leading the NL every year in bunt
singles and infield hits, and would become the scourge of rival
pitchers because of his running skills.
</P>
<P>
   He says Juan Marichal was the best pitcher he ever faced, and
reveals he was partly responsible for the infamous incident in 1965
when Marichal took a bat to John Roseboro's noggin.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the game the night before against the Giants, we needed a
run badly and I was determined to get it any way I could,'' relates
Wills. ``Well, I faked a bunt, pulled the bat back on purpose, and
it hit the mask of the Giant catcher, Tom Haller. The umpire
awarded me first base on an obstruction call. I immediately stole a
couple of bases, and scored a run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, the next inning, the Giants' Mattie Alou tried the same
tactic, but John Roseboro didn't fall for it. Alou kept trying to
hit Roseboro in the mask with the bat, and finally did. Roseboro
lifted Alou up, and warned him never to do that again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess Marichal was mad about what Roseboro did to
Alou---both were from the Dominican Republic---and so in the first
inning the next day Marichal knocked me, Jim Gilliam and Ron Fairly
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really steamed up Roseboro, and he begged Sandy Koufax to
do the same to the Giant hitters. But Sandy wouldn't do it. So
Roseboro told me he was going to hit Marichal in the face with the
ball when Marichal came to bat. But, instead, he nicked Marichal's
ear with the ball, and that started the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Maury Wills stays busy these days, working as a base-running
coach for the Toronto Blue Jays, serving as the director of public
relations for Mainline Incorporated in Torrance, attending
memorabilia card shows and giving drug abuse speeches around the
country.
</P>
<P>
   He lives alone in a condominium in Rancho Palos Verdes, and
regularly dates a tall, attractive lady from Huntington Beach.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon at Phil Trani's, the two are celebrating
her birthday, and Maury Wills is the picture of contentment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a good life,'' he says. ``And it would be complete if I
make it into the Hall of Fame. I just hope I do before I die.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
