<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BONOMI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN G. BONOMI, 76, LAWYER WHO SOUGHT TO DISBAR NIXON 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John G. Bonomi, a lawyer who investigated the role of organized
crime in professional boxing and later successfully sought the
disbarment of President Richard Nixon, died on Saturday at his home
in Irvington, N.Y. He was 76.
</P>
<P>
   As an assistant district attorney in Manhattan from 1953 to
1960, Bonomi investigated dozens of figures connected to boxing,
including Frankie Carbo, the so-called underworld commissioner of
the sport, and James D. Norris, the multimillionaire president of
the International Boxing Club.
</P>
<P>
   Bonomi's work led to Norris' stepping down as president of the
boxing club and the organization's dissolution. Carbo was convicted
on charges of managing boxers without a license; he was sentenced
to three years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation also brought Bonomi, a former collegiate
boxer, to the attention of Sen. Estes Kefauver, D-Tenn., who
appointed him special counsel to the Subcommittee for Antitrust and
Monopoly when it held hearings on professional boxing in 1960 and
1961.
</P>
<P>
   At the hearings, Jake La Motta, a former middleweight champion,
admitted that in 1947 he threw a bout at Madison Square Garden with
Billy Fox, then an undefeated light heavyweight.
</P>
<P>
   Bonomi worked in 1961 and 1962 as a special assistant attorney
general in New York investigating racist and anti-Semitic
literature distributed in the New York campaign for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   From 1963 to 1976, Bonomi was chief counsel for grievances for
the Association of the Bar of the City of New York. In 1974, he
started an investigation that resulted in 1976 in the disbarment of
Nixon in New York on grounds related to the Watergate scandal and
interfering with the legal defense of Daniel Ellsberg, who was on
trial on charges connected with the publication of the Pentagon
Papers.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon had voluntarily given up his license to practice law in
California and before the Supreme Court of the United States and
sought to do the same in New York. The New York bar, however,
refused to allow Nixon to give up his license voluntarily unless he
acknowledged, as state law requires, that he could not successfully
defend himself against the charges. In Nixon's case the charges
included five counts of obstruction of ``the due administration of
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   John Gurnee Bonomi, who was known as Jack, was born in in
Brooklyn in 1923. He graduated from Columbia University and
received a law degree from Cornell University and a master's degree
in law from New York University. He served in the Army Air Corps in
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Bonomi was a visiting scholar at Harvard Law School,
specializing in professional conduct. From 1977 to 1996 he was in
private practice, often defending lawyers and judges accused of
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   He was a member of the committee for grievances and admissions
for the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, a lecturer at Fordham
University Law School, a columnist for The New York Law Journal, a
trustee of the Village of Tarrytown, N.Y., a councilman and deputy
supervisor of the town of Greenburgh, N.Y., and special council to
the village of Irvington.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Patricia; a daughter, Kathryn Bonomi
of Tarrytown; a son, John G. Bonomi Jr. of Manhattan, and a
granddaughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 2243EST &QL; 
