<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 22:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3464 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-BALENCIAGA-FASHION-AR     11-08 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALENCIAGA-FASHION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NICOLAS GHESQUIERE RESCUES BALENCIAGA WITH A GLANCE AT THE PAST 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent. Non-subscribers can purchase by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By CATHY HORYN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In his long, puritanical career as a dressmaker,
Cristobal Balenciaga never gave an interview and seldom saw a
client. He was a recluse deluxe, driving to work in his blue
Jaguar, dining with his friend Coco Chanel, visiting his homes in
his native Spain, but always comfortably cloistered. When a client
asked if she might bring a friend to see his show, one of the
couturier's minions replied, ``Curious women are not welcome
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Balenciaga's clothes were as serious as his customers were
devoted, and when he abruptly closed his fashion house in 1968, it
came as a blow to their elegant lives. Countess Mona Bismark was
said to have been so distraught she took to her room and didn't
emerge for three days. Balenciaga retired to Spain.
</P>
<P>
   In the only interview he gave in his life, he compared his last
years of dressing the world's rich and jet-propelled, who included
Barbara Hutton and the Duchess of Windsor, to ``a dog's life.'' He
died in 1972, just as the man who would eventually revive his label
was beginning to waddle in diapers.
</P>
<P>
   Nicolas Ghesquiere would seem to have nothing in common with the
man Christian Dior once called ``the master of us all.'' The second
child of a French mother and a Belgian father who tends golf
courses, Ghesquiere grew up in central France, where, among other
things, he developed a fascination for ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   Balenciaga, at 13, was making clothes for the Marquese de Casa
Torres. At 25, he had his own couture house.
</P>
<P>
   Ghesquiere, 28, began his career working as an assistant to Jean
Paul Gaultier, then as a knitwear designer. When he was hired by
Groupe Jacques Bogart, the owner of Balenciaga, a French perfume
and ready-to-wear company that bought the brand in 1986 from the
German chemical giant Hoechst, Ghesquiere was designing uniforms
and funeral clothes under a Balenciaga license for Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to Balenciaga from what many people would say is the
worst position in fashion,'' he said last week during a visit to
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in just two seasons, Ghesquiere has emerged as a kind of
cult designer, a favorite with stylists like George Cortina, who
does John Bartlett's shows, as well as the actress Chloe Sevigny.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's good, the clothes are interesting and you want to wear
them,'' said Julie Gilhart, a vice president for women's fashion at
Barneys, which substantially increased its order for next spring.
``It's the same feeling I had when Prada and Helmut Lang were
starting out.''
</P>
<P>
   Annie O'Hayon, a press agent in the music business, bought a
pair of Ghesquiere's trousers at Jeffrey, which was one of the
first American retailers to carry the label. She said: ``At first,
what attracted me was the Balenciaga name. It really has an
emotional connection. At home, I always heard about Balenciaga and
Schiaparelli. But what I really care about is the fit, and the fact
that everybody's not buying it yet.''
</P>
<P>
   What's particularly intriguing about Ghesquiere's clothes is the
way he subtly incorporates references from Balenciaga's styles of
the 1940s and '50s. Nothing is a copy. That would be absurd,
because, for one thing, Balenciaga worked in haute couture, often
sewing a garment himself. And for another, Ghesquiere isn't
interested in trying to revive the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at all these images, and I learn and try to integrate
them, but then I try to forget them,'' he said. ``After all, I am
28 and I can only see things through my eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   But the references are there. They can be seen in the full
sleeves and V-neck tops, the wide shoulders and crinkled Gypsy
skirts, all of which draw on Balenciaga's original style, with its
heavy Spanish and Edwardian influence. Leather sleeves, crushed
tightly above the elbows, evoke a Balenciaga coat with plush,
rippling sleeves.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Ghesquiere's last two collections, which were
presented with a cold severity (another Balenciaga idea), some
fashion writers innocently noted that the clothes looked Edwardian.
One reviewer said of Ghesquiere's spring 2000 collection that it
``was so low key it had virtually no impact at all.'' In 1951, when
Balenciaga deviated from Dior's New Look with the first semifitted
suit, hardly anyone, with the exception of Carmel Snow, the editor
of Harper's Bazaar, saw that he was creating the beginnings of the
modern suit.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, these references point up what a visionary
Balenciaga was.
</P>
<P>
   After Ghesquiere's spring collection last year, with its
high-neck collars evocative of Princess Leia in ``Star Wars,'' a
number of reviewers said it had overtones of the late 1970s. But as
Ghesquiere said, ``I found in that same era the results of
Balenciaga's work, from the '40s and '50s.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, with a laugh, ``You can open a Balenciaga book and see
the religious clothes, the references to the paintings of Goya, and
you can look at `Star Wars' and see almost the same thing. And
`Star Wars' is supposed to be the future.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be the drawback, critics say, with Ghesquiere's
clothes. Are they too referential?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm wondering if he's holding back,'' said Linda Dresner, who
bought the current fall collection for her stores in New York City
and in Birmingham, Mich., but passed on next spring's line. ``I
just don't see enough of his personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Joan Burstein, who owns Browns in London, expressed similar
doubts. ``Collections such as Michael Kors, Marc Jacobs and Celine
are doing very well for us, as they are more forward-looking and
have inspired vision,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Reviving Balenciaga may just be an overwhelming task.
Marie-Andree Jouve, who oversees the Balenciaga archive in Paris
and who is co-author of a primary reference book on the designer,
conceded that Ghesquiere has ``the spirit of Balenciaga.'' But she
emitted the tiniest Gallic wince when it was suggested that he, or
anyone, could successfully follow Balenciaga.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no,'' she said. ``It's impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but Jacques Konckier, the manager director of the company
that owns the Balenciaga trademark and perfume, said that in the
two and a half years since Ghesquiere took over the collection from
Josephus Thimister, who mainly designed evening clothes, sales had
doubled, to around $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nicolas is translating Balenciaga in a very modern way, and he
was right to rehabilitate the house in terms of day wear,''
Konckier said, adding that they are discussing lines of shoes and
handbags.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Ghesquiere doesn't seem the kind of guy to get weepy
with reverence. He grew animated when discussing a film Balenciaga
made in the early '60s, when, in a pique, he put on a show in a
room of empty chairs. No clients, no music, only the clickety whir
of an 8-millimeter camera. But that is just a cool thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say this,'' Ghesquiere said, smiling. ``I have no
Balenciaga complex.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
