<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRS. CLINTON SAYS TRIP TO ISRAEL IS UNRELATED TO NEW YORK RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton said on Monday that her trip
this week to Israel was an official visit and should not be viewed
in the context of her run for the U.S. Senate. Her remarks came as
the White House disclosed more details of the first lady's 36-hour
itinerary, including a visit to the Western Wall in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an official trip,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``That is
something very important to stress. I was invited last spring as
first lady. I'm going as first lady. It is a totally official trip
and I hope it does not have any political questions associated with
it.''
</P>
<P>
   As Mrs. Clinton prepared to leave on Mondayevening for a trip
that will take her to both Israel and Jordan, it was clear that her
visit is to some extent becoming tangled in the often-overlapping
politics of Jerusalem and New York.
</P>
<P>
   At City Hall, Mayor Ehud Olmert of Jerusalem, a member of the
conservative Likud Party and a friend of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani of
New York City, assailed Mrs. Clinton, he said, for not including
any visits to East Jerusalem on her itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very, very sad for the fact that she chose not to visit
the East Side of Jerusalem, which appears to me like a political
statement, which is in somewhat contradiction to her original
statement that she supports the transfer of the American Embassy to
Jerusalem and the unity of the city as our capital,'' Olmert said.
</P>
<P>
   Olmert said he was not taking sides in an American political
race _ Giuliani is the likely Republican candidate in the race for
Senate _ but he offered warm words for Giuliani during their jovial
joint appearance outside Giuliani's office. It came less than 24
hours before Mrs. Clinton was scheduled to leave on a trip to a
country that has historically been a standard visit for any New
York candidate running for office.
</P>
<P>
   Olmert's remarks came after Israeli newspapers reported that
Mrs. Clinton had decided against visiting the Western Wall in
Jerusalem, and some American Jewish leaders had criticized her for
that. In truth, over the last week, Mrs. Clinton and her aides said
that most of the details of the trip _ other than two speeches she
was giving _ had not been worked out and that she might visit the
Western Wall.
</P>
<P>
   Early Monday afternoon, Mrs. Clinton said that her schedule had
not been set but that ``obviously, I'm going to try to go; I've
been there twice before.'' Later in the day, Mrs. Clinton's White
House spokeswoman, Marsha Berry, said the visit to the Western Wall
in Jerusalem and a visit to a children's center in Tel Aviv had
been added to the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Olmert's criticisms about the first lady's not going
to East Jerusalem, Ms. Berry responded: ``No, he's wrong. She is
going to visit East Jerusalem. She's going to the Wailing Wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berry said that additional stops might be scheduled for Mrs.
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's two main public events are to be a speech to a
children's conference at Tel Aviv University and an address at the
Rabin Center. She is also attending a dinner with Prime Minister
Ehud Barak. From Israel, she will go to Jordan for two days before
joining President Clinton in Greece.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said her visit to Israel had become complicated
because it had been reduced from four days, when she first began
planning it last spring, to just over a day. She delayed her last
trip because Barak had just won an election and was in the process
of forming a government.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
