r a BC-GENIUS-AZR &LR;      11-08 1392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENIUS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA'S 12 `GENIUSES' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY MEDLYN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - They ponder fly brains and desert seeds, sexual
reproduction and forest fires.
</P>
<P>
   One has worked 25 years creating art inside a dormant volcano
near Flagstaff. Another is building devices that can detect life on
other planets.
</P>
<P>
   A third is organizing Arizona ranchers to protect open spaces.
</P>
<P>
   They're among the 12 Arizona recipients of the MacArthur
Foundation's so-called ``genius grants'' _ each given thousands of
dollars to spend as they wish.
</P>
<P>
   No strings. No reports. No questions asked.
</P>
<P>
   Though Arizona's 12 differ in many ways, they share two things:
</P>
<P>
   First, all scoff at the ``genius'' label.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even tie my shoe or remember my license number,''
wildlife researcher Marvin ``Phil'' Kahl said.
</P>
<P>
   Second, each remembers that phone call out of the blue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hair on the back of my neck stood up,'' Native American
writer Leslie Marmon Silko said.
</P>
<P>
   Plant ethnobiologist Gary Nabhan: ``I went into shock,
literally.''
</P>
<P>
   The grants _ described by foundation officials as ``venture
capital for intellectual, social and artistic endeavors'' _ ranged
from $176,000 to $330,000. They are dispensed quarterly over a
five-year period.
</P>
<P>
   They are unique in that no one can apply, and no one must
account for how he or she spends the money.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Socolow, director of the program, said the grant ``is a
vote of confidence in (recipients') potential, not an award for
what they have done.''
</P>
<P>
   The recipients, he said, ``are those who have risen to the
challenge of not doing things in the same way, not getting stuck in
categories that so many of us get stuck in.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They are maverick and extraordinary,'' he said, ``approaching
whatever field they are in with a fresh, different and challenging
eye.''
</P>
<P>
   The approach is eased by free money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real godsend,'' Silko recalled. ``I was a single
mother. I was teaching. I had a long novel in mind, and I didn't
have the money to devote myself to it. All of a sudden, there it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   The fellowship enabled Silko to produce the 742-page Almanac of
the Dead.
</P>
<P>
   Silko, of Tucson, was among the first group of fellows ever
named in 1981. University of Arizona linguistics professor Ofelia
Zepeda is the most recent winner, named in June. They are among 563
fellows nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Arizona's 12 relied on the annual stipends as their sole
support while they wrote books or pursued research projects.
</P>
<P>
   Others _ mainly scientists _ are so awash in grants that even
$60,000 a year is a comparative drop in the bucket.
</P>
<P>
   Socolow said the foundation doesn't care where the money goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone were to put an addition on their house to have
their parents live with them, and take that worry off their head,
that could be great,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If buying a car relieves them of other anxieties and stresses
in their lives, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   The effects even span generations. Kahl said his $320,000 award
prompted his mother, then 83, to go car shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``She knew I wouldn't need the money for an inheritance,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kahl, who supported 30 years of water-bird and elephant research
by selling wildlife photos, socked away a chunk of the MacArthur
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came for five years,'' he said, ``but will last for 30.''
</P>
<P>
   Cultural anthropologist Brackette Williams, the daughter of
migrant laborers based in southern Arizona, was notified of her
$285,000 fellowship two years ago as she was leaving a visiting
professorship at the University of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I will go back to the academic world,'' said
Williams, who lives in Tucson. ``In my heart of hearts, I am just a
cowgirl.''
</P>
<P>
   But the exhilaration of economic freedom sometimes carries a
price.
</P>
<P>
   Nabhan, currently director of science and conservation at the
Arizona-Sonora Desert Museum, was so overwhelmed during the first
year of his $245,000 MacArthur award that he developed chronic
fatigue syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so honored by the award that I said yes to anything
people threw in front of me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something about it that is more complex than just
being a blessing. You feel: `I've been given this tremendous gift.
I have to help other people.'
</P>
<P>
   ``You can easily burn yourself out.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabhan said, ``I had been conserving pennies to make it through
the year. When I went into Tucson the next day for the press
conference, my lights went out in the car because I hadn't been
able to pay to fix an electrical problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Nabhan wrote five books over the five-year period, including The
Geography of Childhood, which helps teachers put children in touch
with the natural world. He also crafted a native-food diet to help
diabetes-prone Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fellowship made me feel more comfortable with who I am,''
he said. ``It was always hard to justify to the scientists that I
was a writer, and hard to explain to writers that I cared about all
this technical stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The cross-disciplinary dexterity is not unusual for MacArthur
fellows.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't keep their crayons in the box,'' Socolow said.
``The unusual, highly creative person is someone who will define
things differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``In academe, they often are people who don't fit naturally or
don't feel comfortable in any one place.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of Arizona has five of the 12 fellows; Arizona
State University has one, Stephen Pyne.
</P>
<P>
   Pyne is a professor of history and biology _ an odd combination
for anyone but a MacArthur fellow. Among the world's foremost
experts on fire, Pyne was given $250,000 in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Also a Fulbright fellow, Pyne has produced a suite of
environmental histories, Cycle of Fire. He served 18 seasons as a
firefighter with the National Park Service. That experience
inspired him to write his current book, How the Grand Canyon Became
Grand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I'm back to the old conundrum of not really fitting in,''
Pyne said. He'd like to go to Africa or Canada to study fire, but
hasn't yet found a funding source.
</P>
<P>
   For MacArthur fellows in the hard sciences, the fellowship is
but one of many flowing to them and their departments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tendency to self-breed _ one grant encourages more
grants,'' said Nicholas Strausfeld, a MacArthur winner and UA
professor of neurobiology. He's known as ``flybrain'' in his e-mail
address, denoting his expertise in insect anatomy.
</P>
<P>
   But not all MacArthur fellows have academic pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   William McDonald is a fifth-generation cattle rancher in
Douglas. Last year, he got a $285,000 fellowship.
</P>
<P>
   McDonald assembled the Malpai Borderlands Group, a unique blend
of ranchers, conservationists and scientists devoted to preserving
open space and protecting endangered species on their land.
</P>
<P>
   ``This award has given us recognition we wouldn't have gotten
otherwise,'' McDonald said. ``The money itself has given me a
breather. But I'm not doing anything any differently than I would
have done anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Do Arizona's 12 fellows consider themselves geniuses?
</P>
<P>
   To a one, the answer is no. The media came up with that term,
they note, not the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just fanatic about what I do,'' Kahl said. ``That is the
common thread among these people: They are crazy about what they
do.''
</P>
<P>
   McDonald said his gift lies in cutting to the chase ``to what
needs to be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from that talent, he has no special claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a lucky son of a gun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   UA astronomy Professor Roger Angel said said he reserves the
term ``genius'' for ``Newton, Einstein and Mozart _ people who work
on a plane many levels beyond me.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, everyone can hope for a moment of genius.
</P>
<P>
   For Angel, that came when he discovered that hydrogen atoms in
the presence of a strong magnetic field caused features in a
certain type of star.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you recognize you're the only person who knows that
thing, there are incredible highs to be had,'' Angel said.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly the point, Socolow said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The program has two real goals,'' he said. ``One is to seed
and nurture individual creativity, and the other is to demonstrate
that it is everywhere around us.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Beverly Medlyn can be reached at (602) 444-8213 or at
bev.medlyn(at)pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
