<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER BRUIN FALLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA's cursed season continued Monday when coach
Bob Toledo announced starting center Troy Danoff has suffered a
season-ending knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Danoff, a sophomore, tore the anterior cruciate ligament in his
left knee Wednesday in a routine blocking drill. It was the second
season-ending injury of the bye week: A day earlier, guard Mike
Saffer sprained his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``What more can happen?'' Toledo said. ``It's devastating
because (Danoff) will miss spring practice, which he greatly needs,
as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Danoff, Saffer and reserve center Tony Ippolito (knee
surgery), the Bruins have eight healthy offensive linemen. One,
reserve guard Ed Anderson, has spent most of the season on the
scout team.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, right tackle Brian Polak has moved to right guard.
Reserve guard Matt Phelan will start at center. Left tackle Blake
Worley might start at right tackle _ if true freshman Bryce
Bohlander plays well on the left side _ and Jim Ghezzi is the
backup at three positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all this adversity, we just have to show what kind of
character we have, because we can't change the cards,'' Polak said.
``But I absolutely think this will benefit us next year, because
we've all been through it together.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Full circle: The move to center means Phelan, a senior from
Leona Valley, will start at his third position this year. He opened
the season at left guard because of Oscar Cabrera's suspension,
then he moved to to right guard when Saffer missed several games
because of a sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Center is actually my favorite position,'' Phelan said. ``It's
more cerebral. You have to recognize blocking schemes and call out
the fronts. It's ironic that I started my career there (as a
freshman) and through dumb luck I'm ending it there.''
</P>
<P>
   __ There's more: Toledo said tight end Bryan Fletcher and
defensive tackle Ken Kocher probably won't play Saturday against
Washington. Both have severely sprained ankles.
</P>
<P>
   Their absence means seven expected starters are missing from
UCLA's lineup: cornerbacks Marques Anderson (suspension) and Jason
Bell (heel), receiver Brian Poli-Dixon (broken wrist), Fletcher,
Kocher, Saffer and Danoff.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, five second-stringers are out: defensive end Travor
Turner (knee), left tackle Josh Webb (shoulder), linebacker Asi
Faoa (back), linebacker Ed Stansbury (knee) and Ippolito.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're losing a lot of key players,'' Toledo said, ``and we're
losing players in positions we can't afford to lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The offensive-line injuries are especially damaging, since
UCLA's running game has fueled its eight-game winning streak over
USC.
</P>
<P>
   __ Revving up: As the line falls apart, the playmakers return.
Tailback DeShaun Foster, who had five carries in October because of
a sprained ankle, and receiver Danny Farmer, who has played
sparingly in recent weeks because of a strained groin, are ready
for full-time duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're as healthy as they've been all year, but they won't be
at full speed,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   __ And finally: The UCLA-USC game Nov. 20 at the Coliseum will
start at 12:30 p.m. and be televised on Channel 7.
</P>
</TEXT>
