<SLUG> BC-NJ-REPUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICS CHILLS FORBES-WHITMAN FRIENDSHIP OF MANY YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Steve Forbes brought his Republican presidential
campaign into New Jersey's capital on Monday, speaking on the steps
of a war memorial a block from the office of his childhood pal,
Gov. Christie Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman made her own public appearance in a Revolutionary War
barracks just a few hundred yards away. But Forbes and the governor
did not visit with each other or speak during his daylong stop in
Trenton, and that conspicuous silence was a stark reminder that
their friendship of nearly a half century has become a casualty in
the battle between the various factions of the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Once schoolmates, political allies and young Republican
bluebloods in New Jersey's hunt country, Forbes and Whitman now
find themselves on opposing sides of the Republican Party divide.
They attended Far Hills Country Day School in Somerset County
together, were raised in prominent and politically active
Republican families in affluent Somerset County and grew up in
estates about 10 minutes apart.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman, who has been vilified by her party's right wing for her
support of abortion rights, has publicly criticized Forbes' shift
on social issues several times this year, accusing him of caving in
to the conservative voters who dominate the party's primaries.
</P>
<P>
   When the governor said Monday during a conversation with
reporters that she had not followed the primary campaign closely
and then offered a few kind words for Forbes, she was asked whether
she knew that campaign aides for her longtime friend had been
trying to win votes by bluntly portraying him as the anti-Whitman.
Her expression made it clear that she was hardly heartened by the
news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve was certainly a Christie Whitman Republican when I first
ran for governor,'' Whitman said with a smile, ``and I haven't
changed on the issues that were important to me then and are
important to me now. If he's changed, that's up to him. And that's
fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Forbes came to Trenton to rally social conservatives supporting
a proposal to make every student in New Jersey begin the school day
by reciting part of the Declaration of Independence in addition to
the Pledge of Allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   He also took the occasion to brush aside any suggestion that he
might abandon his presidential bid and seek the party's nomination
for U.S. Senate next year. That race has been in turmoil since
Whitman dropped out of contention in September. Chuck Haytaian,
chairman of the state Republican Party, said he had no indication
that Forbes might be interested in the Senate race if his
presidential bid is unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's running for the presidency. He still thinks he has a
shot,'' Haytaian said. ``Think about it. He spent $37 million to
run for president last time He's spent $15 million this time. After
all that, why would he back away to run for the Senate?''
</P>
<P>
   Other than their background and party affiliation, Forbes and
Whitman have little in common these days. She will complete her
second and final term as governor next year, and has traveled the
country trying to raise money and support for Republican moderates.
Forbes, meanwhile, has spent much of the last four years courting
conservatives, occasionally at the expense of Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   A former Republican governor, Tom Kean, who has known both
Forbes and Whitman for decades, said it was inevitable that they
would go their separate ways once Forbes acted on his ambitions for
national office.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the national stage, there's only room for one person from
New Jersey,'' Kean said. ``There's a rivalry that develops, quite
naturally. So there's a certain wariness among supporters and
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   In the minds of many New Jersey Republicans, young Christie and
Steve were indelibly linked at the Republican presidential
convention in 1956, which nominated Dwight Eisenhower to a second
term in the White House. Christie Todd, age 9, and Steve Forbes,
age 8, appeared on stage together to present ceremonial gifts to
the children of the renominated vice president, Richard Nixon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
