<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PATAKI-ENVIRON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR TESTS THE WINDS WITH MOVES ON EMISSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Last summer, as environmentalists called for air
pollution controls on New York's oldest power plants, Gov. George
Pataki showed no interest, declining to include them in a related
bill. Then, his administration briefly backed away from its demand
that plants in other states cut their emissions, before reversing
itself under intense criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, who praise some aspects of the governor's
record, seized on those events to assail him on air quality. What a
difference a few weeks make. With recent moves to impose strict
emission limits on old power plants and new cars, Pataki has
suddenly jumped to the head of the line among the nation's
governors in fighting air pollution, winning a chorus of accolades
from environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   The governor and his aides insist that his actions should be
taken at face value and that their timing was coincidental. But
Democrats, environmentalists and not a few of the governor's fellow
Republicans say they cannot help but see links to the heat he took
last summer, to his budding rivalry with the state's new,
Democratic attorney general, or to his hopes of being tapped as his
party's vice presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   And for some who have closely followed these events, there is a
nagging suspicion that questions about Pataki's motives stem, in
part, from the reluctance of environmentalists _ not to mention
some reporters and voters _ to give a Republican the benefit of the
doubt on environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that might be true for a lot of environmental
organizations, but I really don't think it's true for us,'' said
Larry Shapiro, an environmental lawyer at the New York Public
Interest Research Group. ``Look, I believe the governor has always
truly cared about environmental concerns. But that doesn't mean
that politics don't enter into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki, in an interview Monday, said: ``It's just amazing to me
that something that I've been deeply involved in since I was a
little kid, people can question my motives. I think it reflects
more of the mind-set of the liberal press and their bias.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a number of things,'' said Val Washington, director
of Environmental Advocates, a coalition of groups, ``that had
called into question the governor's leadership on the environment,
and I think it's clear he has set out to reassert himself because
he sees this as his territory and he wants to protect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and some legislators have long wanted the
state to limit pollution from old power plants that were exempt
from stringent state and federal controls, but Pataki ignored calls
to include it this year in a bill on granting environmental permits
to new plants.
</P>
<P>
   For years, New York and neighboring states have called on the
federal government to crack down on power-plant emissions from the
Midwest and the South, which blow into the Northeast and contribute
to smog and acid rain. This summer, the Pataki administration
floated a proposed compromise with the other regions, only to
withdraw it under fire from other Northeastern states and
environmental groups.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the state attorney general, Eliot Spitzer, said he
would sue 17 out-of-state power plants under the federal Clean Air
Act. A few weeks later, he put eight New York plants on notice that
they, too, might be in violation of the act and could face legal
action.
</P>
<P>
   Not only had the governor suffered a spate of bad publicity on
air-quality issues but also after years of being the state's most
prominent conservationist, he suddenly took a back seat to Spitzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, he was feeling the heat,'' said Assemblyman Richard
Brodsky, chairman of the Environmental Conservation Committee. ``He
felt pressured by Spitzer's moves and the pressure we have been
applying for five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki took back the spotlight last month _ and stunned many
environmental groups _ when he announced that he would order sharp
cuts in emissions by older plants in New York, doing
administratively what a few months earlier, he had refused to do
legislatively.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when the Clinton administration said it would take
enforcement action against power plants in the Midwest and the
South, the governor repeatedly claimed credit for pressuring the
federal government into it.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki announced this week that New York would impose tough new
emission standards on vehicles, starting in 2004, a step that,
unlike his move against power plants, was not a surprise. The
timing made New York the first state to join California, which
created the standards, barely beating Massachusetts, which is
expected to adopt them soon, and allowing the governor, once again,
to claim national leadership.
</P>
<P>
   The latest round of events has spawned a new set of theories.
One has it that Pataki has largely abandoned his hopes of getting
on the national ticket, and is securing his status in New York. But
another holds that since Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the
front-runner for the Republican presidential nomination, may be
vulnerable on his environmental record, the party would do well to
choose a vice presidential nominee who has a stronger environmental
record.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Morris, a Democratic consultant, said, in a reference to
Bush, ``Maybe Pataki read that Houston has the most polluted air in
the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
