<HEADLINE>
2 CITIES VIE TO BECOME PERMANENT HOME OF BATTLESHIP NEW JERSEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (mk) 
 By MARIA NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Call it the battle for the battleship, or the north vs. the
south.
</P>
<P>
   As the much-decorated and now decommissioned battleship New
Jersey heads slowly toward that state, the Navy is trying to decide
which of two cities will become its permanent home.
</P>
<P>
   The contest is between two decidedly unglamorous places trying
to transform themselves: Bayonne, an industrial city in the shadow
of the Statue of Liberty, and Camden, an industrial city across the
Delaware River from Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   The ship, which had been berthed in Bremerton, Wash., since
being decommissioned in 1991, was towed through the Panama Canal
toward the East Coast. Long before its expected arrival on
Thursday, it had become an object of intense attention, from
veterans and military buffs eager to walk its teak decks and from
the two cities eager to attract tourists. Each city is seeking to
persuade the Navy that it is best suited to accommodate the ship
and preserve it as a museum, and the competition has started to
take on the undertones of the north-south rivalry that often
defines New Jersey politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bayonne supporters say that the battleship, the most decorated
in the American fleet, should be where most New Jersey residents
can have access to it. They reason that because two-thirds of the
state's residents live north of Trenton, the state capital, the
ship is likely to attract more tourists if it is in the New York
City metropolitan area, which would help support its expensive
upkeep.
</P>
<P>
   Camden backers say the battleship ought to be near its
birthplace, the Philadelphia Naval Shipyards, where it was built in
1942. The battleship will be set up as a museum on the revitalized
Camden waterfront, next to the two-year-old New Jersey Aquarium and
just across the Delaware from downtown Philadelphia and its
historical attractions. The Delaware River, they also point out,
will provide a freshwater port for the ship, an important
consideration in preserving the battleship's aging steel hull.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides cite a long list of pros and cons, and many who care
about the ship's fate fear that a decision will come down to
politics. If that is the case, some say, North Jersey could
prevail, as it often has.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have more clout up in the north than we do here in the
south,'' said John Horan of Cherry Hill, N.J., who was a signalman
on the original crew for two and a half years during World War II.
Horan, who said he would visit the ship no matter where it ended
up, said he would rather see it in Camden, 10 minutes from his
home, but expected the north to win. ``In the state as a whole,
North Jersey gets a lot more than South Jersey,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe not this time. A few days before the ship is to arrive
in Philadelphia, its temporary home, the scales may be tipping in
Camden's favor. While the Navy wouldn't say what it would do before
a decision was announced, possibly in January, Camden's proposal
has gained powerful support in Washington. Backers include senators
and representatives and the secretary for housing and urban
development, Andrew Cuomo. Meanwhile, the Bayonne plan has been
garnering more critics, including several U.S. representatives from
the New York City area, and the directors of the Intrepid, a
similar floating museum at a Manhattan pier.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-11-08-99 2348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991108.0571 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-11-08 23:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3616 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-PUELICHER-NYT &LR;      11-08 0323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-PUELICHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHN PUELICHER, 78, BANK HOLDING COMPANY CHAIRMAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Ariz., Ill., Fla.)  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   John A. Puelicher, retired chairman of the board of Marshall &AMP;
Ilsley Corp., a bank holding company, died on Oct. 30 at his home
in Milwaukee. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death was liver cancer, said a company spokesman,
M.A. Hatfield.
</P>
<P>
   Puelicher, who was known as Jack, led a venerable
Milwaukee-based company that was previously headed by his father,
Albert S. Puelicher, and his grandfather, John Puelicher. He was
also a prominent benefactor of civic, charitable and educational
causes in Milwaukee and elsewhere in Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   During Puelicher's years as chairman, from 1963 to 1992, M &AMP; I,
as it is often called, grew rapidly, making 44 acquisitions. In
1963, the bank had $420 million in assets; in 1992, it had $7.15
billion, including M &AMP; I Data Services, which provides computer
services for banks.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the company has assets of $23.6 billion in its operations
in Wisconsin, Arizona and Illinois. The Puelicher family has run
the bank since 1920. Samuel Marshall founded the bank in 1847, and
Charles Ilsley joined it two years later.
</P>
<P>
   John Albert Puelicher was born on Nov. 4, 1920, in Milwaukee. He
attended Dartmouth College and graduated from the University of
Wisconsin at Madison. He worked at the family bank for several
years before serving as a lieutenant in the Navy during World War
II.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Puelicher rejoined the bank, working as a vice
president and executive vice president before his election as
president in 1958. Upon his father's death in 1963, he became
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Puelicher's first wife, Jimmie Ann, died in 1989. He is survived
by his wife, Melissa; two daughters, Nancy Phipps of Tallahassee,
Fla., and Mary Uihlein of Milwaukee; a sister, Dorothy Ann Van
Housen of Milwaukee, and three grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
