<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE CIVIC VALUE OF STATIC CLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
(PHOENIX) - For more than a week, the most pow erful politicians in
the state of Ari zona were consumed completely by a sometimes
bitter, often accusatory, al ways boisterous argument over hair
curl ers. Or, perhaps, curling irons.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Depending upon whom you believe.
</P>
<P>
   It began when the state's speaker of the House, Jeff Groscost,
repeated what he thought was a funny story to a reporter from USA
Today. Groscost talked about being on a road trip with Gov. Jane
Hull, Secretary of State Betsey Bayless and state Senate President
Brenda Burns, in which he listened to the women debate the pros and
cons of 2-inch and quarter-inch curlers.
</P>
<P>
   USA Today sent a writer to Arizona to report on how the state's
top five elected positions are held by women. The front-page
article with Groscost's anec dote was printed on a Friday, Oct.
29th.
</P>
<P>
   That same day, Hull told an audience of 2,000 professional women
that she would ``send a pointed message to the speaker . . . to
remind him we don't talk about curlers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about issues, and we talk about what's good for the
state of Ari zona,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's press secretary called it ``a chauvinistic
remark,'' adding, ``(We) are disappointed that the speaker had the
opportunity to showcase the state to the national media and,
instead, made a wise crack that was not true.''
</P>
<P>
   With his veracity in question, Groscost found someone to back up
his story. Early the following week, he trotted out state Rep. Lori
Daniels, the House majority leader, who said she was on the trip,
too, and remembered the women discussing hair care.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking about the size of our curling irons and
driving him crazy,'' Daniels said.
</P>
<P>
   Back and forth the officials went, split ting hairs, stirring up
the kind of free wheeling public debate that hasn't existed in
America since we pondered the ques tion:
</P>
<P>
   ``Does she or doesn't she?''
</P>
<P>
   A COLLECTIVE `NOOOOOO!'
</P>
<P>
   About a week later, when the quarrel ling ended and the
politicians put aside their juvenile carping and promised to de
vote their time and energy to government, it was as if everyone in
the state took a deep breath and let out a collective ``Noooooo!''
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that when politicos are busy getting into each
other's hair, they can't get into ours.
</P>
<P>
   So, if our top officials don't want to talk about curlers
anymore, how about lip gloss? Or dishpan hands?
</P>
<P>
   Why bother with taxation, transporta tion or education, when
we've yet to eliminate ring around the collar?
</P>
<P>
   And what about recipes?
</P>
<P>
   As they used to tell us on TV, ``Nothin' says lovin' like
somethin' from the oven.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Groscost told USA Today, ``I finally understood what
ladies have long talked about: having to endure men's talk about
football and basketball games.''
</P>
<P>
   He should run with that thought.
</P>
<P>
   And if he and fellow members of the state House run out of
football and bas ketball stories, they could move on to baseball
and hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer. Auto racing. Fly-fishing. La crosse.
</P>
<P>
   Or go full circle, to curling. The ``sport.'' The only
competition in the Olympics featuring ice, a stone and a couple of
guys with brooms.
</P>
<P>
   WELCOME DISTRACTIONS
</P>
<P>
   If recent weeks have taught us any thing, it's that politicians
cannot simulta neously pull on each other's pompadours and pick our
pockets.
</P>
<P>
   On a national level, the impeachment of President Clinton served
the same pur pose, protecting the public from politi cians for the
better part of a year.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than dragging the country into that kind of toilet,
however, why not fol low Arizona's model and discuss, say, drain
cleaners? Or static cling?
</P>
<P>
   The women running Arizona proved they can be as small-minded as
any man. With your encouragement, they'll sink to even greater
depths. It won't be easy. And should they ever claim to run out
trivial subjects to argue about, remember:
</P>
<P>
   There's always room for Jell-O. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
